<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUSPECT-SWITCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN INVESTIGATED IN SLAYING HELPS CATCH SUSPECT POLICE SAY IS REAL
KILLER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Afraid he'd go to jail for a crime he didn't
commit, Cesar Quintero did the impossible: He found the man police
say is the real killer.
</P>
<P>
   It looked bad for Quintero: four eyewitnesses identified him as
the Mother's Day killer of Steven Redden; he drove a red Fiero like
the one the suspect fled the scene in and a collection of knives
was found in his home. Prosecutors decided the evidence was
insufficient and police were still investigating him.
</P>
<P>
   And then a red Fiero virtually identical to his drove into the
quick oil-change auto shop where he worked and out stepped a man
who looked remarkably like him. Cool as anything, the 19-year-old
Quintero jotted down the license number for police and changed the
man's oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared,'' Quintero said Wednesday between servicing cars
at the shop in the Los Angeles suburb of Canoga Park. ``For two
weeks, I was terrified. There's not too many Hispanics, chubby guys
like me driving Fieros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to be locked up forever for something I didn't
do. I was just thinking, let justice do good!''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were amazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the years I've worked homicide, I've never seen this
happen,'' said Detective Ron Vega of the Los Angeles Police
Department. ``If you've never believed in divine intervention, I
guess you have to believe it now. Somebody was watching him
upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, detectives thought it was an action to outwit them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are the odds for him to run into the actual suspects?''
Vega said. ``He told me, `He not only drives the same car, but
looks like me.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta figure a guy who's facing murder charges is going to
call me.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was for real.
</P>
<P>
   Police traced the license plate and arrested Edgar Adolfo
Barrientos, 20, on suspicion of murder and his brother, Giovanni
Contreras, 24, on suspicion of battery.
</P>
<P>
   Barrientos pleaded not guilty Wednesday to murdering Redden, a
21-year-old North Hollywood man stabbed in a fight May 10 at a
Wienerschnitzel restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Contreras was released, with no charges filed because his fight
with Redden's 17-year-old friend was determined to be mutual
combat.
</P>
<P>
   Quintero's cousin, Rogelio Galindo, 21, also had been under
investigation, but police now say Quintero's actions have cleared
him of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel relieved,'' Quintero said. ``I feel like everything is
off my chest. I feel like I did a good thing for me and my
cousin.''
</P>
<P>
   An artist's drawing and sophisticated computer-generated
printouts by police of most of the Fieros in L.A.'s San Fernando
Valley led to Quintero and his cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there was always an element of doubt that they were the
suspects, Vega said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes from a good family,'' he said. ``In our hearts, we
always felt that these guys were not the suspects. We turned as
many stones as we could.''
</P>
<P>
   Just days before a polygraph test was scheduled, Quintero, who
says he celebrated Mother's Day at a barbecue at home with his
family, saw the red Fiero pull into his bay with a driver who
looked a lot like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, that's the guy,'' he said. ``He was a chubby
guy, my height, my same style haircut and tan. I knew right away it
was him. I wrote the license down and put it in my wallet.''
</P>
<P>
   Detectives followed up on the tip, which led them to the 8300
block of Willis Avenue in the L.A. suburb of Panorama City, where
they found Barrientos and Contreras, who fit the description of the
suspect and his accomplice, respectively, and were leaving the
apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   At the police station, they were placed in separate rooms and
Barrientos gave an admission, Vega said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I poked my head into one room and Barrientos said, `Hey, I
know why I'm here' and referenced the fight,'' Vega said. ``The
guys basically both copped-out to the murder.''
</P>
<P>
   The intense two-week investigation that zeroed in on Quintero
was a major upset for his entire family, including his sister who
recalled a room full of dozens of officers interrogating the family
during a search of their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time, we cooperated,'' his sister Esmeralda Quintero
said. `` The second time, they came in with a search warrant. We
were all in pajamas. They brought my cousin out in handcuffs in
front of the kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought maybe they're just blaming somebody. They said that
he was their No. 1 suspect,'' she said. ``But I knew my brother
didn't do it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
