<HEADER>
A5894 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-nbadraft-HNS &LR;      06-25 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-nba </SLUG>
 draft-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Lewis feels betrayed by Rockets
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ Many people tried to talk Rashard
Lewis out of his dream of going straight from Elsik High School to
the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Those people wanted Lewis to instead go to school and get an
education.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Lewis feels he got his education Wednesday night, courtesy
of the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who fell out of the first round and was finally taken by
Seattle with the 32nd pick in the annual NBA draft, left General
Motors Place with tears in his eyes and talking about how he had
been lied to by the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lewis, the Rockets promised him that they would
take the 6-10 forward if he were still available with one of
Houston's three first-round picks _ No. 14, 16 or 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me they would take me if I was still there,'' Lewis
said of the Rockets. ``I was still there at 14, but they didn't
take me at 14, or 16, so it didn't really cross my mind that they
really would take me at 18. If they wanted to take me, they would
have taken me.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did tell me that they would pick me, but you can't trust
anyone's words these days.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to tell if Lewis was speaking from the standpoint of
an 18-year-old who had just gone through the most disappointing few
hours of his life, or if he actually had a beef with the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich disputed Lewis' version of their
talks but understood where the youngster might have gotten the
wrong impression from the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did tell him that we liked him and that we couldn't make any
promises,'' Tomjanovich said. ``But I did tell him we liked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll admit this: He was the fourth guy on our list. If one of
our top three guys was gone, we were going to take him. We liked
him, and we think he has a very good future.
</P>
<P>
   ``But those were the top three guys we had penciled in for our
team and our needs. We thought we'd end up with Lewis because one
of those guys was going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets instead took Arizona shooting guard Michael
Dickerson with their 14th pick, Valparaiso point guard Bryce Drew
at No. 16 and Turkish forward Mirsad Turkcan at No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Of those three, only Turkcan, who flew himself in for the draft,
was in the NBA green room behind the stage at General Motors Place.
But Lewis was there, hobnobbing with several other anxious players.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the prospects filed out when their names were
called, striding to the podium to receive a logo cap from the team
that selected them and to shake the hand of NBA commissioner David
Stern.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the second round of the draft rolled around, Lewis
was the only player left, meaning there would be no guaranteed
three-year contract, which comes with being a first-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of disappointment is hard to hide, especially since
TNT, which televised the event nationally, kept cutting to Lewis,
alone in the green room, showing emotions he was obviously feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very emotional,'' said Lewis, explaining the tears he
couldn't hold back. ``Just being selected in the NBA really did
bring tears in my eyes. Knowing that I was supposed to go in the
first round but went in the second round also brought tears to my
eyes, but that makes me want to work even harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was still confident the whole way through (that he would be
drafted), even though I had to sit back there and wait. My family
just kept telling me, `Don't worry about it. The only thing you can
do is just step in the league and make a big impact. Go out there
and work hard, then you can prove everyone (who didn't draft him)
is wrong.' That's what I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Being taken by Seattle means Lewis will see the Rockets at least
four times a season, not counting the playoffs. And according to
Lewis, that's four times he can show the Rockets what they missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle is in the same conference as the Rockets,'' Lewis
said. ``Once we come into Houston to play, I will go out there to
show them what I can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed, but I'm not that much disappointed.
I'm very happy to go to Seattle. I've heard it's a great city. I'm
going to go out there and work hard. I have a heart bigger than
Texas, and I'm just looking forward to working real hard so I can
be able to go out there and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is already learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone would learn from this experience,'' Lewis said. ``I
learned that people tell you one thing, you see one thing in the
books or you see another thing, but some things may be true and
other things may not be true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no regrets at all. I made the decision, and now I have
to step forward and continue on with that decision. I'm going to be
out there every day. Starting tomorrow, I'm going to be in the gym
working out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
