<SLUG> BC-nba </SLUG>
 draft-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Surprises come early, often
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clippers start unexpected moves by taking Olowokandi over Bibby
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ The Los Angeles Clippers had talked
so long about how they needed a point guard, casting loving eyes
toward Arizona's Michael Bibby, rated the best point guard in the
NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby, Bibby, Bibby was all you heard coming out of the
Clippers' front office. So sure was Bibby of being selected by the
Clippers that he didn't work out for any other team. Not only was
Bibby a great point guard, but he was a local legend, the son of
Henry Bibby, who quarterbacked UCLA to three NCAA championships in
the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   It was a natural.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, all that talk turned out to be little more than
Clip service.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers decided to pass up a good thing, instead settling
on potential greatness in 7-0 center Michael Olowokandi with the
first pick in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   So much for all the projections, mock drafts and projected
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Need a point guard? Draft a center. Sure, it works.
</P>
<P>
   But while the center-stage podium at the draft is usually the
final destination on most players' minds, it might not be the last
stop for Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors circulating around General Motors Place on Wednesday
night had the Clippers shipping Olowokandi out in a trade. Even
Olowokandi hinted he might not be in Los Angeles long.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to give my opinion (as to why he was taken by the
Clippers), I think it would be because they figured they could
(draft) me and get something better later on,'' said Olowokandi,
who averaged 22 points and 11 rebounds for Pacific last season. ``I
don't know. Or draft me and have me improve after a season or so.
Like (Clippers general manager) Elgin Baylor said, there is a lack
of available centers in the league right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby didn't have to wait long before hearing his name, going to
Vancouver with the second pick. It was a selection that earned a
standing ovation from the crowd at General Motors Place, home of
the Grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just looking forward to getting drafted,'' said Bibby,
trying his best to not sound disappointed. ``I had no idea where I
was going to go. There was nothing I could do, and nothing I could
control. I didn't know what to expect. Me being No. 1 was just a
lot of talk and rumor, so I didn't expect anything.''
</P>
<P>
   That was certainly the way to approach this year's draft, since
surprise was the order of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Nuggets, who had been talking about selecting Kansas
swingman Paul Pierce, instead slipped their logo cap on Jayhawks
forward Raef LaFrentz with the third pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to play center at all, I have to get into the
weight room and continue to do a lot of hard work, put a lot more
weight and muscle on my frame,'' said the 6-11 LaFrentz. ``But I
think I can definitely do so.''
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina teammates Antawn Jamison and Vince Carter went
with the next two picks, to Toronto and Golden State, respectively.
The two then promptly exchanged hats in a deal that sent Jamison to
the Warriors in exchange for Carter and ``an extra consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas scooped up Robert ``Tractor'' Traylor with the sixth
pick, setting up a three-way trade involving Dallas and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The deal sent Traylor to Milwaukee for German forward Dirk
Nowitzki and Notre Dame power forward Pat Garrity, selected by
Milwaukee with the ninth and 19th picks, respectively. The
Mavericks then shipped Garrity, next year's first-round pick,
Martin Muursepp and Bubba Wells to Phoenix for guard Steve Nash.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 7 pick proved to be one of the biggest surprises, with
Sacramento selecting Florida point guard Jason Williams. Williams,
a tremendous ball-handler and passer, was highly rated, but his
often boneheaded attitude (he was kicked off the team at Florida
last season and suspended twice before that) had many general
managers turned off.
</P>
<P>
   It was thought that the Kings would be looking for a shooting
guard, like Larry Hughes, to replace Mitch Richmond, who had been
traded to Washington. Hughes instead went to Philadelphia at No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee selected Nowitzki with the ninth pick, but he was
shipped out in the Dallas deal.
</P>
<P>
   A very happy Boston organization had Pierce, who just a few days
ago was a sure bet to go among the top three or four picks, land
squarely in its lap at No. 10. Pierce, who has been projected for
stardom by no less than Magic Johnson, gives the Celtics another
full-court, inside-outside threat to go with Antoine Walker and Ron
Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a little disappointed, but it's a situation I had no
control over,'' said Pierce, who averaged 20.4 points at Kansas
last season. ``I am going to use this as motivation and show these
teams (that passed him over) that they should have picked me. But
I'm happy that (Celtics coach Rick) Pitino felt confident in my
ability and gave me a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball State shooting guard Bonzi Wells (No. 11, to Detroit), Utah
center Michael Doleac (No. 12, to Orlando) and UNLV power forward
Keon Clark (No. 13, to Orlando) rounded out the lottery picks.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando added Georgia Tech's Matt Harpring at No. 15 for the
last of its three first-round picks. The Rockets were the other
team with three first-rounders, snapping up Arizona shooting guard
Michael Dickerson at No. 14, Valparaiso point guard Bryce Drew at
16 and then Mirsad Turkcan, a 6-9 power forward from Turkey, at No.
18.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Turkcan underscored how far the high school
prospects had slipped in the draft. Elsik's Rashard Lewis, New
Jersey's Al Harrington and Virginia's Korleone Young all took large
falls.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington was the first of the trio be selected, going to
Indiana at No. 25, while Lewis fell out of the first round
entirely, eventually winding up with Seattle with the 32nd pick.
Young was taken by Detroit at No. 40.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
