<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOORDA-MEDALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMIRAL, A SUICIDE, WINS SOME VINDICATION ON COMBAT AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two years after the Navy's ranking officer, Adm.
Jeremy Boorda, committed suicide amid scrutiny over his right to
wear two combat decorations, the Navy has given him a measure of
vindication.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary of the Navy, John Dalton, has inserted into
Boorda's official record a letter from the former commander of the
Navy, Adm. Elmo R. Zumwalt Jr., declaring that Boorda was eligible
to wear the decorations for his service aboard two warships during
the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton's decision is being reported in the July issue of
Washingtonian magazine, which comes out on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Boorda, the chief of naval operations, shot himself outside his
home in Washington in May 1996 only hours before he was to be
interviewed by reporters from Newsweek investigating whether he had
earned the right to wear two tiny brass ``V'' pins, which signify
valor, for having earned the medals in combat.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary's action stopped short of revising Boorda's
service record, meaning that, officially, the questions about the
decorations have not been resolved. That would have required a
formal review by the Board for Correction of Naval Records, which
considers appeals on the awarding of decorations.
</P>
<P>
   Boorda had decided against such an appeal. Dalton also opted
against an appeal, Navy officials said on Wednesday night, because
it could have revived the controversy over Boorda's service.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a memorandum dated April 3, Dalton made it clear that
there was evidence supporting Boorda's right to wear the
decorations. Dalton wrote that citations awarding Boorda's medals
for his service ``plainly state that they were awarded for service
including `combat operations' and `while operating in combat
missions,''' suggesting the combat decorations were warranted,
though they were not specified.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton's memorandum also noted the views of Zumwalt, who
commanded naval forces in the Vietnam War and served as chief of
naval operations from 1970 to 1974. At the time of the suicide,
Zumwalt said he believed Boorda deserved the combat decorations,
but he put his views in another memorandum, dated May 18, that
Dalton also included in the official record.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has notified the admiral's widow, Bettie Boorda, of the
notations. One official said she had sought some official
recognition from the Navy that her husband had merited the awards.
</P>
<P>
   Boorda was the first sailor in the Navy to rise from the lowest
enlisted rank to become a four-star admiral and later the supreme
commander. He was 56 when he died.
</P>
<P>
   He received the Navy's Achievement Medal as a weapons officer
aboard the John R. Craig in 1965 and the Navy Commendation Medal
for service as executive officer about the Brooke from 1971 to
1973. Neither of those citations specifically awarded the ``V'' pin
designating combat service.
</P>
<P>
   Boorda stopped wearing the ``V'' pins when questions first arose
about them.
</P>
<P>
   In his memorandum, Zumwalt said Boorda's citations noted combat
service. He also said that as chief of naval operations during the
war he personally told officers and sailors that they were
authorized to wear the combat decoration on any medal received
``for duty in the combat theater of Vietnam.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
