<HEADER>
A5913 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-HNS &LR;      06-25 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lesson for Lewis: &QL; 
That's life, kid
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE evening began with Rashard Lewis looking so bright, so dapper
in his tan suit, crisp white shirt and colorful tie that made a
perfect ensemble to go with his beaming, hopeful smile.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a back room at General Motors Place in Vancouver,
British Columbia, this was the face of the future. Until it was
slapped by the cold reality of today.
</P>
<P>
   It was painful to watch, an experience you wouldn't wish on any
18-year-old anywhere, let alone a nice, local kid whose only desire
was to be picked by the hometown team.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern kept coming out from behind the wall to
announce the next selection in the 1998 NBA draft, and each time
you could practically feel Lewis holding his breath, almost hear
his heart beating as he waited, waited for his name to be called.
</P>
<P>
   Picks No. 8, 9 and 10 passed. Then 11, 12 and 13.
</P>
<P>
   The stage was set. The planets were aligned. It was the Rockets'
turn to make a choice, and the hometown kid was right there on the
board at No. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Thrice disappointed
</P>
<P>
   And he stayed there as the Rockets took 6-5 Michael Dickerson of
Arizona. They went for athleticism. They went for a player who lit
up their private workouts with his 3-point-shooting ability. They
went for a guy who can fill the lanes and finish a fast break, who
has played solid defense and won an NCAA championship.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando took Matt Harpring at No. 15, and the TV cameras swung
back into the ``green room'' for another glimpse at Lewis as the
Rockets prepared to make their second pick of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   No. 16 for the Rockets was Bryce Drew, the heady 6-3 guard who
will be immortalized on the highlight reels of March Madness for
decades to come as they replay that incredible, dramatic
last-second shot that lifted his team, tiny Valparaiso, over Ole
Miss. They went for a coach's son, a smart, feisty player. He can
create his own shot. He runs well off picks. He handles the ball
and shows leadership characteristics that could make him a point
guard for a veteran team that has been looking for somebody to step
forward and grab the job by the throat.
</P>
<P>
   In the back room, Lewis' face sagged, and there was a flicker of
doubt in those lively brown eyes.
</P>
<P>
   You tell an 18-year-old that the world isn't his oyster, waiting
to be slurped. Then, tell a high school star who spent his prep
career dunking over players smaller than him, draining 3-pointers,
that life doesn't always work out as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is 6-10 on the court and starred proudly for Elsik. But as
the night wore on, you could almost see him shrinking inside that
nice suit, trying to make himself smaller so those TV cameras
couldn't see him. Boom! It was a dream exploding on TNT.
</P>
<P>
   There was still one more chance at No. 18. Then, Mirsad Turkcan
of Turkey became a Rocket. And Lewis was left stuck on the
launching pad, filled with a sense of what? Shock? Disbelief?
Betrayal?
</P>
<P>
   It's the risk they take when they go straight from high school
to the pros, a big gamble. Who remembers Taj McDavid? He was a high
school phenom from South Carolina in 1996 who was never drafted or
signed by the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Are they really ready? Who will be patient enough to care,
nurture and develop them? Who can afford to wait?
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the kid that we really liked his game,'' admitted
Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich. ``He was fourth on our list. I did
think we would end up with him if one of our other guys was already
gone when it was our turn. Things just worked out perfect for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockets want help immediately
</P>
<P>
   But not for Lewis, who eventually went to Seattle with the 32nd
overall pick, the third choice of the second round. That means a
non-guaranteed contract. No instant millions. He appeared on TNT,
eyes already red, and nearly broke down in tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart is bigger than Texas, and I will show it,'' he said.
Later on, he ripped into the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   That's all right. He is young and had just been taught a harsh
lesson, one more painful than a blind-side pick by Shaquille
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA, in the era of free agency, is a live-for-today
business. There is no time for sentimentality or provincialism. The
Rockets are trying to win a championship now, next season, before
Hakeem Olajuwon and Charles Barkley need canes. They do not have
time to wait on an 18-year-old to mature. The Sonics need backups.
The Rockets need starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This probably disappointed him a lot,'' Tomjanovich said.
``But this might be the thing to get him to go out and prove people
wrong. The guy's got a tremendous upside. But we've got to look out
for our basic needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it post-high school lesson No. 1: It's a cold world,
Rashard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
