<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NELSON REINFORCES HIS REPUTATION, IF NOT MAVERICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ By the time this gets to Phoenix, they'll be laughing.
</P>
<P>
   But they've been laughing at the Mavericks in Phoenix for nearly
two years, so how is this any different?
</P>
<P>
   On a night that brimmed with promise, Don Nelson instead sorted
through the Mavericks' blueprints, surveyed the NBA draft pool,
finessed the telephone lines and, in the end, slipped another
whoopee cushion under loyal Mavs fans.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 draft pick for this year, by most reports, isn't
coming for at least two years. The No. 1 pick for next year isn't
coming _ ever.
</P>
<P>
   Teams with major rebuilding jobs are not supposed to trade their
No. 1 draft pick _ absolved from lottery protection _ for backup
point guards.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix _ again _ they have to be chortling. This was not
like the Jason Kidd thing. This was not like the
Here-Take-These-Big-Contracts thing.
</P>
<P>
   Nellie inherited those earlier mistakes. But this one _ the
unprotected 1999 draft pick for Steve Nash _ he thought up all on
his own.
</P>
<P>
   And when it was over, with vintage Nelson mad-scientist aplomb,
he proclaimed it a great day for the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to turn the franchise around,'' he told a roomful of
media infidels last night, ``and we made a major step in that
direction today.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to the night apparently was Nash. Ensconced behind Kidd
and Kevin Johnson in Phoenix, the 6-foot-3 guard was depicted by
Nellie as an immediate franchise cornerstone.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us might depict him, however, as more like a Mike
Iuzzulino Starter Kit.
</P>
<P>
   But Nelson made it sound as if the price _ extravagant though it
was _ was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of teams were offering a great deal for him,'' Nelson
explained. ``We feel very lucky to get him for what we did. He's a
very fine player.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Nelson's son, Donnie, knows Nash well from their days
together in Phoenix. But let's roll the calendar ahead to next
year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   The habitual 20-win Mavericks could very well be in the lottery
hunt again. And the playoff-likely Suns would get the first pick.
</P>
<P>
   Nellie, of course, had an answer for that _ ``We evaluated the
draft for next year, and we don't think it's a good draft.''
</P>
<P>
   Good grief. There isn't going to be one player in the country
who could help this awful team?
</P>
<P>
   ``The talent level is depleted,'' Nellie said, pointing to the
growing number of early defections.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, next year is ``our free-agent year.'' This
year was for draft choices.
</P>
<P>
   Oh. And for a few minutes there, we thought it was the Year of
the Cow.
</P>
<P>
   For more than an hour, the ample posterior of Michigan's Robert
Traylor was parked next to the Mavericks' name on the NBA draft
board. The ruse puzzled folks. Traylor _ no pun intended _ would
not have been a good fit.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's fondness, as well as his son Donnie's, for German-born
Dirk Nowitzki was predictable. Assistant coach Donnie knows the
international talent pool as well as anyone in an NBA front office.
</P>
<P>
   But the 20-year-old's own coach in Germany has said that there's
no way that Nowitzki will play in America until after the 2000
Olympics. And though Nellie stubbornly thinks he can change that,
what if he doesn't?
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks passed on the opportunity to draft Kansas forward
Paul Pierce and guard Larry Hughes of Saint Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Both likely could have made an immediate impact. If nothing
else, either could have been a living, breathing, uniform-wearing
reminder that the franchise does have a future.
</P>
<P>
   Future? That remains a vague and fuzzy concept around Reunion
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   When he Roto-Rootered the franchise with the trade with New
Jersey two seasons ago, Nelson said he was pleased because the
franchise cornerstone was now in place. He was referring to his new
point guard and center, respectively, Robert Pack and Shawn
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   (Insert winces here).
</P>
<P>
   The latest cornerstone, alas, is now Nash. And talented, young
Michael Finley. And a kid from Germany to arrive later?
</P>
<P>
   That's going to sell tickets?
</P>
<P>
   Nellie, of course, gets paid whether you go to the games or not.
He and son Donnie, literally, have the deal of the century.
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked about whether Mavericks fans should be
excited, Nelson answered, curiously, ``You know, it doesn't matter.
They can be skeptical. But it'll all prove out.''
</P>
<P>
   Patiences are wearing satin-thin. But Nelson, who himself has
been here less than 18 months, seems to think Mavericks fans will
be patient.
</P>
<P>
   He wheels. He deals. He winks.
</P>
<P>
   And at the same time, behind the curtains, he pulls the levers
and delights in the sleight of hand. The franchise's Wizard of
Arrrghs.
</P>
<P>
   No. Sooner or later, that won't sell tickets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
