<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5915 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-DRAFT-T     06-25 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-DRAFT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADES BRING NOWITZKI, NASH TO MAVS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Tuesday, Mavericks general manager Don Nelson called
trading the sixth pick in the NBA draft for Nos. 9 and 19 ``the
dumbest thing I've ever heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Last night, he might have set a new standard.
</P>
<P>
   With potential All-Star Paul Pierce having inexplicably fallen
in his lap at No. 6, Nelson instead pulled the trigger on a
three-team trade that left the Mavericks with Phoenix Suns
third-team point guard Steve Nash, the rights to German
``wunderkind'' Dirk Nowitzki and without a No. 1 pick in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas picked up Mississippi small forward Ansu Sesay with the
first pick in the second round, 30th overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we were tempted to do we got done; it worked like
clockwork,'' said Nelson, who negotiated the complicated deal with
the Milwaukee Bucks and the Suns. ``Nash is the point guard we've
wanted for a long time, and we're hopeful of changing Dirk's mind
and getting him to sign with us right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks first swapped first-round picks with the Bucks,
acquiring Milwaukee's ninth and 19th selections and taking Michigan
forward Robert Traylor for them at No. 6. With the ninth selection,
they took Nowitzki. Then at 19, they drafted Notre Dame's Pat
Garrity and sent him to the Suns along with Bubba Wells, Martin
Muursepp and next season's unconditional No. 1 draft choice in
exchange for Nash.
</P>
<P>
   Despite admitting the success of the night's dealings depended
heavily upon signing Nowitzki now and making the playoffs next
season, Nelson had little sympathy for fans who had sought
immediate help for their perennial loser.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if the fans are excited; they can be
skeptical if they want to,'' Nelson said. ``To me, we took a major
step.''
</P>
<P>
   While freeing salary-cap space after getting rid of Wells and
Muursepp appears to be a plus, surrendering what could turn out to
be a '99 lottery pick is a scary proposition for a team that won 20
games last season and has missed the playoffs a league-high eight
consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to part with No. 1s like that,'' Nelson admitted.
``But we evaluated next year's draft, and I don't like it much.
Plus, we plan on that pick not being very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Relinquishing an unprotected pick backfired on the Mavs in '96,
when they gave their No. 1 to the Celtics in exchange for Eric
Montross. Nelson traded the ineffective Montross at midseason, the
Mavericks finished in the lottery and Boston wound up selecting Ron
Mercer with the sixth pick in last year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   While Nash is expected to be the team's starting point guard,
the key to the deal and the draft is Nowitzki, a 6-foot-11 small
forward who has told NBA teams he won't play in America until
competing for his country in the 2000 Olympics. Nelson and
assistant coach Donnie Nelson left for Germany this morning, where
they are scheduled to hook up with owner Ross Perot Jr. to try to
persuade Nowitzki to come to the NBA now.
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki's agent, Holger Geschwinder, said Tuesday NBA teams
would be ``wasting'' their picks on Nowitzki, who scored 33 points
and grabbed 14 rebounds in his only U.S. appearance, in a high
school all-star game in San Antonio coached by Donnie Nelson. With
their financial allotment from the ninth pick, the Mavericks can
offer Nowitzki a contract of about $1.3 million. Geschwinder said
his player has offers on the table of $2 million tax-free from
teams in Italy and Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shouldn't be optimistic, but this is a special situation,''
said Nelson, who called Nowitzki and Geschwinder immediately after
the selection. ``They told us he wouldn't sign \Rin Europe\S, that
they would at least show us that respect. I'm just hoping, really.
But he's a major player with incredible skills. If we don't get him
now, he's worth the wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of keeping next year's No. 1 pick and drafting Pierce to
fill a desperate need at small forward, the Mavericks are left with
a point guard who couldn't find playoff playing time behind Jason
Kidd or Kevin Johnson in Phoenix and the possibility of waiting at
least two years for Nowitzki. In order to persuade Nowitzki to
leave Europe, the Mavericks must also clear the hurdle of the
looming lockout scheduled to cease league operations July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pierce was my second-favorite player in the draft,'' Nelson
said. ``I just think Nowitzki is going to be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Nash, 24, was the 15th overall pick by Phoenix in the '96 draft.
The 6-foot-3, 195-pounder averaged 9.1 points and 3.4 assists per
game in 21.9 minutes last season. He finished 13th in the NBA in
3-point shooting at 41 percent. Despite the fact Nash rarely played
in Phoenix' first-round playoff loss to San Antonio, Nelson said
the two players and first-round pick was a bargain price.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a hot commodity,'' he said of Nash, entering the last
year of a three-year deal paying him approximately $1 million.
``We're lucky to get him for what we did. He's one of the top point
guards in the league, probably in the 10-15 range. He needs his own
team, and he'll be here for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki, who turned 20 last week, is considered the best German
prospect since Detlef Schrempf, drafted in the first round by
Dallas in 1985 before becoming an All-Star in Seattle. Nowitzki,
offered scholarships from Cal and Kentucky, averaged 17.5 points in
20 games for DJK Wurzburg of the German League last season.
 &LR; tagtop:Richie Whitt (817) 390-7760
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
