<HEADER>
A5916 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-DIAMONDBA     06-25 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-DIAMONDBACKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCLEMORE DOES IT ALL FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Rangers regained the services of second baseman
Mark McLemore on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He provided a catalyst for their offense.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore, who entered the game last night with the third-best
on-base percentage (.426) in the American League, scored all of the
Rangers' runs in a 3-2 victory against the Arizona Diamondbacks
last night at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore's one-out, eighth-inning single off Diamondbacks
right-hander Willie Blair gave right fielder Juan Gonzalez an
opportunity to drive in the potential game-winning run.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez met the challenge, sending a 1-1 pitch from Blair
(2-11) deep into center field, where it glanced off an overhang for
what proved to be the game-winning, run-scoring triple.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Rick Helling (11-3) joined teammate Aaron Sele
(11-4) as the only other 11-game winner in the major leagues by
surrendering two runs (one earned) on five hits and three walks in
7 1/3 innings. John Wetteland pitched a scoreless ninth for his
21st save.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's leading the world in RBI,'' McLemore said of Gonzalez,
``so somebody's got to be on base for him. It just happened that it
was me tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   McLemore was a catalyst for the Rangers' offense the first 10
weeks of the season before being sidelined for two weeks by a
muscle pull in his left hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Yet McLemore, who was reinstated Monday from the 15-day disabled
list, showed for the second consecutive evening that he remains a
force with which to be reckoned. His return became more important
with leadoff hitter Tom Goodwin mired in a 7-for-49 slump.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore played a significant role in the Rangers' first two
runs, giving Helling an early, two-run advantage with which to
work. McLemore's one-out, first-inning single resulted in the first
run.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Rusty Greer drew the walk that advanced McLemore
into scoring position, and Gonzalez delivered a run-scoring single
off Blair for the 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore did the job by himself in the third inning. His fourth
home run this season _ a one-out, solo shot off Blair on a 3-2
pitch _ gave the Rangers a 2-0 lead in the third inning. McLemore
claimed that the 0-2 pitch in that at-bat glanced off his helmet.
But there was no call. ``I said, `Forget it and let's go.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks, though, matched the Rangers with a two-run
fifth inning. Helling surrendered a one-out single to Blair, who
snapped an 0-for-24 streak at the plate. Blair advanced to third on
the ensuing double by second baseman Andy Fox, setting the stage
for the bizarre play that created the tie.
</P>
<P>
   Helling, who entered the fifth having surrendered only three
singles and walk, recorded a much-needed strikeout of center
fielder Devon White with runners at second and third base.
</P>
<P>
   However, catcher Ivan Rodriguez failed to smother the curveball
that Helling bounced in the dirt. Blair scored on the wild pitch,
but Rodriguez's errant throw got away from Helling. Rodriguez's
second error this season allowed Fox to score from second, and
White _ with first base unoccupied _ raced to second base on the
play.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, though, helped prevent the Diamondbacks from taking a
lead by retiring White on an attempted one-out steal of third base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
