<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5917 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-ORIOLES-NYT &LR;      06-25 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS 6, ORIOLES 3 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rick Reed won another game Wednesday night, which
isn't big news considering how well he has pitched the last two
seasons. This time, he beat Baltimore, 6-3, at Shea Stadium,
allowing only one run over seven innings as he improved his season
record to 9-4 and lowered his earned run average to 2.31.
</P>
<P>
   In a game that marked the first time the Orioles have played at
Shea Stadium since the 1969 World Series, Reed was the star of the
show, with Brian McRae and Mike Piazza helping out with home runs
and John Franco picking up another save in the ninth inning. For
Reed, it was just more evidence that he has developed into one of
the best pitchers in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it appears he may not even be an All-Star for the first
time, which would be just another setback for Reed, who bounced
around five organizations over a decade and even became a
replacement player during the baseball strike of 1994-95 before
finding a new life with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Reed is timing. He is scheduled to pitch on
Sunday, July 5, the last day before the All-Star Game break. And
according to Mets Manager Bobby Valentine, ``it has already been
announced that anybody who pitches on the last day of the first
half doesn't make the All-Star team.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Florida Manager Jim Leyland, who will choose the
National League's pitching staff, has not officially announced that
that will be his strategy.
</P>
<P>
   But that is the way Leyland is believed to be leaning, perhaps
because he will only choose 10 pitchers and any starter who pitches
two days before the All-Star Game is usually not available to pitch
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   And when asked if he would shuffle his rotation so that Reed
will not have to pitch on July 5, Valentine, whose team is fighting
for a post-season berth, said: ``Nope. The weather might. But I
won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Should Reed indeed be overlooked by Leyland, who managed him
earlier in his career, his response is certain to be of the ``Aw,
shucks'' variety. Earlier this season, Reed said he needs the three
days off to go house hunting just outside of his native Huntington,
W.Va., anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But Reed _ who will probably use the three days off to do a
little hunting and fishing, too _ has also admitted he could easily
look for another house some other time
</P>
<P>
   Entering last night, Reed was tied for third in the league in
e.r.a. He allowed a first-inning run after hitting Eric Davis in
the elbow with a pitch (Davis left the game three innings later)
and then allowing a Rafael Palmeiro double and a Roberto Alomar
run-scoring groundout.
</P>
<P>
   McRae tied the score with a one-out homer off former Met
right-hander Pete Smith (0-2) in the second. McRae then preserved
the tie by throwing Chris Hoiles out at the plate as he tried to
score from second on a two-out Mike Bordick single.
</P>
<P>
   Reed pumped his fist behind home plate as Piazza tagged Bordick
out. Then the former journeyman pitcher, who allowed nine hits in
all, sparked his own game-winning rally with a one-out single off
Smith in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it was a comedy of errors _ and wild pitches. The
Mets ended up scoring four runs in the inning, all earned, to make
it a 5-1 game, on: four singles, three wild pitches (one by Smith,
two by Norm Charlton on two-strike counts), one Smith throwing
error and a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza added a little emphasis by crushing his 13th home run of
the season to the back of the bleachers in left.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Pulsipher came on in the eighth to a nice ovation in his
first stint at Shea since 1995. But after pitching well in
Baltimore two nights earlier, Pulsipher allowed three hits,
including a two-run B.J. Surhoff home run, before Mel Rojas, of all
people, came on to bail Pulsipher out of the jam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
