<HEADER>
A5931 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-astroslede-HNS &LR;      06-25 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-astros </SLUG>
 lede-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Floodgates open 
on Astros error
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rockies come back for 8-6 win
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DENVER _ The Comeback Kids got a dose of their own medicine, and it
was not an easy pill to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros blew a six-run lead as their Coors Field jinx
continued Wednesday night in a demoralizing 8-6 loss to the
Colorado Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst for the Rockies' comeback was a freakish
third-inning play on which first baseball Jeff Bagwell lost a throw
from shortstop Ricky Gutierrez in the sun. Instead of a 1-2-3
inning for Astros starter Sean Bergman, the error opened the door
for the Rockies to score five of their eight runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play is not why we lost the game,'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker said. ``We had six more innings to keep scoring. As a
pitcher, you can't give up four or five hits just because a guy
makes an error. You have to play the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one play doesn't make a game; but things fell apart for
Bergman and the Astros during the wacky fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed,'' Bergman said. ``Any time the team
gives you a six-run lead, we should win the game. It's my fault
that we lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the blame also should go to the Astros' offense, which
shut down after the third inning. Coors Field may be a
hitter-friendly environment for most clubs, but the Astros haven't
exactly burned out any bulbs on the scoreboard. They were held to
six hits Wednesday, with five of their runs coming on a pair of
home runs by Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' all-time record in Denver dropped to 6-22, including
a 1-3 mark this season. They have averaged 4.6 runs in the three
losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things tend to go in cycles in baseball, and we're in a bad
cycle when it comes to this place,'' Astros second baseman Craig
Biggio said. ``There's nothing you can do about it except keep
coming out here and trying to win a ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   In typical Coors Field fashion, at least one of the starting
pitchers was gone in a hurry, and a parade of relievers beat a path
from the bullpen to the mound. Wednesday, it was Bergman who got an
early hook, lasting 4 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman surrendered nine hits and seven runs, but five of them
were unearned as a result of Bagwell's error. Four of the Rockies'
nine hits against Bergman went for extra bases, including two home
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean didn't make too many good pitches after the third
inning,'' Dierker said. ``This game was a little bit about a
pitcher not being strong enough to get through (a bad inning) and a
little about our offense not scoring enough runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the way the game began, Rockies starter Pedro Astacio
seemed like a good candidate for an early shower. He allowed six
runs on four hits in the first three innings but settled down to an
almost unhittable level over the next five innings. Astacio retired
15 of the last 16 batters he faced and allowed one hit after the
third inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro was a different guy after we got those five runs for
him,'' Rockies manager Don Baylor said. ``He said, `I'm back in the
game. Now, I'd better do some pitching.' He really stepped it up
after that. Earlier in the game, he wasn't himself. Bagwell had
taken him out of his game.''
</P>
<P>
   The first of Bagwell's home runs was a 431-foot blast into the
left-field seats that gave the Astros a 3-0 lead in the first
inning. It also was the 200th homer of Bagwell's career. Homer No.
14 of the season was a two-run shot to straightaway center field to
put the visitors up by six runs in the third. Derek Bell had
singled home Bill Spiers one batter earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies, with some help from the setting sun, erased most of
the Astros' lead in the bottom of third. Astacio led off the inning
with a harmless grounder to short but ended up on second base after
Bagwell lost a battle with the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman retired the next two batters and would have been out of
the inning if not for Bagwell's misfortune. The Rockies took
advantage of the opportunity, scoring five runs on just three hits
in the inning. The big blow was delivered by rookie first baseman
Todd Helton, who unloaded for a three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Dante Bichette's solo homer tied the game in the fifth, and the
Rockies took their first lead when Vinny Castilla tripled off the
center-field wall and scored on Ellis Burks' grounder to short.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Rockies' biggest comeback since they overcame a
seven-run deficit against the Padres on July 12, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Wednesday marked the second time Bagwell had lost a
ball in the glare of the sun at Coors Field. It also happened in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that,'' he said. ``We lost that game, too. They
were supposed to be putting some kind of screen up there to prevent
that, but I guess they didn't. That's not why we lost the game; we
obviously didn't score enough runs to win here. You also have to
give Pedro credit for shutting us down the way he did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
