<HEADER>
A5932 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-BRAVES-NYT &LR;      06-25 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 YANKEES defeat braves, 10-6  
(sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The heat index soared above 100 degrees here on
Tomahawk Spirit Day, and Turner Field patrons fanned themselves
with their red tomahawks, rather than taunt the Yankees with them.
These were less than ideal conditions for pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   But while Atlanta's Kevin Millwood wilted, David Cone of the
Yankees found a way to get through. With sweat filling the hollow
below his Adam's apple, Cone collected the first run batted in by a
Yankees pitcher in 26 years and allowed three runs in seven
innings, beating Atlanta, 10-6, on Wednesday night. ``I like the
heat and humidity,'' the 35-year-old Cone said. ``Old guys can get
loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone became the third pitcher in the American League to win 10
games this season, joining Aaron Sele (11) and Rick Helling (10) of
the Texas Rangers, and bolstered his chances to win a spot as an
American League All-Star. The Yankees (52-19) and Braves (51-27)
will complete their four-game series Thursday, when David Wells
(9-2) throws against Denny Neagle (8-5).
</P>
<P>
   It was so hot in Atlanta that cabdrivers waited for their next
fare with engines running and air conditioners churning. Seen from
a distance, the city's tallest buildings appeared to ripple through
heat waves. Pitching in the heat, Yankees Manager Joe Torre said,
requires much determination and some experience. You have to ignore
the heat, understand that it can be a factor and adjust
accordingly, but determine it won't bother you.
</P>
<P>
   Cone learned about pitching in the heat long ago, throwing in
the blistering Missouri summers. ``I'd rather pitch in heat than
the cold,'' said Cone, who sometimes loses the feel of his breaking
ball when the temperature dips below 50 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   With a chance to become the fourth 10-game winner in the
National League, Millwood, a rookie right-hander, shut out the
Yankees in the first two innings; Cone allowed a run in the first,
on Ozzie Guillen's leadoff home run, and another in the second. And
yet Cone really held the advantage, in the sweltering conditions,
for Millwood had over-extended himself.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood threw 47 pitches in the first two innings, and reached
six three-ball counts the first time through the Yankees' lineup.
``He had a lot of 3-2 counts,'' said Tino Martinez, who was dropped
to the No. 5 spot and had two hits and two rbi for the Yankees.
``We knew eventually we were going to get to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood threw 25 pitches to get through the third inning,
allowing his first run. His fastball, consistently 94 miles an hour
in the first inning, was down to 90 to 91 mph His meter was
running, and fast.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Curtis, the Yankees' center fielder, opened the fourth
inning with an intense seven-pitch at-bat, and walked; the last
pitch thrown to him was an 87 mph fastball. It appeared Millwood
was just about out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wore myself down,'' Millwood said, ``because I didn't throw
strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   As Curtis strolled to first, two infielders went to the mound,
attempting to give Millwood a chance to regain his strength. Scott
Brosius lined a hit-and-run single, Curtis stopping at third, and
with Joe Girardi batting, Millwood flopped a slider out of the
strike zone. Leo Mazzone, the Braves' pitching coach, slowly went
to the mound and, in a deliberate manner, discussed the
circumstances. Baseball rope-a-dope: the Braves were trying to get
their fighter through this one round.
</P>
<P>
   But on the fifth pitch of his at-bat, Girardi slammed a fastball
to right-center field, beyond the considerable range of Atlanta
center fielder Andruw Jones. Curtis scored to tie the games,
Brosius stopped at third and Girardi had a double. Cone dumped a
grounder to the right of Ryan Klesko, who was playing first base
only because Andres Galarraga came up with a sore back. Klesko,
left-handed, gloved the ball with his right hand, and when he saw
Brosius chugging homeward, he turned his body 180 degrees and threw
home, high, with no chance of getting Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez, the Braves' catcher, then threw to first, attempting
to get Cone, and the ball bounced down the right-field line. Cone
ended up on second, bent over and testing his ankle. Giradi came
home, and the Yankees led, 4-2. Cone's rbi was the first by a
Yankee pitcher since Lindy McDaniel homered off Mickey Lolich on
Sept. 28, 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter's single scored Cone and finished Millwood, who had
thrown 93 pitches in his three and a third innings.
</P>
<P>
   Cone had found his control by then, and he whipped through the
middle innings, retiring nine straight batters on one run. He had
thrown only 99 pitches when Torre relieved him after the seventh;
he had struck out seven, allowing five hits and no walks. The
Yankees scored five more runs in the late innings, before a poor
performance by reliever Mike Stanton sullied the score a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Cone was still flushed after the game, his face damp with sweat.
But he cheerfully talked about his prospects of making the All-Star
team, a remarkable comeback considering his shoulder surgery last
fall and the fact he allowed 16 earned runs in his first two starts
this year; he has a 2.98 earned run average since then. The old guy
is on the loose. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 0141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
