<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARIZONA-DRAFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICKERSON'S STOCK RISES WHILE SIMON'S FALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It is an odd twist of fate for an Arizona Wildcat, but
Michael Dickerson's accomplishments at Arizona State's Activity
Center probably catapulted him to the 14th overall pick in
Wednesday's NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the 6-foot-5 forward wowed the Houston Rockets, who
took him with the first of their three first-round selections.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to excel like he did against the competition that
was there, it made a difference,'' said Houston Coach Rudy
Tomjanovich of the recent Desert Classic pre-draft camp. ``We feel
lucky he was still around.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson was one of three Arizona players selected. Guard Mike
Bibby went to Vancouver with the second overall pick, and guard
Miles Simon landed with Orlando in the second round, the 42nd pick
overall.
</P>
<P>
   Two players considered on the bubble _ Arizona's Bennett Davison
and ASU's Jeremy Veal _ were not drafted but could sign free-agent
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson goes to a team in desperate need of athletes at the
swing positions, with Clyde Drexler retiring and Mario Elie likely
moving on through free agency.
</P>
<P>
   And the Rockets have been looking for someone who could create
his own shot ever since Sam Cassell left. They get that in
Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting to go to a team like Houston because they're
definitely looking for players to fill holes,'' he said. ``I
believe if I work hard, there will be a place for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson finished his career as Arizona's fifth-all-time
leading scorer and averaged more than 18 points his last two
seasons. He can score from the outside as well as drive to the
basket. Many scouts believed his defensive skills were underrated.
</P>
<P>
   His struggles in the last two NCAA Tournaments raised some
eyebrows, although some observers, like Suns player personnel
director Dick Van Arsdale, believe his scoring problems were more a
product of the energy he was required to expend on defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets acquired two of their three first-round picks by
trading Kevin Willis to Toronto. They also took Valparaiso guard
Bryce Drew and Mursdad Turkcan of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised to see that we got the top three guys on
our wish list,'' Tomjanovich said. ``We got all-around players,
winners who will complement Hakeem (Olajuwon) and Charles (Barkley)
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Dickerson, Simon expected to get drafted, but opinions
differed on where he would land.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting guard can score from a variety of spots on the
court, which is good news for the Magic, which was the third-worst
offensive team in the NBA last season. Part of that was due to the
63 games that Anfernee ``Penny'' Hardaway missed, but even with him
in the lineup, the Magic felt it had no ``second option'' in case
the first was having a bad night.
</P>
<P>
   Some, including Simon's father, Walt, who played in the American
Basketball Association, believe Miles should have made himself
eligible for the 1997 draft after leading Arizona to the NCAA title
and being named the Most Valuable Player of the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with the decision I made,'' Simon said. ``Even if I
had come out, I would have had to go through the same questions.
This way, I had one more year of college and maturity behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Orlando General Manager John Gabriel: ``He impressed us on
and off the court. He'll be a nice fit here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 0143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
