r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-SUNS-AZR &LR;      06-25 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-SUNS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS DEAL NASH IN BUSY DRAFT DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Suns met one expectation among many Wednesday, but
will have to wait and see whether others can be fulfilled with a
draft-day trade of Steve Nash to the Dallas Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns acquired 6-foot-9 forward Patrick Garrity of Notre
Dame, a 1999 first-round draft pick and two Dallas forwards, Bubba
Wells and Martin Muursepp.
</P>
<P>
   The trade was announced after several possible deals for Nash
apparently fell apart during the earoly rounds of the four-hour
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Nash, a Canadian and a reserve playmaker for the last two years,
had drawn interest from Toronto and Vancouver, which is near his
home in Victoria, B.C.
</P>
<P>
   But the Canadian teams were not willing to give up a high pick
for Nash, who was seen as a possible way to halt sliding ticket
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver kept it's No. 2 pick, which it used to take playmaker
Mike Bibby, an unproven playmaker from Shadow Mountain High and
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto kept its No. 4 pick, which it used to acquire North
Carolina swingman Vince Carter in a draft-day deal with Golden
State.
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors picked Carter at No. 5 and traded him to Toronto
for Carter's North Carolina teammate, forward Antawn Jamison, and
cash. According to NBA sources, the Suns had an interest in Carter,
considered the best athlete in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Suns General Manager Bryan Colangelo said he never received an
offer that included Carter. Colangelo indicated that some teams
were not willing to complete proposed deals for Nash, despite their
reported interest in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say people overestimated his value when it came
to making a deal,'' said Colangelo, who also acquired UCLA shooting
guard Toby Bailey from the Los Angeles Lakers for ``future
considerations.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey was the Lakers' second-round pick, 45th overall.
</P>
<P>
   In large part, the Suns probably had no choice but to trade
Nash, the No. 15 pick in the 1996 draft. In meetings during the
last month, he and his agent, Bill Duffy, indicated that he wanted
a larger role.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted starter's minutes,'' Colangelo said. ``He wanted to
run his own team.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said money was never mentioned in meetings that
included talk about a contract extension for Nash, who has one year
left on his current deal.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Suns general manager did say that starter's minutes
meant starter's money. Translation: $8 million a year. That's more
than the Suns were willing to pay a playmaker, who figured to be
the back-up to Jason Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal fell short of expectations, it was not expressed by
Suns coach Danny Ainge, who was probably Nash's biggest booster
throughout last season. Ainge applauded the trade. He said Garrity
had been projected to go be ahigher pick than No. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee picked Garrity with the 19th and German forward Dirk
Nowitzki with the ninth. The Bucks then traded both of them to
Dallas for Michigan forward Robert Traylor, who was picked No. 6 by
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks than completed the three-way-deal by sending
Garrity, Wells, Muursepp and the 1999 pick to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value for a giy who had been a thrid and fourth guard is
incredible,'' said Ainge, who figures Garrity's initial role will
probably be as a small forward. ``Remember that Steve was a No. 15
pick.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge said he liked Garrity for his toughness, shooting,
versatility and smarts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of see him as another Steve Nash in a forward's body,''
Ainge said of the Momnument, Colo., native, who played at Notre
Dame for John MacLeod, a former Suns coach.
</P>
<P>
   Nash was not available for comment. The schoolboy soccer star
was in Europe for the Wolrd Cup. However, his parent, Jean and Pat,
were in ancouver, where the draft was staged.
</P>
<P>
   His parents said before the draft that they had heard that their
son was probably headed for Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, all the wheeling-and-dealing seemed to both amuse and
surprise Garrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's cool,'' he said from Vancouver. ``But it's bizarre _ a
three-way trade. I'm dumbfounded. That's awesome. I'll never forget
this night.
</P>
<P>
   Garrity said he never had any hint that he might wind up with
the Suns. He never worked out at America West Arena in a pre-draft
visit. He said he never spoke to the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never even talked to them because they didn't have a pick,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   They do now. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
