<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-BIBBY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIBBY VANCOUVER BOUND AS NBA DRAFT'S 2ND PICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER _ Future millionaire Mike Bibby knows what one of his
first investments will be.
</P>
<P>
   He is going to buy an umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   But first Bibby, picked second overall in Wednesday's NBA draft,
has to look in the attic of his mother's Phoenix home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can find one,'' Bibby said. ``There might be one
tucked away at the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby, the former Shadow Mountain High School and Arizona
player, never had much use for umbrella until the Vancouver
Grizzlies chose him. He became the highest UA player and highest
Valley player ever taken.
</P>
<P>
   He thought all along he would be headed to the Los Angeles
Clippers, who had the first pick. But the Clippers decided to take
Pacific center Michael Olowokandi instead of Bibby, a 20-year-old
point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a great lightweight and a great heavyweight,''
Clippers General Manager Elgin Baylor said. ``You always take the
good big man over the good little guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby said he wasn't shocked by the choice. In fact, Olowokandi
said Bibby told him minutes before the draft began that Olowokandi
would go No. 1, ``but I still didn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby's family was the most stunned by the Clippers passing on
him. After all, the Clippers had indicated for several weeks they
would take Bibby, who worked out for no other team.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter, Charlsie, is concerned,'' Bibby's mother,
Virginia, said. ``She's in her senior year (of high school) and
doesn't want to move.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby said his mother will move to Vancouver, where one of the
city's most popular restaurants is The Rainy City Grill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting an umbrella will work,'' his mother said. ``He can
afford one.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's going to another country. That's what Mike was
skeptical about, especially considering his trip (with UA) to
Australia didn't go too well.''
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver General Manager Stu Jackson said he knew Bibby was
surprised by the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the sense he's in a little bit of shock, and we have to
all be a little sensitive to that,'' Jackson said. ``He's a young
man who for a couple of months expected to go Number 1. Then, four
hours prior to the draft, he finds out maybe that wasn't going to
be, and remember that foreign country you studied in grade school.
. .''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby's apprehension ended as soon as the standing-room-only
crowd of 10,000 fans at General Motors Place in Vancouver gave him
a rousing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They greeted me well,'' said Bibby, who left UA after his
sophomore year. ``They made me feel wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a dream of mine to get picked. My heart was beating
so fast, I'm so relieved right now.''
</P>
<P>
   He said all the right things. He didn't mind falling to the
second pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I might use that as motivation,'' Bibby said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had no problem playing for an expansion team.
``They're in the NBA, so that's all that matters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He knows he's joining a team that has been a loser in each of
its three seasons. But he reminded the fans that he's always been
on championship clubs, including winning the state title at Shadow
Mountain and the NCAA crown at UA.
</P>
<P>
   When the draft began, the Grizzlies already had three point
guards. They traded one of them, Antonio Daniels, to San Antonio
later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players will benefit by him (Bibby) being able to get the
ball to the right places,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver Coach Brian Hill said he thinks the Grizzlies are
getting the best player in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a natural point guard, a winner and the perfect
complement to (forward) Shareef Abdur-Rahim and (center) Bryant
Reeves,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   By not going to the Clippers, Bibby also will avoid playing in
the same arena as his estranged father, Southern California Coach
Henry Bibby.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would not have bothered me,'' Bibby's mother said. ``I
don't think it would have bothered Mike, either. But now, we don't
have to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   They do have to deal with going from the dry desert to a rainy
climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to give him some advice,'' said high school teammate
Nick Greene, an Oregon State forward who attended the draft. ``He
should stay inside and shoot. Keep working on his game. He is not
going to want to come out in the weather.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
