A5940 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-MERCURY-COMETS-AZ     06-25 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-COMETS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSON LEARNED: MERCURY HOLDS OF COMETS AFTER BLOWING 11- POINT
LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Mercury promised to learn from its one-point loss
to Charlotte and applied the lesson Wednesday night to the WNBA
champion Houston Comets.
</P>
<P>
   Losing an 11-point lead, as it did against Charlotte, to fall
into another stretch thriller, Phoenix (4-1) executed on the court
and the sidelines in winning, 69-66, at America West Arena. Houston
(5-1) lost for the first time since the 1997 regular-season finale,
leaving no one in the 10-team league undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to screw up this game,'' said Mercury Coach
Cheryl Miller, who accepted blame for the 72-71 loss on Sunday.
``We made some tremendous strides. I'm never a big fan of losing,
but it showed we can learn from it and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Comets went ahead, 62-61, with 2:45 left on a pair of
Sheryl Swoopes free throws, Phoenix responded with a 16-footer by
Jennifer Gillom.
</P>
<P>
   Umeki Webb, even with five fouls, jumped all over league Most
Valuable Player Cynthia Cooper, who heaved a crosscourt pass out of
bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget Pettis inbounded the ball off the back of Cooper's legs,
starting a series that included a missed layup by Gillom, missed
three-pointer by Michele Timms and a rebound by Webb, who scored
for a 65-62 lead with 1:27 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Webb then fouled out, and while Cooper was making both free
throws at 1:06, Miller's assistants were vigorously in her ear,
making sure the bases left open against Charlotte were covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned from that and kept our poise at the end,'' said
Pettis, who had a second consecutive 20-point game.
</P>
<P>
   Gillom's 7-foot fade away over Tina Thompson bumped Phoenix
ahead, 67-64, with 47.5 seconds left. Timms fouled with 39.8 left,
and the Mercury took a timeout to discuss its options before Cooper
hit two more free throws, the last of her game-high 27 points.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix smartly used the 30-second clock to get a 14-footer for
Gillom, which spun out and to Pettis before Houston's Kim Perrot
tipped the ball out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   With 9.5 seconds left, the Comets had to foul. On the second
try, after a 20-second timeout, Andrea Kuklova inbounded to Pettis,
the 1997 league free-throw percentage champion, who was tagged by
Cooper. Pettis made both attempts, leaving the Comets with 7.1
seconds to hit a three-pointer and force overtime.
</P>
<P>
   After a timeout, Swoopes inbounded from half court to Thompson,
whose shot was partially blocked by Toni Foster.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hit a big three-point against us last year and they had
run that play before,'' Foster said. ``She's one of those players
you can't forget about. I was determined she wasn't going to hit
that on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston's big three (Cooper, Swoopes and Thompson) combined for
57 points, a total nearly matched by Pettis, Gillom and Foster
(48).
</P>
<P>
   Cooper and Houston Coach Van Chancellor drew technical fouls for
protesting the officiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to have a rhythm when you're playing rugby,'' Cooper
said. ``I don't think the referees handled themselves in a
professional manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time it (the officiating) has been that blatant
and obvious. Maybe it's because we're the defending champs and they
think we should handle that. It's a shame for women's basketball
that the only way you can get a win is like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury set a defensive tone from the opening tip,
pressuring Houston into an 0-for-4 start from the field. Even when
the Comets busted into 7-2 and 17-11 leads, Phoenix reeled them
back by holding Cooper scoreless for almost 16 minutes and limiting
the big three to 25 combined first-half points.
</P>
<P>
   Down, 18-16, the Mercury staged a 9-0 run that included Gillom's
off balance 7-footer over Thompson and a three-pointer by backup
point guard Kristi Harrower. Phoenix extended the run to 12-2 on a
three-point play by Michelle Griffiths to lead, 28-20, with 3:41
until halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, showing the poise of a champion, ended the half on an
11-3 run. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
