<HEADLINE>
NO ROOM AT THE CUP FOR U.S. SOCCER TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, FRANCE - English hooligans rioted in Marseilles. German
soccer thugs battled police in Lens.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are rampaging in Nantes. No chocolate eclair is safe.
</P>
<P>
   The United States isn't going to win the World Cup, but we have
a real chance to take the sportsmanship trophy. After Germany
blanked us in Paris, we didn't riot. We went shopping. Losing to
Iran was galling, but you didn't see Americans throwing rocks and
bottles and trading punches with the gendarmes.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. soccer fans aren't inclined to riot. Most Americans in
France for the World Cup are preocupied with the daily challenges
that arise unexpectedly in a foreign country. Like spending 20
minutes searching the Renault owner's manual, written in French,
looking for an illustration _ any clue _ that identifies the button
that unlatches the blankety-blank gas cap cover on my rental car.
</P>
<P>
   The language barrier makes simple tasks difficult. In Paris, one
exasperated American wasted the better part of a day walking
aimlessly around the city and inquiring, in his best French,
``Where is the Eiffel Tower?''
</P>
<P>
   Parisians looked at him blankly, or with amusement. Wary mothers
shepherded their children away from the stranger.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to him, the visitor wasn't asking for directions. He was
making a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of ``Where is the Eiffel Tower?'' he announced to
everyone he approached, his voice rising in frustration, ``I ``am''
the Eiffel Tower.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. World Cup team can relate to the misadventure. Our
players are polite, sincere, well meaning. Like summer tourists,
they came to France determined to do everything they could to make
this a fulfilling and memorable experience. Their trip has fallen
well short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years of work, and it's all over in a week,'' U.S. star
Cobi Jones said. That says it all.
</P>
<P>
   Team USA scored one goal in two matches. Today, the Americans
play what for them is an exhibition against Yugoslavia. The
Yugoslavs are pumped. The game means a lot. They desperately want
to finish first in Group F, ahead of Germany. Yugoslavia settled
for a 2-2 draw with the Germans after blowing a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Coach Steve Sampson (who is expected to be fired) will
appeal to his players' competitive spirit and team pride. But even
if the Americans win, and they aren't expected to, they can't
advance to the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Our team hasn't stirred much passion. American soccer fans paint
their faces. They cheer the red, white and blue. But you don't see
impromptu pep rallies or parades. Other citizens of the world
celebrate night and day, marching arm in arm through narrow
cobblestone streets, waving their country's flag. They dance. Sing.
Bang drums. Blow whistles. Toot horns. Stop traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil has advanced to the next round. So has Italy. So has
France. The party atmosphere builds.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans have worked hard, but the talent isn't good enough
to win. So after playing only three matches, as they did eight
years ago in Italy, they will return home as spectators, feeling as
empty as the New York sportswriter who ran to catch a press bus
during the Winter Olympics in Albertville, France.
</P>
<P>
   Breathless, the reporter climbed aboard. His eyes searched the
rows of seats. Every seat was filled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zee boos, eet eez foool?'' he asked the obvious. The writer
couldn't speak a word of French. For some reason, he must have
thought the driver, who spoke no English, could understand him and
sympathize with his plight if he addressed him with a bad accent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zer eez no ruem for ``me''?'' he asked. I recognized the
voice. It was the cartoon skunk, Pepe Le Pew.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, pal. No ruem.
</P>
<P>
   ``C'est la vie''. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. David Casstevens can
be reached at 602-444-8635 or at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
