<HEADLINE>
MOON VALLEY STAR MAKES UA GRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Richard Jefferson crammed correspondence courses,
sacrificed basketball camps for summer school and made himself
academically eligible to play at Arizona next season by finishing
strong in the classroom at Moon Valley High.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, a ``Parade'' and McDonald's All-American who led the
Rockets to the 4A state title last season, said he got four B's and
a C in his final semester, giving him the required grade-point
average in core courses to play as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   There was some doubt whether the 6-foot-7 forward would be
eligible after what he called ``messing up badly'' in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all holding our breath,'' said Art Dye, director of
the Arizona Stars, a club program in which Jefferson played. ``He
did a great job. We all know he's not stupid. He's very bright. He
applied himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson said he attended summer school before his sophomore
year to make up incompleted courses from his first year.
</P>
<P>
   He took correspondence courses throughout his prep career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of hard,'' he said. ``Messing up my freshman year
messed up everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what I was doing the last couple of years. I did what I
had to do. Now I'm just trying to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson is spending the summer working out with a personal
trainer in Phoenix. He said he may spend some time in Tucson in
early July before working as a counselor in the Nike Camp in
Indianapolis, where he emerged as one of the top prep players in
the country last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between my freshman and sophomore years, I didn't play much
basketball because I was going to summer school,'' Jefferson said.
``That hurt me basketballwise. I still think I'm a year behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson scored only two points in the McDonald's All-American
game last spring but said he felt he played one of his more
complete games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played hard. I hit the boards hard. A lot of guys were just
worried about scoring. It's hard for me. I had a great team around
me this year. It's hard to go out there and look out for myself.
I'm used to getting things done off the team atmosphere.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
