<SLUG> BC-GLF-NORMAN-AZ-COURSES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROON GOLF, NORMAN FORM ALLIANCE  
 WILL PERMIT EXPANSION INTO NEW FOREIGN MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Troon Golf, a Scottsdale-based management company, is
jumping into the high seas with Greg Norman and his Great White
Shark Enterprises in a joint venture that also includes
Australia-based Medallist Golf.
</P>
<P>
   The big splash by Troon Golf, which will be announced Friday in
New York, will bring Norman's design skills to Scottsdale and allow
Troon Golf to expand into Asia, Australia and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Troon Golf President Dana Garmany said the formation of the new
company, called Medallist-Troon, includes Macquarie Bank,
Australia's leading property investment institution, which along
with Great White Shark Enterprises forms Medallist Golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``While our partnership with Greg is limited to Asia, Australia
and the Middle East, we will become the preferred management
company for his golf courses in the rest of the world, while
operating from our offices in Scottsdale,'' Garmany said. ``This
arrangement is not an exclusive for either party but will allow us
to further our working relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Garmany also announced that Norman has been retained to design
the new Stonehaven Golf Club in the northeasternmost part of
Scottsdale. The 700- to 900-acre project, which should be approved
sometime in July, is scheduled to open in late 1999. It will be
Norman's first effort in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Garmany said several other projects are under way
internationally, mostly in Asia, where a struggling economy has
opened the door to several courses in dire need of completion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel there is a real opportunity there, and the best part
is that no one in the golf world is bigger in Asia than Greg
Norman,'' Garmany said. ``In fact, he's probably more popular in
Asia than he is in his homeland of Australia, if that's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Garmany said Norman will build the courses, and Troon-Medallist
will manage them with the same ``member-for-a-day'' philosophy
employed by Troon North, the flagship course of Troon Golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we decided to move into the Asian, Australian and Middle
East markets, we felt it prudent to find partners who had expertise
in dealing with local law and custom,'' said Garmany, noting that
those three countries are Medallist strongholds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore, we will operate in North America, South America,
Europe and Africa under Troon Golf, and in Asia, Australia and the
Middle East under the banner of Medallist-Troon.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Stinger of Troon Golf has been named vice president of
operations for Medallist-Troon, with an emphasis on building
contacts in those regions.
</P>
<P>
   Norman has built courses in 12 countries and has five projects
under way in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Troon Golf, which has been in Arizona for the past 10 years,
owns or manages 40 golf courses in four countries and 10 states.
</P>
<P>
   Among Troon Golf's portfolio are such well-known layouts as
Turnberry in Scotland, Innisbrook in Florida, Mission Hills in
California and Castle Pines and Tamarron in Colorado. In Arizona,
it includes Troon North, Legend Trail, Talking Stick and La Paloma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expectations from a golf experience level are just as high
as Greg's expectations are as a player and course designer,''
Garmany said.
</P>
<P>
   Norman is devoting his time to course design and rehabilitation
after undergoing shoulder surgery that has sidelined him for the
rest of the 1998 season. He has won 18 titles on the PGA Tour and
another 60 worldwide, including the 1986 and '93 British Opens.
</P>
<P>
   This might be the perfect fit, as Norman's '86 British Open
victory _ his first major championship _ was played at Turnberry,
which was purchased by Troon Golf late last year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
