<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5946 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-ARIZONA-MOUNT-ORD     06-25 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-MOUNT-ORD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ORD- INARY DESTINATION  
 EASY-ACCESS PEAK OFFERS COOL, SCENIC GETAWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to believe that a 50-mile drive from Phoenix, the vast
majority on pavement, could take you to 7,000 feet and the tall
pine country.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially interesting now that temperatures in the
desert are beginning to soar.
</P>
<P>
   But there stands Mount Ord and its 7,128-foot summit. If you've
driven to Payson on the Beeline Highway (Arizona 87), you must have
seen it. The mighty Four Peaks to the south stand 500 feet higher,
and from the distance are a more prominent landmark. They also
offer a larger area to roam.
</P>
<P>
   But they also are much more difficult to reach, and it takes
considerably more time.
</P>
<P>
   Ord is easy to spot to the east of the highway. It's the one
that looks like a porcupine on top. Besides sporting a U.S. Forest
Service tower for spotting wildfires, the summit also is glutted
with communication towers, some of which look like pieces from the
Starship Enterprise. Come to think of it, perhaps they are.
</P>
<P>
   Access to the mountain can be as difficult as one wants to make
it. Both access points are beyond Sunflower and near the summit of
Slate Creek Pass. For vehicles, at least, one Forest Service access
road is tolerable. The other is more suited for hikers.
</P>
<P>
   It's getting hot at 8:30 a.m. on Monday. Ed Fouts likes it that
way. Fouts, 83, avoids air conditioning as often as possible. He
has his window down, enjoying the weather. The driver isn't so sure
this is the way to go. The vehicle isn't equipped with an air
conditioning compressor for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   But the drive up State Route 87 is pleasant. The new four-lane
sections of the highway make the drive so much more relaxed. At
about mile marker 224, Fouts points out the turnoff to the right.
The turnoff isn't marked, but the path is Forest Road 626. It's the
road used by technicians for the communications systems atop Mount
Ord.
</P>
<P>
   This is a relatively new stretch of road. The original road
farther north (FR 27) takes a shorter path to the summit, but it
also is steeper. It no longer is maintained, and even some
all-terrain-vehicle drivers have tense moments on this trail.
Hikers, however, often park at the bottom and follow this trail
five or so miles to the summit.
</P>
<P>
   The better road isn't at all difficult for a high-clearance
vehicle. Cars, too, can travel this road, but it's rough. To a
point, it is maintained. Erosion has created some areas that need
fill dirt to cover the deeply imbedded rock outcroppings. But
still, an automobile driver willing to go easy can make it. The two
roads join several miles below the summit, and the remainder is
maintained.
</P>
<P>
   The better road is longer than the other. It requires a drive of
eight miles or so to reach a parking area about three-quarters of a
mile below the summit. At that point, a gate closes the road to the
summit to any traffic besides Forest Service personnel or those
service communications facilities at the summit.
</P>
<P>
   The trip toward that parking area is scenic. Fouts, who most
often drives his Jeep on such trips, has an infrequent chance to
look for wildlife. He wants to see a bear, as he has before in this
area. He doesn't this day.
</P>
<P>
   The grass is beginning to turn brown in the dry heat, but bushes
at the lower level still look lush. Once the pines are reached, the
wind blows cool. Fout remarks how strange it is to reach such
comfortable temperatures as heat below become sweltering.
</P>
<P>
   At the parking area, during a pause to eat, Fouts, rather
sheepishly, says he needs to put on a jacket. His companion isn't
cold but is refreshed by the coolness.
</P>
<P>
   Fouts will wait on his companion while the latter hikes to the
summit. The road makes footing good, but the incline causes lung
pains. The road divides again. A sign says the left fork goes to
the fire tower, the other to the electronics area. The left fork is
much steeper. And both forks go to the same area.
</P>
<P>
   This is a beautiful hike, as was the drive into the pines. Some
wildflowers still are blooming, and the large New Mexico locust
bushes along the roadway continue to produce large clusters of
violet blooms. The locusts are considered to be noxious plants
because of the large quantities of water they consume, but their
blooms, now in a declining stage, are beautiful. These plants most
often are found along higher-elevation roadsides where moisture
gathers after rain. They are a native plant to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The summit is even more spectacular than the plants. On one
side, there is a clear view of Roosevelt Lake, Tonto Basin
communities and Four Peaks to the south.
</P>
<P>
   The other side is even better, offering views over the Mazatzal
Mountains of both Horseshoe and Bartlett lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the Forest Service roads, hiking opportunities appear
to be limited. Inclines from the mountain are severe, better suited
for goats than humans.
</P>
<P>
   But for a short day trip that offers plenty in scenery, this one
has a lot to offer. And what a way to escape the heat. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
