<HEADLINE>
AS AN AGENT, LAWTON EXCEEDS EXPECTATIONS  
 REPRESENTS 30 NHL PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's young and aggressive, armed with a mission and an uncanny
resemblance to actor Tom Cruise. Ironically, he's also a hot-shot
sports agent, a role recently portrayed by Cruise in the movie
``Jerry Mcguire''.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I get that a lot,'' Brian Lawton said modestly with an
``aw, shucks'' tone in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there are a few similarities. . . . But I don't think
you'll ever see me in the showers talking to one of my clients like
he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. But chances are you'll be seeing, reading and
hearing an awful lot about Lawton in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The first U.S.-born player ever selected as the first overall
choice in the NHL draft _ Minnesota took him No. 1 in 1983 _ Lawton
is emerging as one of hockey's top representatives since retiring
from the sport only five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Before he walked away, he also spent a couple years in Phoenix
as a key member of the minor league Roadrunners. Little did he know
at the time that someday he and his corporation would be handling
the contracts of nearly 30 NHL stars, including a few who play in
Phoenix for the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much been one steady climb. I haven't stopped to
take a breath yet,'' said Lawton, 33, a part-time Valley resident
who represents Coyotes defensemen Deron Quint and Keith Carney, who
recently decided to change agents. Lawton's new partner, former NHL
goalie Mike Liut, represents Coyotes defenseman Norm Maciver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bizarre. I was extremely anxious when I was getting ready
to retire,'' Lawton said. ``I loved playing, and I never thought
I'd find anything else in life I liked doing as much. But I can
honestly say I enjoy this just as much. Looking back, though, I
curse myself for not enjoying all the free time I had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working 10 times harder now than I ever did.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most hockey agents, Lawton will be extra busy this weekend,
when some of the top prospects he counsels are expected to be
selected in Saturday's NHL entry draft in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's Mike Van Ryan and Colorado College's Paul Manning,
for example, are rated as the 15th- and 38th-best players in the
draft. A recent client, University of Minnesota center Erik
Rasmussen, was chosen by the Buffalo Sabres with the seventh
overall pick in the 1996 draft.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Lawton is moving his way up the charts. He
recently upped his clout by selling his private company, Lawton
Sport, and merging with Advantage International, a firm that
represents sports stars from Steffi Graf to David Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton is director of the company's hockey division.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a funny business,'' said veteran hockey agent Bob Murray
of Boston. ``Agents don't usually talk about other agents. It can
be so cutthroat. But I think Brian has really made an impact since
coming into the business very recently. He's got decent clients,
and from what I can tell, he's doing a decent job.''
</P>
<P>
   He literally landed his first client the day after he retired
from the San Jose Sharks. It was defenseman Tom Kurvers, now a
scout for the Coyotes. Lawton got him a lucrative three-year deal
with the New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best contract I ever signed,'' Kurvers said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton's NHL career never really lived up to all the hype. He
scored 112 goals and 266 points in parts of nine seasons with
Minnesota, the New York Rangers, Hartford, Quebec, Boston and San
Jose. ``The Hockey'' ``News'' labeled him as the worst No. 1 pick
in NHL history.
</P>
<P>
   Players selected behind him that year included Pat LaFontaine
(No. 3), Steve Yzerman (No. 4) and Tom Barrasso (No. 5), not to
mention Cam Neely (No. 9) and Claude Lemieux (No. 26).
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith, who is negotiating with
Lawton on a new pact for Carney, a restricted Group II free agent,
was a teammate of Lawton's that first year in Minnesota. He
remembers the pressure Lawton was under.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came into the NHL straight out of high school, and in
hindsight, he probably should have waited and gone with LaFontaine
to the '84 Olympics,'' Smith said. ``Brian just wasn't a part of
it. We had a new coach in Minnesota, a guy who was coaching to win,
not develop a high school player from Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got traded to Montreal about 10 games into the season, but I
knew it was going to be a tough year for Brian. He was used to
being the star player, and he wasn't getting the ice time.''
</P>
<P>
   Most coaches and general managers now agree there is no sense
trying to rush an 18- or 19-year-old player into the NHL. Usually,
they're just not ready.
</P>
<P>
   That new mentality could be the reason why fewer and fewer high
school players are getting drafted. Since Lawton went No. 1 in '83,
only seven prep stars have been first-round picks. One of the last
was the Coyotes' Keith Tkachuk, the 19th overall pick in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   That year, a total of 57 high school players were drafted. But
the numbers have dropped steadily. In 1995, there were only two. In
1996, there were six. Last year, there were four.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you're 20 or 21, you haven't missed a damn thing in the
NHL,'' Lawton said, noting that Rasmussen and others like him
returned to college after getting drafted rather than rush to the
pros right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong, being 18 and the first American player to
go Number 1 was a big honor for me. But it was the wrong decision
to jump right in. It was devastating.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
