</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DBACKS-RANGERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPLE BY GONZALEZ SINKS D-BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX So much for esthetics. Forget the comforts of home. One
of those cute, little picnic overhangs that jut out in center field
at Bank One Ballpark turned treacherous for the Diamondbacks on
Wednesday, aiding and abetting a 3-2 loss to the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   With two out and Mark McLemore on first base for the Rangers in
the eighth inning, Texas slugger Juan Gonzalez launched a shot to
center off Willie Blair. Devon White went back to the wall and
might have caught the ball, except that it hit the overhang to the
right of the batter's eye and bounced on to the field.
</P>
<P>
   The score had been tied at 2, but no longer. McLemore, who had
three hits, came in with what proved to be the winning run.
Gonzalez, who tripled, now has 93 RBI, tops in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   The play broke up a pitcher's duel between Blair and the
Rangers' Rick Helling. Blair lost his 11th game, most in the
majors, despite giving up just three runs in 7 innings to the big
leagues' highest-scoring team. Helling, who gave up five hits and
one earned run in 7 innings, won his 11th, tying teammate Aaron
Sele for the major league lead.
</P>
<P>
   Helped by a throwing error by relief ace John Wetteland, the
Diamondbacks had a chance in the ninth. But with runners on first
and second and one out, pinch-hitter Mike Robertson fouled out and
another pinch-hitter, Brent Brede, hit into a game-ending force
play.
</P>
<P>
   Helling came in averaging six runs a game in support, and it
looked as if the Rangers would provide him more than that in the
top of the first. McLemore singled with one out and Blair walked
Rusty Greer. That brought up Gonzalez, who seems to have a chance
at Hack Wilson's once-impregnable record of 190 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez promptly singled to score McLemore and make it 1-0.
With runners on first and third and one out, things appeared to be
getting ugly early for Blair. But Blair got Will Clark to hit a
grounder to second baseman Andy Fox, who tagged the base himself
and fired to first for a double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks threatened in the bottom of the inning when
Travis Lee drew a two-out walk and Matt Williams singled. It went
no further because David Dellucci's shot to center field was caught
by Tom Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   Blair gave up a one-out double in the second to Kevin Elster _
who went hitless in the Rangers' 16-5 win over the Diamondbacks on
Tuesday _ without suffering further harm. But in the third,
McLemore, a former Valley resident, re-introduced himself to the
fans in right field by sending a Blair pitch into the seats for a
solo home run and a 2-0 Rangers lead.
</P>
<P>
   Blair escaped a big jam in the fourth _ runners on first and
second with none out _ when Elster hit into a double play and
Fernando Tatis grounded out, and helped himself in the fifth by
picking Goodwin off second base after the speedy Ranger stole his
25th base of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Diamondbacks offered little resistance to
Helling, who had won his last three starts. Helling gave up
harmless singles in the second and third and retired the side in
order in the fourth. Then he and the Rangers were victimized by an
extremely productive strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't Kelly Stinnett's whiff leading off the fifth. It
happened after Blair singled to snap an 0-for-24 skid and Andy Fox
doubled off the wall in right. White swung at a Helling pitch in
the dirt for strike 3, but the ball got past catcher Pudge
Rodriguez. Blair scored from the third and Rodriguez's throw to
Helling covering the plate arrived in the vicinity of Blair's feet
just as he was scoring.
</P>
<P>
   The ball skipped free of the tangled mess, allowing Fox (who
started out on second, remember) to score and tie the game at 2.
White ended up at second base. But on the next pitch, hoping to
catch the Rangers still in a frazzled state, White tried to steal
third and was gunned down by Rodriguez. It wasn't even close.
</P>
<P>
   But the strange stuff wasn't finished. Lee walked with one out
in the bottom of the eighth. Danny Patterson relieved Helling and
was greeted by Williams, who hit a rocket to Tatis at third. Tatis
gloved the ball, but then dropped it. Lee, who had held up, was
forced at second and Williams, who stopped running after Tatis
apparently caught the ball, was out at first. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
