<HEADER>
A5950 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BASEBALL-THE-BOOK     06-25 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-THE-BOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIBLE FOR MANAGERS EXISTS, BUT INTERPRETATIONS VARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It didn't matter whether you were an old-fashioned purist or a
space-aged high-tech baseball fan, just about everyone weighed in
with an opinion concerning one of the most controversial managerial
moves in decades.
</P>
<P>
   When Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter elected to
intentionally walk San Francisco's Barry Bonds with two outs and
the bases loaded in the bottom of the ninth inning, forcing in a
run and putting the tying run at third base, the baseball world
couldn't stop talking about the move for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book I learned from says you play the situations in front
of you,'' St. Louis Manager Tony La Russa said. ``And situations
are constantly changing. All you do is try to be aware of
everything you can in order to pick up an edge here or there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no easy answer to what the book is. Mostly you have
to be able to walk into the clubhouse accepting who beat you.
That's why Buck's move in San Francisco made all the sense in the
world. You can't walk up to an owner or fans or the media saying
you're going by the book and keep losing. You won't have your job
very long.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, nearly a month later, Showalter's move still makes its
way into many conversations. For Showalter and the Diamondbacks,
the unconventional move paid off because the next batter, Brent
Mayne, lined out to right field to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest reason Showalter's gutsy move remains a hot topic is
because Arizona's manager went against everything baseball's
``book'' says you should do.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is no real book. Nothing's ever literally been
written on paper. The book is merely a compilation of baseball
strategies that have been used in the 129 years since professional
baseball began.
</P>
<P>
   After so many years, it's fairly well known which moves work
more than others. It's why a left-handed pitcher is rarely brought
in to face a right-handed batter, or a club should never play its
outfield shallow when leading late in a game.
</P>
<P>
   These are called playing the percentages, which more often than
not will result in winning the countless small battles that take
place during a game.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, going solely by the book also could mean certain
defeat. A manager has to have a feel for his players and who is hot
and who is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't become a prisoner to the percentages or a
computer,'' Showalter said. ``I don't think the human element will
ever be taken out of the game. At least I hope not.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Montreal Manager Felipe Alou, with runners at
second and third, intentionally walked the right-handed hitting
Andre Dawson and allowed his right-handed relief pitcher to face
the left-handed-hitting Derrick May, a move that strictly goes
against the book.
</P>
<P>
   But the move paid off and after the game, a reporter asked Alou
whether he felt lucky since he got away with going against the
book?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Alou answered. ``I went by the book. The book I have
says Andre Dawson has 400 home runs and Derrick May has two. I used
a different book.''
</P>
<P>
   Some managers have been known to stick by the computer printouts
and stay with the percentages at all times, leaving their baseball
instincts out of their managing equation. Most of those managers
wind up fired within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when a manager has the kind of club that needs little
tinkering, he can be accused of not doing enough. Those were the
cases with Cito Gaston during years he won back-to-back World
Series championships with Toronto and with Mike Hargrove, who has
guided the Indians to two of the past three World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the managing you do is not managing,'' Showalter
said. ``People always got on Cito, but he let that team play. Same
thing with Hargrove. You're dealing with humans and there is
day-to-day interaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unfortunate part is that some guys have to establish
themselves as managers before they start gambling. I'd like to
think I gambled my first years but in all honesty, I probably
didn't. If you're always going the orthodox way, you're not always
going to give your club its best chance to win.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
