<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GOMEZ-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS, DODGERS HEAD IN OPPOSITE DIRECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The battle ground is Southern California, and the unthinkable is
slowly happening.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels, who play in Orange County, have lived in the
long shadow cast by their neighbor to the north, the mighty Los
Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   In a span of one month, the Dodgers have managed to detonate two
of the biggest bombs to rock the baseball world in some time,
culminating with the double-firing of Manager  &UR; Bill Russell and
General Manager
 &UR; Fred Claire on Sunday night, the same day former GM  &UR; Al Campanis,
who never had a racist bone in his body, died.
</P>
<P>
   But interim GM  &UR; Tommy Lasorda, one of the least genuine people
ever to wear a major league uniform, started plotting for this day
more than a year ago, when Fox officials first showed serious
interest in buying one of the most storied franchises in all of
sports.
</P>
<P>
   This is a job that Lasorda, who as manager never seemed to take
blame when the Dodgers did poorly but always was ready to take
credit during the good times, has wanted for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda had been whispering into the green Fox folks' ears about
all the changes the Dodgers would need to make their way back to
the top of the heap.
</P>
<P>
   Some within the Dodgers system strongly believe that Lasorda was
the driving force to push Russell and Claire out of the picture.
Back-stabbing is the phrase that comes up most often.
</P>
<P>
   These Dodgers, as talented a collection of players and pitchers
as there is, are even thinking about changing one of the most
famous logos in the game, as well as one of the most traditional
and gorgeous uniforms around.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, the Angels have quietly risen to the top of the
American League West standings, and, amazingly, they are the ones
who now seem to have the model franchise in the greater LA area.
</P>
<P>
   With  &UR; Tim Salmon, Darin Erstad, Garrett Anderson, Jim Edmonds,
Gary
 &UR; DiSarcina and  &UR; Troy Percival, the Angels have built a first-place
club with mostly home-grown talent. The Dodgers, traditionally
known as a club that loved bragging about its farm system, is
heading the other way.
</P>
<P>
   It's shaping up as a battle between media superpowers Fox and
Disney, and the cute little mouse is drawing the raves. &QL; 
The root of it all &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Say one thing for San Diego's  &UR; Kevin Brown: He's one tough dude.
After thinking he was just visiting the dentist for a regular
checkup Tuesday morning, Brown learned he needed root canal
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than waiting another day, when he didn't have to pitch,
Brown elected to have the oral surgery that morning. He then went
out and pitched six innings in leading the Padres to a 7-3 victory
over Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pain was not that bad, but I had no legs under me,'' Brown
said. ``I was tired even before I went out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach  &UR; Dave Stewart said: ``You can't ask for anything
better from a human under the circumstances. I've never seen
that.'' &QL; 
Tabling the former closer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's  &UR; Jose Mesa, who couldn't hold a ninth-inning lead in
Game 7 of last year's World Series, has been booed mercilessly at
Jacobs Field lately. The Indians have lost seven games in the
opponents' last at-bats, and Mesa has been on the mound in four of
those.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not being critical of the fans,'' Cleveland Manager  &UR; Mike
 &UR; Hargrove said. ``But the (fans') reaction to Jose puts him on the
defensive, and that makes it tough for him to pitch that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player, Jose needs to deal with it (the booing) and get
beyond it. I'm not coming down on the fans for booing him, but
we've all got to recognize that it has an effect on Jose's
mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa is available in a trade and  &UR; Mike Jackson remains
Cleveland's closer. &QL; 
Do it right &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once again the geniuses running baseball have managed to bungle
the 1999 schedule. The preliminary, and still somewhat tentative,
schedule for next year has interleague games once again.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that for the third consecutive year, the
divisions will play only among themselves, meaning West vs. West,
Central vs. Central and East vs. East.
</P>
<P>
   The original idea behind interleague play was so fans in every
city would have the opportunity to see players from every club. If
this keep up, the New York Yankees and Boston Red Sox will never
make it to Bank One Ballpark for regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have kind of an advantage in our league. Being in the East,
we get to play the (AL) teams with a lot of history to them,''
Atlanta Manager  &UR; Bobby Cox said. ``Interleague play hasn't been so
great everywhere, but the teams that are in the East, they may draw
a few more people.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
