<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-EMBREE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBREE EMBRACES OPPORTUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - A couple of weeks ago, Alan Embree and his wife,
Melanie, were casually talking in Atlanta and he mentioned that
playing for the Diamondbacks wouldn't be all that bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a rumor that was going around or anything, I was
just thinking I'd get an opportunity to pitch a little more,''
Embree said.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly wasn't a wish _ no one wishes to go from a division
leader to a cellar-dweller _ but his thought came true Tuesday when
the Braves dealt the 28-year-old left-hander to the Diamondbacks
for right-handed reliever Russ Springer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised, but I'm happy to be here,'' Embree said. ``I
knew they were going to make a move, but I thought it would be one
of our right-handers going. I don't have a bad thing to say about
Atlanta. But I'll get my innings here and a chance to show people
how much I've learned.''
</P>
<P>
   When Embree and Kenny Lofton went to the Braves in the deal that
sent David Justice and Marquis Grissom to Cleveland in March of
1997, he said he was a ``confident one-pitch pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd throw one inning, maybe two hitters and throw the fastball
predominantly,'' said Embree, who pitched successfully in four
World Series games for Cleveland in 1995. He also saw postseason
action for Cleveland in '96 and last year with Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Under Braves pitching coach Leo Mazzone, Embree solidified his
slider and learned a change-up. He also said he soaked up
considerable knowledge from the best starting rotation in the game
_ Greg Maddux, John Smoltz, Tom Glavine and Denny Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't learn from those guys, then you're brain-dead,''
he said. ``They're a fountain of information. If you can't pick
their brain and learn something, you're just not trying to be a
pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, Atlanta's starters seldom need help from the
bullpen. After a strong season last year (3-1 with a 2.54 ERA in 66
appearances), he has appeared in only 20 games this year, posting a
1-0 record with a 4.34 ERA in 18 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll get a chance here to show how competitive I can
be,'' Embree said. ``If you go out every day, it keeps you sharp. I
was getting stale just because they had such a strong starting
rotation and because they didn't know which way they wanted to go
in the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter is willing to go with anyone
in the bullpen who can show consistency. It very well could turn
Embree into more than just a situational reliever, although he has
been stingy against left-handed batters, holding them to a .221
average in 137 major league games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been in the fire before and understands the
accountability of a major league relief pitcher's job,'' Showalter
said. ``We didn't get him just because he's left-handed or just to
get out left-handed hitters. We don't have that luxury this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a quality arm. We think it's a step in the right
direction and believe he has a chance to be a big piece of the
puzzle here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
