<HEADLINE>
KLASSEN GETTING HANG OF 2ND BASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The  &UR; Danny Klassen Experiment is a success, and it might only be
a matter of time before the Diamondbacks see the results firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   Klassen is playing second base for the Tucson Sidewinders and is
playing it as if it were his normal position. Until a couple of
weeks ago, he was exclusively a shortstop, although he had logged
practice time at second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny's a great athlete, not just a good athlete _ and I don't
use the word `great' often _ who can do a lot of things,'' said
 &UR; Mel
 &UR; Didier, Diamondbacks director of player development.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we asked him to play center field, he might be one of the
best in the organization. He's picked up second base real well.''
</P>
<P>
   With veteran  &UR; Jay Bell seemingly entrenched at shortstop,
Klassen's immediate future with the Diamondbacks would appear to be
at second base. Then again, there were rumblings that Bell might
eventually be moved to second. Right now, utility man  &UR; Andy Fox is
getting most of the action at second base for the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens, the versatility can't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just increases (Klassen's) value to the organization if he
plays short and second,'' said  &UR; Tommy Jones, director of minor
league operations.
</P>
<P>
   Klassen isn't the only player learning a new position.  &UR; Edwin
Diaz, formerly a second baseman, is playing shortstop and third
base, as is
 &UR; Hanley Frias, who is recovering from hand surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Tucson Manager  &UR; Chris Speier said Klassen's transition is
proceeding smoothly because of athleticism, intelligence and
willingness to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy,'' Speier said.
</P>
<P>
   He should know. Speier was one of the better fielders at
shortstop for many years with the San Francisco Giants before
learning second base later on to prolong his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to pick up things real quickly. It's been easy. You
always need to fine-tune, but for the most part, he's shown he can
make the transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Klassen already had shown marked improvement at shortstop from
last season, when he had a miserable year for the Milwaukee
Brewers' Double-A club in El Paso. But what grabs everyone's
attention is his bat. Klassen hit .331 at El Paso and has shown
little drop-off at Triple-A, batting .304 with nine homers and 40
RBIs through Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly, Milwaukee Brewers owner (and interim commissioner)
 &UR; Bud
 &UR; Selig was ready to choke somebody in his organization when the
Diamondbacks took Klassen with the fifth pick of the second round
of the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has All-Star ability,'' Didier said. ``I've been in this
game for 45 years and I've called a few shots in my lifetime, and
I'm not afraid to say that . . . Klassen is a thoroughbred.'' &QL; 
Brief stints &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frias had 11 stolen bases in only 15 games through Tuesday. He
has been caught just once.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher  &UR; Jeff Suppan, who will pitch for the Diamondbacks on
Friday against Seattle, is 1-1 with a 3.78 ERA for the Sidewinders.
</P>
<P>
   High Desert got off to a fast second-half start in the
California League, winning five of its first six games and four
straight through Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
