<SLUG> BC-BBA-MILLS-TWINS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLS SIGNS CONTRACT WITH TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Arizona State pitcher Ryan Mills wanted to be a
professional baseball player, and he didn't want to spend a lot of
time with the pesky details of contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   He got his wish.
</P>
<P>
   Mills signed a contract Wednesday with the Minnesota Twins and
will report today to the organization's rookie league team in Ft.
Myers, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth overall pick in the amateur draft this month, Mills
received a $2 million signing bonus, according to sources close to
the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talks were positive, and we were able to find a middle
ground quickly,'' said Jeff Moorad, Mills' agent. ``We're very
happy to put the process behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Moorad's dealings with the Twins have not always been congenial.
As the agent for Travis Lee, a Twins draft pick two years ago,
Moorad found a loophole that allowed Lee to become a free agent and
sign with the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Mills was drafted by the New York Yankees out of Horizon High
School but turned down a $575,000 signing bonus to attend ASU.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys spend their whole summer trying to get their
deals done,'' Mills said. ``I'm just excited to get down to Fort
Myers and get my feet wet.''
</P>
<P>
   A junior last season, the left-handed Mills finished with an 8-4
record and a 4.68 ERA. In 115 innings, Mills had 140 strikeouts and
54 walks.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his contract, Mills will attend major league spring
training next year and will donate $7,500 to Horizon's baseball
program, $7,500 to ASU's and $10,000 to a Twins charity in
Minneapolis. He also will receive $30,000 to help him earn his
college degree. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
