A5957 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     06-25 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN EXEL TRADED TO DENVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ The Lakers ended their five-year, sometimes-stormy
relationship with Nick Van Exel on Wednesday, trading the emotional
All-Star to the Denver Nuggets for second-year forward Tony Battie
and the rights to rookie point guard Tyronn Lue.
</P>
<P>
   Van Exel's Lakers career had seen him go from second-round
sleeper in 1993 to bona fide All-Star this season, with an
occasional temper tantrum in between. But a pair of troublesome
knees late this season and a fade in the playoffs, combined with
the emergence of point guard Derek Fisher, made Van Exel
expendable.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, despite a 61-win season, the Lakers were looking to
change the team's chemistry in the wake of being swept in the
conference finals by the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like this are very, very difficult. I really like Nick
Van Exel a lot, but I just think that, for all of us, a change of
scenery would be good for everyone,'' said Jerry West, Lakers
executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a feeling internally sometimes you get, that maybe
the same faces are not always good to have together,'' West said.
``Looking at him, there were times when he didn't look like he was
a very happy player for us. And maybe the pressure of playing,
where we expect a lot of success ... maybe that didn't work for
him. I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Exel and his representatives were not available Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Agent James Bryant told the Daily News last week that Van Exel
wanted input on any trade and that there were some teams he might
refuse to report to. West said there were no indications Van Exel
would hold up the trade.
</P>
<P>
   If that's true, all that remains is for all three players to
pass physical examinations. Van Exel is presumed to be healthy, his
chronically sore left knee notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The trade, consummated at 9 p.m., came after the completion of
the NBA draft and completed an evening in which the Lakers acquired
five players and traded two.
</P>
<P>
   They selected Minnesota swingman Sam Jacobson with the 26th pick
in the first round and grabbed Cincinnati forward Ruben Patterson
and UCLA guard Toby Bailey in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the Lakers dealt Bailey to the Phoenix Suns for
future considerations, then made the long-anticipated Van Exel
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always sad to see one of our guys go,'' said coach Del
Harris, who forged a working relationship with Van Exel despite
some very public spats with him. ``Trading is always a hard thing,
particularly when you've been with a player a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Exel and Elden Campbell have been shopped around the league
for the past month, and the Lakers spent much of Wednesday
attempting various trades to move up and select Florida point guard
Jason Williams. West was disappointed early in the first round when
Sacramento took Williams with the seventh pick, ending the Lakers'
main draft-day pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell and his $7 million contract remain with the Lakers for
now, and West indicated no other changes are likely before July 1,
when the NBA is expected to impose a lockout and freeze all
business until a new labor agreement is reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to gut this team,'' West said, although
additional changes are possible. ``My best guess is this will be it
for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   In Battie, the Lakers get the No. 5 overall pick of 1997, a
promising talent who was later dubbed ``El Busto'' by
commentator-turned-Nuggets general manager Dan Issel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take our chances,'' West said, praising Battie's
shot-blocking and underrated shooting touch. Battie averaged 8.4
points, 1.06 blocked shots and 5.4 rebounds per game as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Lue, rated by some as the third best point guard in the draft,
was taken by Denver with the 23rd pick, three slots before the
Lakers' first-round selection, where they might have drafted him.
</P>
<P>
   The Nebraska product, who averaged 21.2 points and 4.8 assists
as a senior, will back up Fisher, the Lakers' starter for 36 games
and throughout the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kid can really score the ball,'' West said of Lue. ``This
is a real athlete, fellas.''
</P>
<P>
   West is also pleased with first-round choice Jacobson,
Minnesota's fifth all-time scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tremendously athletic kid and really the sort that
grows on you when you see him play,'' West said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
