<HEADER>
A5961 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-LADN     06-25 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS GO WITH CENTER AS TOP PICK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Michael Olowokandi's entire basketball career
spans less than an average NBA season, but the way so many teams
coveted his size and vast potential, it turned out to be too hard
for the Clippers to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   After originally appearing enamored with Arizona point guard
Mike Bibby, the Clippers made the decision practically every other
team in the league endorsed: They selected the 6-foot-11 center
from Pacific as the NBA's top pick Wednesday, despite his thin
resume that included just three years of organized basketball and
77 college games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a great risk in taking him,'' said Elgin Baylor,
the Clippers vice president of basketball operations. ``When he
came in and worked out, it was amazing the improvement that he had
shown from the end of the season to the workout. I was amazed he
did some things ... that I did not see him do in college.''
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi, who was born in Nigeria but grew up in England,
admitted he didn't think until Wednesday that the Clippers would
draft him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing my name in the No.1 spot is unbelievable, especially
when you consider where I came from three years ago _ not having
played basketball _ and then to this, not the No.3 pick but the
No.1 pick,'' Olowokandi said. ``That's something that'll take me a
week or so, or a little bit longer, to get over.''
</P>
<P>
   But once over the shock, he gave his own theory on why the
Clippers bypassed Bibby, who would have solved the need for a
starting point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to give my opinion, I think it would be because
Vancouver got a lot of offers from veteran teams who wanted to
trade up and get me, and (the Clippers) figured they could keep me
and get something better (at point guard) later on,'' Olowokandi
said.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor confirmed as much Wednesday night, when he said the
Clippers hoped to sign one or perhaps two free-agent point guards
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be in a free-agent market to get a point guard,'' Baylor
said. ``We would like to get more maturity on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   With no franchise players available, and little consensus about
who the top 15 players were, the draft contained several surprises.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kansas forward Paul Pierce dropped like a rock to the No.10
spot, after being projected as high as the No.2 pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little disappointing,'' Pierce said. ``That's the way
things go.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Sacramento stunned everyone by selecting Florida point guard
Jason Williams with the seventh pick. Williams was kicked off the
team at Florida and also bounced from Providence and Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   _ The biggest trade involved? Who else but one involving Dallas
coach Don Nelson. The Phoenix Suns sent guard Steve Nash to the
Mavericks in a three-way trade also involving Milwaukee. The Bucks
got the sixth pick, Robert Traylor, from the Mavericks in exchange
for the ninth pick, Dirk Nowitzki of Germany, and the 19th pick,
Pat Garrity of Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Garrity was then shipped to the Suns along with Bubba Wells,
Martin Muursepp and Dallas' 1999 first-round pick for Nash.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any suspense, it came as teams below the Clippers
waited to see if L.A. would play it safe and draft Bibby, or take
the player with the most potential _ Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the expectation I would go to Vancouver,'' Olowokandi
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he began to get a feeling that he would go to the
Clippers last weekend, when they worked him out for a second time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a pretty good indication that they were leaning
toward me,'' Olowokandi said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers denied Wednesday that they worked Olowokandi out
twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers also withstood pressure from agent David Falk to
select Bibby. Falk, who also represents Michael Jordan, met with
owner Donald Sterling on Tuesday to try to convince the Clippers to
draft his client.
</P>
<P>
   According to a source, Falk had also tried to force the Clippers
last week to publically announce that Bibby would be the No.1
choice.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, the first thought was Bibby,'' Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed, however, when Baylor watched Olowokandi work
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the great centers in the league are getting older,''
Baylor said. ``And he is going to be one of the top centers in this
league.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor was also impressed the way Olowokandi scored on
psychological tests.
</P>
<P>
   That should come as no surprise, since he was an exceptional
student at Brunel University in England and Pacific, where he
majored in mechanical engineering.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people (in England) think you have a better chance of
winning the lottery than going to the NBA,'' Olowokandi said.
``This came in a pretty good time in my life and I've reached a
time where I need to be challenged a little bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   Where this leaves the Clippers' free-agent center, Isaac Austin,
remains to be seen. Baylor did not rule out re-signing Austin, but
the chances of that happening appear remote.
</P>
<P>
   With the 22nd pick, the Clippers selected Brian Skinner, a
6-foot-9 forward from Baylor, who averaged 18.1 poits and 9.5
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner said he didn't expect to go to the Clippers, because he
did not work out for them. But Baylor said he wanted to add
toughness and might need a spare forward in case they trade one of
their established forwards this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Baylor said there is no timetable for hiring a head coach.
He did say he has spoken to several candidates. Lakers assistant
coach Kurt Rambis remains a candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
