<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5962 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-25 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS GETTING SERIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In pre-draft interviews, Nigerian-born center
Michael Olowokandi chuckled every time someone mentioned the
Clippers. We took it as incontrovertible proof that the Kandi Man
is a quick learner; only three years of serious schooling in
basketball and already he seemed to understand the NBA's
long-standing joke.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers picked first in Wednesday's stock NBA draft
because, well, somebody had to, and they threw conservatism to the
wind by selecting Olowokandi, whose name is longer than his
basketball resume.
</P>
<P>
   By eschewing the consensus safe choice _ Arizona's 20-year-old
point guard Mike Bibby _ the Clippers showed they're serious about
shedding their image as the league's laughingstock. It was a bold
move inasmuch as the 6-foot-11 player is largely unproven, the
totality of his experience consisting of three seasons and 77 games
at the University of Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers are banking on him eventually becoming as polished
on the court as he is off it. The son of a Nigerian diplomat
stationed in London, Olowokandi has a far-flung perspective and a
genial personality. He'll be an able ambassador for a Clippers team
that long has been as amorphous as Olowokandi's
Nigerian-British-Californian accent.
</P>
<P>
   Long-suffering fans of the Clippers could be forgiven for not
trusting their ears when Olowokandi, speaking from draft
headquarters in Vancouver, B.C., said he was ``tickled to death''
that things worked out the way they did.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years ago, the team's top pick, Danny Ferry, reacted as
though he had been sentenced to death, fleeing to Europe and
playing for a year in Italy rather than setting sail with the
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise's draft history is one in which even the sturdiest
of scenarios have managed to spring leaks. In 1988, the last time
the Clippers owned the No.1 pick, they did the smart thing and
selected forward Danny Manning. He held out and then tore an
anterior cruciate ligament that abruptly cut short his rookie year.
He eventually would beg to be traded, an all-too-familiar story
line in Clipperville.
</P>
<P>
   No matter, said Olowokandi. ``What's happened in the past is
past,'' he said, sounding like someone who's ready to embrace the
franchise with the full force of his 7-foot-6 wingspan.
</P>
<P>
   Now if he can only warm free-agent-to-be forward Ike Austin on
the idea of staying, the Clippers will be blessed with one of the
better frontcourts in the league. Even without Austin it'll be one
of the deepest, with forwards Maurice Taylor, Lorenzen Wright,
Rodney Rogers and Lamond Murray slated to return.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers' backcourt remains in flux. The good news is, with
plenty of money under the salary cap they're free to cast their
line into free-agent waters. Goodness knows it's easier to hook a
solid point guard than a sterling center.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi, 23, was the Big Kahuna of the Big West conference
this past season, blocking 95 shots in 33 games while averaging
22.2 points and 11.2 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   There may have been collegians with more sparkling credentials,
but no one had a more scintillating story than Olowokandi, a long
jumper and triple jumper of national renown in England who decided
to make the leap into basketball three years ago after seeing
``White Men Can't Jump'' in a London movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   A college student in mechanical engineering at the time,
Olowokandi extended his studies to include Basketball 101. He
obtained a copy of Michael Jordan's ``Come Fly With Me'' video and
a copy of Peterson's Guide to American Colleges.
</P>
<P>
   UOP was the first school that jumped out at him from the pages
of the college guide and after a quick transatlantic call to Tigers
assistant coach Tony Marcopulos, he came, he learned, he conquered.
</P>
<P>
   There was quite a bit he had to be taught. Like the rules, for
example. The first time Olowokandi saw a double team, he presumed
it was illegal. It took him a while to discern when he was allowed
only one free throw as opposed to two.
</P>
<P>
   But Olowokandi has a lot on the ball. In addition to the
economics degree he earned in three years from Brunel University in
Middlesex, England, Olowokandi is 12 credits shy of a mechanical
engineering degree at UOP.
</P>
<P>
   In a year where four prospective draft picks barely stayed in
school long enough to collect their high-school diplomas,
Olowokandi's academic history spoke loudly to the player's maturity
and makeup.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanical engineering is on the back burner now as Olowokandi
turns his attention to history. He's making it, not studying it.
</P>
<P>
   Back in his adopted homeland of England, where Olowokandi lived
from the ages of 3 to 20, a World-Cup weary citizenry surely will
turn its sad eyes to him. Alluding to England's disheartening 2-1
loss Monday to Romania in soccer, Olowokandi said, ``They'll
probably need some good news right now. I think people will be
amazed about my being the highest European player picked. It's a
huge compliment.''
</P>
<P>
   Being picked first overall came as a huge surprise to
Olowokandi, who was convinced the Clippers were keen on Bibby.
That's why he laughed off comments about the Clippers in the days
before the draft.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't being crass, as it turned out, just clueless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't understand why (reporters) kept beating on that
issue,'' Olowokandi said. ``I thought I was headed to Vancouver (at
No.2) so I thought the whole (line of questioning) was funny.''
</P>
<P>
   With Olowokandi aboard, the Clippers may enjoy the last laugh
yet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
