<HEADER>
A5972 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-UCLA-DRAFT-LADN     06-25 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-UCLA-DRAFT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH DAY FOR UCLA PLAYERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They arrived at UCLA four years ago as the most
heralded basketball recruiting class in the country. Their
departures were not nearly so memorable.
</P>
<P>
   A week that began with omm'A Givens quitting the Pepperdine team
ended ignominiously Wednesday night when his former UCLA
classmates, J.R. Henderson, Toby Bailey and Kris Johnson, were not
picked in the first round of the NBA Draft.
</P>
<P>
   Jelani McCoy, a junior who left UCLA in February after
reportedly failing multiple drug tests, was the highest Bruin
selected _ going to Seattle with the fourth pick of the second
round (33rd overall).
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, a 6-foot-5 guard, went to the Lakers with the 45th pick
and was promptly traded to Phoenix for future considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, a 6-9 forward, was in danger of not being drafted
until Vancouver rescued him with the 56th pick _ third from the
end.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a 6-3 forward, was not selected and may play in Europe
if he cannot find an NBA employer.
</P>
<P>
   It was a disappointing evening all around for the UCLA players,
one that accentuated their careerlong flaws and inability to
correct them. The same passivity that hampered Henderson, the same
inconsistent shooting that plagued Bailey, the same athletic
shortcomings that shadowed Johnson and the same poor judgment that
unraveled McCoy _ all returned to haunt them on the most important
night of their careers.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy is a 6-9 power forward with superb athletic ability. If
not for his off-court woes and raw offensive skills, he surely
would have been a first-round pick. Unwisely, McCoy spent much of
the spring trying to convince NBA scouts he could play small
forward _ hoisting shots from 15 feet instead of developing a
low-post game.
</P>
<P>
   (McCoy's agent, Arn Tellem, is used to representing troubled
athletes. Latrell Sprewell and Albert Belle are two of his
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   But Seattle seems an ideal spot for McCoy, who interviewed twice
with the Sonics. They have an aging frontline _ forwards Detlef
Schrempf and Sam Perkins are closer to 40 than 30 _ and they are
desperate for young legs to play alongside All-Star center Vin
Baker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turns out it could be a blessing in disguise,'' McCoy said.
``They let me know they were interested. The question was what pick
they'd use, their first-rounder or early in the second round. But
it makes no difference to me if I was the 66th pick, as long as I
have my foot in the door. It's a good chance to play on a
contender.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey learned of his trade moments after being selected by the
Lakers. Whether it's L.A. or Phoenix, however, Bailey must prove he
can make open jumpers _ something he failed to do at the pre-draft
camp in Chicago. His performance there was so poor, in fact,
several teams canceled interviews.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, he'll have a chance to play next to his old friend
and rival, Jason Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Suns coach Danny) Ainge called twice and said he wanted Toby
but they didn't have any draft picks,'' said Bailey's father, John.
``Ainge said he liked Toby's intensity and aggressiveness. He said
he's liked him for years. This worked perfectly. It would have been
great to be a lottery pick, but if you're going in the second round
it's great to go to someone who wants you.''
</P>
<P>
   That was also the theme in Bakersfield, where Henderson watched
anxiously as his stock plummeted. He has the offensive skills
Bailey and McCoy lack, but NBA teams considered him too soft for a
first-round selection. He is finesse incarnate _ a trait scouts saw
in abundance at the Chicago camp, and one that does not fare well
in the NBA low post.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have mixed feelings,'' said Henderson's father, Milt.
``It's a little disappointing he went so late, but we're happy it's
Vancouver, because they really wanted him.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson could not be reached for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
