<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAIRE DISPLAYS NO BITTERNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Fred Claire took the high road Wednesday
afternoon, a road that no longer leads to Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after his firing as the club's executive vice
president and general manager Claire, displayed no bitterness
during a news conference at a Pasadena hotel not far from downtown
L.A.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't rip Peter O'Malley, Rupert Murdoch or even Gene from
Redondo, who used to blast Claire on every talk show from Lancaster
to San Diego. The Daily News has learned Gene was not really Tom
Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   Claire explained his role in the Mike Piazza and Hideo Nomo
deals and the drawn-out nontrade for Randy Johnson. He acknowledged
his mistakes (Pedro Martinez, Eric Davis) and said he even should
have gotten fired after the club's last-place finish in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But what is the legacy of Claire the former sportswriter, who
was O'Malley's first hire in 1969 and his first choice for GM after
Al Campanis self destructed on national television in 1987?
</P>
<P>
   ``I will let others decide that,'' he said, squinting into a
bright sun that was not nearly as hot a last Sunday's meeting at
Dodger Stadium when Claire and manager Bill Russell were canned.
</P>
<P>
   His resume simply reads: Signed Kirk Gibson, GM for 1988 World
Series; signed Darryl Strawberry; hasn't won a postseason game in
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that Fred Claire played a much bigger role in the
shaping of baseball. He was the bridge between where baseball was
and where it is going.
</P>
<P>
   In a way he was the perfect Fox soldier. Sometimes he looked
closer at a player's on-base percentage than his heart.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he was wrong thinking Antonio Osuna would be his closer
for the next 10 years. Actually there is no maybe there.
</P>
<P>
   But he brought Gibson here for that brief shining moment and
there was integrity to his decisions. Years later, Gibson
remembered the day after his Dodgers days turned sour and he
demanded a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little guy almost came over the desk at me,'' Gibson said.
``It was scary. He had a lot fire and I respect that. There were a
lot more there than a lot of people ever got to see. I loved Tommy,
but nobody cared more about the Dodgers than Fred.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Eric Karros agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this game, I never have met anyone who was more of a
straight shooter than Fred Claire. Those people are rare in this
game. He built a confidence in you by telling you the truth. I
asked him last year if I was going to be traded when all that talk
was going around. He told me no, and I'm still here.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Karros who was left unprotected last November
during the expansion draft. Karros said he never asked Claire about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already knew the answer, so there was no need. I didn't like
it, but I understood. He thought it was best for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Claire, the prototype for the job was Campanis, the old
scout molded by Branch Rickey. Campanis was brilliant and even
wrote a book, ``The Dodger Way to Play Baseball.'' Claire has a
good-sized ego but never had the gall to pull off something like
that.
</P>
<P>
   Claire went on the fact-finding scouting missions to the
Caribbean that were more like something out of the Rat Pack. But
Claire did more than sample the seafood.
</P>
<P>
   He learned as much about the fans as he did the players. In
1978, when the Dodgers went over three million in attendance for
the first time, everyone credited Lasorda, who led the Dodgers to
their second consecutive pennant. But it was Claire, the club's
director of marketing, who turned the players into people. When
Steve Garvey was introduced to the crowd during Wednesday's game,
he received an ovation rarely heard around here. And he hasn't
played here in more than 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   When they talk about visionaries, they talk about Walter
O'Malley. But Peter's father was terrified of what television would
do to the game and the precious gate receipts. In the old days the
Dodgers televised only the nine road games in San Francisco. Today,
the new owners at Fox have the cable rights to 22 of the 29 other
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Claire set the tone. He thought big.
</P>
<P>
   Claire probably never was going to get the blessing of Gene from
Redondo. He wasn't an old ballplayer, didn't treat the day-to-day
operation like a Rotisserie League draft. His sense of humor rarely
came off in interviews.
</P>
<P>
   But for the last 11 years, the Dodgers were in good hands. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 0224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
