<SLUG> BC-BBN-BONILLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONILLA CANCER TEST NEGATIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While laying nervously in a Denver hospital bed,
Bobby Bonilla started thinking about the precious time he was
missing on the baseball field.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't Chavez Ravine and the Dodgers' struggles he was
yearning for. It was the much smaller confines of a little league
stadium in Connecticut where he wished he could watch his
4-year-old son Brandon hit a baseball of a tee instead of wondering
if he had cancer.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning, the Dodgers' third baseman exhaled after
learning that his colon cancer test was negative. And that
afternoon, the 35-year-old reflected on the event that he
acknowledged was the scariest occurrence of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I wasn't thinking about baseball. Let me tell you that
much,'' said a relieved Bonilla, who is married and also has a
9-year-old daughter. ``I was thinking about how I hadn't seen my
son play tee-ball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did it put (my life) in perspective?'' he said. ``It was an
eye-opening experience. All I can think about was how fortunate I
have been throughout my career, my two little ones at home and how
I hadn't seen my family since spring training.'
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night while the Dodgers were playing the host Colorado
Rockies, Bonilla was hospitalized due to intestinal problems. Tests
later revealed a colon polyp growth in his large intestine and an
infection surrounding his colon. After having a biopsy to remove
the polyp Sunday, Bonilla waited until Wednesday for results on
whether the growth was malignant.
</P>
<P>
   They were negative. But the Greenwich, Conn., resident is
receiving antibiotics to aid his large intestine inflammation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need additional surgery and that is what I'm doing
jumping jacks about,'' said Bonilla, who was put on the 15-day
disabled list Saturday. ``I was on pins and needles. I wasn't doing
too well.'
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla hasn't felt well since being dealt from Florida in a
blockbuster seven-player trade on May 15. After playing in the
first game during a road trip in Seattle, he spent the next two
days in the hotel with the flu. He has batted just .173 with one
home run in 27 games with the Dodgers, but doesn't know if his
illnesses hurt his play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been trying for him,' said Dodgers physician Mickey
Mellman, who said Bonilla is expected to come off the DL on time.
``He had been ill and it was appropriate to put him on the DL. We
expect him to recover.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
