r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LAD     06-25 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELTRE IS SIGHT FOR SORE EYES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After enduring a week of sadness and turmoil, the
sight of Adrian Beltre coaxed a smile from Dodgers vice-president
Ralph Avila.
</P>
<P>
   Since his arrival from a business trip in Taiwan on Monday
night, the Dodgers' overseer of operations in the Dominican
Republic has dealt with the passing of ex-Dodgers general manager
Al Campanis, the firings of general manager Fred Claire and manager
Bill Russell and the Dodgers not living up to their tradition on
the field.
</P>
<P>
   Those thoughts, however, were temporarily forgotten when he saw
the 20-year-old Beltre wearing No.29 and taking infield practice
before Wednesday night's game at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Avila and scout Pablo Peguero signed Beltre to the Dodgers in
1994. And on this night, Avila's foresight paid off as he saw who
is arguably baseball's top prospect make his major league debut
after being promoted from Double-A San Antonio in a surprise move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've signed a few good ones, but he is one of the best,'' said
Avila, who has been instrumental in signing many Dominicans,
including Raul Mondesi and Ramon Martinez. ``He and Mondy (at
Beltre's age) were pretty close tools-wise and baseball-wise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the pressure that we have, at least we have Adrian
here. That is a good feeling,'' Avila said.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre got an RBI single in his first major-league at-bat
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   How good is Beltre? Check the third baseman's resume:
</P>
<P>
   After batting .317 with 26 home runs and 25 stolen bases last
season, he was named the Class-A Player of the Year by Baseball
America and the Florida State League Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the season, he was ranked as the third-best prospect by
Baseball America, behind Oakland's Ben Grieve and the Dodgers' Paul
Konerko, and was a spot ahead of the Chicago Cubs' Kerry Wood.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-11 player has impressive power and hitting ability,
probably the strongest arm in the organization next to Mondesi and
above-average speed.
</P>
<P>
   What's just as remarkable, the son a former St. Louis Cardinals
minor leaguer doesn't lack confidence or seem in awe of being in
the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel ready to play, mentally and physically,'' said Beltre,
who was batting .409 with 15 RBI in his last 11 games with San
Antonio. ``The jump (from Double-A) can be tough, but I don't think
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very excited. I thought that they would call me up (in
September), but not this soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, who is the first Dodger to make the jump from Double-A
since Gary Ingram in 1994, became the 40th player this season to
wear a Dodgers' uniform. How long he will continue to wear it this
season is up to him, according to Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman.
Even when third baseman Bobby Bonilla returns from the disabled
list, Beltre might still be a Dodger if he is producing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything is possible,'' Hoffman said. ``We just have to take
it one day a time.'
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield reminisces: Dodgers right fielder Gary Sheffield can
relate with Beltre. Sheffield was drafted sixth overall in the 1986
Amateur Draft and voted the best hitting prospect and the most
dangerous hitter in the California League a year later. At 18, he
made his major league debut with the Milwaukee Brewers and batted
.238 with four home runs in 24 games.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Beltre's promotion from Double-A Sheffield
said, ``Everything depends on how developed he is. If he is a true
star, it doesn't matter.'
</P>
<P>
   Etc: Hoffman hasn't given a timetable on when his staff will be
officially named and didn't rule out making changes.... Joe Vavra
replaces Hoffman as the organization's Minor League Field
Coordinator. Vavra previously served as the Dodgers' Assistant
Minor League Field Coordinator and organizational baserunning
coach.... Only 15 players from the Dodgers' Opening Day Roster
remain on the 25-man roster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
