<SLUG> BC-GLF-WILCOX-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLFER'S OBSESSION ENDS IN HAWAII
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobby Orens will go to great lengths to play golf.
Frequent-flier kinds of lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday he chased the sun across North America, a journey
of 5,013 miles that started in Queens, N.Y., and ended in Honolulu
to answer the question: Can a golfer play 18 holes in New York and
18 holes in Hawaii on the same day?
</P>
<P>
   Orens, an Encino resident, is here to tell you that he can.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great, really awesome,'' he said earlier this week
after recovering from jet lag.
</P>
<P>
   Orens' three-day odyssey covered about 10,000 air miles, 36
holes and 178 strokes from the white tees. Another question comes
immediately to mind: Why rack up all those frequent-flier miles on
such a short trip?
</P>
<P>
   Turns out Orens, who has been playing for five years and is a
member of Braemar Country Club in Tarzana, is obsessed with golf.
He is a member in excellent standing of the ``Golf Nuts Society of
America,'' which is headquartered in Phoenix. Members do goofy
stuff like this all the time and earn points in the process.
</P>
<P>
   At year's end the member whose antics warrant the most points
ends up with.... the most points.
</P>
<P>
   That's it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a leaderboard that's on their Web site and so far my
points enable me to say that I'm in 10th place in the country. It's
strictly an ego thing for golf fanatics,'' said Orens, a 16
handicapper.
</P>
<P>
   This is not his most extreme behavior since taking up the game.
Orens, 61, played 128 holes in one day and he's bagged a
granddaughter's birthday and an anniversary to play golf.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the moving-day bailout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I went to play in a tournament back East and we were
moving because of the (Northridge) earthquake. I left the moving to
my wife,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out his wife Carol is one understanding woman. After 37
years of marriage, she's gotten used to her husband's whims.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obsessed,'' she said, laughing. ``I put up with him
because he's a good guy. He gets these little notions in his mind
and he does it.''
</P>
<P>
   Adventures like the New York-to-Hawaii outing take careful
planning, which Orens is easily capable of since he owns Plaza
Travel in Encino, where he bills himself as the director of golf
research.
</P>
<P>
   The first problem was tee times, which were arranged in advance.
The two courses he played, Clearview Golf Course in Queens and Ko
Olina Golf Course in Honolulu, are operated by American Golf. The
company would not let him buy up all four spots, or five as is
sometimes the case, so he could race around the course by himself.
So Orens made a donation to a charity that American Golf supports,
the Jordan and Kyra Memorial Fund, named after two Bay Area
children who lost a fight with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   He flew into JFK International Airport on Wednesday and was on
the first tee at Clearview at dawn on Thursday. Mother nature, who
could have scotched the whole deal, cooperated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather was nice. There were thundershowers the night
before, but when I played it was fine,'' Orens said.
</P>
<P>
   The course provided him with a caddie, who helped track his
shots so time would not be wasted looking for lost balls, and Orens
completed the 18 holes in about 90 minutes, shooting an 84.
</P>
<P>
   Then he rushed back to JFK and caught a 9:15 flight to Los
Angeles, where he had a two-hour layover. He finally landed in
Honolulu at 4:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   That's rush hour _ but Orens had a plan. He chartered a
helicopter for a 15-minute flight from the airport to Ko Olina's
10th tee.
</P>
<P>
   He tackled the back nine first and had the course to himself
when he reached the first tee. He finished the round in an hour and
40 minutes, shooting an 94.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently somewhere over the Pacific his game took a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I attribute that to the length of time on the plane and maybe
one or two too many bloody marys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he did not come home empty-handed. Oren brought his wife a
souvenir of his outing, a gold bracelet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says `I love you more than.... golf,''' Carol Orens said.
``And it's on my wrist right now.''
</P>
<P>
   What's next? Golf around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   On July 23 he will travel to Alaska to play in the Idigolf
Tournament, in which the contestants play for 24 hours straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically a 100-hole tournament. But the record is 250
holes in one day. I'm going to try and beat it,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 0235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
