<HEADER>
A5995 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN     06-25 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
 
DiSARCINA MISSES DH 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One Angels player who hates to see the DH
eliminated as the Angels play in National League ballparks through
the weekend is shortstop Gary DiSarcina.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina went into Wednesday's game hitting .316 batting ninth
in the order, and apparently a lot of it has to do with the fact
that leadoff hitter Darin Erstad follows DiSarcina.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina said that the American League pitchers see Erstad
standing in the on-deck circle and throw him ``cookies'' to hit.
But in the NL ballparks, DiSarcina bats eighth. And with the
pitcher hitting behind him, DiSarcina doesn't get nearly as many
good pitches to hit.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina's theory seemed without merit, though, in his first
at-bat Wednesday in the third inning. DiSarcina hit a ``cookie''
thrown by Dodgers pitcher Darren Dreifort into the left-field
pavilion for a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Protest: Angels coaches Rod Carew, Larry Bowa and Mick Billmeyer
emerged from the visiting clubhouse at Dodger Stadium Wednesday
afternoon for batting practice with index cards stuck on their
caps. On the cards was the message: ``Will throw BP (batting
practice) for food.''
</P>
<P>
   The sign referred to the coaches' mock displeasure that because
of a clerical error, players and coaches did not receive the daily
meal money they normally receive when on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Back in NL: Angels manager Terry Collins, a former NL manager
with the Houston Astros, likes the chance to manage in the NL
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun for me, I like it,'' Collins said. ``You don't ever
sit back, you always have to be aware of what's going on. And it's
where your bench coach really, really has an impact.
</P>
<P>
   Greene update: Catcher Todd Greene will see Dr. James Andrews in
Birmingham, Ala., today to get another opinion on his ailing right
shoulder. Greene is still trying to determine whether or not he
should have season-ending surgery. If he doesn't have surgery,
he'll be limited to DH and first base.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Allen Watson (elbow) will leave for Vancouver today so
that he can throw his third rehab assignment game on Friday. The
Angels would like Watson to reach 90 pitches. If everything goes
OK, Watson could be activated to pitch July 1 vs. his former team,
the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Salmon, who had a cortisone shot in his left foot Monday
night, was unavailable for Wednesday's game. However, he is
expected to be ready for pinch-hitting duties tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
