<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KARIYA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARIYA BACK ON HIS FEET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Little, if anything, has gone right for the Mighty
Ducks in the past year. So, when Paul Kariya says he's feeling
great, it has to be music to their ears.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, who missed 32 games because of a long contract dispute
and played in only 22 games before suffering a season-ending
concussion on Feb. 1, is working out daily and expects to be 100
percent for the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, I couldn't remember the last time I felt good. Now, I
can't remember the last time I felt bad,'' Kariya said this week.
``Time has flown by since I've gotten better.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, who admitted he was concerned about his hockey future
when the post-concussion headaches and dizziness lingered for more
than two months, said a month of acupuncture treatments that he
started a day after the regular season ended helped him turn the
corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like the cloud really lifted and, from that point
forward, everything has been very positive,'' Kariya said of the
treatments recommended by Philadelphia Flyers star Eric Lindros.
``I was pessimistic. I didn't think poking needles in me would
really help. (But) it has been around for thousands of years and,
obviously, it must work.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariya said he feels so good now that he really doesn't want to
talk about the down days of February, March and April.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be in the situation now, where I'm looking ahead,
not looking back,'' said Kariya who hasn't seen the Ducks team
doctor (Craig Milhouse) in more than a month but will pay a return
visit to neurologist James Kelly in Chicago before the season
begins.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, who scored 17 goals and 31 points in his 22 games last
season, said he will do his best not to worry about being hit once
the 1998-99 season begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I've got to shut it out,'' he said. ``It will be
tough initially because everybody will be asking about it. But,
hopefully, after five to 10 games, it's totally forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his career, Kariya will wear a mouthpiece.
But he said he didn't want to become ``a target'' by wearing a new
helmet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
