<HEADER>
A6003 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-PHILLIES-REDSOX-B     06-25 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-PHILLIES-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
  
 Phillies beat Red Sox, 11-8  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Gordon Edes  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ To paraphrase a certain funny fat man whose girth
and mirth eclipsed Mo Vaughn and Rich Garces in both categories ...
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, the Red Sox would rather be anywhere than in the
company of the nine from Philadelphia, W.C. Fields's favorite town.
</P>
<P>
   Losers of two straight to the Phillies in Fenway Park, the Red
Sox took the Logan shuttle here and absorbed another flogging
Wednesday night on the National Leaguers' home artificial turf,
11-8.
</P>
<P>
   Until encountering the Phillies, the Red Sox had not dropped two
straight since losing back-to-back games to another NL team, the
Mets, June 5-6 in Fenway. Despite scoring eight runs for the second
time in three nights, the Sox have lost three in a row for the
first time since they dropped six straight to the Yankees and Blue
Jays, a streak that Thursday night's starter, Bret Saberhagen,
ended by beating the Yankees May 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about momentum and confidence,'' said center fielder
Darren Lewis. ``They come back and now they go into the next day
feeling good. They feel relaxed. In our situation, now we've got to
bounce back as quickly as possible, get back to playing good
fundamental baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   No sign of that last night in Veterans Stadium. The Sons of Jimy
Williams suffered through a seven-run third inning, which matched
the largest output by the opposition in any inning this season,
then fell behind, 10-1, before an out was recorded in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Lefthander Steve Avery had his shortest outing of the season,
lasting just 2 1/3 innings, then was followed to the mound by John
Wasdin, who spotted the Phillies another four runs in the next
three innings. That was too much for the Red Sox to overcome, even
though they stacked nine hits and seven runs between the sixth and
eighth innings after Nomar Garciaparra put them on the board with
his 11th home run, a 434-foot monster to left-center, in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I backed myself into a corner, then couldn't make the pitches
I wanted to,'' said Avery. ``I didn't like my changeup very much. I
wasn't fooling anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery might have spared himself some damage when, with two runs
already in and two Phillies on base in the third, he made a leaping
grab of Kevin Jordan's comebacker. But because the runners were on
the move, Avery's throw to second was late.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the runners go like that, they sometimes go a little easy
into second base, and even if you don't get the runner there, you
still have time for the runner at first,'' Avery said. ``I just
didn't make a very good throw because I was a little off balance.
Bad move on my part.''
</P>
<P>
   The next batter, Mike Lieberthal, shot another ground ball over
the mound that Avery just missed, the ball continuing into center
field for a two-run single that made it 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   When Mark Lewis tripled high off the right-field wall, it was
6-0 and Avery was finished. The Phils, however, weren't. Kevin
Sefcik greeted Wasdin with an RBI single to make it 7-0, and
Philadelphia scored three more in the fourth with an outburst that
began when Doug Glanville's shallow fly to right fell among three
Red Sox: Lewis, right fielder Darren Bragg, and second baseman Mike
Benjamin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see it,'' said Lewis, who earlier had overthrown
late-arriving cutoff man Vaughn on Gregg Jefferies's two-run single
in the third, ``and Braggie didn't see it. Benji could see it, but
when I came running in yelling, `I can't see it, I can't see it,'
it scared him off.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra had two hits to extend his hitting streak to 16
games, matching his longest of the season, but even his night came
with an asterisk, as Phillies third baseman Scott Rolen robbed him
of extra bases with a diving stop of his smash down the third base
line in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Lewis, a paragon of consistency all season, was
involved in another scene born of confusion. Garciaparra managed to
salvage an infield hit on Rolen's play.
</P>
<P>
   The next batter, Vaughn, lifted a fly to center. Third base
coach Wendell Kim held up a stop sign to Wasdin, among the slowest
of all Sox players, but he headed for home. When Lewis, who was on
second, saw Wasdin going, he headed for third, hoping to draw the
throw and spare Wasdin. Wasdin did score, but Lewis was easily cut
down.
</P>
<P>
   The late Red Sox rallies succeeded in stretching out the muggy
night, but nothing more. Thanks to John Harrington, a big proponent
of interleague play, there's a rematch at the Vet tonight. Keep
this in mind: The Sox haven't won a game against the Phillies here
since 1915.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 0311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
