<SLUG> BC-PRESIDIO-FUNDING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE, SENATE PANELS EARMARK PRESIDIO FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LOUIS FREEDBERG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Presidio will receive between $40 million and
$50 million if legislation approved by key committees in both the
House and the Senate Wednesday becomes law.
</P>
<P>
   The House Appropriations Committee approved $25 million for
operating and maintaining the park, as well granting the Presidio
Trust to borrow up to $25 million to rehabilitate and prepare
facilities for leasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This funding recognizes the Presidio as a national treasure in
the coming year, and brings it one step closer to
self-sufficiency,'' said Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., a member of
the committee.
</P>
<P>
   A slightly different bill was approved by a Senate
appropriations subcommittee, providing $40 million for operating
the park.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., the legislation is
part of a longer term plan for the Presidio to become
self-supporting within 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maintaining the beauty and integrity of the Presidio has long
been one of my highest priorities,'' said Boxer. ``This funding
will help the people of the Bay Area accomplish this goal and enjoy
this national treasure for generations to come.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill also calls for $2 million to assist in the
acquisition of Bair Island, which is part of the Don Edwards
National Wildlife Refuge in the South Bay. The island, recently
purchased by the the Peninsula Open Space Trust, is thought to be
the largest unprotected wetland in the San Francisco Bay. The bill
also calls for $5.6 million for construction projects in the Golden
Gate National Recreation Area. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
