<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WIN, THEN FIRE THREE COACHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Fox caught the Goose. And then some.
</P>
<P>
   Just moments after Wednesday night's 6-5, 11-inning win over the
Angels in front of 46,822 at Dodger Stadium, new Dodgers general
manager Tom Lasorda started his purge of the staff by firing three
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda began with first-year pitching coach Goose Gregson who
will be replaced by former Dodgers knuckleballer Charlie Hough.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Hatcher, hero of the Dodgers 1988 World Series
championship, will replace Reggie Smith as the Dodgers hitting
instructor. John Shelby, another member of that World Series team,
takes over as bullpen coach, replacing Mark Cresse.
</P>
<P>
   Third base coach Joe Amalfitano keeps his job and first base
coach Mike Scioscia becomes the bench coach for Glenn Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   The new coaches are all members of the Dodgers minor league
organization. The four fired coaches have been offered positions in
the farm system. Gregson can become pitching coach at Triple-A
Albuquerque and Smith has been offered the batting coach job with
the Dukes.
</P>
<P>
   Cresse, who has been with the Dodgers since 1974, was offered
the manager's job at Class-A San Bernardino.
</P>
<P>
   If the moves weren't enough, the Dodgers took the field wearing
their blue batting practice jerseys, the first time in club history
they did not wear their white tops for a home game.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield and Raul Mondesi had home runs for the Dodgers
off left-hander Chuck Finley and Cecil Fielder and Gary DiSarcina
went deep for the Angels against right-hander Darren Dreifort.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Adrian Beltre, the Dodgers top prospect, singled
home a run in his first major league at-bat. Jim Edmonds crashed
into the center-field wall to take extra bases away from Eric
Karros in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers trailed 1-0 in the second inning when Fielder drove
a 1-2 fastball into the lower left-field stands.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, batting .321 with 13 homers and 56 RBI at Double-A San
Antonio, came to the plate in the second inning with runners at
first and second. He drilled Finley's first pitch into left field,
scoring Paul Konerko and tying the score.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels took the lead in the third when DiSarcina homered to
center, his first of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But Finley, who had dropped two straight after winning three in
a row, did not settle down. Eric Young opened with a single and
stole his league-leading 30th base.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Castro walked and Sheffield drove a Finley fastball into
the right-field pavilion to give the Dodgers a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   They made it 5-2 in the fifth when Mondesi homered with two
outs. It was his team-leading 17th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But just like the first two games in Anaheim, the Dodgers were
unable to hold their lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got two back in sixth, the first on a wild pitch by
Dreifort that scored Dave Hollins. The second came home on a
sacrifice fly by catcher Matt Walbeck.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman came to the mound in the sixth, but wasn't ready to make
a move. But after Fielder opened the seventh with his third hit,
the Dodgers went to left-hander Scott Radinsky, who has been
demoted from closer to set-up man.
</P>
<P>
   Garret Anderson sacrificed pinch runner Damon Mashore to second
and Walbeck singled him home to tie the score at five. Greg
McMichael replaced Radinsky and retired the next two batters to get
out of the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
