<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WIN, THEN DEMOTE THREE COACHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Fox grabbed the Goose. And then some.
</P>
<P>
   Just moments after Wednesday night's 11-inning 6-5 win over the
Angels in front of 46,822 at Dodger Stadium, new general manager
Tom Lasorda started his purge of the Dodgers coaching staff by
reassigning pitching coach Goose Gregson, hitting instructor Reggie
Smith and bullpen coach Mark Cresse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of the Glenn Hoffman era,'' bellowed
Lasorda, who said the Dodgers' new manager was responsible for the
changes. ``This was his first major-league victory and there are
many more to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregson will be replaced by former Dodgers knuckleballer Charlie
Hough. Gregson, who replaced Dave Wallace before the season, will
take Hough's job at Class-A San Bernardino.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Hatcher, hero of the Dodgers' 1988 World Series
championship, will replace Smith as the Dodgers' hitting
instructor. Smith has been offered the manager's spot at Triple-A
Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a positive change and a way to manage in the
majors someday,'' Smith said. ``But it's something I'll talk over
with my wife before I decide.''
</P>
<P>
   John Shelby, another member of that World Series team, takes
over as bullpen coach, replacing Cresse.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman coach Joe Amalfitano keeps his job and first base
coach Mike Scioscia becomes the bench coach for Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things can't be done at the end of the season, they have
to be done now,'' Hoffman said. ``There is not enough time to wait
to see if things turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   Cresse, who has been with the Dodgers since 1974, was offered
the manager's job at San Bernardino three years ago. He is close to
Lasorda, who is godfather to his son Brad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go home and think about it,'' he said. ``I kind of always
thought I'd be here forever.''
</P>
<P>
   If the moves weren't enough, the Dodgers took the field wearing
their blue batting-practice jerseys, the first time in club history
they did not wear their white tops for a home game.
</P>
<P>
   The coaching changes and new jerseys overshadowed the game, the
first Dodgers victory since last Friday and first over the
first-place Angels in three interleague games this season..
</P>
<P>
   Trenidad Hubbard, who returned from a rehab assignment Monday,
drove in the winning run when he singled home Matt Luke against
left-hander Greg Caderet (1-1). Antonio Osuna (4-0), the fourth
Dodgers pitcher, threw two scoreless innings to pick up he victory.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the game was decided, Gary Sheffield and Raul
Mondesi had home runs for the Dodgers off left-hander Chuck Finley,
and Cecil Fielder and Gary DiSarcina went deep for the Angels
against right-hander Darren Dreifort.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Adrian Beltre, the Dodgers' top prospect, singled
home a run in his first major-league at-bat. Jim Edmonds crashed
into the center-field wall to take extra bases away from Eric
Karros in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, batting .321 with 13 homers and 56 RBI at Double-A San
Antonio, came to the plate in the second inning with runners at
first and second. He drilled Finley's first pitch into left field,
scoring Paul Konerko and tying the score.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels took the lead in the third when DiSarcina homered to
dead center, his first of the season. But Finley, who had dropped
two straight after winning three in a row, did not settle down.
Eric Young opened with a single and stole his league-leading 30th
base. Juan Castro walked and Sheffield drove a Finley fastball into
the right-field pavilion to give the Dodgers a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   They made it 5-2 in the fifth when Mondesi homered with two
outs. It was his team-leading 17th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got two back in sixth, the first on a wild pitch by
Dreifort that scored Dave Hollins. The second came home on a
sacrifice fly by catcher Matt Walbeck.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman came to the mound in the sixth but wasn't ready to make
a move. But after Fielder opened the seventh with his third hit,
the Dodgers went to left-hander Scott Radinsky, who has been
demoted from closer to setup man.
</P>
<P>
   Garret Anderson sacrificed pinch runner Damon Mashore to second
and Walbeck single him home to tie the score at five. Greg
McMichael replaced Radinsky and retired the next two batters to get
out of the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
