<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVOLUTION-METROSTARS-BOS </SLUG>
  
 Revolution blasted, 5-3  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Jim Greenidge  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Hoping to reverse their fortunes, the
New England Revolution switched from a 4-4-2 to a 3-5-2 alignment
last night against the New York-New Jersey MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a Plan B?
</P>
<P>
   Finding no problem solving this new look, the MetroStars rang up
14 shots on net and set a team record for goals as they dealt the
Revolution their seventh straight Major League Soccer setback, 5-3,
before a crowd of 10,310 at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was particularly deflating for the Revolution, who erased a
3-1 deficit, then surrendered the winning goal to rookie Mark Petka
of Southern Connecticut State in the 69th minute _ only 30 seconds
after Raul Diaz Arce's second goal of the game had tied things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had a bull's-eye on my chest,'' said Revolution
goalkeeper Ian Feuer. ``It's not an individual thing. It's all of
us. Enough is enough. We had a lot of breakdowns, all 11 players.
Things could have gone better. Even I could have played better.
We're not a team right now. Until we work for each other and cover
up for each other's mistakes ... but we still have the talent to do
something.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution (4-10) climbed within a goal when midfielder
Edwin Gorter belted in a shot from just outside the box along the
right side to the far side in the 64th minute. Then Diaz Arce
converted a setup pass from Gorter, heading it from outside the
6-yard box along the left.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we tied it, I thought we were going to win,'' said
Gorter. ``Every time the MetroStars took shots, though, they scored
goals by having it hit a hand, changing the shot. Maybe it was
concentration for us. Maybe it was intensity. I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it was, Petka, a Rookie of the Year candidate, ripped
in the winner from the top of the box, over Feuer's head, for his
first goal. ``That goal took the wind out of their sails,'' said
MetroStars coach Alfonso Mondelo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We broke down, and with veterans, that can't happen,'' said
Revolution head coach Thomas Rongen, who took leave of his
assistant duties with the US World Cup team in France to fly in for
this match. ``That happens too often. We broke down our
concentration with (Johnny) Torres and (Janusz) Michallik. We fell
asleep. We have to coach the players the whole period.''
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars tried to beat the Revolution to the outside.
``With three men deep, we had a lot of room to the outside to try
to exploit them,'' Mondelo said. ``It was a far different look to
play against us than the last time when they gave us a different
look at 4-4-2.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's the deal with the Revolution's defense? ``We didn't
adjust to our game plan; we didn't stay with their runners,'' said
defender David Nakhid. ``Some players weren't picking up their
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Now two losses shy of the league record for futility they set
last season, the Revolution will have reinforcements for Saturday's
game against the Dallas Burn at Foxboro Stadium. Defender Mike
Burns and forward Joe-Max Moore will be back from the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like we have to go at it again,'' Nakhid said. ``It's
the nature of the beast. We have to somehow find the result and
stay positive and come back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One encouraging thing is that we haven't lost faith, and any
time you get to six and seven straight, you can lose faith,''
Rongen said. ``We've got to do this together. This is especially
tough when you're down, 3-1, and you tie it up, 3-3, so you're
always hopeful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 0513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 06:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6077 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PM-CHINA-CLINTON-0625     06-25 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PM-CHINA-CLINTON-0625-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON GETS POMP AND COLOR AT FIRST CHINA STOP BEFORE FACING
TOUGH ISSUES
 &HT;    With CHINA-ODDITIES-$ADV25; CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV25.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   XIAN, China _ Thousands of Chinese were gathering in the shadow
of this 600-year-old city's walls Thursday evening (China time) to
give a vivid imperial-era welcome to U.S. President Bill Clinton
and his family, opening what promises to be the most controversial
foreign visit of this presidency.
</P>
<P>
   An extravaganza of music, dance and martial arts, patterned
after elaborate Tang Dynasty ceremonies, was awaiting a crowd of
several thousand guests invited to come and greet the Clintons upon
their arrival to the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
   In the hot and hazy summer night, Clinton was expected to walk
to the city's towering South Gate down a red carpet the length of
two football fields. It was lined with 32 hanging red lanterns --
red is for luck in China -- adding their glow to the strings of
tiny white lights that outline much of the seven-mile long walls,
their gates and towers.
</P>
<P>
   Horse guards and Chinese dressed as warriors also were part of
the ceremony, the kind of production that Tang Dynasty emperors
used to mount back in 600-900 A.D. for foreign guests come to pay
homage at Xian, a metropolis that was bigger and grander than any
Western capital.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Clintons arrived to enjoy the outpouring of
hospitality that thousands of Chinese here have worked for months
to prepare, the region's leaders got a taste Friday of the
contentious issues Clinton will be trailing along in the wake of
his entourage.
</P>
<P>
   ``For as long as 1,100 years Xian was China's political economic
and cultural center,'' Mayor Feng Xuchu proudly announced at a
reception for foreign journalists, an event clearly intended to be
a pleasant social respite.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor and provincial governor both were quickly thronged
after their welcoming remarks and peppered with the kind of
questions that journalists for the government-controlled media
would not dare to ask.
</P>
<P>
   What about reports that local dissident Yan Jun had been
arrested, an uncomfortable Mayor Feng was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know this person. I don't even know the name. I deny
it,'' Feng said. Then he added that if anyone was arrested, it was
because he violated the law.
</P>
<P>
   Yan, a dissident in Xian who took part in a letter signed by 70
people asking Clinton to meet dissidents, was taken away from his
home Wednesday afternoon, the Information Center of Human Rights
and Democratic Movement in China said.
</P>
<P>
   Yan's whereabouts were unknown Thursday, shortly before
Clinton's planned arrival in the north China city, the Hong
Kong-based group added.
</P>
<P>
   Also detained Wednesday was Li Zhiying, a county official in
Chengcheng, about 80 miles northeast of Xi'an, who was in frequent
contact with other Xi'an dissidents and had previously signed
petitions to the government, the group said.
</P>
<P>
   Letters and petitions are among the few recourses for Chinese
who take issue with government policy. Even former Communist Party
leader Zhao Ziyang, under house arrest since the June 3-4, 1989,
crackdown on democracy protests centered on Tiananmen Square, has
resorted to penning his grievances.
</P>
<P>
   It was a taste of the difficult questions both the American
delegation and its Chinese hosts will be facing for the nine days
of the Clinton visit, which is the longest presidential foray to a
single nation in nearly eight decades.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Chinese and American sides have characterized this
visit as an important turning point in relations, a chance to usher
into the 21st Century a cooperative liaison that will be vital in
shaping the world of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Yet leaders on both sides have also tried to downplay any
potential controversies. Thus, it is startling that so little about
the final outcome of the summit is pre-determined. It is uncertain
whether any major agreements will be reached, on either trade or
arms controls.
</P>
<P>
   And the Chinese well may take umbrage if Clinton fulfills his
promise to the American public to speak out about human rights
violations and religious oppression.
</P>
<P>
   The American team managed to schedule at least the first night
and following day of Clinton's visit to avoid as much controversy
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's 24-mile journey from the Xian airport to city center
is a motorcade through history, an education for any first-time
visitor to China.
</P>
<P>
   The route passes flowering persimmon trees, orchards of
pomegranates and fields where winter wheat was lately harvested.
Peasants normally are still at work at dusk, the time the motorcade
was scheduled, threshing stacks of wheat by hand or tending their
fruit trees or vegetable plots with primitive farm equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Bumping up from stretches of flat farmland are twin high mounds
of dirt holding tombs of the Han Dynasty that ruled China from 206
B.C. to 220 A.D. Across the four-lane road stands a symbol of a
more modern China, a coal-fired thermal power plant that billows
clouds of white smoke as plants and industries do across China,
making it one of the world's most polluted countries.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Clinton will take the tourist road out to the resting
place of more than 7,000 ancient terra cotta warriors, horses and
chariots, the 2,000-year-old wonder unearthed little more than 20
years ago. Then he will talk to leaders of a local village before
heading on to Beijing on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   For clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
