<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6223 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN28-CO     06-25 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A real-life Viagra joke
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, June 28, 1998.)
 &HT;    (Eds: Bocaiuva do Sul in 5th graf is cq.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The introduction of Viagra to the market has done more than just
resurrect sex lives. It has offered us some relief from the
ferocity of thousands of Monica Lewinsky-Bill Clinton jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The creativity of the public in originating Viagra jokes by the
hundreds is to be admired, although most of them are predictable
and unfunny. So were the Lewinsky-Clinton jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly, we have a new Viagra joke each minute of each day _
and some are based on real-life situations, such as the woman who
sued because her 70ish husband, fortified with Viagra, began
playing the field again after years of dormancy.
</P>
<P>
   A newer story involving Viagra also comes, not in the form of a
ribald joke, but as real life. This, too, can lead to a new genre
of jokes, if not bureaucratic gestures.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern Brazilian town of Bocaiuva do Sul, the mayor is
using Viagra as a key ingredient for participation in Brazil's
formulized revenue sharing.
</P>
<P>
   With the population of his community down to 8,750, Mayor Elcio
Berti has said he will distribute Viagra free to his townsfolk.
Behind it is a shrewd political and economic concept.
</P>
<P>
   The more people in town, the more financial aid the town gets
from the federal government. I am uncertain of the principal
industry of Bocaiuva do Sul but I am beginning to suspect it is
procreation. One wire story more or less confirms this by claiming
federal aid is the main source of income for this town.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier effort to jumpstart the population, the mayor
tried to ban condoms but it was ruled unconstitutional by a judge.
Now, along comes Viagra and Mayor Berti can look at the population
issue from an entirely different perspective.
</P>
<P>
   There are several obstacles to Berti's plan, not the least of
which is fertility. But, also, health authorities in the Brazilian
state of Parana, where Bocaiuva do Sul is situated, are wondering
aloud about the mayor's right to dispense a prescription drug.
</P>
<P>
   He claims he has spent $35,000 from his own pocket on this
project, so one must assume that it will come back to him in some
form of covert reimbursement if and when incremental funds arrive
from the Brazilian feds. The waiting period of fund anticipation,
due to natural necessities, will be no less than nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Also, I wonder to myself, how does the mayor plan to get the
pills from their U.S. manufacturer, Pfizer? Does he go to his local
doctor and get him to write a prescription for several thousand
Viagra pills?
</P>
<P>
   What is the problem with his town in the first place? Are all
the men over 65; is that why they need help in the propagation
process? Or is it that the younger men (and, of course, the women)
aren't interested in having children by the carload? Or is it
because something has happened down there to bring on an epidemic
of impotency upon the entire male population?
</P>
<P>
   No matter which, the mayor has introduced to the world the
formula for a unique form of economic growth. One only can hope
that other cities and towns in Brazil, some of them horribly
overpopulated, do not embrace the same scheme to reap even more
funds into their coffers.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular interest is that the mayor plans to distribute the
pill personally, contending he knows 90 percent of the men in town.
It is reported that Viagra sells for more than $25 a pop in Brazil,
and the mayor is concerned that Brazilians from afar will turn up
in his town for a free, stimulating handout.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest he give the outsiders placebos; he's already increased
the population simply by getting them there. He now just needs a
good gate to keep them in.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
