<HEADER>
A6275 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-CHINA-COMPOUND-$AD     06-25 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CHINA-COMPOUND-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHINESE CHIEF AWAITS CLINTON IN THE COMPOUND WHERE MAO CAVORTED
 &HT;    With CHINA-CLINTON; CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV27.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, June 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Chinese artisans have been renovating a secluded
waterside pavilion inside the communist leadership compound where
President Bill Clinton is expected to hold some of his most
sensitive talks.
</P>
<P>
   The 213-acre complex called Zhongnanhai has no equivalent in
America. It is a Beijing-style amalgam of the White House, Camp
David, parts of Georgetown and an incumbent president's national
party headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Last month President Jiang Zemin told visiting U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright that the vermilion-walled compound was
being spruced up for the Clinton visit.
</P>
<P>
   Zhongnanhai means ``the Central and South Seas,'' a name taken
from two lakes within the walls that were once part of the imperial
palace grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The compound is not just China's seat of the ruling Communist
Party politburo and the government's State Council. It is also
where the patriarch Mao Tse-tung used to live. A few of Mao's
former revolutionary comrades-in-arms still have apartments here,
and so do some of China's senior and not-so-senior leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also the Chinese analog of the White House
Communications Agency, the place where Chinese leaders have located
the secure ``hot line'' for urgent communications with U.S.
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Zhongnanhai is where China has held all important private talks
for the last quarter-century with American leaders, starting with
U.S. National Security Adviser Henry Kissinger's secret mission in
1971. Visiting French, Russian and other top officials also have
been received here.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, it is where Jiang has granted interviews to
well-connected visiting journalists. In the last month, Jiang has
spoken here with columnist Lally Weymouth, the daughter of retired
Washington Post publisher Katherine Graham, and with Agence France
Press board chairman Jean Miot.
</P>
<P>
   A generation ago, Zhongnanhai had quite different uses.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s and 60s, this was where Mao held weekly ballroom
dancing sessions with a stable of beautiful young Chinese women
chosen for their ``political reliability,'' according to the
memoirs of Mao's personal physician Li Zhisui.
</P>
<P>
   The dancers were peasant girls assigned to the Cultural Work
Troupe of the Central Garrison Corps, the doctor wrote in 1994
memoirs that have not been refuted. ``He (Mao) was happiest and
most satisfied when he had several young women simultaneously
sharing his bed,'' wrote Mao's personal physician from 1955 through
the Great Helmsman's death in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Long before that, Zhongnanhai was also the site of pleasure
pavilions for Qing dynasty emperors, who built the compound as an
extension of the Forbidden City during the 18th century reign of
emperor Qian Long.
</P>
<P>
   Situated on an island near the compound's center is the stately
Pavilion of the Soaring Phoenixes. It is famous among Chinese
scholars as the gilded prison where the young reform-minded Emperor
Guanxu was held under house arrest starting in 1898.
</P>
<P>
   The young emperor was confined for a decade by power-hungry
Empress Dowager Cixi. He spent much of the time in the Soaring
Phoenixes pavilion while imperial China teetered toward its final
collapse in 1911.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang told the U.S. secretary of state that the pavilion under
renovation for the Clinton visit dated from the Qing Dynasty
(1644-1911). It was not disclosed whether Jiang was speaking of the
same pavilion where Emperor Guanxu was detained.
</P>
<P>
   Zhongnanhai became the center of power in revolutionary China in
the fall of 1949. It was just after the communist takeover, and
many of the guerrilla fighters set up their apartments and offices
on the water's edge inside the complex. Mao took one of the most
spacious.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, the tranquility ended when China was convulsed by the
Cultural Revolution. Thousands of Red Guard radicals were ushered
into the compound. They rampaged through the houses of suspected
``capitalist roaders'' in the communist leadership, including
China's future leader Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
   Deng's abject ``self-criticism'' didn't satisfy the Red Guards,
who yelled that he was a ``capitalist despot.'' Deng was evicted
from the compound, kicked out of his party offices and banished to
the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Following Mao's death in 1976, Deng was rehabilitated and came
to power as premier in 1980. But instead of emulating Mao, Deng
preferred to live in his own house outside the walls -- a practice
that many in today's top leadership follow.
</P>
<P>
   Deng was a man of simple tastes,'' author Harrison Salisbury
wrote in 1992. ``Mao had celebrated his emperorship by moving into
Zhongnanhai. Deng Xiaoping celebrated his by moving out.''
</P>
<P>
   Access to Zhongnanhai became less exclusive as the aura of Mao
faded.
</P>
<P>
   By 1987, Chinese tourists could get tickets from their factories
to visit a large part of the compound. They tromped through the
shaded ``Hall of Noble Refinement'' in Mao's quarters and gaped at
the ``Hall of Fragrant Robes,'' where Qing emperors used to change
their clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Zhongnanhai was again closed to Chinese tourists during the 1989
Tiananmen Square uprising. If such visits are currently permitted,
there has been no publicity about it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet these days not just heads of state and celebrity journalists
are invited inside to see the ginkgo trees beside the placid lake.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, U.S. House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., and a
12-member congressional delegation were among the compound's
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   China's relations with the U.S. has entered a state of
``sunshine after the rain,'' Jiang said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich was more blunt: ``I told them we will defend Taiwan.
Period,'' Gingrich said. ``The thing that was striking to me is
that we never got into an argument about it.''
</P>
<P>
   For clients of the New York Times News Service.(at)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
