<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6278 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV     06-25 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TIANANMEN SQUARE _ A HALLOWED BAROMETER OF DISSENT
 &HT;    With CHINA-CLINTON; CHINA-COMPOUND-$ADV27.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, June 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ For eight decades, Tiananmen Square has been the
world's best barometer of protest and repression in China:
</P>
<P>
   May 4, 1919 _ May Fourth Movement. About 3,000 university
students protest the post-World War I Versailles Treaty. They
demand that China be treated as a war victor, having sent 100,000
coolie laborers to support Allied combat troops. (The Allies gave
Germany's worldwide ``sphere of influence'' to Japan, including a
German enclave in China.)
</P>
<P>
   1925 _ Anti-British. Students protest a massacre of Chinese
demonstrators by British troops in the British enclave of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 9, 1935 _ ``December Ninthers.'' Thousands of students
demand a war of national resistance against Japan, which now
controls China's northern Manchuria region and most of Hebei
Province, which rings Beijing. In frigid weather Nationalist
Chinese authorities train water hoses on the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 1, 1949 _ Communists. Victorious communist guerrilla Mao
Tse-tung stands on the gate to the former imperial city and
declares to a mass rally, ``the Chinese People have now stood up.''
</P>
<P>
   1952-1958 _ Demolition. Mao's construction brigades raze the
outer palace gate of the Forbidden City to enlarge the square to
its present mammoth proportions of 98 acres, making it the world's
largest public square.
</P>
<P>
   August 1966 _ Red Guards. Mao reviews more than one million
``Red Guards,'' who chant slogans of the Cultural Revolution and
hold up copies of ``The Quotations of Chairman Mao.''
</P>
<P>
   April 4-5, 1976 _ Confrontation. Stirred by the death of
revolutionary hero Zhou Enlai, students pay homage to Zhou and also
demand ``genuine'' Marxism-Leninism. A crowd of 100,000 scuffles
with police, burning a few police cars. Authorities jail at least
388 and send many to labor camps for ``counter-revolutionary
sabotage.''
</P>
<P>
   1976-77 _ Mao's Tomb. In 10 months following Mao's death, one
million Chinese ``volunteers'' erect a massive marble mausoleum for
the leader's corpse, which will be mechanically raised from a
freezer inside its crystal coffin, draped in a red flag, for daily
lines of viewers. Mao's waxy corpse is still on display.
</P>
<P>
   November 1978-March 1979 _ ``Democracy Wall.'' On a wall along
the main avenue leading to Tiananmen Square, near the Zhongnanhai
leadership compound, dissidents paste hand-written ``wall
posters.'' One by a disillusioned Red Guard, Wei Jingsheng, calls
for a ``fifth modernization'' in China _ democracy. Wei is
imprisoned, becoming one of China's most prominent dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   January 1987 _ Long Live Freedom. Students hold a mass
``freedom'' rally in defiance of police bans.
</P>
<P>
   April 17, 1989 _ Anti-corruption. Students begin assembling to
mourn the death of revolutionary leader Hu Yaobang, whose ouster
from the party hierarchy had made him a cult hero. Students decry
corruption and nepotism. Authorities hesitate to crack down,
fearing embarrassment prior to a summit visit by Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev. The crowds increase daily.
</P>
<P>
   May 17, 1989 _ Escalation. Student crowds in the square grow to
one million. About 3,000 hunger-strikers set up a tent city,
occupying the square around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   May 20, 1989 _ Failed crackdown. Premier Li Peng declares
martial law, orders troops into Beijing to evict the students. But
masses of city residents clog the streets, bottling up the troops.
</P>
<P>
   May 29, 1989 _ Goddess of Democracy. Art students from Beijing
University erect a 33-foot statue made of plaster and Styrofoam
resembling the Statue of Liberty. Meanwhile, communist rulers worry
about activists in an unauthorized trade union camped out with the
student hunger-strikers.
</P>
<P>
   June 3-4, 1989 _ Massacre. Tanks and motorized troops of the
People's Liberation Army rumble in, forcing out the last 5,000
protesters. Between 500 and 1,000 demonstrators and a few dozen
troops are killed, most in clashes on the boulevards leading to
Tiananmen. Thousands of students, including protest leader Wang
Dan, are arrested; thousands flee into exile through Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   For clients of the New York Times News Service.(at)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
