<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6281 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-CHINA-YOUTH-$ADV29     06-25 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CHINA-YOUTH-$ADV29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHINA HARVESTS A NEW BREED OF YOUNG GRADUATES
 &HT;    With CHINA-CLINTON; CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV29.
 &HT;    For Use Monday, June 29 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China's new graduates are a rare tribe -- more
informed, more free, more pampered and more job-pressured than any
generation since the 1949 communist revolution.
</P>
<P>
   They herald a new round of university students unbowed by the
burden of their country's tumultuous recent past, as they take
their turn at molding its future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing for us students is to enrich ourselves. On
one hand to enrich ourselves with knowledge, and on the other to
broaden our visions,'' said Wang Qi, an earnest 22-year-old
graduating from Beijing University, where she majors in Japanese
language studies.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual to find students at Beida, as China's most
prestigious, 100-year-old university is nicknamed, speaking of
heavy personal responsibilities to China's future.
</P>
<P>
   That is, when they aren't mesmerized by the NBA Finals or the
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   At Fudan University in Shanghai, another distinguished school in
a more free-wheeling cosmopolitan setting, senior English major
Shen Yi Ming takes a breezier approach to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like rolling stones. It's easy to move from job to
job,'' said Shen, 22, a top student who starts working at the Bank
of China this summer. ``Shanghai will be a financial center. I'm
going to play some role in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, no one can say just how this tranche of young Chinese
will progress through careers and family. It is a generation that
has no precedents.
</P>
<P>
   Even at Beida's gated campus -- strictly closed to outsiders
since its students began the 1989 democracy movement that ended in
blood at Tiananmen Square -- the world's ways are breaking through.
Students are hooked on the internet, play the Shanghai stock market
and expect to own an apartment one of these years. Intrigued by
foreign technology and management techniques, they say they have no
time for anybody's political ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them were not even born when the death knell rang in
1976 for Mao Tse-tung, the Chinese leader who twice led into
pandemonium and destruction the country he had revolutionized. They
missed the Cultural Revolution that finally gasped to a full stop
with Mao's death, though their parents were among its most direct
victims.
</P>
<P>
   And they grew up with the late leader Deng Xiaoping's policies
of economic reform and openness. These doctrines they were
spoon-fed in current affairs classes were policies their elders
never envisioned and still may not fully comprehend.
</P>
<P>
   Another impact is China's ``one-child'' policy that began 18
years ago and left many of them sibling-less, the ``Little
Emperors'' whose families count on them both ``to do good and do
well.''
</P>
<P>
   More and more like them will follow; one-third of China's
population is under age 16.
</P>
<P>
   Despite national growth rates hovering around 8 percent a year,
China's young graduates see gathering clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Guo Xueliang, 20, is in a two-year program of politics and
administrative management at Beida that used to feed civil servants
to China's far-flung bureaucracy. Has she been walking the halls of
the ministries looking for work?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no. I have passed the exam of qualification for public
service. But I'm not likely to work for the government,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Guo is holding out for a private company, because the future of
state jobs looks shorter by the week under bureaucratic downsizing
and bankruptcy of unwieldy state industries.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The official China Daily newspaper reported this month that 80
percent of this year's graduating students have found jobs, which
might be an impressive success rate elsewhere. But this is a
country that used to assign every single graduate to a job.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first year graduating students have been totally
untethered to fend for themselves in the job market. And this
bumper crop of 1.06 million graduates is 17 percent larger than
last year -- the biggest since the People's Republic of China was
founded in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Beida is China's Harvard, Fudan University its Yale. What keeps
these young Chinese optimistic is knowing they are trained for the
new jobs opening up, while the laid-off workers -- often their
parents -- don't have a clue to making it in the high-tech,
high-finance world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of our state-owned enterprises don't pay attention to
management,'' said Chen Feng, 28, an MBA student at Beida. ``So we
are very likely to go to foreign-funded enterprises. In this aspect
foreign enterprises are 100 years ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   They may not want to work for the state, but the young people
who will be the cream of Chinese leadership by 2025 are extremely
patriotic. These students, even when interviewed outside the
presence of journalist-watching monitors, professed not to
understand the flap in America over Clinton visiting Tiananmen
Square, the symbol of democracy's crushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe China is not the same today. Maybe the economy is
different. The economy was partly the cause of the politics (in
1989),'' said Chris Yu, 22, a Fudan student who chose the name
``Chris'' for her new job with the Deloitte Touche accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's more likely for young people today to care more
about their career, their job and making a contribution to their
country,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   They have hard work ahead. Lay-offs and the one-child policy may
make them the sole supporter of their parents before they even
begin their own families. But for now they are still in their final
student days and follow universal student ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aim now is to enjoy life thoroughly,'' said Fudan's
irreverent Shen, ``and have no regrets about university days.''
</P>
<P>
   For clients of the New York Times News Service.(at)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
