<P>
   NEW-PLANET (San Francisco) _ The world's champion planet-finders
have discovered another new world _ one tantalizingly close to
Earth's doorstep. The San Francisco astronomers found the new
planet orbiting a star called Gliese 876, a mere 15 light years
away. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   MINIMUM-WAGE (San Francisco) _ A high-stakes, behind-the-scenes
policy fight over whether San Francisco should have the nation's
highest minimum wage for the employees of city contractors is
testing Mayor Brown's strong ties to organized labor. By CHUCK
FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   CHINATOWN-ANIMALS (San Francisco) _ Chinese merchants and their
representatives appear to be backpedaling from a pact signed in
March to kill and store animals humanely. By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-PARADE (San Francisco) _ Two years ago a young Londoner
joined the throngs of eager tourists who flock each year to San
Francisco's annual gay pride parade. Now, Teddy Witherington is
executive director of the San Francisco Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and
Transgender Parade taking place this Sunday. By MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-HARMONY (Undated) _ For Luciano Perez, the killing fields
of Southeast Asia converted the soldier to a man of peace. His
vision, that skin color and gender should not separate us, that
love should replace violence, became his raison d'etre. Today,
dance and song are his primary tools, along with prayer and sweat,
as he travels the world promoting harmony among people. By DOUG
BLACKBURN
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-BOOKS (Houston) _ Books are Rollerblades and yachts,
kayaks and Explorers, 747s and motorcycles. They take you anywhere
in the world for a summer vacation _ across the street or across
the ocean. The mode of travel is as exciting and varied as the
destination. Hop aboard. These new books for children promise many
journeys full of fun, adventure and learning. By JANE P. MARSHALL.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WINE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Chateau Montelena has announced a new
futures program for its famed cabernet. Futures offerings _ wherein
consumers pony up their cash right after a vintage, usually at a
savings _ are designed to allow consumers to acquire highly
allocated wines that might otherwise not be available. By MICHAEL
LONSFORD
</P>
<P>
   SUPERMARKET-CHEF (Albany, N.Y.) _ When Dave Hamlin graduated
from the prestigious Culinary Institute of America, he opted for a
job as a food service specialist with Price Chopper supermarkets.
Recognizing that more and more people are buying prepared foods,
groceries are putting more emphasis on taste and quality. By DOUG
BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR (San Francisco) _ NASCAR veteran Rusty Wallace can tell
you, race by race, why he hasn't won in Winston Cup competition
this season. He's smiling while he talks, but he's not happy. By
EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
