<SLUG> BC-DOLITTLE-REVIEW26-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe Dr. Dolittle shouldn't have listened this time
</P>
<P>
   By Dave Larsen
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Murphy launched his monumental comeback with a remake of
Jerry Lewis' The Nutty Professor, for which he earned a Golden
Globe best-actor nomination. So it's no surprise that Murphy's next
starring role would be an update of another '60s film.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Dolittle? The original, a 1967 musical-comedy starring
Rex Harrison, was a colossal dud that almost ruined 20th Century
Fox studios.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's sporadically amusing, non-singing update is a slight
improvement, putting a contemporary spin on Hugh Lofting's stories
about a physician who can talk to the animals. The songs, though,
have been replaced by ``litter box'' humor that's much too crude
for small children, earning the Betty Thomas-directed film a PG-13
rating.
</P>
<P>
   Kids in that age bracket would probably rather see The X-Files
or Armageddon than a bunch of chatty critters. Especially when many
of the animals are obviously animatronic puppets.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dolittle's menagerie of voice actors reads like a ``Comic
Relief'' all-star team: Chris Rock, Norm MacDonald, Albert Brooks,
Garry Shandling, Julie Kavner, John Leguizamo, Ellen DeGeneres,
Jenna Elfman, Gilbert Gottfried and Paul Reubens, to name a few.
All but the first three are woefully under-used. The same might be
said of Murphy, who winds up playing straight man to a sarcastic
dog (MacDonald), a fast-talking guinea pig (Rock) and an ailing
circus tiger (Brooks)..
</P>
<P>
   We meet John Dolittle as a boy, when the family pet (DeGeneres)
explains to him why dogs sniff one another's backsides. When John
tries this method to greet the new principal, his pooch is sent to
the pound by his disapproving father (Ossie Davis). John never
talks to another animal.
</P>
<P>
   Not until adulthood, that is, after Dolittle has become a doctor
with a beautiful wife (Kristen Wilson) and two individualistic
daughters (Kyla Pratt and Raven-Symone). His long-dormant ability
is unleashed when he hits a stray dog, whom he hears call him a
``bonehead.'' Soon, wounded and sick animals are flocking to
Dolittle's door, jeopardizing an impending buyout of his medical
practice, and calling his sanity into question.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay opts for too many butt jokes, rather than fully
exploiting the comedic potential of the cast or storyline.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dolittle does have heart, however, and is somewhat redeemed
by a cute ending and a litter of one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy needs to talk to his agent and tell him no more lame
remakes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
