<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6321 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRENDAN-FRASER-INTERV     06-25 1765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRENDAN-FRASER-INTERVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRASER'S EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine _
the rate is not prohibitive _ contact one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     (-----They also have information on how to subscribe to ``HIGH
STYLE AND MORE,'' a complete lifestyle and entertainment package
composed of stories _ with accompanying B&AMP;W and color art _ from
numerous publications issued by Fairchild Publications.-----) 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``e'' entertainment news files.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: Two color slides are available FREE OF CHARGE!)  
 &HT;    
 By LOUISE FARR 
 c.1998 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   A steadicam follows Brendan Fraser and Alicia Silverstone
through the lobby of a Holiday Inn in Hollywood, past the check-in
desk, past a frosted glass mural of Marilyn Monroe, through
faux-grand doors and outside, where the passing traffic hisses and
wheezes on Highland Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The two keep up a steady patter as they go, Fraser gesturing
wildly, like a silent-movie clown.
</P>
<P>
   They're shooting a comedy called ``The Blast from the Past,''
with Fraser playing Adam, a young man who'd been raised in an
elaborate underground bomb shelter since the 1962 Cuban missile
crisis by a paranoid scientist father, Christopher Walken, and
mother, Sissy Spacek _ ``June Allyson on Listerine,'' Fraser calls
her.
</P>
<P>
   Now in the 1990s, in spite of its hydroponic garden and fish
tank, the family is running out of supplies. Adam emerges to seek
batteries, toilet paper _ and a girl.
</P>
<P>
   And here he is, not the psychopath one would expect after a
childhood like this, but a clean-cut, rather starchy fellow with
early-'60s values and impeccable manners.
</P>
<P>
   He develops an instant crush on tough cookie Silverstone, whom
he meets while trying to cash in a l950s Joe DiMaggio baseball
card.
</P>
<P>
   Silverstone, all sausage curls and trademark petulance, is
complaining to Adam about her lack of a boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never works out, because I'm into butts and legs and hair
myself, so I always end up with some guy who's more shallow than I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   No boyfriend? Adam goes into hormonally induced paroxysms of
glee.
</P>
<P>
   Cut. Do it again. And again. And again, as extras playing
Scandinavian tourists mingle with genuine British travelers,
bemused and jet-lagged as they stagger off a bus and wander into a
Hollywood movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brendan was born to play this part,'' says writer-director
Hugh Wilson, a pleasant-faced man in chinos. ``It's all about
innocence, and Brendan exudes innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true that Fraser's furrowed brow always manages to give him
a rather sweet air of faint bewilderment, which he used to comic
advantage in ``George of the Jungle'' and which made him touchingly
vulnerable in ``School Ties,'' the l991 movie about teen-age
anti-Semitism that gave him his big-screen break.
</P>
<P>
   But at 6 feet 3 inches, the 29-year-old Fraser is also a great
lunk of a guy. During a lull in filming, he's settled into a
nondescript armchair, his oversized feet planted firmly on the
carpet in a suite on the 22nd floor of the location hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Against a decorating nightmare of lurid flowered curtains and
fake floral arrangements that could have time-warped out of the
movie, Fraser is talking up a storm, hands flying in all directions
to punctuate his points.
</P>
<P>
   He's usually called shy, a description that makes him balk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm thoughtful,'' he says. ``And I'm told I have
infrared vision. I like to understand people before I present
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, he adds, he likes to save himself for his performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many comedians won't say boo to you, but put them in front
of a microphone and they blister the wallpaper.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what he did to the screen in ``George of the Jungle,''
last summer's surprise hit with kids and critics alike.
</P>
<P>
   A $100 million-plus box-office gross put the movie on Daily
Variety's Golden Reel list of top moneymakers for 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``So hoo ha for the business end of the things,'' says Fraser,
whose price tag jumped from $1 million for ``George'' to several
million. He also gained a new audience of 7-year-olds, who laughed
at earnest George, and their mothers and baby-sitters, who gulped
at the sight of his well-toned muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wardrobe was about the size of a tea-towel,'' says Fraser,
who began a mad weight-lifting routine when he got the part.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it never really seemed like enough,'' he says about his
physique, which he considered nothing more than part of his George
costume. ``I'm glad they took a picture of it, because it sure
doesn't stay that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraser has gotten used to things not staying the same for long.
His father traveled the world promoting Canadian tourism, and the
family went along. The youngest of four brothers, Fraser lived in
Britain, the United States, Canada and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, he was introduced to the Buster Keaton movies that he
draws on now for comic roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's immense dignity in playing a clown. We're
asked to do everything no one else wants to do, only with
panache,'' he says, perhaps remembering his title role in ``Encino
Man'' _ his other loincloth movie _ in which, as a prehistoric man
unfrozen after millions of years, he shared a dish of dog food with
a Labrador retriever.
</P>
<P>
   Life on the move may also have had something to do with Fraser's
becoming an actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It influenced me at an early age to be open to different
people,'' he says. ``Or to invent them, or beg, borrow or steal
from them, and pretend they were mine all along.''
</P>
<P>
   The actor's first brush with theater came in an unlikely
setting: the Upper Canada College in Toronto, a New World
incarnation of a British public school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't paddled, but we were definitely tested again and
again,'' he remembers. ``We were little businessmen in our suits.
We weren't making money, but we were making marks. That was our
income. I can attest to that: All the old boys have gone on to the
Canadian equivalent of Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   He, on the other hand, discovered the small campus theater _ not
as a budding actor, but by stage-managing and selling tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bug had bitten. After a stint at the Actor's
Conservatory at Seattle's Cornish College of the Arts, he was on
his way to grad school in Texas when he stopped in Los Angeles to
make money.
</P>
<P>
   He never left. And just a year later, he landed the coveted lead
in ``School Ties,'' an ensemble movie in which he co-starred with
Matt Damon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was wonderful. The same guy you see today,'' Fraser says of
Damon. ``He wasn't trying to make himself look good to charm an
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraser glances through the hotel window at a grim-looking urban
vista obscured by gray mist, and recalls his first reaction to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt distanced from it,'' he says. ``As I look out right
now, I can't say I recognize this view, because it's always
changing every time I turn around _ if you can see it through the
thick air.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then again,'' he continues, ``there's that kind of misty
quality that makes for great black-and-white photography.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraser, who collects old Polaroid cameras, describes himself as
``a spectacular amateur'' photographer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He takes his cameras everywhere. Takes them to dinner. Maybe
hides behind them. I don't know,'' says director Wilson, who
invited Fraser to his Virginia farm to get acquainted before the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has five children and notes that Fraser, possibly out of
shyness, spent more time playing with the kids than talking to him.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Fraser remembers arriving at the farm after
surviving a combination of back-slapping and ``jealous glares'' at
his Upper Canada College 10th-year reunion.
</P>
<P>
   He'd flown from Toronto into Washington D.C., and the studio
sent a stretch limo to pick him up. He arrived to find Wilson, in
raincoat and hat, waiting for him atop a John Deere tractor.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Fraser lives in Hollywood with girlfriend Afton
Smith, a former actress he describes as ``dreamy.'' They plan to
marry and live somewhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a homebody,'' he says _ dashing the fantasies of a slew of
prepubescent girls and their mothers. ``I've discovered things like
fleece-lined doeskin slippers. Given that and a choice between a
cocktail party ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm drawn to what I don't have,'' he concludes.
</P>
<P>
   What he has very little of, apparently, is free time. With the
success of ``George'' and his newly perceived image as Hollywood
hunk, Fraser is on a hot streak, finding more scripts coming his
way than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Still Breathing,'' which came out in April, he was a
longhaired innocent again, this time a San Antonio street performer
in search of the true love he's envisioned in a dream.
</P>
<P>
   He was also recently in Morocco, shooting a techno-version of
the 1939 ``The Mummy,'' and in the upcoming ``Gods and Monsters,''
he stars as the fictional boyfriend of a movie director played by
Ian McKellen.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the innocence of some of the characters he plays,
the actor himself looks at it all with a faintly jaundiced eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times this is a Restoration comedy,'' he says about
Hollywood. ``We're seeking favor in court. There are jealousies and
rivalries. It's a play.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he adds, ``the meaning of `play,' is fun.''
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
