<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6325 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUSIN-BETTE26-COX     06-25 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUSIN-BETTE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neglected spinster weaves web of revenge
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sculptor Auguste Rodin caused a stink when he unveiled his
phallic statue of the 19th century French novelist Honore de
Balzac. Behind the statue _ or in front of it, you could say _ is
the idea that sex and artistic creativity are somehow synonymous.
</P>
<P>
   This quaint notion took root with the Picassos and Hemingways of
the early 20th century and endures among Hollywood filmmakers of
our era.
</P>
<P>
   Balzac was prodigious _ creatively, at least. His aim was to
document every aspect of the confusing period before the Revolution
of 1848. He did so with a ferocious energy, knocking out book after
book filled with insecure aristocrats, avaricious bankers,
ambitious courtesans, wan artistes _ and in his novel ``Cousin
Bette,'' one very vengeful spinster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Human Comedy'' is the title of Balzac's massive collected
works. ``Cousin Bette'' is now a film starring Jessica Lange, and
it takes the ``comedy'' bit very seriously. As for the ``human'' _
well, the characters tend to be made of cardboard.
</P>
<P>
   But the real problem for this black comedy is a mixed, confusing
tone. Part melodrama, part farce, the strains merge awkwardly when
they come together at all.
</P>
<P>
   Balzac was a master of witty irony. Noted theater director Des
McAnuff, in his feature film debut, has a feel for the ridiculous.
But if it weren't for the subtle Jessica Lange as Cousin Bette, the
film would have missed the irony altogether, not to mention the
poignancy.
</P>
<P>
   Bette is a spinster wronged once too often by her dingbat family
of newly minted aristocrats who are living uneasily off the glories
of the Napoleonic era. Sometimes inadvertently, she gains her
revenge through actions that are invisible to the dopes around her.
</P>
<P>
   Bette is the poor relation of the Hulot clan. When her cousin
(Geraldine Chaplin) dies, she expects to become the lady of the
Hulot household. But the self-absorbed widower Hector Hulot (Hugh
Laurie) ignores her hopes for romance, instead offering her a job
tending to the needs of his pretty daughter Hortense (Kelly
Macdonald).
</P>
<P>
   Bette declines and moves to a poor quarter of Paris. There she
becomes a costumer for the cabaret songbird Jenny Cadine (Elizabeth
Shue), and falls for the young bohemian sculptor Wenceslaus (Aden
Young).
</P>
<P>
   But when love and life pass her by again, Bette begins to subtly
manipulate all of these characters. The Hulots never know what hit
them, although it's an intriguing question whether revenge is
really sweet for Bette since it's a bit by-the-way and ultimately
empty.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some bad casting and an inconsistent tone, the film has
enjoyable moments, thanks largely to Lange. She proves that you
don't have to be a vixen to be vindictive. Doing her best to look
dowdy, Lange proves the master of The Stare. Indeed, she stares so
hard and meaningfully that, at times, she seems cross-eyed. But she
also adds gravity to a film in constant danger of slopping over
into Monty Pythonism.
</P>
<P>
   Shue is horribly miscast as a theatrical thrush; Laurie, a
wonderfully goofy comedian, is just a tad too silly as Hulot; Young
is a tiresome caricature of a bohemian artist; and Bob Hoskins
should have lost the wig as the banker Crevel.
</P>
<P>
   For every scene that captures your attention, there's one that
seems simply wrong _ an absurd duel, for example, and the
inevitable sex scenes, including a bout of chocolate-covered
love-making that will put you off the procreative act for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   When it avoids the absurd, ``Cousin Bette'' is fun, as only rude
justice, cleverly obtained, can be. But the film is far too
farcical for its own good.
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-24-98 1745E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
