<HEADER>
A6326 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIARY-EYMAN26-COX     06-25 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIARY-EYMAN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Diary'' truly a delicious, frothy farce
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGET JONES'S DIARY, by Helen Fielding. Viking; 271 pages;
$22.95.
</P>
<P>
   All is not well in Bridget Jones' England. Her mother is
sleeping, not with Bridget's father, but with a newly acquired
Portuguese lover. Her friend Jeremy is sleeping with a terrible
slut. Prince Charles is sleeping with Camilla Parker-Bowles. Worst
of all, Bridget is sleeping with a man who only shows up when every
other woman has turned him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bridget Jones's Diary'' was last year's must-read in England
and is being touted as this summer's must-read here. It began as a
weekly newspaper feature and seems ready-made for a movie. It's a
year in the life of a 30-something girl mired in mid-level
publishing, whose biological clock is resounding like Big Ben.
</P>
<P>
   Unattached and loathing every minute of it, she especially
bridles at impertinent questions from family and friends about her
love life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't married people understand that this is no longer a
polite question to ask? We wouldn't rush up to them and roar,
`How's your marriage going? Still having sex?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the novel's daily entries is preceded by Bridget's
careful notations of her weight, the number of cigarettes she's
smoked, the units of alcohol she's drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget wishes she was a literary figure like Kathleen Tynan,
who radiated poise and could be found writing at a small, bare
table in the center of a room, sipping an exquisitely chilled glass
of white wine.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget, on the other hand, is given to white whine. In spite of
her good intentions, it's a daily struggle to just muddle through.
Dignified hauteur is quite beyond her.
</P>
<P>
   When she notices the tell-tale signs of early aging _ creases
around the eyes, etc. _ she decides to go for a more upscale look.
Elizabeth Hurley seems to be the goal. She ends up looking like
Barbara Cartland.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget has an extended family of friends, including Tom, Jude,
Shazzer and Magda, all of whom she adores, relies on emotionally,
and, behind their backs, slags mercilessly. They undoubtedly return
the favor, for they're as adorably confused as she is.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget's friend Magda, a former commodities broker, goes into
an earth-mother kick when she gets pregnant, only to lose her nerve
and begin shrieking, ``Give me the drugs, you fat cow!'' as soon as
her water breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The plot, such as it is, relates to Bridget's giddy mother,
whose affair with the Portuguese has devastated her husband even as
it has liberated her. Once a nominal housewife, she lands a job as
an inquiring reporter for the BBC on issues relating to
osteoporosis. In other words, Mum's doing better than Bridget, and
Bridget isn't happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   This ratchets up the anxiety level, and Bridget flings herself
desperately from pillar to post, from ecstasy to oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bridget Jones's Diary'' is largely delicious, frothy farce,
the sort of stylized romp the English do so well.
</P>
<P>
   It's also frankly derivative; Bridget is really the compulsive,
desperate and doomed Basil Fawlty with a sex-change, set loose in
the boozy, upscale, gloriously irresponsible world of ``Absolutely
Fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that Basil, Patsy and Edina had only the
prospect of more chaos in front of them; Helen Fielding gives
Bridget a highly unlikely, not to mention retro, happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I suspect Fielding has captured a moment in time here,
and not just in England _ Bridget is a perfect representation of a
modern girl/woman flummoxed by time and change, vacillating between
what she really wants and what she thinks she should want, aspiring
to be mistress of the universe when she can't quite manage to
untangle her pantyhose.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
