<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DR-DOLITTLE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Look who's talking to the animals: Eddie Murphy!
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Old comics don't die. They just become kiddie fare.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the best way to describe Eddie Murphy's career
these days. After a decade of mostly forgettable movies _ did
anyone actually see ``Beverly Hills Cop III''? _ the former
``Saturday Night Live'' star has resurfaced in a couple of fine
children's films. First, he was the wise-cracking voice of the
dragon in ``Mulan'' and now he's the eponymous hero of a remake of
``Dr. Dolittle.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget any memories you have of a dry-as-sherry Rex Harrison in
the 1967 original. With lots of help from some furry friends,
Murphy turns the 1998 ``Dr. Dolittle'' into a bust-a-gut delight
that will appeal to kids and adults alike.
</P>
<P>
   It's a performance that overlooks plenty of faults in Nat
Mauldin and Larry Levin's script (based upon Hugh Lofting's classic
stories) and Betty Thomas' direction. It's a performance that even
overlooks Murphy's weaknesses as a dramatic actor.
</P>
<P>
   But when you witness the spectacle of Murphy giving
mouth-to-mouth to a dying rat and then proclaiming upon the
rodent's recovery, ``It was just gas,'' you've got your money's
worth.
</P>
<P>
   In this updated ``Dr. Dolittle,'' Murphy is a successful San
Francisco physician who is considering selling his practice to a
managed-care firm and who is guiding his youngest daughter (played
by a charming Kyla Pratt) through a nerdy stage of childhood. These
troubles serve as a catalyst for what Dolittle's friends and family
mistake as a nervous breakdown. But Dolittle ain't nuts: He's just
talking to the animals.
</P>
<P>
   And what animals they are: In addition to the rat with gas,
we've got a dog with an attitude, a guinea pig who takes a dip in a
toilet bowl, a pigeon who fantasizes he's a bluejay and a tiger
who's contemplating suicide. Once the word is out that Dolittle's
the man who can hear them, they all find their way to his door.
Literally.
</P>
<P>
   When Murphy is interacting with the animals, ``Dr. Dolittle'' is
at its strongest. Murphy's timing and mannerisms reveal his natural
comic instincts, the script sizzles with lots of good gags and
Thomas plays each scene for its hilarious worth. Add to that the
cast of celebrity voices _ Norm Macdonald, Chris Rock, Albert
Brooks, Garry Shandling, Julie Kavner and Ellen DeGeneres, among
others _ and you have a smart concept movie a la ``Look Who's
Talking.'' Only funnier.
</P>
<P>
   Then, about midway through, everyone starts to worry that the
gags aren't enough; the script gets bogged down with too many
unlikely scenarios and the need to project a statement. We're led
to believe that the reason Dolittle must talk to the animals is the
same reason his daughter must continue on her nerdy trajectory _
it's all about being who you are. The self-important tone doesn't
suit Murphy, nor does Thomas find a way to deliver the message
without the film lapsing into sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   But remember the rodent with gas. There's nothing like a little
bathroom humor to bring out the kid in all of us.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
