<HEADER>
A6328 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVERGLADE-RESTORATION     06-25 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADE-RESTORATION26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Untested water storage plan is Florida's best hope for
protecting Everglades
 &HT;    By Joel Engelhardt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The federal plan to save the Everglades
depends on the untested practice of storing up to 1.7 billion
gallons of water underground every day during wet years and pulling
it back up during dry times.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that it's never been done before on such a massive
scale.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that federal regulators at the highest levels are
agonizing over the idea of injecting untreated _ and possibly
tainted _ lake water into underground drinking sources.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the alternatives are not well-defined, could
cost millions or even billions more and would fill at least 100,000
acres with water ringed by levees 112 miles long.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers' plan for the Everglades relies
on the approach known as Aquifer Storage and Recovery, or ASR,
because of its promise.
</P>
<P>
   The system could be a savior of the 21st century, reducing the
need for reservoirs that turn valuable farmland into swamps while
replacing a brackish layer of ground water with enough fresh
watercq to meet the demands of Florida's fast-growing population.
</P>
<P>
   It has so much promise, it should be attempted on a scale five
times as large as planners envision, said a Gainesville consultant
who has shepherded such projects in Florida since the procedure's
infancy in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fear is that without ASR the cost will be so high it would
take us a long time, maybe decades, to solve the problems,'' said
David Pyne, ASR director for CH2MHillcq. That engineering firm has
worked on all five underground storage projects operating in
Florida and about half of the 30 in planning or construction
stages.
</P>
<P>
   Yet critics say the approach is so uncertain it should be
consigned to backup status. The plan's reliance on the underground
storage system to meet the demands of people while water from other
sources flows into the Everglades is too extreme, said Gary
Dernlan, who manages the Palm Beach County water and sewer system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to take a stance to restore everything and forget
the 5 million people who are here. We don't feel that's the best
route to go,'' Dernlan said.
</P>
<P>
   For the water managers crafting the plan, the answer is in the
middle, a cautious approach that doesn't rely entirely on the
underground storage system but still makes it a significant factor.
They are rushing to create backup plans if the system doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   The most pressing concern is whether they would have to treat
the water before injecting it underground.
</P>
<P>
   Planners estimate that building 200 underground storage wells
around Lake Okeechobee will cost $600 million. But if the water
must be treated first, it would cost nearly another $1 billion,
making the ASR system as expensive as other storage options, if the
water must be treated first.
</P>
<P>
   The science involves digging a hole more than 1,000 feet deep to
reach the brackish Floridan aquifer. The injected water pushes
aside the brackish water, creating a bubble of fresh water that
eventually can be pulled out and pumped through canals to treatment
plants.
</P>
<P>
   The only question is whether the water will still be there years
later.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, water managers have worked to persuade the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency to let them send untreated water
into the aquifer. The EPA refused, worried about the presence of
coliform bacteria in the injected water. But at a meeting last
week6/9/98, EPA official Richard Harvey said the agency would allow
untreated water to be injected as long as it met other
water-quality standards.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came from EPA Secretary Carol Browner, Harvey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure that our legacy down here is not that we
allow the ground water to be trashed,'' Harvey said. ``The only
reason we're willing to consider this is because of the potential
economic benefits for the whole South Florida system.''
</P>
<P>
   By summer, an underground storage project in the city of West
Palm Beach may get the nation's first permit to inject untreated
water.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is promising, water managers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plan is beginning to look like it will be an A-plus with
ASR and maybe a B-minus without it,'' South Florida Water
Management District Chairman Frank ``Sonny'' Williamson said at an
April 15 meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Palm Beach County environmentalist Rosa Durando put it:
``ASR is really our only hope. If it doesn't pan out we're dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
