<SLUG> BC-NO-FIREWORKS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No fireworks for a dry Florida Fourth
 &HT;    By Ron Hayes
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Celebrate your liberty this Fourth of
July by setting off a bottle rocket anywhere in Palm Beach County
and you might wind up under arrest.
</P>
<P>
   But only if a law enforcement officer actually sees you light
the fuse.
</P>
<P>
   While county officials were trying to decide how best to enforce
their ban on private fireworks, Gov. Lawton Chiles prepared to
cancel all public displays as well.
</P>
<P>
   In Tallahassee, Chiles said the lack of any forecast for
sustained rainfall could lead him to ban all municipal Fourth of
July fireworks displays.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something that we look forward to doing,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Gardens has already canceled its $15,000 Fourth of
July fireworks display on The Gardens mall property because of the
fire danger.
</P>
<P>
   The site north of the mall _ the only one that could accommodate
the 20,000 to 30,000 people who attend the annual event _ has brush
and woods, and firefighters put out a small brush fire there
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County officials acknowledged they're largely
depending on voluntary compliance to not set off fireworks to
reduce the threat of brush fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a statewide state of emergency,'' warned county Fire
Marshal Jim Sweat, ``and we're hoping people will pitch in just
like they did after Hurricane Andrew. People said hurricanes can't
happen here. We've had 150 brush fires in June, and it can happen
here, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The emergency resolution, signed Tuesday by County Commission
Chairman Burt Aaronson, restricts until Aug. 6 the use of all
fireworks, sparklers and open burning to people or groups with a
government permit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will fully enforce this resolution and make arrests when
necessary,'' said sheriff's Capt. Ed Bieluch, ``but the violation
must occur in the presence of officers.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, Bieluch said, violators will be given a notice to
appear, unless they're drunk or belligerent. Juveniles will be
turned over to their parents, and officers will confiscate any
fireworks in plain view.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really hoping our 1 million-plus sensible and
law-abiding citizens will recognize the severity of the
situation,'' Bieluch said.
</P>
<P>
   Three deputies are working solely on illegal fireworks sales and
use, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the county, police responded to the ban with varying
degrees of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   West Palm Beach police also will issue notices, spokeswoman Dena
Peterson said. ``But our best advice is for people to police
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In Palm Beach Gardens and Jupiter, officers will have the option
of issuing warnings instead of notices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If kids are doing it, it would probably be a warning,'' said
Gardens police chief Jim Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   Greenacres will have two extra officers on duty July 4 from noon
to midnight to watch out for bootleg fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   While setting off fireworks is banned, buying them isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been exceptionally quiet,'' said Ronald Hunnewell, owner
of Galaxy Fireworks at Boca Rio Road and Florida's Turnpike.``We
anticipate we're going to have about a 50 percent drop in business
from last year, but we'll have a better picture after the
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   In court, Circuit Judge Edward Fine heard a request by Hunnewell
for an injunction to bar the county from enforcing its new vendor
ordinance, which requires vendors to post a $15,000 bond, check
photo IDs, take down names and addresses of anyone who buys
fireworks and note the exemption in the law that allows them to
make the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Hunnewell claims the county's new rules violate state and
federal laws that permit fireworks sales.
</P>
<P>
   Ira Schwartz, manager of Phantom Fireworks in West Palm Beach _
a year-round fireworks business _ said the county's ban on the use
of fireworks already has decreased his customer traffic. It will
only get worse, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very devastating blow to our business,'' he said.
``This is our Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz's employees tried to go about business as usual,
stopping people as they came through the door and asking them to
fill out the affidavits and show a driver license or other forms of
identification.
</P>
<P>
   But as far as John Lewis and his 10-year-old son Devon are
concerned, they're lighting up on July 4 _ ban or no ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Fourth of July, you should be allowed to have
fireworks,'' Lewis said. ``I know I'm going to do it. I think the
ban will be pretty tough to enforce.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Farkas, manning a Forest Hill Boulevard fireworks tent,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more tempted to do stuff that's illegal,'' said
Farkas, who by early afternoon had sold fireworks to about six
people. ``It's like telling a little kid not to do something, and
then it just makes them more determined to do it. And this is the
kind of thing you can get away with.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Joe Brogan, Alexandra Clifton, Shannon
Colavecchio, Shirish Date, Tim Pallesen, Africa Ragland and
Christine Stapleton contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
