A6338 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WATER-SWT26-COX     06-25 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-SWT26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pumping at SWT springs criticized
 &HT;    By Rebeca Rodriguez
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MARCOS, Texas _ As Central Texas continues to swelter under
a merciless June sun and water becomes an ever-more-precious
resource, a 6-inch-wide pipeline behind a popular seafood
restaurant is creating watery battle lines in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline, the water that will run through it and Joe's Crab
Shack restaurant are owned by Southwest Texas State University. The
pipeline will carry water from San Marcos Springs directly to
university chilling plants that run the air-conditioning systems
around campus. The springs _ locally referred to as Spring Lake _
are on the 90-acre grounds of the old Aquarena Springs theme park
east of the university campus. The university paid $7 million for
the park and rights to the spring water four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The lake, former home to Ralph the Swimming Pig, has become a
stage for ongoing debates over water rights. Local environmental
groups say the pipeline is an example of ivory tower administrators
putting corporate concerns above the delicate ecosystem in the
region. The university says pumping from the lake will reduce the
school's direct draw on the aquifer and free up water for other
users.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the pipeline comes at an especially sensitive
time, as temperatures around the state inch up and aquifer levels
steadily drop. Statewide burning bans have been in place for weeks,
and the City of San Marcos has issued Stage I water restrictions,
which ban lawn watering during the day. Within days, the city is
likely to impose the second level of restrictions, which allow
once-a-week lawn watering and restrict restaurants to serving water
only when customers ask for it. Because the university is a state
institution, it does not have to abide by the water restrictions,
although it does try to be sensitive to them, said William Nance,
vice president for finance and support services.
</P>
<P>
   Pipeline construction on the banks of the San Marcos River will
last only through the end of the month, and the university has put
up signs to keep the community informed.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not good enough for some.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very distressed about the Spring Lake pumping. It is a
wrong thing to be doing at a time when the aquifer is getting lower
and lower,'' said Dianne Wassenich, president of the San Marcos
River Foundation, a nonprofit organization that works to preserve
and beautify the river. ``The very web of life that we all depend
on is based on those rivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Aquifer levels are dropping at the rate of almost a foot a day,
said Tammy Valentine, a spokeswoman for the Edwards Aquifer
Authority in San Antonio. The elevation Wednesday was 642.2 feet
above sea level. Regional Stage II measures take effect whenthe
aquifer drops to 642 feet, which Valentine estimated will be this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The aquifer is the sole source of water for SWT, as well as many
Central and South Texas cities, including San Antonio and San
Marcos. About 1.5 million Texans rely on the aquifer for water
either directly or through another water source fed by the aquifer.
</P>
<P>
   San Marcos plans to begin drawing surface water from Canyon Lake
within a year, a move that will ease its demand on aquifer
reserves. University officials say the new pipeline will achieve
the same effect by using aquifer water that has already bubbled to
the surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the water gets into Spring Lake, it is going to end up in
the Gulf of Mexico,'' Nance said. By taking it from the surface of
the springs, Nance said, the university will not have to pump as
much water out of the aquifer itself.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Nance said, the amount of water to bepumped to the
university will be only 1/1,000 of the average annual flow from the
springs. ``It's bizarre to think that will drastically affect river
levels,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That argument rings hollow for Wassenich, who said the
university has not considered how its actions could affect San
Marcos and other cities downstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story goes all the way to the coast,'' she said, ``but
this Spring Lake problem is a showy one because it's right at the
head of the river.''
</P>
<P>
   The springs feed into the San Marcos River, which eventually
enters the Guadalupe River as it wends southeast to the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
