<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAND-GIRLS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Land Girls'': World War II homefront hokum
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not all women who joined the work force in World War II became
Rosie the Riveter. Instead of heading into factories, some plucky
lasses volunteered to farm, as the well-meaning but mawkish movie
``The Land Girls'' illustrates. It should have been about women in
detergent plants, because it quickly degenerates into a soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   There's an interesting true drama to be told in the stories of
those English maidens who joined the Women's Land Army, but
apparently screenwriter-director David Leland (``Wish You Were
Here'') didn't want to tell it. Instead, he was content to make a
sentimental, randy ``Masterpiece Theatre'' episode about three
women conveniently drawn from different social classes, thrown
together by the hardships of wartime.
</P>
<P>
   With most men off in combat, they are left to fight over a
farmer's shy son, as if the movie were the mirror image of a joke
some traveling salesman would tell.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers, there's Stella (Catherine McCormick), a banker's
daughter engaged to a navy officer, there's Ag (Rachel Weisz), a
Cambridge ivory tower academic, and there's Prue (Anna Friel), a
down-to-earth, earthy hairdresser. ``The Land Girls'' celebrates
how they adjust to the rural life _ or don't _ and how they put
aside their differences of background and breeding _ or don't _ for
the war effort.
</P>
<P>
   Although it would have been far less explicit, you can imagine a
film like ``Land Girls'' being made right after the war. It's an
old-fashioned women's picture that is harder to accept from a '90s
perspective, though it is based on Angela Huth's 1994 novel.
</P>
<P>
   Rejected for service in the Air Force is Joe (Steven
Mackintosh), the handsome son of the farm owner, whom the three
Land Girls quickly set their sights upon. Prue simply seduces him,
though she also decides he should relieve Ag of her cumbersome
virginity. Stella, however, takes an instant dislike to Joe, which
is a cliched set-up for the serious romance that follows. War
effort or not, Joe soon doesn't have much time for plowing the
fields, for he has his work cut out for him in the hayloft.
</P>
<P>
   The three attractive women compete with the Dorset countryside
for visual attention. They win that skirmish but are frequently
defeated by some of the overripe dialogue they have to deliver. The
picture looks good, with a lot of care taken over period details.
Ultimately, though, the work of the Women's Land Army gets
trivialized, as Leland's script reduces the characters and their
actions into formula hokum.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
