<HEADER>
A6341 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPPOSITE-OFSEX26-COX     06-25 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPPOSITE-OFSEX26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bizarre and funny, ``Opposite'' attracts
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Caution: Those who want to like and trust the characters they
watch are going to have a lot of trouble with Dedee Truitt. She's a
precocious, mean-spirited 16-year-old who narrates ``The Opposite
of Sex,'' describing the trouble she stirs up and leaves in her
wake. She's unrepentant bad news, manipulative and trashy, a
refreshingly different comic springboard for a cross-country road
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a heart of gold, and I'm not going to get one,''
declares Dedee (a snide Christina Ricci), playing with our
expectations earned from so many more conventional movie comedies.
We quickly understand, as she desecrates the casket of her
stepfather at his funeral and then leaves her Louisiana home to
live with her homosexual half-brother Bill (Martin Donovan), a
Midwest schoolteacher.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, she is seducing Bill's lover Matt, convincing him
he impregnated her, running away together to California with money
they stole from Bill and the ashes of Bill's former lover. Did I
mention that Dedee is pure trouble? And that that's the only thing
about her that is pure?
</P>
<P>
   So Bill, suspended from his job because of accusations of sexual
abuse from a jealous ex-student, heads westward in pursuit. He is
accompanied by teaching colleague Lucia (``Friends''' Lisa Kudrow),
the angry, repressed sister of Bill's ex-lover, who pines for Bill
to notice her romantically. Also on the trail is a droopy-eyed
sheriff (Lyle Lovett, showing no signs of learning to act) and
Randy, a Southern twerp with a genital abnormality who happens to
be the real father of Dedee's baby.
</P>
<P>
   Add a little water, stir vigorously, and you've got the makings
of a modern day screwball comedy. Writer-director Don Roos (whose
scripts range from ``Boys on the Side'' to ``Love Field'') keeps
juggling these diverse, ditsy elements and keeps coming up with
deliciously deadpan dialogue for Dedee. Among his merry devices is
having her narration mess with the audience's minds, as she lies to
us, sees how far she can go, then erases what we've just been shown
and returns _ briefly and reluctantly _ to the truth.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of this satirical stew, there are also some pointed
observations about gays, homophobia, sexually active teens and
abortion. While it is easy to feel superior to these wayward souls,
``The Opposite of Sex'' keeps landing rabbit punches of
recognition. And when we see the lengths to which these characters
go because of sex, we can certainly understand why Dedee concludes
that she wants the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   This is a far cry from ``The Addams Family'' for Ricci, who
gives the movie a poisonous spark and is sorely missed when not
onscreen. Between this and her chilling performance in ``The Ice
Storm,'' she has truly made that treacherous transition from child
star to adult actress. Also eye-opening is Kudrow, who _ for the
first time, it seems _ does not fall back on her dumb blonde
shtick. The rest of the cast _ except for Lovett _ is on target
too, which suggests Roos works well with actors or he's got great
instincts for casting.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Roos is a filmmaker to keep an eye on. And Dedee
Truitt is a character worthy of a sequel.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
