<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6352 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIND-NOT-GONE26-COX     06-25 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIND-NOT-GONE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Frankly, ``Wind'' still a tour-de-force
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back on theater screens for the first time since 1989, ``Gone
With the Wind'' looks good, sounds good and remains an almost
completely absorbing experience.
</P>
<P>
   What animates this great melodramatic war horse of the movies,
beyond the splendor of the romantic setting, and what keeps it
continually interesting for nearly all of its 222 minutes is the
struggle for supremacy between two strong-willed, egocentric,
thoroughly selfish adults.
</P>
<P>
   The battle between Scarlett and Rhett involves property, status,
money, power and sex. Basically, she's a manipulative bitch, and
he's a bastard. But _ and this is no small thing _ he loves her. In
their self-absorption and lack of pieties, they're a startlingly
modern couple.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at it for the first time in nearly 10 years, two things
struck me about the film itself as opposed to its presentation
(more on that in a minute).
</P>
<P>
   First, the amazingly propulsive story-telling. Every scene
advances the story, and nearly every shot. The script is reasonably
literate, often wry, and manages the difficult task of integrating
its central characters into a believably vast panorama.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the quality of the acting. Vivien Leigh has always been
regarded as first-rate, but Clark Gable is at least as good. Gable
had the narrow range common to most movie stars, but within that
range he was capable of considerable variations.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, Gable always played a lovable tomcat. But in ``Gone
With the Wind,'' when he has to handle a fair amount of the kind of
thankless expositional dialogue usually given to supporting
players, Gable does it beautifully. The man was a total pro. Beyond
that, Rhett's anguish over the death of his daughter remains
completely convincing. Gable's performance has snap, energy and
passion, he moves well, and, God knows, looks fantastic.
</P>
<P>
   What doesn't work? As always, it requires a distorting
suspension of disbelief to believe that a woman of Scarlett's
wiliness and erotic energy could carry such a strong torch for the
hapless Ashley Wilkes _ one of the worst parts ever written, which
Leslie Howard is helpless to disguise.
</P>
<P>
   (By contrast, Olivia de Havilland's Melanie, a stock,
one-dimensional part, is nearly believable and rather touching.)
</P>
<P>
   What about the technical changes in this revival? The use of
dye-transfer Technicolor for the new prints shows up most
prominently in grace notes _ the creamy complexions, the vibrance
of a red hair ribbon, the electric blue of a sash, the amazingly
black blacks.
</P>
<P>
   The digitizing of the soundtrack has largely avoided the
artificial and unpleasant sharpness that can result from that
process. The new print offers more of a bass range than is common
in soundtracks from the '30s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone With the Wind'' remains an ultimate example of the dream
factory at its best.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6353 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MODEL-T26-COX     06-25 1644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODEL-T26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A way back machine
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The barber's tale had the ring of urban
legend.
</P>
<P>
   He'd heard about a wealthy man who was so fascinated by Model A
Fords that he tried for years to collect one in every shape and
style: sedan, convertible, pickup truck, you name it.
</P>
<P>
   They're all hidden in warehouses, the barber said, right here in
Palm Beach County. Fifty or more old cars, covered with tarps but
ready to run. The owner hates publicity. Probably no point trying
to talk to him.
</P>
<P>
   All the barber could offer to back up his story was the vague
location of a long-shuttered storage yard, and this advice: ``If
you can find the place, look around for a man named Mouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding the place took three tries.
</P>
<P>
   Way back beyond the road, beyond the weeds, beyond the broken
asphalt and the thick line of knotted trees stood a row of
signless, numberless warehouses so worn and weathered you might
miss them if you drove past a hundred times.
</P>
<P>
   And in the withering heat of the second bay, wrench in hand and
bandanna around his head, stood a slim but sinewy mechanic with
biceps toned by the weight of so many cast-iron engines and steel
fenders: ``Mouse'' Walborn.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 12 years now, Walborn _ who does not remember when
people stopped calling him Mike, much less why _ has opened shop at
7 a.m., seven days a week, and resumed the work of recreating an
era.
</P>
<P>
   After a bit of talk, and a couple of promises, Walborn put down
his tools long enough to roll back the big warehouse doors and
reveal his employer's remarkable secret: a movable document of life
and commerce during the most trying of modern times.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, Walborn uncovered what could be every car and truck
parked on any Main Street in the United States in 1931, second full
year of The Depression. ``Now you know how people lived back
then,'' Walborn said.
</P>
<P>
   Not just how they lived, but how they played, worked and died.
</P>
<P>
   He first uncovered an elegant, open-topped DeLuxe Phaeton with
rich leather seats, a car to defy the worst of times. Next, a coupe
with a sure cure for dour mood: a rumble seat.
</P>
<P>
   Then he uncovered a telephone repair truck, with tools and wires
ready to be strung. Then a milk truck, with crates and bottles; a
police car, with siren and spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   An open-back truck that carried cows to slaughter. A closed one
that carried the meat to butcher shops.
</P>
<P>
   An ambulance, a school bus, a United Parcel Service van, a
hearse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday, when people see this, they'll understand that time
and the people a lot better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has been waiting quite a while for that someday and has no
idea how much longer it will be. The goal is to build a museum to
preserve these cars and showcase those times, but where and when
are really up to The Boss, and he isn't close to working out those
details.
</P>
<P>
   The Boss is how Walborn refers to the man who pulled into a Palm
Beach gas station more than 20 years ago in a green Model A coupe.
Walborn was the station's mechanic, a trade he took up after years
on the road as trumpet-playing band leader of Mouse and the
Matadors. The man liked Mouse's work enough to come back with his
next Model A and the one after.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he hired Walborn full time, gave him a stack of
credit cards and checks and told him to buy more cars and hire
whomever else he needed to restore them. Walborn pointed out that
he was hardly an expert on Model A's. The Boss told him to become
one.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Walborn has at least three and often as many as six
people helping him grind, mill, sand and paint _ and 56 Model A's
to keep them busy.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of a handful of rusty shells, they all run
fine and many look better than new. Keeping them road-worthy is an
essential part of the job, because Walborn never knows when The
Boss will show up and call for the tan phaeton or the blue-green
convertible pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cars are meant to be driven, and he drives them,'' Walborn
said. ``So do we.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the only way to keep the batteries charged and the
bearings lubricated. Every day, Walborn and crew take one or two
Model A's out for a ride, twisting knobs and pulling levers in a
rhythmic routine that would confound anyone who learned to drive in
a modern car.
</P>
<P>
   A Model A driver adjusts the timing, sets the choke, raises or
lowers the idle and, most important in a car with no fuel pump,
opens a valve that lets gasoline flow from a tank mounted behind
and slightly above the engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, even we forget to open the valve and the car won't
start,'' Walborn said. ``And if you forget to close it, you come
back to the car and find a big puddle of gasoline and none in the
tank.''
</P>
<P>
   People stare, shout, wave and insist on sharing stories about
Sunday rides and first dates. From time to time, someone follows
them back to the shop, and then others are sure to come after.
</P>
<P>
   The Boss has two problems with that: There's still work to be
done, and he worries that vandals will ruin what's already been
accomplished. So The Boss was willing to be interviewed, but only
if the cars' location was kept secret, along with his name.
</P>
<P>
   He enjoys showing his cars to fellow Model A owners, but he
doesn't want to be bothered by speculators who want to buy his cars
or sell him theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has no taste for publicity, The Boss is no recluse.
At 60, he's still active in business and sport, dividing time
between Palm Beach and favorite hunting spots. Except for his
hunting truck, he drives nothing but Model A's, like the car he
learned to drive in.
</P>
<P>
   He has no idea what he has spent on his cars or their
restoration and upkeep and doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   While rising labor costs have shifted old-car restoration
heavily toward more unusual and expensive cars, The Boss is
interested only in 1930 and '31 Model A Fords. ``It's an aesthetic
consideration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His practiced eye recognizes them as slightly rounder and more
rakish than the 1928 and '29 models. Brand new, in a profusion of
striking colors such as Andalusite Blue and Rose Beige, they sold
for as little as $435. Nicely restored roadsters often sell today
for less than $20,000, little more than some owners invest in
parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never make a business of your hobby,'' The Boss said.
``Whatever you collect, you can't ever expect to sell something for
more than you paid.''
</P>
<P>
   The Model A was the successor to the Model T, that tipsy-looking
contraption seen flickering down rutted roads in old movies. The
Model T put America on wheels, but the Model A kept it there when
the bottom dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Ford, who showed no more regard for alphabetical order
than for other people's ideas about cars, made the Model A more
complicated and comfortable than the Model T, but it was just as
rugged and nearly as popular.
</P>
<P>
   In four years, including two that followed the stock market
crash of 1929, Ford sold more than 4 million Model A's. In a
country with twice the population, Toyota would need 10 years to
sell that many of today's best-selling car, the Camry.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just proliferation that infused America with Model
A's, it was permutation. As different as they look, all the cars
and trucks (known as Model AA's) are built around the same
40-horsepower, four-cylinder engine and basic mechanical parts.
</P>
<P>
   There are still thousands of Model A's running, but The Boss has
given Walborn a challenge that past success makes more difficult:
finding new ones different from the rest. He figures there were
more than 120 body styles but doesn't know how many still exist.
</P>
<P>
   The latest acquisition is the milk truck, with familiar stand-up
driving position, from the Rockford Dairy in Illinois. It's the
first addition in three years, and there won't be another until the
next really different Model A is discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the distinctions are easy to spot: Tudor or Fordor
sedans; open cars or closed. Others, such as the difference between
Standard and DeLuxe models, demand study.
</P>
<P>
   It's the commercial vehicles that are truly distinctive. The
taxi, for example, is one of only 10 built. The lettering, Capitol
Cab, faithfully follows the original, as does the trim on every
truck that could be read or discovered through research. Others are
whimsical: Gwen's Catering is a salute to a friend's cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Walborn has chased down cars all over the country, following
leads from classified ads and from other collectors. The best
prospects are often the least convenient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to Montana when it was freezing and Wichita Falls
when it was 100 degrees,'' Walborn said.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he's made friends and gained notice. A man called
from Germany recently to ask for help aligning a Model A's doors.
``I told him it was a little hard to tell what the problem was from
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At 48, Walborn has no plans except to find more Model A's and
keep working on the ones already in the collection. There is no
end, in sight or beyond, because a restored car does not stay
restored forever. One or the other will always need new paint or an
overhauled motor.
</P>
<P>
   The deterioration is accelerated by the heat and humidity of the
warehouses, with further damage caused by rats and wild cats that
scratch the paint and upholstery. But Walborn shows no sign of
exasperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no stress to this, because The Boss just says to do
what needs to be done, and he leaves it up to me,'' Walborn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stress is working for some guy who's screaming that he wants
his Porsche right now,'' he said. ``Stress is fixing the guy's car,
and then he doesn't pay you. Here, if a fender gets scratched, it
just gives us something to do tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6354 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN26-COX     06-25 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When windows opened
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The Sun Belt owes its prosperity to air
conditioning. Few normal people would choose to live where it
starts getting into
</P>
<P>
   the triple digits in Spring and doesn't even cool down that much
at night.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the walk to the car, people can ignore the summer
heat in this part of the country. We travel in air-conditioned
cars, work
</P>
<P>
   and shop in air-conditioned buildings and eat our meals, watch
television and sleep in air-conditioned homes.
</P>
<P>
   But we can't ignore the heat when the air-conditioner goes out,
as it did the other night at the home of a Colorado ex-patriot and
colleague.
</P>
<P>
   Even though I am descended from generations of questionably
normal relatives who chose to live in this sweltering heat, I know
how my Rocky Mountain colleague felt sweating through the night
without air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a boy, no one I knew had air conditioning. I had a
bed on a screened sleeping porch in one house. That was a darned
good even when it didn't get below 80 at night.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes when the house refused to cool at night, and if the
mosquitoes weren't too bad, we drug our mattresses out in the back
yard under the Texas stars and hoped for a slight breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone back then slept with the doors and windows open. Those
who could afford it kept oscillating fans trained on their beds.
</P>
<P>
   Some people hung wet sheets over a window. Others put wet sheets
on their beds, a cooling trick I never liked. Sheets got wet enough
with sweat.
</P>
<P>
   A block of ice in front of an electric fan would have been an
excellent primitive air conditioner except no one could afford such
luxury. Ice was considered expensive and was needed for the icebox.
</P>
<P>
   The coolest place anyone could go in the days before air
conditioning was the ice house, a miraculous refuge from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Most towns of moderate size had an ice house. Before air
conditioning and before average homeowners could afford electric
iceboxes (later
</P>
<P>
   known as refrigerators), ice was in such demand that the owner
of the ice house was often the richest man in town.
</P>
<P>
   Later when we moved into town, some homeowners installed devices
in windows that dripped water over screens in front of a powerful
fan. Those devices were used in many stores. Some motorists
installed small, ugly units on their cars. I seem to recall those
devices were called evapo-transporaters.
</P>
<P>
   Houses before the days of air conditioning had tall ceilings to
allow the heat to rise. In the evening, people gathered on porches,
sipped ice drinks, told stories and sometimes turned a bucket of
homemade ice cream while the children scurried about tiring
themselves out before bed.
</P>
<P>
   Poster-board fans stapled to tongue depressors were popular,
especially with women. The fans were tucked in with the hymnals in
church pews but
</P>
<P>
   often found their way home. Funeral parlors liked to put their
advertising on those fans.
</P>
<P>
   Every school kid knew how to fold a sheet of notebook paper into
a handy fan for those days when the classroom was like a sweat
lodge and the heat-rashed teacher was just one spitball away from a
pressure-cooker explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Families also used to go for car rides just to catch a cooling
breeze.
</P>
<P>
   In the days before cars, I suppose it was buggy rides. The first
``conditioned air'' stores and movie theaters were indeed a wonder.
It was like watching a movie in the ice house.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses with air conditioning quickly got a lot of business.
Finally, air conditioning window units became common in houses.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners lowered their ceilings for cooling efficiency. New
homes were built with air conditioning in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Now few people can imagine how anyone lived in this heat before
air conditioning, including me.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNeth(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
