<P>
   MOVIES-BETTE _ Review of ``Cousin Bette,'' with Jessica Lange.
It's a comedy of ill manners based on the Balzac book of the 1840s.
Grade: A-. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-SEX _ ``The Opposite of Sex,'' with Christina Ricci, Lisa
Kudrow. Ricci heads an odd group of people looking for contentment
in an immoral '90s. Grade: B+. (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-SIGHT _ ``Out of Sight,'' with George Clooney. He plays a
career bank robber who tangles with a federal marshal (Jennifer
Lopez). Grade: A-. (Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8
p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-LANDGIRLS _ Review of ``Landgirls.'' A film set in 1940s
Britain that look at the city girls who became farmhands to help
the war effort. Grade: C. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-SILENCE _ Review of ``Beyond Silence,'' an
Oscar-nominated German feature about the struggles of a deaf father
to understand his hearing, musician daughter. Grade: B+. (Ringel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-SEAGO _ Internet interview with Howie Seago, the deaf
actor who stars in ``Beyond Silence.''
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-DOOLITTLE _ Eddie Murphy talks to the animals. Review.
(StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES
</P>
<P>
   DR-DOLITTLE _ Forget any memories you have of a dry-as-sherry
Rex Harrison in the 1967 original. With lots of help from some
furry friends, Murphy turns the 1998 ``Dr. Dolittle'' into a
bust-a-gut delight that will appeal to kids and adults alike.
(Passy, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DR-DOLITTLE-DAYTON _ Eddie Murphy launched his monumental
comeback with a remake of Jerry Lewis' The Nutty Professor, for
which he earned a Golden Globe best-actor nomination. But the songs
in Murphy's sporadically amusing, non-singing ``Dr. Dolittle''
update have been replaced by ``litter box'' humor that's much too
crude for small children, earning the Betty Thomas-directed film a
PG-13 rating. (Larsen, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COUSIN-BETTE _ Honore de Balzac's aim was to document every
aspect of the confusing period before the Revolution of 1848. He
did so with a ferocious energy, knocking out book after book filled
with insecure aristocrats, avaricious bankers, ambitious
courtesans, wan artistes _ and in his novel ``Cousin Bette,'' one
very vengeful spinster. ``Cousin Bette'' is now a film starring
Jessica Lange, and it takes the ``comedy'' bit very seriously.
(Schwan, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LAND-GIRLS _ Not all women who joined the work force in World
War II became Rosie the Riveter. Instead of heading into factories,
some plucky lasses volunteered to farm, as the well-meaning but
mawkish movie ``The Land Girls'' illustrates. It should have been
about women in detergent plants, because it quickly degenerates
into a soap opera. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OPPOSITE-OFSEX _ Caution: Those who want to like and trust the
characters they watch are going to have a lot of trouble with Dedee
Truitt. She's a precocious, mean-spirited 16-year-old who narrates
``The Opposite of Sex,'' describing the trouble she stirs up and
leaves in her wake. She's unrepentant bad news, manipulative and
trashy, a refreshingly different comic springboard for a
cross-country road picture. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WIND-NOT-GONE _ Back on theater screens for the first time since
1989, ``Gone With the Wind'' looks good, sounds good and remains an
almost completely absorbing experience. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   DIARY-EYMAN _ ``Bridget Jones's Diary'' was last year's
must-read in England and is being touted as this summer's must-read
here. It began as a weekly newspaper feature and seems ready-made
for a movie. It's a year in the life of a 30-something girl mired
in mid-level publishing, whose biological clock is resounding like
Big Ben. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADE-RESTORATION _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The federal plan
to save the Everglades depends on the untested practice of storing
up to 1.7 billion gallons of water underground every day during wet
years and pulling it back up during dry times. Never mind that
federal regulators at the highest levels are agonizing over the
idea of injecting untreated _ and possibly tainted _ lake water
into underground drinking sources. (Engelhardt, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADE-RESCUE _ A half-century ago, weary from an unending
cycle of flood, drought and fire, South Florida residents asked
Washington to build them a barrier against the extremes of nature.
It worked. All too well. Now, the Everglades strangled in its
man-made straitjacket. Now the engineers say it's time to start
over. They want to redesign the entire drainage system.
Environmentalists call it the Everglades' last chance. (King, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NO-FIREWORKS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Celebrate your liberty
this Fourth of July by setting off a bottle rocket anywhere in Palm
Beach County and you might wind up under arrest. But only if a law
enforcement officer actually sees you light the fuse. (Hayes, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WATER-SWT _ SAN MARCOS, Texas _ As Central Texas continues to
swelter under a merciless June sun and water becomes an
ever-more-precious resource, a 6-inch-wide pipeline behind a
popular seafood restaurant is creating watery battle lines in the
city. Construction of the pipeline comes at an especially sensitive
time, as temperatures around the state inch up and aquifer levels
steadily drop. (Rodriguez, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MODEL-T _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ For more than 12 years now,
``Mouse'' Walborn _ who does not remember when people stopped
calling him Mike, much less why _ has opened shop at 7 a.m., seven
days a week, and resumed the work of recreating an era. One by one,
Walborn uncovered what could be every car and truck parked on any
Main Street in the United States in 1931, second full year of The
Depression. (Kalajian, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SOMETHING-OLD _ Dietrich became Mrs. Russell Warner during a
brief ceremony at the nursing home where they met less than two
years ago. It was the first wedding anyone remembers at the Port
St. Lucie, Fla., Convalescent Center and the staff did everything
they could to make it a memorable one. (Nesmith, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-KHAKIS _ To distinguish yourself from the khaki-clad
masses, you've got to complement those tan pants with black, Jack.
(Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED 6/24. EMBARGOED UNTIL
6/28.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-WATCHES _ Whether you run a marathon or sun yourself at
the pool this July Fourth, celebrate your fashion independence in
patriotic colors. (Johnson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
6/24. EMBARGOED UNTIL 6/28.
</P>
