<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TIANANMEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BRACES FOR TIANANMEN SQUARE VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Clinton is walking a political tightrope by
accepting China's official welcoming ceremony overlooking the
98-acre expanse of Tiananmen Square where hundreds of unarmed
pro-democracy activists were killed by army troops in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be the first American president to visit China
since the massacre and is expected to receive the standard
ceremonial welcome for a state visit. The ceremony is scheduled to
begin at 9 p.m. EDT Friday in front of the Great Hall of the People
overlooking the plaza that has been at the heart of Chinese
politics for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision to accept the Chinese salute is evoking a
storm of controversy back home. Congressional Republicans and
Democrats and human rights organizations have condemned his
readiness to participate in a ceremony near the site where
demonstrators erected a towering foam and plaster replica of the
Statue of Liberty before Chinese army troops moved in.
</P>
<P>
   The president will come face to face with that army _ the
People's Liberation Army _ when he reviews ranks of PLA troops. PLA
units will fire the 21-gun salute that welcomes heads of state. A
PLA band will play the Chinese and American national anthems.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Clinton nor Chinese President Jiang Zemin will speak
publicly during the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   For many Americans, the televised image of Clinton taking part
in a ceremony adjacent to Tiananmen Square will be their first
extended look at the site since the televised coverage of the
protests and the aftermath in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The president, arriving in the city of Xian late Thursday to
begin his nine-day visit to five cities, made only an elliptical
appeal for China to broaden human rights. Political issues are
touchy topics in a nation of 1.2 billion people that remains edgy
about organized political dissent five decades after a tumultuous
civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Respect for the worth, the dignity, the potential and the
freedom of every citizen is a vital source of America's strength
and success,'' Clinton told his Chinese hosts at a colorful,
drum-pounding, flag-waving welcome pageant beneath a massive
eight-story gate of a city that rivaled Rome and Constantinople in
the ancient world.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``In this global information age, where both
economic growth and individual opportunity are based on ideas, a
commitment to providing all human beings the opportunity to develop
their full potential is vital to the strength and success of the
new China, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton flies to Beijing after completing a two-day visit to
Xian.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Chinese authorities rounded up dissidents and
assigned work crews to sweep streets and paint buildings at sites
awaiting Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
   In Xian, police detained Yan Jun, one of 70 Chinese who signed a
letter asking Clinton to meet dissidents during his visit. In the
southern city of Guilin where Clinton stops next Thursday, police
arrested Li Xiaolong, 34, a member of the now-defunct dissident
group Human Rights Voice.
</P>
<P>
   Police, however, permitted tens of thousands of Chinese to line
Clinton's 30-mile motorcade route into Xian from the airport.
</P>
<P>
   At a refueling stop at Elmendorf AFB in Alaska, Clinton
described his approach to China during remarks to Air Force
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to human rights, we should deal respectfully,
but directly with the Chinese,'' Clinton said. ``That's more
effective than trying to push them in a corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton repeatedly defended his decision to take part in the
15-minute official welcoming ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial ceremony takes place adjacent to Tiananmen
Square about 100 yards across a multi-lane boulevard in front of
the Great Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Clinton hopes to deflect criticism back home by
publicly _ and subtly _ urging Jiang to apologize for the crackdown
when the two leaders hold a news conference after the welcoming
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton road tested the approach in a June 11 address at the
National Geographic Society. Chinese leaders ``can only move beyond
the events of June 1989 when they recognize the reality that what
the government did was wrong,'' Clinton declared. ``Sooner or later
they must do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's bid won the support of former Communist Party chief
Zhao Ziyang, who urged Chinese leaders to admit the mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than let it become an obstacle to international
relations, it would be better to resolve the June 4 problem
ourselves voluntarily,'' wrote Zhao, 78, who was ousted as general
secretary of the Communist Party in 1989 after resisting the
crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government has never apologized. The pre-Jiang
leadership appeared on state-run television five days after the
killings to praise the PLA for suppressing a ``counterrevolutionary
rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said Clinton does not plan to meet with
Chinese dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials who stubbornly resisted private U.S. efforts
to shift the welcoming ceremony elsewhere are hailing the Tiananmen
Square ceremony as a sign that U.S-China relations have recovered
from the post-Tiananmen chill.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is important is the visit itself, its symbolic value,'' a
senior Chinese officials told a White House pool reporter. ``It
means that we now can finally leave behind us the problems we have
and open a new era in the relationship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
