<SLUG> BC-DANCE-HARMONY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOSPEL OF PEACE ARISES FROM CONFLICT IN VIETNAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Luciano Perez, raised in the late 1950s in a hard-scrabble
section of Los Angeles, had a vision while stationed in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The killing fields of Southeast Asia in fact changed Perez
permanently. They converted the soldier to a man of peace. His
vision, that skin color and gender should not separate us, that
love should replace violence, became his raison d'etre.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, 47, director of the Inter-Tribal Peace and Healing Center
in Valley Center, Calif., now is hoping to lead as many people as
possible in his quest for world peace. Dance and song are his
primary tools, along with prayer and sweat, as he travels the world
promoting harmony among people.
</P>
<P>
   Perez is of Purepecha Indian and Mexican heritage. He was named
a Lakota chief, a title of the highest respect, two years ago. Six
years ago, coinciding with the 500th anniversary of Europeans'
arrival in North America, Perez completed 40 days of fasting and
praying for a vision, a means by which to deliver his gospel of
peace.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was a four-day dance in southern California
devoted to the principle of unity, the first of what was to become
an annual peace dance. The October dances draw people from many
nations, and for the past three years they have taken place in the
White Mountains of Arizona on land purchased by the Inter-Tribal
Peace and Healing Center.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to make the peace dance available to people unable
to travel to Arizona, Perez is holding versions of the dance this
year throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Next week he will be in upstate New York, leading a three-day
dance for peace amid the fertile, rolling hills near Cooperstown.
The dance, spiritual in nature, embodies Perez's quest for harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sacred, spiritual event for anyone interested in the
`old' ways,'' said Lenny Singer, who owns the property where the
dance will take place. ``Chief Luciano wants to bring together both
victims and victimizers, because he believes it's the only way
indigenous and all people will be able to live in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   While Perez, as a representative of the Lakota nation and
director of the Inter-Tribal Peace and Healing Center, is
particularly sensitive to Native-American issues, his perspective
regarding victims is all-embracing, according to Singer. Indians,
women, people of color, all merit a more level playing field in
Perez's view.
</P>
<P>
   Perez and Singer hope the peace dance will encourage the
participants to take part in a peace walk planned for Sept. 15 in
New York. The walk, being held during the week of the World Street
Peace Summit, an annual United Nations-sponsored event, will start
in Harlem and end at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The walk, just like the peace dance, is about unity and
breaking down barriers between people of different colors and
backgrounds,'' Singer explained. ``This is all part of Luciano's
particular vision, and what he sees as his role in replacing
violence and abuse with love and respect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
