<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CHATEAU MONTELENA, IT'S BACK TO THE FUTURE(S) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL LONSFORD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I saw these consecutive quotes the other day, and talk about
your jarring juxtaposition:
</P>
<P>
   ``Wine is bottled poetry'' _ Robert Louis Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poetry is the devil's wine'' _ St. Augustine.
</P>
<P>
   Wine and poetry _ now there are two subjective topics that could
keep a conversation going for hours.
</P>
<P>
   That came to mind the other day when I ran across this Spanish
proverb couplet:
</P>
<P>
   ``Con pan y vino
</P>
<P>
   se anda el camino.``
</P>
<P>
   (Literally: With bread and wine you can walk your road.)
</P>
<P>
   Well, I guess I could keep on truckin' with those two staples,
although some red meat occasionally wouldn't hurt. Especially if
the red meat was braised lamb shanks and if the red wine was a
California cabernet sauvignon such as Chateau Montelena.
</P>
<P>
   Chateau Montelena dates to the 1880s, but fell dormant for years
before being resuscitated in 1972 by the Barrett family. It gained
instant fame in 1976 when its 1973 chardonnay came in first in the
famous Paris taste-off between top California and French wines. The
Montelena chardonnay, along with the 1973 Stag's Leap Cabernet, put
California on the world map, bending a number of French noses out
of joint in the process.
</P>
<P>
   While Montelena continues to make a fine chardonnay that's made
for food, not for lovers of overextracted white wines, its fame
today rests primarily with its estate cabernet sauvignon.
</P>
<P>
   Winemaker Bo Barrett was in Houston recently to show off a
vertical (consecutive vintages) of the Montelena cabernet, as well
as announce a new futures program for the cabernet. Futures
offerings _ wherein consumers pony up their cash right after a
vintage, usually at a savings _ are designed to allow consumers to
acquire highly allocated wines that might otherwise not be
available. Those offerings also allow the winery to get the money
up front and adjust prices according to market demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think our estate cabernet is underpriced,'' Barrett said,
``but how do you raise prices without abandoning the people who
brought you to the party 25 years ago? It's not the money, it's the
prestige. But the futures offering has to benefit the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the French, particularly the Bordeaux merchants, have
been offering wines this way for eons. Futures offerings in
California are a much newer proposition, and one with a spotty
track record.
</P>
<P>
   There are some pitfalls in a futures offering, not the least of
which is what happens when the vintage is a lousy one?
</P>
<P>
   The current Chateau Montelena cabernet is the 1994 vintage, but
that vaunted vintage has been snapped up. Montelena's distributor,
Republic Beverage, will have the 1995 vintage available this fall.
Estimated retail price will be in the $60-$70 a bottle range.
</P>
<P>
   As for tasting the skein of vintages, I did find a consistency
in style, but the wines did vary by vintages.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest wine was a barrel sample of the 1996 Chateau
Montelena cabernet, which won't be available probably until next
year. Too young and grapey to assess fairly.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest wine was the 1991, which you may find on a stray
restaurant wine list (at a dear price), and it was terrific.
</P>
<P>
   The other outstanding vintage was the 1994, which in a couple of
years (did anyone say the year 2000?) should be hitting its peak.
</P>
<P>
   The 1992 was thinner and a bit acidic, the '93 showed some
leather and tobacco nuances, not unlike an aging Bordeaux, and '95
showed good fruit, but it's a bit young to drink right now.
</P>
<P>
   As for what the future _ not futures _ will bring, the 1997
Chateau Montelena cabernet, Barrett said, is going to be
sensational. ``It's a career vintage.''
</P>
<P>
   But going back to the Spanish proverb: With the '91 and '94
cabernets I nibbled on a piece of bread, the wines were that good,
and I didn't want any palate distractions. The others I drank with
the lamb shank. But with the ``starter'' course, which was some
outstanding raviolis and wild mushrooms, I drank water; I found the
cabernets too hard and iron-fisted for the delicacy of the pasta.
The raviolis and mushrooms would've been excellent with a red
burgundy or pinot noir, though.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lonsford can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and question to
michael.lonsford(at)chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
