<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SMOKE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS FINALLY FREE OF SMOKE FROM MEXICO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The smoke from Mexican forest fires that turned Texas skies a
murky brown for more than a month appears to have paid its last
visit across the border.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rain during recent weeks, combined with the efforts of
more than 1,300 firefighters, has reduced the number of Mexican
fires to 34. Since January, 13,634 fires have consumed more than
1.25 million acres in Mexico, according to the U.S. Agency for
International Development, which is coordinating U.S. firefighting
assistance to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   A patch of smoke from the fires moved across West Texas on
Friday, said Bryan Lambeth, senior meteorologist for the Texas
Natural Resource Conservation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was pretty much the last gasp we're going to see,''
Lambeth said. ``I think it's likely we will not see any more of it
_ for this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather in southern Mexico and Central America has
dramatically changed during the past three weeks, said Steve Fano,
a National Weather Service meteorologist.
</P>
<P>
   A tropical wave moved onto Mexico's east coast at mid-week and
Hurricane Blas was sitting off the country's western coast. Both
systems were pumping moisture into Mexico's dense forests, which
firefighters have found virtually impenetrable. Satellite images
showed much of the fire-plagued states of Chiapas and Oaxaca hidden
beneath clouds on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A report released Tuesday by the Agency for International
Development said only 17 Mexican fires were still considered out of
control as of June 18.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven fires were still listed as ``large priority fires'' _
five in Chiapas, three in the state of Tamaulipas, and one each in
the states of Nuevo Leon, Hidalgo and San Luis Potosi.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent flyovers, which ended June 14, found that fires
in Chiapas and Oaxaca had dramatically declined because of recent
thunderstorm activity, the report said. As recently as Sunday, 2.13
inches of rain fell in sections of Chiapas, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Showers also helped dampen fires in Guatemala, Nicaragua, El
Salvador, Honduras and Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   Satellite images still detected slight traces of smoke moving
along the Pacific coast of Mexico on Monday, but clouds and rain
either hid the remaining haze or had caused it to dissipate, Fano
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm not confident to say any plume of smoke is in
that area of southern Mexico,'' Fano said. ``There may be a plume
hiding in there somewhere but I can't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Texas, the rainy weather in Mexico shows no
sign of moving north, forecasters said.
</P>
<P>
   Even a tropical disturbance in the Gulf of Mexico will likely
bring relief for only the southernmost portions of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brownsville is a little bit excited about it, but for the rest
of us it doesn't look good,'' Fano said. ``If it does keep going
way the way it is going, the southern tip of Texas may see some
relief. But forecasts have it going 100 to 150 miles south of
Brownsville. That won't bring much relief for them.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
