r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-DEMOCRATS-TEX     06-25 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEMOCRATS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DEMOCRATS GATHER IN SAN ANTONIO FOR STATE CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAX B. BAKER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED _ At their convention this month, Texas Republicans were
elated at the idea of Gov. George W. Bush leading a historic
statewide sweep in November, including taking control of the Texas
House.
</P>
<P>
   But as 8,500 Democratic delegates and alternates gathered in San
Antonio's Alamodome on Thursday for their state convention, party
leaders scoffed at the notion of a Bush-led political blitzkrieg
ending Democrats' hold on the House.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are confident of maintaining their control of the
House and predict that they will retake the state Senate after
losing it in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see no evidence of their taking the state House,'' said
Jorge Ramirez, executive director of the Texas Democratic Party.
``They will have a difficult time holding on to what they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say they have recruited a strong slate of candidates
that will help them protect their eight-seat majority in the House,
and they say they are targeting three Republican state Senators for
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   And one Republican political consultant said that although
Bush's message is extremely popular with Democrats and Republicans,
Texas voters also like split-ticket voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common trend is that in rural districts where Republicans
do well at the top of the ticket, Democrats still control the local
offices,'' said Bryan Eppstein, a Fort Worth Republican political
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   In the March primaries, Democrats had 664,690 ballots cast
compared with 597,011 for the Republicans. The Democrats' higher
vote total came despite most of the action being in the Republican
primary.
</P>
<P>
   The theme at the Republican State Convention in Fort Worth this
month was ``Changing the Course of Texas History,'' reflecting the
Republicans' goal of commanding all branches of state government.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish that feat, Republicans will have to hold onto
their majority in the Senate and win eight additional seats to take
control of the 150-seat state House.
</P>
<P>
   Six House seats are up for grabs in November that are being
given up by Democrats, including heavyweights such as Beaumont Rep.
Mark Stiles, Huntsville Rep. Allen Hightower and Gatesville Rep.
Allen Place.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans predict that they will take no fewer than four of
those seats and more likely all six. Depending on the length of
Bush's coattails, the GOP could win as many as 12 new House seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush will have to do poorly to get four or less,'' said
Arlington Rep. Kent Grusendorf, a leader in the Republican Party's
``8 in 98,'' an organization dedicated to winning control of the
Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP is equally upbeat about maintaining control of the
Senate and electing _ for the first time since Reconstruction _ a
Republican lieutenant governor to set the agenda in that chamber.
Rick Perry is the GOP nominee for that post.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are forecasting double-digit gains in the House,'' said
Robert Black, spokesman for the state Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said Republicans are being presumptuous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans are hoping for George Bush to pull voters over
in the House races. They will fail in that,'' Ramirez said. ``The
one thing that is clear is that Bush doesn't have coattails.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent Texas Poll helps proves their point, Democrats said.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush holds a 70 percent to 17 percent lead over Democratic
challenger Garry Mauro, Perry holds only a 3 percentage point lead
over Democratic nominee John Sharp in the race for lieutenant
governor. The margin of error in the poll is plus or minus 3.7
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   In the race for attorney general, Democrat Jim Mattox leads
former Texas Supreme Court Justice John Cornyn, 44 percent to 35
percent, according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are mounting aggressive and well-financed campaigns to
retain the six House seats being given up by Democratic incumbents
, said Rafe Bemporad, a state party spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Ritter, a businessman from a well-known family in the
Beaumont area, is seeking Stiles' seat, and insurance agent and
Vietnam veteran David Lengefeld is putting on a ``first-rate''
campaign for Place's seat, Bemporad said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Democrats are targeting Republican state Sen.
Michael Galloway from The Woodlands for defeat, as well as Bryan
Sen. Steve Ogden and Wichita Falls Sen. Tom Haywood.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Mary Moore is challenging Ogden, who barely defeated
Moore in a special election in 1997. David Bernsen, a former state
transportation commissioner, is expected to run a close race with
Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   Former Bowie Mayor Greg Underwood is taking on Haywood, who was
elected in 1995 in a district that was traditionally a Democratic
stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats will campaign on issues such as education, welfare
reform and tax fairness _ issues that resonate with most of Texas
voters, Bemporad said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the important things that the Democrats have
done this year is articulate where they want to take the state in
the future on issues important to voters,''Bemporad said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have concrete ideas that will help families. The
Republicans haven't done that. All they have is Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
