<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6474 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEDBUD-SURPLUS-0625-$     06-25 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDBUD-SURPLUS-0625-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOME DEFICIT FOES ARE NOSTALGIC FOR RED INK
 &HT;    With FEDBUD-DATA
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a three-decade struggle that included a
national crusade to add a balanced-budget amendment to the U.S.
Constitution, the federal deficit monster has morphed into a budget
surplus. So why, instead of dancing in the streets, are some
thrift-minded conservatives positively glum?
</P>
<P>
   For many of these deficit warriors, it's a hollow victory. After
the long push to shrink government, trim waste and attack fraud,
the red ink has turned black. But the government itself is no
smaller, arguably no less wasteful and still running on billions of
dollars borrowed from the Social Security trust fund reserved for
future retirees.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, without the menacing threat of huge deficits, the
restraint on spending is easing up on Congress and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prospect of a surplus as far as the eye can see has
obliterated the need to cut spending,'' opined Scott Hodge, author
of numerous budget studies for the Heritage Foundation, a
conservative Washington research group. ``It's a missed
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the budget is technically in balance, Hodge and
other fiscal conservatives point out that:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Federal spending continues to climb to historic levels, rising
an estimated $70 billion this year, a 4.3 percent increase that is
more than double the rate of inflation.  &QR;  Revenues are soaring
toward a new historic high, consuming at least 20.4 percent of the
gross domestic product this year. It is this largely unexpected
windfall of tax receipts from the booming U.S. economy _ not
spending cuts _ that produced the first balanced budget since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The big federal bureaucracy has survived largely intact.
Although the federal work force has been trimmed by 300,000
workers, Republicans did not fulfill their promises of dramatic
cutbacks when they won majority control of Congress in 1994. Not a
single major agency has been closed, and when House Budget Chairman
John Kasich, R-Ohio, made a run this spring at closing the Commerce
and Energy departments, he was criticized by lawmakers in his own
party and dropped the plan.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Massive waste and mismanagement continues largely unabated, as
documented by a steady flow of reports issued by the government
itself. Medicare makes an estimated $23 billion a year in improper
payments, enough to pay for the entire food stamp program. In a
recent attempt to account for all of the government's assets, the
Federal Aviation Administration could not find $245 million in
spare parts, and the Navy could not immediately locate 21 vessels.
The Treasury Department was unable to reconcile $100 billion in
transactions among agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, when you have a time when the government has
plenty of money, the urgency to fix these problems is reduced,''
said Stephen Moore, vice president of the Cato Institute, a
Washington-based libertarian group. As exhibit A, he cited the
just-enacted $204 billion highway bill, the largest in history,
with its record-breaking pork-barrel projects that lawmakers
inserted for their home districts.
</P>
<P>
   For Moore and some others, the solution is to reduce the
surpluses before the lawmakers find new ways to spend. ``These
politicians see a surplus and dollar signs are dancing in their
eyes,'' he said. ``A tax cut is a pre-emptive measure to prevent
them from establishing new entitlement programs that got us into
this trouble in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Still others are seeking ways to bring back the specter of the
deficit by reminding the public that it has never really gone away.
Forecasts show that without huge and growing Social Security trust
fund surpluses, the government's operations will continue to run in
the red for the foreseeable future. However, the ``unified''
accounting system, set up during the 1960s under President Lyndon
Johnson, makes the overall government appear to have a surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Although some lawmakers have discussed taking the trust fund out
of the deficit calculations, there has been no serious attempt by
congressional leaders to change the accounting system, which
critics see as a shell game to hide the operating deficit. ``We
don't have a surplus,'' said Robert Bixby, policy director for the
Concord Coalition, a non-partisan group that is seeking to reduce
spending and reform Social Security. ``We're actually still running
a budget deficit. It's just that everybody ignores it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need to focus people's attention on is that until we
can balance the budget without counting the Social Security
surplus, we don't really have a surplus to spend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that has been a difficult case to make, said Stan Collender,
a federal budget consultant at the public relations firm of
Fleishman-Hillard Inc. and one of the capital's foremost budget
experts.
</P>
<P>
   Fiscal conservatives are now in a quandary, he said. ``This is
for them what defense hawks felt when the Berlin Wall fell. There's
no enemy out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Mitchell, an economist at the Heritage Foundation,
conceded that balancing the budget has sent his organization back
to the drawing board. ``We just need to focus back on the merits or
demerits of particular government programs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we really wanted to do is shrink the federal government
to its proper constitutional functions,'' he said. ``But we sort of
used the deficit as the reason, and it's come back and it's bitten
us.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
