<HEADLINE>
`OUT OF SIGHT' IS ENTERTAINING, CHARMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's definitely something in the air this movie summer.
Filmmakers seem to be serving notice they're sick to death of the
formulas and cliches that have ruled the multiplexes for the past
two decades and they're not going to take it any more.
</P>
<P>
   And this revolution, if that's what it is, is not coming from
the independent, art or foreign film scene, which is still very
much mired in mediocrity. It's coming from mainstream Hollywood,
and films like ``The Truman Show,'' ``Bulworth,'' and even ``The
X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest example of the phenomenon is ``Out of Sight,'' which
is the movies' umpteenth version of an Elmore Leonard novel in
recent years, done, in fact, by the same screenwriter (Scott Frank)
and production team that gave us the 1995 Leonard-adaptation, ``Get
Shorty.''
</P>
<P>
   But this time out, their film is visually innovative,
structurally fragmented, cavalier in its attitude toward plot, and
determined to go against expectations at every turn. It's very
close to one of those Robert Altman genre deconstructions of the
'70s, only more entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   The story is about a charming bank robber (George Clooney) and a
beautiful federal marshal (Jennifer Lopez) who met cute one night
in the trunk of a car (yes, that's right) when he's escaping from a
Florida prison and she's briefly taken hostage.
</P>
<P>
   They can't stop thinking about one other, and the rest of the
movie has her chasing him as he moves from Florida to snowy Detroit
and wanders through a complicated scheme to steal some diamonds
from a Mike Milkin-like Wall Street tycoon (Albert Brooks).
</P>
<P>
   But the movie cares less about the credibility of its plot than
perhaps any major Hollywood movie in years. And director Steven
Soderbergh (``sex, lies and videotape'') goes for a bewildering,
three-part, non-linear structure, flashing back and forth between
the present and two of the hero's past prison sentences.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the film assiduously avoids all the little
audience-pleasers and de rigueur scenes that have become the
cliches of the romantic thriller genre. When the plot calls for a
mass murder, for instance, Soderbergh is happy to not rub our faces
in it: he merely implies what happens with a few hasty visual
symbols.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, ``Out of Sight'' is that rare Hollywood movie of the
'90s that is not afraid to operate off the energy of its romance.
The only motivation the characters really have in the script is
that they're crazy for each other. Not surprisingly, the best scene
in the movie is an impressionistic but sexy love scene.
</P>
<P>
   Does it work? Maybe not for everyone. Audiences of the '90s are
so conditioned to formula conventions that the structure, pacing
and even the glossy, surreal visual style of the movie (it often
looks computer-animated) are probably going to put a lot of people
off. In many ways, it's a demanding movie, especially in its first
act.
</P>
<P>
   Those willing to be stay with it, however, will be rewarded with
a film that's funny, sophisticated and packed with irresistible
dialogue and delightful supporting performances (especially Dennis
Farina as Lopez's over-protective father). It's probably the
movies' best evocation to date of the distinctive world of Elmore
Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   It's also one terrific star vehicle. Soderbergh seems to have
taught George Clooney that, on the big screen, less is always best,
and, for the first time in five tries, he actually comes off as an
appealing, high-octane movie star. Jennifer Lopez is even better _
tough, vulnerable, poetry-in-motion. Together, they make a most
combustible team.
</P>
<P>
   Out of Sight. Directed by Steven Soderbergh. Screenplay by Scott
Frank. Cast: George Clooney, Jennifer Lopez, Ving Rhames, Albert
Brooks. Universal. 120 minutes. Rated R for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
