<HEADLINE>
LITTLE FEELS NEW IN UPDATE OF `DR. DOOLITTLE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1967 family film ``Dr. Dolittle,'' which starred the suavely
arrogant English actor Rex Harrison as a doctor who can talk to
animals, had only marginal charm.
</P>
<P>
   So it's hard to figure why either star Eddie Murphy _ who seemed
to be making a comeback after ``The Nutty Professor'' _ or Betty
Thomas, the director of such surprise hits as ``Private Parts'' and
``The Brady Bunch Movie,'' would have much interest in doing a
remake of a mediocre movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Dolittle'' has been updated with a '90s sensibility, but
outside of throwing in endless scatological references (the word
``butt'' is uttered at least 10 times), sexual innuendos as prime
jokes and a vogue soundtrack that includes Aaliyah and Twista &AMP; The
Speed Knot Mobsters, there's very little that feels new or
contemporary about it.
</P>
<P>
   In its heart, it still extols the virtue of good old-fashioned
family values, individuality and honesty over greed.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Dolittle has the capacity to communicate with animals _
an ability he suppressed in childhood but which has suddenly
re-surfaced. It's wreaking havoc on his medical practice, which is
about to be bought out by a big company, his family and his life.
</P>
<P>
   But his four-legged patients are thrilled by the fact that they
have a human to communicate with and to share their complaints
about aches and pains and woes at living in a world run by people
and their unpredictable ways. Dr. Dolittle must decide whether to
forego wealth for integrity _ and it certainly isn't much of a
surprise which way he goes.
</P>
<P>
   Though Murphy is known primarily as an edgy stand-up comedian
and comic actor, he plays the title role with dull restraint and
reserve. He brings so little of his usual flair and characteristic
humor to the part that it feels as if any actor could have filled
the lead. He definitely takes a backseat to his furry friends.
</P>
<P>
   Though the animals are the real stars of the show, even they
feel contrived and ordinary. There have been so many recent films
that feature talking animals _ ``Babe,'' ``Paulie,'' ``Look Who's
Talking'' and the upcoming DreamWorks production, ``Antz'' _ that
the idea feels worn and threadbare.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the impressive lineup of voice talent, including Albert
Brooks, Ellen DeGeneres, Chris Rock, John Leguizamo, Jenna Elfman
and Garry Shandling (among others), there's very little originality
or creativity to the story and the humor is tepid.
</P>
<P>
   Even its moral message _ that animals have feelings and are our
friends on the planet _ doesn't take hold with any real force.
Though ``Dr. Dolittle'' doesn't put the actors _ or animals _ to
shame, it certainly doesn't have anything exciting to offer either.
It's uninspired, formulaic and doesn't have much bark _ or bite.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dolittle. Directed by Betty Thomas. Written by Nat Mauldin,
Larry Levin. Cast: Eddie Murphy, Ossie Davis, Oliver Platt. 20th
Century Fox. 85 minutes. Rated PG-13 for intense scenes with
animals, animal surgery, sexual innuendo.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
