<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-BOOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN'S BOOKS PROMISE JOURNEYS FULL OF FUN, ADVENTURE AND
LEARNING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JANE P. MARSHALL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Books are Rollerblades and yachts, kayaks and
Explorers, 747s and motorcycles. They take you anywhere in the
world for a summer vacation _ across the street or across the
ocean. The mode of travel is as exciting and varied as the
destination.
</P>
<P>
   Hop aboard.
</P>
<P>
   These new books for children promise many journeys full of fun,
adventure and, yes, learning.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``My Life With the Wave'' (Lothrop, Lee &AMP; Shepard, $16) based
on the story by Octavio Paz; translated and adapted by Catherine
Cowan; illustrated by Mark Buehner. Cowan and Buehner have honored
Paz's wonderful story with this version for children. A young lad,
on his first trip to the beach, falls in love with waves. One
follows him to shore, where they play. The wave wants to go home
with the lad, and, finally, his parents agree. You can imagine the
problems when you live with a wave. This enchanting tale captures
the essence of youth, of summer, of a life led with imagination and
joy.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I Lost My Bear'' (Morrow, $16) by Jules Feiffer. This is a
true story. Ask any parent. Ask any kid. A girl loses her favorite
stuffed animal _ her bear. And she looks and looks. She gets advice
from others on detecting. What an adventure _ a familiar one.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Journey Home'' (Lee &AMP; Low, $15.95) by Lawrence McKay Jr.;
illustrated by Dom and Keunhee Lee. Mai and her mother travel to
Vietnam to search for roots. Mai's mother was a war orphan, and
this is her first trip back to her homeland. Together they learn
who they are and feel the tug of belonging to two places.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Jukebox Man'' (Dial Books, $15.99) by Jaqueline K.
Ogburn; illustrated by James Ransome. Poppaw is a jukebox man.
Every Saturday he takes Donna on his rounds to repair broken
jukeboxes, change records, and empty dimes and quarters from the
money box. They stop at diners, truck stops and fish camps.
Everybody knows Poppaw, and everybody knows Donna's favorite song
is B-6 _ ``Blue Suede Shoes.'' The story and pictures (oils on
paper) take young readers to an unfamiliar time. But the feeling is
familiar. It is that special bond between a child and a grandparent
who takes time to let the child into his world.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Legend of Mexicatl'' (Turtle Books, $15.95) by Jo
Harper; illustrated by Robert Casilla. Harper tells the story of
how the people of Mexico got their name, their flag and their
capital city with clarity and empathy. Young Mexicatl learns, after
a harsh lesson, the difference between being a good leader and a
poor leader as he guides a group of followers from the desert (some
believe the Aztecs came from as far north as Utah) to a lake
surrounded by mountains. They founded the city of Tenochititla'n,
where Mexico City now stands.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``My Father's Boat'' (Scholastic, $15.95) by Sherry Garland;
illustrated by Ted Rand. Garland, a Houston author who specializes
in books for children and young adults about the Vietnamese
culture, has another winner with this story of a
Vietnamese-American boy who spends a day on his father's shrimp
boat. The boat takes them into the Gulf of Mexico, but Father's
story, unwinding throughout the day, takes them to the South China
Sea, where the father and his father learned to be fishermen. The
story is about sharing family history and about not forgetting.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Baba Yaga and the Wise Doll'' (Dutton, $15.99) retold by
Hiawyn Oram; illustrated by Ruth Brown. Just when you wanted to
holler ``enough of the Baba Yaga stories,'' one like this comes
along. It involves child-gobbling toads, a little girl named Too
Nice, and two evil sisters named Horrid and Very Horrid. The
illustrations are as magical as the witch Baba Yaga, who has never
looked so enchantingly devilish. Her toads look even grander.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Mapped Out!: The Search for Snookums'' (Gibbs-Smith, $19.95)
by Carol Baicker-McKee; illustrated by Traci O'Very Covey. This is
a halfway-to-Colorado book. It starts with a lively story of Lon
Stori, who let the iguana he was pet-sitting be pet-napped.
Snookums is no ordinary iguana; it's an endangered Pukapukan iguana
that belongs to Lon's grandmother, the famous naturalist. Lon begs
Bianca Beare, the renowned blind detective who solves most of her
cases from the comfort of her specially constructed rocking chair,
to take the case. The reader takes on the persona of Eyeballs, Ms.
Beare's summer assistant. Eyeballs must be the detective's eyes,
following maps, figuring coordinates, and navigating with compasses
and train timetables. Maps, ransom notes, and other clues to solve
the case and find Snookums come with the book. Kids won't even
realize they are learning. A clever idea cleverly executed.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Summer My Father Was Ten'' (Boyds Mills, $15.95) by Pat
Brisson; illustrated by Andrea Shine. That summer, Father learns a
hard lesson when he and his friends vandalize Mr. Bellavista's
garden. As he rebuilds, he does more than replace the garden. He
builds a friendship and a tradition that he shares each summer with
his son. The watercolors are rich and beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Special Effects in Film and Television'' (DK Publishing,
$17.95) by Jake Hamilton. No, ``Deep Impact'' and ``X-Files''
aren't here, but you can learn how the New York skyline turned
futuristic in ``The Fifth Element,'' how big became bigger in ``The
Borrowers'' and how Jim Carrey bugged his eyeballs out of his skull
in ``The Mask.'' SFX (special effects) also turn men into monsters,
create fake snow and windstorms, and make toys breathe fire. Each
page is heaped with photographs and drawings to illustrate an
amazing world we recognize but don't understand.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Pegasus'' (Morrow, $16) retold by Marianna Mayer;
illustrated by K.Y. Craft. The art, oil over watercolor, captures
the drama and loveliness of this Greek myth urging man to live in
harmony with nature. Mayer expertly retells the story with
compassion and spirit. It's important that children know the real
myths, not just the TV and movie versions.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Cats'' (Kingfisher, $15.95) by Amanda O'Neill. This book
will capture many hours away from the TV. Good. For a cat lover or
a new kitten owner, O'Neill covers cats from myths and magic to
teeth and claws. In typical Kingfisher fashion, illustrations,
photographs and graphics help distribute all this information.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Circus: an Album'' (DK Publishing, $19.95) by Linda
Granfield. Also a nonfiction book for the whole family, ``Circus''
packs facts, photographs, old posters and lore into a tantalizing
look at the big top. P.T. Barnum once said, ``As long as there are
children, there will always be a circus.'' This book feeds the
fascination.
</P>
<P>
   Bon voyage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
