<HEADLINE>
EMERGENCIES EXPLODE ON JULY FOURTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Firecracker warnings have become as much a part of the Fourth of
July as the glare of rockets bursting in the hot night air.
</P>
<P>
   But tummy troubles, scrapes, sprains, bug bites, sunburns and
dehydration are even more likely than bottle rockets or Roman
candles to mar July Fourth celebrations for young children.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital emergency rooms still treat patients of all ages who
have been seriously injured by fireworks, most of them set off by
amateurs, but more families today heed the warnings and let the
professionals handle the fireworks displays, put on by hundreds of
municipalities and organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see fingers torn off by fireworks and burns and wounds to
faces,'' says Dr. Ronald Charles, assistant professor of emergency
medicine at the University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center at
Dallas. ``Clothes can catch on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most serious injuries involve eyes damaged by hot,
burnt-out sparklers, usually considered the safest of fireworks for
children to handle. Also, explosive noises can cause permanent
hearing loss, especially when they are being thrown and explode
near the ear, Charles notes.
</P>
<P>
   Still more common are the all-American boo-boos _ skinned knees,
sunburns, upset stomachs, bug bites and heat complaints _ that
never make it to the emergency room, but can spoil outdoor
activities, says Dr. Paula Elbirt, assistant clinical professor of
pediatrics at Mount Sinai Medical Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Elbirt maintains a Web site (www.drpaula.com), and says she
often answers questions until 2 or 3 a.m. from parents eager to
keep their children happy, healthy and out of harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``July Fourth is the single most busy day of the year for most
pediatric emergency centers,'' Elbirt says. ``We need to address a
wide variety of concerns to keep our children safe and make the
Fourth of July a fun day.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, picnics, barbecues and too many star-spangled
treats spell belly bummers, ranging from common indigestion to food
poisoning. Children may vomit once from too much candy, and the
problem can be solved with plenty of clear liquids and some
children's Mylanta, but if there is fever, rampant diarrhea or
repeated vomiting, the illness should be considered a medical
emergency, Elbirt says.
</P>
<P>
   She recommends a first-aid kit for every outing. For prevention,
it should include a sunscreen with a sun protection factor of 30
and an insect repellent containing DEET.
</P>
<P>
   For treatment, pack adhesive bandages, an ice pack, antibiotic
cream, antihistamine cream such as Benadryl, hydrocortisone, a
lotion to soothe sunburn, tweezers and epinephrine for
life-threatening allergic reactions.
</P>
<P>
   Wine-fortified: The latest dietary supplement, hyped this
summer, is a multiformula vitamin-mineral supplement ``pumped up''
with red wine, green tea and garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Radiance includes a full complement of vitamins and minerals
(including time-released forms of the water-soluble vitamins B and
C for a more prolonged benefit from once-a-day dosing), plus herbs
and ``support components'' such as co-enzyme Q10 and Pycnogenol
(antioxidants), chromium picolinate (to boost metabolism and lower
cholesterol) and ginseng (to enhance energy and improve physical
performance).
</P>
<P>
   The garlic is identified as ``an herb many people have included
in their overall regimen,'' and the red wine and green tea extracts
are included ``for their antioxidant properties.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7687. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) .MDBU/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
