<HEADLINE>
`GONE WITH THE WIND' RE-RELEASE IS TOP DRAWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there was any lingering doubt after the spectacular
theatrical return of the ``Star Wars'' trilogy, the success of the
recent re-release of ``Grease'' should cinch it: the ``first-run''
re-release is going to be a regular feature of the new movie
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   With no new production costs involved and the possibility of a
big payoff at the box-office, the risk of a few restored prints and
a modest ad campaign seems irresistible to the studios. And even if
the re-release flops _ as did last year's ``The Godfather'' _ the
inevitable media hoopla (critics love old movies) promotes the
video re-release.
</P>
<P>
   So in the months and years ahead, we can expect a special
anniversary edition or a director's cut of some great golden oldie
almost every month or so. This weekend we have two: the
technologically retooled edition of 1939's ``Gone With the Wind''
and the director's cut of 1975's ``Picnic at Hanging Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``GWTW'' is, of course, a film that needs no introduction. For
the past 59 years, producer David Selznick's adaptation of Margaret
Mitchell's epic civil war novel has been universally regarded as
the high point of the Golden Age of Hollywood, and the phenomenon
of movie phenomenons, with enough books written about it to fill a
Carnegie library.
</P>
<P>
   It's simply the most popular, most beloved film of all time. In
fact, it was estimated back in the mid-1950s that the total number
of tickets sold for ``GWTW'' was more than the then-population of
the United States. In inflation-adjusted dollars, it far
outdistances its new competitor, ``Titanic'' _ and probably always
will.
</P>
<P>
   The film is also (and this does not necessarily follow from the
above statistics) a genuinely great film, a shattering masterpiece
that just sweeps an audience up and carries it to a different
place. It's been at the top of every critical poll ever taken of
the ``greatest films of all time'' _ even the most snooty European
ones. (Last week's AFI poll put it at number 4.)
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, ``Gone With the Wind'' is the movie that wrote
the book on first-run re-releases. It's enjoyed a successful
national theater re-release in every decade since its debut (except
the '80s, when it finally went to video). Each one of these runs,
in inflation-adjusted dollars, is comparable to the re-issued
``Star Wars'' grosses.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation in the movie trade press is that it could happen
again in the '90s _ despite the film's advanced age and daunting
222-minute running time. The AFI's vote of confidence will help,
and it could be the public's appetite for epic historical romances
has been whetted by ``Titanic,'' which, you may recall, Janet
Maslin of the New York Times dubbed the ``GWTW'' of our time.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the film again for the first time in decades, it
seems almost too good to be true, and certainly superior to
``Titanic'' in every department. It has a script of shocking
subtlety and intelligence, characters of amazing complexity and
depth, movie star performances (Clark Gable, Vivien Leigh, Olivia
de Havilland) of dizzying power and production design so epic and
thrilling it actually gives one goosebumps. It's a love story that
captures a huge chunk of American history in one rapturous,
operatic gulp. It's magic.
</P>
<P>
   The sound on this new print has been digitally reproduced for
greater clarity, and the color has been fully restored (using the
old Technicolor die transfer printing process). Unlike the film's
more recent theatrical revivals in the '60s and '70s, the 1998
``GWTW'' will also be presented in its original aspect ratio of
1:33X1. It's never looked better or sounded so good. Don't miss it.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's second welcome return is ``Picnic at Hanging
Rock,'' Peter Weir's 1975 Australian classic _ adapted from a novel
by Joan Lindsay, but supposedly based on a true story _ about a
trio of schoolgirls and their teacher who inexplicably vanish from
the face of the earth one summer day on a school picnic, circa
1901.
</P>
<P>
   This revival, which is playing one week only at the Varsity, is
being billed as the ``director's cut,'' but instead of the usual
addition of new footage this revised cut has actually lost six
minutes from its original 110-minute running time. Reportedly,
these are a handful of trims here and there to tighten scenes and
speed up the pacing.
</P>
<P>
   The first of Weir's metaphysical masterpieces (the others
include ``The Last Wave,'' and the current Jim Carrey hit, ``The
Truman Show''), ``Picnic'' is one of the great films of the '70s
and a one-of-a-kind experience: a haunting, unsettling drama that
eerily communicates the idea that _ just on the other side of the
ordinary _ there is a vast, unknowable, perhaps malevolent
dimension of existence.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone With the Wind (1939). Directed by Victor Fleming. Cast:
Clark Gable, Vivien Leigh, Leslie Howard, Olivia de Havilland. New
Line/MGM. 222 minutes. Rated G, suitable for all audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _ Picnic at Hanging Rock (1975). Directed by Peter Weir. Cast:
Rachel Roberts, Dominic Guard, Helen Morse, Vivien Gray. 104
minutes. Varsity (one week only). Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
