<HEADLINE>
`THE LAND GIRLS' NEEDS A LITTLE DIRT UNDER ITS FINGERNAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is it about wartime that makes us get all weepy and
sentimental and forget our morals and obligations? Films about
illicit love affairs during battle evoke such forgiving responses
in audiences and filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Think back on John Schlesinger's ``Yanks,'' about the women who
dallied with American soldiers stationed in England, or ``The
English Patient'' and its tale of infidelity _ even the passionate
trysts between Lara and Zhivago in ``Dr. Zhivago'' _ and we're
swept away on a wave of nostalgia and feelings of hope in the face
of death.
</P>
<P>
   The same chin-up nobility and sacrifice wafts through David
Leland's ``The Land Girls,'' partly because the film is a male
fantasy disguised as female sensibility and partly because it's
such an idealized view of the tranquil English countryside
contrasted against the altered state of reality created by war's
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Land Army was formed in 1917 just at the end of
World War I. It boasted 80,000 members at its peak in the 1940s and
``land girls'' were dispensed to every part of England to fill the
jobs left by the men who went off to battle. Most were volunteers
from every class and walk of life. They worked in factories and on
farms to keep England productive and functioning.
</P>
<P>
   Leland, who also directed ``Wish You Were Here,'' based his
script on a book by Angela Huth and it has some appeal despite
glaring problems. It's 1941 and three gorgeous young ``land girls''
have responded to a call for help on a muddy, industrious milk farm
in a remote part of Dorset. Stella (Catherine McCormack) has a
fiance who is in the navy; Ag (Rachel Weisz) is a no-nonsense
Cambridge-bred intellectual and a virgin at 26, and Prue (Anna
Friel) is a flirty hairdresser intent on making the best of a rough
situation.
</P>
<P>
   They're dispatched to the Lawrence farm where Lawrence, his wife
and their son, Joe (Steven Mackintosh), labor to keep the place
afloat. Joe desperately wants to enlist and become a pilot but to
abandon his parents would be fatal to the business. Lawrence at
first disapproves of the ``land girls,'' (``They're not an army,
just an excuse for a lark,'' he says) but soon comes to admire
their uncomplaining willingness to toil and slave in the fields.
</P>
<P>
   They're also willing to bed Joe, who is the only available man
for miles. And this is the most problematic part of the film. The
three women take a tumble with the lucky lad for very distinct
reasons, and since the actresses are good _ as is Mackintosh as the
frustrated son _ they almost make us believe they'd do such a
thing. Still, it's a stretch of the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the problem is the pacing. The story demands a leisurely
unfolding of character and motivation but everything happens far
too quickly _ and conveniently. But the biggest hurdle is the
sanitized world the land girls have come to inhabit. Even death and
deformity is pretty and glamorous on this farm.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine McCormack and Rachel Weisz, especially, make the very
best of very little. Still, the film belongs to a time in history
that has been romanticized out of proportion for the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Leland goes so far as to show white doves floating through the
landscape as a symbol of the peaceful nature and patriotism of the
English. Everyone in ``The Land Girls'' pitches in to make this
cinematic view a scrupulously serene, lush and clean guilty
pleasure that, in all truth, could have used lots more dirt under
its fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   The Land Girls. Directed by David Leland. Written by Keith
Dewhurst, Leland. Cast: Catherine McCormack, Rachel Weisz, Anna
Friel, Steven Mackintosh. Gramercy Pictures. 112 minutes. Rated R
for sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
