<HEADLINE>
`COUSIN BETTE' UNFAITHFUL TO ORIGINAL BALZAC SOURCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even allowing for the major changes that are always necessary
when a great novel is adapted to the screen, the screenplay for
this rather dismal version of Balzac's 1846 novel, ``Cousin
Bette,'' seems strikingly unfaithful to its source:
</P>
<P>
   _ Balzac's entire back story of how Baron Hector Hulot d'Ervy
(Hugh Laurie) ruined his family's reputation and fortune via a
series of scandals is omitted, so the movie has no context. Also
missing is Hector's primary motivation _ to marry one of his
kitchen maids.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hector's wife, Adeline (Geraldine Chaplin) is killed off in
the first scene of the movie, while in the novel she's a major
character, lusted after by Crevel (Bob Hoskins), often conspiring
with her husband's many mistresses, and the drama's one figure of
dignity and sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Josepha, a young Jewish singer in the Opera and a minor
character in the novel, has been combined with the character of
Madam Valerie Marneffe and elevated into a major character who is
not in the novel at all, Jenny Cadine (Elisabeth Shue).
</P>
<P>
   _ Hector's son, Victorin (Toby Stephens), another character in
the novel with some dignity and resourcefulness, is burlesqued and
turned into a fool; Crevel doesn't have a wife and doesn't die of a
mysterious illness.
</P>
<P>
   _ And so on and on.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing the movie takes from Balzac is the central
plot line in which Hector's old maid cousin, Bette (Jessica Lange),
seeks revenge on her relatives after her beloved _ a young Polish
sculptor (Aden Young) _ marries Hector's niece, Hortense (Kelly
Macdonald).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, such a wholesale reworking of a classic would barely
be noticed if it led to some happy cinematic end. But the changes
have only served to broaden and vulgarize the characters, destroy
the novel's uniquely satisfying sense of texture, and so muddle up
the storyline that it's hard to figure out exactly what's happening
at any one time.
</P>
<P>
   First-time movie director (but Broadway heavyweight) Des McAnuff
seems to have gone less for the subtlety and depth of Balzac's
``Comedie Humaine'' than for its characters' occasional
extravagance and for a rapid, almost dizzying pace _ so his film
feels like a ``Masterpiece Theater'' episode run at fast-forward
speed.
</P>
<P>
   Lange is suitably malevolent and passive-aggressive as the title
character, Aden Young is quite funny as the self-obsessed sculptor
and Bob Hoskins supplies a touch of humanity as Crevel. Elisabeth
Shue, with her flat, inexpressive, prototypically American voice
seems to have taken a wrong turn from the ``Leaving Las Vegas''
set.
</P>
<P>
   Cousin Bette. Directed by Des McAnuff. Produced by Sarah
Radclyffe. Screenplay by Lynn Siefert and Susan Tarr. Cast: Jessica
Lange, Elisabeth Shue, Hugh Laurie, Bob Hoskins. Fox Searchlight.
108 minutes. Rated R for sexual situations and nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
