<HEADLINE>
INSPIRATIONAL SUCCESS STORIES MAY CHALLENGE READER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the hot summer sun takes its toll on our body and spirits,
some of us may need a little inspiration. So get something cool to
drink, find a pool (even the inflatable kind) and pick up a copy of
``Unstoppable: 45 Powerful Stories of Perseverance and Triumph from
People Just Like You'' (Sourcebooks, 316 pages, $12.95).
</P>
<P>
   The book is similar in type to the bestselling Chicken Soup for
the Soul series, but richer in detail and fact. I always wondered
if I was reading a true story when I looked at a Chicken Soup book,
and I'm not sure that it was the authors' point to tell one. They
may have just been looking for an illustrative story to match their
ideas of a meaningful life.
</P>
<P>
   But in ``Unstoppable,'' there is little doubt as to the validity
of the stories. For one thing, many of them are about well-known
people and businesses, such as Millard and Linda Fuller, the
founders of Habitat for Humanity; or Paul Orfalea, founder of
Kinko's; or Anita Roddick, founder of The Body Shop.
</P>
<P>
   All have amazing stories of overcoming major obstacles that were
seemingly unsurmountable, yet these people persevered and created
something impressively useful, generally in markets totally missed
by corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the story of Maria Ilena Ibanez, a native of Colombia
who earned a computer engineering degree in the United States
during the 1970s. After graduation, she saw a tremendous market for
personal computers in Latin America, where prices for personal
computers were 10 times what they were in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But all the major U.S. computer companies turned her down,
saying that Latin Americans were poor and couldn't afford even the
cheaper models. Finally, she told Altos Computers that she would
sell $10,000 of their products in a year and the company gave her a
distribution agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In just three weeks, using the Yellow Pages as her sole source
of contacts, she came back to the United States with $100,000 worth
of orders in the form of cashier's checks.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next five years, sales at her company, International
Micro Systems, grew to $15 million. By 1988, when Ibanez sold the
company, sales had reached $70 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly resting on her laurels, Ibanez is doing the same thing in
Africa. Her new company's sales have averaged $13 million in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Ibanez's advice?
</P>
<P>
   ``When you encounter a hurdle _ and I do that every week _ view
it as an opportunity, not the end of the world,'' she says in the
book. ``Do whatever you need to do to get past it quickly. If you
believe in your dream, you'll definitely get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Another woman featured, Sharlyne Powell, developed an exercise
class for overweight women, a market of about 60 million in the
United States. Despite being met with disdain by the fitness
industry, Powell developed the Women at Large fitness clubs and has
sold thousands of fitness videos.
</P>
<P>
   Powell is quoted in the book: ``I haven't done anything anybody
else can't do if they find something that truly inspires them. It
will require taking some risks and possibly subjecting yourself to
ridicule and ignorance. There's always a price. But if you push
through, you can go places you never dreamed you could go.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all stories in the book concern business. One is about a
woman who started writing encouraging notes to ill children after
the death of her son and has developed a booming, but nonprofit,
volunteer service reaching thousands of kids.
</P>
<P>
   Another story tells of an African boy who left his village with
no money, but a dream of attending college in the United States.
Legson Kayira is now a widely acclaimed author and professor of
political science at Cambridge University.
</P>
<P>
   His advice: ``I learned I was not, as most Africans believed,
the victim of my circumstances, but the master of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Author Cynthia Kersey, who has launched several companies and
tours the country speaking on fulfilling careers, has identified
seven characteristics of ``unstoppable people'' and devotes a
chapter to each.
</P>
<P>
   Such people, she says:
</P>
<P>
   _ Devote themselves to their true purpose.
</P>
<P>
   _ Follow their heart's passion.
</P>
<P>
   _ Believe in themselves and their ideas.
</P>
<P>
   - Prepare for challenges.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask for help and build a support team.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seek creative solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Persevere, no matter what the challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stories of these unstoppable dreamers awaken in us our own
potential to dream again, to act on those dreams, and see them
through to the finish line,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They illustrate that anyone _ no matter how difficult their
circumstances _ can achieve their goals and overcome any obstacle,
if only they will commit themselves to doing so. The qualities that
assured their success are qualities that can be learned and
developed by anyone with the will to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6490 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-ASHLAND-SPI &LR;      06-25 2766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-ASHLAND-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASHLAND SHAKESPEARE FESTIVAL HAS GROWN INTO A SLICK, MODERN EVENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOE ADCOCK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHLAND, Ore. _ What started out in 1933 as a shrine of
nostalgic amateurism is now America's premiere destination resort
for innovative theatrical professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   The Oregon Shakespeare Festival used to be quaint and cozy, the
ultimate West Coast Renaissance Faire. Now the festival is
cosmopolitan and diverse, slick and contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   Gone this year is the last vestige of Ye Olde Ashland: dancers
in Elizabethan costumes who cavorted nightly in exhibitions of
antique choreography.
</P>
<P>
   Festival artistic director Libby Appel has replaced them with
modern dance viruosi in sleek unitards. Their work gives a flashy
choreographic preview of themes from that evening's mainstage play.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, her second season as head of the festival, Appel
fired long-time Ashland director Pat Patton. He is now artistic
director of the Tacoma Actors Guild. Patton specialized in
museum-quality productions with actors in full Elizabethan regalia
declaiming in a mid-century Stratford-on-Avon or Stratford,
Ontario, festival style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time the festival has made a change over the years,
there has been an angry outcry from a few people,'' Appel says.
``When the policy of casting fully professional actors began in
earnest there were protests: `They've destroyed everything the
festival stands for! It's supposed to be community theater!' But
the festival has been growing and changing from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   Appel finds vindication in numbers. The festival audience is
getting bigger. Last year set a record attendance of 364,602, the
highest for any American non-profit theater. ``And the way things
are going, it looks as if we may set another record this season,''
Appel says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if Elizabethan costumes are now forbidden. It's
just that they are generally not part of our directors' vision of
Shakespeare in America.''
</P>
<P>
   And so this season the festival is offering ``Midsummer Night's
Dream'' in a Dickensian surrealist mode, ``Henry IV, Part One'' as
a metal dude's excellent adventure, ``A Comedy of Errors'' as a
crazy costume caper, ``Measure for Measure'' as a modern
psychodrama (directed by Appel), and ``Cymbeline'' as a fairytale.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Shakespeare component of the festival. Also featured
are an 18th-century English farce by Richard Brinsley Sheridan, a
19th-century Russian drama by Anton Chekhov and plays by four
20th-century Americans: Eugene O'Neill, Sandra Deer, Lorraine
Hansberry and Ernest Joselovitz.
</P>
<P>
   Rebellion is rife throughout the 1998 repertory. Rebels arise in
medieval Britain and Lithuania, in 20th-century Ireland and Africa,
and even in timeless terrains of fairytale and myth.
</P>
<P>
   First some short reviews of works by that noted playwright
William Shakespeare, 17th-century celebrity and the abiding genius
behind Ashland's 20th-century boomtown legend:
</P>
<P>
   _ A Midsummer Night's Dream. Director Penny Metropolous'
production is total dream: It glides from unnerving nightmare to
erotic fantasia to absurd hallucination. The result is marvelous.
</P>
<P>
   At least the conception and the design are marvelous. Some of
the acting is so vehement that it tatters the subtle vision.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Seattle actor G. Valmont Thomas brings extreme clowning
to bear on the part of Thisbe, the farcical-tragical heroine of a
play within the play. The result is hilarious. Thisbe's sweety,
Pyramus, is played by another dextrous clown, David Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas and Kelly are part of an excellently done low-life plot.
The high-life plot _ romantic foibles among the well-born _ is less
interestingly acted. And the supernatural plot _ jealous
manipulations and hissy fits amongst opposing gangs of fairies _ is
only a little more nuanced.
</P>
<P>
   But the look and feel of this show is what makes it marvelous. A
set by William Bloodgood, with doors 20 feet off the ground opening
out of oddly angled walls, instantly makes unreality real. From
time to time, frantic characters find themselves trapped in a
plexiglass phone booth ... that has no phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alice in Wonderland'' costumes, enhanced by some beyond-punk
gravity-defying wigs, are surreal, as are wild lighting effects and
dreamy musical moments (costumes by Deborah Trout, lights by Ann G.
Wrightson and sound by Jeremy J. Lee).
</P>
<P>
   _ Henry IV, Part One. Director Michael Donald Edwards' take on
this medieval action adventure drama looks like slackers from the
Crocodile Cafe joining forces with suits from the Rainier Club and
heading off for a military mop up of the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is sensational, even if the theme _ nothing like
violence to turn an effete punk into a real man _ is dispiriting.
The hand-to-hand combat, devised by fight director John Sipes, is
spectacular, as are special battle effects contrived by set
designer William Bloodgood and lighting designer Derek Duarte. The
final scenes look like the worst of times in Kosovo or Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   In the central role (a prince who goes from dissolute to
resolute), Dan Donohue makes the implausible seem at least vivid.
Early scenes, outfitted by David Zinn, look like Halloween on
Capitol Hill. Then come scenes that look like a Pentagon show of
the latest looks in mass murder attire.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle audiences may remember actor John Pribyl as a sort of
Marlboro Man who performed at various theaters 10 or 15 years ago.
Pribyl is now an Ashland regular. In a much-padded costume, he
plays a desperately dissolute old hippie, Sir John Falstaff by
name. Pribyl drolly orchestrates the slacker gang's frolics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry IV, Part One'' was presumably inspiring and patriotic
400 years ago. Now it is cynical and disheartening. However, the
play's world-weary presentation of male bonding as a curse benefits
in this production from gorgeous, garish visuals.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Comedy of Errors. Director Kenneth Albers' spectacular
production is so giddy and gaudy that one almost forgets that the
characters are superhumanly stupid.
</P>
<P>
   One of Shakespeare's earliest plays (1594 or thereabouts), ``A
Comedy of Errors'' features two sets of twins, separated at birth.
After about a dozen mistaken identity incidents, you'd think the
four long-lost brothers would put two and two together. But
thinking is definitely not in their bags of tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the various bags of tricks are brimming with goodies.
Albers would seem to be a long-lost Flying Karamazov Brother _ the
one who got all the money. His costume budget is huge. Never before
have so many sequins, fringes, feathers, ribbons, beads and
irridescent everythings been brought together in one place at one
time (costumes by Charles Berliner).
</P>
<P>
   The whole cast clowns madly. Two of the brothers are played by
women, which is novel. Amid the explosions, tumbles and supposedly
comic beatings, one bit of shtick stands out: Terrilynn Towns, as
an eligible bachelorette, clowns with her eyes. They flit wildly,
denoting everything from guilty conscience to innocent lust.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cymbeline. With reason, this Celtic/Roman mishmash of a
fairytale is rarely produced. ``Cymbeline'' is largely a matter
nonsensical people doing nonsensical things. Not only are the
people nonsensical, they are also tiresome. And their nonsensical
doings are boring.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the main character, Imogen, is nicely played by Jodi
Somers. Though Imogen is a sort of combination Snow White,
Goldilocks and Sleeping Beauty, Somers makes the girl's peculiar
behavior pass as youthful passion. Also, Somers speaks loudly and
clearly and expressively.
</P>
<P>
   The plot is absurd. Along the way, true love proves false but
not really and invading Roman legions are defeated by the dotty
King Cymbeline, but they can be friends, anyway. The incidents are
as convoluted and contrived as the Celtic knot patterns with which
designer Richard L. Hay profusely festoons the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Ashland's mandate extends beyond Shakespeare to include works _
classic, modern and contemporary _ that might be called
Shakespearean: ``large in scale and rich in language,'' as the
festival's mission statement puts it.
</P>
<P>
   Among the non-Shakespeare works included in this year's festival
are the following:
</P>
<P>
   _ Vilna's Got a Golem, by Ernest Joselovitz. This is a
fantastic, wonderful play. But unless you dash off to Ashland right
this very minute, you will not see it. It closes on Saturday to
make room for ``Measure for Measure.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe some adventurous Seattle company will produce it.
``Vilna's Got a Golem'' raises issues that are both primordial and
immediate. It is about, so to speak, the kid who takes a gun to
school, the third world country that gets the bomb and the ethnic
cleansers who are at work everywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   It is also about Jews in Europe in 1540 and in 1899. A Jewish
theatrical troupe in Vilna is putting on a play about a about a
Medieval legend, a secret weapon, a killing machine that should
stop pogroms once and for all. As ethnic satire, the show indicts
both Israel's tough-guy policies and assimilated American Jews'
nice-guy, secularist culture.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Barbara Damashek, the drama is at once playful and
horrifying. Peppy klezmer (traditional Jewish dance band) music by
Damashek is performed by an on-stage trio. Joselovitz's achievement
is in the style of the 20th century German theatrical revolutionary
Bertolt Brecht. ``Vilna's Got a Golem'' combines tragedy and ``just
kidding'' reassurances. As Brecht insisted, such a style is
entertaining. But it precludes escape. It makes you think.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vilna's Got a Golem'' makes you think.
</P>
<P>
   _ Uncle Vanya. Libby Appel's staging of this comedy drama by
Anton Chekhov is like a string of firecrackers with a long fuse.
After about 90 minutes of anticipation, the characters explode one
by one _ bang, bang, bang. Actually, the title character goes off
with two bangs.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Elmore is an unusually combustible Vanya. The other
characters seem to become inflamed by his chafing agitation.
</P>
<P>
   The play focuses on a family and their visitors. They are cooped
up in a country house, Russia, summer, late 19th century. Desire
and desperation are in the air. Frustration and fear are on the
ground. The tedium is sometimes tedious.
</P>
<P>
   Appel uses a sleek adaptation by American playwright Jean-Claude
van Italie. The show's only linguistic eccentricity is an arch
English accent used by one of the actors.
</P>
<P>
   Helping to build tension are little visual emblems before each
of the four acts: Vanya asleep atop a grand piano; a wine bottle
and a bucket to catch the rain that comes through a leaky roof; a
bouquet of roses; a map of Africa. Set designer Robert Brill and
lighting designer Robert Peterson help Appel to create a
loaded-and-ready-to-explode atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   _ The School for Scandal. Richard Brinsley Sheridan's 1777
satirical farce is at least more stylish than a two-and-a-half hour
CNN wrap-up of the latest Washington sex 'n' chicanery scandals.
</P>
<P>
   But the talk of London two centuries ago was so similar to
contemporary twaddle that Ashland director Lillian Garrett-Groag's
extremely elegant production might be an enactment of an
extraordinarily well-written edition of People magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Brown's costumes are as fancy as can be, as are settings
by Richard L. Hay.
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan's caricatures, however, are only ludicrous if they are
preposterous. And just now they are not. They are more like
unflinching realism, an expose of hypocrisy, hoaky news leaks and
rampant malice among the high and mighty.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett-Groag finds funny things for a platoon of servants to
do. The menials' clowning is at least an improvement over the long
faces presented in interviews with White House underlings.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes timeliness works in favor of a revival. But this
``School for Scandal'' is too timely: CNN with hoop skirts and
three-cornered hats.
</P>
<P>
   _ Les Blancs. In 1970, this dramatization by Lorraine Hansberry
of African nationalist independence struggles was written off as a
ploddingly literal confrontation between one-dimensional
categories. The one-dimensional categories and the plodding are
still there. But now, nearly every line of ``Les Blancs'' tinkles
with unintended irony.
</P>
<P>
   Hansberry, though living in a time of dirty little wars in Asia
and Latin America, understood and maybe even condoned
anti-imperialist violence in Africa. The actors representing
independence fighters have heroic lines and in Ashland, anyway,
they also have heroic physiques.
</P>
<P>
   But these warrior's faith in ethnic cleansing is anti-heroic in
1998. Starting with a glance at Ruanda and Burundi, circling around
central Africa, and then widening the focus to include the whole
world, one sees very little justification for hatred and violence
other than historical inevitability.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Les Blancs,'' white liberalism, white humanitarianism and
white imperialism; black anti-imperialism, black moderation and
black ambivalence all have their say before historical
inevitability takes over. Director Tim Bond (former artistic
director at the Group Theatre in Seattle) gives ``Les Blancs'' full
honors. The 17 performers are desperately committed to bringing
their respective categories to life. But that commitment is about
as futile as bringing dramatic life to a philosophical dialogue by
Plato.
</P>
<P>
   Jungle outpost settings by Richard L. Hay, costumes by Helen
Qizhi Huang and lighting by Dawn Chiang are all spectacular efforts
to transfuse vitality into a lifeless political tract.
</P>
<P>
   Hansberry is remembered as the author of ``A Raisin in the
Sun,'' which was funny and dramatic and righteous. ``Raisin'' was a
huge success in 1959, when Hansberry was 28. A few unpopular
Hansberry plays, including ``Les Blancs,'' followed.
</P>
<P>
   Hansberry died in 1965. Till the end of her short life, she was
annoyed by the question, ``Why doesn't Lorraine write another
`Raisin'?'' One can understand her annoyance. But one can also
understand why the question came up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sailing to Byzantium. Playwright Sandra Deer mixes civility
and barbarity, senimentality and harshness in this highly literary
drama about the highly literary.
</P>
<P>
   Questions of taste arise: Are the the horrors of World War I and
the Easter 1916 nationalist rebellion in Dublin thrown in as
picante seasoning for insipid incidents and characters? Are famous
and semi-famous and almost famous personages _ poets Ezra Pound and
William Butler Yeats, Irish revolutonary Maud Gonne and novelist
Olivia Shakespear _ exploited to give celebrity sensation to banal
relationships?
</P>
<P>
   I found the show mildly interesting but vaguely distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain, the word ``love'' is spoken as often in
this two-hour play as it is sung in two hours of top 40 pop music
radio. And unrequited love, hopeless love and abusive love are as
prevalent as they are at a country music concert.
</P>
<P>
   Director Chris Coleman's staging of ``Sailing to Byzantium'' is
elegant. All the actors perform fiercely. Linda Alper as Maud Gonne
sings a beautiful bit of an Irish martyrdom ballad. And James
Edmondson, as a staunch and stuffy Englishman, is a refreshing
zephyr in Deer's emotional hot house.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets to Oregon Shakespeare Festival productions range from
$10 for matinees after Oct. 6 to $47 for summertime box seats in
the outdoor Elizabethan Theatre. Standing room at Elizabethan
Theatre is available for $11. The festival offers discounts for
students, seniors and groups. An hour before showtime, unsold
tickets are sometimes available at half price. The festival box
office number is 541-482-4331.
</P>
<P>
   The festival operates three theaters: the 600-seat Angus Bowmer,
the 1,200-seat open-air Elizabethan and the 140-seat Black Swan.
Productions at all three theaters continue through the end of
October. In addition to dramatic productions, the festival offers
lectures, exhibits, play readings, concerts and tours.
</P>
<P>
   The festival is not the only live entertainment in the Ashland
area. The slickest of the so-called ``off bardway'' enterprises is
the Oregon Cabaret Theatre in Ashland. The current production is a
nostalgic musical farce, ``Song of Singapore.'' Tickets are
$12-$21. Dinner, drinks and desserts are available; 541-488-2902.
</P>
<P>
   The Shakespeare festival brochure, available by calling the box
office, includes information on accomodations, camping, golf,
shopping, child care, river trips, tours, exhibitions and
restaurants throughout the Ashland region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
