<HEADLINE>
WALTER LIKES WESTPHAL, BUT NOT LABOR STRIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a guy who thinks UCLA remains the center of the universe,
Bill Walton's willingness to even talk about ex-Trojan Paul
Westphal is, for him, a considerable descent from the mount.
</P>
<P>
   Then to offer him a compliment, well ... will boiling oceans and
flaming skies be next?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how much integrity he has?'' Walton said. ``He turned
down John Wooden.''
</P>
<P>
   In Walton's mind, Westphal did the unimaginable. As a
well-regarded prepster from Aviation High in Los Angeles in the
late 1960s, Westphal chose USC over UCLA, where he could have
studied under the coaching legend, not to mention teaming with
Walton for a season.
</P>
<P>
   But Westphal also would have had to share the ball with stars
Sidney Wicks, Curtis Rowe and Steve Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wooden would have made him dump the ball inside to those big
guys,'' Walton said. ``Paul wanted to shoot. So he went to USC and
established their program.''
</P>
<P>
   To the point where in Westphal's junior season of 1971, formerly
bedraggled USC found itself the nation's fifth-ranked team with a
24-2 record, 12-2 in the Pac-8.
</P>
<P>
   You know who provided the two losses. The 29-1 Bruins were the
national champions, so Walton needed only to chuckle over the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   He was, however, quick to overlook that shortcoming in assessing
Westphal's latest basketball decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hiring Paul is a terrific move for the Sonics,'' Walton said.
``As a player, he was visionary, one of the most skilled and
creative offensive players in the game. Same with his coaching. The
players will love playing for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton has been in the area all week as a principal speaker at
the annual Seafirst Jammin' Hoops Camp, including the Seattle
portion tomorrow at Garfield High School. The free sessions, which
last year drew 6,300 kids around the state, feature current and
former NBA players, including Nate McMillan and Sam Perkins, who
hang out and talk about making good decisions in hoops and in life.
</P>
<P>
   Walton has been a part of the popular one-day fests since they
began in 1990 with the encouragement of former Sonic staffer (and
another ex-Trojan) Jim Marsh, now with Seafirst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim and Paul,'' Walton said, laughing, ``are the only Trojans
I associate with.''
</P>
<P>
   The camp is another way for Walton, a member of the Hall of Fame
as well as NBA champions in Portland and Boston, to feed his
basketball jones.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate as he might look on NBC's telecasts, where his
disarming honesty remains refreshing, Walton still aches to swap
elbows in the paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``(NBA players) have the greatest lives in the world,'' he said.
``And I've been fortunate to be coached by six Hall of Fame
coaches. When you are touched like that, life is never the same
again. You try to chase that the rest of your life, trying to make
that happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years removed from his playing days, which were shortened
to nine seasons by injuries, Walton has a particularly hard time
accepting the idea that Michael Jordan is seriously considering
retirement for no good reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Play as long as you can,'' he said. ``You can play only a
short time in your life. I don't believe his stature will be
diminished at all if he keeps playing ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he wins, people feel good for him, and that kind of
feeling is what sports entertainment is all about. People like
Jordan, John Lennon, Jerry Garcia, Mozart . . . these are people
who can provide joy, enthusiasm and hope that the world is a great
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally foolish is the potential breakup of the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so hard to win a championship,'' he said. ``It's the
greatest feeling in the world. It never leaves you. If (players and
management) trade that opportunity away for money, they will learn
a very hard lesson in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael already learned it once.''
</P>
<P>
   A harder lesson will be learned by the entire industry next week
when, as expected, the NBA locks out its players in order to force
changes in the collective bargaining agreement _ a decision that
has the potential to be a calamitous act of self-destruction, given
the growth of the NBA's global popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of really rich people dividing up a pie,'' Walton
said. ``The biggest advantage the NBA has is that the games have
become special events that fans want to be part of. Anytime you do
anything to jeopardize that trust, you risk losing the advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA has special players and teams that when you watch them
play, it's never about money. It's about the joy of basketball. If
that feeling can be kept, instead of falling down into the gutter
of labor and money, the game is going to be so much better.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony of the moment is that Walton, who as a player was one
of the most marvelously gifted expressions of team-game
selflessness, is spending a week here giving a little more, while
the game that grew him is on the verge of taking much away.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to convince kids to stay out of the gutter when their
heroes roll in it.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
