<SLUG> BC-SUPERMARKET-CHEF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEFS TRADE CHAOTIC RESTAURANTS FOR GROCERY STORES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Dave Hamlin has worked side by side with some of
the top chefs in the country. As an alum of the esteemed Culinary
Institute of America, Hamlin refers to these men and women as his
peers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Hamlin graduated from the Hyde Park, N.Y., school in
1991, he took a job as a food service specialist with Price Chopper
supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for a quality of life change,'' explained
Hamlin, 37, who is married with two daughters. ``I didn't want to
be a slave to a saute pan for 80 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting home at one or two in the morning after working 12
hours in a kitchen does not promote a healthy family life,'' he
added. ``What I was looking for was a job that would challenge me
without completely consuming me.''
</P>
<P>
   Little did Hamlin know that he was at the forefront of a
nationwide trend. More and more grocery stores are turning to
first-class chefs as they battle head-to-head with restaurants for
a public increasingly eager for quality take-out lunches and
dinners.
</P>
<P>
   While Hamlin was the second CIA graduate hired by the Golub
Corp., which has Price Chopper stores in five states, the company
has been actively adding chefs to its staff. There are now more
than a dozen culinary school graduates overseeing the deli
departments and fresh-meal stations at Price Choppers, as well as
another eight to 10 interns from the culinary program at the
Schenectady County Community College in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin, now corporate program development specialist for Price
Chopper, created the Roasters, Bella Roma and Coyote Joe's sections
that are highly visible in many of the stores.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two months he has been working at a frantic pace on
the redesign of a Price Chopper in Glens Falls, N.Y., targeted as
the company's new flagship store.
</P>
<P>
   Steve McKee, director of food service for Golub and an '86 CIA
graduate who spent the last 12 years as director of purchasing at
the CIA, is working with Hamlin on the project.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Golub has been combing restaurants to recruit
chefs who may not have the CIA on their resume, but have proved
themselves with years of practical experience.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent study by the Food Marketing Institute, the
number of shoppers who purchase prepared food from a supermarket to
eat at home (known in the industry as HMR, or home-meal
replacement) has doubled in the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   And this trend is exploding. The FMI survey found 22 percent of
consumers bought ready-made food from grocery stores last year,
nearly double the 12 percent who did so in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   From a chef's perspective, the supermarket doesn't have the same
ring as a gourmet cafe or trattoria, but the pluses far outweigh
whatever ego is attached to the image of an eatery.
</P>
<P>
   Stability is another factor. The prospects for an independent
restaurant are bleak; more than half fold within their first year.
</P>
<P>
   The marriages between supermarkets and chefs appear to be a
perfect match on the onset of the next century mostly because it
fits both parties' needs. The supermarkets need culinary experts as
the traditional grocery store morphs into a take-out restaurant,
and chefs are eager to have a life as well as a career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally feel like I could get married now, but a
relationship was a hard thing to juggle when you're a chef at a
restaurant,'' said John Mazzacco, a former restaurant chef in the
Troy, N.Y., who now works for Price Chopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I have a personal life and my life has changed for the
better, without a doubt,'' said Mazzacco, 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``For more than eight years I could never spend Mother's Day or
Easter with my mom and dad. Restaurant chefs get one day off a
year, Christmas, and all the other holidays you're working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quality of life is more important than words can express. You
can't put a price tag on time you can spend with your family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
