u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-PROULX-BOS &LR;      06-25 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-PROULX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARL PROULX: FIXING IT WITH PLAIN TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SURRY, N.H. _ Earl Proulx did not set his sights on being a
nationally known columnist. He just wanted to make a decent living
_ something his father, a skilled carpenter and contractor, thought
might be beyond the reach of his middle son.
</P>
<P>
   Proulx proved him wrong. Not only did he make a darn good living
over the years as a supervisor for large contractors, he became the
Monadnock region's answer-man for people seeking solutions to
building problems big or small. Then at age 66, seemingly the
twilight of his career, he parlayed his down-home wisdom into a
successful column called ``Plain Talk'' for Yankee magazine. After
20 years, it's still running.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all began when I was 11 or 12,'' says Proulx, sitting in
his office on the ground floor of the house he built himself in the
1950s. ``I overheard my father telling my brothers that they had to
be prepared to `take care of Earl.' He didn't think I would be able
to make a living because I was born with a club foot. After that my
brothers didn't want anything to do with me. So I became a loner
and spent a lot of time in my bedroom reading.''
</P>
<P>
   He read anything he could find that had anything to do with
building and making things. He would cut out the instructions,
painstakingly arranging clippings in notebooks. Today, Proulx
continues to clip and file, but his routine has been updated a
little by the use of a yellow highlighting marker.
</P>
<P>
   He also has a computer, but don't mention e-mail to this tall
man whose unlined face belies his 85 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hooked up to e-mail,'' says Proulx, dressed in gray
polyester slacks, a white nylon shirt, and patterned tie. ``But I
hate it. It's not personal enough.''
</P>
<P>
   So every Monday, Proulx drives over to Yankee magazine's
headquarters in nearby Dublin in his dark-cherry Oldsmobile and
collects his mail. He gets up to 20 letters a week. Back home, he
organizes them in their appropriate slots _ letters he can answer
off the top of his head go in one slot, queries that need some
research in another, and ones that require a lot of homework go up
top.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started filling these binders with clippings when I was a
kid,'' says Proulx. ``And these books over here help me identify
old tools for readers. This one here is a Sears Roebuck catalog
from 1902. And this one up here is filled with thank-yous from
readers.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything has a place. Nothing is out of order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been neat,'' he says. ``Even my room as a teenager
was neat. My mother never had to speak to me about picking up my
room. The only thing she disliked was the wooden snake I kept in my
desk drawer.''
</P>
<P>
   And his neatness does not just pertain to his office. His large
workshop, now seldom used, is immaculate. Over the years he has
also collected a treasure-trove of old tools that line the walls. A
painting easel, parked in a corner, has not been touched since his
third wife died 21 years ago. Upstairs the bed is made, the kitchen
picked up, and the dog leashed outside.
</P>
<P>
   Proulx honed his skills, he says, first by working for his
father and then with other contractors. His second marriage
produced a son, who lives in San Diego and has three children. It
was his son and Proulx's third wife who helped him build his dream
house, with its spectacular view of Mount Monadnock.
</P>
<P>
   After searching for the perfect spot for five years, he bought
the land in 1951, then it took four years to dig the long driveway
up the hill by hand _ shovel load by shovel load. And another year
to build the house. He is most proud of a dumbwaiter he built to
bring firewood up from the basement. He used an old coal stoker as
the carrier.
</P>
<P>
   During his years working for contractors, he built homes and
office buildings as well as dams, bridges, and roads. And he laid a
lot of driveways. ``I could build anything anyone asked for,'' says
Proulx, whose formal education ended with high school. ``One of my
favorite jobs was dismantling an old house, moving it to Keene, and
then putting it back together again. I also got 27 barns built in
27 days at the race track in Hinsdale. Each of those barns had 20
stalls and five tack rooms. We put up a barn a day. I was directing
50 carpenters for that job.''
</P>
<P>
   Proulx emphasizes that he always did things the least expensive
way, but that he never scrimped on quality. He practices good
old-fashioned frugality in his home life but makes exceptions when
it comes to cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, he took a job at Yankee maintaining buildings. Since he
helped build most of the company's structures in Dublin, he was
well suited for the job. When the magazine was looking for a
columnist, an employee suggested Proulx: He was always answering
everyone's questions about old tools and helping with home building
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked me if I wanted to write a column and I said, `Sure,
for the heck of it, I'll try,''' says Proulx. ``So I made up some
questions and answered them. Then they sent it to be edited by some
guy, and he changed everything. I told them I couldn't put my name
on the changed column. I said I was writing for the ordinary guy
and I wanted it to be my wording. So they said they'd run the
column any way I wanted it. And they have.''
</P>
<P>
   He has written three books, all of which provide valuable tips
on everything from cleaning methods to bee stings, odor removal to
roof repair, crab grass control to car maintenance. His most recent
book is ``Yankee Magazine's Practical Problem Solver, 1,001
Ingenious Solutions to Everyday Dilemmas.'' There are suggestions
on how to cut your washing in half, make jewelry sparkle, and keep
pigeons away from the eaves of your house. Before that there was
``Yankee Magazine's Make It Last, Over 1,000 Ingenious Ways to
Extend the Life of Everything You Own'' and ``Earl Proulx's Yankee
Home Hints, From Stains on the Rug to Squirrels in the Attic, Over
1,500 Ingenious Solutions to Everyday Household Problems,'' with
over 500,000 copies in print.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, Proulx might write another book. For now the man Yankee
calls ``America's favorite handyman'' is content signing copies of
his latest tome at nearby bookstores and continuing to disseminate
advice in plain-talk style.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
