<HEADLINE>
IN THE END, IT WILL BE PLAIN OLD TELEPHONE SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Too much time on the Internet can warp your judgment. Your ideas
about the world come to you in jagged little bits instead of
flowing human voices, and that can mislead you.
</P>
<P>
   I found myself falling into the trap Wednesday, as I thought
about AT&AMP;T Corp.'s acquisition of the cable TV company
Tele-Communications Inc. My first reaction was a surge of what can
only be called bandwidth lust. All I could see at first was AT&AMP;T
using all that coaxial cable to deliver high-speed Internet service
to 33 million homes. Broadband data services, a reality at last.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe one of these days. But the track record of our local
cable company MediaOne brought me back to earth. A couple of years
after rolling out ambitious broadband plans, MediaOne is still
basically a cable company. In the same way, AT&AMP;T will come out of
the TCI deal as much a telephone company as ever.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it'll be a couple of years before the company
will serve up a full spectrum of broadband offerings to all its
customers. I can sympathize. MediaOne has so far managed to install
its hot new system almost everywhere except my neighborhood in
Quincy. We're supposed to get lucky sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps MediaOne is in cahoots with my boss to make me spend
more time at the office. Here at the Globe, my computer is
connected to our corporate network, which links to the Internet at
1.5 million bits per second, far faster than my telephone modem at
home.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is immense. Not just because our Internet service
is fast, but because it's always on. Suddenly, the Web is the most
convenient source for information. I never use a Yellow Pages at
work; it's faster to look up phone numbers on the Web. When I want
corporate financial data, I download it directly from the
Securities and Exchange Commission. When I must question an
industry executive, I send an e-mail. It's often faster _ no
mucking around with voice mail _ and there's a written record of
our discussion.
</P>
<P>
   There's no need to dial a phone number and wait to log on. I'm
always on. Suddenly, the Internet isn't ``out there'' any more. It
works like a very large hard drive inside the computer. This is why
I've defended Microsoft Corp.'s plan to build Web browsing into its
operating systems. It's precisely the best place for a browser.
Many more people will realize this as high-speed Internet access
spreads across the land.
</P>
<P>
   But that could take forever, and not because of technology.
Here's the dirty little secret of home broadband services: &UR;  &LR; most
people don't seem to want them.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne is one of the leaders in deploying advanced cable
technology. Almost half of the company's 5.1 million customers are
capable of using cable modems. Yet only 40,000 of them have signed
up. That's a lousy 2 percent subscription rate. MediaOne spokesman
Rick Jenkinson won't say whether MediaOne can make money at that
level of market penetration, but it's not hard to guess.
</P>
<P>
   Still, MediaOne is &UR;  &LR;  not counting on Internet service alone to
pay the freight, any more than AT&AMP;T is. The real money is likely to
come from the sale of boring old telephone service. ``Customers
spend a lot more on telephone than they do on cable or Internet at
this time,'' said Jenkinson.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts alone, Bell Atlantic serves up 4.5 million
phone lines, many to businesses and individuals that lease them by
the handful. These lines bring in revenues of $1.75 billion.
MediaOne wants a piece. Its &UR;  &LR;  upgraded cable systems will be able
to handle voice traffic, and the company plans to start peddling
the service this fall. If MediaOne can get just a slice of Bell
Atlantic's business, that'll justify the expense of converting
its &UR;  &LR;  cable system to broadband.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is thinking the same way. It's &UR;  &LR;  mainly interested in
selling telephone service to those 33 million TCI subscribers _ and
not having to pay local phone companies for handling the start and
finish of the long-distance calls made by those customers. Today,
AT&AMP;T is locked out of the residential market because it doesn't
have wires running directly into customers' homes. They soon will.
And while those lines will provide millions of bits per second to
avid gearheads, it'll be plain old telephone service that pays the
freight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (You can send Hiawatha Bray electronic mail at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
