<SLUG> BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S THIS DOG, YOU SEE ... 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE BARNICLE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has this ever happened to you? You're leaving for work or
perhaps going out your driveway en route to a vacation with the
nagging thought that you've forgotten something.
</P>
<P>
   Like, maybe, your pants? Or the tickets? Or shutting the
windows? Or turning off the gas stove? Stuff like that. Well, the
other day, I forgot to do something before leaving: Kill my dog.
</P>
<P>
   My dog is a moron. And he is bigger than Macedonia, so plotting
his death required planning as well as thought: Run over him in the
driveway as the kids sleep? Drench him in charcoal lighter, and
flip a match out the window as I leave?
</P>
<P>
   No. Too cruel. Plus I didn't want my children scarred for life
from living with someone guilty of dogicide.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the reason I wanted him dead is simple as well as
understandable: He ate my golf clubs, including the only one I
consistently hit with any authority, the 7-iron.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is not all he has eaten over the past year. His
appetite has included 612 pairs of sneakers, a dining room set, and
a Ford Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to train him and failed. I took him to doggie school.
His tuition _ room and board _ was the rough equivalent of two
years at Milton Academy.
</P>
<P>
   He enjoyed great success there. He loved it so much that I began
wondering what fool ever came up with the saying, ``Works like a
dog'' or ``Is treated like a dog.'
</P>
<P>
   I mean, dogs wake up, get both breakfast and supper delivered to
them, take a nap, take a walk, take a dump, take another nap. They
do nothing. They don't work. They don't have to report to any
office. They don't have to explain why they were out so late, who
they were with, or why they did what they did to the French poodle
across the road.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, he did anything and everything for the trainer: He read
``Ulysses,'' prepared his own meals, cleaned his room, and
generally behaved better than Julia Child.
</P>
<P>
   Then he graduates and does nothing for me other than stare at me
with the eyes of a complete dope, looking exactly the way Christie
Brinkley would look while listening to a discussion of why India
and Pakistan went nuclear.
</P>
<P>
   So, the trainer asked to see me. I went and paid attention to
the guy for about an hour. He explained how I had to be stern and
consistent and use no big words.
</P>
<P>
   I went home. I thought about what I'd learned, got up from my
chair and began drinking water out of a toilet bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Something was terribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the golf clubs. They are the athletic equivalent of dogs;
they represent an idea that sounds good in theory, but turn out to
be worse than water torture in reality.
</P>
<P>
   Golf, of course, is the '90's version of crack for middle-age
males. We will go out at any hour of day or night and humiliate
ourselves worse than a whore on a corner in our lust to acquire the
latest equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Graphite shafts. Heads larger than Ted Kennedy's. Gloves that
take seven strokes off your game. All of this while forgetting my
late, great Dad's official slogan: ``It's a poor workman who blames
his tools.''
</P>
<P>
   Think about how nutty this is: When men were boys and perhaps
played baseball, if anybody said there was a better bat on the
market or that a newer glove would make them superior performers
you would quickly figure the person to be fresh out of an asylum.
</P>
<P>
   A glove was a glove. A bat was a bat. You throw the ball, catch
the ball, and hit the ball. Simple enough, and if you couldn't do
it, you went home and became a genius.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, let one guy tell you that graphite shafts will improve your
golf game and you are in the car headed toward the store. Just
yesterday, right after I gave up the thought of killing the dog, I
am in the Wayland Golf Shop when one of the all-time great golfers,
Steve Israel, tells me to buy Callaway irons rather than the
Taylor-Made I held in my hand.
</P>
<P>
   At the time he told me this I had known Israel for all of four
minutes. Yet his advice had a huge impact on me because golf causes
such huge insecurity in people that the slightest suggestion from
anyone can cause your convictions to resemble Kleenex in a
hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   So today I have a new set of irons and the same old phobias
about this miserable little pill that sits on a tee or settles in
grass, does not move at all when you try to hit it, but torments
and terrorizes millions across the country. Maybe, instead of doing
the dog, I should think things over and simply burn my sticks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Barnicle is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
