<HEADLINE>
BREWERS HOPE SPORE WILL TAKE A POWDER IN THE US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAC DANIEL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANVERS, Mass. _ If you attended the American Society of Brewing
Chemists conference here this week, you likely heard three words
that could make suds-soaked American lips tremble.
</P>
<P>
   Hops powdery mildew.
</P>
<P>
   Last September in Washington state, 1,500 acres of hops, a plant
that is the basic element in beer, had to be destroyed because of
this airborne spore. It was the first time that this lethal mildew
had been found in America.
</P>
<P>
   Europe has been dealing with the disease for more than 300
years. And one of the reasons that American hops have dominated the
market for so long is the domestic crops' resistance to disease.
After last fall, this is no longer the case.
</P>
<P>
   This year's hops growing season has also featured an outbreak of
mildew, maybe worse than last year, and the nation's brewing
scientists are quietly scared while trying to find ways to fight
this disease.
</P>
<P>
   Some people believe the diseased hops do not affect the flavor
of beer. Nonetheless, there is ample concern that the outbreak of
mildew could have a serious impact on the American hops industry,
the largest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were cautiously optimistic a few weeks ago, but now we
think we still could have a major problem,'' said David Hysert, a
vice president with John I. Haas Inc., the largest grower and
seller of hops in the world.
</P>
<P>
   As for beer drinking itself, there seems to be little worry.
</P>
<P>
   While some trial brews have produced a ``mushroom-like aroma,''
others have found no noticeable difference between beer brewed with
hops powdery mildew and beer brewed without.
</P>
<P>
   And with a glut of hops in the world market now, some are
quietly saying that the arrival of the mildew in America is more a
blessing for the industry than a curse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average beer drinker in America right now shouldn't really
be affected by hops powdery mildew,'' said Mike Dutelle, director
of sales and marketing for John I. Haas Inc., in North America.
``It really hasn't been that significant.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-day conference ended Wednesday with a gala dinner and
an informal taste testing, in which spiked samples of beer were
swooshed and sniffed for aromas and tastes ranging from medicinal
to road kill, the result of beer that has been hit by too much heat
and light.
</P>
<P>
   The conference dissected beer into it finest elements. There
were abstracts ranging from developing a technique to detect
heat-induced flavor damage in beer to the frozen stability of beer.
</P>
<P>
   There was also new research presented by Jan F. Stevens of
Oregon State University that demonstrated the potential of a
component of hops in fighting breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which doesn't mean that women should go out and start drinking
more beer,'' said one researcher. ``It's just another possible use
for hops.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
