<SLUG> BC-FILM-SODERBERGH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DIRECTOR WHO GOT GEORGE CLOONEY TO ACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Steven Soderbergh shows up for his interview almost an
hour early, and without a retinue of publicists. He's alone, with
his shiny new Apple G3 laptop. He's also unguarded and easy to talk
to, surprising since his ``sex, lies, and videotape'' set the world
on its ear nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first indie film to win at the Cannes Film Festival
and to make an impact at the mainstream box office; it produced $25
million on a $1.5 million investment. Since 1989, Soderbergh has
directed a handful of films, including the smart and underrated
coming-of-age story ``King of the Hill'' (which has nothing to do
with the animated show of the same name), and the noirish ``The
Underneath.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I aimed low,'' he says of ``Underneath,'' ``and I missed.''
</P>
<P>
   His newest picture, the adaptation of Elmore Leonard's ``Out of
Sight,'' smacks the target dead center. The story revolves around
an escaped bank robber (George Clooney) and the federal marshal
(Jennifer Lopez) bent on recapturing him. It may not be the kind of
project _ big budget, with a major star _ you'd associate with
Soderbergh. ``In this case, I had to go get this job, and audition
for it,'' he confesses.
</P>
<P>
   How does a director audition for a job? ``It means going to meet
with the producers, and with Clooney, who was attached at the time.
And saying, `This is how I want to do it. If you don't want to do
it this way, then I'm the wrong guy.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I made reference to a lot of films from the early '70s, that
period we all liked. The two I mentioned most specifically were
`The French Connection' _ in terms of its ground-level style,
really unadorned, nothing fancy _ and `The Last Detail,' which I
thought had a great balance of humor and drama. I guess I mentioned
the right movies, or the right reasons, because the other people
they were talking to fell away.''
</P>
<P>
   He has also been credited with freeing Clooney from that tic of
his, where he holds his head down and peers up into the camera.
``People see this performance of (Clooney's) and say, `Gee, how did
you get him to stop doing that?' I really didn't. He came in
knowing what he had to do. I was very impressed by him. He's smart
about acting. Or rather, smart about his acting,'' Soderbergh says
with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt this role provided George with the opportunity to do
the things that he does very well, and he's not often asked to do,
or allowed to do, or given the time to do. There's a ``gravitas''
to George that he hasn't got to show very much, a resigned quality
to him that, in this film, I think is very compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a formidable task, restructuring Leonard's fiction for the
screen, one resolved by Soderbergh and screenwriter Scott Frank.
The Detroit-based Leonard is beloved in the film business, but what
works in his novels doesn't exactly translate to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, if you break his books down into the plot, into what
happens,'' Soderbergh muses, ``then you've eliminated the most
interesting part of the books, which is the characters. The
characters aren't self-reflective, which is what I like about them.
They make decisions entirely based on emotions, and not any sort of
real logic. And as soon as you try to impose some sort of external
logic on this material it sort of falls apart. Or becomes not very
interesting. I try to maintain a style and tone throughout the film
that's true to Leonard, and sets that up, so that the audience
still comes away satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an intriguing time for Soderbergh now, being the midst of
the media storm for ``Out of Sight.'' But such scrutiny is not new
for him. The character study ``sex, lies, and videotape'' _ a
combination of melodrama and romantic comedy _ propelled him into
the spotlight and brought a whole new interest to the independent
filmmaking world. ``The great thing about winning at Cannes, was
that it was a surprise. I didn't anticipate it or ask for it,'' he
says, smiling. ``I just showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's great about it, is that it's impossible to predict.
Somewhere out there right now _ anywhere in the world _ someone is
writing, or editing, or directing a movie that we're not aware of.
And it's gonna turn the (film) industry on its ear, again, six
months or a year from now. Last year, on two ends of the spectrum,
it was ``Titanic'' and ``The Full Monty.'' That what's exciting
about movies, is that somewhere out there, there's another surprise
lurking. I love the unpredictability of it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Call him at (817) 390-7614. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
