<SLUG> BC-FILM-THELANDGIRLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LAND GIRLS' MIRED DOWN ON THE FARM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writer/director David Leland's new historical drama ``The Land
Girls'' is like a cryogenically preserved rose _ cold and
completely lifeless, yet still strangely beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   That is, of course, until you touch it and it crumbles into a
thousand pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why pretty settings and lush photography might be
appealing on the surface, but Leland's inability to create any kind
of involving story line or characters worth giving a flip for
disintegrates into an experience about as entertaining as an
outdoor insurance seminar in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   Set during World War II (and seeming to last longer than the
entire conflict), ``The Land Girls'' refers to the Women's Land
Army, an organization for war brides and able-bodied young women
who were dispatched across England to pick up the slack for
soldiers serving in the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to do their duty, three spirited lasses find
themselves teamed at a rural Dorset farm under the watchful eye of
a less-than-thrilled head of the household.
</P>
<P>
   Stella (Catherine McCormack) is the level-headed, moon-eyed
romantic, promised to a handsome naval officer. Ag (Rachel Weisz)
is the flaky but proper one of the bunch, and Prue (Anna Friel) is
the hellcat, a quick-witted hairdresser with an eye for the
farmer's son.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, everyone's got an eye for the farmer's son,
but poor Joe (Steven Mackintosh) is too clueless to notice. Not
that that stops the girls, of course. By the time poor Stella gets
around to falling for him, both of her buddies have already had a
go. She doesn't seem to mind, though. (Were all war-time romances
this shallow?)
</P>
<P>
   In between these developments, there are lots of sumptuous shots
of green meadows and forest lanes along with plenty of scenes of
the girls wallowing in mud and engaging in other filthy manual
labor (bet this was a fun shoot, huh?).
</P>
<P>
   But the only emotion ``Land Girls'' manages to muster is intense
indifference. Nobody ever ``does'' anything, and there are so many
shots of the gals engaging in menial farm chores, you leave the
picture feeling like you've done most of them yourself.
</P>
<P>
   The players are good, McCormack especially, but without any
dramatic impact to play with, their efforts are wasted and the
point of this whole tedious exercise escapes even the most
attentive audience member. When a damaged German fighter plane
crashes onto one of the meadows, you find yourself regretting the
doomed chap didn't take out the whole lot with him.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Land Girls''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 stars on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: David Leland
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Catherine McCormack, Rachel Weisz, Anna Friel
</P>
<P>
   Length: 112 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult situations, sexual subject matter, brief
nudity, violence and profanity
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
