<HEADLINE>
SHARK IN THE PRESS POOL 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; Steven Brill is moving around his modest Fifth
Avenue office mentally replaying Sunday's ``Thrilla in Washington''
battle with Tim Russert. The editor and publisher of the new
Brill's Content magazine went on Russert's ``Meet the Press'' to
discuss his explosive story charging independent counsel Kenneth
Starr and the press corps with grievous misdeeds in the handling of
the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   When the cameras rolled, host Russert quickly pounced, summing
up the complaints of angry journalists who accused Brill of shoddy
work in his article headlined ``Pressgate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather a dubious debut for a so-called media watchdog,
wouldn't you say?'' Russert asked Brill.
</P>
<P>
   Brill quickly counterattacked, accusing Russert of erroneous
punditry that he hadn't admitted to. And he suggested to another
guest, Weekly Standard executive editor Fred Barnes, that his
magazine had attacked Brill because Content is working on a story
revealing the fat sums that people like Barnes pull down on the
speaking circuit. All in all, pretty sweaty stuff for a Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two days after the ``Meet the Press'' dust-up, Brill is in
his office working on a sharper response to the Russerts of the
world. In starting a magazine of media criticism, Brill obviously
wanted to watch the watchers. The grand irony is that he is now the
most scrutinized man on the media radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly toying with his famous unlit cigar _ before stowing it
when the photographer starts clicking _ he suddenly seems to find a
strategy for dealing with all this.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more Mr. Nice Guy,'' he says with a sly smile.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Nice Guy is not something that the 47-year-old Queens native
(and Deerfield Academy, Yale, and Yale Law grad) gets called very
often. Throughout his rather amazing career _ from freelance writer
to youthful founder of The American Lawyer and Court TV to the man
behind the magazine that has the media all atwitter _ Brill has
been known primarily for two things. He is a demanding boss who
doesn't suffer fools: In a 1986 Wall Street Journal profile, his
sister said, ``He can be a real SOB.'' And he is a driven and
highly intelligent journalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very courageous guy,'' says Tom Rosenstiel, vice
chairman of the Committee of Concerned Journalists. ``Very smart
and full of the kind of hubris that is necessary for a journalist
who takes on his own craft. ... The guy is a monumental figure in
his business.''
</P>
<P>
   Brill rolls his eyes when you bring up the old war stories _ how
he made underlings cry with his cutting assessments of their work
or how, years ago, he supposedly bit someone during a water polo
match. For the record, Brill denies the chomp occurred, saying the
alleged victim _ financial writer James Cramer, who contributed to
the first issue of Content _ ``swears I did.'' But, jokes Brill,
``he had to be on drugs at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' says Brill, ``I am tough about ...'' and then to
illustrate what he is tough about, he grabs a story manuscript. In
the margin is scribbled the word ``sidebar,'' meaning Brill is
going to ask the writer to go back and do more reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Says Boston Globe staffer Gregg Krupa, who worked at Brill's
Manhattan Lawyer for several years: ``If you could put up with the
occasional vituperative comment, there was the reward of this
feeling that we were really doing cool stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't relish the resurfacing of the big-bad-Brill
stories, the Content boss had better get used to the attention.
He's got a reporter in his office, The Washington Post is
supposedly working on a big story about him, and the Los Angeles
Press Club is on the line, asking him to speak. Now Brill is the
guy under the microscope.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Genesis in Time trial
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The idea of creating a magazine of media scrutiny began
percolating in Brill's head when he wrote a 1985 American Lawyer
piece attacking Time magazine for its story on former Israeli
defense minister's Ariel Sharon's role in the 1982 Palestinian
massacres, coverage that made Time the defendant in a libel trial.
Several years back, when he was partnered with Time-Warner, Brill
broached the idea of buying the Columbia Journalism Review to
Time-Warner boss Gerald Levin.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the publication of the first issue of Content,
Brill's every move has been dissected. An ill-conceived plan to
link his magazine with NBC's ``Dateline'' program quickly surfaced
in the media and had to be scrapped. Stories have already
questioned whether his partnership with Content investor and cable
executive Barry Diller will deter him from examining Diller's
friends. And when Brill delivered a speech to students at a tony
New York private school urging them to toughen up the school paper,
he earned a skewering from New York Times columnist Maureen Dowd,
who called him the media's ``very own Godzilla.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was nothing compared with the response generated by the
``Pressgate'' story that Brill released June 13. Its provocative
thesis _ that Starr improperly leaked the ``most damaging details''
of his investigation to a scandal-starved press corps that became
``an enabler of Starr's abuse of power'' _ created a furious
backlash. Starr responded with a 19-page letter accusing Brill of a
``reckless and irresponsible attack'' bordering on libel. ABC News
president David Westin wrote a little letter to Brill noting that
``it is tempting to point out the various inaccuracies in your
reporting.'' One Brill target in ``Pressgate,'' NBC reporter David
Bloom, retorted, ``Just a willingness to hurl insults shouldn't be
mistaken for sound journalism.'' Another, The Washington Post's
Susan Schmidt, wrote an angry letter to Brill.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6532 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-BRILL-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     06-25 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-BRILL-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... to Brill.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And then there was the revelation that Brill hadn't disclosed
contributions he and his wife made to the Clinton-Gore campaign and
Democratic congressional candidates. That was something Russert
grilled Brill about on Sunday, pointedly noting that ``there is a
lot of concern that perhaps you did have a political agenda in
writing this article.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if had anticipated all this attention, Brill says
that on an intellectual level he was prepared. As he began
disseminating copies of ``Pressgate,'' he recalls saying that ``I
feel like I'm about to go over Niagara Falls in a barrel.''
</P>
<P>
   But the intensity of the reaction, he admits, ``surprises you at
a gut level.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Always an entrepreneur
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Steven Brill was a boy, he organized a neighborhood
snow-shoveling operation by collecting an up-front fee of $25
apiece from a group of homeowners and subcontracting the work to
chums. When an unusually mild winter delivered only one or two
snowfalls, Brill had a tidy little profit. But he never returned to
the enterprise, figuring ``you can't get lucky two years in a
row.''
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, no one should have doubted his
entrepreneurial bent. He was in his 20s when he founded The
American Lawyer and barely in his 40s when Court TV debuted in
1991. Brill will not say how much he banked when Time-Warner bought
out his American Lawyer Media last year, other than to say that the
$30 million figure most frequently bandied about is ``not right.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Brill, he and his three minority partners invested
a total of $25 million in Content, which has an annual budget of
around $13 million. The magic number he is aiming for five years
down the line is a circulation of 500,000. Content starts making
money, he says, at about 400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers are skeptical that a magazine that examines the
media can put up those kinds of numbers. In a recent New York
magazine article, one analyst compared Content with the movie
``Primary Colors,'' warning that ``in media centers, that film did
very well. In the hinterlands, nobody gave a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to Brill's crafty Saturday release of ``Pressgate,''
_ timed perfectly to make him the talk of the next day's Washington
TV panel show circuit _ Content is out of the gate at a full
gallop. The magazine has already announced that because of
``unexpected demand,'' it is going back for a second printing of
the first issue. And Brill calculates that he will sell well over
300,000 copies of that edition.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sabato, a University of Virginia government professor,
calls Brill's promotion of the debut issue ``a master stroke. It
was about salesmanship and it succeeded. ... He managed to play the
media like a fiddle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve has certainly achieved a huge buildup,'' notes Columbia
Journalism Review editor Marshall Loeb.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be wrong to accuse Content, or Brill, of being more
sizzle than steak. Regardless of one's opinion of ``Pressgate,''
the rest of the magazine features an intelligent, eclectic, and
eminently readable lineup of stories that cover everything from the
lives of those who book guests on TV news shows to the Barnes &AMP;
Noble executive who decides which books go on the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   The American Lawyer reflected Brill's ability to broaden the
appeal of narrow subject matter. The legal profession wasn't used
to being seriously covered when Brill started the publication and
``was absolutely freaked out,'' says Krupa. American Lawyer stories
_ ranging from a look at Hillary Rodham Clinton's duties at the
Rose law firm to Brill's listing of the ``Am Law 100'' top-grossing
law firms _ expanded a trade publication into something both
accessible and interesting to a wider audience.
</P>
<P>
   Brill says the idea behind Content is to ``make it much broader
than a journalism review. ... We've been very careful to make the
magazine's voice such that it is for people outside the industry.''
And despite long odds, some are betting that if anyone can sell
media criticism to the masses, it is Brill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done something very few people thought he could do,
potentially ... secure a larger subscriber base than anyone thought
possible,'' says Sabato.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Course corrections
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Brill prides himself on being a guy who can say he's
sorry. He has admitted he was ``dumb'' on the ``Dateline''
collaboration and wrong for not disclosing his political
contributions. In the next issue, he will apologize for making an
error about The Wall Street Journal's handling of the Lewinsky
scandal. And he is going to run all of Starr's 19-page letter in
Content.
</P>
<P>
   But the battling Brill quickly emerges when he is asked for a
response to the independent counsel's critique of ``Pressgate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to slough it off; it did take someone a long time
to type it,'' he says, doing a poor job of concealing the sarcasm.
``But there's not a lot to respond to.''
</P>
<P>
   This is man who clearly relishes the contest, whether it be on
the baseball field _ he has built a diamond at his home and is
famous for his competitive approach to the game _ or in the world
of journalism.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he chose the role of media policeman rather than,
say, editor of a major newspaper, Brill says simply: ``In some
ways, I think I can have much more impact.'' And the negative
reaction to the magazine from what Brill calls the ``dark ...
underbelly of journalism'' is ``the single best argument'' for
publishing it, he says.
</P>
<P>
   He concedes that Content could sow the seeds of its own demise
if it succeeds in getting the media to police themselves. ``That's
the weak link in my business plan, that I exist (because of) their
arrogance.'' Then he tacks on three words that will disabuse anyone
of the Mr. Nice Guy notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'm safe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1337EDT &QL; 
