<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALLACE GETS RUSTY AS WINNING NASCAR STAR HAS RUN OF BAD LUCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONOMA, Calif. _ NASCAR veteran Rusty Wallace can tell you, race
by race, why he hasn't won in Winston Cup competition this season.
He's smiling while he talks, but he's not happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dover, Delaware,'' he said. ``As soon as I hit the pit road
the caution flag comes out. That put me down two laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bristol, Tennessee. I was on the pole, big, big lead, and the
motor blows.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the California 500 I was running second with eight laps to
go. Blown motor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week the car was just flying. Thirteen laps into the
race, blown engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the one that really hurt _ the Coca-Cola 600 at Charlotte.
I'm running really good at the end, the caution flag comes out and
we all pull into the pits ... put on two new tires. (Jeff) Gordon's
running seventh, his crew chief says, `What've we got to lose?
Let's put on four tires,' and he just flies out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who finished second behind Gordon at Charlotte, said,
``That one cost me a million, 200,000 dollars ... But my life's
been that way _ either hero or hobo.''
</P>
<P>
   The end result of Wallace's troubles is a drop to sixth place in
the points standings as Winston Cup racers head into this weekend's
Save Mart/Kragen 350 at Sears Point Raceway near Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, with 1,992 points, trails Jeremy Mayfield (2,208
points), Gordon (2,172), Dale Jarrett (2,160), Mark Martin (2,155)
and Terry Labonte (2,008) as the Winston Cup field heads into
Friday's qualifying runs.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, whose Miller Lite Ford runs on the same Penske team as
Mayfield's Mobil 1 Ford, said ``it's just luck'' that his cars have
had three blown engines while Mayfield's have cruised to the points
lead. Last week, for instance, the crankshaft on Wallace's Ford
broke in two, smashing his engine to pieces. ``It was a brand-new
engine, and the crankshaft only had a thousand miles on it, which
isn't much. But the way it broke ... it was like having an atom
bomb under the hood.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't have those blown engines, I'd probably be a leader
in the standings,'' said Wallace, who has twice won the pole
position and finished second four times. ``But at 220-something
points behind, it's going to take some kind of heroic move by my
team to get back out in front.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's purse is set at $2.016 million, and in order to take
the $90,025 first-place money, Wallace will have to run full-out.
Having a faster Sears Point track, with a new straightaway at the
top of the course, should help.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who tested the track for the first time Wednesday, said
eliminating two curves to create ``The Chute'' will make the race
``real, real fast. I don't think you're going to want to go
side-by-side through there, hitting 150 miles an hour, the wall 4
feet off to your left.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are drawbacks to wiping out two curves, Wallace added
_ ``Exiting that carousel before, that was a real good spot for me
to set up a pass. Now that's gone. I'm going to have to find
another spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are also complicated by new NASCAR rules, including
downsized rear spoilers, that have led to floating crashes. Wallace
said Dale Earnhardt wasn't too happy when, two weeks ago at
Michigan, the Miller Lite Ford ``got loose and got up into him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
