<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-REVENUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS WRESTLE WITH PROBLEM OF LOST TOBACCO BILL REVENUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid the ashes of last week's Senate defeat of the
tobacco bill was a nearly unnoticed vote on child care. By a 2-to-1
ratio, conservatives and liberals agreed to expand
child-development initiatives by 25 percent, pumping an extra $7
billion into child-care and Head Start programs.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the massive tobacco bill is dead, along with its
$516 billion in potential revenues over 25 years, the enthusiasm
for spending so much money on children seems only a memory.
President Clinton, who proposed his own version of the child-care
initiative, is not pushing alternative funding. Congressional
support is in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two-thirds of the Senate agreed on child care,'' said Helen
Blank, director of child-care services at the Children's Defense
Fund. ``When Congress thinks something is important, it finds a way
to pay for it. They found billions for highways.''
</P>
<P>
   But money for an array of initiatives that Clinton wanted to pay
for with a cigarette tax increase is not available _ and the White
House so far has no plan B for funding. Earlier this year, Clinton
proposed spending money on everything from school construction to
hiring more teachers. Now the White House strategy is to try to
revive tobacco legislation partly by stressing that no money will
be available for these programs.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also had plans to spend the $516 billion in revenues
expected from the cigarette tax increase, most notably a proposal
to eliminate the ``marriage penalty'' that adversely affects many
couples who file taxes jointly.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the debate on the tobacco bill, senators lined up
with proposals about how to spend the money that would be
generated. Senator John F. Kerry cosponsored the measure that would
have provided $7 billion over five years for child-care and Head
Start programs. The Senate voted 66-33 against tabling the
proposal, which was approved by voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said he will continue fighting for child-care money,
especially funds that would have gone to Head Start, a federal
program to help low-income preschool children. The Massachusetts
Democrat said the money is needed because only 30,000 out of 3
million 3-year-olds _ or 1 percent _ who are eligible for the Early
Head Start program now participate, and only half of the 1.6
million 4- and 5-year-olds eligible for Head Start are in the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Since the tobacco bill was killed last week in the Senate,
Clinton may be remaining silent about other funding purposefully in
order to put pressure on Republicans to agree to a modified tobacco
bill that includes child-care money.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the states to get that money for child care, they need to
press for the tobacco bill,'' said Bruce Reed, assistant to the
president for domestic policy. ``We are not giving up on the
tobacco bill and will keep pressing forward in any event.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry, who is considering a run for the presidency, said the
White House strategy may be unrealistic. ``I'm not sure that will
be the big pressure point'' to persuade senators to back tobacco
legislation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry is hardly alone in trying to revive social programs that
were debated as part of the tobacco bill. Senator Edward M. Kennedy
hoped the tobacco bill would provide $12 billion in extra funding
for the National Institutes of Health, $6.5 billion for school
construction, and enough money to hire 100,000 teachers. The money
for schools and teachers was not in the last version of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy vowed to continue to fight for the measures, but without
the leverage of a tobacco bill, it is unclear whether he can
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also had proposals for spending the billions of
dollars that would have been generated by the $1.10-per-pack tax
hike. The GOP, with some Democratic support, wanted to use part of
the tobacco revenues to offset the so-called marriage penalty in
the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty affects many couples in which spouses earn roughly
equivalent salaries. Such couples pay more taxes filing jointly
than they would as individuals. Under the GOP proposal added to the
bill, all couples earning less than $50,000 would have received a
tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Phil Gramm, Republican of Texas, said the fight to
eliminate the marriage penalty will continue in the debate over the
budget. Gramm said support was so impressive during the tobacco
debate that he is calling for expanding the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm wants the marriage penalty to be eliminated for all
married couples, a far more expensive proposition than what was
contained in the tobacco bill. Instead of costing $46 billion over
10 years, Gramm's proposal would cost $101 billion, he said. He
estimated that an average family earning $40,000 would get a tax
cut of $1,400 under the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe all we did in the tobacco bill was prove this is
Congress's top priority,'' Gramm said about the marriage penalty.
``Even though the bill is dead, the principle lives on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
