<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6536 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-25 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE MY VOTE CREAM FILLED
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Soon Massachusetts may have a state polka, but will it ever have
a state doughnut?
</P>
<P>
   According to a story in Tuesday's Globe, we already have a state
bean (navy), a state insect (lady bug), a state cookie (chocolate
chip, or, strictly speaking, Toll House). We even have a state cat
(tabby), which came as a surprise to me, and perhaps to the yellow
tabby chosen to illustrate the story, who stares into the camera
with an expression that seems to say, ``Who me? State cat?''
</P>
<P>
   However a campaign initiated by Emma Krane, 8, and backed by her
classmates in Mary McDermott's third grade class at the Brown
School in Somerville to have the Boston cream doughnut named the
state's official doughnut was rejected by the State Administration
Committee. In the same session the committee recommended a song
with the catchy title ``Say Hello to Someone in Massachusetts'' be
named the state's official polka.
</P>
<P>
   Putting a state polka ahead of a state doughnut strikes me as
unfair and shortsighted in light of the important role doughnuts
play in the life of our Commonwealth. At any given moment, there
are more people in Massachusetts eating doughnuts than doing the
polka. True, they may not all be eating Boston cream (or creme or
kreme, depending on where you buy them) doughnuts, but according to
Dunkin Donuts, their stores alone sell 14 million Boston Kreme
Donuts annually in this state. That's an awful lot of doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative committee rejected the Somerville third-graders'
petition on the grounds that the Boston cream doughnut ``lacks
historical significance.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the Boston cream doughnut may not figure as
prominently in the history of the Commonwealth as the cod, which
fueled our economy for centuries until it was fished to the brink
of extinction. (That's one thing you can be sure of with any kind
of doughnuts, they'll never be a threatened species.) And it may be
true that the Boston cream doughnut isn't as firmly connected in
the public mind with our state capital as the Boston baked bean.
</P>
<P>
   But how many beaneries do you see hereabouts? How many
codderies? And yet, seemingly on every other streetcorner, there's
a doughnutery, which is what doughnut shops were once called,
according to H.L. Mencken's ``The American Language.'' Now they are
all called Dunkin' Donuts, a company that was founded in Quincy and
has its international corporate headquarters in Randolph, where it
lays plans to deluge the world with doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   The Somerville third graders' Boston cream doughnut proposal may
have been done in by political regionalism, ever the bane of
progress in our Commonwealth. Leading the fight against it was Rep.
Cele Hahn (R-Westfield) who took time from her busy schedule to
post what I can only describe as an anti-doughnut diatribe on her
web page. ``I ask you, do we need an official donut?'' Hahn writes.
</P>
<P>
   And if we do, she writes, why should it be the Boston cream?
``Isn't that just a little too eastern?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she'd get behind a Westfield cream doughnut.
</P>
<P>
   Hahn notes that in some places in her constituency the Boston
cream doughnut is known as the Bavarian cream doughnut. She
speculates that if it were named official state doughnut it might
lead to ethnic strife. ``Would, say, the Norwegians demand another
type of donut?'' she asks. ``How about the Czechs? The Irish?''
</P>
<P>
   She may be onto something with that Irish cream doughnut idea.
Sounds tasty. Meanwhile, Emma Kane, reached yesterday on her last
day of school, said she and her classmates haven't given up.
They've written a letter to the governor. The're planning another
campaign. The doughnut issue isn't dead yet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
