<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEDDING A TEAR FOR INNOCENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was sitting in an elementary school gymnasium, watching first
and second graders perform in an end-of-the-school-year play. The
set, made out of refrigerator cartons by my daughter Laura and her
friends, showed the sides of a sailing ship, complete with rigging,
cannons, and pilings while the youngsters on stage pretended to be
powder monkeys on  &UR; board the USS Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The kids were singing their hearts out. Each parent and
grandparent, I'm sure, had eyes for no one but their own incredibly
talented little monkey. I was having trouble watching my
granddaughter, however, because of the tears running down my
cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, this is a happy occasion.'' My daughter Julie was staring
at me, astonished. ``Why are you crying?''
</P>
<P>
   You had to be there. It wasn't only the words:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I have often dreamed of a far off place
</P>
<P>
   Where a hero's welcome would be waiting for me,
</P>
<P>
   Where the crowds will cheer when they see my face
</P>
<P>
   And a voice keeps saying this is where I'm meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You had to see the children's shining eyes and radiant faces.
You had to experience how deeply those words resonated within them.
They weren't acting. They want to be heroes when they grow up _
brave, virtuous, and idealistic _ and be recognized for eir
courage. I know because I remember how I felt when I was their age.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'll be there someday.
</P>
<P>
   I can go the distance.
</P>
<P>
   I will find my way if I can be strong
</P>
<P>
   I know every mile will be worth my while
</P>
<P>
   When I go the distance,
</P>
<P>
   I'll be right where I belong.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These children still believe the future holds a challenge large
enough for their abilities and an occupation meaningful enough to
become their life's work. To a child, they are planning on making
the world a better place. We haven't yet shrunk them small enough
to fit within the narrow confines of our consumer culture.
</P>
<P>
   Not that we haven't started. After all, we enrolled them in
Consumer U. the day we sat them down in front of the TV. They've
already mastered some of the vocabulary they'll need if they're
going to pass the SAT (Self-indulgent Acquisition Test) we use for
admission to the world we're offering them: Beanie Babies, Nike
sneakers, Barbie dolls, Big Macs, L.L. Bean backpacks, Froot Loops
...
</P>
<P>
   But they haven't gotten the following mathematical formula down
pat yet: Getting good grades (EQ) getting into a good college (EQ)
getting a good job (EQ) making a lot of money (EQ) buying
everything you want (EQ) fulfilling the American Dream. Or taken
the class called ``Living Beyond Your Means: Magic Tricks You Can
Do With a Credit Card.''
</P>
<P>
   They still need to develop keener observational skills, such as
how to judge their friends by what they own, how to find out what
products are ``in'' or ``out'' at any given moment, that pretty and
thin is never pretty and thin enough. Then there's social studies.
They're just learning that looking out for No.1 is the key to
success, that they should feel contempt for those uglier, fatter,
poorer, or stupider than they are, that salary is the only measure
by which jobs are worth pursuing, and that those who wish to win
must be willing to sacrifice everything and everyone else to their
ambition.
</P>
<P>
   Soon we'll teach them how much more profitable it is to be a
celebrity than a hero. (Goodbye, shining eyes.) We'll inform them
that all our leaders are self-serving charlatans. (So long, radiant
faces.) We'll convince them that everyone lies. (Farewell, trust.)
We'll numb their sensitivity with 10,000 televised murders. (Who
needs compassion?) We'll demonstrate that making money always takes
precedence over protecting the environment. (Of what use is hope?)
By the time they're teens, they'll know the only power worth
exercising is buying power.
</P>
<P>
   Then the girls can concentrate on weighing themselves while the
boys breathlessly follow their favorite teams. Unless we commit
ourselves to keeping this from happening, by the time they go the
distance, they'll be just where they belong _ where the only mile
that is worth their while leads to a shopping mall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
