</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-PORTALS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRMS SEE PORTALS PAVING THE ROAD TO WEB RICHES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: An illustration and a graphic are being sent to NYTNS
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A portal, according to the dictionary, is a grand and impressive
doorway. It's the sort of entrance you would find on a Gothic
cathedral or the US Capitol _ and now, the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Companies ranging from Internet specialist Yahoo Inc. to media
giant Walt Disney Co. are building ``portal sites'' on the World
Wide Web _ attractive, easy-opening front doors to the vast
information storehouse of cyberspace. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It makes for the hottest trend on the &UR;  &LR; hot and ever trendy
'Net. &UR;  &LR; The rush to develop or acquire such digital gateways has
sparked a flurry of corporate dealmaking, prompted efforts to
develop portal brand names, opened up huge new potential for
advertisers, and boosted the market value of leading Internet
companies. Indeed, so many players are piling into the portal
market that some predict a shakeout before long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt the most contagious disease running amok among
Web marketers is portal-itis,'' jokes Gregory Wester, research
director for the Yankee Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the portals started as Internet ``search
engines,'' &UR;  &LR; where Web surfers go to track down information by
keying in terms _ for example, ``World Cup soccer'' _ and then
clicking on the sites found by the service. They are now expanding
themselves into gateways to dozens of on-line resources: news
headlines, weather reports, electronic mail, classified
advertising, shopping, even advice for small-business owners.
</P>
<P>
   Already, portals like Yahoo, Lycos, and Excite are among the
most popular sites on the World Wide Web, attracting millions of
visitors every month. But these firms face competition from some of
America's biggest media companies, which are eager to gain wider
audiences for their programming and other content.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two weeks ago, the NBC broadcasting unit of General
Electric Co. invested $165 million in Snap, a relatively new and
little-visited portal operated by the popular Internet news service
CNet Inc. Then last Thursday, Disney, which owns the ABC television
network, acquired a 43 percent stake in Infoseek Corp. in a complex
deal worth about $900 million. Infoseek is an Internet search
service that's among the 10 most popular sites on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the browser war between software companies Microsoft
Corp. and Netscape Communications Corp. is turning into a portal
war. Both firms make Internet software that &UR;  &LR; automatically directs
millions of users to their corporate Web sites. Microsoft and
Netscape are beefing up these sites, turning them into full-service
portals that will be the first Web sites many people see when they
dial into the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The portal services &UR;  &LR; should sound familiar to users of such
traditional on-line computer networks as America Online or
CompuServe. These companies provided the same kind of service to
millions of customers over private computer networks long before
the Internet became popular. Indeed, many portal executives admit
that they want to duplicate the formula that has made AOL, with 12
million subscribers, far and away the world's most successful
consumer on-line business. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become like a free version of America Online,'' says Bob
Davis, chief executive of Lycos Inc. Started as a site for looking
up other Internet sites, the Waltham, Mass. company now offers
about 200 services ranging from free e-mail to on-line parlor games
like chess and backgammon.
</P>
<P>
   The comparison amuses Barry Schuler, president of AOL's
interactive services unit. Not only does his company dominate the
commercial on-line service business, its Internet Web site,
aol.com, is the Web's second-most-popular location, with 22.8
million visitors in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers buy brands. That's an absolute,'' Schuler says.
``America Online is the only true national brand in the Internet
on-line world.''
</P>
<P>
   There are problems with AOL as a role model for portals. More
than 80 percent of AOL's revenue comes &UR;  &LR; from subscriber fees. By
contrast, portals don't charge customers a dime. Anyone with
Internet access is welcome.
</P>
<P>
   The portal players think the Internet can be made to pay just as
television has: by rounding up viewers and bombarding them with
advertising. The profits come from corporations ready to pay
millions for a chance to hawk their wares to an audience of
millions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, portals cut distribution deals with major Internet
retailers. For example, the on-line bookstore Barnes&AMP;Noble.com pays
a premium to the Lycos portal. In exchange, Barnes &AMP; Noble gets
listed on the Lycos home page as the site's preferred source for
books.
</P>
<P>
   But comparing portals to TV channels suggests that a shakeout is
inevitable. After all, the bulk of TV ad revenues are earned by the
four major broadcast networks, with dozens of cable companies
fighting for the leftovers. Portal competitors think the same thing
will happen on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzied battle for the top slots among portal sites has
begun.
</P>
<P>
   As with television, the key is ratings. The winners will be
portals that can attract tens of millions of regular visitors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
