   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ XIAN, China _ Clinton arrives and plans to visit
Tiananmen tomorrow after talk with China village elders.'' The
re-lede will cover Clinton's visit to the prosperous village of
Xiahe, outside Xian, Clinton plans to spotlight the growth of
Village capitalism in China. (Kunstel, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-LEADERS _ BEIJING _ The enigmatic Chinese leadership that
awaits President Bill Clinton is like a carriage hitched to three
galloping stallions: one sturdy, one limping, one flashy. Loping
along behind the ruling troika is a well-groomed yearling that few
outside China have ever heard of. If one of the three lead horses
falters, this fresh horse looks ready to make his move. Why not
become your own amateur China-watcher? Just tune in events over the
next two days and scrutinize these four big steeds of the Chinese
Communist Party politburo. You can bet that every professional
China follower around the world will be glued to the coverage of
Clinton during his 21-gun greeting at Tiananmen Square and the
banquet later in the Great Hall of the People. They'll be watching
for bits of byplay, body language and facial expressions to gain
insight into such questions as these: How will these four cunning
survivors of a generation of sometimes deadly party intrigue
interact with each other, and with the Clinton entourage? Which of
the three leading rivals-in-harness really pulls the most weight?
Are they pulling in different directions? Who will be ``in'' and
who will be ``out'' by the year 2000? (Albright , Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-HISTBOX _ A century of U.S.-Chinese dealings. (Albright ,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO _ WASHINGTON _ The House task force on tobacco will
unveil their plan Thursday to cut down on the some 3,000 teens who
start smoking every day. The GOP proposal, largely seen as an
attempt to give Republicans cover in the fall elections, is a
scaled down anti-teen smoking bill. Sources say there will be
provisions to allow FDA regulation of tobacco, but it will be a
much narrower bill than the one killed by the Senate. For example,
it is not expected to call for a price increase to pay for the wide
range of programs proposed by the McCain bill. Will get reaction
from health care community. Also will include a look at how the
Republicans and Democrats are vying for control over a host of
issues they think will resonate in the public such as health care,
tobacco, and campaign finance. (Carr, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   COURT-VETO _ WASHINGTON _ In an important curb of presidential
power, the Supreme Court ruled 6-3 on Thursday that ``line-item''
vetoes of specific items in tax and spending bills are
unconstitutional. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   COURT-ARTS _ WASHINGTON _ In a ruling that provoked outrage from
free-speech advocates, the Supreme Court ruled 8-1 on Thursday that
the government can deny federal funding to artists who violate
``general standards of decency.'' (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI0626 _ Updating number of new cases, how many states
involved, where the investigation is going; health officials were
saying Wednesday that the worst may be over. DNA/culture tests may
be in on the hospitalized kids, seeing if the ecoli hotline is
flooded; what's attendance today at White Water, are numbers back
to normal, are people at the amusement park still talking about
E.coli; we still haven't answered how White Water's chlorine level
fell below the state standard on June 20, if chlorine levels are so
closely monitored -- as the amusement park claims. (Lore, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-POOLS _ Has the cluster of E. coli cases generated a push
to fast-track those pool regulations to get them on the books by
summer's end, do other states have such regulations, are there
other pool-related health problems (other than drowning) that
someone tracks? (Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GLENN _ HOUSTON _ Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, and other astronauts
slated for a fall shuttle mission hold a crew training exercise
that will be open to the press. Glenn is expected to meet with
reporters afterward. (Montgomery, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moving after 7 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-GANGS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ ``There is no way out . . .
except by death.'' This rule, among 30 that make up the group's
constitution, is much like ones in written dictums governing Texas'
other prison gangs and, authorities say, the growing web of murder
and mayhem that those groups are spreading across Texas. Soon, a
Senate committee is scheduled to open a hearing in the Senate
chambers into whether the activities of those gangs _ both inside
and outside of prison _ have helped turn Texas' corrections system
into an incubator for racism and organized crime. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADE-RESTORATION _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The federal plan
to save the Everglades depends on the untested practice of storing
up to 1.7 billion gallons of water underground every day during wet
years and pulling it back up during dry times. Never mind that
federal regulators at the highest levels are agonizing over the
idea of injecting untreated _ and possibly tainted _ lake water
into underground drinking sources. (Engelhardt, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADE-RESCUE _ A half-century ago, weary from an unending
cycle of flood, drought and fire, South Florida residents asked
Washington to build them a barrier against the extremes of nature.
It worked. All too well. Now, the Everglades strangled in its
man-made straitjacket. Now the engineers say it's time to start
over. They want to redesign the entire drainage system.
Environmentalists call it the Everglades' last chance. (King, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NO-FIREWORKS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Celebrate your liberty
this Fourth of July by setting off a bottle rocket anywhere in Palm
Beach County and you might wind up under arrest. But only if a law
enforcement officer actually sees you light the fuse. (Hayes, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WATER-SWT _ SAN MARCOS, Texas _ As Central Texas continues to
swelter under a merciless June sun and water becomes an
ever-more-precious resource, a 6-inch-wide pipeline behind a
popular seafood restaurant is creating watery battle lines in the
city. Construction of the pipeline comes at an especially sensitive
time, as temperatures around the state inch up and aquifer levels
steadily drop. (Rodriguez, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
