<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6546 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-PORTALS-2ND     06-25 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-PORTALS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... regular visitors.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A portal is a site that can successfully broker a significant
share of consumers' information, communication, and commerce
needs,'' says the Yankee Group's Wester. ``Anyone who doesn't have
significant share is just a damn Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest to a sure thing in the portal sweepstakes is Yahoo,
which practically invented the concept. Yahoo was created as an
Internet directory by two Stanford University graduate students.
But it quickly evolved into a one-stop center for many on-line
services. Today, Yahoo is not only the most popular site on the
Internet, with more than 30 million visitors a month. It's also one
of those rare Internet businesses that actually turns a profit _
$2.2 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo and the other search services have a major advantage in
the portal sweepstakes. They are perhaps the only Internet sites
that virtually everyone has to visit sooner or later. The Web is
now so big _ more than 320 million pages according to one recent
estimate in the journal Science _ that a search service is the only
way anybody can hope to find information.
</P>
<P>
   Other search services are moving quickly to take advantage of
their high traffic rates. In the past year, Lycos has added free
e-mail, chat rooms, and a software library where visitors can get
free or low-cost computer programs. In February, Lycos acquired
Tripod Inc., a Williamstown, Mass. company that provides free
personal Web pages to more than a million people. Davis says that
Tripod and other new features are leading Web surfers to spend more
time at Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were originally a go-through site. ... The success of Lycos
was based on how soon you left,'' Davis says. ``Now we've become a
destination site.''
</P>
<P>
   In Marlborough, Mass., the staff at AltaVista is heading in the
same direction. AltaVista is a high-powered Internet search service
created in 1995 by Digital Equipment Corp. to show off the speed of
its Alpha computers. Today, AltaVista is still one of the most
popular search sites on the Web, but the company has lagged in
converting itself into a portal.
</P>
<P>
   No more, says director of marketing Kathy Greenler. Even before
Digital's acquisition last week by Compaq Computer Corp., AltaVista
had begun making moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken a slower path, but we've taken a global
perspective,'' Greenler says.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista has begun to offer the same kinds of services
available at other portals. The AltaVista site now features a link
to ABC News and CBS Sportsline and a free e-mail service. But
Greenler is especially proud of the site's translation
capabilities. AltaVista can make rough translations into English of
Web pages written in French, Spanish, Portuguese, Italian, and
German. It can also translate English pages into any of these
languages.
</P>
<P>
   If search services can count on high traffic volumes, the makers
of browser software might have an even sweeter deal. The leading
browsers from Netscape and Microsoft are usually preset so that the
first Web site to appear on a screen belongs to the browser maker.
</P>
<P>
   That's too good an opportunity for Netscape, which is reeling
from Microsoft's competitive thrusts in the browser and server
software markets. Netscape is turning its Netcenter Web site into a
portal in hopes that visitors will linger to use the free e-mail
and discussion groups.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape senior vice president Jennifer Bailey says that 5.5
million Web surfers have registered to use the site since it was
opened in September. In the quarter ended in April, Netcenter
racked up $31 million in revenues from advertisers wishing to reach
those visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Netscape brand is by far more recognized and associated
with the Internet than any other portal brand out there, including
Yahoo,'' Bailey says.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft hopes to change that. Already the company runs several
of the most popular Web sites. Now Microsoft is testing a prototype
for a new portal called Internet Start, which will pop up on the
screens of future users of Microsoft's browsing software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to be the home for Microsoft customers on the
Internet,'' says Ed Graczyk, a Microsoft product manager. He sounds
modest enough until you remember that ``Microsoft customers'' are
about 90 percent of the world's computer users.
</P>
<P>
   Now established media companies, eager not to be shut out of the
Internet, are moving to make portals of their own. While Disney's
investment in Infoseek is the bigger of the two recent deals, NBC's
choice of a partner is more interesting. Infoseek is already a
major Web site, while Snap isn't in the top 25. NBC is betting that
its marketing clout can turn a little-known Web site into a
top-tier portal.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBC knows about audiences and mass marketing,'' says NBC
spokesman Robert Silverman. Besides, according to Silverman, less
than 5 percent of Americans have ever heard of Yahoo, largely
because most people still don't use the Internet. Silverman sees
this as evidence that there's still plenty of room in the portal
market.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, any number of other firms are trying to create
mini-portals &UR;  &LR; for specialized audiences. For example, the leading
personal finance software firm Intuit Inc. offers Quicken.com, a
site laden with financial news and information.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, everybody agrees that only a few of these
companies will get enough regular visitors to attract a profitable
level of ad revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there'll be three winners _ Yahoo, AOL, and
Microsoft,'' says Chris Charron, an analyst at Forrester Research
in Cambridge. He also gives an outside chance to Netscape because
of the popularity of its browser.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other players, including Lycos and AltaVista, Charron
sees them as also-rans, and possibly as takeover bait for a media
company looking to build its own gateway to the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
