<HEADLINE>
_BAD GENE MAY TEMPER THE DESIRE TO LIGHT UP   
 _HOW PNEUMONIA HITS IN NURSING HOMES   
 _DRUG-RESISTANT FORMS OF HIV RAISE ALARMS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Bad gene may temper the desire to light up &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Life isn't fair. Some people can eat and not get fat, others can
smoke and not get addicted. With smoking, researchers have now
discovered why.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsmokers and casual smokers, it turns out, are twice as likely
to have a defective gene for a liver enzyme called CYP2A6 that
breaks down nicotine, the addictive chemical in cigarette and cigar
smoke. That means nicotine stays in their system longer, blunting
the desire to smoke more to keep blood levels high.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principle is that people who remove nicotine more slowly
have to refuel less often,'' said Rachel Tyndale of the University
of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Smokers with the defective enzyme smoked 20 percent fewer
cigarettes per week than those who didn't, Tyndale, Dr. Edward
Sellers, and Michael Pianezza report in the current British journal
Nature.
</P>
<P>
   But how would a defective enzyme prevent people from becoming
smokers in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   ``In people who are naive to nicotine, it tends to cause
dizziness or nausea,'' Tyndale said. ``As you learn to smoke you
get tolerant to those effects. We think people with a reduced
ability to remove nicotine are tipped toward finding it even more
aversive. When they have a second cigarette, they still have more
nicotine around, which reduces their desire to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto report represents the first time researchers have
discovered a genetic basis for smoking risks _ a behavior that,
according to earlier studies of twins, appears to be about half due
to social environment and half by genetic factors.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery suggests ways to help some of the 62 million
Americans who smoke to stop. First, by blocking the normal
nicotine-clearing enzyme (which apparently has no other critical
role in the body), scientists hope to convert a 30-cigarettes-a-day
smoker to a 10-a-day habit. ``It's much easier to quit if you're
smoking less,'' Tyndale notes.
</P>
<P>
   The enzyme blocker could also be a boon in preventing relapses
among quitters. ``We think in those people we can, especially in
high-risk situations like a social event or during stress,
reproduce the protective effect we see in nonsmokers with the
defective enzyme when they try to smoke,'' Tyndale says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; How pneumonia hits in nursing homes
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Daniel M. Musher, a Houston physician, tells in the current
New England Journal of Medicine about his medical-student
daughter's reaction to the news of an outbreak of pneumococcal
pneumonia at a Texas nursing home last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is that possible?'' she asked. ``Hadn't all the residents
of the nursing home been vaccinated?''
</P>
<P>
   Nope. And that's not uncommon in US nursing homes, judging from
a study in this week's issue of the journal.
</P>
<P>
   The study details an ``explosive'' outbreak of pneumonia in an
Oklahoma nursing home in February 1996, involving a strain of
pneumococcus resistant to many drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 84 residents of the rural nursing home, only three had
been vaccinated against pneumonia. Eleven residents developed the
lung disease, and three died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pneumococcal disease accounts for more deaths than any other
vaccine-preventable disease,'' Dr. J. Pekka Nuorti and co-workers
write. Since 1990, they note, drug-resistant strains have become
increasingly common, making treatment difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Inertia among doctors and nursing home staff is largely the
reason why ``some public health recommendations that are so well
known to medical students are so poorly implemented,'' Musher
writes in an editorial, adding that it will probably take public
pressure to wake up the professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was, after all, the Rev. Cotton Mather who urged the
adoption of smallpox (vaccination) in the 18th century over the
objection of Boston's medical establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Drug-resistant forms of HIV raise alarms
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another form of drug resistance is the focus of articles in
today's Journal of the American Medical Association.Resistant forms
of the human immunodeficiency virus, which causes AIDS, are
increasingly common. A panel of 13 experts is calling for
resistance testing among some groups, such as HIV-infected pregnant
women, to warn doctors when to use drugs that will still work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We desperately need more prevalence data in a variety of
places before we can make accurate recommendations on what
physicians should do,'' said Dr. Martin Hirsch, a Boston AIDS
specialist who chaired the group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
