<SLUG> BC-NY-HARLEM-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HARLEM A CRUCIAL TEST FOR PRIVATE ENTERPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (f and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The last time Sikhulu Shange, proprietor of the
Record Shack on Harlem's 125th Street, felt threatened by
development, he blamed it on Racism. This time, he blames it on
Capitalism. In the strange alchemy of urban revitalization, that's
progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are lambs to the slaughter,'' 57-year-old Shange declared
recently. ``We are being driven from existence,'' he said of his
tiny shop, which was at the center of a violent outburst three
years ago when the white store owner from whom he sublet space
tried to evict him in order to expand.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of Shange's new worry is a 265,000-square-foot mall
scheduled to begin rising this summer in the heart of this poor
black community, the first substantial commercial project here in
more than 70 years. It will house an HMV record store that Shange
fears will entice away his customers and a host of other upscale
retailers that have never done business before in a place like
Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   The mall is emerging as a giant test of America's renewed faith
in free markets, and especially of its conviction that private
forces, egged on by substantial tax breaks and low-interest loans,
can reverse the kind of urban blight that a generation of public
programs and billions of dollars of taxpayer money have not.
</P>
<P>
   It is a test as well of a new generation of black leaders who
are often more educated, more affluent, and more at ease with the
business ethos of the era than their predecessors, and one that is
surprisingly, almost shockingly, casual about gestures and
alliances that have largely defined race relations in America since
the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have three, perhaps five, years to prove this thing can
succeed, no more,'' said Deborah C. Wright, the three-time Harvard
graduate (Harvard College, Harvard Law, Harvard Business School)
and president of the Upper Manhattan Empowerment Zone, the agency
responsible for using hundreds of millions of dollars in public
funds to encourage private revitalization of Harlem. ``We can't
give money to people who can't put together a business plan or make
a financial target, no matter how deserving or who they know.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the people almost certain to be looking for money is
Shange. One of the most politically charged decisions Wright is
likely to make is on how to handle his request.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To watch television, where six of the top 10 network shows are
now set in cities, you'd think that urban America is back. To
listen to some business and government leaders, you'd think that
poor urban America is well on its way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inner cities offer market opportunities that are greater than
most countries' and that is beginning to be recognized,'' said
Harvard Business professor Michael E. Porter, who has made himself
a spokesman for private sector revitalization of urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   But inner-city opportunities have yet to produce many results.
Whether they can will be most prominently decided in Harlem _
arguably the nation's best-known inner city, the emotional home
base to millions of African Americans, and a place where the forces
of decline and revival are squared off as almost nowhere else.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most heavily patrolled sections of New York, it has a
murder rate that is still twice the citywide average. Only a
10-minute subway ride from the corporate headquarters of Midtown,
it has an unemployment rate that is four times the national
average. Some streets are lined with elegant brownstones, but
almost one third of its buildings are abandoned. Some affluent
families have begun to return, but more than one third of its
households remain on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   To tackle these problems, ``We're trying to build businesses and
create jobs, not expand social service bureaucracies and erect
monuments to government,'' said New York's Republican governor,
George E. Pataki, whose administration provides Wright's agency
with one third of its funding. ``If our approach can succeed in
Harlem, then there is absolutely no reason it can't succeed
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One measure of the odds against it succeeding can be found in
the story of what happened at the Record Shack three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The current revitalization effort did not begin with Congress's
1993 passage of empowerment zone legislation, but with a series of
skirmishes between street vendors and police along 125th Street
that ended in murder and arson. City officials insisted then that
they were simply trying to maintain order, but some Harlem
residents saw the plight of the black vendors as part of a larger
struggle to free Harlem from what they believed to be its mostly
white store owners.
</P>
<P>
   The battle lines hardened in late 1995 when the white owner of
Freddy's Fashion Mart on 125th Street, Fred A. Harari, told one of
the few black store owners that he could no longer sublet space.
The black owner was Record Shack owner Shange.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6558 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HARLEM-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-B     06-25 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HARLEM-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (f and a coding)  
 NEW YORK: ... owner Shange.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shange said recently that, now as then, he believes ``people
have the right to protest when there is an injustice towards
them.'' When he protested Harari's move, angry picketers appeared
in front of Freddy's.
</P>
<P>
   Then on a cold day in December, Roland J. Smith Jr., a one-time
vendor, picketer, and self-described black revolutionary, took
matters into his own hands. He entered Freddy's with a .38-caliber
handgun, wounded four people, set a fire in which seven perished,
and shot himself in the chest. The memory of the massacre still
haunts 125th Street. In a similar episode two months ago, a black
man threatened to firebomb a white-owned store across the street.
When police caught up with him, they discovered his duffel bag
contained an AK-47 assault rifle, seven banana clips, a .22-caliber
pistol, a two-way radio, and a ski mask.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One pattern that often emerges after violent outbursts like the
Freddy's attack is that the government pumps money into programs to
revitalize poor communities. A second is that the programs almost
invariably fail. To almost everyone's amazement, that hasn't
happened here _ at least so far.
</P>
<P>
   On its face, the current revitalization effort looks a lot like
previous ones, a government program that promises to use public
dollars to lure private business, but often wind up spending its
money on ancillary things like housing, social services, and
politically connected projects.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are two differences here. First, officials are
actually spending the bulk of their funds on businesses like the
new mall. Second, they are beginning to argue what until recently
would have been heretical in Harlem: that what the community really
needs to do is get ready to compete in the mainstream capitalist
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard for African Americans to wholly embrace capitalism
because we started out in the system as slaves, but the truth is
it's the only thing you can count on,'' said Wright, the
empowerment zone president. ``We've tried the legal system and
we've tried the political system, and that's gotten us part of the
way. But we've got a very, very long way to go,'' she said. ``I
don't see that we have much of an option but to make our peace with
capitalism.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Wright and her colleagues can offer the community a
considerable cushion against the rigors of capitalist competition _
almost $550 million in publicly funded grants, low-interest loans,
and tax breaks over the next 10 years. But their call for Harlem to
get over its problem with free markets is more than rhetoric; to
the shock of some local business people, they have begun enforcing
some rudimentary standards of the mainstream economy.
</P>
<P>
   When Dorothy Pitman Hughes, a politically connected community
activist and owner of Harlem Office Supply, applied for a loan two
years ago, she was rejected. ``Debbie Wright told me the
reason...is I'm not a good businesswoman,'' Hughes said. Hughes
admitted owing $23,000 in back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   How empowerment zone officials have managed to take such action
when it is so at odds with what most of Harlem was saying and doing
about its problems only a few years ago is hard to explain. More
than anything else, it appears to be that residents believe the
officials' promise to land something big for the community. And the
first and crucial ``something'' is Harlem USA, a $65 million
glass-walled mall that will house a nine-screen Loews theater, an
Old Navy clothing store, a Modell's sporting goods store, an New
York Sports Club gym, and a Disney store, as well as an HMV
Records.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of the mall, together with a Pathmark supermarket
going up nearby, is almost impossible to overstate, according to
local leaders. Upper Manhattan (which includes the Harlem, East
Harlem, Washington Heights, and Inwood sections) has 520,000
residents, or only slightly fewer than Boston. But is has only one
movie house, and no full-sized supermarkets, upscale clothing
stores, or chain record stores.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody is thrilled with the progress. People like Hughes
see a dark purpose in the empowerment zone's strategy. ``They are
trying to move the mass of black people out of Harlem as part of
gentrification,'' asserted the office supply store owner. Hispanic
store owners almost succeeded in killing the Pathmark supermarket
because Abyssinian Development was involved in the project and
Abyssinian is black.
</P>
<P>
   Still with the coming of the mall, something fundamental is
changing in Harlem and nobody knows it better than record store
owner Shange. After complaining recently about the project's
failure to respect ``the essence of the community'' and its
``onslaught against community-based businesses'' such as his, he
abruptly switched gears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a different ballgame,'' he said of the mall and the HMV
record store. ``It's just another business competing with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Shange is willing to go head-to-head with HMV, but he said needs
something in order to do it. ``Working capital.''
Two-hundred-thousand dollars of it. And he wants it from the
empowerment zone.
</P>
<P>
   Told of the figure, Wright remarked, ``That's an awful lot of
working capital for a little record store.'' Perhaps, but this is
the question that has got to be in the back of her mind: Is it an
awful lot for racial calm?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
