<SLUG> BC-NEW-PLANET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTRONOMY TEAM FINDS NEW PLANET BIGGER THAN JUPITER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The world's champion planet-finders have
discovered another new world, one tantalizingly close to Earth's
doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   Two San Francisco State University astronomers and two of their
colleagues found the planet orbiting a star called Gliese 876, 15
light-years away. It is far closer than any previously known
extrasolar planet, or one outside Earth's solar system.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of an extrasolar world so close to our own, and
orbiting such a low-mass star, implies the galaxy is even more
jam-packed with these planets than previously believed, said lead
researcher Geoffrey Marcy of San Francisco State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's by far the closest star around which any planet has been
found,'' Marcy said Wednesday. The previous closest-known
extrasolar planet orbits a star about 35 light-years away. A
light-year is 5.9 trillion miles, the distance light travels in one
year.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the star is unusually low in mass to have its own planet.
``It's by far the faintest star around which a planet has been
found,'' Marcy said. The star is too faint to be seen with the
naked eye, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The star's size is another hint that extrasolar planets may be
common throughout the galaxy, Marcy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the stars in the galaxy are these little puny stars
that are a tenth to a third the mass of our sun,'' he said. ``It
certainly tells us that low-mass stars can harbor planets, and so
there may be many more planets in the galaxy.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the seventh planet find since 1995 for Marcy and his
associates. So far, 12 such planets have been found by the world's
astronomers.
</P>
<P>
   The latest planet was detected using one of the two giant Keck
Observatory telescopes atop Mauna Kea on the big island of Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The planet was not seen directly by Marcy and his colleagues.
Rather, they detected subtle wobbles in the star's motion caused by
the back-and-forth gravitational tug of the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Marcy's other partners in the discovery are Paul Butler of the
Anglo-Australian Observatory in Australia, Steve Vogt of the
University of California at Santa Cruz and Debra Fischer of San
Francisco State.
</P>
<P>
   The planet is about 1.8 times as large as Jupiter, the biggest
planet in our solar system, Marcy said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he described it to colleagues at an astronomy conference
in Canada this month.
</P>
<P>
   Although this is Marcy and his associates' seventh planet
discovery, the quest hasn't gotten dull.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what Paul Butler and I have devoted our lives to,'' Marcy
said. ``We don't have kids. We work until midnight at this. This is
what we're after in life. The main thing we like to do is to find
more planets.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 28, astronomer Susan Terebey and her colleagues at a
private research firm in Pasadena announced they had used the
Hubble Space Telescope to spot what might be an extrasolar planet
escaping from a star system about 450 light-years from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Marcy reacted cautiously to Terebey's claim. Her
planet explanation ``is only one of several interpretations'' of
the object, he said. ``The jury is certainly still out. One of the
leading alternative interpretations is that it's a background
star.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
