<P>
   COURT-VETO (Washington) _ 1stLd-Writethru will be filed for
story that moved earlier _ The Supreme Court says Congress violated
the Constitution's separation of powers rule when it passed the
Line Item Veto Act giving the president authority to cut individual
projects out of tax and spending bills. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-ATTORNEY-CLIENT (Washington) _ The Supreme Court
sidetracks Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's effort to obtain
notes of a conversation between White House aide Vincent Foster and
his lawyer shortly before Foster committed suicide. The court
upholds the attorney-client privilege of confidentiality even
though Foster is dead. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACC0-HOUSE (Washington) _ A week after the Senate killed
sweeping anti-smoking legislation, House Republican leaders outline
a much narrower bill that would include a national advertising
campaign to curb teen smoking but is unlikely to impose new
cigarette taxes. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-TRENDS (WASHINGTON) _ Methamphetamine, an ``upper'' drug
long popular in California, is emerging as a problem for drug
enforcement officials elsewhere in the country, particularly on the
East Coast, a new report says. By NICOLE TSONG.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TIANANMEN (Beijing) _ already filed _ President Clinton
is walking a political tightrope by accepting China's official
welcoming ceremony overlooking the 98-acre expanse of Tiananmen
Square where hundreds of unarmed pro-democracy activists were
killed by army troops in 1989. The welcoming ceremony begins at 9
p.m. EDT Friday. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
