<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6593 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-MEXICO-CHICANOS-$A     06-25 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-MEXICO-CHICANOS-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHICANOS AND MEXICANS EXPLORE SIMILARITIES, DIFFERENCES IN
MEXICO CITY
 &HT;    With photo placed in the International folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, June 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Maybe it's the fact that she favors whole-grain
cereal in the morning over ``pan dulce,'' traditional Mexican sweet
bread.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the jolt she felt when she scanned newspaper ads here
and found companies openly demanding job applicants who were
``unmarried, pretty girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Certain things Monica Sahagun has experienced in Mexico remind
her that many of her sensibilities were shaped by her Southern
California upbringing -- although Spanish was her first language,
she was raised by Mexican parents and, as she puts its, she
``camouflages'' herself well here.
</P>
<P>
   Sahagun is a Mexican-American living in Mexico City, and an
organizer of the first meeting to be held in Mexico City of a U.S.
academic group, the National Association for Chicana and Chicano
Studies.
</P>
<P>
   An underlying theme at the June 24-27 conference is an
exploration not just of the ties that bind Mexicans and Chicanos,
but also the cultural clashes and mutual resentment that sometimes
plague their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has a special attraction for Mexican-Americans, and even
though they've heard stories from their immigrant relatives about
hardship and corruption, Mexico's culture is familiar enough to
many to make them feel at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here for survival of the ``alma,'' the soul,'' said
Sahagun.
</P>
<P>
   With the population and political clout of Mexican-Americans
growing, the Mexican government has taken more of an interest in
the Chicano community in the United States. Mexico's Congress
recently voted to allow Mexican-born U.S. citizens or their
children to regain their Mexican nationality, a decision that might
allow some to eventually vote in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   And through the art exhibits and panels convened by this
conference, organizers hope, more Mexicans may be persuaded to put
aside their sometimes snobbish views of Chicanos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of Chicano conferences in places like Germany,
Holland and Spain. It's about time Mexicans had a conference for us
here,''' said Maria Herrera-Sobek, a Chicano Studies instructor at
the University of California, Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Sobek travels to Mexico often for research on her speciality,
``corridos,'' Mexican folk songs. She believes Mexicans are growing
less judgmental of Chicanos, who are sometimes mocked here for not
speaking Spanish perfectly or for showing an interest in
traditional Mexican music and art that some urbane Mexicans find
old-fashioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're beginning to be seen here as something other than
traitors who crossed the border,'' Herrera-Sobek said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet differences persist.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference held recently in Mexico City to promote the
Chicano Studies meeting, some Mexican journalists were irritated
that the program appeared to be mostly in English, although
translation would be provided.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers patiently pointed out that English is the dominant
tongue of many Chicano scholars because they live and work as
professionals in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Mexicans, Chicanos are like the great tome, 'Don Quixote.'
All Mexicans know about 'Don Quixote,' but few have ever read it.
Likewise, Chicanos are known, but rarely studied or understood,''
said Alex Ramirez, a Mexican conference organizer and professor of
Chicano Studies at Mexico's Autonomous National University.
</P>
<P>
   At a Chicano art exhibit hosted by the conference, some Mexicans
were startled by paintings and etchings that blended symbols of
ancient Mexico with low rider cars or scenes from U.S. Latino
barrios.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why so much nostalgia for Mexico?'' asked a puzzled Margarita
Martinez, a Mexico City elementary school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Margo Gutierrez, a Latino Studies librarian at the University of
Texas, Austin, said, ``Being Chicano and coming to Mexico or living
in Mexico can be a poignant experience. Mexicans sometimes don't
know what to make of us.''
</P>
<P>
   For young Chicano students, she added, attending a Chicano
Studies conference in Mexico offers a healthy dose of reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of them idealize Mexican culture, and that's natural.
It's part of their roots,'' she said. ``So it's good for them to
come here and see how different Mexico is, yet appreciate where
they came from and celebrate the good things that we have
maintained.''
</P>
<P>
   Maryana Carsillo, who is studying Chicano and Latin American
literature at the UC-Irvine, said Chicanos seem to ``either hold on
really tight, or let go'' of Mexican culture as they try to sort
out their identity.
</P>
<P>
   As a child in Los Angeles, she said, she realized she wasn't
really as Mexican as Mexicans when she would visit her cousins each
summer in Guadalajara.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my cousins would tell me jokes in Spanish, I realized I
couldn't tell them back to them,'' she said. ``And they thought you
were being stuck-up when you mixed English into your Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   Raquel Marquez, a Ph.D. student in sociology at UT, grew up on
the border, closer to Mexico, and in her work she regularly blends
both worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Marquez was in Mexico City for a panel called ``Mexicanas and
Chicanas Bridging Two Worlds: A Study of Poverty on the
Texas-Mexico Border.''
</P>
<P>
   Her research takes her back to Brownsville, Texas, where she
grew up, and over to Matamoros, in Mexico, where she gathers life
histories of women on both sides of the frontier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love traveling in Mexico,'' she said. ``The culture shock is
only what you make of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicano Studies Association is 25 years old, and reflects a
scholarship that grew out of the 1960s civil rights movement to
recognize Chicano history and ethnicity. About 600 U.S. students
and teachers signed up to come to the Mexico conference, along with
dozens of Mexican researchers and speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of panels addressed subjects as diverse as ``Violence and
Militarization on the Mexico-U.S. Border'' to ``A Catholic Church
and its Role in the Barrio.''
</P>
<P>
   Several panels on gay Chicanos, gender conflict and the
generally favorable Chicano reaction to the Zapatista rebel
movement in Mexico's southern state of Chiapas tread on sensitive
ground in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Chicanos have followed the Zapatista Indian uprising in Chiapas
with interest and support, said Monica Sahagun. After living in
Mexico for a year, she said, she now compares the Chicano community
in the United States with the dispossessed Indians in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education, health care, work -- the demands are the same,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sahagun, who works as a translator for the Mexican news agency
Notimex, performed a one-woman show about bilingualism and
biculturalism to help open the Chicano Studies conference here.
</P>
<P>
   She danced to Mexican folk music and to Chicano rap, and slid
effortlessly between Spanish and English while describing how she
balances between ``hot and cold, happy and sad, English and
Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My world has always been double,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
