</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TWO CENTURIES OF U.S.-CHINA UPS AND DOWNS
 &HT;    With CHINA-CLINTON-0626; CHINA-LEADERS-$ADV26.
 &HT;    For Use Friday, June 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Some of the high points and low points in the
two-century relationship between the United States and China:
</P>
<P>
   1800-1820 _ Opium Trade. American merchant ships, many belonging
to Russell &AMP; Co. and other respectable Boston shipowners, join the
British in smuggling Indian opium to Chinese ports to feed the
addiction of 1 million Chinese, in return for Chinese silks and
spices and tea.
</P>
<P>
   1821 _ Terranova Incident. A crewman of the U.S. merchant ship
docked in Canton harbor accidentally drops an earthenware pitcher
that kills a Chinese fruit seller. The ship's captain, afraid that
his illegal opium cargo will be confiscated, surrenders the man.
The crewman, named Terranova, is executed after a secret one-day
Chinese trial, causing outrage in America.
</P>
<P>
   1843 _ Treaty Rights. American President John Tyler sends
Massachusetts Congressman Caleb Cushing as an emissary to the
Chinese imperial court. Cushing concludes the Treaty of Wanghia,
granting American merchants extra-territorial rights in five
Chinese ports. The treaty also opens China to American missionaries
by allowing American-run ``hospitals, churches and cemeteries.''
</P>
<P>
   1865-1880 _ Coolie Labor. Chinese by the tens of thousands
immigrate to the United States, most to work in labor gangs
building America's western railroads. Without the Chinese, ``it
would be impossible to complete the Western portion of this great
national enterprise within the time required by Congress,'' the
governor of California writes to President Andrew Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   1880-1900 _ ``Yellow Peril.'' Unemployed American whites spread
hatred against Chinese immigrants, culminating in scalpings of
Chinese workers in Montana and other western states. U.S. Congress
restricts immigration by Chinese, and the Chinese population in the
United States drops from 110,000 to 60,000.
</P>
<P>
   1908 _ Chinese Students. U.S. Congress allocates $12 million to
bring Chinese students to the United States. Over the next two
decades, 1,268 Chinese scholars study in America.
</P>
<P>
   1940-1945 _ Flying Tigers. With Japan occupying the northern
Chinese region of Manchuria, President Franklin D. Roosevelt's
administration authorizes ex-U.S. Army officer Claire Chennault to
recruit ``the Flying Tigers,'' an unofficial force of American
pilots. Their combat missions from Chinese bases against Japanese
fighters eventually help expel Japan from China.
</P>
<P>
   1949 _ Communist takeover. The United States does not recognize
the new communist regime of Mao Tse-tung.
</P>
<P>
   January 1950 _ Green Light? Public declarations by the Truman
Administration define a new Pacific ``defense perimeter'' that does
not include Taiwan or South Korea among America's key strategic
interests. Republicans later charge that Truman gave communist
forces a green light to attack South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   June 25, 1950 _ Korean War. North Korean armies strike south
across the 38th Parallel and capture South Korea's capital, Seoul,
drawing Truman to order U.S. troops into combat to help South
Korea. After an initial stalemate, China joins the invasion,
sending 700,000 troops into South Korea. Chinese ``human wave''
tactics cause revulsion in America.
</P>
<P>
   July 1953 _ Nuclear Threat. Korean war ends in an armistice,
following a veiled threat by President Dwight Eisenhower to bomb
China with nuclear weapons. America's Korean War losses reach
54,000 dead and 103,000 wounded, Chinese casualties reached
800,000.
</P>
<P>
   1957 _ Nuclear Tension. United States deploys nuclear-armed
Matador missiles on Taiwan. Mao gave a cold-blooded riposte: ``If
the worst came to the worst and half of mankind died, the other
half would remain while imperialism would be razed to the ground
and the whole world would become socialist.''
</P>
<P>
   February 1972 _ Isolation Ends. President Richard Nixon visits
China, ending two decades of U.S.-China hostility. Nixon's trip
brings about a rapprochement that has continued, with fits and
starts, until now.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
