<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6618 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-CHINA-LEADERS-$ADV     06-25 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CHINA-LEADERS-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BECOME AN INSTANT CHINA WATCHER: HERE'S THE POLITBURO SCORECARD
 &HT;    With CHINA-CLINTON; CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV26.
 &HT;    For Use Friday, June 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The enigmatic Chinese leadership that awaits President
Bill Clinton is like a carriage hitched to three galloping
stallions: one sturdy, one limping, one flashy.
</P>
<P>
   Loping along behind the ruling troika is a well-groomed yearling
that few outside China have ever heard of. If one of the three lead
horses falters, this fresh horse looks ready to make his move.
</P>
<P>
   Why not become your own amateur China-watcher? Just tune in
events over the next two days and scrutinize these four big steeds
of the Chinese Communist Party politburo.
</P>
<P>
   You can bet that every professional China follower around the
world will be glued to the coverage of Clinton during his 21-gun
greeting at Tiananmen Square and the banquet later in the Great
Hall of the People. They'll be watching for bits of byplay, body
language and facial expressions to gain insight into such questions
as these:
</P>
<P>
   How will these four cunning survivors of a generation of
sometimes deadly party intrigue interact with each other, and with
the Clinton entourage? Which of the three leading rivals-in-harness
really pulls the most weight? Are they pulling in different
directions? Who will be ``in'' and who will be ``out'' by the year
2000?
</P>
<P>
   China is run by a self-perpetuating, secretive and extremely
status-conscious leadership collective.
</P>
<P>
   Those with real power number only about 200, of which more than
180 are men. They are the chieftains of China's ruling communist
party, along with a dwindling cadre of retired revolutionary elders
in their 80s and 90s. (Most of those not yet retired hold second
hats as cabinet ministers, province chiefs, or generals of the
People's Liberation Army.)
</P>
<P>
   On questions as crucial as how to handle the Clinton visit, a
rough consensus will have to emerge among all China's collective
leadership, and especially among the roughly 20 members of the
party's ruling politburo. The leaders who matter the most in
shaping any consensus are the seven men who make up the politburo's
Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Of these ``big seven'' in the politburo's inner sanctum, the
most interesting to watch during the Clinton visit are:
</P>
<P>
   _ The sturdy work horse: State President Jiang Zemin, 71, who
ranks first in the politburo and also chairs the vital Central
Military Commission. China-watchers used to deride Jiang as ``the
flower-pot'' because he managed to look good without doing
anything. Others sneered at him as ``the weather vane'' because he
seemed to have no beliefs of his own. To their surprise, this bland
figure _ long viewed as a mere transitional leader put in after the
Tiananmen Square debacle _ has clung to the top job in the Chinese
communist party for nine years. That is longer than any party
general secretary since the Great Helmsman, Mao Tse-tung, who died
in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   _- The limping war horse: the chairman of the rubber-stamp
legislature, Li Peng, 69, who ranks second in the politburo. To
dissidents and foreign human rights monitors, Li is the ``butcher
of Beijing.'' As premier in May 1989, Li issued the infamous
martial law declaration that led to the Tiananmen massacre. Despite
worldwide excoriation, the party allowed this cautious hardliner to
serve out two full five-year terms as premier, the maximum allowed
by constitution. Then just three months ago Li stepped down as
premier to chair the National People's Congress, where he
occasionally receives second-level foreign deputations in his
quarters in the Great Hall of the People. Otherwise he is little
seen.
</P>
<P>
   _ The flashy race horse: The new premier Zhu Rongji, 69, who
ranks third in the politburo. The darling of today's Chinese
student generation and of many Western financiers, the hard-driving
``Boss Zhu'' is credited as the magician of China's economic growth
miracle. When Zhu was made ``economic czar'' in 1993, inflation was
soaring at 24 percent a year and China's dollar reserves were down
to a dangerous $20 billion. Using his own blend of market
mechanisms and a communist-style nonconvertible currency, Zhu
engineered a ``soft landing.'' He brought inflation to zero, kept
economic growth roaring and increased dollar reserves to $140
billion. Some have compared Zhu with Ludwig Erhard, the engineer of
Germany's post-war recovery. ``No matter what is waiting in front
of me _ whether it be land minds or an abyss _ I will blaze my
trail,'' Zhu said when he was promoted to premier three months ago.
Zhu's handicap: he lacks an independent power base and he's stepped
on too many toes. If the Chinese economy sours, Zhu could be put
out to pasture.
</P>
<P>
   -- The young horse: Vice President Hu Jintao, 55, the
fifth-ranking member of the politburo. Dubbed the ``golden boy''
and ``rising star'' of the politburo, Hu is the youngest in the
party's inner circle. He got there because of his tough, yet adroit
handling of separatist unrest in Tibet, where he became regional
party boss in 1989. Within a month of Hu's arrival in Tibet, the
death of the 10th Panchen Lama led to independence demonstrations.
By wielding a news blackout, tear gas and martial law, Hu snuffed
out the protests without embarrassing Beijing. Returning to the
capital in 1992, Hu immediately vaulted into the politburo standing
committee, reportedly on the say-so of then Chinese communist
patriarch Deng Xiaoping, who died in 1997. Barring a stumble, Hu is
on track to become the next communist party general secretary by
2002 and president of China by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
