A6619 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-IRAN-SOCCERSCRIBE-     06-25 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-IRAN-SOCCERSCRIBE-0626-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SPORTS REPORTER FIRST IRANIAN WOMAN TO ATTEND SOCCER MATCH
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i ) International and (s ) Sports
categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox Newspapers 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ For this sports reporter to get the story, she
has to break the gender barrier in Iranian soccer.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Mahin Gorji became the first Iranian woman to attend a
soccer game here since the Islamic revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   She credits the new moderate Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
for making it possible, but it's still hard for a woman sports
reporter in a country where most sporting events are segregated by
gender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud. I'm Iranian. I prove to men that women are
powerful,'' said the enthusiastic Gorji, a 29-year-old reporter
with the Jameah (Society) daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   While Iranian women can hold important jobs in Iran _ one is
vice president _ and are freer than women in countries nearby, they
still live under strict limits.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious rule is that they must wear a head scarf and
large cape or raincoat-styled covering, in keeping with ``modesty''
customs.
</P>
<P>
   Less obvious, but more important, women's court testimony is
worth only half that of men's and they automatically lose custody
of the children in a divorce, for which the husbands must give
approval.
</P>
<P>
   The sports rules seem arbitrary. Women cannot attend soccer
games or play organized soccer. They can attend men's basketball,
but are told it is too dangerous for them in a stadium of crazed
male soccer fans.
</P>
<P>
   Women can play several organized sports, but men cannot attend
when women are not fully covered. Men can attend women's canoeing,
skiing and shooting, but not volleyball or swimming.
</P>
<P>
   Gorji does not appear to be a trendsetter. While other Iranian
women are pushing the limits by wearing colorful head scarves far
back on their heads, she wears a traditional black hood and
repeatedly pulls it over her hair.
</P>
<P>
   But, she works at one of Iran's most progressive newspapers _
conservatives are attempting to close it down. She loves sports
and, in Iran, soccer is number one.
</P>
<P>
   When Iran hosted a soccer match against Kuwait in April, Gorji's
editor got permission from the government for her to attend.
</P>
<P>
   She said other reporters, players and coaches welcomed her, at
times too much.
</P>
<P>
   The Kuwaiti coach offered a handshake, but Gorji knew police
nearby would object to any physical contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, I'm sorry. I'm a Muslim. I'm not allowed to shake
your hand,''' she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   That game was in a small stadium in the Iranian city of Tabriz.
Gorji later covered a game in Tehran's 100,000-seat Azadi Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Indicative of current Iranian debate over how to reform Iran
nearly 20 years after the Islamic revolution, some praised Gorji.
But a female editor at Iran Sports, a sports daily, said she was
acting too much like Western women.
</P>
<P>
   Gorji, an avid volleyball and pick-up soccer player herself, is
bothered that other women cannot attend soccer matches.
</P>
<P>
   The desire is there. When the Iranian soccer team returned to
the country in December after qualifying for the World Cup
Tournament, several thousand women forced their way into the
stadium to honor the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not allowed to do something, you want to do it,''
she said. ``It's their right and I'm angry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   For clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
