<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, June 27.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUPREME COURT &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has issued a number of significant
rulings today. Here is how our coverage will be organized:
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-VETO (Washington) _ The Supreme Court strikes down as
unconstitutional the line-item veto that let the president cancel
specific items in tax and spending measures. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-AIDS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court says that even
HIV-infected people who suffer no AIDS symptoms are covered by
disability-bias law. The justices do not agree on the question of
whether action in the specific case (a dentist refusing to treat an
HIV-positive patient) is discrimination, sending it back to a lower
court for more evidence. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-STARR (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules against
Kenneth Starr in attorney-client privilege dispute over notes taken
by Vincent Foster's attorney. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-RDP (Washington) _ A roundup of three cases: The high
court upholds the decency provision of National Endowment for the
Arts, saying Congress can deny grants to artists whose work is
considered indecent. The court also rules there is no Fifth
Amendment protection in cases in which foreign governments
prosecute Americans; and rejects, in a mining case, retroactive
rules about liability, saying they amount to a taking. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, we plan to run text as warranted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Sydney Blumenthal testifies before
the grand jury; other developments in Kenneth Starr's investigation
of the president.
</P>
<P>
   (See also SOCTUS-STARR, above)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TOBACCO (Washington) _ House Republican leaders
announce the outline of the tobacco legislation they will offer to
replace the measure that died in the Senate last week. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-ENVIRON (Washington) _ House opponents of the Kyoto
protocol on global warming put a provision in the EPA's spending
bill forbidding it to do almost anything to implement the
unratified treaty: no rules, no orders, no proposals, not even any
``educational outreach or informational seminars.'' It's part of a
broad assault on one of the administration's main environmental
initiatives. By John H. Cushman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN-LUTERANS (Undated) _ The Vatican has substantially
accepted a statement, which Roman Catholics and Lutherans have been
working on for more than 30 years, that spells out whether good
works or God provides salvation. This brings to a close an
important chapter of the Reformation. By Gustav Niehuhr.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-RAMSEY-MURDER (Denver) _ The parents of the slain
6-year-old beauty queen JonBenet Ramsey are being interviewed this
week by investigators from the Boulder County District Attorney's
office, a television station has reported. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON IN CHINA &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SCENE (Xian) _ The scene in Xian and the voices of
ordinary Chinese as Clinton arrives. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON (Xian) _ With the pageantry of thundering drums
and clanging gongs, President Clinton is welcomed to China, the
first american president to visit this country in nearly a decade.
By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSIDENTS (Beijing) _ Just hours before Clinton arrived,
three political dissidents applied to establish an opposition
political party in China; two dissidents were reported arrested in
Xian area. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PEONY (Shanghai) _ Negotiation and debate at the airport
between Chinese cultural officials and the head of Lincoln Center
over the ``Peony Pavilion.'' By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   Others as needed.
