<SLUG> BC-MINIMUM-WAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHER MINIMUM WAGE LEAVES LABOR-FRIENDLY MAYOR DIVIDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHUCK FINNIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A high-stakes, behind-the-scenes policy fight
over whether San Francisco should have the nation's highest minimum
wage for the employees of city contractors is testing Mayor Willie
Brown's strong ties to organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has tried negotiating a deal on the ``living-wage''
ordinance to make it palatable to all sides. On June 1, he met with
representatives of businesses and nonprofit agencies, which would
have to pay their workers the higher wages, and the labor unions
that support the ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   Differences over a possible living-wage law and other city
regulations have led both sides to talk of taking their cases to
voters in November through a ballot initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Brown wants to avoid a messy, costly campaign that is likely to
generate bitter feelingsand end with the loser continuing the
fight in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted them to set aside ballot measures so they could reach
an accord on something so basic as a living wage,'' Brown said
recently.
</P>
<P>
   A living wage, the cornerstone of labor's legislative agenda at
City Hall, is as complicated and politically loaded as any issue to
face the mayor during his two years in office.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the mayor's close political allies at the Service
Employees International Union, labor wants San Francisco to top
other municipalities that have passed living-wage laws, which set
pay minimums for the employees of those who do business with a city
or receive a municipal benefit, such as a grant.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring Oakland has a rate of $8 per hour with health
benefits, or $9.25 without benefits, the highest of a half-dozen
cities in the country that have living-wage laws.
</P>
<P>
   Business interests, while not opposing such a law in San
Francisco, want the measure to exempt small companies and
entry-level jobs. They also hope the pay rate doesn't go so high
that it makes doing business with the city unprofitable.
California's minimum wage is $5.75 per hour; the national minimum
is $5.15 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofit social service agencies want their contracts with the
city increased to cover any higher wages they might be required to
pay under the living-wage minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, nonprofit agencies formed a political
alliance with corporate San Francisco to fight other regulatory
measures at City Hall _ including labor-backed bids for new job
protection for laid-off janitors and restaurant workers and for
easing union organizing drives.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who has enjoyed the support of labor throughout his
political career, could nonetheless prove to be an obstacle in the
minimum wage push.
</P>
<P>
   Labor got a taste of Brown's resistance to part of its agenda at
the June 1 meeting in his office.
</P>
<P>
   When the unions talked about extending the living wage to
general assistance recipients in the city's workfare program, the
mayor let his labor friends know he thought they were going too
far.
</P>
<P>
   Josie Mooney, of Service Employees International Union Local
790, acknowledged her differences with Brown on the point, but said
it would be hypocritical for the city to impose a living wage on
the private sector while exempting workfare participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard (for the city) to hold people to a standard it
doesn't hold itself to,'' Mooney said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mosher of the Committee on Jobs, an association of San
Francisco's biggest corporations, said Brown should be able to help
business, labor and social service groups reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the business community and nonprofit community would
be very amenable to try to build some kind of consensus around a
living-wage issue,'' Mosher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd rather come up with a solution that lifts people out of
poverty without destroying entry-level jobs and harming nonprofit
service delivery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mosher said the mayor's first step was helping persuade both
sides to drop, for now, measures aimed at the November ballot.
</P>
</TEXT>
