<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6628 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-2000-0625-$     06-25 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-2000-0625-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. THREATENED BY DELAYS ABROAD ON 'MILLENNIUM BUG'
 &HT;    620&AMP;add. With COMPUTERS-DATA
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Saturday, June 27.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRFAX, Va. _ American prosperity could be eroded by slow
progress in many other countries toward updating millions of
computer systems and billions of microchips to recognize the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The damage ``would be about the same size as the expected
economic damage from the turmoil in East Asia,'' Maria Livanos
Gattaui, secretary general of the International Chamber of
Commerce, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do we inject a sense of urgency without generating
doomsday hysteria?'' she asked some 1,700 senior high-tech and
government leaders at the World Congress on Information Technology
here.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates from 93 countries spent hours comparing notes on
the political and technical changes needed to fix or replace
millions of pre-1997 computers and software programs and billions
of embedded chips in electronic devices that won't know whether the
two-digit date ``00'' stands for 1900 or 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irrespective of whether it is a problem of $1 billion or $1
trillion, it is a problem that is going to affect every country,''
said Ahmad Kamal, a Pakistani diplomat who heads the United Nations
working group on information technology. ``Due to the mere
existence of information-technology networks, no country is in an
isolated pocket that can be hermetically sealed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, government and corporate decision-makers
began focusing seriously on the problem in 1995. Prosperous
European and Asian countries followed up within the next two years.
A survey this year of governments in 158 of the world's poorest
countries showed that more than half had done nothing _ mistakenly
thinking of the so-called Y2K bug was a ``rich nations' problem''
that wouldn't affect their phones, power grids, shipping or fuel
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of late right now for many of us,'' acknowledged
diplomat Carl Frances of Trinidad and Tobago. ``The World Bank is
using British grants to sponsor 20 meetings, including one in
Jamaica for Caribbean countries within a few weeks, to see a
presentation an Italian firm has developed on what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In China, we do not have today the manpower with the precise
skills needed to do this work, `` said Junjie Li, a professor
working for a joint state-private software firm in Qingdao.
Imported software riddled with Year 2000 bugs is used to run
Chinese computers that handle everything from airports and military
missiles to the payrolls at government-owned factories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are outsourcing to Americans for the fixes,'' Junjie said.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's government recently decided to give tax credits to
businesses that make deadlines and punish government officials who
miss them, said Kuo Yun, the former general who heads Taiwan's
official Year 2000 efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some American firms are subcontracting Year 2000 work
to India, where lower wages and longer hours cut the cost by
three-fourths.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are running three shifts a day right now, doing a lot of
work right from Calcutta for customers in the United States,'' said
Tapan Mukerji, director of a systems integration firm. ``Of course,
we have our own Year 2000 problems, though not as intense or
extensive as in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't put it in the category of 'we're satisfied and we
don't worry about it,' or, you know, 'we're hysterical and our hair
is on fire.' It's somewhere in the middle,'' said Michael Dell,
chairman and chief executive officer of Dell Computer Corp. His
Texas-based company depends on the Internet, phone calls, faxes and
trips to coordinate operations in 42 countries.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Small firms, exporters and importers will bear the brunt of the
risks, predicted David J. Cassano, general manager of Year 2000
global initiatives for IBM Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many small companies are still holding out hope that someone
will come up with the one tool, the silver bullet, that they can
install on a Friday and be okay on a Monday. It isn't going to
happen,'' Cassano said. He said IBM polls of its own customers
suggest that three-fourths of them ``either haven't gotten started
or are in denial.''
</P>
<P>
   Even among large companies, ``globally, many of them are still
in the assessment phase _ sorting out what really has to get
fixed,'' Cassano said.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts in Europe are handicapped by the diversion of many
programmers to work on converting financial systems for next year's
switch from marks, francs and other currencies to the new euro.
</P>
<P>
   Asia's economic turmoil has drained corporate and government
budgets that could have been diverted to Year 2000 fixes, as well.
</P>
<P>
   In many African and Latin American countries, private and public
leaders alike were concentrating on switching from
government-commanded economies to free-market systems, and did not
pay much attention to warnings from their technical staffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some executives tell me 'I'm working on it,' and they just
mean they're still deciding which outside vendor they will try to
hire to perform a miracle,'' said Fernando Parra, president of DTS
Software Latin America, which works on Year 2000 fixes for clients
in many countries.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Parra said, ``Here in Brazil and in
most of Latin America the worst problem is huge governmental firms
_ telephone companies and banks and electrical companies _ that
move so slowly because they need to ask for public bids, and need
budgeting in advance.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If a telephone company in Peru or in Brazil stops
working, or if an insurance company or bank shuts down for a few
days or a few weeks or whatever, it is a problem for everyone in
every country that is doing business with them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Face it, everybody's behind schedule everywhere, and not all
the work will be done,'' said Barry Ingram, a vice president for
Texas-based Electronic Data Systems Inc., which does systems work
in most countries of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people have to do is assess all their systems, designate
the mission-critical ones that they must repair or replace, and
find ways to live with the errors in the rest of them,'' Ingram
said.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting problems should be kept in perspective, said
Cassano of IBM. ``If an ATM won't give you money, it doesn't mean
your money is not safe. It means the ATM is broken,'' Cassano said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
