<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6636 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HARLEM-2TAKES-BOS &LR;      06-25 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HARLEM-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HARLEM A CRUCIAL TEST FOR PRIVATE ENTERPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (f and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The last time Sikhulu Shange, proprietor of the
Record Shack on Harlem's 125th Street, felt threatened by
development, he blamed it on Racism. This time, he blames it on
Capitalism. In the strange alchemy of urban revitalization, that's
progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are lambs to the slaughter,'' 57-year-old Shange declared
recently. ``We are being driven from existence,'' he said of his
tiny shop, which was at the center of a violent outburst three
years ago when the white store owner from whom he sublet space
tried to evict him in order to expand.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of Shange's new worry is a 265,000-square-foot mall
scheduled to begin rising this summer in the heart of this poor
black community, the first substantial commercial project here in
more than 70 years. It will house an HMV record store that Shange
fears will entice away his customers and a host of other upscale
retailers that have never done business before in a place like
Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   The mall is emerging as a giant test of America's renewed faith
in free markets, and especially of its conviction that private
forces, egged on by substantial tax breaks and low-interest loans,
can reverse the kind of urban blight that a generation of public
programs and billions of dollars of taxpayer money have not.
</P>
<P>
   It is a test as well of a new generation of black leaders who
are often more educated, more affluent, and more at ease with the
business ethos of the era than their predecessors, and one that is
surprisingly, almost shockingly, casual about gestures and
alliances that have largely defined race relations in America since
the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have three, perhaps five, years to prove this thing can
succeed, no more,'' said Deborah C. Wright, the three-time Harvard
graduate (Harvard College, Harvard Law, Harvard Business School)
and president of the Upper Manhattan Empowerment Zone, the agency
responsible for using hundreds of millions of dollars in public
funds to encourage private revitalization of Harlem. ``We can't
give money to people who can't put together a business plan or make
a financial target, no matter how deserving or who they know.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the people almost certain to be looking for money is
Shange. One of the most politically charged decisions Wright is
likely to make is on how to handle his request.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To watch television, where six of the top 10 network shows are
now set in cities, you'd think that urban America is back. To
listen to some business and government leaders, you'd think that
poor urban America is well on its way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inner cities offer market opportunities that are greater than
most countries' and that is beginning to be recognized,'' said
Harvard Business professor Michael E. Porter, who has made himself
a spokesman for private sector revitalization of urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   But inner-city opportunities have yet to produce many results.
Whether they can will be most prominently decided in Harlem _
arguably the nation's best-known inner city, the emotional home
base to millions of African Americans, and a place where the forces
of decline and revival are squared off as almost nowhere else.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most heavily patrolled sections of New York, it has a
murder rate that is still twice the citywide average. Only a
10-minute subway ride from the corporate headquarters of Midtown,
it has an unemployment rate that is four times the national
average. Some streets are lined with elegant brownstones, but
almost one third of its buildings are abandoned. Some affluent
families have begun to return, but more than one third of its
households remain on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   To tackle these problems, ``We're trying to build businesses and
create jobs, not expand social service bureaucracies and erect
monuments to government,'' said New York's Republican governor,
George E. Pataki, whose administration provides Wright's agency
with one third of its funding. ``If our approach can succeed in
Harlem, then there is absolutely no reason it can't succeed
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One measure of the odds against it succeeding can be found in
the story of what happened at the Record Shack three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The current revitalization effort did not begin with Congress's
1993 passage of empowerment zone legislation, but with a series of
skirmishes between street vendors and police along 125th Street
that ended in murder and arson. City officials insisted then that
they were simply trying to maintain order, but some Harlem
residents saw the plight of the black vendors as part of a larger
struggle to free Harlem from what they believed to be its mostly
white store owners.
</P>
<P>
   The battle lines hardened in late 1995 when the white owner of
Freddy's Fashion Mart on 125th Street, Fred A. Harari, told one of
the few black store owners that he could no longer sublet space.
The black owner was Record Shack owner Shange.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1438EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
