<SLUG> BC-WOM-NOTES-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN 1977, SHE WAS ONE OF THE BOYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects Leslie Greis, sted Linda)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty-one years ago,  &UR; Leslie Greis  &LR; was playing golf with the
guys at Harvard. Not necessarily because she wanted to _ Harvard
didn't have a women's team.
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward to last week. Greis was rubbing elbows with
professional golfers at the US Open in San Francisco, and  &UR; Arnold
Palmer  &LR; presented her with an Achievement Award from the College
Golf Foundation and Rolex at a dinner hosted by Palmer and  &UR; Jim
Nantz. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Greis, who grew up in Holden, Mass., recalls that when she
entered Harvard in 1977, ``it came on the heels of Title IX,
(enacted in 1975) so absent a women's team, I was welcomed onto the
men's team.'' She went on to earn three varsity letters before
graduating with a degree in economics in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Greis, 39, said that being a minority on the team didn't strike
her as especially unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had done the same thing at Wachusett Regional High School,
so playing with guys was not anything different,'' she said. She
admits the caliber of play was different, though. ``It was at the
college level, and we played at The Country Club.''
</P>
<P>
   While none of her teammates treated her differently, Greis
acknowledged that competitors often did a double take. ``I'm sure a
couple of heads turned,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since a women's team was not formed at Harvard until 12 years
after she entered, Greis was allowed to enter women's tournaments,
and in 1979 was named Massachusetts Women's Intercollegiate Golf
Champion. She also played on the Harvard women's basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, Greis wanted to stay on the golf circuit, and
tourned nationally in pursuit of her LPGA card. She even attended
the LPGA qualifying school three times, but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally hung up my spikes and decided to put my economics
degree to use,'' Greis said.
</P>
<P>
   She currently works for Cambridge Associates, advising nonprofit
institutions in investment issues, and was previously a senior
executive vice president at the Peoples Bancorp of Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   On the volunteer side, Greis has been a director of the YWCA of
Central Massachusetts and is a former director of the Harvard
Alumni Association. And she still supports the Harvard teams by
``writing checks, and showing up to cheer them on.''
</P>
<P>
   At the award ceremony last week in San Francisco, Greis was
honored along with former vice president  &UR; Dan Quayle &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was
captain of the golf team and top player his senior year at DePauw
University.
</P>
<P>
   Each received a Rolex watch, and their alma mater's golf
programs each received a $2,500 donation. Greis noted that both the
men's and women's golf teams at Harvard will benefit from the
award.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Climbing for charity
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 80 women who spent the weekend climbing the White Mountains
to benefit the Elizabeth Stone House are no doubt soaking their
feet now.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Beth Shapiro &LR; , founder of the four-year-old Wilderness Heals
hike, declared it a success, and said that the Stone House in
Jamaica Plain should reach its goal of $130,000. The Stone House
offers services for women ranging from protection from domestic
violence to skill training to get women back in the workforce.
</P>
<P>
   She reported that the ropes given each team for emergency stream
crossings weren't necessary, but rain ponchos were.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you I've never seen lightning from up close before
_ it's amazing,'' Shapiro said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
