<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HARLEM-WRIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARLEM AGENCY`S PRESIDENT STRIKES RIGHT BALANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For a teenage Deborah C. Wright, growing up the
eldest daughter of a black Baptist minister in the South meant a
life full of givens. Chief among them: attending Atlanta's Spelman
College, the proper school for generations of middle-class
African-American women.
</P>
<P>
   But Wright would have none of it; she would go to Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew my dad was upset when he offered me a car if I wouldn't
go north,'' laughed Wright, now 40 and president of the Upper
Manhattan Empowerment Zone, the agency charged with doling out $550
million in public funds to help jump-start Harlem's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Wright has made a specialty of such cautious, finessed
rebellions, ones that shake up those close to her, but that let her
reach from one world into another. It is a talent that could serve
her well as she tries to bridge the gap between high finance and
grinding poverty, between &UR;  &LR; a white elite and a black underclass, to
help lift up Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   When it was time for Wright to pick a career, her family assumed
she would follow her famous aunt, social activist and FOH (Friend
of Hillary) Marion Wright Edelman, and go to law school. But to
their dismay, she discovered that her real passion was business.
(She compromised by earning advanced degrees in both law and
business, both at Harvard.)
</P>
<P>
   When it was time to go to work, she landed one of the hottest
jobs at the hottest firms of the 1980s: corporate finance at First
Boston Inc. But she threw it over for a modest marketing position
with a nonprofit housing agency.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, with her job as politically and racially sensitive
as any in this notoriously sensitive city, she continues to buck
the expected. After finishing work in poor black Harlem, she takes
what for almost anybody else would be a politically suicidal step:
She goes home to predominantly white and trendy Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the pattern, friends and colleagues seemed offended,
insisting it reflects no uncertainty or conflict in Wright. But
Wright herself had a different reaction. ``There's no question,''
she said. ``There's a duality.'' And to all appearances, it has
been there from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Wright is the product of two very different
worlds: a child of rural and static Bennettsville, S.C., who came
of age in the upheaval of the civil right movement; and a daughter
of the town's leading black pastor who is also the niece of one of
America's fiercest liberal advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the friction between those worlds is still apparent
today in what her father and aunt have to say about Wright's early
life and their roles.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Harry S. Wright, who is now minister of the Cornerstone
Baptist Church in Crown Heights, said his daughter was a ``very
determined and impatient'' young person for whom he sought to
provide ``a stable presence'' and ``some sense of sanity.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Edelman, founder and president of the Children's
Defense Fund, one of the nation's most forceful advocacy groups,
described her niece as someone with ``great grit'' who ``challenged
the segregated mores of the town far more than her parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright's challenges have traced the arc of a generation of
African Americans from activism to protest to separation and back.
Her class was the first to attend Bennettsville's formerly
all-white elementary school. When her sixth-grade principal refused
to lower the flag after the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.'s
assassination, she led a walkout. By the time she'd finished
Radcliffe, she had retreated into a black enclave. She remembers
her mother remarking at graduation that she had not introduced any
white friends, and Wright responding, ``I don't have any.''
</P>
<P>
   Her return to the mainstream was too abrupt. Not long after
leaving Harvard, she found herself a $135,000-a-year investment
banker and deeply unhappy. ``She told me she'd spent eight years
preparing for a professional life that she didn't want,'' said
Kathyrn S. Wylde, who was running a nonprofit housing agency at the
time and is now chief executive of the New York City Investment
Fund. ``She was profoundly shaken by that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wright recovered her footing, first in a $35,000-a-year job
with Wlyde's group; then in a series of high-profile positions for
both Democratic Mayor David Dinkins and his Republican successor
Rudolph Giuliani; and now as empowerment zone president.
</P>
<P>
   Even critics say she is maintaining a near-perfect mix of
combativeness and conciliation in her current job, a vital
ingredient for someone with millions of dollars to give away, but a
wild array of political factions to appease.
</P>
<P>
   Wright herself traces the ability to her long search or the
proper balance between the minister and the advocate in her
life.``I feel like I spend 80 percent of my time trying to find the
middle ground on the spectrum from Dad to Marion,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
