<HEADLINE>
GAY PRIDE EVENTS MEAN BIG BUSINESS IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two years ago a young man from London joined the
throngs of eager tourists who flock each year to San Francisco's
annual gay pride parade. Like most, he was electrified by the scene
played out before him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the most enobling moments in my life,'' he
recalled this week. ``You get a sense of the tremendous power of
the queer community in the Bay area.''
</P>
<P>
   He was particularly impressed by the participation of prominent
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from outside the Bay area,'' he said, ``it is quite
awesome to see that level of support.''
</P>
<P>
   The eager Briton _ Teddy Witherington _ is now executive
director of the San Francisco Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and
Transgender Parade taking place Sunday. As the parade's first paid
honcho, he found himself wondering how many others venture into San
Francisco from distant locales to attend the world-famous
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Ask those in the know and the answer is: Lots. Many. Mobs of
'em. Which is to say that those in the know don't know.
</P>
<P>
   They fill the hotels. They ring up pre-Christmas levels of sales
at restaurants and trinket emporiums. But data _ how many come and
how much they spend _ have never been gathered, Witherington
admitted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until now there's been this acceptance that, yes, all these
people come and, yes, it's a great economic engine for the city,
but nobody how many or whether they're coming from Arkansas or
Nevada or Washington State,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, parade organizers will have a visitor's
center at the event this year and _ more importantly _ a team of 30
researchers will comb the crowd ``to give us a start, at least'' in
obtaining data about visitors, Witherington said.
</P>
<P>
   For businesses, the figures will confirm what they already know
_ oodles of out-of-towners spend gobs of money on the day before
the parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it Pink Saturday,'' said Irv Spivak, past president of
the Golden Gate Business Association, a gay business organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, this is like our Christmas and likewise go the
sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Spivak said some businesses report that the Saturday before the
parade is their highest grossing day of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who really benefits from it are the gift shops, the
restaurants, the hotels and the bed and breakfasts,'' said Steven
Perlmutter of The Lavender Pages, a gay business directory. ``A lot
of these people do really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime hotel rooms become scarce during the gay pride weekend,
said John Neal of Travel Trends, a San Francisco travel agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europeans stop in and say `Where are we going to stay?''' he
said. ``There are still rooms in the city, out by Fisherman's
Wharf, out in the suburbs. That's not what they want, but if they
come unprepared, that's what they end up with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
