<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6674 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENTERTAINMENT-BUDGET-     06-25 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-BUDGET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
.
</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
LEONARD-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ Call him Dutch. That's what
novelist/screenwriter Elmore Leonard's friends do. Now call him
successful. That's because Quentin Tarantino, Danny De Vito and the
rest of Hollywood finally have figured out how to capture Leonard's
effortless realism, offbeat characters and ear for offbeat dialogue
on celluloid. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
TRUMAN-FILM (Los Angeles) _ In a clear case of life imitating art,
all eyes were on ``The Truman Show'' at the recent San Diego
International Film Festival, where it dominated the awards for
studio entries. By Bob McCarthy. 
. 
SIGHT-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Out of Sight'' continues the recent
string of successful Elmore Leonard big-screen adaptations that
began with ``Get Shorty'' and leading-man George Clooney finally
delivers the goods. 3{ Stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
DOLITTLE-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ With its computer-generated effects
that bring the animals and their verbal skills to life, ``Dr.
Dolittle'' undoubtedly will will appeal mostly to the ``Babe''
crowd: kids and soft-hearted animal lovers. 2{ Stars. By Glenn
Whipp. 
. 
TANGO-STAGE (Los Angeles) _ Luis Bravo knows there are many other
tango shows out there. Too many? ``To be honest, I didn't see the
other ones,'' replies the ever-diplomatic musician and impresario.
As for judging the relative merits of these fast-spawning tango
tributes, Bravo demurs, ``I leave that for the people.'' By Reed
Johnson. 
. 
SYSTEM-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Bet you've never heard of an Armenian
hard rock band before. But the Valley-based System of a Down _ the
strange name comes from the title of a poem written by the band's
guitarist _ built up such a buzz on the local club scene that major
labels launched a bidding war. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
POP-BEAT (Los Angeles) _ On its first album four years ago, the
funky North Carolina band Dag proved it could lay down deep soul
grooves in an age of synthetic effects. With ``Apartment 635'' due
Tuesday, Dag is still doing things the old-fashioned way. By Fred
Shuster. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Top local club band Ozomatli is a
melting pot all by itself. The 11-member group's politicized fusion
of salsa, jazz, rap and funk is bolstered by a solid rhythm section
that often makes up for a lack of outstanding material on its
self-titled debut from the Almo Sounds label. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
MORI-ART (Los Angeles) _ She could be the star of a '50s sci-fi
serial, or perhaps a high priestess of some exotic,
technology-based religion. In fact, Japanese artist Mariko Mori
sees technology not as art's implacable foe, but as an ally in an
ongoing quest for spiritual equilibrium. By Reed Johnson. 
. 

