<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6683 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLITTLE-REVIEW-LADN     06-25 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLITTLE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DR. DOLITTLE' TICKLES THE FUNNY BONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2{ Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Eddie Murphy does, indeed, talk to the animals in
the newly updated version of ``Dr. Dolittle.'' It would be nice,
though, if this frequently funny film would also occasionally speak
to its audience above the level of, say, an 8-year-old. As it
stands, ``Dr. Dolittle'' will appeal mostly to kids and
soft-hearted animal lovers who will enjoy the film's entertaining
and often sympathetic stable of chattering critters.
</P>
<P>
   With its computer-generated effects that bring the animals and
their verbal skills to life, the movie undoubtedly will remind many
of that porcine classic, ``Babe.'' ``Dr. Dolittle'' certainly can
match that movie laugh for laugh, but director Betty Thomas (``The
Brady Bunch Movie,'' ``Private Parts'') is unable to wring any
poignancy from the pedestrian script. What we're left with is cute
animals and sight gags involving pigeon poop.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's anything wrong with that _ up to a point. This
remake is vastly superior to the 1967 musical, a movie so bad it
almost bankrupted 20th Century Fox. There are no sappy songs here _
just a cute little guinea pig (voiced by Chris Rock) who does a
mean version of Bob Dylan's ``Blowin' in the Wind.'' Murphy's
doctor is much more engaging than Rex Harrison's M.D., although in
fairness to Harrison, he did try to escape the project when he
realized just how bad it was going to be.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Dolittle'' never sinks to that level, mostly because it
never aspires to be anything more than a funny movie for kids.
</P>
<P>
   When we first meet Dolittle, he's a young boy conversing with
the family dog. His father (Ossie Davis) thinks that's a little
odd, particularly after the little Dolittle greets his new school
principal by sniffing his butt. Following that episode, Dad sends
the pooch away and the child comes to believe that he should keep
his unique gift to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward 30 years and Dolittle is a family man with a wife
and two daughters (who would have thought we'd ever buy Eddie
Murphy as a patriarch?) and a thriving medical practice. Then one
day, he starts hearing those voices again. And they're not inside
his head _ the cacophony of conversation is coming from the family
guinea pig, stray dogs he sees on the street and mice in garbage
cans. He can understand every word and, just as significantly, they
can understand him. Dr. Dolittle soon becomes a magnet for every
creature in need.
</P>
<P>
   The film's premise _ a man who dismisses animals as a nuisance
suddenly can't stop hearing what they have to say _ works well and
creates many funny situations. The animals and computer effects
blend to produce some memorable characters, including a
wisecracking stray terrier and a monkey whose beverage of choice is
Jack Daniel's. The vocal talent is uniformly good, too, including
performances by Norm MacDonald, Albert Brooks, Garry Shandling and
the aforementioned Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the movie never goes beyond its premise. Would-be
heartfelt moments involving a sick circus tiger, a stay by Dolittle
in a mental hospital and some father-daughter bonding all fall
rather flat. And although the movie runs for less than 90 minutes,
its novelty begins to flag after about an hour. It's at this point
that a decent script would have come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a time where the nation's favorite television
character is a taco-loving Chihuahua, there's bound to be an
audience who just wants to listen to the animals _ even if they
don't have much of anything original to say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1505EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6685 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYSTEM-MUSIC-LADN     06-25 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYSTEM-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN WITH A HARD-ROCK SYSTEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Armenian rock _ it may just be the Next Big Thing.
</P>
<P>
   System of a Down _ made up of four young Armenians from the
Valley _ built up such a buzz on the club scene that major labels
launched a bidding war.
</P>
<P>
   In the three years the group has been plying its trade, its
eclectic, aggressive sound has won fans in Europe and the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Lead singer Serg Tankian says it's merely a coincidence that
System of a Down's four members are Armenian, but concedes that the
common bond may have something to do with the music's strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe being Armenian has allowed me to see more clearly
injustice in the world,'' said Tankian, 30, of Sherman Oaks,
referring to his country's troubled history. ``We're in touch with
our heritage and culture, and we're proud of it.''
</P>
<P>
   System of a Down's Rick Rubin-produced self-titled debut on
American/Columbia is due Tuesday. The unusual band name stems from
a poem by the quartet's guitarist Daron Malakian.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meaning is open to interpretation,'' Tankian said. ``It
can mean different things for different people.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard-rock genre has never been famous as pop's United
Nations, but System of a Down _ which blends metal, rap, rock and
even Middle Eastern melodies _ isn't the only ethno-metal outfit.
</P>
<P>
   This week's hard-rock chart features East German band Rammstein
and Brazil's Soulfly with ex-Sepultura singer Max Cavalera.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built up interest on the street by playing clubs when
nobody was interested,'' Tankian explained. ``We entered the scene
from nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   System of a Down, which recently opened a short tour for label
mates Slayer, is currently on the road with Ozzfest, the
hard-rocking summer trek featuring Ozzy Osbourne and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Slayer crowd is very intense,'' Tankian said. ``We got a
tremendous response, taking into consideration that Slayer is the
heaviest band you could ever open for. When we started out with
them, we were wondering what would ever become of us. But whenever
I went into the crowd after a show, kids were coming up and saying
how much they liked us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tankian said the game plan for his band involves lots of steady
touring.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the first day, we never did this knowing we'd get played
on the radio,'' the singer said. ``We don't even have a video
concept or a single figured out yet. Building our roots is what's
important right now. We do what we do and if it hits radio, fine.''
</P>
<P>
   System of a Down's diverse sound (which sometimes includes a
cover of Berlin's angsty '80s radio hit ``The Metro'') comes from
the wide-ranging listening tastes of the band members, Tankian
claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're into goth, jazz, hip-hop, pop, alternative, Armenian
music _ all sorts of things,'' said Tankian, who grew up in
Hollywood. ``In other words, whatever is good. Someone told me
there's no magic in finding good music but you know it when it hits
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Tankian, whose group has played often at such Sunset Strip clubs
as the Viper Room, the Whisky and the Roxy, says there's more
camaraderie than competition among bands on the local scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I see it, the idea of competition is more an invention
as far as I'm concerned,'' he said. ``On the street, everyone's
just trying to do their best and be themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
