<SLUG> BC-TRUMAN-FILM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRUMAN SHOW' TAKES TOP PRIZE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ All eyes were on ``The Truman Show'' at the recent
San Diego International Film Festival, where it dominated the
awards for studio entries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truman'' was chosen best major studio film, Peter Weir best
director, Ed Harris best actor; it also took the award for best
screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, writer Andrew Niccol's title character, Truman
Burbank, has grown up with the world watching him on television,
only he doesn't know it.
</P>
<P>
   The only major award ``The Truman Show'' didn't win was best
actress, which went to Gwyneth Paltrow for ``A Perfect Murder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke Signals,'' by director Chris Eyre, was the judges'
choice for best American independent feature. It won other awards
in the independent category: Eyre was chosen best director, Adam
Beach best actor, and Sherman Alexie took the prize for best
screenplay. The film is being distributed by Miramax.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvie Testud was chosen best actress for her performance in
``Beyond Silence,'' also a Miramax release. The French film ``Gadjo
Dilo'' won best foreign film honors.
</P>
<P>
   Audience members voted ``En Garde'' by director Phillipe De
Broca best foreign film and ``The Waiting Game'' by Chris verr Wiel
best American independent feature.
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime achievement awards were presented to actor Martin
Landau, who won a Best Supporting Actor Oscar for ``Ed Wood,'' and
director John Frankenheimer, whose 1962 political thriller, ``The
Manchurian Candidate,'' starring the late Frank Sinatra, was among
the 80 films screened during the festival's 10-day run.
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF TRUMAN: Missouri's own ``Give-'em-Hell'' Harry
Truman wore many hats in his day: president, senator, farmer,
husband, father and, ironically, haberdasher. After leaving the
White House in 1952, &UR;  &LR; he returned to Independence, Mo., where he
lived to be 88.
</P>
<P>
   This American folk hero's long and eventful life is the subject
of a documentary, ``Harry S. Truman, 1884-1972'' showing 7:30 p.m.
Tuesday at Skirball Cultural Center, 2701 N. Sepulveda Blvd., Los
Angeles. Academy Award-winning director Charles Guggenheim will
introduce his film, commissioned by the Harry S. Truman Library
Institute, at its West Coast premiere.
</P>
<P>
   Momentous world events occurred on Truman's watch as president _
the decision to use atomic weapons against Japan, the Korean War,
the recognition of Israel and the Berlin airlift _ and Guggenheim's
film examines the difficulties Truman faced in deciding what action
the United States should take. The presentation is the last in the
``Vantage Point'' symposium under the ``50 Years of Friendship:
America &AMP; Israel'' exhibitions and programs.
</P>
<P>
   Call (310) 440-4500 for program and ticket information.
</P>
<P>
   COMING OUT: The 16th annual gay and lesbian film showcase,
``Outfest '98,'' opens July 9 with a gala and premiere of ``Relax
... It's Just Sex'' at the historic downtown Orpheum Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   The Sundance Film Festival entry ``Relax,'' follows a tight-knit
group of 30-somethings who begin drifting in different directions.
Sundance program director John Cooper praised it as ``emblematic of
a refreshing trend in independent cinema with gays, lesbians and
straights co-existing together, just like real-life Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 250 films and videos will be shown over the July 9-20
schedule, including an outdoor evening of cinema at the John Anson
Ford Amphitheatre. A coming-of-age film, ``Edge of Seventeen'' by
David Moreton and Todd Stephens, will be featured.
</P>
<P>
   Winners in the six juried, six audience and two special
programming categories will receive ``Outies.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign films from 25 countries are included. Sir Ian McKellen
(``Richard III,'' ``Gods and Monsters'') will be presented with a
lifetime achievement award for excellence in gay filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   For program information, call (213) 951-1247. For tickets, call
(213) 782-1135.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
