<SLUG> BC-CHINATOWN-ANIMALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISAGREEMENT MARS ACCORD ON ANIMAL TREATMENT IN CHINATOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Brokers of a compromise agreement on the humane
treatment of live animals in Chinatown markets fear the deal is
falling apart even before it is to take effect.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese merchants and their representatives appear to be
backpedaling from an agreement signed earlier this year to kill and
store animals humanely. Part of the agreement is scheduled to be
implemented July 1.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has been a hot one in San Francisco's Chinatown for
more than two years. It is an ideological and procedural quagmire
that combines science, ethics, culture and, as some Chinese are
fond of pointing out, 5,000 years of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fear is, if this fails, it'll end up being a racial issue
which will divide the city,'' said City Administrator Bill Lee, who
has helped negotiate between merchants and animal groups.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was brokered by the San Francisco Society for
Prevention of Cruelty to Animals and the Chinese Consolidated
Benevolent Association, a group with a 150 year history in
Chinatown that is also known as the Chinese Six Companies.
</P>
<P>
   It is a voluntary set of guidelines. The rules on killing
animals take effect July 1 and rules on storing animals go into
effect Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   After the agreement was signed, the SPCA began to hold weekly
meetings with merchants to discuss implementation, such as humane
ways to kill a turtle.
</P>
<P>
   Separate from the SPCA agreement is a lawsuit filed in April by
a coalition of animal groups, not including the SPCA, asking for an
end to all sales of live animals for food in San Francisco. The
groups sued after the city's Board of Supervisors declined to enter
into the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Closing arguments in the trial were heard in late April and a
Superior Court judge has until late July to issue a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things were moving along pretty well when the attorney
representing the merchants in the litigation basically advised his
clients to not attend the meetings pending the outcome of the
litigation,'' said SPCA President Richard Avanzino.
``Unfortunately, that brought our discussions to a screeching
halt.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Wartelle, the lawyer representing the merchants, denied he
instructed his clients to stop attending the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   However, in a letter dated April 28 to the Chinese Six
Companies, Wartelle clearly stated that he instructed his clients
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Wartelle said his clients already meet the guidelines in the
agreement, including not dismembering or cutting an animal while it
is alive. But several animal rights activists said they have
witnessed live turtles being de-shelled in Chinatown markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately we're still facing some internal politics in the
community,'' said Pius Lee, a real estate broker and community
figure helping with negotiations between merchants and animal
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain groups are encouraging the merchants to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Avanzino said the agreement should be implemented regardless of
the outcome of the litigation, which could drag on with appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reconciliation is superior to litigation or legislation that
creates winners and losers,'' he said. ``We're trying to achieve a
win-win accommodation, as opposed to an outcome where one side
could raise the flag of victory, angering and upsetting the other
side.''
</P>
<P>
   The SPCA and the Chinese Six Companies are preparing to send a
letter to merchants urging them to resume discussions.
</P>
<P>
   The city administrator, Bill Lee, said the voluntary guidelines
would avert escalating the disagreement from a cultural one to a
racial one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people don't come to the table and talk, we're never going
to resolve anything,'' the city administrator said. ``If we can't
resolve an issue of live turtles and frogs, how are we going to
resolve other ethnic and cultural differences in the city?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1507EDT &QL; 
