<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6697 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TANGO-STAGE-LADN     06-25 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANGO-STAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEST FOR THE PERFECT TANGO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Luis Bravo knows there are many other tango shows
out there.
</P>
<P>
   Too many?
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I didn't see the other ones,'' replies the
ever-diplomatic musician and impresario.
</P>
<P>
   As for judging the relative merits of these fast-spawning tango
tributes, Bravo demurs, ``I leave that for the people.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past eight years, the people have been voting with their
feet by the tens of thousands for Bravo's ``Forever Tango.''
</P>
<P>
   After opening at UCLA in 1990, where it played nine weeks,
``Forever Tango'' has toured in Argentina, London and New York. It
returned to Los Angeles in 1994 for an engagement at the Wiltern
Theatre and later spent a phenomenal 92 weeks in San Francisco,
where it was voted Best Touring Musical of 1996 by the Bay Area
Theatre Critics.
</P>
<P>
   Such success would seem to certify ``Forever Tango'' as a
genuine cult article. But then tango's darkly eroticized nature has
always inspired a furtive following.
</P>
<P>
   Bravo, however, insists that despite its clenched couplings and
its origins in Buenos Aires brothels, tango is not primarily about
sex.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, he says, tango speaks to the loneliness of the
sailors and cowboys who landed in Buenos Aires after leaving their
families behind in Europe. Tango's melancholy, nostalgic sound
externalizes the pain of the immigrant's isolation, he says, and
its stylized aggression suggests a subliminal death wish more than
sexual passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You dance it by yourself, with your own history,'' he
observes. ``You dance it with somebody, but you're by yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bravo finds a similar quality of painful yearning in
African-American spirituals, although tango reverberates with
something closer to fatalistic despair than hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to do with the Argentinian psychology. Argentinians are
very unstable people because of our heritage and our history,''
says Bravo, who has made his home in the Los Angeles area since the
early 1980s. ``Our history changes every 30 years with the economy,
in cycles. Argentinian people never know about their future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes us a very fatalstiic people. That's why everything in
Argentina is a Greek tragedy. It comes from the Italians, you know.
We're Latins.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, so much for subtext.
</P>
<P>
   What really sets his show apart from its imitators, Bravo
believes, is its emphasis on music. A cellist himself for many
years, Bravo gave his last concert in 1993 with the National
Symphony of Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   He calls ``Forever Tango'' a very simple show and particularly
loves one critic's description of it as an ``illustrated concert.''
</P>
<P>
   In performance, he wants audiences to experience the passion of
the music _ as well as the passion of the dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a big passion and conviction of what you're
doing. It's an obsession of perfection. And being a musician, it's
your destiny to have that obsession for perfection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1509EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6703 &Cx1f; tad-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV28-C     06-25 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: MANAGING THE POLITICS OF SURPLUS
 &HT;    For release Sunday, June 28
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It took the end of the Cold War for the Senate to
debate and approve the expansion of the NATO security umbrella to
Eastern Europe. It will take until the end of the debate over
federal budget deficits for the Congress to approve Social Security
reform.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is Social Security legislation widely viewed as the
``third rail of American politics _ touch it and you die.'' A broad
consensus has emerged that the program must be fixed in one way or
another _ if only because otherwise, sooner or later, it will go
broke. The game has changed into one of when to act, how to present
it to the people, and, most important, just what should be done.
</P>
<P>
   It looks as if 1999 will be the year of Social Security. That's
because both Republicans and Democrats have decided to drag their
feet until after the mid-term elections. At the same time, key
figures in both parties want the Social Security issue resolved
before the 2000 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, when Social Security was last on the fiscal ropes,
a Republican president, with backing from congressional Democrats,
named a blue-ribbon panel to cut the needed deal. The legislation
raised payroll premiums well beyond current needs, taxed benefits,
covered federal workers and increased retirement ages in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will spend some time this year holding forums
around the country, in hopes of building a public consensus of what
to do, which is lacking. Meantime, his own folks have been meeting
in the White House in hopes of building a private consensus within
the administration of what to do, which is also lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, after these efforts end, Clinton will copy Ronald
Reagan's model and name his own commission, probably in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the Social Security trust fund solvent, the next set of
dealers can basically play any one of four tough hands, or maybe
some combination of them. They can either raise taxes, lower
benefits, inflate the currency or privatize the system.
</P>
<P>
   Most reformers, dubbing themselves conservatives, argue that the
last choice is the best one.
</P>
<P>
   They see the 63-year-old system as a huge pyramid scheme _ one
in which taxes drawn from today's younger workers cover the
benefits paid to today's retirees, while tomorrow's benefits for
today's workers are to be paid by tomorrow's taxes on tomorrow's
workers. Without the infusion of fresh cash from equity markets,
the reformers fear rising life expectancies and declining birth
rates will cause the pyramid to topple.
</P>
<P>
   Many preservationists, ducking the liberal label, claim the
would-be reformers fail to tell the whole story.
</P>
<P>
   They view Social Security as a combination pension plan,
insurance plan and income redistribution plan. They note that,
unlike private investment accounts, the system should continue to
provide a much greater return to poor people than to high earners.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, flush with a current budget surplus that would ease the
pain of reform, claims the middle ground. He says some allowance
could be made for private accounts. But he opposes full
privatization ``because then you couldn't have a universal system
that was fair that had a benefit certain.''
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
