<HEADER>
A6764 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-MEXICO-N     06-25 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-MEXICO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO RALLIES TO TIE THE NETHERLANDS, 2-2, SENDING BOTH TEAMS TO
NEXT ROUND  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-ETIENNE, France _ It is a thrilling but dangerous way to
play, falling behind and frantically playing catch up. Three times
in this World Cup, Mexico has given up the first goal, or the first
two goals, and three times it has scrambled back for a victory or a
tie. Thursday, the Netherlands took a 2-0 lead and played for 60
minutes as if there were only one team on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mexico got a goal out of thin air, and four minutes into
extra time it produced another by Luis Hernandez for a stunning 2-2
draw. The result sent both teams into the second round and
threatened to send goalie Jorge Campos to the hospital with a heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like these kind of situations,'' Campos said with a
laugh. ``It's very difficult, a lot of nerves. But this team has
much courage.''
</P>
<P>
   In extra time, the Netherlands (2-0-1) appeared to have held on
for a 2-1 victory to win its group and set up a second-round match
against Germany or Yugoslavia. But Mexico (1-1-1) finished with
sublime desperation, not knowing the result of a simultaneous match
between Belgium and South Korea, and forged a tie despite playing
with only 10 men.
</P>
<P>
   If Belgium had won and Mexico had lost, the Mexicans would have
joined Jamaica and the United States as failures from the North
American, Central American and Caribbean region. As it turned out,
Belgium drew 1-1 with South Korea, but the Mexican players were
unaware of that outcome, so they fought on with relentless
determination.
</P>
<P>
   They were rewarded in the 94th minute, when substitute forward
Ricardo Pelaez bounced a header toward the charging Hernandez. Jaap
Stam, the Dutch defender, had smothered Hernandez all afternoon,
but this time he whiffed upon trying to clear the pass and
Hernandez punched a left-footed shot for the tying goal.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates mobbed him, and when the game ended, the Mexican
players did airplane dives in delirious exhilaration as their fans
chanted ``Ole, ole, ole'' and tossed sombreros at their heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has a lot of character to come back in the second
half,'' said Hernandez, the diminutive blond forward who wears a
rawhide strap for a sweatband. ``From a young age, we all develop a
winning attitude. It is in our blood.''
</P>
<P>
   In the opener, Mexico gave up a goal before routing South Korea
3-1. Then it gave up two goals to Belgium before earning a
white-knuckled 2-2 tie. Again Thursday, it spotted the Netherlands
a pair of goals by Phillip Cocu in the fourth minute and Ronald
DeBoer in the 18th minute before frenetically pulling even. Mexico,
as the second place finisher in its group, will now play Germany or
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holland is one of the favorites and we demonstrated that
Mexico can compete with these teams,'' Pelaez said. ``We are not
afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelaez and midfielder Jesus Arellano had the effect of jumper
cables, entering in the second half and energizing Mexico's dead
battery. In the 75th minute, Pelaez bounded a header off a corner
kick into the net as teammate Cuahtemoc Blanco shielded Edwin
Vander Der Sar, the Dutch goalie. The goal was the first
surrendered by Holland in this World Cup and halved its lead to
2-1.
</P>
<P>
   In the 89th minute, Ramon Ramirez, the Mexican playmaker, was
ejected for vehemently protesting an offsides ruling that negated
the apparent tying goal by Blanco. Shorthanded, Mexico still scored
again in extra time. For the first time, it qualified for the
second round in a World Cup held outside North America.
</P>
<P>
   Before the World Cup, Mexico appeared to be in full panic. It
fired Bora Milutinovic despite not losting a game in the final
round of qualifying. Then it came to Europe two months ago and
played miserably in exhibition matches, threatening the job of
Milutinovic's replacement, Manuel LaPuente.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them to have faith,'' LaPuente said. ``You can never
lose faith.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
