<HEADLINE>
AMERICA IS GETTING LITTLE EUROPEAN HELP IN JAPAN CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In dealing with the Japanese financial crisis, America
finds itself virtually alone, getting little help from its friends.
</P>
<P>
   It's a familiar situation for U.S. officials. Ever since Asia's
economic storm burst nearly a year ago, they have found themselves
carrying most of the burden in trying to contain the damage
although several other western nations including Germany, France
and Britain are also heavy investors in the region.
</P>
<P>
   German economist Wolfgang Munchau, writing in Britain's
Financial Times, noted that, while European officials expect their
new single currency, the euro, to supplant the dollar as the
dominant world currency, last week's massive monetary intervention
to bolster the staggering Japanese yen would not have occurred
under European aegis because ``nobody would have been in charge.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to America's ability to take the necessary crisis
measures alone and quickly, the Europeans have no capacity for
united action despite their claim to have created a monetary union
with political backup, he said.
</P>
<P>
   So the European authorities, as usual, waited for Washington to
act and were content to serve as cheer leaders for the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, officials of the so-called Group of Seven
industrial nations met in Tokyo to consider how to deal with
Japan's long-running banking woes, which are the key problem in
that country's stumbling economy.
</P>
<P>
   But few observers were fooled by the presence of representatives
of France, Britain, Germany, Italy and Canada as well as the United
States and Japan. The G7 it may have been, but as a French
newspaper pointed out, ``What really mattered was the Group of One,
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort to persuade inward-looking Japanese officials to take
swift steps to meet the crisis that has dealt a sharp blow to the
international value of the yen has really been a U.S. endeavor. As
far as the other western nations are concerned, Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin has performed as chief strategist and field commander
in the battle to prevent Japan's problems from spilling over
globally and possibly setting off a worldwide recession.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union's Executive Commission in Brussels has
undisguised ambitions to be the continent's government.
Nonetheless, its president, Jacques Santer, has been remarkably
silent about Japan and the Asian crisis as a whole. ~``Santer
possesses no mandate to deal with such matters and he knows it,''
according to Laurent Wilms, a Paris banker and specialist on the
EU. ``Individual EU governments would pounce on him if he tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the European Central Bank, created to manage the euro,
now exists under its Dutch president, Wim Duisenberg, it lacks
authority over such questions as intervention in currency markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly everything is still unclear,'' said Frankfurt banker
Reinhold Meltzer. ``Governments still consider currency
intervention to be a national perogative. How cooperation will be
handled between the European Central Bank and the EU finance
ministers remains unsettled.''
</P>
<P>
   The German financial expert said, ``It will take years for these
questions to be worked out. Until they are, the euro is likely to
have a strictly limited impact on the world scene.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the role of riding to the rescue in international
economic crises to the United States and its trusty dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1548EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0233 </DOCNO>
