<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6771 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PILOBOLUS-DANCE-2TAKE     06-25 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOBOLUS-DANCE-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCER ALERT: PILOBOLUS HOLDS AN OPEN AUDITION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Terry Teachout is the music critic of Commentary and a contributing
writer for Time magazine.  
 By TERRY TEACHOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY, MAY 27, 11:30 a.m. Forty barefoot women are lined up
along the dingy walls of City Center's fourth-floor rehearsal hall,
waiting to improvise a 30-second dance that could change their
lives. Some look alert, some nonchalant, a few terrified. All are
here in response to a terse notice posted in a handful of New York
dance studios and published in the trade press: Pilobolus Dance
Theater is holding open auditions, starting today.
</P>
<P>
   Between now and Friday, one of these women will crash through
the blank wall of anonymity and win a place in one of the world's
most popular modern-dance troupes. Not only will audiences across
the country applaud her, but she will also earn a living wage,
perhaps for the first time in her career as a professional dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Most dancegoers know Pilobolus as a company famous for its wit
and sensuality. These qualities will be on display in the three
programs being presented during the group's annual monthlong season
at the Joyce Theater, which opens Tuesday night with the New York
premiere of ``The Hand That Mocked, The Heart That Fed,'' a new
dance featuring an original score by the noted jazz composer Maria
Schneider.
</P>
<P>
   (Two other dances, ``Apoplexy'' and ``Orangotango,'' will
receive their New York premieres during the run.)
</P>
<P>
   But professional dancers also know Pilobolus as one of the few
modern-dance troupes that provides a regular paycheck, a rare
commodity in a profession whose members regard unemployment
benefits as an integral part of their skimpy incomes.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the company's six dancers performed about 130 shows
and were paid 45 weeks out of 52. That's one reason more than 200
people showed up today to compete for the jobs of Tamieca McCloud,
Trebien Pollard and Mark Santillano, who are leaving at the end of
the season to pursue their own projects.
</P>
<P>
   Though the company's four artistic directors are in the enviable
position of being able to take their pick of some of the best
dancers in the business, they know their requirements are unusually
idiosyncratic. Many otherwise talented dancers are baffled by
Pilobolus's elusive style, a homegrown blend of gymnastics, modern
dance and performance art; moreover, the company's dances are
choreographed collaboratively, with the dancers playing a key role
in the creative process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't looking for conventional dancers,'' says Jonathan
Wolken, the executive director and one of the company's founders in
1971. Just as important, he adds, is the need to hire mature men
and women who are capable of getting along during the many weeks
they will spend together on the road. ``It's a tightly knit family,
and the emotional weather is very important,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Wolken, Robby Barnett, Michael Tracy and Alison
Chase have devised a system that allows them to sift more or less
efficiently through the large numbers of dancers their auditions
invariably attract.
</P>
<P>
   In the first stage, the dancers learn a phrase, then perform it
in groups of eight, after which they are allowed to improvise
briefly on their own. ``It's grueling,'' Wolken says, ``but it's
also fun to watch, a kind of human circus.''
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY, 10:45 a.m. Ten women and nine men were called back for
the second day of auditions. Rebecca Anderson, a friendly faced
blonde who is Pilobolus's dance captain, is concentrating on the
women this morning. ``I'm looking for somebody with some spark to
her,'' she says. ``And of course she has to be able to lift me, and
I her. We had to cut some of the bigger women yesterday just for
that reason.'' (Ms. Anderson is 5 feet 4 inches.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anderson and Ms. McCloud demonstrate a phrase from ``Duet,''
an intricate exercise in female partnering. Then the women pair off
and repeat it. ``Watch the way they lift each other, and the way
they're lifted,'' Wolken whispers. ``Who's a sack of potatoes?
Who's a part of a sculpture? Who's doing Rodin? Who's
embarrassed?''
</P>
<P>
   A petite dancer with exotic features is singled out for special
treatment, and as Ms. Anderson helps her polish the phrase, you can
see the other women trying to decide whether their chances for
success have gone up or down.
</P>
<P>
   NOON The directors and dancers huddle briefly and make the next
cut. Then the six men and six women who are left are told how
Pilobolus works. Members are expected to live near the company
studio, in rural Connecticut; there are no understudies, so
everybody must be willing to dance hurt; relationships with
significant others are often strained by the lengthy touring
schedule; some dances involve full or partial nudity. ``You're
going to be lonely, hurt, poor and naked,'' interjects Matt Kent,
Pilobolus's class clown. Everybody laughs; nobody leaves.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY, 10:30 a.M. Ben Pring, one of the remaining male dancers,
is taken to the back of the hall for a whispered conference while
the other men continue to improvise. Michael Tracy and Robby
Barnett offer him a job. ``We think you'd be really good,'' says
Tracy, ``and I think you'd find this a good dance job.'' (He will
accept over the weekend.)
</P>
<P>
   11:45 Josie Coyoc, the elfin dancer who was singled out Thursday
morning, has now emerged as one of the two front-runners among the
women. An elegant performer whose demeanor is quiet and
self-contained, she has spent the last five years with Bill T.
Jones's company but is concerned about its financial stability.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to keep dancing,'' she says, ``but I also want to be
able to pay my bills _ I'm actually going into debt _ so I told
Bill in February that I was going to have to look for something
else. It was hard. But I love what Pilobolus does _ all the
partnering, and the beautiful movements.'' Suddenly she starts to
cry. ``It's like leaving one family, perhaps to go to another.''
</P>
<P>
   12:15 p.m. The other front-runner is Jennifer Binford, a tall,
ebullient woman who makes fetchingly funny faces as she improvises.
``This is the most creative audition I've ever had,'' she says
excitedly. ``I feel like I fit in, like I can be myself. I'm having
a great time!'' Then she sheepishly confesses that she hasn't slept
for two days.
</P>
<P>
   1 p.m. One man and three women are sent home. Each is taken
aside and gently given the bad news. ``Dancers are always telling
us: `You treat us like humans; you actually (italics)talk(end
italics) to us!' '' Tracy says after they leave. ``Which gives us
some idea of how things must work at other companies' auditions.''
He shudders.
</P>
<P>
   3:30 p.m. Another male dancer is sent home. The rest line up
side by side as Wolken barks out a series of unlikely commands:
``Look straight out. Relax your face. Now show us pure, unmitigated
hatred ... falling asleep ... one drink too many ... horrified ...
flabbergasted ... you just walked through poison ivy ...
(italics)dignified!''(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   The dancers dissolve in laughter, then sit down for more talk.
``Do any of you keep a journal?,'' Wolken asks them. ``What do you
read?'' The answers range from ``One Hundred Years of Solitude'' to
``The Seven Habits of Highly Effective People.''
</P>
<P>
   4:20 p.m. The directors and company members excuse themselves
and begin an intense, sometimes testy debate. Otis Cook, an
extroverted improviser with a shaved head, is called over for a few
more questions; the group then decides to offer him the second male
slot, which he accepts at once. Choosing between Ms. Binford and
Ms. Coyoc proves more difficult. ``Rebecca was right when she said
that it's basically going to be an esthetic decision,'' Barnett
says. ``Jennifer and Josie are both excellent dancers, they can do
all the moves, but they're very different in size, appearance and
character. So what do we want the company to look like? Where do we
want to go as a group?''
</P>
<P>
   After 20 minutes of increasingly heated talk, a compromise is
reached: the company will assemble in Connecticut next week to make
a final decision, having had the weekend to think it over.
</P>
<P>
   AFTERWARD The members of Pilobolus reconvened the following
Monday and voted unanimously to ask Ms. Coyoc to join them. ``I
needed a day to let it wash over me,'' she says a few weeks later.
``Then I accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   She speaks wistfully of telling her soon-to-be-former boss that
she will be leaving his company: ``I think Bill understood it was a
choice I had to make, so I could continue to do what I love.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Coyoc, Cook and Pring will report to Connecticut on Aug. 10
for their first rehearsal. ``I think we have a terrific looking new
company,'' Barnett says. ``We have a lot of faith in our audition
process. It's not infallible, but it gives us an unusually good
sense of who we're working with, and we've never had to let anyone
go. On the basis of those three days, I think all of us are
positive and enthusiastic about the year to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1550EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6778 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRISHA-BROWN-OPERA-2T     06-25 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRISHA-BROWN-OPERA-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTER OF MOVEMENT DECIDES TO TELL A STORY WITH AN OPERA  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Roslyn Sulcas is writing a book on the choreographer William
Forsythe.  
 By ROSLYN SULCAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ What makes a master of one art form turn to
another after a lifetime of perfecting and refining her craft? For
the choreographer Trisha Brown, probably the same impulses that
have impelled her to build a career from challenge and change, and
to occasionally infuriate but more often thrill audiences with her
slippery, elusive gestural poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown, at age 61, is an internationally renowned
choreographer, acclaimed for the subtle and complex style of dance
that she has developed with her eponymous company. From
experimental beginnings in the '60s, when she formed part of the
Judson Church group in New York, Ms. Brown has moved toward the
status of an institution: she has performed in famous opera houses,
danced with Mikhail Baryshnikov and Bill T. Jones, received
prestigious awards, and last year celebrated the Trisha Brown
Company's 25th anniversary with a three-program season that drew
from her substantial repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ms. Brown recently put herself in the position of a novice
once again by seeking out and accepting the chance to direct an
opera, a role that had her working for the first time with singers
and musicians as well as her own dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, her production of Claudio Monteverdi's ``Orfeo'' _
regarded as the first important opera in the history of Western
music _ received its premiere to great acclaim at one of Europe's
most distinguished opera houses, La Monnaie in Brussels, as part of
the city's Kusten Festival des Arts.
</P>
<P>
   It later played at the Barbican in London and will next be seen,
starting July 14, in four performances at the Festival
International d'Art Lyrique et de Musique in Aix-en-Provence in
France. Next year it will travel to the Brooklyn Academy of Music. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From her earliest days as a choreographer, Ms. Brown has been
open to a myriad of influences. She has found inspiration in
Manhattan's architecture for early ``equipment'' pieces that set
dancers walking on walls and semaphoring across rooftops. She has
collaborated with artists like Robert Rauschenberg and Donald Judd.
And she has applied John Cage's notions of chance to dance
composition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The classes I took with Robert Dunn when I got to New York
gave me a concept of how one might make art,'' Ms. Brown says.
``And I use that word purposely, as applied to all disciplines. My
training is in dance and choreography, but my connection is to form
and content, as for any artist. Once I understood that, it was just
a matter of time before I could flesh it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown's first working contact with opera came in 1986, when
the filmmaker Lina Wertmuller asked her to choreograph a short
section of ``Carmen.'' The result was a dense movement haiku _ the
entire narrative compressed into a relentless progression across
the stage as the two protagonists moved toward their grim destiny. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Working on `Carmen' was like a vacation,'' she says. ``It was
very enjoyable to have so many elements _ story, history, context _
built in. It's so hard to make what I usually do, strict
abstraction, believable.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown's ``strict abstraction'' involves complex gesture
stripped of narrative context and counterpointed by supple,
beguiling chains of movement that defy the eye to single out
original impulses or rhythmic dynamics. For a long time (until
1981, when she created ``Son of Gone Fishin' '' to a computerized
organ score by Robert Ashley), Ms. Brown eschewed musical
accompaniment, believing that it distracted from the development of
her own style of dancing.
</P>
<P>
   And for another 14 years she used solely contemporary scores,
turning to the canon of classical music for the first time in 1995
with ``M.O.,'' set to J.S. Bach's ``Musical Offering,'' followed in
1996 by ``Twelve-Ton Rose,'' set to Webern.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Brown's sights had in fact been set on opera for some
time, and rather than representing an independent evolution toward
more conventional scores (a view that seemed to fit her growing
status as a pillar of the dance world), the works set to Bach and
Webern were part of the preparation for ``Orfeo.''
</P>
<P>
   `` `Carmen' had opened things up for me,'' Ms. Brown says. ``I
was a little tired of the stigma of abstract art, and I wanted to
reach a wider audience. I began to think about character, the
differences between men and women, and to choreograph
gender-specific roles. I became interested in gesture that is
ostensibly neutral, but nonetheless holds meaning, and the way in
which people read gesture, whether consciously or not. I decided
that I had less life to live than that which I'd already lived, and
thought about what I wanted to do and hadn't done. And it was
opera.''
</P>
<P>
   When Frie Leysen, the founder and director of the Brussels
festival, which had commissioned ``M.O.,'' discovered that it ``was
a dream of Trisha's to do an opera,'' she immediately thought of
the Monteverdi cycle that she had been planning for the 1998
festival. Ms. Leysen talked to Bernard Fouccroulle, the director of
La Monnaie, who had already worked with Ms. Brown on musical issues
concerning ``M.O.''
</P>
<P>
   Fouccroulle didn't hesitate despite the gamble such projects
might seem to represent. ``Opera has enjoyed a renaissance since
the '80s because great theater directors like Peter Sellars and
Robert Wilson gave it new energy,'' he says. ``It seems to me,
though, that dance is in a healthier state today than theater, and
that a choreographer who is perhaps more used to the notion of
abstraction can open up an opera in a new way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown is not the first choreographer to take on opera; Mark
Morris, Martha Clarke, Anne Teresa de Keersmaeker and Pina Bausch,
among others, have all made successful forays into the genre. But
she was determined not to let a lifetime of making dance dictate
the way she would approach her task.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than thinking about ``Orfeo'' in choreographic terms, she
approached the work thematically, aware from the outset that she
wanted to do far more than produce a danced accompaniment to the
singing.
</P>
<P>
   A commission from the American Dance Festival in June 1997
allowed her to develop a physical vocabulary before addressing
other directorial issues (``It made sense to use the opportunity to
work on `Orfeo,' '' Ms. Brown says pragmatically.) But almost from
the moment that Foucroulle confirmed the project in 1995 (three
years, almost to the day, before the opera's premiere on May 14),
Ms. Brown had been reading and analyzing Alessandro Striggio's
libretto with the help of Guillaume Bernardi, a specialist in
Italian Renaissance poetry who also works in theater.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at how Monteverdi had used the text in relation to
the music, where there were spaces for breathing and gesture, how
Trisha's language could fuse with Striggio's,'' Bernardi says. We
literally went through the text word by word, over the course of a
year. She was unbelievably hard-working and precise.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early in 1997, Ms. Brown began to work with her dancers with the
goal of creating a vocabulary of movement that would be used by
everyone on stage. ``At first we made movement that attempted to
depict what was in the text,'' Ms. Brown says. ``Rounded arms for
mondo, or world, for example. Then I `culled' the gestures to
create a vocabulary that was both abstract and representational. I
wanted to convey the sense of a larger, metaphoric meaning. But I
also retained my criteria for good dance composition, which people
usually don't have to bother about when staging an opera!''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown blocked out each act, piece by piece, often finding
``physical solutions'' to various directorial questions, but
leaving certain sections open when she thought it would be more
useful to work directly with the singers at a later stage. These
physical solutions included the creation of a machine to move
identically costumed (in loose cream-colored pajama suits) singers
and dancers on and off the stage without the contrivance of
conventional exits and entrances.
</P>
<P>
   The result is magical: rippling lines of figures that peel
smoothly around one another and create a unified framing device for
the principal characters without separating the dancers and
singers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not dance per se,'' comments Ms. Brown. ``It's a
theatrical solution that is informed by my ability to structure
movement.'' She decided to place her pure-dance sections (the only
moments where the dancers emerge from the choral group) where she
wanted to build toward climactic moments.
</P>
<P>
   Magical aerial dances, which might be seen as an echo of Ms.
Brown's equipment pieces, were made for Diane Madden as an
incarnation of La Musica, Orfeo's entrance, the loss of Eurydice,
the hero's death.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown also decided to add the opera's original ending _
Orfeo torn to pieces by the Bacchantes _ to the later version in
which he is saved by his father, the god Apollo.
</P>
<P>
   In making these choices, Ms. Brown was both supported and guided
by the musical director, Rene Jacobs. ``He is both incredibly open
to imagination, and immensely knowledgeable about tradition,'' she
says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also intricately linked to Ms. Brown's dramatic conception of
the opera is Roland Aeschlimann's striking design and lighting.
They are near-Japanese in their subtle simplicity: a bare stage,
framed by an enormous cutout circle that variously represents the
moon, the sun and the world, glowing with heavenly blues and
oranges and sometimes eclipsed by a wall that moves from right to
left and back again during the course of the work.
</P>
<P>
   Although used to making final decisions about her own work, Ms.
Brown describes this intensely collaborative experience as sheer
heaven, ``if fair argumentation can be called heaven!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During a six-week period in Brussels last fall, collaboration
became more complex as each singer _ chorus as well as principals _
was tutored by a dancer in the movement vocabulary specific to his
or her role. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We were amazed that dancers knew the music and words better
than we did at that stage,'' says Simon Keenlyside, who is Orfeo in
one of the two casts. ``Trying to learn the movement was
horrendously embarrassing at first, but ultimately it's one of the
most interesting things I've ever done. We're certainly not
dancing, but we are doing a form of what Trisha wants, and it's
part of the musical experience. There are times in performance when
I don't know whether I'm singing or moving because conceptually
it's so fused.''
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, as ``Orfeo'' unfolded, it became clear that Ms.
Brown had neither produced a choreographed version of the opera,
amplified by singing, nor echoed the sung narrative in analogous
dances.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, she has used her medium _ movement _ to clarify and
enlarge the musical domain, incorporating musicians, singers and
dancers into the same dramatic universe with rare skill and
finesse.
</P>
<P>
   After the hugely successful premiere in Brussels, Ms. Brown
confessed that she had felt ``completely numb'' while watching the
performance. ``I had to remind myself to breathe,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But breathe she did later when, glowing with pleasure, Ms. Brown
accepted the tributes of the audience. Once again she had succeeded
in her restless refusal to accept familiar solutions; she had
reinvented her own visions and in the process had reimagined a
genre.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1552EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
