<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARLA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     06-25 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARLA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CARLA'S SONG': JOBLESS SCOT IN NICARAGUA DISCOVERS POLITICAL
INSIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes at end)  
 (JT)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine a more unlikely visitor to Central America
in wartime than George (Robert Carlyle), an unemployed Scottish bus
driver who is astounded to find himself in mortal peril jouncing
along a rutted mountain road in Nicaragua with a group of soldiers
dressed in camouflage. It is 1987, when right-wing contras are
waging a guerrilla war against the leftist Sandinista government,
and George has impulsively flown all the way from Glasgow with his
Nicaraguan fiancee Carla (Oyanka Cabezas) on a risky quest that
could turn out to be a wild-goose chase.
</P>
<P>
   George's culture shock and political awakening form the
emotional core of Ken Loach's angry and sorrowful film ``Carla's
Song.'' This intermittently powerful film, directed from a
screenplay by Paul Laverty, is never quite sure of what kind of
movie it wants to be. In its early scenes, which have a
documentary-like realism, it appears to be a microscopic
examination of the life of a discontented city worker whose chafing
at the rules of his job have an unexpectedly shattering effect on
his life. Later, it becomes a somewhat unwieldy allegory in which
the search for a casualty of war assumes Conradian allegorical
overtones.
</P>
<P>
   The bus driver's journey into a strange new life begins when he
takes pity on a mysterious passenger who is being harassed by the
police for not paying her fare. George's resistance, along with
other small acts of rebellion, cause him to be dismissed from his
seemingly secure job. And when he befriends and falls in love with
the passenger he defended, a beautiful Nicaraguan refugee named
Carla who dances in the streets to raise money for the Sandinista
cause, the rigid moorings of his life become untethered.
</P>
<P>
   Carla, whom Ms. Cabezas portrays with a quicksilver intensity
that cuts against acting cliches, turns out to be a lot more
trouble than George had bargained for. Suffering from
post-traumatic stress, she is suicidal. As bits and pieces of her
story emerge, George becomes convinced that the only way she can
conquer her demons is to return to Nicaragua to find a former lover
and fellow Sandinista named Antonio, who was caught and tortured by
the contras and who has since disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, ``Carla's Song'' lurches boldly but unsteadily
into a hybrid of quasi documentary, angry political tract and
turgid fable. Abruptly moving from Glasgow to Nicaragua, the movie
plunges you into the state of dazed bewilderment that George
experiences in his first few days abroad. And in the not terribly
believable figure of Bradley (Scott Glenn), a hard-boiled former
CIA operative who is now a conscience-stricken worker for a human
rights organization, it also gives the movie its blunt political
mouthpiece.
</P>
<P>
   A former enemy turned advocate of the Sandinista cause, and a
witness to unspeakable CIA-sponsored atrocities, Bradley is
bursting with secrets, most of which are withheld until the end of
the film. It turns out he knows where the elusive Antonio is
living. The movie wastes valuable time withholding information to
build up a bogus head of suspense that turns out not to have been
justified once the ugly but unsurprising facts are revealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carla's Song'' is at its most effective in scenes that feel
semi-improvised, in which George breaks through the barriers of
language and culture to establish a warm camaraderie with
Sandinista soldiers and peaceful villagers who are under attack
from the contras. Its portrait of an idealistic peasant-based army
and its supporters standing up to a ruthless enemy is unabashedly
nostalgic for the leftist dream the Sandinistas once represented.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   CARLA'S SONG
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ken Loach; written by Paul Laverty; director of
photography, Barry Ackroyd; music by George Fenton; released by
Shadow Distribution. Running time: 127 minutes. This film is not
rated.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Robert Carlyle (George), Oyanka Cabezas (Carla), Subash
Sing Pall (Victor), Stewart Preston (McGurk), Gary Lewis (Sammy),
Scott Glenn (Bradley) and Margaret McAdam (George's Mother).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
