<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6805 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOYAGE-FILM-REVIEW-NY     06-25 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOYAGE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VOYAGE TO THE BEGINNING OF THE WORLD': FADING IN A WORLD THAT
SEEMED ETERNAL  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ``Voyage to the Beginning of the World'' was shown as part of
last year's New York Film Festival. Here are excerpts from Stephen
Holden's review, which appeared in The New York Times on Oct. 6.
The film opens Friday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Wisdom is bodily decrepitude,'' wrote William Butler Yeats,
who railed as eloquently as anyone about the indignities of
senescence. This bitter observation runs to the heart of ``Voyage
to the Beginning of the World,'' an exquisitely sad and moving
reflection on memory and personal roots by the 88-year-old
Portuguese-French director Manoel de Oliveira.
</P>
<P>
   The movie also is the final film of Marcello Mastroianni, who
completed it shortly before his death and appears to be seriously
ailing on the screen. Pale and gaunt and moving unsteadily with a
cane, the great Italian actor gives one of his finest performances
as a stand-in for the director, a crotchety old realist who has no
use for the soothing blandishments of his younger traveling
companions while they tour Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voyage to the Beginning of the World'' is really two vignettes
stuck together. In the first part of the film, Mastroianni
(portraying a director named Manoel) and three colleagues, one of
them a 40-ish actor named Afonso (Jean-Yves Gautier), travel around
rural Portugal. Along the way, Afonso, a successful French
television actor born in Portugal, decides to pay an unannounced
visit to an aunt he has never met in an obscure country village.
</P>
<P>
   As the camera lingers on a vandalized roadside sculpture of a
mustached man toting a log, the battered artwork becomes a symbol
of the aged director himself carrying on in a world that barely
seems to notice. A visit to an abandoned, crumbling, once grand
hotel powerfully evokes the impermanence of a physical world that
seemed almost eternal.
</P>
<P>
   Manoel's childhood memories are only a prelude to Afonso's
heart-rending meeting with his ancient aunt, Maria Afonso (Isabel
de Castro), a cadaverous, hard-bitten crone dressed in black who
initially refuses to accept him as a relative because he doesn't
speak Portuguese. The spare, hand-to-mouth way of life the old
woman shares with her aged husband is clearly on the verge of
extinction. And as she reminisces about wars in other places that
have drawn away the young men of the village, where livestock is
still herded through the winding stone streets, the place feels
like a spiritual oasis.
</P>
<P>
   The film's rhythm is the measured contemplative pace of a mature
filmmaker moving slowly and taking deliberate care to observe the
world as clearly and fully as his senses allow. As the car glides
through the countryside, the camera is always pointed back, and the
pictures of the world literally receding have a piercing poignancy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1556EDT &QL; 
