<HEADER>
A6813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN26-COX     06-25 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: This Fourth of July, think of the
Soviet Union
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Best Fourth of July I remember is the only Fourth of July I
remember crying.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1990. I was in Moscow. This was back when it was still
the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   I'd been there two weeks, staying with Russian friends in their
cramped little apartment _ this in a complex of buildings dating
back to the 1950s and known as Khrushchev's teeth, yellow and
crooked as they were.
</P>
<P>
   My friends were breaking the law simply by having me as a guest.
Russians were forbidden even from being seen on the street talking
with Westerners. Such were the bad old days of communism.
</P>
<P>
   I'd brought a suitcase full of American cigarettes, the coin of
the Soviet realm. That, too, was illegal _ something on the order
of contraband.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anybody ever actually smoked them. They were too
valuable. Russians swapped packs of cigarettes for luxuries
available only through the black market. Food, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   But you couldn't buy a beer in Moscow for any price, except at a
small foreign-owned grocery that catered to diplomats and their
families.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about exclusive. You had to show an American Express card
to get in the door. No kidding.
</P>
<P>
   What I missed most were Cokes over ice. Coca-Colas I could buy
at the diplomat mart. You couldn't find ice anywhere. This in the
country that boasts of Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   But each Fourth of July the U.S. Embassy hosted a celebration at
its country estate, what's called a dacha (rhymes with gotcha.)
Anybody American _ even journalists _ were welcome.
</P>
<P>
   There was baseball, hamburgers, hot dogs, cold beer and, thank
heaven, even Cokes on ice!
</P>
<P>
   Kids were running barefoot. Guys were tossing frisbees. I
remember a pretty lady sitting beneath the shade of a tree, reading
a Danielle Steel novel.
</P>
<P>
   It was like a miracle. It was like America.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Marine color guard marched in, the brass band struck up
``The Star-Spangled Banner'' and everybody stood in reverence as
Old Glory of the United States fluttered in a summer breeze from
atop the flagpole.
</P>
<P>
   There I was, half a world away from home, hand over my heart,
the words of the National Anthem on my lips, and tears rolling down
my cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   Communism has since disappeared from what was the Soviet Union.
For that matter, so has the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The New Russians _ Yuri the Yuppie, if you will _ drive Jeep
Grand Cherokees, pronounced sure-ROCK-yees.
</P>
<P>
   Billboards advertise Wonder Bras.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy a Coca-Cola on most any corner, or coke if that's
what you're into.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   So are food stores, with giant neon signs that say ``Food
Stores'' in good ol' American English.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the KGB. Think KFC.
</P>
<P>
   In a way I guess it's a miracle. But it's not America.
</P>
<P>
   There's more to freedom than fast food, fancy cars and franchise
operations. It's a matter of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure Russia will ever get it right. But being there all
those years ago taught me a lesson in patriotism I'll never forget.
</P>
<P>
   This Fourth of July, be thankful you're an American.
</P>
<P>
   Salute the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Sing the National Anthem.
</P>
<P>
   Shoot off a firecracker.
</P>
<P>
   Shed a tear.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News,
</P>
<P>
   is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
</P>
<P>
   AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1600EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6816 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOOLITTLE-FILM-REVIEW     06-25 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOOLITTLE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DR. DOLITTLE': ANIMALS WITH ATTITUDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end)  
 (JT)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When last seen talking to the animals, Dr. Dolittle sounded like
Professor Henry Higgins (Rex Harrison starred in the 1967 musical),
and his unorthodox friends were a treacly crew. That could have
been the beginning and end of the doctor's film career, but the
idea of a nouveau ``Dolittle'' has unexpected appeal. Chalk that up
to Eddie Murphy's ability to play the straight man with hilarious
aplomb, and to the director Betty Thomas' ability to turn kitsch
(``The Brady Bunch Movie'') or worse (``Private Parts'') into
mischievous fun. Her breezy, undemanding ``Dr. Dolittle'' is the
sunniest family film so far this season.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone charting the course of American entertainment over the
last 30 years can predict one thing point-blank: The animals have
gotten ruder. (``Watch your head, I'm flyin' here!'' exclaims one
winged creature.) But they're also funnier, thanks to a stellar
array of vocal talent that gives acerbic flair to the animal
wisecracks. In any case, this ``Dr. Dolittle'' is a children's
storybook compared with Murphy's version of ``The Nutty
Professor.'' Jon Farhat, the visual-effects supervisor who gave
Murphy a believable case of multiple personality disorder for that
film, does an artful, unobtrusive job of integrating
computer-generated animal acting with real creatures here.
</P>
<P>
   In an adaptation that owes little to either the musical
``Dolittle'' or to the well-loved stories by Hugh Lofting, Murphy
plays a mild-mannered San Francisco doctor. He treats only people,
since his father insisted he quit talking to pets many years
before. (Ellen DeGeneres is the voice of the pooch who encouraged
little Dolittle to sniff his grade-school principal.) But as the
film quickly demonstrates, human patients can be a lot less cute
than wildlife. And people doctors may have to contend with
occupational hazards like greedy partners (Oliver Platt, with all
due smarminess) and HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   A life-altering event occurs when the film's main character,
while driving at night, accidentally injures a dog. (See
Kieslowski's ``Red'' for the more sophisticated version of this
premise.) This time, the dog (Norm McDonald) says ``Bonehead!,''
and the amazed Dolittle understands him. Next thing he knows,
Dolittle is driving his daughter's guinea pig on a car trip and the
guinea pig begins sounding like Chris Rock. When the doctor reaches
his destination, he finds a raccoon (Paul Reubens) rooting through
trash and asking, ``Can I get tuna in oil instead of water?''
</P>
<P>
   Like ``The Nutty Professor,'' this film becomes a Jekyll-Hyde
comedy. But this time, it's the creatures who are the wild things
and Murphy who remains the soul of politesse and reason. Or tries
to: the laughs here come from watching Dolittle try to keep up
appearances, as when he hides from his family the presence of
ducks, sheep, a goat and even penguins in their apartment. Even Ace
Ventura would envy the menagerie assembled for this scene.
</P>
<P>
   That Murphy remains the funniest figure in the movie is all the
more amazing since the screenplay (by Nat Mauldin and Larry Levin)
drags him into some inspirational moments (``No matter what
happens, you be who you are, and you love who you are!''), and
since the critters get the best lines. Overheard at the dog pound:
``Dead dog walking'' and ``I am Keyser Soze!'' And this exchange,
between two rat cronies (Reni Santoni and John Leguizamo) when one
gets sick: ``If he dies, I don't know what I'll do!'' ``You'll take
me outside and eat me.'' ``Only out of respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert Brooks plays the troubled tiger who prompts McDonald's
dog to bark, ``Will you stop looking at me like I'm a side dish?''
Replies the tiger wearily, ``Don't flatter yourself, pal.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's human cast includes Ossie Davis, in the brief but
imposing role of Dolittle's father, and Kristen Wilson as his
pretty, exasperated wife. But it's the animal acting that's out of
the ordinary. The pet performers have body and beak language to
suit their dialogue and are smoothly integrated with the people
around them. The creatures look real even when computer-generated.
Murphy has said he faced the acting challenge of delivering much of
his performance to a tennis ball or a moving piece of string. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   DR. DOLITTLE
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Dr. Dolittle'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It includes mild, jokey profanity and occasional
scatological exams, like a doggie rectal exam. Since the dog can
talk, he asks about the veterinarian, ``Why would a guy go into a
line of work like that?''
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Betty Thomas; written by Nat Mauldin and Larry
Levin, based on the ``Doctor Dolittle'' stories by Hugh Lofting;
director of photography, Russell Boyd; edited by Peter Teschner;
music by Richard Gibbs; production designer, William Elliott;
visual effects by Jon Farhat; produced by John Davis, Joseph M.
Singer and David T. Friendly; released by 20th Century Fox. Running
time: 85 minutes. This film is rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Eddie Murphy (Dr. John Dolittle), Ossie Davis (Archer
Dolittle), Oliver Platt (Dr. Mark Weller), Kristen Wilson (Lisa);
AND WITH THE VOICES OF: Norm Macdonald (Lucky), Albert Brooks
(Tiger), Chris Rock (Rodney), Reni Santoni (Rat No. 1), John
Leguizamo (Rat No. 2), Ellen DeGeneres (Prologue Dog) and Paul
Reubens (Racoon).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
