<HEADER>
A6832 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-CONCERT-MUSI     06-25 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-CONCERT-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YES, VIRGIL, THERE WERE COMPOSERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Joseph Horowitz teaches at the New England Conservatory, where he
will direct a weeklong festival exploring the music of Chadwick and
other turn-of-the-century Americans next March.  
 By JOSEPH HOROWITZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A venerable article of faith holds that American concert music
``came of age'' after World War I. Previous American composers, we
are told, were second-rate clones of German teachers. Virgil
Thomson called the music of George Chadwick, Edward MacDowell, John
Knowles Paine, Amy Beach and other prominent turn-of-the-century
Americans ``a pale copy'' of ``Continental models'' and reckoned
their scale of achievement ``a sort of adolescence.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Bernstein termed this ``the kindergarten period of
American music,'' whose ``fine, academic imitations'' of European
masters were actually intended to sound like Brahms and Liszt:
``the more they did, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Only with the waning of modernism does this article of faith
begin to seem a bill of goods: the wholesale rejection of an
American past richly indebted to Germanic culture, science and
scholarship. The act of repudiation was both political and
esthetic.
</P>
<P>
   Its origins included acute Germanophobia occasioned by the Great
War, during which ``Kultur'' became a dirty word, Wagner and
Strauss were banned by certain orchestras and opera companies, and
Karl Muck, the distinguished conductor of the Boston Symphony, was
interned in Georgia as an enemy alien.
</P>
<P>
   In music, the new postwar culture-bearers were modernist
Francophiles, like Thomson and Aaron Copland, who vastly preferred
Stravinsky to Wagner or Brahms. America's Germanic genteel
tradition, with its emphasis on spiritual uplift, seemed musty and
vague, anything but ``American.'' In no European nation was the
continuity of musical culture fractured by a schism of such
magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein, whose various scenarios of American musical
accomplishment typically denied the existence of an American school
before the advent of jazz in the 1920s, was never able to account
for the genius of Charles Ives, who, no less than his genteel Yale
mentors, espoused Beethoven and Brahms, ennoblement and uplift. If
Ives' First Symphony, completed in 1898, is a maverick excursion,
it is an excursion within genteel terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was Ives the first genteel composer whose music sounded
``American.'' A steady stream of recordings of the music of George
Whitefield Chadwick should suffice to convince any sympathetic
listener that his was a voice both genteel and _ pace Thomson and
Bernstein _ unmistakably American.
</P>
<P>
   It was Chadwick's own opinion that he found his voice with an
Allegretto scherzando that became the second movement of his Second
Symphony. At its premiere, in 1884, this six-minute scherzo proved
the first music to be encored by the Boston Symphony, and Julius
Hegyi's recording with the Albany Symphony on New World shows why.
</P>
<P>
   A model of ingenious construction and melodic invention, it even
makes the orchestra giggle and guffaw. The breeziness of its humor
is a Chadwick trademark.
</P>
<P>
   So is the pentatonic flavor of the main tune, steeped in
Anglo-American folk song. The methodology of this music may be
Germanic, but its composer is American.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a new observation. Henry T. Parker, the dean of
Boston's music critics in Chadwick's day, once wrote: ``Chadwick
does not write American music because he was born in Lowell, or
because he lives and works in Boston, or because he now and then
recalls an American folk tune. He writes it because it is often ...
intrinsically American in mood, spirit and appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1854, Chadwick studied at the Leipzig Conservatory,
where he was considered a greater talent than his German
classmates. From 1897 until his death in 1931, he directed the New
England Conservatory in Boston. His music was frequently performed
by the Boston Symphony under such conductors as Arthur Nikisch and
Muck.
</P>
<P>
   This was a great American epoch for symphonic culture:
Chadwick's colleagues included Antonin Dvorak, who, as director of
the National Conservatory in New York, awarded him a prize for his
Third Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Chadwick's lifetime, his most popular work was the concert
overture ``Melpomene'' (1887). The Boston Symphony played it 14
times between 1887 and 1902 (and twice thereafter, in 1921 and
1942). Anton Seidl, Gustav Mahler, Josef Stransky and Henry Hadley
conducted it 11 times with the New York Philharmonic between 1896
and 1921. Theodore Thomas and Frederick Stock performed it a dozen
times with the Chicago Symphony. It was also heard in Copenhagen
and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the muse of tragedy, ``Melpomene'' is entertainingly
earnest. But here Chadwick lives up _ or down _ to his reputation:
the opening English-horn solo is almost comically derivative from
the Prelude to ``Tristan und Isolde.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jubilee'' (1895), from the ``Symphonic Sketches,'' more
embodies Chadwick's metier. Its Yankee exuberance and heartwarming
nostalgia evoke something like Mark Twain's America. When this
music isn't busy shouting, it sings lovingly of hearth and home.
The big tune begs for an Oscar Hammerstein lyric. With three
recorded versions currently available, ``Jubilee'' is today
Chadwick's best-known composition, but less familiar than it should
be.
</P>
<P>
   A prime example of ``serious'' Chadwick, eclipsing
``Melpomene,'' is the 35-minute Third Symphony (1894), the one
honored by Dvorak. After the first performance, by the Boston
Symphony under Chadwick's baton, the composer confided in a memoir:
``The orchestra and all the musicians agreed that this was my best
work so far. Of course, it does show the influence of Brahms in
places. ...'' When Chadwick led the symphony in Leipzig in 1905, a
local critic wrote, ``I hold George W. Chadwick to be the most
important living Anglo-American composer _ Edward Elgar not
excepted.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Chadwick Third evokes Brahms, it is a more blithe and
sprightly Brahms than the one we know. The symphony's virtues
include a ravishing slow movement with such magical constructive
touches as Chadwick's way of easing into the recapitulation, with
its big cello tune, through a halo of violins.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the finale's stentorian horn theme and contrapuntal
bustle, this isn't ``victory'' music, a la Beethoven or Brahms; it
is merely happy. (A Polish musician friend for whom I played Neeme
Jarvi's recording thought this movement's ranginess and optimism
suggested ``the great American West.'')
</P>
<P>
   Chadwick's catalog is also rich in vocal and chamber music. Of
his five string quartets (recorded by the Portland Quartet on
Northeastern), the Fourth (1896) was the most popular in his
lifetime. It is a hearty work, echoing with New England hymns and
fiddle tunes yet distinguished by a finale incorporating elements
of passacaglia and fugue. The Chadwick scholar Steven Ledbetter
speculates that Dvorak's ``American'' Quartet, introduced by the
Kneisel Quartet in Boston in 1894, was a likely source of
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, according to Ledbetter, the two composers influenced
each other during Dvorak's years in America. ``Both were masters of
warmhearted melody and gifted orchestrators; both created themes
that sound like, but are not, folk song.'' And both experienced the
American heartland: Dvorak traveled west to Iowa, where the
``American'' Quartet was born; Chadwick taught in Michigan and
traveled west, to Nebraska and Minnesota, while working on his
Fifth Quartet.
</P>
<P>
   Rediscovering Chadwick can refine our understanding of our
musical past. If so, we will have to overcome stubborn prejudices
about American music in relation to its European parents, and about
19th-century American music in relation to its rebellious
20th-century progeny.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complex thing being an American,'' Henry James once
observed, ``and one of the responsibilities it entails is fighting
against a superstitious valuation of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, a composition student at a leading American
conservatory was invited to sample the Chadwick Third. Asked what
he made of it, the student thought for a time, then volunteered,
``It's better than I thought it would be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1608EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
