<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6864 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV02-     06-25 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN AND NEW HOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday July 2)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My 7-year-old stood by the creek behind the house, spellbound by
the shadows of minnows darting through the shallow water.
</P>
<P>
   I looked up the back yard toward the tan, two-story brick with
dormer windows. The family who lives there now is moving out, and
we will be moving in within the month.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I took our eldest up for the house closing,
having read that it would ease his anxieties to get a preview of
our new town, choose his room, meet the principal of his new
school.
</P>
<P>
   The first day we drove by the house, Adam wouldn't even look out
the car window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-huh, I see it,'' he said, crouched down in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   But the next day, the day we are to sit in a lawyer's office and
sign form after duplicate form, he quietly tours the house, climbs
the basement stairs, gazes out the windows of the upstairs
bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may choose this room or that one,'' his dad and I say.
</P>
<P>
   We cheerfully point out the downstairs fireplace, the rec room,
the tree-filled yard, the nearby playground and community pool.
</P>
<P>
   We've picked the neighborhood _ a quiet, 25-year-old suburb
northwest of Atlanta _ largely for the school district and the
affordable homes.
</P>
<P>
   The elementary school, Knight Elementary, meets expectations.
It's warm and homey, with shining suits of armor standing at regal
attention in the lobby and live plants on every table in the
lunchroom.
</P>
<P>
   A goldfish named ``Piggy,'' the mascot of the library, splashes
Adam when he looks into her bowl.
</P>
<P>
   When we return to the house, it is rightfully and legally ours.
I begin to have my own anxieties.
</P>
<P>
   Who's going to mow the lawn, water the grass, collect the mail
while we're 500 miles away wrapping up our other lives? Why didn't
I notice this atrocious pineapple wallpaper in the kitchen before?
What can we do to the kitchen deck to make sure our 2-year-old
doesn't tumble off it?
</P>
<P>
   I try to memorize the house number, to mentally retrace the way
to the elementary school, to choose a color to repaint the upstairs
bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   I try, also, to envision our life replanted here.
</P>
<P>
   How this residential street and mail box and school newsletter
and bus schedule will soon become our daily reality.
</P>
<P>
   Then I walk back down the back yard _ our back yard _ to where
Adam has wandered back to the creek. He's throwing stones in the
water, disrupting the minnows, stirring up the silt.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, we've arranged to meet with friends who live
here and who, best of all, have an 8-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   He and Adam will have a great time splashing in the motel pool,
playing chicken on their dads' shoulders, watching the Bulls play
the Jazz for the championship.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, we sit and watch the muddy water, waiting for it to
settle.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what do you think of the house?'' I ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice,'' he says, shrugging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want to go back in one more time before we leave?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope,'' Adam says, throwing another rock.
</P>
<P>
   He's probably right. There will be plenty of time for that
later.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a feature writer for The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
