<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6879 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUBBLE-PEOPLE-INTERNE     06-25 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUBBLE-PEOPLE-INTERNET-TRUMAN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE ARE THE `BUBBLE GENERATION' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Central time zone, call CONNIE WHITE at
1-800-444-0267. Or fax her at (816) 822-1444.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Pacific or Mountain time zones or in Latin
America, call OLIVIA VASQUEZ at (310) 996-0075. Or fax her at (310)
996-0089.
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Even if you haven't seen ``The Truman Show'' _ and you should,
it's an oddly beautiful and intricately multi-layered fantasy _ you
probably know the trick of the movie is that Jim Carrey's whole
life is an orchestrated TV show taking place inside a gigantic
studio masquerading as a Florida seacoast town, with Carrey the
only one in the world who's not in on the secret.
</P>
<P>
   It's Voyeur TV.
</P>
<P>
   The main character's name is Truman Burbank. He's a true man,
get it? As for the surname, ``beautiful downtown Burbank,'' as
Johnny Carson used to call it, is home to countless TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   Logic tells us nothing like ``The Truman Show'' could happen in
the real world _ that Truman Burbank would never make it to age 30
without figuring out he's living inside television. And the second
he realized it was all a charade, he'd demand to be released from
the studio-prison.
</P>
<P>
   Or would he? One of the alternate endings considered for ``The
Truman Show'' had the hero opting to remain inside the blissful
biosphere, where the days were sunny and bright and the people were
kind and considerate, and his own disposition was so optimistic and
worry-free he greeted the neighbors each day with: ``Good morning!
And if I don't see you, good afternoon, good evening and good
night!''
</P>
<P>
   Why give up a comforting bubble for the frightening unknown?
</P>
<P>
   As it is, there's a growing subculture of people who are living
in a kind of ``Truman Show'' of their own making _ the key
difference being that these human beings are volunteering to live
in a video fishbowl.
</P>
<P>
   On June 16, a woman Elizabeth gave birth while her husband, her
three children, a cameraman, a producer, a play-by-play announcer
and an online audience looked on. The event was billed as the
world's first Internet delivery, and viewers caused an online
traffic jam in their rush to have a virtual front-row seat in the
delivery room.
</P>
<P>
   Most amusing to me was that Elizabeth, 40, didn't want the media
to use her last name. Privacy concerns, don't you know.
</P>
<P>
   That's also the practice on ``The Real World,'' the long-running
``documentary'' on MTV in which seven young people, selected from
thousands of auditioning hopefuls, live together for three months
while film crews record their every waking moments _ outside of the
bathroom and bedroom, that is.
</P>
<P>
   This year's edition was filmed in Seattle. They've already done
New York, L.A., San Francisco, London, Miami and Boston. Sooner or
later they're going to come to Chicago, whether we want them to or
not.
</P>
<P>
   They never use last names on ``The Real World,'' either. They
have, however, shown a young woman named Tami as she went through
an abortion and also had her jaws wired shut in a sad effort to
lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   These women are saying: Film me as I deliver a child, record me
as I battle an eating disorder and go through an abortion _ but no
last names, please!
</P>
<P>
   Interesting where some people draw the line.
</P>
<P>
   Starring in their own personal ``Truman Show'' adventures _
though once again it's the subjects, and not some unseen
megalomaniacal artiste, who are initiating the filming process _
are the hundreds of ``personal cam'' and ``live cam'' websites
popping up all over the Internet. All you have to do is click on
these sites and you can watch real-time photos or in some cases
videos of people living their lives in stultifying detail.
</P>
<P>
   There's a guy in New England who has a camera looking out his
window at his backyard, all time.
</P>
<P>
   Another man in Las Vegas keeps a camera focused on himself as he
works all day. He types, he drinks coffee, he taps away at his
computer, he answers the phone.
</P>
<P>
   A young woman in downstate Illinois keeps a camera in her
bedroom _ but don't get any ideas, the footage is strictly G-rated.
</P>
<P>
   Several college students have set up dorm cams. Watch 'em drink!
See 'em study! Wait for Friday night and see if the boyfriend gets
to stay over!
</P>
<P>
   The most famous personal cam website is operated by a
21-year-old woman named Jennifer (http://www.jennicam.org), who has
been featured in numerous magazine and newspaper articles,
discussing the ``jennicam'' way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Each day hundreds of visitors to the website can view
continually-updated images of Jennifer combing her hair, Jennifer
talking on the phone, Jennifer kissing her boyfriend, Jennifer
eating dinner, Jennifer taking a nap, and yes, Jennifer taking off
her clothes in a very non-sexual kind of way.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not about Peeping Tomism, it's much deeper and weirder
than even that. Jennifer is a New Age exhibitionist who delights in
sharing her world, all of it, with thousands of strangers. She is
the spiritual godchild of Andy Warhol; she likes to be watched, all
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the wannabe-stars on ``The Real World,'' Jennifer seems
completely oblivious of the camera _ yet we know that's not true.
The camera is the center of her being. As a child of the multimedia
age, Jennifer seems to believe her very ordinary life will somehow
take on greater importance and weight if it's broadcast on the
Internet, and as long as people keep visiting her website, how can
we tell her she's sadly mistaken?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) can be heard on the
``Media Creatures'' show, which airs daily in Chicago from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. on WMVP-AM (1000) and appears Tuesday and Thursday at
7:55 a.m. on WFLD-TV's ``Fox Thing in the Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A daily columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, Roeper has also
written for TV Guide, Spy, Playboy, Chicago magazine and many other
publications, and has appeared as a guest on ``Nightline'' and
``Oprah.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1629EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
