<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6901 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-COURT-ART0624     06-25 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-COURT-ART0624 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    COURT UPHOLDS RESTRICTIONS ON ARTS FUNDING
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Creating fears for free speech advocates, the
Supreme Court ruled 8-1 on Thursday that the government can deny
federal funding to artists whose works are deemed indecent.
</P>
<P>
   The decision will have a ``chilling effect'' on controversial
artists who would otherwise seek grants from the National Endowment
for the Arts for projects outside the mainstream, predicted Majorie
Heins, an attorney for the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   But the ruling was hailed by critics of the federal arts agency
who have objected to taxpayer funding of works such as Andres
Serrano's depiction of a crucifix immersed in urine and the late
Robert Mapplethorpe's homoerotic photographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government is in the arts business, it has every right
to call the tune,'' said Robert Knight, cultural director of the
Family Research Council, a conservative advocacy group. ``No
individual has a right to be granted tax dollars with no strings
attached.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the court, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor said the
First Amendment guarantee of free speech does not preclude Congress
from requiring the NEA to consider general standards of decency, as
well as artistic excellence, in allocating its funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any content-based considerations that may be taken into
account in the grant-making process are a consequence of the nature
of arts funding,'' O'Connor wrote. ``The NEA has limited resources
and it must deny the majority of the grant applications that it
receives....
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the First Amendment certainly has application in the
subsidy context, we note that the government may allocate
competitive funding according to criteria that would be
impermissible were direct regulation of speech or a criminal
penalty at stake. So long as legislation does not infringe on other
constitutionally protected rights, Congress has wide latitude to
set spending priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Compromising as conservatives sought to abolish the NEA,
Congress established the decency rule in 1990. The law directs the
NEA to take ``into consideration general standards of decency and
respect for the diverse beliefs and values of the American public''
in making its grants.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was quickly challenged by several performance
artists, including Karen Finley, known for expressing feminist
outrage by smearing her nude body with chocolate. Lower courts
struck down the statute, declaring it unconstitutionally vague and
a violation of artists ' rights of free expression.
</P>
<P>
   Overturning that decision, the Supreme Court concluded that the
law ``is facially valid, as it neither inherently interferes with
First Amendment rights nor violates constitutional vagueness
principles.''
</P>
<P>
   While conceding disappointment in the ruling, civil libertarians
were not devastated by the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been worse,'' said Heins, the ACLU attorney.
``Basically, they upheld the law by saying it is meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   That was also the reading of David Cole, a Georgetown law
professor who represented Finley and the other artists who took the
case to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority opinion accepted our theory that the First
Amendment applies when the government distributes money to the
arts,'' said Cole. ``They just interpreted this statute as not
being in violation'' because it instructs the NEA to consider the
decency standards but does not issue edicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the court went wrong is failing to recognize the
real-world effect'' of the statute -- which has been to stop
funding of controversial projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cole said his reading was bolstered by a concurring opinion
written by Justice Antonin Scalia and endorsed by Justice Clarence
Thomas. They said the majority had upheld the law ``by gutting it''
in their interpretation. O'Connor was joined in full by Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices John Paul Stevens,
Anthony M. Kennedy and Stephen G. Breyer, and in part by Justice
Ruth Bader Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David H. Souter dissented, saying the law should be
struck down because it was ``overbroad and carries with it a
significant power to chill artistic production and display.''
</P>
<P>
   But the court rejected the notion that the statute was too broad
or vague.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the context of selective subsidies, it is not always
feasible for Congress to legislate with clarity,'' wrote O'Connor.
``Indeed, if this statute is unconstitutionally vague, then so too
are all government programs awarding scholarships and grants on the
basis of subjective criteria such as 'excellence.'''
</P>
<P>
   Imposing the decency standards did not end the jeopardy for the
NEA, which was established in 1965 and has been opposed from the
start by some critics who believe taxes should not support the arts
at all. The agency's budget has been reduced in recent years. The
full House is expected to vote soon on the issue. Last year, the
House voted to abolish the agency but the Senate saved it during
conference negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
