<HEADER>
A6914 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIANANMEN-SQUARE-HNS &LR;      06-25 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIANANMEN-SQUARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIANANMEN SQUARE MARKS A HISTORY OF VIVID CONTRASTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: The reception for the president is scheduled at 9 p.m. EDT
Friday, 9 a.m. Saturday in Beijing.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ORVILLE SCHELL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ What makes President Clinton's scheduled reception in
Tiananmen Square in front of the Great Hall of the People so
sensitive is the historical resonance of this place in the minds of
the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tiananmen Square _ the largest public square in the
world _ was constructed by Mao Zedong after ``liberation'' in 1949
to celebrate the triumph of a secular revolution, for most Chinese
it also has an almost mystical dimension as the place where the
soul of China resides.
</P>
<P>
   Because Tiananmen, the Gate of Heavenly Peace, was the portal
into ``the great within'' of the Forbidden City where emperors held
court during imperial times, it became the most symbolic point of
connection between ordinary Chinese and the Son of Heaven.
</P>
<P>
   It was from the Gate of Heavenly Peace that imperial edicts were
lowered in gilded ``cloud trays'' to berobed officials prostrated
below for transmission across the empire. It was through the gate's
portals that the emperor and his vast retinue passed whenever they
left the Forbidden City.
</P>
<P>
   And because Mao chose to build the mammoth Great Hall of the
People on the enlarged square's west side and then to take up
residence just adjacent to the emperor's old palace, Tiananmen
Square also became the symbolic interface in contemporary times
between the Chinese Communist Party and the ``broad masses of the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it was a traditional emblem of the state's figurative
bond with its people, Tiananmen Gate and the area in front of it
became the place to which people began coming to seek a redress of
grievances when ideas about democracy began to filter into China at
the turn of the century. Thus it acquired something of a split
personality _ the figurative seat of state power, on the one hand,
and a place of remonstration and dissent, on the other.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous of all demonstrations was the May 4th Incident
in 1919, when patriotic students marched in front of the Gate of
Heavenly Peace to protest the government's accession at Versailles
to giving Germany's concessions in China to Japan after World War
I.
</P>
<P>
   Although the demonstrations _ China's first _ lasted only one
day, this led to a much larger movement that inspired a whole
generation of intellectuals, including most of the founders of the
Chinese Communist Party, with the new watchwords of the day:
``science and democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1919, demonstrations in the square have followed one on
the other as these contradictory forces _ led by those who viewed
it as a symbol of the state's right to rule and by those who saw it
as a place of the people's right to remonstrate with official power
_ struggled over its symbolic power.
</P>
<P>
   Again in 1925, Chinese rallied in front of Tiananmen Gate
against the ``unequal treaties'' that gave foreigners
extraterritorial rights in China.
</P>
<P>
   In 1926, the first blood was spilled when government troops
fired on crowds protesting capitulation to Japanese demands. When
50 people were killed, China's most famous writer, Lu Xun, wrote
prophetically that ``Lies written in ink can never disguise truths
written in blood. Blood debts must be repaid in kind; the longer
the delay, the greater the interest.''
</P>
<P>
   These words were to resonate with eerie prescience in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In 1935, students again gathered before Tiananmen, this time to
protest Chiang Kai-shek's refusal to form a united front with Mao
to fight the Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, Mao himself stood atop Tiananmen to proclaim that, at
last, China had ``stood up'' to establish a new independent and
sovereign government. In 1966, Mao was back, ironically, to rally a
million young Red Guards and to launch the Cultural Revolution in
an attack against the very Communist Party he himself had set up.
</P>
<P>
   Not until 1976, when beloved Prime Minister Zhou Enlai died, was
the square rebaptized with mass dissent. On April 5, tens of
thousands of grief-stricken Chinese spontaneously flooded in to pay
their respects to Zhou and indirectly to voice a protest against
the extreme leftist policies of Mao and the Gang of Four.
</P>
<P>
   Again in the winter of 1986-'87, students demanding more rapid
political reform and democratization broke through police cordons
and reached the square.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1989, the demonstration-of-all-demonstrations
erupted when, after the death of liberal ex-Communist Party Chief
Hu Yaobang _ who had been unceremoniously defrocked by Deng
Xiaoping _ Chinese again spontaneously poured into the square to
pay their final respects.
</P>
<P>
   These demonstrations ended six weeks later in the massacre of
June 3, which confirmed as never before the square's significance
as a place of protest against official power.
</P>
<P>
   It is into this highly symbolic place so supercharged with
history that President Clinton will be greeted by Chinese President
Jiang Zemin beginning at 9 p.m. EDT Friday. Indeed, Clinton will be
officially welcomed to Beijing at almost precisely that spot at the
east entrance to the Great Hall of the People where in April 1989
students were rebuked as they kneeled on the steps to present their
petition of grievance and where soldiers mustered to expel students
from the square.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   China's leadership has made Clinton's appearance here as a one
price of entry for this state visit and a tithe to be paid in
advance of creating the ``new strategic alliance'' between the
United States and China that has become the centerpiece of the
president's trip.
</P>
<P>
   For Americans, Clinton's symbolic presence in Tiananmen Square
will recall the vivid imagery of the 1989 student movement and the
massacre that ended it.
</P>
<P>
   For Chinese, however, the imagery will resonate with far more
history. It will harken all the way back to the May 4th Movement of
1919, when the clarion call for democratic reform first broke out
as public protest.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's appearance, which will be broadcast all across
China, also will help reinforce the part of the square's symbolism
that has centered around state power. It will help the Chinese
leadership re-establish in the minds of its people a sense that the
Communist Party _ and not those who have used it to seek a redress
of grievances _ is the rightful heir to Tiananmen Square's
conflicted legacy.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Orville Schell, the dean of the Graduate School of Journalism
at the University of California at Berkeley, is the author of
numerous books on China, including ``Mandate of Heaven'' and the
forthcoming ``Virtual Tibet.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
