<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6915 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAIMLER-BOOK-REVIEW-N     06-25 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIMLER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DAIMLER-BENZ IN THE THIRD REICH': AN INDUSTRIAL STOP BEFORE
AUSCHWITZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By HERBERT MITGANG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ranks of the Third Reich were filled both with true
believers and opportunists in every field of the arts, sciences and
professions _ musicians, physicians, professors, rocketeers,
bankers, lawyers, judges, journalists _ who lent their names and
talents to the Nazi regime.
</P>
<P>
   They were not just Hitler's legions committing war crimes in
uniform but also a cross section of Germany's civilian society. Not
everyone was involved, to be sure, but opposition was minuscule and
occurred only late in the war, when defeat clearly loomed.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not surprising that industrialists helped build the vast
military machines of the Wehrmacht and the Luftwaffe; turning out
armaments instead of passenger cars was a natural progression for
German big business on the home front.
</P>
<P>
   What is startling to read in ``Daimler-Benz in the Third
Reich,'' Neil Gregor's well-documented study of the automaker in
wartime, is the extent of complicity by owners and managers in the
deadly excesses of their country. At the same time that the
manufacturer of Hitler's favorite car, the Mercedes-Benz, was
building tanks, trucks and aircraft engines for the war effort, it
was also a transit point for people going to the death camps, with
the collusion of the SS, the fuehrer's most-feared special police
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``In pursuit of their own interests,'' Gregor coolly writes,
``companies actively participated in the exploitation of foreign,
concentration camp and Jewish labor, in `Aryanization' policies and
in the exploitation of the occupied territories. Daimler-Benz was
no exception here.''
</P>
<P>
   In an analysis, the author offers a bold conclusion: ``Without
the collaboration of industry, none of these crimes would have been
possible. Industry placed its own interests _ directly and
indirectly, the pursuit of profit _ above those of the victims of
the regime.''
</P>
<P>
   In retaliatory measures that followed the enemy's own terror
tactics against Britain and occupied Europe, Allied bombers hit
industrial targets deep inside Germany with increasing
effectiveness. Damaged plants were moved to remote areas or placed
underground. A great need arose for slave and foreign labor to take
the place of workers and soldiers called to the Eastern and Western
fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Here the interests of Daimler-Benz and the SS both merged and
clashed. The auto maker-turned-armament-maker needed replacements
for skilled and unskilled workers to keep their factories running
and profitable; the SS needed more bodies to fulfill the quotas for
the ovens at Auschwitz and the other concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   A Nazi racial hierarchy developed inside the Daimler-Benz
factories, with thousands of Jewish slave laborers being treated
even worse than Polish workers. The author writes: ``In other
words, as soon as the company had trained their replacements, it
was ready to release the Jews for deportation _ in the full
knowledge of what this meant for the Jews concerned. For
Daimler-Benz, only the securing of a steady production was
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Daimler-Benz, like other companies producing arms for the Third
Reich, became one of the way stations to the death camps. For a
comparatively lucky few, being assigned to the factories sometimes
meant being saved by Allied ground forces as they conquered
Germany. But that was hardly the concern or the intention of
Daimler-Benz's management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Self-identification with the company took precedence over any
self-identification with the real suffering of humans,'' Gregor
writes. ``The company was able to survive in a relatively healthy
position down to the end of the war at least partly at the expense
of the health, and indeed in many cases the lives, of these
thousands of victims of forced labor.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no ``Schindler's List'' at Daimler-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   In a left-handed compliment, the author leaves the impression
that the owners and managers of Daimler-Benz were shrewder than
Hitler, his lieutenants and the SS. With some exceptions, they were
not fighting for the barbarian ideals of the Third Reich but for
the future of their company. When the SS put pressure on them to
increase armament production near the end of the war, they went
through the motions but made sure to save their most expensive
machinery for postwar cars and trucks. Wars end, but business is
business.
</P>
<P>
   The book doesn't cover the personal finances of the company's
management; it would be useful to know whether the owners enriched
themselves during the war. The author does note that the company
introduced ``new pay and incentive structures'' to help increase
production.
</P>
<P>
   Another omission is the matter of civilian criminality and
postwar clearing of industrialists. Undeniably, Daimler-Benz and
other companies used slave labor and prisoners of war in their
factories. Their top boss, Albert Speer, the Nazi minister of
armaments, was sentenced to 20 years as a major war criminal at the
Nuremberg trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daimler-Benz in the Third Reich'' isn't polemical in tone; its
devastating facts speak for themselves. Gregor, a lecturer in
European history at Southampton University in Britain, was given
access to the Mercedes-Benz archives. He also drew upon documents
recently made available after East and West Germany were united.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a strong addition to our knowledge of the role of
big business under the Nazis. Gregor's book graphically
demonstrates how industry was essential for Hitler's dreams of
conquest. It deserves a place on the shelves with William L.
Shirer's ``Rise and Fall of the Third Reich,'' Primo Levi's
``Survival in Auschwitz'' and Arthur D. Morse's ``While Six Million
Died.''
</P>
<P>
   Since this history was written, Daimler-Benz of Stuttgart and
the Chrysler Corporation of Detroit have agreed to merge. That
makes ``Daimler-Benz in the Third Reich'' all the more timely; but
don't expect to find the book in the glove compartment of any of
their new cars.
</P>
<P>
   Publication notes:
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLER-BENZ IN THE THIRD REICH
</P>
<P>
   By Neil Gregor
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 276 pages. Yale University Press. $30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
