<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Thursday, June 25. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON (Xian, China) _ With the pageantry of thundering
drums and clanging gongs, President Clinton was welcomed to China
tonight, the first American President to visit this country in
nearly a decade. The 30-minute ceremony was a made-for-TV
spectacle, replete with warriors in Tang dynasty costumes, a score
of maidens in flowing white gowns bearing baskets of flowers and
yellow-robed riders astride strutting horses. Red paper lanterns
hung from the lampposts and bright silk banners bearing images of
mythical birds of good fortune flapped in the breeze on a mild
smoggy night. By John M. Broder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SCENE (Xian, China) _ On this steamy summer night, the
people of Xian took to the streets to welcome Bill Clinton on the
first stop of his state visit, in what may well be the largest
spontaneous public display of affection in modern China. ``There's
never been another event like this here, I don't think I've ever
seen this many people come out for anything,'' said Sun Qinqi, an
engineer, who said he'd decided to pass up the World Cup to cram
onto the sidewalk just inside the South Gate to catch a glimpse of
the Presidential motorcade's arrival. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-VOTE (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ The Northern Ireland
peace effort marked another milestone today as residents of the
long polarized province turned out in large numbers to elect
members of a new legislature. Voters were choosing 108 lawmakers
from a field of nearly 300 candidates from once warring parties to
serve in the Northern Ireland Assembly. The new body will restore
local government here for the first time since the British imposed
direct rule in 1972. By Warren Hoge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-VETO (Washington) _ The Supreme Court ruled today that
the president could not cancel individual items of federal spending
and tax breaks approved by Congress because such ``line item
vetoes'' circumvent the law-making procedure prescribed by the
Constitution. The ruling is a major blow to Congress and to
President Clinton, who, like many of his predecessors, coveted tax
and spending powers that he did not have. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-AIDS (Washington) _ People with H.I.V. infection need not
have any symptoms of disease or obvious impairment to be covered by
the Federal law that bars discrimination on the basis of
disability, the Supreme Court ruled in a major victory for people
with the virus that causes AIDS. Voting 5 to 4, the Justices agreed
with a Federal appeals court's ruling that a woman with
asymptomatic H.I.V. infection, who was refused care in a dentist's
office, met the definition of disability under the Americans with
Disabilities Act. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-STARR (Washington) _ The Supreme Court today broadly
affirmed the rights of clients to take to their graves their
consultations with lawyers. The ruling was a legal setback to the
Whitewater independent counsel, who was seeking notes taken by the
lawyer for Vincent W. Foster Jr., the deputy White House counsel
who committed suicide nearly five years ago. The justices' 6-3
decision found that the three pages of notes taken by Mr. Foster's
lawyer, James Hamilton, of a meeting between the two did not lose
its protection under the lawyer-client privilege when Mr. Foster
died nine days later. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN-LUTHERANS (Undated) _ In a decision that brings to a
close a divisive chapter of the Reformation, the Vatican said
yesterday that the Roman Catholic Church will sign a joint
declaration with the world's Lutherans that affirms that Catholics
and Lutherans share a basic understanding of how human beings
receive salvation. The document, approved last week by the Lutheran
World Federation, declares that Catholics and Lutherans have common
ground to overcome the issue that split the Western Christian world
nearly 500 years ago -- the question of whether ``justification''
comes solely through faith in God, as Luther held, or whether a
person's good works also play a role, as Catholics emphasized. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEW-PLANETS (Undated) _ The discoveries of planets beyond
the solar system, stimulating renewed speculation of other possible
worlds throbbing with life, are now drawing closer in cosmic terms
to the world of their discoverers. The latest detection, made this
month by American astronomers, is of a planet about twice the mass
of Jupiter orbiting the star Gliese 876, one of the Sun's nearest
neighbors at a distance of only 15 light-years away. Previous
confirmed extrasolar planets have been observed at stars 40 to 80
light-years away. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GM-STRIKE (Flint, Mich.) _ Like a large stone thrown in a pond,
the strikes at two General Motors' parts factories are producing
economic effects that are slowly rippling out across North America.
The first effects were felt immediately in this town when the
strike began, because General Motors accounts for more than half
the employment and taxes here. When 3,400 workers went on strike at
a metal parts stamping factory here on June 5, nearby restaurants
lost half their business immediately, while the pool table and bar
stools at the pub across the street have been deserted for the last
three weeks. The next ripples came over the last two weeks as the
company has closed 26 of its 29 assembly plants in North America
and curtailed production at nearly 100 parts factories. Now the
effects are reaching across the country, into communities and
states where the auto industry has been less visible than here in
the industrial Midwest. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-NY-YANKS-METS (New York) _ If the heavens cooperate tonight,
