<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-PORSCHE (Portland, Ore.) _ This year, as Porsche
marks the 50th anniversary of its first car, it has reinvented
itself by remaking its 34-year-old flagship. It has set about
remaking the 911 completely for the first time since the car bowed
in 1965. By Keith Martin.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART-SUVs (Undated) _ Porsche and Volkswagen are teaming up
to build high-end sports utility vehicles for sale in the United
States and Europe. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-HNS (Undated) _ The old adage ``If it ain't
broke, don't fix it'' often applies to the world of automotive
design, which is why Mazda took a real chance when it remade the
popular Miata roadster for 1999. But I have to agree with the
gushing publicity material that Mazda included with the test
vehicle I drove last week. By golly, they did improve the car, and
they didn't mess anything up. By G. Chambers Williams III.
</P>
<P>
   CARS-TECHNOLOGY-NYT (Undated) _ Automakers and their dealers are
facing a severe shortage of automobile service technicians _ they
used to be called ``mechanics'' before computer chips took over
most of a car's functions. While the auto companies are recruiting
newcomers, they are also looking for ways to help current workers
do their jobs more efficiently and precisely. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-AUTOS-BLOOM (Undated) _ General Motors Corp.'s
second-quarter earnings will drop sharply because of current
strikes by the United Auto Workers, while Chrysler Corp.'s earnings
will double from a strike-weakened year-ago period. Ford Motor Co.,
enjoying labor peace, could set another quarterly earnings record
for U.S. automakers. By John Lippert with reporting by Brian
Lysaght.
</P>
