<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER CHANCE FOR `AMISTAD'  
 NEW VIDEO RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another Chance For `Amistad'
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those films that had big hype in the beginning
and never panned out in theaters,'' said Michael Becker. ``That
always leaves the door nice and open to do well on video.''
</P>
<P>
   Becker, proprietor of the Video Room, a store on the Upper East
Side of Manhattan, was referring to ``Amistad,'' Steven Spielberg's
film about a slave ship revolt in 1839. Not that the movie flopped
completely in theaters last winter: it eventually collected $44.3
million at the box office. But a much better result was expected
for the heavily promoted film from Dreamworks, the studio whose
co-founder was Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Universal will issue ``Amistad'' the video in standard
and wide-screen versions. What's the prognosis? In tone and heft
the film is somewhat reminiscent of ``Schindler's List,''
Spielberg's 1993 epic about the Holocaust. Generally speaking,
though, video dealers aren't as excited about ``Amistad'' as they
were about ``Schindler,'' which rented and sold strongly in many
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Amistad'' opened in theaters, reviewers hung terms like
``serious,'' ``important'' and ``earnest'' on the film, a solid
acknowledgment of worthiness if not exactly a rallying call to a
broadly appealing entertainment. Video more or less holds the same
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The Movie Monitor, a tip sheet for video dealers that grades
films and recommends the number of copies the average store should
carry, calls ``Amistad'' a film for ``serious'' renters. In the
Monitor, the movie rates highly in star power (Anthony Hopkins,
Morgan Freeman and Djimon Hounsou), gets a respectable if not
superlative B for reviews by major critics and scores strongly for
``legs,'' meaning length of theatrical run (the film ran into the
spring).
</P>
<P>
   That translates into a recommendation of 10 copies for the
average store, which is a moderate number for a big film. ``It
isn't for middle America,'' said Rich Thorward, publisher of The
Monitor. ``It's not wide-scale black, either. It's like
`Schindler's List' that way: upscale areas did well, blue-collar
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Debbie Allen, who proposed the idea for
``Amistad'' to Spielberg in 1994 and produced the film with him and
Colin Wilson, said video would ``open a wider viewership.''
</P>
<P>
   Becker agrees. In an affluent area, his store will stock about
20 copies. ``Because of the subject matter, upscale customers will
watch,'' he said, ``but it will get others who will watch for $3 or
$4 and not $8,'' a typical box office price in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Allen also said she hoped that the film had by now gained
enough distance from the controversies of last winter, when the
writer Barbara Chase-Riboud accused Spielberg of appropriating much
of ``Amistad'' from one of her books and critics complained that
the movie had been misrepresented as a nonfictional account. (Ms.
Chase-Riboud dropped her lawsuit in February.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the storm is over and we'll be looked at differently,''
Ms. Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   Wag the Dog
</P>
<P>
   The president has groped a pre-teen-ager, his opponent's
commercials are set to the tune of ``Thank Heaven for Little
Girls'' and damage control is in high gear at the White House under
the direction of the master troubleshooter Conrad Brean (Robert De
Niro). No simple spinmeister, Brean decides to fabricate a crisis
with Albania to deflect the nation's attention. Reaching out to
Hollywood, he enlists the producer Stanley Motss (Dustin Hoffman),
and together they concoct a scenario that makes Barry Levinson's
satire, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``as scarily
plausible as it is swift, hilarious and impossible to resist.''
</P>
<P>
   1997. New Line. $106.77. Laser disk, $39.99. 97 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ma Vie En Rose
</P>
<P>
   The way young Ludovic (Georges DuFresne) explains it, the
chromosome that would have made him female accidentally fell into
the garbage, leaving him as a little boy with a preference for
dresses and an urge to marry the boy next door. But what begins as
a charming eccentricity eventually costs his father his job,
threatens to tear apart his parents' marriage and forces his family
to move from their proper Belgian neighborhood. Fortunately in such
circumstances, Alain Berliner's film avoids pathos and weighty
social commentary to tell a modern fairy tale ``with irresistible
good humor and minimal psychologizing'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1997. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36. 89 minutes. French with English
subtitles. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Replacement Killers
</P>
<P>
   Antoine Fuqua's film is so sleek that it unrolls like a long
dance record. The Hong Kong action star Chow Yun-Fat and Mira
Sorvino are teamed as a hit man with a conscience and a forger of
passport papers who is comfortable around guns. Add shootings. If a
fusion of ``action-adventure style and cool, Los Angeles street
chic has a certain seductive charm, it is the only charm of a movie
that is otherwise devoid of content'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77. Laser disk, $34.95. 86
minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   No Looking Back
</P>
<P>
   Edward Burns moves the Irish-American ambiance of his earlier
films (``The Brothers McMullen'' and ``She's the One'') to Bruce
Springsteen country in bleakest New Jersey. Plain-as-vanilla
Michael (Jon Bon Jovi) is trying to keep his girlfriend (Lauren
Holly) out of the clutches of her former boyfriend Charlie (Burns),
who's back after a failed try at the big time in Los Angeles. But
in reaching for an epic American sadness, Burns makes the mistake
of employing actors whose own ``prospects look considerably
brighter than the dead-end futures the movie insists on giving
them'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Polygram. $102.96. Laser disk, $39.99. 96 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   STRAIGHT TO VIDEO
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television.
</P>
<P>
   OVER THE OCEAN (1991, 89 minutes). Winner of nine Israeli
Academy Awards, Jacob Goldwasser's comedy tells the story of
Rosinka and Menachem, two Holocaust survivors struggling along in
Tel Aviv in 1962 who are tempted by stories of improbably glowing
possibilities in America. Three other Israeli titles are newly
available on video: NEWLAND, about family life in Israel's refugee
camps; AUDITIONS (1995, 92 minutes), with young performers
struggling for success, and THE HERITAGE (1994, 85 minutes), two
love stories, one modern and the other set during the Spanish
Inquisition. Sisu. $59.95. None are rated. Information: (800)
223-7478.
</P>
<P>
   THE RISE OF LOUIS XIV. Roberto Rossellini's majestic biography
of the Sun King portrays the young French monarch's flair for
fashion and his ability to mold his domain to satisfy every nuance
of his sophisticated tastes. 1966. Hen's Tooth. $24.95. 100
minutes. French with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   THE DAY THE EARTH STOOD STILL (1951, 92 minutes) and THE FLY
(1958, 94 minutes). Robert Wise's classic science-fiction drama and
Kurt Neumann's film about a scientist who gets mixed up with an
insect are part of a four-film drive-in package from Fox. The other
titles, both new to video, are THE LOST WORLD (1960, 98 minutes),
directed by Irwin Allen, with Michael Rennie and Jill St. John as
adventurers stranded among the dinosaurs, and THE ALLIGATOR PEOPLE
(1959, 74 minutes), directed by Roy Del Ruth, with Beverly Garland,
who discovers the effects alligator serum has on her new husband.
$14.98 each. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
