<HEADLINE>
TOP 100 MOVIE LIST RAISES HOWLS IN HOLLYWOOD
</HEADLINE>
  (Advance for Sunday, June 28) 
 (ja) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Where's the brilliant silent clown Buster Keaton?
Where's Garbo? Where are Fred and Ginger? Or the great comedies by
Preston Sturges? Or Ernst Lubitsch's classic films, ``Ninotchka''
and ``Little Shop Around the Corner.''
</P>
<P>
   And what on earth are ``Fargo,'' ``Rocky,'' ``Easy Rider'' and
``Guess Who's Coming to Dinner'' doing on a list of the 100
greatest movies ever made?
</P>
<P>
   Those are some of the questions that have puzzled and distressed
Hollywood during the last week in the aftermath of what many
executives, filmmakers and producers viewed as the flawed and
over-hyped American Film Institute's list of 100 great movies.
There are other issues, too.
</P>
<P>
   Meryl Streep, speaking at a luncheon honoring women in the movie
business, deplored the absence of films on the list with women as
leading protagonists. Curtis Hanson, director of ``L.A.
Confidential'' and a former film critic, said that having only four
titles from the silent era, a period that many film experts
consider the peak of movie-making, as well as other omissions was
unforgivable. ``This list cannot be taken seriously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a popularity contest,'' he continued, ``which is why it's
so heavily skewed toward movies of recent decades.''
</P>
<P>
   A critic at Variety, the show business newspaper, called the
list ``scholastically challenged.'' Kenneth Turan, the chief film
critic at The Los Angeles Times, said that ``the omissions on the
AFI list, and they are numerous, are frankly a scandal,'' and he
added that the entire exercise was both wasteful and a shame.
</P>
<P>
   And Russell Baker, writing in The New York Times, detailed what
he saw as the numerous films and stars that were ignored, including
Edward G. Robinson and ``Gunga Din,'' the greatest boy's adventure
in movies.
</P>
<P>
   Film institute officials were shaken by the onslaught. The
prestigious organization, which runs a film school and is dedicated
to advancing and preserving movies, initially saw the list as a way
to raise money, especially after financial cuts for the arts in
Washington. The organization teamed with CBS for a three-hour
special on the list, and Newsweek, one of the sponsors of the
television show, published a special issue. The TNT network also
began a series based on the list.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,500 members of the film community, as well as
President Clinton, were asked to select the best 100 films from a
list of 400 prepared by the institute. Orson Welles' ``Citizen
Kane'' (1941) was chosen the best. But the list was so heavy with
contemporary films that Steven Spielberg was the most chosen
director, with five films, and Martin Scorsese had three, an honor
that, as Turan said, may have embarrassed Scorsese, whose grasp of
films is second to none, because so many great films were shut out.
</P>
<P>
   The institute struggled to put the best possible light on the
controversy. Seth Oster, the director of communications for the
group, said the institute welcomed the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It meant that there was a dialogue going on about films that
was being created and fostered by the AFI through this
celebration,'' he said. ``That was our main goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Still. No Buster Keaton movies?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Seeing Double at Disney  &LR;  Nancy Meyers, a veteran writer and
producer of the hit comedies ``Private Benjamin'' (1980), ``Baby
Boom'' (1987) and ``Father of the Bride'' (1991) and its 1995
sequel, didn't think she'd find many surprises in making her
directorial debut in the new and updated Disney family classic,
``The Parent Trap.'' After all, in making her hits, she was on the
set every day and participated in most decisions made by her
longtime partner, Charles Shyer, who directed those movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I'd be surprised, and I was shocked,'' said Ms.
Meyers. ``When Charles was directing, I slept at night. And I never
slept at night when I was directing. The night was torture. I
worried about everything. From midnight to three, I worried about
the day before. From three to six, I worried about the mistakes I'd
make the next day. I wrote notes in the dark. When I woke up, I
could barely read them.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. The film, which opens on July 29 and stars Dennis
Quaid; Natasha Richardson, who just won a Tony award for
``Cabaret,'' and a newcomer, Lindsay Lohan, in the Hayley Mills
role, has emerged as one of Disney's most anticipated movies of the
summer. The original 1961 movie, which has been extraordinarily
popular among young girls through the years, is about twins, raised
on different continents, who meet at a summer camp in Maine and
devise a scheme to reunite their divorced parents.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the fact that the children controlled the story line
and pulled all the strings,'' Ms. Meyers said. ``I was, frankly, a
little worried about doing another remake after `Father of the
Bride,' but it finally seemed to me OK. There's a comfort level for
the audience in seeing something they've seen before. The challenge
is to tell the story in your own way. Why are people rushing to see
`Cabaret'? They know it. They want to see this interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Meyers said she has wanted to direct for a while, but held
off because the consuming hours would have taken her away from her
two daughters with Shyer. But the girls are now 17 and 10, and Ms.
Meyers felt now was the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the decisions on movies were made by the two of us but,
finally, all the shots and final choices were Charles','' she said.
``At a certain point I said, `I want to have a chance.'''
</P>
<P>
   There are few female directors, and Ms. Meyers was a bit
concerned about dealing with crews that sometimes patronize women
filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were fabulous with me,'' she said. ``They were mostly
young, and they helped me a lot. We have many special effects, and
I was fearful of that. When I met the effects crew, I thought it
would be like car mechanics talking to women, `Oh little lady, let
us worry about these complicated things, you just turn on the key
and push the pedal.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like that at all,'' said Ms. Meyers, who is planning
to direct another film as soon as she can.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Patience, Patience  &LR;  Like any actor, Tony Shalhoub has had his
share of rejection. He would have been delighted, he says, to have
been in the forthcoming Steven Spielberg film, ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' or to have won the Greg Kinnear role in ``As Good as It
Gets.'' Shalhoub said, ``All those roles I tried for _ they're
almost too numerous to mention.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shalhoub isn't too worried. The actor, best known to
audiences as the Italian cab driver, Antonio, in the television
show ``Wings,'' saw his film career take off as the uncompromising
risotto-specialist chef and Stanley Tucci's brother in ``Big
Night.'' Although some roles still elude him, Shalhoub now has a
film being released almost every other month or so through
December.
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old actor, who grew up in Green Bay, Wis., earned a
master's degree at the Yale School of Drama and spent four years at
the American Repertory Company in Cambridge, Mass., will appear in,
among other films, ``A Civil Action'' (he plays John Travolta's law
partner); ``Against All Enemies'' (he's an FBI agent with Denzel
Washington), and ``The Imposters,'' a screwball comedy set in the
1930's and directed by Tucci.
</P>
<P>
   Shalhoub, who has spent years working on and off Broadway, said
that probably his most important learning experience as an actor
occurred while he was an undergraduate at the University of Maine
in Portland. He had decided to become an actor and so performed at
children's theaters across the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a lot of bad work and early experimentation,'' he said
with a laugh. ``The audiences could be very captive and very
disruptive. I got all my humiliations out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that actors can't let rejections shake their confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become somewhat easier for me since I'm married and have
two children and I've shifted my priorities somewhat,'' said
Shalhoub, who met his wife, the actress Brooke Adams, while working
on a Wendy Wasserstein play, ``The Heidi Chronicles.'' The couple
and their children live in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are consumed by the business and their careers so that
rejection can be devastating and the effects can be long-lasting.
It can become an unhealthy way to live. I was like that for years.
I was lucky. I met the right woman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
