<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CITIES-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PROMOTES BUSINESS DEVELOPMENT IN INNER CITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 28)   (EDs: Filed in Washington, ``w,'' and Financial, ``f,''
categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the face of congressional opposition to its
urban agenda, the Clinton administration is finding other ways to
fulfill its vision of bringing jobs and development to hard-pressed
inner-city neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   At a little-noticed White House meeting June 5, Vice President
Al Gore hosted chief executives of nine corporations that already
have invested heavily in building commercial enterprises in
poverty-stricken areas. Each used the meeting to make commitments
to major expansions.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, the White House Business and Entrepreneurial
Roundtable on Community Empowerment, marked a turning point in the
often tenuous relationship between businesses and impoverished
urban neighborhoods. During the riots of the 1960s, images of
looting and burning convinced many retailers and manufacturers to
shift investments to upscale neighborhoods, suburbia or industrial
zones far from cities. A significant number of urban areas became
wastelands with few, if any, jobs or amenities.
</P>
<P>
   However, with the economy improving and urban unemployment down,
executives and government leaders gradually are coming to view
these same neighborhoods as opportunities. At the meeting, Gore
equated investment in impoverished neighborhoods with good business
sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``By working in partnership with the private sector, we can make
our communities and our nation stronger and more competitive,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Henry McKinnell, head of New York-based Pfizer Inc.'s
pharmaceuticals group, said his company would develop a
supermarket, low- and moderate-income housing, and expand a school
and industrial space on land it owns near its original and
still-operating Brooklyn plant.
</P>
<P>
   And Martin Grass, chief executive of Rite Aid Corp. in Camp
Hill, Pa., pledged to open 40 new drugstores over the next two
years in economically depressed urban areas nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful symbiotic relationship,'' said Suzanne Mead,
Rite Aid's vice president for corporate communications. ``We invest
in the community and in return we are able to increase our sales.
And our growth actually helps benefit the community because we
employ local people, and we buy products and services from local
vendors.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 1999 budget, Clinton called for an ambitious effort to
make inner cities more business friendly. He asked Congress to
spend $400 million to establish a new Community Empowerment Fund,
which officials said would spur about $2 billion in private
investment and create 280,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also wants to spend $1.5 billion to expand
empowerment zones, where businesses receive tax breaks for
investments in defined urban areas. Also, Clinton proposed adding
an extra $50 million to the ``brownfields'' effort to clean up
polluted urban sites, and provide $283 million in rental assistance
to families moving from welfare to work.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican congressional aides say new programs and
expansions of old ones are unlikely to get past the GOP-controlled
Congress, especially with the demise of a cigarette tax increase
that was the centerpiece of tobacco legislation. Clinton was
counting on that money to fund $10 billion in domestic social
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can assume the likelihood on most of these proposals is
nil,'' said one Republican aide, who asked not to be
identified..MDRV/.MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   One exception, aides said, is Clinton's proposal on rental
vouchers for welfare-to-work families. Republicans are likely to
support a modified version, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is to empower people and help pay their rent,''
said another Republican aide. ``That's the most we can
realistically do in this budget environment.''
</P>
<P>
   With the nation's economy humming along, many cities that
languished in the 1970s and 1980s are in the midst of a remarkable
comeback. Now that crime is down, New York is a tourist mecca. And
even old industrial cities such as Cleveland and Baltimore have
attracted business and tourism with ambitious downtown
redevelopment projects.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment in cities averaged 5.3 percent in March. In March
1993, the rate was 8.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But problems persist. The exodus of middle-class families
continues, with six million middle-income families leaving inner
cities since 1970. Unemployment rates for minority youth in central
cities average 26 percent, five times higher than the overall
unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's answer is a host of bully-pulpit efforts
such as Gore's business roundtable that do not require
congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   However, in calling for increased inner-city business
investment, the administration is placing itself atop a wave
already rolling to shore, said Bruce Katz of the Brookings
Institution, an independent Washington-based think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Katz, an urban specialist who served in Clinton's first term as
an official at the Department of Housing and Urban Development,
gave the administration high marks for stimulating the urban
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Katz said, ``the vice president didn't manufacture
these commitments. The corporations aren't doing this out of
charity. They're doing it because they know they can profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Such investments, Katz added, represent a better-late-than-never
recognition that contrary to the general perception that poor urban
dwellers have little disposable income, ``these neighborhoods have
long been under-served by retail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
