<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7030 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROADWAY-DANCE-2TAKES     06-25 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-DANCE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBTLY DISGUISED, DANCE SLIPS BACK TO BROADWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dance fans at more than one Broadway show this summer
might feel like the protagonist of Moliere's ``Bourgeois
Gentilhomme,'' who was unaware that he was speaking ``prose.''
</P>
<P>
   Audiences might be surprised to learn how much choreography runs
through musicals that resemble anything but the standard
dance-driven show. A closer look would show that dance can go
beyond the time-honored integrated number that advances the plot.
Dance is there, whether we know it or not.
</P>
<P>
   How, for instance, can one separate Garth Fagan's spectacular
rhythmic processionals and anthropomorphic dances from the action
as a whole in ``The Lion King''? The entire show dances.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone caught on at first; it took a Tony Award for best
choreography to Fagan to give him Broadway's seal of approval. His
contribution was so subtle, albeit brilliant, that even experienced
dancegoers did not recognize a dance sequence when they saw it.
</P>
<P>
   But musicals now on Broadway rarely offer the old set pieces,
and the idea that dance furthers the action is even harder to spot.
Again, can one separate song from dance in Ann Reinking's
super-polished staging of ``Chicago''? Dance is visible here but it
is glued to the songs it enhances and vice versa. Neither would
make sense without the other in this current version.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Cabaret,'' star performances from Natasha Richardson
and Alan Cumming may conceal how much choreography weaves through
the show. But where would the piercing, aggressive tone of this
revisionist production be without the insidious bump-and-grind
images that Rob Marshall, significantly co-director (with Sam
Mendes) as well as choreographer, uses to stylize the show so
shrewdly?
</P>
<P>
   Most of these musicals play by relatively new rules. One says
``relatively'' because even ``Le Bourgeois Gentilhomme'' can be
seen as an antecedent. Moliere's 17th-century comedy was termed a
comedie-ballet and was a new hybrid form. Neither just a play nor
just a ballet, it integrated music and dance into dramatic
structure, a witty entertainment fit for a king: Louis XIV.
</P>
<P>
   What is fit for the ticket buyer in New York does not fall into
one category. This might not be the best season for dance in
Broadway musicals, but it signals an innovative approach that banks
on a hybrid genre of its own. This is why the boundaries between
dance and other elements in each musical are not clearly defined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bring In da Noise, Bring In da Funk'' is a sterling example.
What looks like a tap-dancing show is actually a dramatic conceit
in which tap becomes a vocabulary to tell a story. At the other end
is ``Rent,'' in which the dance component appears minimal but
contributes the vernacular energy essential to the musical's tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago,'' ``The Lion King,'' ``Cabaret,'' ``Rent'' and
``Bring In da Noise'' are experimental productions. In between,
there is conventional show dancing with period flavor, seen to
blockbuster effect in ``Ragtime,'' but with blander results in
``High Society.'' Graciela Daniele's choreography for ``Ragtime''
is a model of professionalism, but even these two shows are led by
singers, not singer-dancers. No Ray Bolger or Chita Rivera here.
</P>
<P>
   A view of dance as a creative medium is what most of these shows
offer those who remember that Broadway musicals, before Andrew
Lloyd Webber, were song (italics)and(end italics) dance shows.
</P>
<P>
   Dance on Broadway made a comeback in 1992 but is now seen in a
new guise. A pastiche of older styles, common in revivals like
``Show Boat'' a few years ago, is mainly out. In ``Chicago'' and
``Cabaret,'' dance is used to comment on the original productions.
</P>
<P>
   Their current choreographers are less concerned with reproducing
authentic dances of the 1920's and 30's than with creating a gloss
on the ``Cabaret'' of Joel Grey and the ``Chicago'' that
telegraphed Bob Fosse's choreographic style to the world.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Reinking's choreography comments on Fosse's work. Marshall's
burlesque-house entertainers in ``Cabaret'' say less about the
Germany in which his dances are set than about restylizing a
musical for today. One could complain just a few years ago that
virtually all musicals were about the past, even ``Tommy'' and
``Grease.'' Where was the counterpart of ``West Side Story,''
written in the 1950s about the 1950s?
</P>
<P>
   ``Rent'' was the reply, a look at aspiring artists on the Lower
East Side in a time of AIDS. ``The Lion King,'' for all its
fantasy-filled animal kingdom, and ``Bring In da Noise'' are also
streetwise shows imbued with a hip-hop influence. Their dances
borrow from the street.
</P>
<P>
   Dance on Broadway today is not identified with a superstar
choreographer like Jerome Robbins, who influenced the art form for
decades. Whether this is a weakness or not, many choreographers
tailor their styles to specific shows, even to the point of
submerging dance into an organic whole, as a selective overview of
the following musicals suggests.
</P>
<P>
   `Cabaret'
</P>
<P>
   The sinister, as opposed to merely decadent, atmosphere of
Berlin's Kit Kat Klub in this revisionist production owes much to
the invidious slink of its denizens. Rob Marshall, the
choreographer, keeps the nightclub entertainers on the move and in
Cumming, the master of ceremonies, he has an actor with the
physical agility of a remarkable mime.
</P>
<P>
   Still, women in underwear and torn hose who squat in a deep plie
and a crotch-clutching compere will soon suggest that
pelvis-swiveling variations on basic bump-and-grind can go only so
far.
</P>
<P>
   Where Marshall succeeds is in using dance and stylized movement
to evoke a general emotional state. Virtually everyone is a victim
in this production, which ends with Cumming's snapping into a
cruciform pose in concentration camp uniform, identified as a Jew
and homosexual by the gold star and pink triangle pinned on his
chest.
</P>
<P>
   For all its intended shock value, this ending has been implied
all along. No one, including the folk who turn into Nazis
overnight, has a bright future, and as the female entertainers
slither into sexually provocative poses or grovel on the floor for
money, toughness becomes equated with mere tawdriness.
</P>
<P>
   There is a message in the movement. As the Nazis rise to power,
all that writhing on the floor suggests a willingness to submit, in
more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   `Chicago'
</P>
<P>
   Fosse's pelvis-popping choreography is reinvented by Ms.
Reinking in a vibrant geometric style that suits this minimalist
concert staging, which originated with the ``Encores'' series at
City Center.
</P>
<P>
   The black costumes by William Ivey Long are functional in the
best sense. The performers stand out in relief against the band
behind them. There is less of a hard edge to the movement than one
might expect from a Fosse star and disciple, but that is because
the show is more brassy than sordid in this rendition.
</P>
<P>
   nn
