<HEADER>
A7034 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROADWAY-DANCE-2NDTAK     06-25 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-DANCE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: this rendition.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ms. Reinking, in the starring role, has been replaced by Karen
Ziemba as Roxie Hart, the aspiring vaudeville star on trial for
murdering her lover. Velma Kelly, her jail-house rival, was played
by Mamie Duncan-Gibbs last week when Bebe Neuwirth was temporarily
absent from the show.
</P>
<P>
   If the two leading roles were created for star dancers who can
sing, the choreography is so solid and so inclusive of its dynamic
ensemble that the dancing has a built-in impact, no matter who
leads.
</P>
<P>
   The idiom is stylized jazz dance, two generations down from Jack
Cole, Fosse's mentor and the pioneer of jazz dance on Broadway and
in Hollywood. Jazz dance is not reticent; it implies a hard sell,
and Ms. Reinking concentrates on what Martha Graham called ``The
House of Pelvic Truth,'' the lower body. It is all sexy but in this
version, never sardonic.
</P>
<P>
   `The Lion King'
</P>
<P>
   Garth Fagan, one of modern dance's most innovative
choreographers, has brought something new to Broadway in his
collaboration with Julie Taymor, the show's director. Rarely has
dancing been integrated so fully into stage action to create a
spectacle in the truest sense.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the stage version of ``Beauty and the Beast,'' the Walt
Disney Co.'s first Broadway musical, Disney's ``Lion King'' does
not duplicate the cartoon images of the animated film on which it
is based. The choreography has its own vision and is, in fact,
visionary.
</P>
<P>
   The story of a lion cub's rite of passage takes place in an
animal kingdom and, thanks to Fagan, all the flora and fauna enter
into the dance. The grasslands are symbolized by trays of grass
atop the swaying performers; a fierce stampede of beasts is an
African warrior dance in disguise.
</P>
<P>
   With all their human characteristics, the animals reveal their
personalities through dance. The nasty hyenas are street toughs who
have a break-dance routine. By contrast, the hunt by the lionesses
is embodied in fleet leaps across the stage in pursuit of graceful
gazelles.
</P>
<P>
   In the dazzling opening processional, there is an introduction
to the distinctive rhythms and gaits that Fagan gives animal
groups, each moving in counterpoint to another.
</P>
<P>
   Served by a committed cast that is rendered anonymous under its
masks and headdresses, he offers a remarkable achievement: in true
ritual fashion, he has the dancer identify with the mask. The
imagination soars.
</P>
<P>
   `Ragtime'
</P>
<P>
   The dancing and choreography here is the kind that Europeans
consider a specifically American marvel. In a musical that attempts
to distill E.L. Doctorow's panoramic novel of America in the
century's first decade, Ms. Daniele skillfully boils the essence of
several ethnic groups down to archetypes or stereotypes, depending
on your view.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants, blacks and suburban whites are defined through
choreography that expresses character. There are some cliches, but
there are also exuberant evocations of a period: a boardwalk band
that freezes in silhouette, a machine dance that recalls an
assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   A new industrial America in which class and ethnic distinctions
will yield to mobility and money is described conventionally but
with admirable fluency in these dances.
</P>
<P>
   `High Society'
</P>
<P>
   Lar Lubovitch, one of the country's major modern dance
choreographers, is listed as the musical's official choreographer,
although Wayne Cilento, another choreographer, and Des McAnuff, a
director, were reportedly brought in to make final revisions.
</P>
<P>
   The dancing is used conventionally to hurry the plot along, but
there is also a welcome acerbic tinge that could have been
developed further. The spicy touch comes from the servants who
comment on the mores of a high-society household, descended from
Philip Barry's play ``The Philadelphia Story'' and the 1956 film
musical ``High Society.''
</P>
<P>
   As is common with an upstairs-downstairs situation, the servants
are pictured as more snobbish than their employers. Their
snootiness comes through in their straight-back stiffness and
disciplined movement patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Except for some negligible ballroom dances for the other
characters, the choreography consists of permutations of cumulative
gestures for the household staff. Anyone familiar with minimalist
works in experimental dance will know where the inspiration comes
from.
</P>
<P>
   `Rent' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Bring in da Noise, Bring in da Funk'
</P>
<P>
   These long-running hits touch a nerve, in part because their
young casts move onstage the way people move on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Marlies Yearby, the choreographer for ``Rent,'' is not required
to define the East Village subculture onstage with a big production
number. It is all a matter of theatricalizing natural gesture to a
rock beat. There is a mock tango, but for all its sad retelling of
the opera ``La Boheme,'' ``Rent'' is full of disco and hip-hop
rhythms, channeled into overall exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   Savion Glover, the choreographer and original star of ``Bring in
da Noise,'' took tap into a new dimension with a multilevel
exploration of a dance idiom. History _ America, blacks and tap _
is the subject. But the show is also about the new style that
Glover has developed in his brilliant dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Baakari Wilder, the virtuoso who took over Glover's role, has
the same kind of deceptive nonchalance. The footwork is emphatic
and grounded. The upper body looks relaxed: tap dancing from a new
generation.
</P>
</TEXT>
