<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: MODERNISM WITH A BIT OF HERESY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas., Minn.)   (bl)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who studied art history in college will remember H.W.
Janson's ``History of Art,'' the bible in the field for more than
three decades. In it, Janson explains what makes 20th-century
architecture distinctive: ``Modernism means aversion to decoration
for its own sake, without a trace of historicism. It favors clean
functionalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Janson devotees will be provoked by an exhibition that opened at
the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth, Texas, this week and runs
through Sept. 13. The show, ``Modernism: The Art of Design,
1880-1940,'' includes nearly 200 of the 450 pieces of decorative
arts collected by the Norwest Bank in Minneapolis since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   There are elaborate William Morris wallpaper sheets from the
1870s that depict trellises and bowers of flowers, as packed with
vegetation and as intricate as any Iznik tile. There are Alfonso
Maria Mucha's sinewy ``Flowers'' posters of 1897. There is what may
be the most lyrical bronze-plated cast-iron bank teller grill ever
designed, a tour de force by the draftsman George Grant Elmslie for
Louis H. Sullivan's National Farmers Bank, a 1908 masterpiece in
Owatonna, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   This is modernism? What happened to the Bauhaus boys: Breuer,
Mies and Gropius?
</P>
<P>
   Proving that modernism started in 1880 is one of the points of
the exhibition, which was organized by David Ryan, the curator of
collections for Norwest Corp. He was the director of the Museum of
Modern Art in Fort Worth in the late 1970s and early '80s and went
to Norwest almost by accident.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that he was invited to go to Minneapolis to see
Cesar Pelli's new 57-story office tower for Norwest in 1987, before
the building was completed. ``I was asked to kick the tires and
look at the building to see how it might be used to show art,'' he
said. ``There was not a lot of attention being devoted to how to
decorate the halls. There were high, light-filled spaces but we
didn't want to apply artworks as decals.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested starting what is still probably the only corporate
collection devoted to modern decorative and applied arts. The bank
agreed and he was retained to assemble a group of objects that
reflects design reform after 1870.
</P>
<P>
   He admits there is confusion over the terms modern, moderne,
modernist, modernism and contemporary as applied to the arts, but
for him modernism means simply the conviction to move away from
historicism and the pastiche of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Using this as his criterion, Ryan began collecting from six
distinct movements: the British and American Arts and Crafts
(1875-1915), Art Nouveau (1880-1910), Wiener Werkstatte (1903-1933)
in Vienna, De Stijl (1917-1928) in the Netherlands, Bauhaus
(1919-1933) in Germany and Art Deco in Europe and America
(1920-1940).
</P>
<P>
   Modernism, for Ryan, applies to architects, designers and
craftsmen who managed to escape historicism, the tyranny of
previous historical styles and a calcified culture. As he writes in
the introduction to the book that accompanies the exhibition,
``Modernism'' by Alastair Duncan (Antique Collectors Club),
``Centuries of servitude to revivalist design in form and
decoration were forever liberated.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan felt strongly about the collection because ``so many of the
designs that have been produced are by virtual unknowns,'' he said.
``These are designs that have never seen the light of day before
but deserve to be preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, for example, a tall, narrow sterling silver pitcher
from 1901 attributed to a Scot, Archibald Knox, and made by Liberty
&AMP; Company. It looks as streamlined as a torpedo. A hot-pink ceramic
ewer and basin, circa 1905, is attributed to George Logan, also
Scottish, for Wedgwood &AMP; Co. It has a transfer print of a Scottish
rose decoration and a chic black-and-white checkered rim.
</P>
<P>
   These designers, many of them women, shared a forward-looking
vision.``These artist-designers felt the future offered endless
possibilities,'' Ryan said. ``We look around and see endless
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, the art consultant who wrote the companion book for the
exhibition, said it was important because it was formed by a single
eye and did not focus on precious pieces. These are collectibles
that can still be found: Norman Bel Geddes skyscraper cocktail
shakers, for example, and RCA Victor portable record players.
Duncan's definition of precious is anything that costs $10,000 or
more. As he said, ``When it's over $10,000, people begin to
reconsider.''
</P>
<P>
   One sure crowd-pleaser is the deluxe model Singer vacuum cleaner
from 1938, designed by Malcolm S. Park. It is the machine as a work
of art, with a sinuous aerodynamic aluminum casing and a handle
with a shiny circle that seems meant to advertise Singer in large
capital letters.
</P>
<P>
   Other noteworthy designs in the show include examples from a
line of furniture called Holland Dutch Arts and Crafts, created by
Charles Limbert, an American furniture designer and maker who
marketed his eclectic designs in Grand Rapids, Mich. One oval table
in the show, circa 1910, has flared legs and stained oak stretchers
with cutouts that look as if they were lifted from a piece by
Charles Rennie Mackintosh.
</P>
<P>
   Another stunning piece is a laminated birch armchair designed by
Gerald Summers around 1934 for a London company, Makers of Simple
Furniture Ltd., that went out of business in 1940. Summers was one
of the few British designers in the 1930s whose works rivaled the
design greats on the Continent. He has been compared to Breuer and
Alvar Aalto.
</P>
<P>
   His chair is cut from one sheet of plywood, with certain parts
bent for armrests, others contoured to form the seat and four legs,
and another part fluidly shaped into the backrest.
</P>
<P>
   As Duncan explains in his book, the chair was commissioned for
use in tropical climates; by eliminating joinery and upholstery,
Summers avoided the problems of weakened joints and rotting caused
by extreme humidity. It is both functional and devoid of ornament,
modern in style and materials. ``As an early work of single-piece
construction,'' Duncan writes, ``it would not be equaled again for
several decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Hiesinger, the curator of decorative arts at the
Philadelphia Museum of Art, spoke at a symposium on modernism at
the Kimbell on Saturday. She pointed out that this spring there had
been exhibitions of Rene Lalique at the Cooper-Hewitt National
Design Museum in Manhattan, of Archibald Knox at the University of
Chicago and of Dagobert Peche at the Museum of Applied Arts in
Vienna. The Victoria and Albert Museum in London is planning a
large Art Nouveau component for its millennium exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   If the Paris exhibition of 1900 brought widespread acceptance to
the emerging Art Nouveau movement, perhaps it is time to study the
earliest roots of modernism as we approach the year 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
