<HEADLINE>
FROM PREP SCHOOL TO THE PROJECTS: CHECKING IN AT AGE 14 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `14 UP IN AMERICA' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showtime, Sunday night at 8 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written and produced by Vicky Bippart. Phil Joanou, narrator and
director; Marc Reshovsky, cinematographer. A Granada production in
association with the BBC. Michael Apted, Ruth Pitt, executive
producers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rich girls get your attention, as rich girls do. Lucy, Kate
and Alexis, once 7-year-old classmates at the Nightingale-Bamford
School in Manhattan, have gone their separate ways: to boarding
school in New Jersey, to a suburban public school and to Chapin.
</P>
<P>
   But here they are together again at age 14, talking to the
director and the cinematographer about subjects like divorce,
money, religion, careers and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   They are among the 16 teen-age subjects of ``14 Up in America,''
a consistently fascinating documentary that has its premiere Sunday
night at 8 on Showtime. Michael Apted, this show's co-executive
producer, started it all when he interviewed an assortment of
British 7-year-olds about their lives and turned the talks into a
1963 film called ``7 Up.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned to the same children every seven years and made a
new film each time (``42 Up'' is coming soon). The American
version, ``Age 7 in America,'' directed by Phil Joanou, won a
Peabody Award in 1991; this is its follow-up.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming message of this ``14 Up'' is how different the
teen-agers are from one another. There's Eric in Chicago,
sophisticated beyond his years, saying things like ``I have a
wonderful staff of designers'' and ``I guess I'm a good CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   He has his own business, creating Web sites for customers around
the world. In another part of Chicago, there's Leroy, who has only
recently moved out of the projects, stating his philosophy about
future romance: ``These girls nowadays can't be trusted.''
</P>
<P>
   There's Joey, who is photographed carrying his hunting rifle
(``You get kind of a rush whenever you kill a deer''), announcing
his complete lack of interest in seeing any part of the world but
his hometown, Dexter, Ga. ``I'm just going to stay around here,''
he says with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Salina, the daughter of Chinese and Vietnamese immigrants, is
bored because since ``7 Up'' she and her family have moved from Los
Angeles to a small town in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, Kennisha, who seven years ago told the camera, ``You
have to learn how to talk right'' to get ahead, now says,
``Knowledge is the key to life.''
</P>
<P>
   The children in the British ``7 Up'' series turned out to be
surprisingly prescient. Despite disappointments and detours, many
ended up doing exactly what they had predicted. When the subjects
of ``14 Up in America'' grow up, they say, they want to go into
law, medicine, science, computers, rap, basketball or comedy.
</P>
<P>
   And they all say they were happier when they were 7. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `When Trumpets Fade'
</P>
<P>
   HBO, Saturday night at 9 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The closing music for HBO's World War II drama ``When Trumpets
Fade'' is Bing Crosby singing ``White Christmas.'' But that's the
only note of forceful irony in this story of a largely forgotten
battle in Germany, that of the Hurtgen Forest, which makes the
point that even a ``good war'' is filled with senseless bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Eldard is fine as Manning, a burned-out private who keeps
getting promoted and ordered to lead other inexperienced soldiers
into harm's way, and Zak Orth stands out as one of Manning's
particularly frightened men.
</P>
<P>
   But the script, by W.W. Vought, a former industrial-video writer
and director, could have used a little originality. Fans of the
genre may be satisfied, but lines like ``Hey, Sanderson, out there
in the woods with the Krauts, what was it like?'' and ``This is
suicide!'' (shouted into the battlefield radiophone) are so
familiar they border on parody. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
