ATTN: Managing editors, weekend editors, lifestyle editors,
business editors
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following articles on jobs and the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-REVIEW-NYT _ These days, it seems people are trying to
be all they can and must be at the office, as the workplace has
become an increasingly popular but elusive spot to look for meaning
and fulfillment in life. It's fine to take the road less traveled,
as long as it means finding a less-congested route to get to the
office earlier. By Adam Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   JOB-HUNTING-HNS (San Francisco) _ Every job hunting guru will
tell you that understanding a company and an industry is crucial,
especially when you're applying for a job. Vault Reports of New
York publishes employer profiles _ some longer than 50 pages _ plus
industry guides based on more than 25,000 surveys and interviews
with workers. By Dave Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS _ The workplace of the 1990s might seem
threatening to Boomers. Generation Xers, by contrast, have
experienced little else but change. By Diane Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   GRADS-CONSULT-BOS (Undated) _ When Eric Moffett graduated from
Princeton University last year with a degree in economics, the
Houston native knew he wanted to be a businessman. Rather than
choose an industry, however, Moffett took what is becoming a more
familiar road for recent college graduates: He became a consultant.
By Chana Schoenberger.
</P>
<P>
   ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN (Kansas City) _ A disclaimer: Generalizations
and stereotypes follow. You've been warned. I spent a day last week
at a management training seminar in which a communication expert
talked about all the reasons why men are from Mars and women are
from Venus. Or is it the other way around? No, it wasn't the guy
who wrote that book _ which, by the way, I heaved across my bedroom
floor in frustration at the apparently intractable gender
differences. The speaker was another ``he said vs. she said''
author//researcher, who said the brains of men and women appear to
be hard-wired differently to begin with. Then we spend our
formative years playing different kinds of games that push us
further apart. Then we go to work. By Diane Stafford.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN-HNS (Undated) _ Running your own business can be
rough, but it's doubly hard when your clients are a group of
unhappy people. Documented Reference Check is in the business of
checking references. By L.M. Sixel.
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMITH-SPI (Undated) _ Bosses have long
suspected their workers are getting less loyal. Now there is
evidence. According to a study released this week, American workers
are less committed to their employers and more likely to switch
jobs for small increases in pay, a trend that is making it
increasingly difficult for companies to hang on to their best
employees in a tight labor market. By Carol Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
