<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE ART: BY PICASSO, FROM HIS MUSE; MAGRITTE, SEPARATELY; AT
ARTISTS SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dora Maar, the photographer and painter who was Picasso's lover,
died last summer, with no survivors and no will. But Maar, who was
the principal model for many of Picasso's so-called weeping women
portraits, left an important collection of paintings, drawings and
artifacts, predominantly by Picasso, that is conservatively
estimated to be worth $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   So the French government, as it does in cases like this, brought
in a state-certified genealogist to try to determine whether any
relatives, no matter how distant, were still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Two were discovered, although their names have not been released
to the public. These mystery beneficiaries are to receive the
proceeds of a sale of the collection, to be held on Oct. 27, 28 and
29 at Maison de la Chime in Paris. Two French auction houses _
Mathias and Piasa _ will be holding the sale together.
</P>
<P>
   Piasa is now affiliated with Phillips, the London-based auction
house that also has premises in New York, so a selection of works
in the sale will be on view there from Sept. 25 to 28.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights are seven portraits Picasso painted of
Maar. Some of the most important include ``Crying Woman'' (1937),
one of many studies for ``Guernica,'' which is expected to sell at
$2.5 million to $3.3 million; ``Dora Maar Straight On With Green
Nails'' (1936), expected to bring $3.3 million to $5 million, and
``Seated Profile of Dora Maar'' (1936), which carries an estimate
of $1.3 million to $1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   There are also dozens of drawings and small objects, like a
matchbox on which Picasso drew and stones that he carved when the
couple went to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Lucien Solanet, a partner of Piasa, said the sale was unusual
because it included ``all kinds of personal items like books that
Picasso had made notes and drawings in, jewelry and even a
champagne cork he had decorated.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Blondeau, the former director of Sotheby's in Paris who is
acting as a consultant for the sale, said that while he was
examining the property, he could ``really feel the passion between
these two human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was so totally in love with him that these things were
like her fetishes,'' Blondeau added.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's and Christie's expend a considerable amount of effort
trying to get French property to sell in London or New York; they
are eagerly waiting for the European Union to open the French
auction market to other Europeans and Americans, a change expected
to take place this fall.
</P>
<P>
   But given the French government's involvement in the Maar
estate, it is not surprising that two French auction houses were
chosen to sell the property.
</P>
<P>
   Under French rules, selling in Paris, rather than in London or
New York, gives French museums first crack at works of art.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be like the duke and duchess of Windsor sale, but
with more substance,'' Blondeau said. ``Rather than shopping at
Cartier, she shopped at Picasso.''
</P>
<P>
   Magritte, Separately
</P>
<P>
   The cover of the July-August issue of Christie's Magazine shows
a surreal scene: a naked woman against a cloudy sky with a white
bird on her shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   It is from one of a series of eight paintings called ``The
Enchanted Domain,'' studies Rene Magritte made for a monumental
surrealist mural in the Casino Communal at Knokke-le Zoute in
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   The paintings have been on and off the market for 17 years, but
each time, they were offered together, as one work. Now, for the
first time, each will be available for sale individually at
Christie's in London on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   That the paintings are not being kept together has caused a good
deal of debate among art experts in the United States and
elsewhere. Many believe that the paintings should not be separated.
The seller, an unidentified American businessman, bought the suite
purely as an investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about break-up value,'' said a New York dealer, who
spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``It's questionable
art-historically not to sell them together. It goes against the
artist's wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   The group first came on the market at Christie's in New York on
May 19, 1981, where it failed to sell. At the time, Georgette
Magritte, the artist's widow, stipulated that the works be sold as
a single lot, in accordance with her husband's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   From there they went through various dealers' hands and ended up
at the Fuji Gallery in Japan, with a price tag of $14 million to
$16 million for the group. But again no one wanted them. They were
also exhibited in New York on behalf of Fuji. The suite was finally
sold to the man who is Christie's seller next month.
</P>
<P>
   The paintings, which are takeoffs on some of the artist's
cliched subjects, are expected to sell at $600,000 to $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   At Artists Space
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the eve of the 25th anniversary of Artists Space
in September, the nonprofit institution at 38 Greene St. in SoHo
has big plans.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a series of special exhibitions beginning in the
fall, and the publication of a book, ``5,000 Artists Return to
Artists Space: 25 Years,'' in November. The alternative space is
also opening a new gallery at its present site, to be called
Project Space II. It will feature the work of New York-based
artists in shows that will change every month.
</P>
<P>
   That's not all. Artists Space also plans to revive its
long-standing practice of making small grants to artists who live
in New York City and whose proposed project will take place there,
too. The grants, discontinued in 1991 for want of money, will
consist of 20 $500 awards to artists and groups of artists who
propose projects in nontraditional, noncommercial public venues.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are modest grants to encourage artists to do projects
outside of the structure,'' said Claudia Gould, director of Artists
Space.
</P>
<P>
   Grant applications, which will be awarded on a lottery basis
three times a year, will be available at Artists Space beginning on
Sept. 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
