<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, June 26, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(ja) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hottest day so far the year will occur in parts of the
Northeast and Middle Atlantic States as increasing breezes from the
southwest import part of the torrid air mass that is been over the
South and Middle West.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of increasing heat and oppressive humidity near
the ground and some cooling aloft will set the stage for clusters
of strong thunderstorms over much of the region. A front moving
slowly south through New England will be the focus for heavy
showers and thunderstorms during much of the day. Farther south,
potent thunderstorms, some with high winds and hail, will erupt
during the heat of the afternoon and evening.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Southeast will remain hot and humid with ample
sunshine. A few isolated afternoon thunderstorms may for near the
southern Appalachians and southern Florida. Meanwhile, bands of
clouds and heavy showers swirling around a tropical disturbance
will swipe coastal Texas and Louisiana. Onshore winds will increase
near the western Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Searing heat will persist from western Texas to the central
Plains. Strengthening low pressure over the Dakotas promote some
strong afternoon thunderstorms near the northern Missouri Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonably cool air will rush across the Northwest and
northern Rockies, where clouds and showers will be abundant,
especially over the higher terrain. The highest elevations of the
Bitterroots and northern Cascades will have some wet snow.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HEAT WAVE
</P>
<P>
   A record maximum of 99 degrees was recorded in Little Rock,
Ark., on Wednesday and some residents wondered if this would
constitute a heat wave. There is no official definition of a heat
wave, but in the Northeast, when the mercury rises above 90 degrees
for three consecutive days in Boston or New York, it would be
considered a heat wave. But in Little Rock or Dallas, where the
normal summer maximums rise above 90, an even higher threshold is
required for a heat wave. Melbourne, Fla., which has now set 14
consecutive record highs, is clearly in the midst of a great heat
wave. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
