<SLUG> BC-JESSE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEAR JESSE': APPROPRIATING HELMS AS A FOIL AND FELLOW TRAVELER 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time the documentary ``Dear Jesse'' comes to an end, one
question above all seems to press for an answer: Is this film,
written and directed by Tim Kirkman, likely to change any voter's
mind about Jesse Helms, the conservative Republican who has
represented North Carolina in the Senate since 1972?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Jesse'' is a combination of road movie, personal
exploration, lament for lost love and political statement. What it
is not is a serious journalistic inquiry that might actually
provide a reasoned, fact-based argument for replacing a lawmaker
who has been elected time and again, though never by more than a
slim majority.
</P>
<P>
   So those who already abhor Helms for his outspoken opposition to
homosexuality, abortion, affirmative action and government
financing for the arts and AIDS research are likely to find the
senator to be the Devil they already knew. And those who, as the
film shows in its interviews, find him acceptable because he is
predictable and, as one man says, trustworthy, will encounter
nothing to shake their support.
</P>
<P>
   When it is suggested that big business, including the tobacco
industry, lies behind Helms' success, ``Dear Jesse'' makes no
effort to pursue the assertion. Intrepid journalism is not its
strong point.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the interviews in the documentary are with people like
Mike Nelson, the gay mayor of Carrboro, N.C.; a lesbian couple and
the single mother of a biracial HIV-positive child. All would have
good reason to oppose the senator. In the end, ``Dear Jesse''
amounts to little more than a succession of man- and
woman-in-the-street interviews.
</P>
<P>
   At his most witty, Kirkman, addressing himself to Helms, says:
``For a long time, I thought we had nothing in common, but I
realize now I was wrong. You and I were both born in Monroe, North
Carolina, and raised as Southern Baptists. We both attended Wingate
College for one year each before transferring to other schools.
We've also both worked in journalism and radio broadcasting. But I
believe we have a more significant similarity _ for most of your 24
years in the U.S. Senate, you've been obsessed with homosexual men;
for most of my adult life, so have I.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, after a breakup with his lover in New York City and as
Helms was announcing plans to run again, Kirkman returned to North
Carolina to film ``Dear Jesse'' and to come to terms with his gay
identity and his loss while visiting home and attending a college
reunion. The personal elements of the film make an uneasy fit with
its political message.
</P>
<P>
   Helms was re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   DEAR JESSE
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Tim Kirkman; produced by Mary Beth Mann;
released by Cowboy Booking International. At Cinema Village, 22
East 12th St., Greenwich Village. Running time: 82 minutes. This
film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Tim Kirkman, Sen. Jesse Helms and residents of North
Carolina. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
