A7082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FISHKIN-THEATER-REVIE     06-25 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHKIN-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OEDIPUS, SHMEDIPUS: GIVE 'EM A HAPPY ENDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The heyday of Yiddish theater on Second Avenue may
long be over, but the time machine that is the new musical ``The
Fishkin Touch'' is up, running and ready to transport theatergoers
back to that storied past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fishkin Touch'' may not be ``My Fair Lady,'' but this
workmanlike show provides plenty of entertainment by means of a
solid cast, bright lyrics, a plot filled with heartache, heartburn
and romance, and some genuinely funny moments.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much in the way of dancing, the music may not set
the toes to tapping, and the plot resolutions are so foreseeable
that they can seem a long time coming; but ``The Fishkin Touch,''
which closes the 1997-98 season of the Jewish Repertory Theater,
will send a lot of people home happy.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a story by Greg Armbruster, who wrote the music, and
Lenore Skenazy, who wrote the estimable lyrics, ``The Fishkin
Touch,'' with a book by David Javerbaum, revolves around the the
Fishkin Playhouse in 1910.
</P>
<P>
   With its guarantee of ``a happy ending or your money back,'' the
Fishkin troupe stars the conceited Boris Fishkin (Mike Burstyn), a
combination of ladies' man and mama's boy who is growing a bit too
long in the tooth for some of his roles.
</P>
<P>
   This may not matter in his version of ``Oedipus Rex,'' where his
wife happily turns out not to be his mother; but in ``The Scarlet
Aleph'' or when, as Romeo McCoy, he sings of love to the ``Jew, Jew
Juliet,'' his age is becoming a problem.
</P>
<P>
   His troupe, which includes the warmhearted Sophie (Carolann
Page), one of Boris's old flames, and his domineering and conniving
mother, Zelda (Joan Copeland), could use some fresh blood. Ah, but
the bachelor Boris, it seems, has no heirs; and his theatrical
magic, which he refers to as the Fishkin touch, seems destined to
die with him.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Boris cannot pass it along to the company's newest
member, young Reuben (Jordan Leeds), the actor and aspiring
playwright fresh from the Old World bearing secrets, because he and
Reuben are fundamentally at odds.
</P>
<P>
   The serious Reuben objects to Boris's tampering with classics to
produce happy endings, and soon they part ways, with Reuben forming
a rival company, where his ``Cinderella'' has him jamming his
heroine's foot into workman's boots and singing that ``glass
slippers cannot take the masses where we want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Reuben is soon waiting on tables at the
restaurant where Boris breakfasts and falling in love with the
manager, Rachel (Beth Thompson), whom he rightly suspects would
love to be an actress.
</P>
<P>
   At last, the stage is set for the machinations that compel Boris
to produce Reuben's play, despite its unhappy ending, and for the
assortment of revelations that produce the altogether happy
conclusion of ``The Fishkin Touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Burstyn, whose Broadway credits include ``Barnum,'' revels in
the hammier aspects of Boris's character. Ms. Copeland, whose
award-winning roles include Vera in ``Pal Joey'' and Rose Baum in
``The American Clock,'' hits heights of humor when at last she is
alone with the consequences of her deviousness.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Page makes Sophie a pillar of comfort and love. Ms. Thompson
furnishes the perky romantic charm and dauntless optimism her role
requires. And with his singing and acting, Leeds, seen on Broadway
in ``Les Miserables'' and in previous Jewish Repertory Company
productions, provides ``The Fishkin Touch'' with its essential
chemistry and glue. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE FISHKIN TOUCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Book by David Javerbaum; music by Greg Armbruster; lyrics by
Lenore Skenazy; directed by Alan Fox; original story by Armbruster
and Ms. Skenazy; sets by Craig Clipper; costumes by Gail
Cooper-Hecht; lighting by Robert Williams; sound by Josh
Bender-Dubiel; production stage manager, Ruth E. Kramer; musical
director, Christopher McGovern; production supervisor, Harris
Production Services. Presented by the Jewish Repertory Theater, Ran
Avni, artistic director; Michael Lichtenstein, managing director,
in association with the 92d Street Y. At Playhouse 91, 316 East
91st Street, Manhattan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Mike Burstyn (Boris Fishkin), Joan Copeland (Zelda
Fishkin), Carolann Page (Sophie), Jordan Leeds (Reuben) and Beth
Thompson (Rachel). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
