r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENEZUELA-TAR26-COX     06-25 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-TAR26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Venezuela tar fuel banned in Florida
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ Florida officials slammed the tanker door shut on
a controversial tar fuel from Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Cabinet officials decisively rejected Orimulsion recently after
years of back-and-forth debate over whether it should be burned in
a U.S. power plant for the first time. Hundreds of sign-carrying,
button-wearing partisans on both sides of the issue overflowed the
Capitol meeting room.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-1 vote stands to cost a Boca Raton company, Bitor America
Corp., $160 million a year. It is ready to fill a contract with
Florida Power &AMP; Light Co. to supply the fuel to a Manatee County
power plant from Bitor's parent Venezuelan exporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 3.5 million customers of FPL are the real losers,'' said
Juan Pulgar, president of Bitor America, referring to claims
customers would save up to five percent on their power bills over
the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   It was a big victory for environmental groups who said the
potential savings were not worth poorly-understood risks of water
and air pollution. CSX Corp., a coal shipper with an economic
interest in stopping Orimulsion, helped coordinate opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cabinet system works,'' said a jubilant Tom Reese,
attorney for ManaSota88, a group opposing FPL's plan. Unlike most
other states, Florida has an elected Cabinet that rules on issues
such as power-plant proposals.
</P>
<P>
   FPL, owned by FPL Group Inc. of Juno Beach, said it would
actually reduce sulphur and other emissions by burning the gooey
mixture of bitumen and water in its Manatee County plant and
perhaps later in other plants including Indiantown in Martin
County. FPL said it will consider an appeal to the First District
Court of Appeal in Tallahassee on the grounds the Cabinet did not
properly show why it is turning down the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we're very disappointed,'' said FPL President Paul
Evanson. ``We'll have to look at the order and make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote was the clearest rebuff yet by the Cabinet in three
cracks on Orimulsion, interspersed with rulings by an
administrative law judge who twice approved FPL's plan.
</P>
<P>
   It is backed by a 50-page order detailing what FPL has failed to
show about nitrogen oxide emissions and other possible
environmental dangers.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Commissioner Bob Crawford cast the lone vote for
Orimulsion without comment.
</P>
<P>
   One Cabinet member who supported Orimulsion in two previous
votes said public opinion was running so strongly against it that
she was changing her vote even though she found FPL's plan
reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the facts seem to support this application, the people
don't,'' Secretary of State Sandra Mortham said.
</P>
<P>
   Calls and mail to her office ran against Orimulsion 100-1, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people have spoken to me on this issue, and my job is to
listen,'' Mortham said, a former state representative from the
Tampa Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Katherine Harris, who is trying to tar Mortham with
the Orimulsion issue in the Republican primary for Secretary of
State, claimed credit for her opponent's change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased that phone calls generated by my television ad
played a role in Sandy Mortham's decision to changer her position
on this critical issue,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Education Commissioner Frank Brogan said what bothered him was
that Venezuela does not burn the fuel within its own borders.
</P>
<P>
   Pulgar said that is because Venezuela's needs are 70 percent met
by hydroelectric power and most of the rest by natural gas that is
a byproduct of the nation's oil drilling and refining.
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-24-98 1956E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
