<HEADER>
A7088 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENCOMPASS-OPERA-REVIE     06-25 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENCOMPASS-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPERA REVIEW: CHARACTER STUDIES FROM THREE COMPOSERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Encompass Music Theater, a company that
specializes in contemporary American chamber opera, and the Amas
Musical Theater, a group devoted to multicultural programming, have
joined forces for an inventive and mostly pleasing triple bill at
the Salon Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The three works _ Dominick Argento's ``Miss Havisham's Wedding
Night'' (1981), Victor Kioulaphides' ``Ocean Dream'' (1992) and
Arif Mardin's ``I Will Wait'' _ share a fascination with the
psychological dynamic of a single central character.
</P>
<P>
   In the Argento work, which is based on a character in Dickens'
``Great Expectations,'' that dynamic is madness and subtle
malevolence. Miss Havisham, abandoned on her wedding day, smashed
all her clocks and has been roaming her house dressed in her
wedding gown for decades. Argento treated this material more
extensively in ``Miss Havisham's Fire,'' a full-length work that
was performed at the New York City Opera a few years before he
composed this extended mad scene.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Wedding Night,'' which has a libretto by John
Olon-Scrymgeour, Miss Havisham relives her wedding day, confronts
an apparition meant to be Matt, her departed beau, and in the end
settles down for an afternoon with young Estella, telling her,
``Now let us drink our tea, and I will tell you all about men.''
</P>
<P>
   Argento is more sensitive to the natural limitations of the
voice than many contemporary composers; but he is also unafraid to
stretch a singer's limits, and in this work he has kept the great
Donizetti and Bellini mad scenes in mind. This proves a wonderful
star turn for Elizabeth Keusch. At the Wednesday evening
performance, she had both the vocal power and color and the
dramatic flexibility to make Miss Havisham alternately pitiful and
terrifying.
</P>
<P>
   Kioulaphides and Mardin look at healthier developments. In
``Ocean Dream,'' which has a libretto by Nancy Rhodes (who also
directed the three works and is artistic director of the Encompass
company), a young woman at the beach discovers her inner child and
becomes a more integrated personality. We have to take her word for
this: the work offers no sense of her back story.
</P>
<P>
   Kioulaphides' music is accessible and lush, and draws
occasionally on Baroque and Renaissance elements. Malaika Sims was
energetic and agile as the child, and Leah Fitschen sang the
woman's music with the right proportions of anxiety and sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   Mardin, who is best known as a producer of jazz and pop
recordings for Atlantic Records, wrote his own libretto for ``I
Will Wait,'' a look at the transition from life to afterlife. The
central character, an unnamed young man, has died but resists
moving on despite the entreaties of his already dead wife, who
sings that they can now be together forever.
</P>
<P>
   Mardin is at his best in music that draws on exotic sources; the
atonal and angular sections don't work as well, and even given the
subject, the vocal music is often too overwrought. Juliana
Janes-Yaffe gave the sometimes overwrought Young Woman's music a
fair spin; a few vocal dry patches marred Kyle Pfortmiller's
account of the Young Man.
</P>
<P>
   John Kochansky, the set designer, put abstract paintings and
whimsical elements at the service of the works at hand. A chamber
orchestra, conducted by John Yaffe provided polished accompaniments
for the Argento and Kioulaphides works, but was less consistent in
the Mardin score.
</P>
<P>
   The performances continue through Sunday at the Salon Theater,
432 E. 91st St., Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1743EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
