<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEATS-BREWER26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BREWER'S DEFENSE IMPRESSES HEAT WITH 51ST PICK
 &HT;    By TOM D'ANGELO
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ For most second-round picks, the odds of making the NBA
are overwhelming. And although Corey Brewer will have a difficult
time sticking with the Miami Heat, he does have one advantage: He
could be the second-best point guard on the team during training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat selected Brewer, a 6-foot-2 point guard from Oklahoma,
with the 51st pick in Wednesday's draft. Brewer was rated as high
as No.3 on some point guard lists, below No.2 pick Mike Bibby and
Florida's Jason Williams, the seventh overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think we need more support at that position and any time
you get a player who has the skills this guy has and defensive
ability, I think you got to pick him,'' Heat coach Pat Riley said.
``He will defend the ball better than anybody in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hardaway is the only true point guard on the Heat's roster.
Backup Eric Murdock is a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer is noted for his defense and toughness, but struggled
with turnovers and was sometimes used as a shooting guard. He
averaged 20.8 points last season but shot just .428 in his two
seasons at Oklahoma. He was an honorable mention All-America and
first-team All-Big 12 as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kid is one of the hardest playing, hard-nosed,
tough-minded competitors,'' Riley said. ``He's a real, real
winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said Miami had three players it was interested in when it
came the Heat's time to pick.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat had to wait more than three hours after the draft
started to participate after trading their first-round pick in
February to the Clippers in the Isaac Austin-for-Brent Barry deal.
</P>
<P>
   If Miami had retained the pick, it would have had a choice
between 6-10 Brian Skinner (22nd to the Clippers), point guard
Tyronn Lue (23rd to Denver), guard Felipe Lopez (24th to San
Antonio), guard Corey Benjamin (28th to Chicago) and center Nazr
Mohammed (29th to Utah), among others.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said the Heat inquired about moving up in the second round
but, ``it's ridiculous what teams want for second-round picks,'' he
said. The Heat did not make a serious effort to get into the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   Among the higher-rated players available when the Heat finally
selected were point guard Anthony Carter of Hawaii; forwards Corey
Lewis of Florida State and J.R. Henderson of UCLA; and center Brad
Miller of Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   (endit)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-25-98 0007E
</P>
