<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7090 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STODA-COLUMN26-COX     06-25 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STODA-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA DRAFT A TRUE CLINIC IN INEXACT SCIENCE
 &HT;    By GREG STODA
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the NBA college draft (and, hey, it's really a high
school/college/around-the-world draft) is so important, how come
the so-called lottery teams _ the ones with the most advantageous
positions for making selections _ look so familiar year after year
after year?
</P>
<P>
   Because, by deductive reasoning, the draft isn't all that
important. The typical exercise results in some kid going to a bad
team, making little or no difference and falling into the
monotonous rut of losing season after losing season.
</P>
<P>
   There is, after all, only so much a Michael Olowokandi can do
for the Los Angeles Clippers. Or a Mike Bibby for the Vancouver
Grizzlies. Or a Raef LaFrentz for the Denver Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   Think there's a sudden rush for playoff tickets in any of those
cities?
</P>
<P>
   None of it makes any sense, really.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, you think it made sense that Antawn Jamison
and Vince Carter, recent teammates at North Carolina, were traded
for each other after being picked back-to-back by the Toronto
Raptors and Golden State Warriors, respectively, during Wednesday
night's annual shopfest.
</P>
<P>
   And, no, there's not much Jamison or Carter can do for Toronto
or Golden State, either, regardless of which player is in which
place.
</P>
<P>
   Go right on down the list of the evening's player-to-franchise
weddings, and you'll find not one union that is a sure thing to
improve a downtrodden team to any significant extent.
</P>
<P>
   (Oh, sure, Tim Duncan popped up in the first spot last year and
made a better team of San Antonio, but that was something of an
aberration. The Spurs had averaged 54-plus wins per season for the
previous eight years before injuries dropped them to a 20-62 record
just before Duncan's arrival.)
</P>
<P>
   The truth of the matter is that for all the scouting reports and
all the workouts private and public, the draft is hardly an exact
science.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for perfect example, the case of Olowokandi, a 7-footer
who grew up in England the son of a Nigerian diplomat and has been
playing basketball for only three years. He attended the University
of the Pacific only because he called an assistant coach at the
school, and told him he was interested in playing there.
</P>
<P>
   You have to wonder how that conversation went, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello. My name is Michael Olowokandi. I'm calling from
England. I'm very tall. I would like to come play basketball at
your school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, right. But just for fun, Mr. Candy, how tall are you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is Olowokandi. O-L-O-W-O-K-A-N-D-I. I am 7 feet tall.
I have set jumping records in track in England, and I am a good
soccer player, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Spell that again, give me your number, and don't lose this
one. Don't call anyone else, either. We'll get right back to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why someone like Heat boss Pat Riley wants no part of
the high-priced, high-risk guesswork involved with the draft.
Besides, Riley regards NBA rookies with the same disdain he
reserves for soft defense.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, since arriving in South Florida prior to the 1995-96
season, it should come as no surprise that Riley has been almost
completely uninvolved in first-round speculation.
</P>
<P>
   He did trade for Utah's first-round selection (Martin Muursepp)
in 1996, but soon thereafter packaged him with Kurt Thomas (the
Heat's first-round pick in 1995) and Sasha Danilovic in exchange
for Dallas' Jamal Mashburn. He drafted Charles Smith out of New
Mexico in last year's first round, but quickly traded him and Ike
Austin plus this year's first-round selection for Brent Barry of
the Los Angeles Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   So, for all practical purposes, the Heat's first-rounders during
Riley's regime have been Mashburn and Barry.
</P>
<P>
   As inexact science goes, that's not bad.
</P>
<P>
   (endit)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-25-98 0012E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
