<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7091 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEDDING-INSURANCE26-C     06-25 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEDDING-INSURANCE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WEDDING PLANNERS SAY `I DO' TO NEW INSURANCE
 &HT;    By LYNDA EDWARDS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tell a couple that a certain day positively, absolutely must be
the happiest day of their life _ and an audience of friends and
relatives will be watching for happiness verification _ and you've
got the makings of a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what happens every June wedding season. And this can
mean trouble for brides, grooms and the people tapped to make
matrimony happen.
</P>
<P>
   This wedding season, though, there is protection of sorts; last
fall, the Florida Department of Insurance approved the sale of
wedding insurance.
</P>
<P>
   When a high-end wedding goes wrong in Palm Beach County, the
wedding consultant is vulnerable to a lawsuit from an irate bride
or groom, says Gayle Lebenow, a West Palm Beach-based events
planner and Florida Coordinator of the National Association of
Bridal Consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Weddings can be competitive, Lebenow says, with parents
comparing the flowers, the dresses, the food and the decorations.
``If there's a glitch'', she says, ``their enemies notice as well
as friends, so what the bride usually sues for is emotional
distress and mental suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   The policies are underwritten by Fireman's Fund Insurance, which
has covered about 5,000 weddings since it created the concept in
1992. Other companies offer, for a one-shot fee, ``weather
insurance,'' which covers cancellation of an event due to rain or
snow.
</P>
<P>
   Wedding insurance, however, covers everything from a stained
wedding dress to bitter cake icing.
</P>
<P>
   And bridal consultants have seen it all.
</P>
<P>
   One bride sued her wedding planner because pink flowers were
used in a flower girl's basket, said Gerard Monaghan, president of
the National Association of Bridal Consultants. The bride wanted
white. The florist corrected the error before the ceremony but the
bride claimed she was traumatized by her attendants' tittering.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, concerns are mostly weather related.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 300 to 400 requests out of Florida last hurricane
season,'' said California-based Robert Nuccio, the sole
administrator assigned to Fireman's wedding insurance program. He
won't say how much money wedding insurance brings Fireman's, ``but
this is not a moneymaker.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do it for the publicity, to be honest,'' he said. ``Too
many things can go wrong in a wedding due to the emotionally
charged nature of the day. We have to pay out fairly often.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest amount Fireman's Fund had to pay in Florida was a
``half-million dollars for host liquor liability,'' Nuccio says.
``Someone got drunk and into an accident on the way home from the
wedding.'' The guest not only sued the newlyweds and their planner
but the deejay and photographer as well. The plaintiff blamed them
for contributing to the merriment that prompted him to knock back
cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   A fee of $3,500 gets the payer $200,000 worth of wedding
insurance coverage. The simplest, cheapest deal is a $200 policy
that reimburses the buyer $3,000 in case of a wedding cancellation
due to weather, dresses not arriving on time, the photographer
failing to show up or ``any reason other than change of heart on
the part of the bride or groom,'' said Nuccio. (Even Lloyds of
London, which insures everything from starlets' legs to zoos,
wouldn't touch that. Too much chance of collusion between phony
lovebirds.)
</P>
<P>
   Photographers, too, should consider wedding insurance, says
Patrick Lyons, vice president of the Wedding Professionals of
Central Florida. Lyons says a bride refused to pay him because a
woman she no longer liked was in one picture.
</P>
<P>
   One uninsured wedding consultant had to restage three weddings
at her own expense when the photographer she had contracted snapped
abysmal pictures. It cost her more than $8,000 to re-bake the three
cakes, duplicate the decors and transport guests back to pose and
mimic mistiness, surprise and delight before a new lensman.
</P>
<P>
   Nuccio's individual client list is confidential. He can state
that institutions, such as the Lowe Art Museum at the University of
Miami, buy the policies at the urging of their risk managers when
weddings are held there. If a drunken guest tumbles into a
sculpture, the museum can recoup.
</P>
<P>
   But the most frequent reason a claim is filed for lavish
weddings? ``It's because dad loses his job and can't pay for the
scheduled wedding, even in this boom-boom economy,'' Nuccio says.
``We paid a ton of money out when Xerox downsized.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the truest test of love is that it survives a bad wedding.
One way to ease jitters is to remember that if this really were the
happiest day of a couple's life, the marriage would then be an
anticlimax.
</P>
<P>
   ``The couples who have the best times are the ones who believe
that the best is yet to come,'' Lebenow says. ``And that mind-set
is a result of personality, not money.''
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-24-98 1614E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
