<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7092 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRISP-THEATER-REVIEW-     06-25 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRISP-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRISP, SO STYLISHLY 89, GETS TO THE POINT, WELL, CRISPLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ People may think Quentin Crisp is joking when he
says, ``I never read books; I wait for it all to be on
television.'' On Wednesday night, during the question-and-answer
period of ``An Evening With Quentin Crisp,'' someone tested him by
asking just what shows he watched. `` `Homicide,' `The Practice,'
`Brooklyn South,''' he said. ``I like the programs that threaten
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he has been asked that question a thousand times and
answered the same way. Maybe, in fact, Crisp's new two-hour
production does not contain a single sentence that he has not
already used elsewhere. But if so, no one seemed to care. As those
NBC advertisements say, pushing the network's reruns this summer,
it's new to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Evening With Quentin Crisp,'' which continues Wednesdays
through Sundays through July 5, is a delight. It is also a low-key
affair. In the cozy setting of the Grove Street Playhouse, it's a
little like sitting at the feet of a favorite professor. There's a
lot of affection in the air, and the acolytes sometimes have to
strain to hear the words of wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Crisp sits in a gilt-accented chair beside a small table that
holds a vase of plump pink roses. (Well, he does stand up once, to
do an imitation of Eva Peron.) He wears a black velvet suit, a
wide-brimmed gray hat, an ascot-style scarf and a large, glittery
pin. He will be 90 in December, but the only sign of possible
frailty is an occasional cough.
</P>
<P>
   Crisp devotes much of the first act to his recommendations for
achieving style, a subject he knows a good deal about. Some of his
tips: Get rid of everything in your house or apartment that doesn't
represent who you are.
</P>
<P>
   (``You should regard your home as your dressing room.'') Do not
take any evening classes, unless they are in singing or dancing.
Live alone. Try not to get stuck in a job in which you deal only
with ``things,'' even if those things are books or sculptures. Take
up one of the stylish professions: teaching, acting, preaching.
Most important, ``You have to take a long, hard look at what your
friends call `the trouble with you.''' Use it. Then ``polish up
your identity until it becomes a style.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's second act is devoted completely to questions from
the audience, so each night's performance is different, at least
hypothetically. On Wednesday night, he ended up talking about his
admiration for Elizabeth Taylor, his bad reviews in San Francisco,
a recent visit to David Hare's play ``The Judas Kiss'' and why no
one in England goes to the gym.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was asked his opinion of Noel Coward. Avoiding a
thumbs-up or thumbs-down assessment, Crisp said simply that Coward
``wrote lines that actresses liked to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Crisp, who has made a career of being quotable, in books like
``The Naked Civil Servant'' and ``How to Become a Virgin,'' writes
lines that audiences love to repeat. ``Beauty is a complete waste
of time,'' he said. ``Style begets style.'' And ``I am so old that
I can remember when Bette Davis was a nice girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course it's a little hard to work that last one into a
conversation. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AN EVENING WITH QUENTIN CRISP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sets by Rob Wolin; lighting by Scott Davis; production stage
manager, Louis Lopardi; stage manager, Teresa Fischer. Presented by
the Glines. At the Grove Street Playhouse, 39 Grove Street,
Greenwich Village.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Quentin Crisp. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
