<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVY-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT     06-25 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVY-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ ARTISTS GATHER TO HONOR THEIR MANAGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jazz history has yielded so many tales of strife-torn
relationships between artists and their business associates that
when performers of the stature of Joe Williams, George Shearing,
Shirley Horn and Nancy Wilson gather to honor a happy long-term
relationship with a manager, attention is due.
</P>
<P>
   The man whom they celebrated at a Beacon Theater concert on
Monday evening as part of the JVC Jazz Festival is John Levy, the
86-year-old former bass player with Stuff Smith who has been
managing artists since 1951. One after another, Levy's clients
rhapsodized about their trust in him and the personal attention he
has devoted to their careers. Levy came briefly to the stage at one
point.
</P>
<P>
   Although the tributes being offered seemed genuinely heartfelt,
the musical aspect of the evening was decidedly uneven. Williams
was by far the most exuberant performer, but his abbreviated set at
the end of the show left the audience hungry for more. This great
swing and blues vocalist, who will turn 80 in December, remains in
full command of a rangy bass-baritone voice that is equally
striking crooning a ballad (a nostalgic ``Trust in Me'' that showed
off the mellow expansiveness of his upper register) or swinging out
in a rich, husky blues bark (``Muddy Water,'' done as a
call-and-response with the audience).
</P>
<P>
   Shearing, accompanied by his longtime bassist, Neil Swainson,
dug way back to unearth a jump tune, ``Strolling,'' composed by
Levy in 1949. The pianist's spare, careful renditions of songs like
his own neatly patterned ``Conception'' and of the Billie
Holiday-associated ``That Old Devil Called Love'' had an almost
dainty precision and reminded one of the garden-party gentility of
so much English jazz in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Horn, at her best, transforms songs into lingering jazz-pop
meditations in which her pianism and quiet husky singing seamlessly
weave together to cast a spell. But at Monday's concert, in which
she performed two ballads (``Close Enough for Love'' and ``Where Do
You Start?'') and one uptempo song (``Fever''), Ms. Horn lost the
thread of the lyrics more than once, and the aura of concentrated
emotional intensity that she can bring to a song flickered only
intermittently.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Wilson, who ended the first half of the evening with the
show's longest set, can't be faulted for lack of concentration. But
her extremely mannered renditions of signature songs like ``Guess
Who I Saw Today'' substituted eccentrically flashy dynamics (half
whispered interpolations and abrupt yodeling whoops at the ends of
phrases) for considered lyrical readings.
</P>
<P>
   One of the brighter segments of the evening was a set by the
partly reconstituted Cannonball Adderley quintet, led by Vincent
Herring on saxophone and Longineu Parsons (substituting for the
ailing Nat Adderley) on trumpet. The set featured two upbeat
favorites, ``Jive Samba'' and ``The Work Song.''
</P>
<P>
   The pianist and jazz educator Billy Taylor and Nicole Yarling, a
singer and jazz violinist who is a recent addition to Levy's client
roster, opened the festivities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
