<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7096 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORRIS-DANCE-REVIEW-5     06-25 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORRIS-DANCE-REVIEW-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MEDIUM': MOURNING SCHUBERT WITH OBLIQUE SIMPLICITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mark Morris Dance Group returned to the Brooklyn
Academy of Music on Wednesday night with Morris' familiar staging
of Purcell's miniopera ``Dido and Aeneas'' and the New York
premiere of ``Medium.''
</P>
<P>
   The new work radiates a tantalizing, even mesmerizing,
simplicity that should not be equated with directness. Levels of
meaning seem to hang in the air in a complicit dialogue between the
choreography and the music by the contemporary composer John
Harbison.
</P>
<P>
   The score's title is ``November 19, 1828,'' referring to the
date of Schubert's death, and Harbison has incorporated snatches of
Schubert's music and even apparently written a fugue out of the
source material that the 19th-century composer had planned to use
himself.
</P>
<P>
   The temptation is to decode the choreography for references
contained in the music, which reportedly plays with the musical
counterpart of the letters of Schubert's name. But to see
``Medium'' as a hidden tale about Schubert is to see it as a
studied exercise rather than a work that invites feeling from the
viewer.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography is all aura, which spreads an eerie texture
that originates in another dialogue. This one is between a pianist,
Ethan Iverson, and a string trio, Sara Roth, Carol Benner and Jason
Duckles, all in the pit.
</P>
<P>
   The small units of dancers onstage are initially identified with
the alternating strings or piano but this musical visualization is
abandoned by Morris as his structures onstage become more complex
and all six dancers do similar movements but at different times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medium,'' nonetheless, is not a purely formal work; Schubert
may not die onstage, but by the time one of the women, Tina
Fehlandt, lies down with another dancer, comforting her at the end,
the piece has moved toward an image of tender mourning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medium'' is an unaffected piece; affecting would, in fact, be
the term for it. Three men, Joe Bowie, David Leventhal and
Guillermo Resto, and three women, Ms. Fehlandt, June Omura and
Mireille Radwan-Dana, lie or stand in the beginning and move in
short segments, often stopping to strike poses that Michael
Chybowski's ever fine lighting renders painterly.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Pakledinaz has designed high-waisted and transparent
gowns for the women while the men are in yeoman gear. Nothing
specific occurs onstage but the strange beauty of the piece lies in
its constantly changing spatial composition. It is the ether around
the humans that seems more potent and enveloping.
</P>
<P>
   There are, nevertheless, encounters. The trio lying on the floor
at the start breaks up to regroup with the standing dancers;
sometimes one dancer slips in between two. The medium of the title
is less the idiom (palms held out in broad gestures in the Morris
free style) through which the dancers communicate than the music,
as the spiritual messenger through which the dancers seek to
commune into the great beyond.
</P>
<P>
   After the music grows emphatic, three of the women recline
serenely. The dancing, like the score's four movements, is full of
constant awakenings. People start up or suddenly sit up until the
light dims on Ms. Fehlandt. The final image, like the entire piece,
has an elegiac purity.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The same could be said this time around for ``Dido and Aeneas,''
which Morris originally directed and choreographed a decade ago. As
a man portraying both an austere Dido, queen of Carthage and her
nemesis, the uninhibited Sorceress, Morris was somewhat on the
self-aware side in his performances in the past.
</P>
<P>
   But now his Dido dies a moving death, slumped over a small piece
of a balustrade, and his focused performance lends a new
seriousness to the endeavor. This is not a ``Dido'' for every
taste, and its use of singers and musicians performing in the pit
while dancers mime the words is an old device.
</P>
<P>
   But all the elements come together in what is essentially an
exercise in stylization that ends by illuminating aspects of the
opera. The vocal side was richly represented by the soloists
(Stephanie Novacek as both Dido and the Sorceress, Christine
Brandes as Belinda, James Maddalena as Aeneas, and Eileen Clark
Reisner and Philip Anderson) and the New York Collegium Orchestra
and Chorus, conducted with verve by Craig Smith.
</P>
<P>
   For all its communal exuberance, the Morris troupe is exemplary
in its discipline, as seen in its precise friezelike groupings.
Resto was the onstage Aeneas hoodwinked by the galumphing witch.
The provocative touches are still there (the witch mimes an
auto-erotic moment). But these are fleeting images to test audience
perception.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we have become used to Morris' hair style: long curls
clipped at the nape for the dignified queen, hanging loose for the
couch-potato witch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
