A7104 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOTORCYCLE-ART-FONDA-     06-25 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTORCYCLE-ART-FONDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MOTORCYCLE OF ONE'S OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (see also MOTORCYCLE-ART)  
(ja) 
 By PETER FONDA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bikers ride as nomads, in clubs and in gangs, but no matter how
you ride, if you're a biker you're an individual: Nobody has a
motorcycle quite like yours.
</P>
<P>
   Motorcycles come off the factory line looking very much alike,
but most riders customize their bikes to get the look they want.
This is because to a biker a motorcycle is an imperative extension
of the self, an interpretation of an inner attitude. In this way, a
motorcycle is a work of art to the rider.
</P>
<P>
   Motorcyclists will repaint their bikes and change the
headlights, the taillights, the carrying bags, the footboards and
the seat. They'll decorate with pinstriping, more chrome or less
chrome, more lights or fewer lights. There are endless
possibilities for personalizing a bike. To me, it doesn't matter
how much customizing is done. A few changes here or there may
suffice. But I want to ride my own motorcycle, one that nobody else
has.
</P>
<P>
   I owned my first motorcycle in 1961, when I was 21, but the
first bike I customized was the one I rode in ``Easy Rider,'' which
became an international icon. I had faith that the film would be
successful but was not sure how successful. I took delight that at
the least I had designed myself a very cool and unique chopper.
</P>
<P>
   For the movie, I bought four Los Angeles Police Department
motorcycles at auction, for $500 apiece. Two were for Dennis Hopper
to ride, and two for me. I came up with a redesign for them and did
the work with the help of several friends. I have owned or ridden
some of the great motorcycles in the world, but I have a particular
feeling for my ``Easy Rider'' bike because it was the first I made
my own.
</P>
<P>
   We burned one of the bikes in the film, and, sadly, the other
three were stolen before we finished production.
</P>
<P>
   I own several bikes now, but my favorite is my '98
Harley-Davidson Road King. As soon as I bought the motorcycle, I
began to modify it to my liking. I changed the leather panniers to
black plastic ones and had them repainted red and pinstriped on the
bottom half _ a reverse of the paint scheme on the gas tanks. I
changed the footboards, handlebars and grips, tail lights and other
trims. There's no other bike like mine.
</P>
<P>
   As I do on all my bikes, I also changed the seat, to a solo, as
I never carry a passenger. Riding a motorcycle is something I do
alone. I love to ride. I have no timetables, no reservations. I
travel with a tent and sleeping bag, so I can stop anywhere and be
covered. On the road there are no fences and an extraordinary sense
of freedom. It could have been this way 150 or 100 years ago, in
the Old West, with the sense of endless possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   I have ridden down the west side of the Continental Divide to
the Mexican border and back up the east side, returning to my
ranch, north of Yellowstone Park. It's more than 2,500 miles. I
ride as many summits as I can. I never ride freeways longer than
necessary. Sometimes I bring a seven-piece Hardy fly rod and fish
for trout. Barbless catch-and-release. So free.
</P>
<P>
   I need to ride like this. I never feel alone. I never feel
separated from the Earth. In fact, the experience makes me feel
even more a part of the planet.
</P>
<P>
   (Peter Fonda, the actor, recently wrote his autobiography,
``Don't Tell Dad'' (Hyperion Press))
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1752EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
