<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7106 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RODCHENKO-ART-REVIEW-     06-25 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODCHENKO-ART-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEXANDER RODCHENKO: WHEN RADICAL ART AND POLITICS MARCHED
TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Great Experiment. The term is frequently applied
to the modern art of Russia in the years between 1919 and 1927,
when Russian Constructivism, one of the most radical manifestations
of early 20th-century art, was, for all intents and purposes, the
official style of the newly formed communist government.
</P>
<P>
   It was a time when a handful of contentious avantgarde artists,
under the slogan ``Art Into Life!,'' cast themselves as
full-fledged participants in the Russian Revolution. Subjugating
personal expression to the state's utilitarian needs in the belief
that art could help form a new society, they designed everything
from stationery to household objects to public monuments, made
films and took photographs, some of which are modernist landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Radical political thought and radical art seemed to be in step
with each other as never before, or since. But like most
experiments, this one was short-lived and was soon ground beneath
the heel of the 20th-century's first totalitarian state.
</P>
<P>
   By 1932 Stalin's brutal regime had imposed Socialist Realism as
the official style, ordered the destruction of modernist works in
state museums, imprisoned and even executed some artists, dismissed
others and forced still others into the humiliating posture of
``reconstruction'' to exorcise tendencies deemed formalist,
imperialist or elitist.
</P>
<P>
   To know this history intellectually is not the same as seeing it
played out in visual form _ as it is in the Museum of Modern Art's
survey of the career of Alexander Rodchenko, Russian
Constructivism's most politically adept protagonist.
</P>
<P>
   This is the largest survey of Rodchenko's work mounted in the
United States, and represents a curatorial collaboration between
Magdalena Dabrowski, senior curator, department of drawings at the
Modern; Peter Galassi, chief curator of the museum's department of
photography, and Leah Dickerman, an assistant professor of art
history at Stanford University. It contains 300 paintings,
sculptures, drawings, linocuts, photographs and examples of graphic
design whose numbers include posters, book covers, candy wrappers,
magazine spreads _ many involving ingenious uses of photomontage.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition's reading room is a meticulous re-creation of the
``Workers' Reading Room'' designed by Rodchenko for the 1925
Exposition of Decorative Arts in Paris, complete with stark gray
chairs that are about as comfortable as Pilgrim stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Most impressive are the graphic designs, especially the nearly
three dozen magazine covers for the magazine of leftist esthetics
``Lef'' and its successor, ``Novyi Lef,'' which exploit the bold
geometry of Cyrillic lettering, and many of the photographs from
the mid-1920s, after Rodchenko made some of art history's first
monochrome paintings and announced the death of the medium.
</P>
<P>
   As a whole, the show is by turn illuminating, tragic and
chilling and generally more historically interesting than visually
thrilling. It portrays a fiercely cerebral, problem-solving artist,
bent on progress, who may have been so successful at expunging the
personal from his art that it sometimes seems hollow or to possess
little more than a period look.
</P>
<P>
   But if Rodchenko's art is short on psychological insight or the
pleasures of the eye _ for that there's the Bonnard exhibition on
the floor below _ he is so versatile and diversely innovative that
simply presenting the first two busy decades of his career sums up
a great deal about Constructivism and its time. In many ways he was
the Great Experiment's greatest utility player.
</P>
<P>
   Rodchenko arrived in Moscow in 1915 at the age of 24, having
already absorbed most of the innovations of Cubism and Futurism and
made some abstract art of his own. These geometric ink drawings,
hanging near the show's entrance, were included in an exhibition in
1916 organized by Vladimir Tatlin, whose designs for the Cafe
Pittoresque, of 1917, are generally viewed as the beginning of
Constructivism.
</P>
<P>
   By 1920, Rodchenko was part of a rare phenomenon: an
institutionally supported avantgarde that included filmmakers Dziga
Vertov and Sergei Eisenstein, and poet Vladimir Mayakovsky, as well
as Malevich, Kandinsky and Varvara Stepanova, Rodchenko's lifelong
companion. With others they established and taught at art schools,
organized state exhibitions and new museums, hammered out esthetic
programs and founded magazines, like ``Lef.''
</P>
<P>
   And they fought over turf. As Rodchenko's materialist,
objectivist approach to art gained ground over Kandinsky's more
subjective approach, Rodchenko was prominent in a group that ousted
Kandinsky from his teaching position, prompting him to leave the
Soviet Union for the friendlier waters of the Bauhaus.
</P>
<P>
   Rodchenko's sensibility should be familiar to anyone with a
passing knowledge of Minimal and Conceptual Art, and it makes sense
that interest in his art began to revive in the early 1970s, when
those styles held sway. (In 1971, the Museum of Modern Art mounted
a small show of works from its collection, the first outside the
Soviet Union.)
</P>
<P>
   In the opening galleries of the exhibition, where Rodchenko
rapidly pursues formalist reduction to its logical conclusion, one
catches intimations of the work of Dan Flavin, Mel Bochner and Sol
LeWitt. His black on black paintings, made in response to
Malevich's white-on-white works, presage the subtleties of Ad
Reinhardt's shadowy canvases. His statements announcing the death
of painting, the importance of physicality, new materials and
``real space,'' the triumph of construction over old-fashioned
composition sound surprisingly like those of Donald Judd.
</P>
<P>
   The almost relentless formal innovations of these early years
can be measured in circles. First there are the fuzzed, glowing
orbs of ``Composition No. 113 on Yellow Ground,'' which borrows
some of Malevich's visionary light. These are followed by linear
ones in ``Construction No. 127,'' drawn with geometry-class
precision in white chalk on black. The circle then leaps into real
space in the concentric ellipses of Rodchenko's hanging ``Spatial
Construction No 12.'' (That all these works were possibly made
within a single year, 1920, only adds to the sense of ferment.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By 1922 Rodchenko subjected form to function: the circles become
the dominant motif in designs for fabric and tea sets.
</P>
<P>
   A similar path can be traced in Rodchenko's use of diagonals,
which again originate in the floating forms of Malevich's more
elaborate Suprematist works, are distilled and systematized into
the fanning lines of ``Construction No. 89 (on Light Yellow)'' of
1919 and become representational in many of his best-known
photographs: the tilting plunging images, shot from above above or
below, of buildings, trolleys and people in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Next is a phase in which Rodchenko moves increasingly toward
mass communication, often in collaboration with Mayakovsky.
Illustrating Mayakovsky's poem ``Pro Eto'' he echoes the clotted,
jumbled photomontages of the German Dadaists Hannah Hoch and Raoul
Hausmann. But the two friends also collaborated on advertisements
for Mossel'prom, the state-owned grocery-store chain, and Dobrolet,
the state-owned airline.
</P>
<P>
   For the latter, Rodchenko designed posters, stationery, lapel
pins, stock-offering brochures and the company insignia of a black
and red biplane, creating what is, in effect, an early example of a
coordinated advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mayakovsky, who once defined advertising copy as the highest
form of poetry, wrote propagandistic texts announcing that Russians
who didn't own stock in Dobrolet were not true communists.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything they did together was so ideologically loaded:
one of the show's few emotional hot spots are Rodchenko's
photographs of Mayakovsky, his angular features and confrontational
stare reminiscent of sculptor Richard Serra, himself a latter-day
Constructivist.
</P>
<P>
   Rodchenko was swept up in revolutionary ideals from such an
early age that when the Revolution turned sour, he seems not to
have had much to fall back on, at least not enough to help him face
reality. The conventional photojournalism in the exhibition's final
section exceeds the usual distortions of propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to regain official favor, Rodchenko made three trips
to photograph the construction of the White Sea Canal, where gulag
conditions were killing 10,000 workers a month. This fact, which
must have been unavoidable, was not touched on in either his images
or his letters home. The workers, described as criminals in the
magazine that published these photographs, were in fact simply
``enemies of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   None of Rodchenko's work made after 1935, when he took up
painting again, are included here, which is unfortunate because it
might have revealed more about the man himself. It is intriguing to
read in the catalog that he began painting images of clowns and
circuses. The circus had been a childhood passion, and the return
to them suggests a case of arrested development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alexander Rodchenko'' is at the Museum of Modern Art, 11 W.
53rd Street, Manhattan, through Oct. 6. It will travel to the
Kunsthalle Duesseldorf (October-January, 1999), and the Moderna
Museet, Stockholm (March 6-May 24).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
