A7109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DARA-WILSON-JAZZ-REVI     06-25 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DARA-WILSON-JAZZ-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ FESTIVAL REVIEW: THE SOUTH IN SOUNDS AND IDEAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By PETER WATROUS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The musical fertility of the black South during the
first half of the century, though it shaped the pop music of the
world, has mostly fallen out of the public consciousness, at least
in a direct way. But Olu Dara and Cassandra Wilson, who performed
at Carnegie Hall on Tuesday night as part of the JVC Jazz Festival,
went directly into the culture.
</P>
<P>
   They're both from Mississippi, and both used blues and jazz
ideas, melodies, rhythms, songs and tonalities to reimagine a past
that for the most part doesn't exist anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Dara sang ``Bubber (If Only)'' _ for Bubber Miley, the cornetist
in Duke Ellington's early jungle band _ and he made a joke about
the two people in the audience who knew of him. He sang ``Rain
Shower,'' using blues melodies, and ``Harlem Country Girl,'' about
taking walks around New York with a woman he liked.
</P>
<P>
   There's something laconic and relaxed about him, and it obscures
Dara's talent as a music maker; he's so intent on creating a mood,
usually of a good time, that how he gets to the mood is overlooked.
He played cornet, and on one tune he walked into the audience,
finding people to play too; the hall's acoustics let him be heard,
unamplified. The music, lodged between jazz and blues and pop and
loaded with archaic details, was there to remind people that
culture can be lost and forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wilson appeared next, and her show moved from standards like
``Surrey With the Fringe on Top'' and ``Old Devil Moon'' to blues
pieces by Robert Johnson and Son House. Backed by a quartet, she
improvised, using jazz ideas, blues moans, pop and gospel music,
filling the gaps between melodies with texture.
</P>
<P>
   In the past Ms. Wilson has often relied on the sound of her
voice to move listeners; she can be inarticulate. But Tuesday the
words and her melodies were in order, and the conception, her
ability to merge disparate styles and ideas, was working. She was
dramatic, and her talent finally made even her conception
irrelevant; the emotional response she elicited was, finally, what
was important.
</P>
<P>
   And she was elegance on two feet, her improvisations curling
like spiraling cigarette smoke. She changed textures, and dropped
notes into the basement of her range. The way she moved emphasized
her melodies, and she turned music into motion. When she sang the
words ``love is blindness,'' it was easy to understand what she was
singing about.
</P>
<P>
   She knew, at least for that moment, the relationship between
sadness and knowledge and that just the act of knowing eased
whatever pain the narrator might have; she shared it with the
audience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
