<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7112 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-25 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IS A FEMINIST? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A majority of American women don't want to be
called feminists, according to a new poll. Who can blame them?
</P>
<P>
   What is a feminist anyway? That once-proud word has been
distorted over two decades so much that no one really knows what it
means any more.
</P>
<P>
   Resistance to the label by ordinary women doesn't necessarily
mean they are turning against the struggle for equal rights or
rushing to conform to the Southern Baptist Convention's new decree
that a wife should ``submit graciously to the servant leadership of
her husband''.
</P>
<P>
   It reflects confusion over how to define feminism itself rather
than ingratitude for the opportunities created by the women's
movement. Many advocates of women's rights have veered from the
original goal of reforming society by ending gender discrimination
in the workplace, marketplace and home. Now they are preoccupied
with female sexuality and the liberation of individual egos and
libidos.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us old-fashioned types, however, believe that bad taste
is not a requirement of feminism. A woman's private sex life is
nobody's business and is irrelevant to the basic cause of retaining
and consolidating the cultural and economic gains we have won.
</P>
<P>
   This current detour into erotic self-absorption is a reflection
of the fact that many women now take for granted their equality
with men and feel free to focus less on political and legal issues
than the early feminists did.
</P>
<P>
   But it is premature to relax. The religious right is still
trying to undermine our new freedoms by crusading, in subtle and
not-so-subtle ways, for women to cradle babies, tend to their men
and return to a humble position by the hearthstone.
</P>
<P>
   The poll by Time magazine and CNN reported that 65 percent of
women surveyed did not consider themselves feminists. Only 32
percent had a favorable impression of such women while 43 percent
had an unfavorable impression.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this image problem, the majority surveyed credited
feminists as working for serious causes such as equal rights, equal
pay, abortion rights, sexual harassment laws and affordable day
care.
</P>
<P>
   Yet only 48 percent _ less than half _ said feminism today is
relevant to most women. A mere 28 percent said it is relevant to
them personally. And 37 percent said feminists don't like most men.
Something is going wrong here.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, as the legal crusade for equal rights was in its
infancy, and the early 1980s, as it matured, there was no ambiguity
about the meaning of ``feminism.'' The 1984 Democratic presidential
nominee Walter Mondale _ having just picked Geraldine Ferraro as
his running mate and the first woman to appear on a major party's
national ticket _ proudly called himself a feminist.
</P>
<P>
   Webster's Collegiate Dictionary describes feminism as ``the
theory of the political, economic and social equality of the
sexes.''
</P>
<P>
   The patronizing ``theory'' bit aside, we old-timers still agree
with that definition and identify feminism with the social changes
that have expanded women's choices and opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The bad old days of overt discrimination in everything from job
pay to lines of credit are largely gone. Women still earn less
money than men and are underrepresented in corporate boardrooms. We
never did get a constitutional amendment guaranteeing our rights.
But pent-up fury over our unfair treatment has given way, on the
part of some women, to a cultural indulgence in obscene and
self-asserting female behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In a cover story dramatizing its poll findings, Time magazine
makes a big fuss about the ``frivolization'' of feminism.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine cites an appalling list of sexually explicit and
tasteless books, music and teen-oriented magazines written and
promoted by women who are celebrating their gender by demeaning it.
</P>
<P>
   Among others, Monica Lewinsky typifies the new female arrogance.
Although she was just a young White House intern, she wrote a
letter to President Clinton _ the leader of the free world, mind
you _ saying ``I want you in my life.'' She was thinking of
herself, not of him. This was not a request; it was a selfish
demand.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan is notorious for nurturing liberal foolishness,
including sensationalized sideshows. Time reports that at a New
York City theatrical reading of something called ``The Vagina
Monologues'' even that mature, wonderful actress Glenn Close got
into the spirit of the new mood by offering a ``homage'' to an
obscene word for female genitalia. Say it isn't so, Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, female goofiness in New York does not reach very
far beyond an insular circle of limited influence. The radicals do
not speak for anyone but themselves. They have little to do with
true feminism, no matter how they may masquerade as its leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Feminism is about empowerment in all aspects of life, not simply
through private sexual pleasure. It is about independence,
intelligence, emotional stability and cultural worth. It is about
seeking for women that which men have always had _ an opportunity
to demonstrate personal merit in a chosen rather than socially
imposed way.
</P>
<P>
   But it may be too late to rescue the word from its present
contorted image. If so, serious advocates of women's rights would
be politically wise to call themselves something else.
</P>
<P>
   (Editors: Marianne Means will be on vacation for one week
beginning Monday, June 29. Her column will resume July 6.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
