<HEADER>
A7113 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-1     06-25 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The Times of new or
noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in New York
City. Ratings and running times are in parentheses.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``BULWORTH,'' starring Warren Beatty, Halle Berry and Oliver
Platt. Directed by Beatty (R, 108 minutes). A revitalized Beatty
directs this political satire with jubilant wit and energy, playing
the ultimate limousine liberal with comic panache as a white
politician suddenly turned homeboy (and turned on to black urban
culture and a passionately liberal agenda). Taking a potentially
cheap fish-out-of-water gimmick and making it deeply, disarmingly
funny, he returns to the anything-goes tradition of 1970s dropout
comedy. As the fretful, spin-controlling aide to Beatty's wayward
senator, Platt is uproariously sly (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``COUSIN BETTE,'' starring Jessica Lange and Elisabeth Shue.
Directed by Des McAnuff (R, 108 minutes). Balzac's great novel of
1840s Paris, like Tom Wolfe's ``Bonfire of the Vanities,'' of which
it is an obvious forerunner, is far too big and sprawling to be
compressed into a film of average length. The gifted theater
director McAnuff, making his feature-film debut, has staged the
novel's greedy social climbing and revenge as a cartoonish
``Masterpiece Theater'' spoof in which an avaricious courtesan (Ms.
Shue) and an ambitious young sculptor (Aden Young) who wreak sexual
havoc are charmless buffoons. Ms. Lange is grimly opaque as a
vengeful, scheming cousin who manipulates these narcissists into
destroying the aristocratic relatives who have humiliated her
(Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``GODZILLA,'' starring Matthew Broderick and Hank Azaria.
Directed by Roland Emmerich (PG-13, 139 minutes). The ads for
``Godzilla'' proclaim that ``size does matter.'' But it turns out
that bigger doesn't necessarily mean better. The animatronic lizard
that rises from the ocean and stomps on New York City landmarks has
thundering metallic footsteps but the impact of a weightless
cartoon monster. The movie doesn't get scary until halfway through,
when the beast's eggs hatch (in what's left of Madison Square
Garden) and an army of more lifelike baby Godzillas threatens to
devour the search party. The storytelling and acting in this $120
million wad of gummed-up popcorn reaches new depths of crudeness
and ineptitude for a so-called ``event movie'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``HAV PLENTY,'' starring Christopher Scott Cherot and Chenoa
Maxwell. Directed by Cherot (R, 105 minutes). Cherot not only
directed, wrote and edited this amusing, lighter-than-air screwball
comedy about contemporary buppie-mating rituals but also stars, as
Lee Plenty, an affable, self-effacing and broke young writer
secretly in love with a snooty rich girl named Havilland Savage
(Ms. Maxwell). Most of the story is set in Washington over a New
Year's holiday in which Havilland and her well-heeled friends
exchange stingingly funny one-liners, while Lee comments wryly to
the camera. The movie is flawed with a pat, tacked-on ending
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``HENRY FOOL,'' starring Thomas Jay Ryan, James Urbaniak and
Parker Posey. Directed by Hal Hartley (R, 138 minutes). The
affectless precision of this filmmaker's previous work is
absolutely no preparation for the brilliance and deep resonance of
this contemporary parable. Without forsaking the clean, spare look
and hyperreal clarity that are his trademarks, Hartley moves into a
much larger realm with a meditation on, among other things, art,
trust, loyalty, politics and popular culture. When Henry Fool
(Ryan) bursts mysteriously into the thankless life of Simon Grim
(Urbaniak) and urges this silent garbage man to start writing, the
results are strange and sublime. Ms. Posey plays Simon's slatternly
sister with nonchalant wit in one of her best roles. A few
glaringly scatological touches don't detract from the film's
elegance of vision (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``HIGH ART,'' starring Ally Sheedy and Radha Mitchell. Directed
by Lisa Cholodenko (R, 96 minutes). Ms. Sheedy gives a fierce,
tricky performance in the role of a once celebrated photographer
spooked by fame who long ago retreated from the art world to live a
reclusive, druggy life among lesbian friends. This steamily intense
story follows her spider-fly relationship with Ms. Mitchell's
bright-eyed, ambitious ingenue, who works for a desperately stylish
photography magazine. Ms. Cholodenko's seductive, powerfully
atmospheric first feature explores their relationship with
intelligence and avidity. But it sacrifices any hope of raw edges
and real emotion to its own chic sensibility, which proves so
studiously alluring that it overwhelms the story. Patricia Clarkson
does a scene-stealing turn as Ms. Sheedy's lover, a glamorously
decadent German actress who never got past the Fassbinder years
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE HORSE WHISPERER,'' starring Robert Redford and Kristin
Scott Thomas. Directed by Redford (PG-13, 164 minutes). There's a
blunt soap opera of a movie inside Nicholas Evans' widely popular
novel. But Redford, directing himself for the first time, with
intelligence and restraint, has found a visually eloquent way to
turn it into something much more thoughtful and tranquil.
Magnificently photographed by Robert Richardson, this film is a
wide-screen love affair with the West, and a story more of peace
and healing than of ardor. Though it's long and its resolution is a
problem, this is an enveloping film that richly rewards the
viewer's attention (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE LAND GIRLS,'' starring Catherine McCormack, Rachel Weisz
and Anna Friel. Directed by David Leland (R, 112 minutes). A
sentimental valentine to the Women's Land Army, the legion of young
women dispatched across Britain during World War II to assume jobs
vacated by fighting men, this film presses familiar nostalgic
buttons but not so aggressively that it makes you feel queasy. Good
girl Stella (Ms. McCormack); bad girl Prue (Ms. Friel), and nerdy
academic Ag (Ms. Weisz), women from varying backgrounds, share
cramped quarters on the same Dorset farm where they plow fields,
milk cows and have their romantic turns with the owner's frisky
son, Joe. Rich with period detail and atmosphere, the movie leaves
the inner lives of its characters largely unexplored to paint a
heroic canvas of romantic turmoil and noble self-sacrifice
(Holden).
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
