<HEADER>
A7120 &Cx1f; taf-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIAN-ART-REVIEW-NYT     06-25 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POINTING UP THE WRY SIDE OF THE INDIAN CLASH WITH WHITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``We don't serve Indians,'' a waitress said to two
Indians as they sat in a diner just outside their Mesquakie
settlement in Tama, Iowa. ``We don't want Indians,'' replied one of
them. ``We want cheeseburgers.''
</P>
<P>
   This story, which involves his father, is told by Duane Slick of
Sauk-Fox ancestry, one of 38 artists whose work appears in the wry
and illuminating contemporary show, ``Indian Humor,'' at the
National Museum of the American Indian.
</P>
<P>
   Including the anecdote in a catalog statement about his art,
Slick sees the fast, funny cheeseburger zinger as the kind of
equalizer used by Indians to arm themselves against the put-downs
of white America.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the strongest theme of the show is the clash of
American Indian values with those of the contemporary world _
specifically, the white world _ and how Indians deal with being, so
to speak, low men on the totem pole in a country they still see as
a bastion of colonialism. Every topic that touches on Indian-white
contact is ripe for gibes, from the Bureau of Indian Affairs to
television to casinos, even.
</P>
<P>
   The show, organized by American Indian Contemporary Arts, a
nonprofit center in San Francisco, must certainly be a first in the
annals of Indian-white relationships. One of its primary aims is to
counter ``the popular notion that Indians are stoic and serious,''
writes Janeen Antoine (Sicangu Lakota), executive director of the
San Francisco center, in the catalog preface.
</P>
<P>
   A contribution directly assailing that notion is the cartoony
lithograph, ``Lady in Waiting'' (1987) by Robert Freeman
(Dakota-Luiseno), who describes himself as a creator of ``Indian
babes,'' rather than ``typical Indian maidens.''
</P>
<P>
   In this work a voluptuous young thing wearing sunglasses, a
feather headdress, clunky ``Indian'' jewelry and not much else sits
before a tepee in whose suggestive opening can be glimpsed a large
television. Behind her clumps of giant phallic cacti stretch back
to a string of idyllic blue mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Fake ``Indian'' tchotchkes, toys and nostalgia are satirized by
Joanna Osborn-Bigfeather (Cherokee-Mescalero Apache) in ``May I
Serve You? Cultural Artifacts'' (1994) and Bently Spang (Northern
Cheyenne) in ``The Beginning of the End for the End of the Trail''
(1994). Kay Walkingstick (Cherokee-Winnebago) has produced
``Talking Leaves: You're an Indian?'' (1993), a book of comments
made to her over the years by whites. Next to a lively
self-portrait in pseudo-Indian dress, for instance, appears the
remark, ``You're an Indian? I thought you were a Jewish girl from
Queens who changed her name.''
</P>
<P>
   George Blake's (Hupa-Yurok) ``Hang Around the Fort Injun''
(1993) is an over-life-size carving in painted redwood of a
long-haired brave smugly dressed in white man's clothes and a Stars
and Stripes necktie. ``Hang around the forters,'' Blake explains,
were Indians who ingratiated themselves with white officials sent
to govern them from headquarters in fortlike buildings on the
reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Acting as servants, scouts, Indian policemen and so forth, the
hang-arounds wound up working for the Bureau of Indian Affairs
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also themes that are peculiarly Indian, like the
folk hero Coyote, a trickster who embodies the devilish side of
human nature. (Could he be the inspiration for the Wile E. Coyote
character in the ``Road Runner'' film animation series?) A
quintessential survivor who adopts many guises, Coyote looks out
for himself. He likes to play jokey pranks, but he is also a sly,
hard-biting dog.
</P>
<P>
   In Slick's work, ``Coyote Television Bookpiece'' (1994), Coyote
lurks in mock television screens and the pages of books, making
fleeting appearances to jeer at the distortions of Indian culture
by the mass media.
</P>
<P>
   In three paintings by Harry Fonseca (Maidu) done from 1987 to
1993, Coyote turns up as a vaudeville Uncle Sam, a hipster in a
black leather jacket and a saint surrounded by clouds and flowers.
On the other hand, Jean LaMarr (Paiute-Pit River) portrays Coyote
as a woman, addressing the issue of male-female inequality that is
by no means confined to Indian communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Coyote'' (1992), a leering coyote wall mask that wears an
earring and a rose on its head, goes so far as to suggest that
women can be tricksters on a par with men.
</P>
<P>
   In the artists' humor there is often the angst of seeing ancient
traditions eroded. Funny as it sounds, ``The Zen Electric Jingle
Dress Dancer: The Sound of One Jingle Jangling'' (1994), by Arthur
Amiotte (Oglala Sioux), is a gentle lament for the disappearance of
Indian craftsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   In the painting, an Indian dancer is seen in a flashy ceremonial
costume bedizened with sequins and rickrack, wearing on her head a
sort of tennis cap adorned with tiny American flags. While he means
his painting to be amusing, Amiotte writes, ``it also represents
something of the shoddiness that has replaced the fine and
delicately wrought traditional techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   Beadwork, as a symbol of ancient Indian traditions now degraded,
is very much part of the show. Take Marcus Amerman's (Choctaw)
``Iron Horse Jacket'' of 1993. On the back of a nail-studded black
leather motorcycle jacket, he has embroidered a kitschy rendition
of Brooke Shields, something of an innovation in that the tiny
beads, traditionally used in abstract patterning, here create a
realistic image.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of this sole white pop culture figure also
suggests, in a roundabout way, the absence of Indians from the mass
media.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Larson Bread (Southern Blackfoot) uses her mastery of
beadwork to comment on the inroads of white culture. In ``Traveling
Through Indian Country'' (1994), she has beaded a white travel
pouch on the front with a design reflecting onetime Indian control
of a large piece of American geography.
</P>
<P>
   On the back, she uses clan patches with Indian tribal symbols
separated by lots of white space to indicate the sparseness and
separation of Indian communities today.
</P>
<P>
   Like most group shows, ``Indian Humor'' is uneven, and it
contains material that is not altogether accessible if you're not
an Indian. But it has real punch and a refreshing absence of
polemics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth remains that there hasn't been much to laugh about
in Indian country since contact'' (an Indianism for the historical
confrontation with white Europeans), writes the show's curator,
Jolene Rickard (Tuscarora) in the catalog. ``The irony is that it
almost seems an unnatural task to share a joke with the continually
colonizing `west.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But by sharing these jokes, ``Indian Humor'' sets up a beguiling
approach to Indian attitudes and feelings, of which most other
Americans are sadly unaware. See it and laugh. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)``Indian Humor'' remains at the George Gustave Heye
Center, National Museum of the American Indian, 1 Bowling Green,
lower Manhattan, through Aug. 2.(end italics)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
