<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7155 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACTOR-SEAGO-COX     06-25 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTOR-SEAGO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gulf between 2 worlds: Deaf actor's crossed that bridge
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Considered one of the foremost deaf performers in the United
States, Howie Seago has worked as an actor, director and producer
for two decades. In the film ``Beyond Silence,'' now playing, he
portrays Martin, the deaf father of a hearing daughter. An Oscar
nominee for best foreign film of 1997, the German drama charts the
attempts of parents and child to bridge the gulf between the
hearing and nonhearing worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Seago, who lives in Seattle, answered questions about the film
by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was your childhood anything like Martin's, in terms of
barriers to communication?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. There were many similar parallels. I was not allowed to
use sign language while growing up. This method does not always
work for all deaf children and I strongly believe that American
Sign Language should be used with deaf children for all purposes,
educationally and socially. I feel that I missed out on a lot when
growing up. I do have a good, loving family and appreciate all that
my parents provided for me. I just wish that they had and would now
learn to sign so we can communicate more naturally and efficiently.
My father is a minister, now semi-retired. There is a parallel
between my father's passion for religion and Martin's father's
passion for music, both taking precedent over the son's needs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you worry that director Caroline Link, a hearing person
with no direct experience with deaf people, might not get the story
right?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, at first when she faxed me about my interest in doing
the film. I told her that to be culturally and politically correct,
she should cast German deaf in the roles. I thought she might have
been naive about the differences of the cultural and linguistic
aspects of deafness between countries. Then she faxed back a
four-page, very well-articulated explanation that showed me she had
done her homework. So next I requested and read her screenplay and
was convinced to do it. And it improved throughout the process.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It seems that ``Beyond Silence'' has strong parallels with
your own life, since you're the father of two hearing boys. Did
your personal experience influence the script of the film?
</P>
<P>
   A: Maybe in some small ways. It was so long ago and so much has
happened since then that I don't recall just how much influence I
had on the script. I do know my personal experience did influence
my performance of the role, naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did you get into acting?
</P>
<P>
   A: My first deaf college roommate recruited me to perform in a
sign language play. At first I was petrified, as my ASL skills were
still rudimentary, but he explained that I would just have to learn
and repeat my lines for every show. That it would not be an
extemporaneous presentation. Ummmm ... heck, why not? Then after
the performances, people would approach me with compliments in sign
language and I had to tell them to slow down or repeat. They were
shocked that my ASL skills were different from what I presented
onstage. I thought that was neat. Also I enjoyed getting into the
mentality of someone who is different from what I am in real life.
So I was hooked. Since then, I have learned a lot about life and
humanity by playing an interesting range of characters.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you do for fun?
</P>
<P>
   A: My favorite recreation is cross-country skiing and kayaking.
I like to play with my kids and read novels. I also have a theater
troupe called Deaf Moose Theatre that I enjoy performing in
occasionally as a ``hobby'' with my younger deaf brother and
youngest son.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
