<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-BETTE-COX     06-25 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BETTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A `Cousin Bette' to reckon with
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Based on Honore de Balzac's 1846 novel, ``Cousin Bette'' is a
deliciously tart comedy of ill manners and worse morals that slowly
ripens into a revenger's tragicomedy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1840s Paris, the rich are getting richer while the poor are
getting, well, revolutionary. The well-off pamper themselves while
purposely ignoring the unruly mobs of hungry and homeless gathering
around them. Think ``The Bonfire of the Vanities'' (the book, not
the movie).
</P>
<P>
   Against this precarious social backdrop, Balzac spins a tale of
revenge as implacable as it is sweet. But purists beware; the
filmmakers have whittled his novel down considerably, so if you're
looking for an unwaveringly faithful rendition, this isn't it. It's
more of a showcase for a memorable performance by Jessica Lange and
an excuse for well-known stage director Des McAnuff to apply his
theatrical flair to the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   The film begins with a mordantly funny deathbed scene. Inside
the richly appointed Hulot home, Adeline (Geraldine Chaplin), the
mistress of the household, is dying. The family doctor makes sure
to hand her his bill before she succumbs, while her foolish,
philandering husband, Hector (Hugh Laurie), swears he'll never
cheat on her again (gee, about five minutes of utter faithfulness).
And then there's Adeline's sister, Bette (Lange), who promises her
sibling that she'll take care of the family. She does, sort of the
way Lizzie Borden took care of her parents.
</P>
<P>
   A bitter, 40-ish spinster, Bette has spent her life in her
sister's shadow. (``A family like ours could only push forward one
girl,'' she says, trying to sound gracious. ``Your beauty benefited
us all.'') But once Adeline is dead, Bette gets a final-straw shock
that we won't spoil here. Suffice it to say that Bette's passive
resentment becomes active scheming.
</P>
<P>
   While seeming to be the epitome of selfless helpfulness and good
will, Bette plots to destroy the entire silly, shallow Hulot
family. Her primary instrument of destruction will be Jenny Cadine
(Elisabeth Shue), a burlesque star who's more courtesan than
chanteuse. Jenny, whose many admirers include Hector, becomes
friendly with Bette. ``You will be the ax and I will be the hand
that wields you,'' Bette says.
</P>
<P>
   There are many complications, ranging from Hector's insipid son
(Toby Stephens) to the lustful lord mayor (Bob Hoskins), who thinks
his money can buy him anything. But the film's focus is always on
Bette. Dowdied down to look like Mrs. Danvers in ``Rebecca,'' Lange
plays her with a tight-lipped fury so seethingly convincing you're
never quite sure how far she'll go. More to the point, you realize
that Bette herself isn't sure how far she'll go. She is, as Peter
Finch so famously put it in ``Network,'' mad as hell and not going
to take it anymore. But boy, is she going to dish it out.
</P>
<P>
   There are moments when you feel that ``Cousin Bette'' should be
more darkly angry than devilishly arch. McAnuff has diluted some of
Balzac's bitter human comedy and therefore lessened its power. But
his artful cast and wicked tone are hard to resist. As Jenny's
musical director tells her in rehearsal, ``You're singing about
lust and seduction. Put a little crocodile in it.''
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of crocodile in ``Cousin Bette.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cousin Bette''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jessica Lange and Elisabeth Shue. Directed by Des
McAnuff. Rated R for sex (intercourse, oral sex) and nudity. 1
hour, 48 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A wicked comedy of revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
