<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Almost 60, `Wind' remains a force
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rhett Butler was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, my dears, we still do give a damn about Scarlett,
Melanie, Mammy, Ashley, Tara, Bonnie Blue's pony and all the rest.
After almost 60 years, ``Gone With the Wind'' remains the essential
Hollywood movie. Not a happy fluke such as ``Casablanca'' or a
maverick vision such as ``Citizen Kane,'' but a superbly crafted
apogee of Hollywood's Golden Age.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the most profitable movie in history. No small thing
in an era when a movie's entire reputation rests on its opening
weekend grosses. Translate those 1939 dollars, as well as all the
money earned in subsequent re-releases, into 1990s bucks, and
``Titanic'' becomes an also-ran. The American Film Institute
recently voted ``GWTW'' one of the best American movies ever made.
</P>
<P>
   Producer David O. Selznick's masterful adaptation of Margaret
Mitchell's Civil War best seller returns to theaters today in a
spruced-up version. New Line Cinema, a division of the Ted
Turner/Time Warner media empire, has spent a reported $1 million to
restore ``Gone With the Wind'' to its original glory.
</P>
<P>
   Just what does this state-of-the-art overhaul mean? Well,
Godzilla hasn't been added to the burning of Atlanta, and Forrest
Gump doesn't show up at Belle Watling's. There are no ``lost''
scenes, no rediscovered director's cut. Mostly, this is a chance
for older fans and for a new generation to experience ``Gone With
the Wind'' on the big screen, something that, aside from perennial
summer screenings at Atlanta's Fox Theatre, hasn't happened since
the film's 50th anniversary celebration in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Technically speaking, what's most noticeable are the digitalized
improvements to the picture's original Technicolor process. The
colors are more vibrant, thus reintroducing us to the genius of
William Cameron Menzies' production design and Walter Plunkett's
costumes. At the famous Atlanta benefit, for example, the stark
black clothing of newly widowed Scarlett (Vivien Leigh) and her
scandalous dance partner Rhett (Clark Gable) stands out
astonishingly against the Confederate pale grays and the Southern
belle pastels. The contrast gives the scene more power.
</P>
<P>
   Max Steiner's famous, Oscar-nominated score (it lost to ``The
Wizard of Oz,'' but ``GWTW'' won best picture and eight other
Oscars ) has been digitally remastered. Many of the smudges and
scratches accrued over decades of revival-house screenings have
been erased. One flaw: In trying to approximate the picture's
original aspect-ratio (it has to do with width vs. height), some
clarity has been lost.
</P>
<P>
   But even though it remains an outstanding example of studio
craftsmanship at its peak, ``GWTW'' has never been about
technology. It's about Scarlett and her battle to survive the war,
win back Rhett, save Tara. It's about immortal characters and an
enduring story. The movie's racism remains unavoidable. Hattie
McDaniel (Mammy), Oscar Polk (Pork), Everett Brown (Big Sam) and
Butterfly McQueen (Prissy) give tremendous performances; in fact,
McDaniel became the first African-American to win an Oscar. But
they were, are and always will be variations on the ugly ``happy
darkie'' stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   I made a deal with myself decades ago to never forget the
picture's inherent racist context. But I also realized that
condemning ``Gone With the Wind'' for its civil rights and wrongs
would be like judging ``The Godfather'' solely on its attitude
toward women, or evaluating ``Lawrence of Arabia'' only in terms of
its Arab stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone With the Wind'' is a myth. A myth of Old Hollywood as
much as a myth of the Old South. The ``vanished civilization'' that
Ben Hecht wrote of in his celebrated introduction to the film
(which, apparently, Mitchell never much cared for) is the 1930s as
much as the 1860s.
</P>
<P>
   Times change, yet ``Gone With the Wind'' remains rooted in our
nation's collective movie memory. A harmonic convergence of a South
that never really was as imagined by a Hollywood that will never be
again. The movie has been worshipped; it has been reviled. Either
way, it has never been forgotten. It remains what it always was: a
grand illusion. Perhaps the grandest of them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone With the Wind''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Vivien Leigh and Clark Gable. Directed by Victor
Fleming. Rated G.
</P>
<P>
   3 hours, 42 minutes, plus intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
