<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SEX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ricci takes `Sex' to a nasty level
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christina Ricci has been a talent to reckon with ever since she
stole scenes from Raul Julia and Anjelica Huston in the two
``Addams Family'' movies.
</P>
<P>
   In the acerbic, yet strangely sweet, black comedy ``The Opposite
of Sex,'' she's at the heart of a smart ensemble that includes Lisa
Kudrow (``Friends''), Martin Donovan (``The Portrait of a Lady'')
and singer Lyle Lovett.
</P>
<P>
   Ricci plays Dedee, a foul-mouthed teenage tart who flicks a lit
cigarette into her stepfather's grave and takes off to find her
half brother Bill (Donovan). Bill is, as Dedee observes in her
archly bitchy narration, ``like, dozens of years older than me and
an actual real-life homo.'' Bill has an actual real-life homo
lover, a dim-bulb pretty boy named Matt (Ivan Sergei), whom Dedee
easily seduces.
</P>
<P>
   A virtually unrecognizable Kudrow plays Lucia, the repressed
schoolteacher sister of one of Bill's former lovers. She takes
Dedee's shenanigans as a personal affront to his memory. Then, as
Dedee warns us, ``Things get very complicated very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Beneath ``Sex's'' black humor and self-conscious plot twists is
a heartfelt look at relationships _ especially, but not
exclusively, gay relationships _ in the late 1990s. Writer-director
Don Roos, whose screenwriting credits have been good (``Love
Field''), not too bad (``Single White Female'') and really ugly
(the ``Diabolique'' remake), turns out to be a true believer when
it comes to the love thing.
</P>
<P>
   Most of ``Sex'' is nasty, however, with Ricci setting the tone
and pace as the hard-hearted heroine whose unabashed me-first
approach keeps the plot going full speed. She's outrageous, yet
captivating. And she always gives us fair warning: ``If you think
I'm plucky and surprising and all I need is love, you're in over
your head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Opposite of Sex''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Christina Ricci, Martin Donovan and Lisa Kudrow.
Directed by Don Roos. Rated R for vulgar language, sexual
situations, nudity and sexual references. 1 hour, 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Christina Ricci's teenage harlot burns a hole in
the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
