</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SILENCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Silence'' moral: Children must learn to separate from their
parents without cutting them off.
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a longtime fan of classic horror movies, I couldn't help but
think of Lon Chaney, the original Phantom of the Opera, throughout
the fine new German film ``Beyond Silence.'' Like this picture's
protagonist, he was the hearing child of deaf parents. But in his
case, a childhood spent using sign language enhanced his career as
a silent film star. In ``Beyond Silence,'' our heroine's gift
pushes her further from her parents.
</P>
<P>
   We meet Lara (Tatjana Trieb) as a bright, vivacious 8-year-old.
Adept at sign language, she is her parents' (hearing-impaired
actors Howie Seago and Emmanuelle Laborit) crucial link to the rest
of the world. She acts as interpreter and, sometimes, as protector.
Negotiating between her father and an unhelpful bank officer, for
instance, she wisely tempers her dad's more irate comebacks.
Conversely, she's not above using her translating skills to her
advantage. Say, softening a teacher's more critical comments during
a parent-teacher session.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs is a tight-knit, happy family. That is, until the day
Lara's glamorous Aunt Clarissa gives her a clarinet. The girl's
affinity for the instrument is immediate. Almost as immediate as
her father's growing fear and disapproval. Not only is music one
area he cannot share with his beloved daughter, but the gift
revives old sibling resentments he has against Clarissa.
</P>
<P>
   Rather abruptly, the movie cuts to 10 years later, when the
nearly adult Lara (Sylvie Testud) must choose between her family's
dependency and her growing desire to study at a Berlin
conservatory. It's a universal situation. The tensions that arise
when a child strikes out on her own are made more poignantly urgent
by her parents' hearing impairment.
</P>
<P>
   An Oscar nominee for best foreign language film (it lost to
``Character''), ``Beyond Silence'' is a lovely, sensitive movie
that lacks dramatic cohesion. Somehow its two halves fail to fit
together. But filmmaker Caroline Link has given us characters who
concern us, and she has cast them well (especially the two Laras).
And if the tear-jerker father-daughter ending is exactly what we
expected, it's also satisfying because it's exactly what we wanted
to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond Silence''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Tatjana Trieb and Sylvie Testud. Directed by Caroline
Link. In German with subtitles. Rated PG-13 for brief nudity.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A film worth listening to.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
