<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7167 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-LANDGIRLS-COX     06-25 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-LANDGIRLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Land Girls' muddied by melodrama
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   During World War II, which Prime Minister Winston Churchill
called his nation's ``finest hour,'' everyone in England pulled
together to save the world from Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   The new movie ``The Land Girls,'' directed by David Leland,
focuses on Britain's equivalent of Rosie the Riveter. When
England's farmers traded their overalls for uniforms, young women
volunteered to take their places and keep the country fed. Thus we
meet three single city girls ready, willing and able to get all
mucked up in the name of king and country. Their war zone is a
dairy farm in Dorset. Their commander, so to speak, is a taciturn
farmer who isn't overjoyed with what the government thinks are
suitable farmhands.
</P>
<P>
   His new workers are a mixed lot. Stella (Catherine McCormack) is
a soulful, strong-willed beauty with a fiance in the service. Ag
(Rachel Weisz) is an upper-crust type, snobby but ultimately
lovable. Prue (Anna Friel) is the earthy one who knows that
haylofts are good for more than storage.
</P>
<P>
   The lushly beautiful English countryside holds up its end, and
there's an inherent fascination in this little-known slice of
history. But ``The Land Girls'' isn't just set in the 1940s; it
could easily have been made in the 1940s. Its old-fashioned
approach to character and story is mildly bothersome at first, then
downright irritating. The three leads act like silly twits, and
it's difficult to become involved with them.
</P>
<P>
   You can't fault the cast, especially McCormack, who was so
dazzling in ``Dangerous Beauty.'' But despite the actors' efforts,
the picture feels clumsy and manipulative, much like a
run-of-the-mill romance novel. Leland had a hit about a decade ago
with ``Wish You Were Here,'' another period piece. In retrospect,
you have to wonder if that movie's sparkle had more to do with star
Emily Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Land Girls'' comes off as more outlandishly soapish than
genuinely affecting. It's a missed opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Land Girls''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Catherine McCormack, Rachel Weisz and Anna Friel.
Directed by David Leland. Rated R for sex (intercourse). 1 hour, 55
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Not anyone's finest hour.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
