<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7168 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-SIGHT-COX     06-25 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SIGHT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This caper's a sight better than most
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's easy to believe that Jack Foley has 200 bank robberies
under his belt. And other kinds of conquests, too. As played by
George Clooney, he knocks over a Florida SunTrust with a sunny,
seductive ease that makes the bank teller respond to his ``have a
nice day'' exit with ``You, too.''
</P>
<P>
   In the crooked world of ``Out of Sight,'' Foley's courtly
professionalism raises him above a sea of small-timers who figure
no crime is too crazy to attempt, no jackpot too puny for the risk
it entails. Jack is methodical, intelligent, addicted to his job.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for Karen Sisco (Jennifer Lopez), a federal
marshal whom we first spy girlishly enraptured by the handgun her
dad (Dennis Farina) has bought for her birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Karen and Jack have a few other things in common: They don't
always have perfect days in their chosen lines of work. That
explains why Jack lands behind bars (not for the first time). And
why Karen winds up kidnapped by him on the night he makes a
jailbreak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a federal marshal and you're under arrest,'' she shouts.
He tosses her into the trunk of her own car and climbs in as his
pal Buddy (Ving Rhames) guns the gas.
</P>
<P>
   In a Hollywood lousy with meet-cute scenes, this one's a doozy.
And it has novelist Elmore Leonard's genre-bending fingerprints all
over it. In outline, he's given us a screwball romantic comedy. It
just happens to be propelled by firepower, betrayal, bloodshed _
and the erotic gravitational pull between Clooney and Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   The movie quickly gets Karen out of that trunk and sends her and
Jack on separate, but linked, paths. He plans his next robbery, she
a way to bust him. But our main concern is when and how they'll get
together. It's a '90s ``Romeo and Juliet,'' but what's keeping them
apart is their work.
</P>
<P>
   After some not-great movie adaptations (``52 Pick-Up,'' etc.),
Hollywood has figured Leonard out, most notably with ``Get
Shorty.'' It seems that the slightly absurd, postmodern realities
of the '90s have come to reflect his savory stew-plots, simmering
full of pungent characters and odd spices.
</P>
<P>
   Jack's ex-wife (Catherine Keener) answers the phone carrying a
white rabbit; she's a magician's assistant. For another character
in ``Out of Sight,'' clumsiness is more than a quirk; in a
sick-humor payoff, it becomes a matter of life or death. Like
playwright David Mamet, Leonard creates an alternative universe
that looks realistic but is highly stylized.
</P>
<P>
   Director Steven Soderbergh knows to play the film as a fable,
underlining the visual contrasts when the action skips from sunny
South Florida to snowy Detroit. The narrowing plot involves a
white-collar ex-cellmate of Jack's (Albert Brooks) and a fortune in
uncut diamonds. But the main pleasure comes from the movie's
digressions, such as a scene in which three businessmen take turns
trying to pick up Lopez at a hotel bar.
</P>
<P>
   As for the stars, Clooney and Lopez each get to prove their
street credentials, facing down various thugs. (Lopez's response to
a guy who invites her to ``tussle'' is a classic of self-defense
minimalism.) So do the actors make us believe they're a con and a
fed? Not even close. It doesn't matter: They're sexy and magnetic
in the old-school style of movie stars, floating on the shoulders
of the film's rich supporting cast.
</P>
<P>
   That cast is the best thing about the flick, with every role
filled by an interesting actor. Rhames and Brooks are their
reliable selves, while Steve Zahn steals all his scenes as a
doped-up felon who gets stuck working with Jack's old jailhouse
nemesis, Maurice ``Snoopy'' Miller. Don Cheadle makes that
character all the scarier by downplaying his ruthlessness.
</P>
<P>
   The movie isn't perfect. It's too long, and toward the end it
meanders when it should be tightening up. So it's not totally outta
sight, but ``Out of Sight'' is still an unexpected adult pleasure
in a silly, shallow summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of Sight''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring George Clooney and Jennifer Lopez. Directed by Steven
Soderbergh. Rated R for language. 2 hours, 9 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Another shaggy winner from the brain that cooked up
``Get Shorty.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
