<SLUG> BC-PETS-PRODUCTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stores hoping new products to become people's pet projects
 &HT;    By Bette Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--Browsing through the national Pet Products Trade Show,
which opened Thursday at the Georgia World Congress Center, we
sampled some new things that may turn up in pet stores soon:
</P>
<P>
   -- Wordy Birdy, by Wordy Birdy Products. $30. Want to teach
Petey to talk but don't have the time? Wordy Birdy is a tape
recorder that stays on indefinitely (or until the batteries run
down). Just record what you want Petey to say, then leave the
gadget running and running and running. If Petey isn't driven
insane, in a month or so he might be repeating the message himself.
</P>
<P>
   -- The CatFinder, by Pet Friendly. $40. ``They can run, but they
can't hide,'' says the packaging for this product, a radio-remote
doodad that attaches to kitty's collar. The manufacturer also
suggests using it to find car keys, TV remotes and cordless phones.
Wouldn't it be great if it worked on teenagers, too?
</P>
<P>
   -- Aqua Dog, by Black Sheep. $8-$15. Fluorescent pink, orange,
yellow and green life preservers for dogs.
</P>
<P>
   -- Fool-A-Bug, by Alternative Control Systems. $3-$6. According
to the manufacturer, the patented design of a Fool-A-Bug bowl
messes up insects' navigational systems so they move on to greener
pastures.
</P>
<P>
   -- Emergency Feeding Kit, by Pet-Ag. $7. A small package
containing everything needed to feed an orphan kitten, hamster,
raccoon, badger, porcupine or other small animal. The kit also
includes a guide to ``saving little lives.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The Canine Oral Hygiene Machine, by TheraFlow. $150. A Water
Pik-type device for doggies.
</P>
<P>
   -- Quantum, by Mensa Products. $7. You know those embarrassing
moments when you're sitting on the couch with your significant
other, when suddenly a malodorous scent fills the air and everyone
looks at Precious? Quantum claims to be the first internal stool
and urine deodorizer for cats. Enough said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Serenity Pet Casket. $35. It's pretty, lined with blue satin
and holds any deceased loved ones weighing up to 15 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   -- The ActivityTower, by Petmate Pro Kat Furrniture. $179.
Salvador Dali meets George Jetson in this zany, stylish play tower
for kitties, with integrated toys and sleeping alcoves. The
furniture line includes sleeping beds that look like dripping TVs,
chairs and bureau drawers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
