<HEADER>
A7177 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     06-25 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI, CAPTRIATI LEFT WITH THEIR MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Andre Agassi is saying, ``Life doesn't wait for you,''
and Jennifer Capriati is saying nothing that enlightening, just
packing her bags and wondering how she could lose to somebody ready
for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   He's right, she's bewildered, and those Sisters Sledgehammer _
Venus and Serena _ are what's happening at Wimbledon if you're
talking about latter-day bundles to Britain from the USA.
</P>
<P>
   It's not so far back that the ``Jenerator'' _ Jenny Capriati _
was throwing off sparks and power around this place, bumping off
the champ, Martina Navratilova, and perching in the semifinals. She
was 15. It was 1991. Or that Andre Agassi was making rubber lemons
magically vanish with his gut-strung wand as foes scuttled about
feverishly and vainly trying to find them. He was 22, the new
champion. It was 1992.
</P>
<P>
   A twinkling ago, but a century in sports. Jenny and Andre were
the child phenoms of their day _ Thursdays _ but this time they
were out on the curb among remnants in the Wimbledon discard pile,
along with the empty champagne bottles and the plastic bowls that
contained the signature treat, overpriced strawberries and cream.
</P>
<P>
   Andre was hanging from a very high window sill and Jenny from a
very low ranking when they reported for duty Thursday, an afternoon
subjecting 36,003 parishioners to a blend of rain, sunshine, and
tricky gusts. Once Professor Nick Bollettieri's glittering pupil,
Agassi was left dangling perilously at nightfall Wednesday by his
successor as teacher's pet, 20-year-old Tommy Haas. Haas led, two
sets to one, towering, at 6 feet 2 inches, over Andre in stature
and, surprisingly, in shotmaking.
</P>
<P>
   When they returned to Centre Court for Act II, Haas started
shakily, losing serve. Andre held for 2-0 and had two break points
for 3-0. The old pro was OK. Not for long. Haas, who grew up at the
Bollettieri Academy in Bradenton, Fla., ``looking up to Andre,
admiring him,'' turned on his own muscle and won their Thursday set
to complete a 4-6, 6-1, 7-6 (7-4), 6-4 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi feels ``there's more good tennis in me. It'll come back
like his form did for Michael Jordan. But it took him a while after
he quit baseball. I have time _ but life doesn't wait.'' It does
when Jordan takes wing.
</P>
<P>
   The dismal facts, however: Agassi has lost his last two starts
to relative nobodies, and these matches happened to be
first-rounders at the French (Russian qualifier Marat Safin) and
now Wimbledon and No. 44 Haas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre used to play with me once in a while at the academy,''
says Haas, a German, who acts and talks like an American kid but is
billed in the fatherland as the next Boris Becker. ``But I couldn't
stay close to him the first time we played as pros, Scottsdale in
March (6-2, 6-1). So this is very special, to beat Andre on the
court where he won Wimbledon in 1992.''
</P>
<P>
   Capriati, drifting, rudderless, ranked No. 151 and in on a
freebie as a wild card, hadn't passed through the tall iron Doherty
Gates at the All England Club entrance since 1993, when she lost a
tough quarterfinal to the champion, Steffi Graf. It was a last
moment of glory before her personal troubles hijacked the immense
promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you know, I think my comeback is going well, you know,''
she says, chewing gum and scores of conversational ``you know's.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to be back here after so long. I think I'm playing
even better than in 1991 and 1992.''
</P>
<P>
   The flimsy 4-6, 6-4, 6-2 defeat by another wild card,
34-year-old, downwinding Lori McNeil, testifies otherwise, speaks
of self-delusion.
</P>
<P>
   You feel for Jennifer. Rich, a good kid, but in need of
direction to find out what she really wants. If it is tennis, then
she requires a coach to get her in shape, care about her _ far from
the father who made her the family provider at 13, pushed her and
played her when she was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Products of a different, more careful parental environment,
Venus and Serena Williams are cruising joyfully toward a
fourth-round collision. Venus, setting a female speed record with a
125-mile-per-hour serve for one of six aces _ not many guys can
match that _ beat Barbara Schett, 6-1, 6-2, in her second-rounder.
Serena, in a ``really special moment, my first time on Centre
Court,'' whomped the Croatian teen whiz, 16-year-old Mirjana Lucic,
6-3, 6-0, in 48 minutes, undercutting big sister's clocking by five
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like grass,'' says Serena after merely her fifth
match lifetime on same. ``But it doesn't matter what surface. I
adjust fast. But you know what I don't like about Venus? She's so
much taller than I am (4 inches at 6-2). She can serve faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus retorts, with a great smile, ``You know what I don't like
about Serena? She steals my cookies. Oatmeal raisin today. But I
watched her first set. Serena's a juggernaut. I predict the winner
of our match will win the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   What does it take to beat a juggernaut? ``A nemesis,'' replies
Venus. ``I'm a nemesis.'' Laughter takes over.
</P>
<P>
   Andre and Jennifer can remember when they were juggernauts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
