<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7180 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-LEONARD-COX     06-25 1577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-LEONARD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leonard: Hollywood's bookmaker
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beverly Hills, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Easy Does It'' read the bumper stickers handed out by Alcoholics
Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   And Elmore Leonard, who's always been forthright about how AA
helped him more than 20 years ago, does it easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just sit down and write the book and it works,'' he says.
``Instead of trying to write the book.'' And he mimes how he looks
when he's trying too hard, hunched over, fingertips downturned and
rigid like monster claws, hovering over an imaginary typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   Walker Percy called him ``the greatest crime writer of our time,
perhaps ever.'' His stories, with their pimp-walk prose and their
lovable lowlife heroes, are oddly structured, always a couple of
narrative bubbles off plumb. But ever since 1985's ``Glitz,''
they've invariably been best sellers, through ``Cuba Libre''
earlier this year, and bound to continue with ``Be Cool,'' the
sequel to ``Get Shorty,'' due out early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been writing for 47 years; I ought to be able to throw
some people together and have something come out of it,'' he says,
sounding a bit side-of-the-mouth insouciant, like one of his
characters, although in a more measured, Midwestern way.
</P>
<P>
   When readers visualize him, it's probably in those American
Express ads from the late '80s, the Annie Leibovitz photo of
Leonard on a beach at sunset, sitting in a straight-back chair,
typewriter in his lap, black cap on his head. Doing it easy.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent sunny L.A. day, though, the godfather of the modern
American crime novel is sitting in a hotel suite in the Four
Seasons Hotel, casually elegant in an expensive-looking
cream-colored sweater over white shirt and bluejeans. (Leonard
describes his characters' wardrobes usually even before he
describes the firepower they're carrying.) He's having a smoke,
tapping the ashes into a china coffee saucer because the room is
ashtray-free.
</P>
<P>
   At 72, he's as focused as a professional hit man.
</P>
<P>
   Saying: ``I always considered myself a commercial writer. I want
a lot of people to read my books. I want to make money doing
this.''
</P>
<P>
   And making money he is. The novels are a good business, but the
big score, the kind his characters are always seeking, comes from
the movies. Leonard sold the rights to 1996's ``Out of Sight'' for
$2.5 million; it opens Friday, starring George Clooney, Jennifer
Lopez and Ving Rhames.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one of his 34 novels have been made into movies or are
being made into a movie or are optioned, which means Leonard gets
some money whether a movie gets made or not.
</P>
<P>
   Quentin Tarantino, who turned ``Rum Punch'' into ``Jackie
Brown,'' has the rights to film three more Leonard novels. ABC has
a summer TV series based on ``Maximum Bob,'' the novel about a
comically corrupt Florida judge; coming in late July, it stars Beau
Bridges. The Coen brothers of ``Fargo'' fame are adapting ``Cuba
Libre,'' and John Travolta is reading an advance copy of ``Be
Cool'' to decide if he'll reprise the role of Chili Palmer he
swaggered through in ``Get Shorty.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the buzz in Hollywood is that the movie business
``gets'' Leonard. At last. That the days of straight-to-video
schlock and Burt Reynolds smirking his way through 1985's ``Stick''
are long gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott Frank was the first to understand how to adapt Elmore
Leonard,'' says Clooney, referring to the young screenwriter who
wrote the movie versions of ``Get Shorty'' and ``Out of Sight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Screenwriters will just take what the plot is, but Elmore's
plots aren't really that interesting,'' Clooney continues. ``Scott
understood that it was about characters and dialogue, that
everything the characters do is just organic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a nearly Dickensian ability to create major and minor
characters who stretch credulity but never break it,'' says Rod
Cockshutt, who teaches a course on detective fiction at North
Carolina State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who are able to roll with the punches and
look at life with a jaundiced and ironic eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Character and attitude. Tarantino understood the attitude of
Leonard's characters, and the two have a little mutual admiration
riff going. The director likes to tell a story about how, as a
teenager, he ``boosted'' a copy of Leonard's novel ``The Switch''
from a store, and Leonard praised ``Jackie Brown'' more than some
critics did.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Leonard describing how ``Out of Sight'' came to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a picture in the Detroit paper of a woman, a federal
marshal, in front of the courthouse in Miami, with a shotgun on her
hip. Kind of a provocative pose. And I thought, `That's a book.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been thinking about doing a professional bank robber, a
clean-cut bank robber. And get them together and see what happens.
They're both attracted to one another and it's too bad they meet
under these circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then there was a prison break in Palm Beach County in 1995
when six Cubans tunneled out. So I'll have my guy follow them out.
And the girl is there for some reason, and I'll see what happens.
Like all my books, I make it up as I go along.''
</P>
<P>
   For some writers, hearing that their novels sound as if they
were written to be made into movie is a grievous insult. Leonard
brings it up himself, with a chuckle. ``Be Cool,'' which gets
former loan shark Chili Palmer into the rock music business, ``was
obviously written to sell as a movie. No doubt about it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard still lives in Birmingham, Mich. He's lived in the
Detroit area since he was 10, after being born in New Orleans, and
although many of his books reflect a native's knowledge of the
Florida Gold Coast, he's only visited there, never moved in.
</P>
<P>
   Every weekday morning he goes into the living room, which he
converted into his office, switches on jazz (bebop or big band) and
writes; four pages on an average day. He uses a $150 Mont Blanc pen
(he started with a 39-cent Scripto mechanical pencil, he jokes) and
unlined yellow pads that he has specially made at a print shop.
That's what he wrote on when he worked at an advertising agency in
the '50s and '60s, turning out Chevrolet commercials by day and
western short stories at night. (A collection of Leonard's western
shorts, ``The Tonto Woman,'' will be published in September by
Delacorte.)
</P>
<P>
   When the pulp magazines that published his westerns dried up,
Leonard turned to crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't influenced by any crime writers,'' he says. ``I
didn't come out of the Raymond Chandler school. My style developed
with the writers I read and studied, beginning with Hemingway and
then through John O'Hara.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, with a cult following but still nowhere in sight of a
best seller or a major review, Leonard was divorced from his first
wife, Beverly, the mother of his five children, and also
successfully stopped drinking after several attempts with the help
of Alcoholics Anonymous. He has remarried twice (his second wife
died), but he's stayed with his sobriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally the program caught on, or rather I caught on to the
program and realized what was involved was changing your whole
attitude. I haven't been to a meeting now in 12 years or more, but
I still think about the principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of not taking yourself so seriously is the first
thing. The idea of not looking at writing as the most important
thing in the world, but just something that I do.''
</P>
<P>
   `` I have a lot of fun watching as the characters come on stage
and become real for me,'' he says. ``They have to be able to talk
or else they're out.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard gets to his talking through listening. Although he
employs a full-time research assistant, he likes to hang out with
cops and listen to the details of their jobs, the little things
like how just the sound of a shotgun being racked will shake most
perps. He has a loose network of contacts, like an old friend who's
a private eye in Miami, who introduced him to the real Chili
Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   The real Chili, like the fictional, was a low-level mob guy who
needed a new, more legit, job when his godfather got whacked. The
real Chili became a legman for the Miami private eye, while the
fictional Chili, largely Leonard's invention, went into the movie
business, was played by John Travolta, and told Gene Hackman, ``I'm
the guy who's telling you the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   That line is pure Leonard: seemingly simple, but in context it
has an undercurrent of m enace and the suggestion of an existential
chuckle. It's pure Leonard because it is Leonard. The guy who's
telling us the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   ELMORE JOHN LEONARD
</P>
<P>
   -- Born: Oct. 11, 1925, New Orleans
</P>
<P>
   -- Home: Birmingham, Mich., a Detroit suburb
</P>
<P>
   -- Family: Married to Beverly (divorced, 1977); Joan (died
1993); Christine. Five children.
</P>
<P>
   -- Religion: Roman Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   -- Military: U.S. Navy, 1943-46
</P>
<P>
   -- Books: 34 novels, including ``Hombre,'' ``The Hunted,''
``City Primeval,'' ``Glitz'' (first best seller), ``LaBrava,''
``Killshot,'' ``Cuba Libre.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Screenplays: 12, including ``The Moonshine War,'' ``Joe
Kidd.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Awards: Mystery Writers of America Grand Master Award, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   -- Quote: ``I sit there and think sometimes, `Jeez, I don't
believe it, I'm sittin' here all by myself makin' up a story that
somebody's gonna give me a lot of money for.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
