<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELAY-RELIGION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAY LEADS GOP DEFENSE OF FIRED NEW YORK TEACHER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Conservative Republicans led by House Majority Whip
Tom DeLay called for the reinstatement Thursday of a New York City
substitute teacher who was fired for allegedly sharing her
Pentecostal beliefs with her students to help them deal with the
death of a classmate.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal last week of Bronx sixth-grade teacher Mildred
Rosario provoked an outcry of protest from leaders of the Christian
right, whose demands that Republican leaders take a more activist
role in pushing their ``family values'' agenda has been paying off
lately.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have Republicans embraced the socially conservative
agenda, but they have moved to put much of it into law over the
objections of moderates in the party and some in the business
community who have threatened to scale back financial contributions
to the party if the GOP leadership does not stop courting the
religious right.
</P>
<P>
   Those rumblings did not stop DeLay and other GOP lawmakers from
rushing to Rosario's defense at a news conference with Family
Research Council President Gary Bauer, a leading GOP social
conservative. They also gathered later with Bauer, who is
considering a run for the presidency in 2000, to hail the
introduction in Congress of the Ten Commandments Defense Act, which
would allow the display of individual expressions of religious
faith on government property.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, R-Texas, opened the Rosario news conference by offering a
prayer for the 43-year-old Bronx woman, whom he described as a
``blessed teacher'' willing to put her faith on the line to help
her students.
</P>
<P>
   He called on New York education officials to reinstate her,
saying that she should not have been fired ``for offering comfort
to her students during a time of tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it that people object to? What was wrong with bringing
that kind of message to children?'' DeLay asked.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Riley, R-Ala., said the Rosario case was an example of
what he called a ``religious intolerance'' that denies people of
faith the right to express themselves. Riley said it was time for
the nation ``to re-examine its moral soul'' and begin to teach
children that ``God is not a dirty word.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, who called Rosario ``a decent God-fearing woman,'' also
praised the teacher for ``reminding'' her students about ``who made
them'' and ``what the source of their freedom is.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosario, a substitute bilingual teacher, was fired last week
after education officials determined that she had violated
separation of church and state laws by crossing the line between
teaching students about religion and advocating a particular
religious view.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said Rosario had admitted in a statement that she
had promoted her own Pentecostal views of Christianity after being
asked by one of her students if a classmate who had drowned
recently was with God in heaven. According to reports about the
firing, Rosario encouraged the students to ask Jesus to save them
as she walked around the room patting her charges on the head.
</P>
<P>
   By championing Rosario's cause, Republicans are hoping to shore
up what was until just a few weeks ago a shaky relationship with
the party's social and religious conservatives. With control of
Congress hanging in the balance in this fall's mid-term election,
DeLay has been leading the charge to the right as GOP leaders
search for votes.
</P>
<P>
   Voter turnout this year ``is predicted to be one the lowest
ever,'' said one Republican aide, responsible for helping to
maintain the ties between House Speaker Newt Gingrich's leadership
team and the party's social and religious conservatives. The aide
said the ``the conservative wing of the party, the Christian Right
... or whatever you want to call them,'' are among the party's most
loyal supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is to get them to the polls by reminding them that we
best represent their views,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
