<HEADER>
A7184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER26-COX     06-25 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HBO's ``Trumpet'' doesn't dress up this war
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This isn't your father's World War II movie. The ``good war''
gets a post-'Nam rejiggering in HBO's ``When Trumpets Fade'' (9
p.m. EDT Saturday). Call it ``Apocalypse, Then'': a grisly, grimly
chilling trek into the nature of war, bravery, cowardice, survival
_ all the stuff that's large, ambiguous and has life-or-death
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, if I can help you in any way without endangering my own
life, I won't hesitate,'' Private David Manning (Ron Eldard), tells
a superior on a battlefield so desperately dismal he can get away
with saying that. ``But I'm not taking a bullet for anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not good enough,'' his superior answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's as good as it gets,'' Manning says, and that's that.
</P>
<P>
   Manning is his company's lone survivor during the three-month
Battle of Hurtgen Forest in 1944, on the Beligian-German border.
More than 24,000 U.S. troops were killed or wounded during this
barely-known siege, which had little strategic importance and was
called ``the death factory'' by those who fought it (it was largely
forgotten in the wake of the Battle of the Bulge, which began a few
days later). The movie opens with Manning leaving a fellow soldier
in the field to save his own skin, and he now sees survival as his
only goal.
</P>
<P>
   But the prospects for survival here become so dire that Manning
keeps finding himself promoted _ he's one of the few experienced
soldiers in a killing field constantly replenished with fresh human
fodder. Finally, Manning's only way out is heroism.
</P>
<P>
   As directed by John Irvin (whose previous war movies include
``Hamburger Hill'' and ``The Dogs of War''), the bleak landscape is
populated with a terrifically living-dead cast: Zak Orth as pudgy,
fresh meat; Martin Donovan as the captain who follows orders he
knows doom his men; Dylan Bruno as the sergeant who has Manning's
number.
</P>
<P>
   It all moves with a stylized slow-motion that piles tension on
top of itself; battle scenes then flash with severed limbs and open
wounds. It's all at ground level; there are times when you have to
spit the dirt out of your mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The post-modern take on it all only makes the tragedy more
unsettling; when the credits roll over soldiers shuffling through
the battlefied, Bing Crosby croons ``White Christmas.'' It'll break
your heart.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Esposito joins ``Homicide''
</P>
<P>
   Character actor Giancarlo Esposito will join the cast of NBC's
cop drama ``Homicide: Life on the Street'' next season playing the
estranged son of Lt. Al Giardello (Yaphet Kotto).
</P>
<P>
   Although his character is still being fleshed out and hasn't
been named yet, Esposito will debut in the season opener as an FBI
agent assigned to the violent crimes unit in Baltimore where the
show is set.
</P>
<P>
   Esposito is best known for his performances in several Spike Lee
films including ``Do The Right Thing,'' ``School Daze'' and ``Mo
Better Blues.'' He also played a cigaratte smoking G-man on the
trail of Keyser Soze in the Oscar-winning nouveau noir thriller
``The Usual Suspects.''
</P>
<P>
   ``CHiPS'' on patrol...again
</P>
<P>
   Hold onto your handlebars. TNT is reuniting Erik Estrada and
Larry Wilcox for ``CHiPS '99,'' a two-hour update of their 1970s
series (could it have been a drama?) about California motorcycle
cops who headed out on the highway each week accompanied by blaring
disco music. The plotline will go something like this: following a
15-year self-imposed retirement from the California Highway Patrol,
Ponch (that would be Estrada) reunites with Jon (that would be
Wilcox) to break up a car theft ring. What will they ride? BMW
motorcycles. The film, to air this fall just ahead of 1999, will be
directed by Jon Cassar (``Assault on Devil's Island'').
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Lyle V. Harris and Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
