<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7192 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-EXPANSION-2TAKES-     06-25 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-EXPANSION-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG DECISIONS FOR THE PREDATORS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ By early Friday afternoon the Nashville
Predators will finally have a bunch of names and faces that will
fill the franchise's shirts for the start of its inaugural National
Hockey League season.
</P>
<P>
   And the names are?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been going over that for months now,'' said Predators
general manager David Poile, the former Washington Capitals boss
who was hired a year ago to steer the expansion club's destiny.
``Based on who we thought would be available, we'd make a list, and
then at the end of every month, we'd tear it up and start over
again, because as deals would occur, everything would change.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes came fast and furious last week as a number of the
NHL's Original 26 conducted what amounted to a shell game sur
glace. There were four netminders moved in trades, including former
Bruin/Capital Bill Ranford, whom the Predators had targeted as
available in the expansion draft. By the weekend, all four had been
protected by their new clubs, leading Poile and his pals to
reconfigure their wish lists and perhaps simultaneously reach for
the jumbo-sized bottle of antacid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had interest in all four of them,'' said Poile, who'll
submit his finalized list to NHL bosses Friday morning and then
attend an afternoon news conference to announce his team. ``Our
plan was to take five goalies _ the maximum we're allowed _ but we
may have to rethink that strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ranford went from Washington to Tampa Bay. Ken Wreggett was
flipped from Pittsburgh to Calgary. Eric Fichaud left the Islanders
for the Oilers. Steve Shields departed as Dominik Hasek's backup
here and now will block pucks, and plenty of 'em, for the San Jose
Sharks. Not all four would have suited up for the Predators, of
course, but a couple of extra worthy netminders would have allowed
Poile to make follow-up deals that could have made his club deeper
at defense and/or forward and better able to compete when the puck
is dropped in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to take anything away from what the Florida Panthers did
collectively as an expansion team,'' mused Poile, ``but you take
John Vanbiesbrouck out of the equation and would they have had that
kind of early success? His impact was huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps ironically, Vanbiesbrouck is one of the netminders Poile
can place on his roster. Unable to come to contract terms with
their fan favorite, the Panthers have left the 35-year-old
Vanbiesbrouck exposed in the draft. But Vanbiesbrouck comes with a
few caveats: his age, his asking price ($5 million a year or
better), and the fact that he becomes an unrestricted free agent
Wednesday. Given the last condition, the Predators could draft him
only to see their golden goalie solution turn to fool's gold in
less than a week.
</P>
<P>
   High-scoring winger Brett Hull and goalies Curtis Joseph and
Mike Richter are three more of the UFAs available to the Predators.
It's not likely, however, that the Predators will bite. Marquee
players cost a lot of money _ many established clubs are loath to
reach into their pockets for more than one, if that many _ and a
name up in lights doesn't always equate to points in the win
column. There are few slam dunks on the frozen pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's the direction we're going in,'' said
Poile, asked specifically about his interest in Hull, who is
rumored to be headed from St. Louis to Chicago when July 1 arrives.
``I think I have too much respect for the game being a team game,
believing that one player rarely is going to mean the difference to
a club. As the years go by, we'd like to be able to say we were
better the second year than the first, even better the third year.
We know there's no quick fix here.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Picking through leftovers
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like all the NHL expansion teams before them, the Predators must
sort through a pile of has-beens and castaways in hopes of slapping
together a club that will be, at the very least, entertaining. Had
the likes of Messrs. Ranford, Wreggett, et al been available, the
chances of doing just that would have been much greater. Instead,
about the best the Predators can do is grab a polished role player
like the Red Wings' Doug Brown, now owner of two Stanley Cup rings,
and hope to get lucky with some younger players who might have been
underused elsewhere and suddenly thrive once they get loads of ice
time thrust upon them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the situation's right, we might be able to hit on one or
two; that's what you hope,'' said Poile. ``Look at the way (Brian)
Skrudland played when he got to Florida _ better than anywhere he'd
played before. And they picked up a couple of guys like Paul Laus
(from Pittsburgh) and Bill Lindsay (from Quebec), minor leaguers
who, once given the chance, really blossomed.''
</P>
<P>
   For the expansion fee of $75 million, these are slim pickings.
But it has always been that way. The NHL's Lords of the Boards are
always happy to collect the expansion cash, but they're deathly
afraid to part with personnel to make the new kid on the block
anything more than a skating version of the Washington Generals.
The expansion formula is a cash-but-no-carry business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the czar of expansions,'' chuckled Bill Torrey, who
oversaw the Islanders' entry in 1972 and then the Panthers' arrival
in 1993. ``Let's put that another way: I'm the survivor of
expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   Torrey's Islander team debuted a moribund 12-60-6, the worst
opening in league history. The Panthers were a far more respectable
33-34-17, the best in league history, thanks in large part to
goalies of Vanbiesbrouck's ilk being made available on expansion
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``No two expansion drafts are entirely alike,'' said Torrey, an
NHL Hall of Famer in the builders category. ``In my personal
experience, it changed dramatically, as well it should have when
you're talking about an expansion price that went from $2 million
to $50 million. At that price, you'd better get something better
than a ribbon around the package.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
