</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-SAFETY-385&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO SAFETY: ACHILLES' HEEL FOR GASOLINE TRUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Also moved in ``f'' category.)  
(lb) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gasoline tanker-truck accidents usually kill only a
few people at a time, but they can be among the best remembered and
disruptive highway accidents because they can close roads for
months. The reason, according to the National Transportation Safety
Board, is bad design.
</P>
<P>
   But the Transportation Department, which regulates tanker
trucks, is resisting any change, because of tax laws.
</P>
<P>
   The tanks on gasoline tanker trucks are pretty tough, but their
loading lines, the pipes through which they are filled and emptied,
are not, and they are at just the height to be struck by
automobiles, according to the National Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   The board issued a report last month on an accident in Yonkers,
N.Y., in October 1997 in which a sedan ran a red light and hit a
tank truck under an overpass of the Gov. Thomas E. Dewey Thruway.
The car driver was killed, and the ensuing fire necessitated $7
million in repairs to the overpass, which had to be closed for six
months. ``The significant element of this crash is not its cause as
much as its severity,'' the transportation safety board said.
</P>
<P>
   The overpass was partly melted when the thousands of gallons of
gasoline in the tank burned, but that gasoline would probably not
have ignited, experts say, but for the approximately 28 gallons in
the loading lines, which ruptured and poured into the car's hot
engine compartment.
</P>
<P>
   The board lined up 12 different passenger-car models near the
loading pipes of a tank truck and found that all of them were at
the right height to hit the lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department's Research and Special Programs
Administration, which is in charge of hazardous materials, proposed
more protection of those lines in 1985. But when the rule took
effect in 1990, an exception was made for petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
   One possible solution mentioned by the board would be to drain
the gasoline from the lines and pump it back into the tank.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with this plan, however, said William Vincent,
director of policy at the hazardous-materials office, is that
states tax the gasoline as it leaves the tank and enters the pipes,
and if that gasoline were put back into the tanks, it would be
taxed twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to figure out what to do to respond,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Asphalt Rumble
</P>
<P>
   As highways are being rebuilt or repaved around the United
States, engineers have been adding ``rumble strips'' to the
shoulders. These bands of asphalt are grooved in a continuous
pattern that sends a mild jolt of vibration to a driver who drifts
out of the roadway. The goal is to reduce the number of accidents
involving drivers who fall asleep at the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure how effective this is, partly because it is hard
to tell how many accidents are caused by people falling asleep at
the wheel. From 10 percent to 24 percent of crashes are estimated
to involve fatigue or inattention of some kind, but these numbers
are based on guesswork.
</P>
<P>
   Some drivers do not live to talk about why they crashed, and
others survive but do not admit what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have estimates, but there's an awful lot of guessing,''
said Dr. Richard Pain, a research coordinator at the Transportation
Research Board, a federally financed agency that's part of the
National Research Council.
</P>
<P>
   At an accident scene, Pain said, ``It's extraordinarily
difficult for an officer to determine, unless someone says, `I was
asleep at the wheel.'''
</P>
<P>
   The New York State Thruway Authority, which is served by a
single police agency (State Police Troop T) and thus can gather
statistics well, has published what safety experts say are the most
authoritative figures so far. They show that rumble strips have
reduced by two-thirds the accidents believed to have been caused by
drivers' falling asleep, and have produced a fatality reduction of
three-quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The 641-mile New York State Thruway system finished installing
grooves in 1996; in the previous five years, it averaged 12
sleeping-driver fatalities a year, and in 1996 and 1997, three
fatalities a year.
</P>
<P>
   (The experiment is not pure, however, because Troop T has also
been conducting a campaign to reduce drunken driving and increase
seat-belt use, both of which would also reduce the number of fatal
vehicle accidents.)
</P>
<P>
   Shoulder grooves work best on long, straight sections, engineers
say. Many people are killed in accidents when a car leaves a curve
on a country road, but grooves usually will not help in that
situation, engineers say, because the reason for those accidents is
not driver inattention but excessive speed.
</P>
<P>
   At the American Association of State Highway Transportation
Officials, which recently endorsed the use of rumble strips, David
Hensing, the deputy executive director, said the strips were very
cheap to install during repaving and could often be done by running
a wheel made of steel rods over softened asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hold their ability to resonate for quite some period of
time,'' he said. Pain of the Transportation Research Board said
they cost as little as 25 cents a foot when installed during
repaving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
