<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7197 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-EXPANSION-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     06-25 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-EXPANSION-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BUFFALO, N.Y.: ... the package.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Torrey's Islanders went on to capture the Stanley Cup in 1980,
less than eight years after opening for business in Uniondale. The
key to quick success wasn't the expansion draft, however. Hardly.
The Islanders' four consecutive Cups were rooted in some shrewd
picks in the amateur draft, including the likes of Denis Potvin
(No. 1 in '73), Clark Gillies (4/'74), Bryan Trotter (22/'74), and
Mike Bossy (15/'77). The expansion draft brought the Islanders
Eddie Westfall, a valuable role player from the Bruins, and unknown
netminder Billy Smith (from Los Angeles), who blossomed into a
franchise goalie, but it otherwise was a field full of more turnips
than dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got my list, I got sick,'' recalled Torrey, thinking
back to the the players made available in '72. ``Here I am in the
New York market, with the Rangers and Canadiens running 1-2 in the
league. The Rangers have got guys like (Rod) Gilbert, (Vic)
Hadfield, (Eddie) Giacomin, the Cat (Emile Francis). I'm thinking,
`Look at this!' I sure can tell you I didn't turn to my scouts and
say, `Whoopee, guys, we're gonna have some fun now.' You didn't
have to be Einstein to figure out we were in trouble.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
No helping hands
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   History has it that Wren Blair, then the GM in Minnesota,
stopped by the Flames' table in '72, the same day the Islanders
were picking, and congratulated Atlanta GM Cliff Fletcher on his
picks. The Flames finally had their faces, most of them highly
forgettable, such as Bobby Leiter (via Pittsburgh), Ernie Hicke
(California), and Larry Romanchych (Chicago). A gracious Fletcher
thanked Blair and asked if the North Stars' boss really liked his
picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' Blair reportedly told Fletcher, ``and as soon as you
get rid of those bums, you'll have yourself a good club.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair spoke from experience. He was GM in Minnesota when the
North Stars entered the league in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Torrey recalled a similar incident in 1970 when George ``Punch''
Imlach was the GM making the picks for the expansion Buffalo
Sabres. Like Poile today, Imlach had to select a player from every
NHL roster. Imlach's last pick, recalled Torrey, was off the roster
of the Maple Leafs, a club that didn't make the playoffs in
1969-70.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Campbell was running the draft that day,'' said Torrey,
referring to Clarence Campbell, the late league president. ``And
I'll never forget him saying, `Mr. Imlach, you have to pick from
Toronto.' After this long pause, you hear Punch say, `Do I have to?
... Pass!' A couple of years later, when it was my turn on the
Island, I remember going up to Punch and saying, `Hey, Punch, can I
pass? You didn't leave me much.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins Hall of Famer Milt Schmidt was the GM in Washington when
the Caps entered the league in 1974. There were very few diamonds
in the rough that year, too. Washington entered the league the same
year as Kansas City, and when Schmidt saw what both clubs were
being offered, he knew the two upstarts were in for some long
nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a very nice experience, to be honest,'' said
Schmidt, whose roster was dotted by unknowns such as Denis Dupere
(via Toronto), Ron Lalonde (via Pittsburgh), and Michel Belhumeur
(via Philadelphia). ``All expansion clubs think they'll be well
looked after, but the truth is, the other clubs just let you be,
without very much help. Unless you get very, very lucky, why, you'd
better make up your mind you're going to suffer for the first few
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the start-up problems for Washington and Kansas
City, said Schmidt, was a reversal in league policy that allowed
clubs to demote players to the minors without first exposing them
to waivers. Originally, he said, the league's governors planned to
make such players available to the expansion clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``KC and ourselves were supposed to get first whack,'' said
Schmidt. ``But the last couple of days before the draft, all the
GMs went to Mr. Campbell and the ruling was changed. I talked to
Sid (Abel), the (Kansas City) GM, and I said, `Sid, there's no way
we can stand for this. We just can't let it happen.' But when it
came time to vote, there's Sid saying, `For!' Heck, I was the only
one against it. That was a bad situation. Most of the good players
were protected in the entry draft, and then that just made it all
the worse.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the few positive notes, said Schmidt, could be found in
net, where the Caps were able to place Ron Low (now the Oilers'
coach) after prying him away from the Maple Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were set there,'' said Schmidt. ``He was a pretty good
goalie. But for the most part, we got a couple of players with NHL
experience and then a bunch of college and minor league players.
Obviously, our record shows we weren't very good. Grin and bear it
_ it's all you could do.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Making do
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Flyer center Mel Bridgman, now an IMG agent, was at the
controls as GM when the Ottawa Senators entered the league in '92.
What was true for Torrey and Schmidt in the '70s was still in play
when Ottawa came marching back into the league as an expansion club
after a decades-long absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You realize you aren't going to get the elite players,'' said
Bridgman. ``Every player in the NHL is somewhat skilled and
talented, but the very best just aren't going to be available. Our
expectations in Ottawa were to draft and build a team with good
character, so when we made our first pick in the amateur draft,
Alexei Yashin, we had guys like Brad Marsh and Laurie Boschman in
place who could show them the right work ethic. Some of that is
probably paying off to this day.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before the sun sets, the NHL officially will be a 27-team
league. Atlanta, Columbus, and Minneapolis-St. Paul are soon to
follow. By the year 2,000, what was once the Original Six will have
grown fivefold. Chances are the expansion drafts to follow will
have an original, olde-tyme look: unrecognizable names and
questionable talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't control the hand we are dealt,'' said Poile,
referring to the talent pool at large that has been made available
to him. ``But I have a philosophy of what kind of team I want, and
we'll develop a philosophy as time goes. The reality is, we aren't
going to be as high on skill as other teams, but with a good
goalie, the right work ethic, I think we'll be OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
