<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DEMOCRACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO VIEW EXPERIMENT IN DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   XIAHE, Shaanxi Province, China _ In this thriving village of 400
people that President Clinton visits Friday in midwestern China, a
quiet experiment in democracy is under way that could eventually
reshape the body politic of the world's last major communist state.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment is village elections, and over the last decade it
has been implemented gradually with varying degrees of success
across China's 930,000 rural hamlets, home to three-quarters of the
country's 1.2 billion people.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Xiahe (pronounced SHEAH-huh), a wealthier-than-average
village with paved roads, a couple of satellite dishes,
electricity, and an elected mayor, Clinton will see the best of
economic and political progress in rural China. But beneath the
showcasing, lies a deeper truth. Even if residents do not have a
keen understanding of democracy as Americans think of it, they do
know it makes a difference to choose their own leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is getting better for us, because the ordinary farmer has
the right to check on our village heads now, like how they spend
village funds,'' Yang Gongqian, a 32-year-old craftsman, said
Thursday over tea with a reporter at the spacious, two-story brick
home he shares with his extended family of six. ``Before, it was''
the village chief's ``right to decide what to do. Now, he has to
think of the village people; we are happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The system is far from flawless, and central government
officials estimate as many as half of villages are not conducting
elections ``up to standard.'' In some places, ballots are not
secret, the father votes for the whole family, or only one
candidate runs. In some communities, the Communist Party secretary
still dictates to elected village leaders, or tries to sabotage
elections to maintain his privileges.
</P>
<P>
   But in many places, according to US observer delegations,
villagers are learning the tremendous power of the vote: the
ability to turn out bad leaders and keep new ones honest and
hard-working.
</P>
<P>
   The larger question for the future of China is whether
grassroots democracy, however imperfect, will become a model for
direct elections and meaningful representation at higher levels of
government _ or whether it will remain confined to peasants who
wield no influence on national affairs and pose little threat to
Communist Party leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a vast country with no history and experience of free
elections. The question is where do you choose to start?'' said
Robert Pastor, director of the China project at the Atlanta-based
Carter Center. Pastor is in China this month introducing a pilot
data collection system to determine if voting is fair and to help
the government standardize procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many things we take for granted, like a secret ballot, are
quite alien here,'' Pastor said. ``It's not easy to implement
democracy in China, which is why it makes sense to start in
villages. You start in a place where people are less likely to
understand it, but where three-fourths of the people live.''
</P>
<P>
   For thousands of years, village elders or feudal lords ruled
over rural areas, and after the 1949 communist victory, chiefs were
appointed by party officials. In the last 10 years, 600 million
voters have elected four million officials in 24 provinces and
autonomous regions, according to officials. Village committees are
elected for three-year terms to administer basic services like
education, irrigation, road-building, and family planning.
</P>
<P>
   In his visits to several provinces, Pastor has seen
irregularities that he believes stem more often from
misunderstanding than malfeaseance. He has observed voters looking
over each other's shoulders, ballots taken home, and votes counted
in secret. But he also watched scrupulous balloting; heard
candidates pledge to post accounts and stop spending taxpayer money
on party officials, and saw non-party members defeat incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   Xiahe villagers give contradictory explanations of how their
process works. One 28-year-old woman said everyone votes until 10
people are chosen, then everyone votes again for five committee
members. A 32-year-old man said villagers split into groups of 10
that each select a person, and those delegates vote for leaders. A
group of villagers said the government gives them a candidate list
and tells them to vote from that list.
</P>
<P>
   What was consistent was that villagers seemed happy with their
mayor, and even more with their power to make suggestions to
officials and to reelect or kick them out. One man said villagers
persuaded leaders to build an underground irrigation system to save
water lost to evaporation. Elections make a difference ``if we get
someone we trust,'' said Yang Shuiyan, 75, a retired teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be cynical and say the whole purpose is to stabilize
the system and keep the Communist Party in power, but stability is
absolutely critical for economic development,'' said David Zweig, a
China scholar at Hong Kong University of Science and Technology.
``If it's a more open system and people are more able to influence
outcomes, that's an important first step to establishing
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The obvious question is what the next step will be, and why
after a decade, voting has not trickled up even to townships, much
less to the national level. The urban equivalent of grassroots
voting is for neighborhood committees, but they have do not control
funds or set important policies.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews in Beijing this week, many residents said they had
never voted for any leader and never heard of village elections.
``Rural elections don't matter,'' scoffed Ma Wenting, 26, a
joint-venture company employee. ``The central government election _
now that would be important.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the late paramount leader Deng Xiaoping suggested
village elections were part of a 50-year process that would
eventually lead to national elections. Three months ago, Premier
Zhu Rongji said he believed in direct national elections, but said
leaders needed time to consider the idea.
</P>
<P>
   There is no sign now that the Communist Party has any interest
in multi-party elections, nor is there any hint of a lessening of
the party's control. Yet the last year has seen openings on many
fronts, and discussions under way this week to amend the election
law to ensure fairness are significant.
</P>
<P>
   Liu Yawei, a history professor at DeKalb College, in DeKalb,
Ill., &UR;  &LR; and member of the Carter Center team, likens China to ``a
big kaleidoscope. It seems to be out of focus and so many things
are happening. We have talked to scholars who say that after''
Chinese President ``Jiang Zemin's trip to the US, they were
commanded to study and write about the presidential system, Western
capitalist democracy, how to expand village elections.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next 10 years or even sooner,'' Liu predicted,
``everything will come into focus, and the end result will be a
more democratic China.''
</P>
<P>
   But Xu Liugen, a director-general at the Ministry of Civil
Affairs, which is in charge of village elections, cautioned that
``very often Westerners, outsiders, judge China's practice from
their own experience. This is Chinese democracy at the grassroots
level, with Chinese characteristics. Outsiders can give your
comments, but we have to do things our way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
