<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PEONY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 COMPROMISE IN DISPUTE OVER CHINESE OPERA PRODUCTION
</HEADLINE>
 (bl)  
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ At precisely the same time that President
Clinton arrived to a colorfully choreographed welcoming ceremony in
Xian on Thursday evening, a remarkable drama about a different
strand of U.S.-Chinese relations was wrapping up at Shanghai
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   In a seedy-looking departure lounge, Nigel Redden, director of
New York's Lincoln Center Festival, sat down for a final talk with
Shanghai Culture Bureau Director Ma Bomin, who has been blocking
the classic Chinese opera ``The Peony Pavilion'' from arriving in
New York in time for its scheduled opening July 7.
</P>
<P>
   Redden's flight was scheduled for 7:40 p.m., and he was informed
in the late afternoon that Ms. Ma would go to the airport to see
him off, because she had something to say.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 p.m. in the bar, Ms. Ma informed Redden that her bureau was
now willing to compromise on the matter that kicked off this whole
drama a week ago: blocking the shipment of elaborate sets, costumes
and props. The shipment, Ms. Ma said, could now proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Redden, suspicious after days of fruitless negotiations, quickly
asked a pertinent question: What about the actors? Would they be
allowed to go too ?
</P>
<P>
   No, Ms. Ma said with a grimace, the actors of the Kunqu Opera
Company would not yet be allowed to perform, as she had said over
and over, unless the opera was fully restaged to fit government
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Costumes, but no actors. Perfect. So a high-profile example of
cultural exchange between the United States and China lay in ruins,
on the day President Clinton arrived for a state visit, precisely
the time when Chinese and United States officials are most eager to
clear away unnecessary public conflict.
</P>
<P>
   To an arts executive like Redden, it is stunning that Chinese
authorities would want to prevent any ancient Chinese opera from
being performed in New York (especially since Lincoln Center is
paying). But it became clear in recent days that Chinese
officialdom was not against ``The Peony Pavilion,'' so much as one
particular official was, and her name is Ma.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ma's comments suggest that some petty political motives _
power over artistic troupes, professional jealousy, the right to
censor _ may play as big a role as the artistic objections she
cited, complaining that the work was a national treasure that
needed to be protected from unorthodox interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   And the reluctance of any higher Chinese authority to rein her
in suggests that she wields considerable political clout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep asking about it, and the reaction is always `It's
extremely complicated,' '' said Raymond Burghardt, U.S. consul
general in Shanghai. ``Well, why is it so complicated?'' Burghardt
was asking the question rhetorically, since as a diplomat with long
experience in China he knows that calling a matter ``extremely
complicated'' is a polite way of saying that there are a lot of
politics involved.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Burghardt fudged when asked whether President Clinton would
inquire about the opera, even though one polite question from
Clinton, voiced to a Chinese leader, could conceivably solve the
issue in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   At the airport Thursday evening, Redden began to let his
frustration show after making so little headway in negotiations,
particularly when Ms. Ma, a former opera singer, tried to tell
reporters who had been hastily assembled that her compromise showed
how her bureau had been so flexible in these talks
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no flexibility at all,'' Redden protested.
``I've been here since Monday, and have been met with no
cooperation whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   As her aides started insisting that Redden leave because his
flight was boarding, Ms. Ma turned to the reporters again to say,
in Chinese, that perhaps both sides should continue to keep
talking, since there were more avenues to be pursued.
</P>
<P>
   When the comment was translated to Redden, he apparently thought
Ms. Ma had actually meant what she said. He immediately ripped up
his boarding pass and said, ``So let's talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking shocked, as though a major headache on the verge of
flying away had now decided to stick around, Ms. Ma again described
her concern about the opera's script, and how it would be necessary
to unpack the costumes to rehearse. So maybe, she said, that
shipment should not actually be allowed to go to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, Redden was presented with a new boarding pass. It
was clear that Ms. Ma had no real interest in negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   After Redden left, Ms. Ma turned to the reporters again and made
another pitch: maybe Lincoln Center would accept a safer version of
``The Peony Pavilion,'' one that was simpler to stage, that used
none of the innovative techniques of Chen Shi-Zheng, the director
hired by Lincoln Center, whom Ms. Ma, to put it mildly, does not
like.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have already started rehearsing,'' Ms. Ma said,
brightening. ``We could certainly take it to Lincoln Center in time
for their festival.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen, dejected by the opera's demise, lamented that bureaucrats
like Ms. Ma seemed to have no sense that a serious arts festival
like Lincoln Center's actually valued artistic integrity and
vision, and would not simply slap in a replacement performance by
another troupe if the original was blocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, `The Peony Pavilion' itself is about pursuing a
dream, and how you need it to survive,'' said Chen, who left China
in 1987 and became an American citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Musing about his own dream of staging the opera in its original
and full 55-act, 20-hour form, he said, ``In China today, it is so
clear, that kind of spirit is not allowed to live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
