<HEADLINE>
ANTIUNITY BOMB RAISES CYNICISM IN IRISH TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTOWNHAMILTON, Northern Ireland _ Less than 24 hours after a
bomb damaged her fish 'n chips shop, Andrea Clark sat in the corner
of the Horseshoe Bar Thursday, having a lunch that consisted of a
Snickers bar and a bottle of Harp lager.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's election of a Northern Ireland Assembly was hailed as
the dawn of a new era. But from Andrea Clark's vantage point,
looking across the street at the boarded up windows of her shop, it
looked very much like the old Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you call this a peace process?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Her shop didn't get the worst of it. Less than 100 yards down
the street, the roofs of shops and homes had been torn off by a
bomb left in a car outside a police station by a group of Irish
republican dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish National Liberation Army, a small paramilitary group
that is more radical than the IRA, claimed responsibility for the
midafternoon explosion, which left a 15-year-old boy hospitalized
and dozens of schoolchildren traumatized.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the eve of Thursday's election, the results of which
are not expected until Friday, the bombing was seen by many as a
cynical exercise by those who see Northern Ireland moving forward
without them.
</P>
<P>
   One could forgive Clark for being cynical. In the past eight
years, her shop here has been damaged twice by bombs, as has her
home in nearby Markethill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still haven't fixed my house from the last one,'' she said,
referring to a bomb last September that was the work of republican
dissidents trying to disrupt the resumption of the negotiations
that led to the Good Friday agreement in which most political
parties agreed to share power.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Clark voted against the agreement in last month's referendum,
which was approved by 71 percent of voters in Northern Ireland. The
bombing persuaded her to vote Thursday for candidates who oppose
the agreement and who have vowed to wreck the Assembly. She was
defensive when asked if she was reacting exactly as the bombers
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm more cynical than anyone else in Northern
Ireland,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Newtownhamilton is a town of about 1,800, of which 60 percent
are Catholic and 40 percent are Protestant. People say relations
between the two communities are good, and don't expect the bombing
to change that.
</P>
<P>
   Locals say there have been at least five big bombs over the
years. Voting Thursday was supposed to take place in the community
center, but it was badly damaged by the blast and polls were moved
to the high school on the outskirts of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before it was a community center, it was a courthouse, and
they bombed that, too,'' said Carl Warmington, 75, a local
veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
   Warmington, a Protestant unionist who wants Northern Ireland to
remain part of Britain, believes the bomb was sanctioned by the
IRA, despite its cease-fire. Standing outside the high school after
voting, he pointed accusingly at a campaign poster that showed the
Sinn Fein president, Gerry Adams, whose party is close to the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family's been here for 300 years, and we're not leaving,''
said Warmington, who thinks the peace process is a naive attempt to
appease terrorists who reserve the option of using violence
whenever it suits them.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a trailer across from the polls, Sinn Fein supporter
Pat Hughes said it was ludicrous to suggest mainstream republicans
had anything to do with the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that does is hurt Sinn Fein,'' said Hughes. ``A good
strong vote for Sinn Fein would cut out the likes of these
things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
