<HEADER>
A7230 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-OPPOSITEOFSEX-TE     06-25 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-OPPOSITEOFSEX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRUSTRATING ATTEMPT AT `THE OPPOSITE OF SEX'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes, you wish first-time filmmakers wouldn't try so hard.
Case in point: ``The Opposite of Sex,'' which announces its
self-consciousness from the first few frames, when Christina
Ricci's voice comes on the soundtrack and tells us that she's the
narrator, and if you don't like movies with narrators, tough.
</P>
<P>
   Just what you want: a film that starts off with an apology. And
make no mistake, despite Ricci's snide tone, the film itself is
apologizing for its narration.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing wrong with narration, as long as the tone and flow are
consistent. But Ricci's character, Dedee, lectures us from time to
time and keeps reminding us that we're watching a movie, even doing
us the service of pointing out the cliches. Kinda hard to get lost
in a movie when she does stuff like this.
</P>
<P>
   Dedee's words and actions are the creations of Don Roos, a
veteran screenwriter (''Single White Female,'' ``Boys on the
Side'') taking his first turn behind the camera. Roos has concocted
an ambitious, outrageous and perceptive script with some
laugh-out-loud moments _ although those often come from cheap shots
at easy targets. But as a director, he keeps undercutting himself,
forcing his points or emphasizing them as if he didn't have enough
confidence in his words.
</P>
<P>
   And often, they're deliciously vicious words. Dedee's a truly
nasty character: After her stepfather dies, she migrates from
Louisiana to Indiana, where she drops in on her brother Bill
(Martin Donovan), a gay schoolteacher. Faster than you can say
``switch-hit,'' she seduces Bill's boyfriend Matt (Ivan Sergei) and
convinces him that they should get married because she's pregnant.
They run off to California with some of Bill's money and the ashes
of Bill's deceased lover.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's still more _ as Dedee says, things get very
complicated very quickly. Jason, an old flame of Matt's (Johnny
Galecki) accuses Bill of molesting him, prompting Bill and his dead
lover's sister Lucia (Lisa Kudrow) to chase down Matt so that he
can clear Bill's name. Told you it was complicated, and that's not
even counting Lyle Lovett as a good-hearted sheriff or William
Scott Lee as a fundamentalist sort who also has an interest in
Dedee.
</P>
<P>
   Roos isn't interested in teaching tolerance here, but you may
have to practice tolerance anyway just to be able to stomach some
of the characters. Galecki gets on your nerves enough that you're
likely to wish it was real when Bill does a number on one of
Jason's many piercings, and the versatile Kudrow is just too
strident as the spinsterish sister.
</P>
<P>
   Roos shows promise as a director, especially in the one-on-one
scenes. But he makes a lot of rookie errors, most specifically in
trying too hard to involve the audience in what should already be
an involving story. Like Dedee in the movie, Roos the writer might
have been wise to let his child be nurtured by more experienced
hands.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Opposite of Sex''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 stars on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Don Roos
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Christina Ricci, Martin Donovan, Lisa Kudrow
</P>
<P>
   Length: 101 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ much strong language, sexual situations and dialogue,
and some violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
