<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DISSIDENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OFFICIALS EXPRESS CONCERN OVER DETENTION OF DISSIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-SCENE, CHINA-CLINTON, HINA-PEONY) 
(th) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ U.S. officials expressed concern to the Chinese
government Thursday over reports that several dissidents had been
detained and others harassed in relation to President Clinton's
state visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very concerned that some dissidents may have been
detained or otherwise disrupted,'' White House spokesman Mike
McCurry told reporters soon after Clinton's arrival in Xian on
Thursday evening. He said that U.S. Ambassador James Sasser had
conveyed this to Chinese officials.
</P>
<P>
   In the Xian area, three democracy advocates were reportedly
detained and a fourth was forced to temporarily leave the area.
</P>
<P>
   Yang Hai of Xian, one of about 70 people around the country who
had signed an open letter calling on Clinton to meet with
dissidents during his visit, was taken away by police Thursday,
according to the Information Center of Human Rights and Democratic
Movement in China, a Hong Kong-based monitoring group.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Yan Jun, also of Xian and another signer of that
letter, and Li Zhiying, who lives in a nearby town and has signed
various petitions to the government, were detained as well, the
center said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another Xian resident who had signed the open letter to
Clinton, Fu Sheng, was put on a train to Qingdao on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Security forces in China often use temporary detentions as a way
to intimidate dissidents and prevent their activities at sensitive
times, such as Clinton's visit. In addition, more than 2,000 people
are believed to be in labor camps or prison for longer terms for
their pro-democracy activities.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the months since the Chinese government released the
prominent dissident Wei Jingsheng into exile in the United States
last November, after President Jiang Zemin's state visit to the
United States, scores of people around the country have been
signing petitions and writing open letters calling for democracy
and a reappraisal of the military crackdown in Tiananmen Square in
1989, in which hundreds of civilians were killed. Many of them face
constant police harassment.
</P>
<P>
   In the eastern city of Hangzhou on Thursday, three democracy
campaigners applied to register a new political party, the Chinese
Democratic Party, and one of them was later detained, his wife told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Party has a total monopoly on power and allows a
few token parties to operate only under its guidance. In an unusual
and risky move, Wang Youcai, Wang Donghai and Lin Hui left
application papers for their opposition party with a Zhejiang
provincial office.
</P>
<P>
   Wang Donghai, 53, was arrested Thursday evening, his wife, Cheng
Yunhui, told the Reuters news agency.
</P>
<P>
   The best known of the three, Wang Youcai, 31, was a student
leader in the 1989 demonstrations that ended in the Tiananmen
massacre. He was sentenced to four years but released early for
good conduct in November 1991. This spring, he was detained when he
tried to attend centennial celebrations at Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, after applying to form the new party, Wang
told reporters, ``We hope Clinton will pay attention and support
the establishment of an opposition party in China, so we chose
today to register.''
</P>
<P>
   A separate group led by Wang Bingzhang, who lives in exile in
the United States, says it has established a small underground
opposition party in China called the China Democracy and Justice
Party.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing on Thursday, one of the most outspoken democracy
advocates, Xu Wenli, said he is conspicuously followed by agents
when he leaves his home and that four friends who tried to visit
him were briefly detained and questioned. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
