<SLUG> BC-FAGAN-ARRAIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAGAN ARRAIGNED ON KIDNAPPING CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ With both his daughters by his side, Stephen
H. Fagan returned to Massachusetts from Palm Beach, Fla., Thursday
and pleaded not guilty to charges that he kidnapped his children
from his ex-wife 19 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   After entering his plea during a brief arraignment in Middlesex
Superior Court Thursday, Fagan was released on the same $250,000
bail set shortly after his arrest in April.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Joseph A. Grasso Jr., acting on a request by Middlesex
prosecutor Lynn C. Rooney, also set additional secret conditions on
Fagan's release.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Rooney nor defense attorney Richard M. Egbert would
comment on the new bail conditions, which were immediately sealed
by the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan, 56, is charged with two counts of kidnapping and one
count of contempt of a probate court order that had prohibited him
from taking the children out of state in 1979. Grasso scheduled a
pretrial conference July 21.
</P>
<P>
   A former Framingham resident, Fagan allegedly kidnapped his
daughters, then ages 2 and 5, after a bitter custody fight with
Barbara Kurth, his ex-wife. Fagan took the children during a
weekend visit, traveled to Florida, told them their mother had died
in a car crash, and assumed a new identity.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kurth hired several private investigators but could
not find him or her daughters.
</P>
<P>
   In newspaper and television interviews, Fagan has never denied
taking his daughters, but insisted he did so because their lives
were in danger from their mother's alcoholism and neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Kurth, a research scientist at the University of Virginia, has
denied she was neglectful and had a drinking problem.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Fagan nor his daughters spoke to reporters Thursday.
After the arraignment, Egbert urged the media to leave the family
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very difficult times. Their support for each other
is unwavering. It is particularly important that they go on with
their family life,'' Egbert said.
</P>
<P>
   In an outline of the case filed in court Thursday, Rooney said
that when Fagan and his children came to Florida in 1979, they
stayed at the home of Carolyn Garrison, an acquaintance of Fagan's
from his days as a doorman at the Kenmore Club in Kenmore Square.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison said the girls were ``shellshocked'' when they arrived,
according to the prosecution summary. Fagan told Garrison that
police had found his ex-wife's car at the side of the road and they
believed she was dead.
</P>
<P>
   The summary said that after arriving in Florida, Fagan told the
younger child, Wendy, then 2, that he would be calling her Lisa.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Wendy asked why, he simply said that it was her middle
name and that was what he intended to call her,'' the summary said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7244 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-OUTOFSIGHT-TEX     06-25 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-OUTOFSIGHT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIGHT' ONE OF SUMMER'S BEST MOVIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If crime novelist Elmore Leonard were to pick music to accompany
his books, he probably would make the same choice as director
Steven Soderbergh does in ``Out of Sight'': the stand-up funk of
the Isley Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   A tasty, down-low organ vamp from the greasy groove of ``It's
Your Thing'' opens the picture, one of the best movies to hit
multiplex screens this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Soderbergh and screenwriter Scott Frank flip the script in a
number of ways; this is the smartest adaptation of Leonard ever,
taking Leonard's fascination with recidivist behavior that unfolds
in anecdotal fashion and twisting it into a compelling, fractured
narrative. They give ``Out of Sight'' flow, and as a result the
movie's a scrumptious blend of humor and drama, with a hint of
maliciousness, for spice _ an adult jolt of caffeine that goes down
great when matched with the summer's other antic sugary junk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of Sight'' begins with George Clooney, who plays
compulsive bank robber Jack Foley, doing something he isn't often
given the chance to do _ show anger. Rage bursting out of him, he
stomps out of a downtown Florida office building and grapples with
his necktie, snatching it off his throat.
</P>
<P>
   By starting the picture like this, we see some actual feeling in
Clooney. He's not working the camera like some gigolo on a Carnival
Cruise, the way he often does on ``ER'' (It's genre pictures that
seem to make Clooney break through; he had a grim, reflexive
swiftness in the vampire-slaughter fest ``From Dusk Till Dawn.'')
</P>
<P>
   Foley makes a prison break just as federal marshal Karen Sisco
(Jennifer Lopez) shows up at Glades Correctional Facility to deal
with a convict complaint. Foley and his partner, Buddy (Ving
Rhames), grab her and take her along.
</P>
<P>
   One of the oddest pickup scenes in movie history, and one of
several that plays on the simmering rapport between Clooney and
Lopez, is his chatty, chivalrous attempt at courtship while the two
of them ride along, locked in the trunk of a car.
</P>
<P>
   From there, ``Out of Sight'' shifts into a caper film in
Detroit. Soderbergh sets an instant contrast with the sunny, pastel
amiability of Florida; Motown is all business, full of blacks,
grays and dark blues, a winter's night without a moon.
</P>
<P>
   It's there that a plan to hit a mansion (owned by the owlish
white-collar criminal Albert Brooks) brings Foley and Buddy
together with Snoopy (Don Cheadle) and his squad: his angry
brother-in-law (Isaiah Washington) and a loser side-of-beef named
White Boy Bob. Snoopy is the standard Satan in Leonard's fiction, a
thug who loves the rush of violence, but as played by the lithe,
talented Cheadle, it's just one more plus in his way of doing
business.
</P>
<P>
   Sisco's pursuit leads her there as well, wearing a
contour-fitting leather jacket from the Catwoman collection that
seems to have been chosen more for fashion than for
wind-chill-fighting comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard's writing technique doesn't exactly lend itself to the
movies, because his books don't rely on standard plot construction.
He couldn't be less interested in narrative momentum. He'd rather
use incidents to build character brick by brick. Leonard doesn't
write suspense novels or thrillers _ he writes crime novels, thick
with hoods alive with pleasure from a noseful of a good rip-off.
</P>
<P>
   It's Quentin Tarantino's slavish devotion to the tenor of
Leonard's material that crippled ``Jackie Brown;'' even when it's
good, it seems to be going nowhere, and in no particular hurry.
``Get Shorty,'' which Scott Frank also adapted, was staged like a
comic strip, with John Travolta doing a charismatic star turn right
in the center of the frame.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard's strengths happen to coincide with Soderbergh's. Both
are interested in tracking the flaws that lead people to follow the
impulses that cause them the most trouble, a pack of moths happily
hurling themselves into a campfire.
</P>
<P>
   It's the way that Soderbergh fills in the details that makes
``Out of Sight'' lively and smart. Each location in the movie acts
as another character; when the picture moves to Detroit, everything
feels right, from the use of the Kronk gym where manager Emmanuel
Stewart has tutored boxers from Tommy Hearns to Oscar de la Hoya,
to the red-pop finger-waves on Washington's head, a coiffure that's
hilariously ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of Sight'' meanders a little, but that's inescapable when
adapting Leonard. (However, there are some cameos that will delight
those who've seen other Leonard films.) The only problem is that it
may be a little mature and melancholy for the summer, generally a
time of year for movies that you can take in their entirety with
one eye closed.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Out of Sight''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 1/2 stars on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Steven Soderbergh
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: George Clooney, Jennifer Lopez, Ving Rhames
</P>
<P>
   Length: 123 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language, violence and sexuality
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
