<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES ATTORNEY-CLIENT PRIVILEGE PROTECTS FOSTER NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Thursday sidetracked
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's effort to obtain notes of a
conversati
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7262 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-ATTORNEY-CLIENT     06-25 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-ATTORNEY-CLIENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES ATTORNEY-CLIENT PRIVILEGE PROTECTS FOSTER NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Thursday sidetracked
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's effort to obtain notes of a
conversation between White House aide Vincent Foster Jr. and his
lawyer shortly before Foster committed suicide in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In a 6-3 ruling, the court said the attorney-client privilege,
the principle that conversations people have with their lawyers are
confidential, does not end with the death of the client. It thus
blocked Starr's attempt to force James Hamilton, Foster's lawyer,
to turn over the notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been overwhelmingly, if not universally, accepted, for
well over a century, that the privilege survives the client's death
in a case such as this,'' Chief Justice William Rehnquist wrote for
the court.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist said that eroding the attorney-client privilege could
make people reluctant to tell their lawyers the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing that communications will remain confidential even
after death serves a weighty interest in encouraging a client to
communicate fully and frankly with counsel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling represented a setback for Starr. The prosecutor has
said the notes could be important to his investigation into
allegations that White House aides or First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton lied under oath about her involvement in the firing of
seven career employees of the White House travel office in May
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, a boyhood friend of President Clinton and a Little Rock
law partner of Mrs. Clinton, came to Washington in 1993 to join the
new administration as deputy White House counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Within months, Foster was embroiled in a controversy surrounding
the firings at the White House travel office.
</P>
<P>
   Republican critics have charged that Mrs. Clinton ordered the
firings to make room for friends of the Clintons. Mrs. Clinton has
said she had no role in the dismissals.
</P>
<P>
   But a memo of a former White House staffer, David Watkins,
turned over to prosecutors in 1996, said Foster had ``regularly
informed me'' of Mrs. Clinton's ``insistence'' that the travel
office employees be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   In personal notes written at the time, Foster worried that
administration officials would face a congressional inquiry and
possibly a criminal probe of the firings. He also expressed concern
that Mrs. Clinton's role would be misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   On July 11, Foster consulted Hamilton about what he should do.
During their two-hour meeting Hamilton took three pages of notes.
</P>
<P>
   Nine days later, worried about the travel office controversy,
charges about Whitewater land deals and the hostile political
atmosphere in Washington, Foster drove to Fort Marcy Park in nearby
Virginia and shot himself to death.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Starr, investigating the charges that Mrs.
Clinton had lied about her role in the travel office case,
subpoenaed Hamilton's notes.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Washington rejected the subpoena, but in
August 1997 the U.S. Court of Appeals here overturned that
decision, ruling in favor of Starr.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday the Supreme Court decided the appeals court was
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist was joined by Justices John Paul Stevens, Anthony M.
Kennedy, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G.
Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas
dissented.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the three, O'Connor said that when no other sources
of evidence are available, a prosecutor's need to find the truth
overrides the late client's desire for confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, the cost of silence warrants a narrow exception to
the rule that the attorney-client privilege survives the death of a
client,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers' groups hailed the decision as a victory for privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good for clients. It's important for the legal
profession; and I think it's good for the country that people will
have confidence in that what they tell their attorney will remain
in confidence,'' said Jerome Shestack, president of the American
Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setback, Starr showed no signs of ending his
travel-office probe. ``In all events, we continue to pursue our
investigation as thoroughly and expeditiously as possible,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official accompanying the president in China
called the ruling ``an important validation of the vital issue of
attorney-client privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   Another attorney-client privilege case is pending in Starr's
investigation of whether Clinton had sex with former White House
aide Monica Lewinsky and lied about it. In that case, now before a
federal appeals court here, White House lawyer Bruce Lindsey is
trying to keep from disclosing his conversations with various
people in the Lewinsky probe.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the attorney-client privilege, courts have recognized
that a confidentiality privilege exists between people and their
spouses and their doctors and between priests and penitents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
