<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LANDS IN CHINA, WADES INTO HUMAN RIGHTS ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   XIAN, China _ In a swirl of pageantry, controversy and hope,
President Clinton arrived at the gates to this ancient capital last
night to begin his nine-day journey through China, and immediately
delved into the sensitive issue of human rights with a gentle
rebuke of the country's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   As dusk gave way to dark, Clinton and his wife left their
limousine at the head of a 50-car motorcade and walked slowly down
a block-long red carpet toward the glowing wall of Xian, waving and
smiling at the hundreds of citizens who lined the way.
</P>
<P>
   In an elaborate emperor's welcome, dozens of men in warrior
costumes, bathed in the soft light of red lanterns, pounded on
massive drums with cloth-covered sticks. Strains of Tang Dynasty
music echoed off the 600-year-old city wall and carried over the
surrounding moat. Virgin flower girls knelt before Clinton in
formation as men marched with paper dragons nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, looking visibly worn from an 18-hour flight, greeted
the crowd with a few words of Chinese and launched directly into a
brief lecture on human rights -- in a likely harbinger of a
stronger message to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Respect for the worth, the dignity, the potential, and the
freedom of every citizen is a vital source of America's strength
and success,'' Clinton said to the silent audience. ``A commitment
to providing all human beings the opportunity to develop their full
potential is vital to the strength and success of the new China as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Clinton delivered his short speech, a fresh controversy
over human rights erupted around him. A Hong Kong-based human
rights group said the Chinese government had detained a pair of
well-known dissidents Thursday, one of whom, Yan Jun of Xian, had
signed a letter asking Clinton to meet with dissidents during the
visit.
</P>
<P>
   The actions appeared to alarm White House officials, who were
already sensitive to Republican criticism that Clinton was
overlooking human rights violations in his pursuit of an economic
engagement of China. Officials said United States ambassador James
R. Sasser would raise the issue with Chinese authorities today and
Clinton would implicitly touch on the dissidents with President
Jiang Zemin on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are aware of reports of dissidents being detained,'' said
P.J. Crowley, a White House spokesman. ``The president, in his
meetings with President Jiang, will encourage China to allow freer
political dialogue so that all Chinese citizens can be free to
express their political beliefs without government interference.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's arrival to this inland city of 6.5 million people was
designed by White House strategists to be heavy on ceremony and
light on the substance of his trip, a soft opening of sorts for his
nine-day, five city tour that ends July 3. Friday, Clinton will
extol the virtues of local democracy with a visit to a tiny village
which elected its mayor by popular vote. Friday afternoon, he plans
to tour the famed Terra Cotta Warriors, an army of some 6,000
lifesized clay statutes buried near the tomb of Emperor Qin
Shihuang, and discovered by a local farmer digging a well in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy awaits Clinton Friday night (EST) when he arrives in
the capital of Beijing for a formal welcoming ceremony at the Great
Hall of the People, just off Tiananmen Square. A group of
Republican lawmakers and some key human rights advocates have
sharply criticized Clinton for appearing on the square where
Chinese authorities killed hundreds and even thousands of
protesters in June 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, anxious over the sybolism of Clinton's
appearance, intentionally scheduled his arrival for a time of
minimal news exposure back home, and plans to have Clinton make
remarks to US reporters about human rights within a few hours of
his arrival.
</P>
<P>
   In a half-day of meetings between Jiang and Clinton Saturday,
the Chinese are expected to push the US to distance itself from
Taiwan, an island off the coast of China which the US does not
officially recognize but with which it maintains friendly ties.
Jiang is also expected to campaign for greater US support for
China's bid to enter the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Clinton is expected to push Jiang to play a greater,
more constructive role to defuse the nuclear arms buildup between
India and Pakistan. Clinton will also prod Chinese officials to
tear down trade barriers to US goods.
</P>
<P>
   Not since George Bush visited Beijing in the pre-Tiananmen
Square massacre days of February 1989 has an American president
stepped on Chinese soil. And not since Richard Nixon visited
Beijing -- then Peking -- in 1973 has a presidential trip generates
so much controversy in the corridors of power back home.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1992 reelection, Clinton accused Bush of ``coddling
dictators,'' in his approach to China. Since then, Clinton has
jerked from one China policy to the next, first ignoring the
country because of human rights. In 1996, in a low point in the
relationship, Clinton dispatched two aircraft carriers to the
Chinese coast after authorities lobbed a series of missiles towards
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Within the past two years, the White House has settled on a
strategy it describes as engagement, designed to involve Chinese
leaders in high level discussions with the hope of spurring change.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be those here and back in America who wonder whether
closer ties and deeper friendship between America and China are
good,'' Clinton said last night. ``Clearly, the answer is yes. We
have a powerful ability to help each other grow. We can learn much
from each other. And as two great nations, we have a special
responsibility to the future of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, Clinton arrived to a far different China than
even the one Bush left behind a decade ago. As he stood with his
back to the venerable city wall last night, Clinton looked out
toward a glittering office tower -- a bank building --in downtown
Xian. Nearby billboards defined the virtues of various brands of
liquor, while the drummers in warrior costumes puffed cigarettes
between sets and took pulls from metal flasks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
