r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-DRDOOLITTLE-TEX     06-25 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DRDOOLITTLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDDIE MURPHY RUNS WITH THE PACK, BUT IT ISN'T ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stand-up comic Richard Lewis used to do a joke about his mother
laying such a guilt trip on his family that their dog became
neurotic; it would cough before it barked.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is about the only comedian missing from the ranks of the
comics who voice the animals in the remake of ``Dr. Dolittle,''
starring Eddie Murphy (see sidebar). Albert Brooks is the furry
creature who could've come out of Lewis' mom's house: a headachy,
suicidal tiger.
</P>
<P>
   This roster of comics gives ``Dr. Dolittle'' most of its charm.
Otherwise, it's a strange spectacle _ a family comedy with a bunch
of raunchy remarks you wouldn't expect to see in a picture aimed at
kids and their parents. But then, you wouldn't expect to see Eddie
Murphy in a film for the whole family, unless it was the Wu Tang
Clan.
</P>
<P>
   But Murphy, with a headful of sculpted dreadlocks and intoning
his lines in his best Dark Gable voice, slides through the picture.
He plays a grown-up; family man Dr. John Dolittle, who has
repressed childhood memories of talking to the animals.
(Specifically, his dog, voiced by Ellen DeGeneres.) He scoots
around wearing a pair of glasses and having little patience for
animals, of course, and for anything that's the slightest bit
weird.
</P>
<P>
   When he almost runs over a wandering pooch (Norm MacDonald), he
suddenly starts to hear the animals _ all of them _ talking again.
This, of course, greatly annoys his wife (the shockingly gorgeous
Kristen Wilson) and his greedy partner (Oliver Platt), who wants to
sell their medical practice to a corporation run by the indifferent
Peter Boyle.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting the rapidly growing crew of animals who seek him out
with their ailments, Dolittle learns to get in touch with his inner
freak, thereby exemplifying the lesson he teaches one of his kids:
Be yourself and love yourself, because geniuses were considered
weird, too. (He then recites a list of geniuses _ Albert Einstein,
Muhammed Ali _ fresh from those annoying ``Think Different'' Apple
ads.)
</P>
<P>
   Betty Thomas (''Private Parts,'' ``The Brady Bunch Movie'')
directs in a style best described as slapdash, and _ in an age when
even the lamest movies look polished, if impersonal _ delivers one
of the lousiest-looking major-studio releases in some time.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Thomas persists in using Steven Gilborn, the
skilled actor best known for his role as ``Ellen's'' befuddled dad.
He made quite an impression in ``The Late Shift,'' the HBO movie
about the Leno/Letterman feud, which was also directed by Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone expecting a connection to the first ``Dr. Dolittle''
movie will have to make do with a quick glimpse of the
pushmi-pullyou in the background, and a bit of Louis Armstrong's
lovely cover of ``Talk to the Animals.'' The movie is energetic,
occasionally amusing, and mostly painless. Even for those who may
think they've lived too long when an Eddie Murphy movie becomes an
Afterschool Special.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Look who's talking
</P>
<P>
   An impressive roster of comics gives voice to the animals in
``Dr. Dolittle:''
</P>
<P>
   Norm MacDonald is the mutt whose narration starts the story.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen DeGeneres and Gilbert Gottfried join him as canines in
cameos.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Rock is the lascivious, hungry guinea pig.
</P>
<P>
   Garry Shandling and Julie Kavner are a pair of feuding pigeons.
</P>
<P>
   Jenna Elfman is a wounded owl.
</P>
<P>
   John Leguizamo is a rat.
</P>
<P>
   Paul ``Pee-wee'' Reubens is a raccoon.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Brooks is a depressed tiger.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Dr. Dolittle''
</P>
<P>
   Director: Betty Thomas
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Eddie Murphy
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 stars on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Length: 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ adult language and literal toilet jokes
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
