<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-STRUMINSKI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOHDAN STRUMINSKI, LINGUIST, 68; FOUGHT SOVIET LANGUAGE POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bohdan A. Struminski, a linguist and translator who spent three
years in a Polish prison for protesting Soviet language policies in
the Ukraine, died of cancer Tuesday in his home in Arlington, Mass.
He was 68.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Struminski was a specialist in Ukrainian, Polish, and Old
Slavic languages. He was the author of ``Linguistic Interrelations
in Early Rus'' and a translator of scholarly source materials for
the series Early Ukrainian Literature published by Harvard
University and the University of Alberta. He also translated
Czeslaw Milosz's ``The Captive Mind'' from Polish into Ukrainian
and was the author of more than 100 scholarly articles.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Bialystok, Poland, the city for which the bialy,
a round, flat bread roll, is named. He graduated from Warsaw
University, where he also earned a doctorate in philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, he was convicted of anti-Soviet activities for
protesting Soviet language policies in the Ukraine and spent nearly
three years in a Polish prison.
</P>
<P>
   He came to the United States in 1975 and was a visiting
professor at Harvard University until 1979, when he became a
research associate at the Harvard Ukrainian Research Institute,
where he remained until his retirement in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   He contributed to Polish and Ukrainian literary publications
such as ``Kultura'' and ``Suchasnist'' under the pen names A.
Skiwski and D. Bajurs'kyj.
</P>
<P>
   Though he bristled at the term Polish-American, he was
editor-in-chief of Zycie Polonii, a publication of the Eastern
Massachusetts division of the Polish-American Congress. In a story
published in the Polish American Journal on Jan. 1, 1994, he
described himself as a ``Polish citizen residing in America.'' He
denounced the Polish-American title ``because,'' he said, ``it
would suggest that I am only a vestigial Pole, still liking the
polka and kielbasa, but no longer a perfect speaker of Polish, with
all the cultural, historical and psychological consequences
thereof.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Kathleen M. Lestition; and a son, Igor of
Poland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1848EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
