<HEADLINE>
CROWDS LINE CHINA'S STREETS TO GREET CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-CLINTON, CHINA-DISSIDENTS, CHINA-PEONY) 
(ps) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   XIAN, China _ On this steamy summer night, the people of Xian
took to the streets Thursday to welcome President Clinton on the
first stop of his state visit, in what many here said was one of
the largest spontaneous gatherings they could remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been another event like this here, I don't think
I've ever seen this many people come out for anything,'' said Sun
Qinqi, an engineer, who said he had decided to pass up televised
soccer matches from the World Cup to cram onto the sidewalk just
inside the old city's South Gate to catch a glimpse of the
presidential motorcade's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   He scanned the high-spirited crowd wondering aloud: Did more
people turn out to celebrate the arrest of the infamous Gang of
Four in 1976, which brought the decade-long Cultural Revolution to
an end? Were there more in the spring of 1989, when people gathered
to express sympathy for demonstrators in Beijing's Tiananmen
Square?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he concluded, ``there just weren't so many then.''
</P>
<P>
   As early as 9 Thursday morning, factory workers, students,
bankers and public officials started vying for position on the
sidewalks around the square before the city's South Gate, where the
president was to give a short speech. And by Thursday evening, a
crowd five deep extended out of the square for two miles down South
Avenue, along the route Clinton was rumored to be taking back to
his hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a massive police presence, the green uniformed officers
stoically tolerated a large, ebullient crowd of spectators that
perched in trees and atop newspaper kiosks. They watched as men in
Adidas shirts and women carrying beepers jumped blithely over the
barricades in front of Kentucky Fried Chicken to applaud when the
president's black limousine, bearing American and Chinese flags,
finally passed.
</P>
<P>
   It was a heady evening for Xian, the once-proud capital of
ancient China, that in recent years has been plagued by a stagnant
economy and hundreds of thousands of layoffs. Indeed, many
enthusiasts expressed hope that Clinton's visit would help restore
Xian's name _ or at least bring new business opportunities to town.
</P>
<P>
   The young, diverse crowd's open chattiness, spontaneity and
optimism reflected the greater freedoms Chinese enjoy today. But
this was also a celebration that excluded _ at times forcibly _
those elements of Chinese society that have not fit into the
government's reforms, like Liu Guiqing, a poor pedicab driver, who
was three weeks ago ordered off the streets, or Fu Sheng, a
political dissident who was forced on Wednesday to leave town.
</P>
<P>
   On the street Thursday night, few seemed to mind that they could
neither see the elaborate welcoming ceremony nor hear the president
speak.
</P>
<P>
   Gu Fuyin, a factory director, and his wife, Cao Mingli, had
dressed up, brought stools and waited four hours to catch a glimpse
of the motorcade. Some work places had urged their employees to be
welcoming toward Clinton. Nonetheless, the middle-aged couple
marveled at a celebration that was ``spontaneous'' and ``not
required by politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The two country's relations are developing quickly and now we
are feeling much more friendly,'' Gu explained.
</P>
<P>
   Ren Liansheng, 25, a Xian native who is currently working on a
construction project in Gansu, took off three days to attend the
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of the United States welcomed Jiang Zemin last
year,'' he said. ``Also, this is great for Xian, to promote
economic development.''
</P>
<P>
   And Li Yuhua, 45, a factory worker in a flower print dress who
was crammed onto the sidewalk just across from the magnificent
South Gate, only slightly overstepped the mood of the crowd when
she exclaimed: ``He's young and he's achieved so much. And we hope
he'll achieve more. He's an epic-making man.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Clinton's plane touched down shopkeepers could
feel the benefits of his visit.
</P>
<P>
   On Wenyibei Street, a bustling commercial street outside the
city wall, Jia Jiwan, 34, had decorated the window of his
fashionable clothing store with pictures of the president and the
message ``Welcome to Xian Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We always say we should grasp the opportunity to reinvigorate
the economy and this is like a windfall,'' he said. ``So this visit
could be a turning point. Afterward, Xian _ and its products _ will
be better known in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   At a small outdoor market near Xian's beautifully ornate
18th-century Bell Tower, Lu Xiurong, 47, said the impending arrival
of Clinton had done wonders for her business, which sells
children's clothes, skimpy underwear and bras.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just saying how happy we were he is coming,'' said Ms.
Lu. ``When the people are in a good mood, as they are now, they
wander through the market and buy.'' She said that sales had
increased 60 percent in the last two weeks, with American-flag
pajamas a best seller.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A sales girl at the state-owned Foreign Language Bookstore said
that 200 copies of a Chinese book about President Jiang Zemin's
visit to the United States last fall had sold out in two days last
week, and sales of translations of American novels had doubled in
recent days.
</P>
<P>
   But other businesses did not fare so well.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, a 45-year-old widow named Liu Guiqing who had
been laid off from a candy factory paid $100 for a pedicab that she
drove to support her two children.
</P>
<P>
   But on June 1, Xian police informed Ms. Liu and other pedicab
drivers that they could no longer ride in the city center. The move
supposedly was to relieve Xian's traffic congestion, but she and
many others say the Clinton visit was to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say that these look bad, are not modern, that modern
people take taxi cabs,'' sniffed an elderly driver who would only
give his name as Lu. Lu's fancy pedicab, with its stripped canopy
and lace curtain, slowly moved alongside the city's North Wall,
hauling only a large tank of cooking gas.
</P>
<P>
   With no other way to make money, Ms. Liu has decided to play the
odds, in order to earn a few dollars a night. In a city center now
devoid of pedicabs, she goes out after nightfall and turns down
rides that involve traveling on main thoroughfares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen a few police trucks but they have so far left me
alone,'' she said. ``I think its because I am a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, as Clinton was traveling to Xian, Fu Sheng was
aboard a train out of the city, to the seaport of Qingdao. Fu, 38,
who in 1989 had led Xian workers in a demonstration to support the
protests in Beijing, was ordered to leave town before Clinton's
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Three times in recent weeks, the party secretary at Fu's work
place, the Xian Institute of Navigation, gave him the choice of
being laid off or going to Qingdao.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally left, he was accompanied by a co-worker assigned
to make sure that he arrived at his destination. But he was upset
that he had to leave Xian while his wife had to work and his
9-year-old was preparing for examinations.
</P>
<P>
   ''The meeting between the Americans and the Chinese is a good
thing, another handshake,'' he said before his departure. ``But why
have authorities violated my rights?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
