<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7312 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2     06-25 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RUSH TO JUDGMENT IN CLINTON'S CASE IS DANGEROUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 28)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Clinton has one indisputable claim that sets
him apart from all his predecessors. His private life has been
scrutinized more meticulously than that of any president before
him.
</P>
<P>
   The House, the Senate, independent counsels, the Justice
Department and the news media all have peered with microscopic
thoroughness into the doings of the current commander-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   In a number of administrations, investigators have looked
closely at the president _ the sins he might have committed, the
secret commitments he might have made, the promises he reneged on,
the relationships he depended on and the activities he indulged in.
</P>
<P>
   Ulysses S. Grant, Warren G. Harding, Harry S Truman, Richard M.
Nixon and Ronald Reagan are among those whose machinations have
been carefully dissected.
</P>
<P>
   When Republicans reclaimed control of Congress in 1947 after 14
years of Democratic rule over the White House and Capitol Hill,
they launched lengthy inquiries into the late Franklin D.
Roosevelt's conduct during the months leading up to the 1941
Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor and the commitments he made to the
Soviet Union's Josef Stalin at the Yalta conference in 1945. The
probes produced little of substance.
</P>
<P>
   But never has there been anything to equal the spectacle of the
Clinton years.
</P>
<P>
   The investigative focus has fallen not just on the president,
but also on the vice president, the first lady, several Cabinet
members, White House aides, party fund-raisers and men and women
with whom Clinton did business before becoming president.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans are weary of the continuing inquiries and the
money and time that have been expended on them. According to the
latest NBC-Wall Street Journal poll, 83 percent of the respondents
said they are tired of the probes and 63 percent said they approve
of Clinton's presidential performance. Still, others hope for a
more intensified probe of the president, with impeachment as their
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the whole process, as far as much of the public is
concerned, has come down to a question of whether Clinton had sex
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky and whether he lied
under oath about it and sought the help of others in a cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   There are many other facets of the Clinton investigation, all
jammed together under the umbrella called Whitewater. But to most
Americans, the Lewinsky affair is the key to his fate and his
future. The closest parallel to an investigation endangering a
president's tenure would be the Watergate probe of Nixon in the
early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   When Nixon finally bowed to reality and resigned in 1974, it was
because White House tapes revealed that he had sought to obstruct
justice by using the CIA and the FBI to cover up wrongdoing. But no
one ever suspected Nixon of having a secret sex life.
</P>
<P>
   The current situation is considerably different.
</P>
<P>
   When the founding fathers provided in the Constitution for
impeachment of a president, it is doubtful that any of them
anticipated that an extramarital relationship would be labeled a
high crime or misdemeanor or that it would become the vehicle to
carry a president permanently out of the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Treason, theft or a deliberate subversion of the Constitution
are grounds for impeachment. But some of the good founders
themselves may have indulged in private illicit sex without
endangering their public careers.
</P>
<P>
   The question that must resolved eventually, therefore, is
whether Clinton attempted to obstruct justice by lying and getting
others to lie about the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   There is a tendency to believe that presidents are different
from the rest of us because their scale of living is so at odds
with that of the average American. They reside for a limited period
of time, usually four years or eight, in a great white mansion on
Pennsylvania Avenue and fly off to Camp David in Maryland's
Catoctin Mountains for quiet weekends.
</P>
<P>
   They travel in chauffeur-driven limousines, helicopters and a
Boeing 747 known as Air Force One. They are protected by a constant
coterie of Secret Service agents and have all menial tasks
performed for them.
</P>
<P>
   When their presidency ends, they draw a nice pension and pick up
additional cash by writing books, lecturing and/or serving on
boards of directors. With large contributions from private donors,
they establish libraries and museums that recount the glories of
their White House years and provide visitors with a fascinating
panorama of history.
</P>
<P>
   In that after-the-presidency life, they continue to have Secret
Service protection, office help and other benefits paid by the
government.
</P>
<P>
   But basically, they are like the rest of us. In them, we find
strength and weakness, honesty and dishonesty, wisdom and
stupidity. All the frills provided them by the taxpayers do not
make them incorruptible or infallible.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton's influence on Capitol Hill and with the public
has been diminished by investigations and revelations, he has not
been found guilty of any crime and he has not been indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of his own party have found it difficult to defend
Clinton and, in the current climate, have found it easy to distance
themselves from him on free trade and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   But as was the case with previous presidents, a rush to judgment
can lead to a false conclusion. Presidents, like the rest of us,
are innocent until proved guilty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
