<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DROPS THIRD WORLD CUP MATCH, 1-0 TO YUGOSLAVIA  
 (JT )
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France _ America lost 1-0 Thursday to Yugoslavia,
bringing down the final curtain on a dismal American performance in
the World Cup, one that brought the United States just one goal in
three matches.
</P>
<P>
   The American showing _ marked by squandered chances, sloppy
passing and the absence of a single player with the authority to
give direction to the team _ underscored the weaknesses that have
beset the United States since its opening match against Germany and
again revealed the gulf separating it from the top teams in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goal scoring opportunities are not easily created at this
level of soccer, and we have to learn to take them,'' Steve
Sampson, the coach, said after the game. ``We showed a lack of
precision in front of goal, an inability to get the ball in the
net.''
</P>
<P>
   After the promising American showings before the World Cup,
including victories over Brazil and Austria, the results here
amounted to a bumpy return to earth. Energetic, busy, somewhat
bewildered, the U.S. players often looked like innocents abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The victory ensured Yugoslavia's ascent to the second round of
the competition, emerging in second place in Group F behind
Germany. The Yugoslav side, which has shown its ability to play
great soccer but was not required to do so Thursday, will face the
Netherlands in a battle of European giants next Monday. Germany,
having clinched victory in the group with a 2-0 win Thursday over
Iran, will play Mexico on the same day in the elimination phase of
the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   This was another game between political rivals, but the
camaraderie and exchanges of flowers that marked America's game
with Iran was absent here. The Serbian-dominated Yugoslav crowd
booed as the Star Spangled Banner was played before the game, and
handshakes between players were perfunctory. There were no flowers.
</P>
<P>
   America surged forward in the opening minutes, and a few slick
exchanges of passes momentarily suggested that the team had turned
a page, throwing off its hesitations and nervousness. Frankie
Hejduk's long, floating cross from the right bemused the Yugoslav
goalkeeper, Ivica Kralj, floating over his flailing hand before
glancing back into play off the far post.
</P>
<P>
   The American momentum was quickly stifled. When a free kick for
a foul on Yugoslavia's star striker, Predrag Mijatovic of Real
Madrid, was awarded in the fourth minute, Sinisa Mihajlovic blasted
a swerving shot from 25 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Friedel, the American goalkeeper, playing his first game of
the tournament, seemed to see the ball late and pawed it away
beyond his left post. But the Yugoslav right back, Slobodan
Komljenovic, was waiting there, and, from an acute angle, headed
the ball into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were caught ball-watching,'' Friedel said after the game.
He evidently believed he had pushed the ball far enough to be out
of danger.
</P>
<P>
   The United States returned to the attack, but a note of
amateurish desperation was always evident. There was not an
American player on the field prepared to put his foot on the ball,
look up, take stock, and make the intelligent pass. In front of
goal, with reasonable chances, center forward Brian McBride and
midfielder Claudio Reyna repeatedly blasted the ball wide or high.
Clinical finishing was not in America's repertoire here.
</P>
<P>
   Reyna, in whom coach Sampson had placed great faith, was one of
the major disappointments of the tournament, squandering his
evident potential with rushed passes. By the end of Thursday's
match, he looked perhaps the most frustrated player on the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Two bright spots for the United States were the goalkeeping of
Friedel, who plays for England's Liverpool, and the outstanding
play of David Regis in the heart of the defense. It was their
combined efforts that kept Yugoslavia to a single goal.
</P>
<P>
   Friedel saved brilliantly from Yugoslav forward Savo Milosevic
in the 31st minute, and Regis often intervened as Yugoslav strikers
seemed poised to increase the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Mijatevic, the dangerous Yugoslav striker, was substituted late
in the first half with a slight knee injury. The young Perenica
Ognjenovic, who took his place, missed several chances,
particularly one late in the game when he was put through and had
only Friedel to beat.
</P>
<P>
   America's play grew more scrappy in the second half, and the
team had a chance for a draw. The best scoring opportunity came in
the 80th minute, when Ernie Stewart broke away on the right flank
and crossed well to McBride.
</P>
<P>
   The striker controlled the ball well, but his left-foot shot
from just six yards went straight into Krajl's arms. Two minutes
later, American substitute Predrag Radosavljevik, who started his
career in Yugoslavia, wasted a well-placed free kick, firing over
the bar from the edge of the penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a good game,'' captain Thomas Dooley said, ``and we
showed we can play good football. We deserved to draw. The USA team
leaves the World Cup heads held high.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson was more sober in his assessment. ``The first half
against Germany was our biggest learning experience,'' he said.
``We saw we had to wake up to the level of soccer being played in a
world championship.'' The awakening promises to be long and
painful.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
