<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-VOTE-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTER TURNOUT LARGE IN NORTHERN IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ The Northern Ireland peace effort
reached a milestone Thursday as residents of the long-polarized
province turned out in large numbers to elect members of a new
legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Voters chose 108 lawmakers from a field of nearly 300 candidates
from once warring parties to serve in the Northern Ireland
Assembly. The new body will restore local government here for the
first time since the British imposed direct rule in 1972. It will
also set up a structure to meet the elusive goal of power-sharing
between the Catholics and Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   In a pointed symbol of the profoundly changed attitudes in this
province, among those running for office were men who had been some
of the most notorious bombers and killers of the last three
decades, in which more than 3,200 people died in sectarian
violence.
</P>
<P>
   The election was a test of the public's faith in its conversion
to political means to settle its disputes, and of its trust in the
peace settlement that emerged on April 10, after 26 months of
negotiations in Belfast. The accord was endorsed on May 22 by
referendums in Ireland and Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of the Assembly was one step called for in the
accord, which was patterned to give equal weight to the Catholic
longing for eventual unity with Ireland and the Protestant desire
to remain part of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   In a departure from the norm in Northern Irish politics, a
surprisingly low key and conciliatory campaign turned not so much
on conflicts between the province's two principal religious groups
as on disputes and competitions within them.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican Army,
whose president is Gerry Adams, was looking to gain converts from
the moderate Catholic Social Democratic and Labor Party of John
Hume.
</P>
<P>
   Dissident Protestants, led by the Rev. Ian Paisley, the
78-year-old firebrand, worked to elect enough legislators to bottle
up the work of the Assembly, which will almost certainly have as
its speaker David Trimble, leader of the largest Protestant party,
the Ulster Unionists. Hume, whose party is the second biggest in
the province, will probably be the deputy speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble has warned people that Paisley's purpose is to place as
many of his followers in the Assembly as possible to ``wreck'' it.
Emerging from voting Thursday, Paisley protested that description,
saying, ``The role we play will be as saviors of the union.''
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign progressed, it became apparent that what divided
the electorate was not the traditional religious schism, but
people's views about the validity of the Assembly itself. That, in
turn, has produced an unaccustomed scenario for Northern Ireland,
in which some Catholics and Protestants may end up voting knowingly
for the same objective.
</P>
<P>
   While the progression of the men who once committed savage acts
of terror to a commitment to peaceful negotiations and the ballot
box represents the most dramatic change in the conduct of politics
in Northern Ireland, the transformation of Trimble has in recent
months attracted notice of its own.
</P>
<P>
   The last time that Northern Ireland tried to create a
power-sharing legislature, in 1974, Trimble, then a leader of the
hard-line Ulster Vanguard, led the protests that forced its
collapse. Today he guides a campaign for inclusive government,
giving speeches of populist fervor about reaching across community
divides. Perhaps the best measure of his conversion is the fact
that his old ally, Paisley, has branded him a traitor to
Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly is to meet for the first time next week. But its
order of business will be brief. It will formally select its two
leaders and then move into a ``shadow'' existence in the fall,
creating its rules and committees and selecting the other members
of the 12-member executive that will in effect be Northern
Ireland's government.
</P>
<P>
   That will almost certainly make Adams a minister, an eventuality
that Paisley and hard-line opponents of Trimble in his own party
have continually cited as a reason for opposing the peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   The areas for which the Assembly will be responsible include
agriculture, health, education, the environment and economic
development.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Assembly will not formally be up and running for
an estimated six months, there was an urgency to having the vote
now, so that the process would be completed before the Protestant
marches that have been flash points for violence begin in July.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Assembly's most important early chores will be
creating a cross-border council that will bring members of the
Northern Ireland government together with ministers from the Irish
government. That responds to the desire of most Catholics for
closer ties to Dublin and is the part of the peace settlement that
Paisley and his followers are most eager to stymie.
</P>
<P>
   The businesslike campaign and the orderly vote were conducted in
an atmosphere of unexpected stability. Although a splinter
republican group, the Irish National Liberation Army, succeeded in
bombing the market square of the rural village of Newtonhamilton
near the Irish border on Wednesday, there have been far fewer
outbreaks of violence than had been predicted by Chief Ronnie
Flanagan of the Royal Ulster Constabulary.
</P>
<P>
   All the major paramilitary groups have been maintaining a
cease-fire, and the election Thursday was at once a product of that
achievement and a guarantor of its continuation.
</P>
<P>
   No results will be known until ballot counting begins on Friday.
But the era of formalized cross-community action in Northern
Ireland actually began Thursday because of the nature of the
ballot. Voters were asked to fill in as many as 12 names in order
of preference in a proportional-representation procedure that lets
winning candidates with surplus votes ``transfer'' them to
finishers behind them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
