<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-STRUMINSKI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOHDAN STRUMINSKI, LINGUIST, 68; FOUGHT SOVIET LANGUAGE POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bohdan A. Struminski, a linguist and translator who spent three
years in a Polish prison for protesting Soviet language policies in
the Ukraine, died of cancer Tuesday in his home in Arlington, Mass.
He was 68.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Struminski was a specialist in Ukrainian, Polish, and Old
Slavic languages. He was the author of ``Linguistic Interrelations
in Early Rus'' and a translator of scholarly source materials for
the series Early Ukrainian Literature published by Harvard
University and the University of Alberta. He also translated
Czeslaw Milosz's ``The Captive Mind'' from Polish into Ukrainian
and was the author of more than 100 scholarly articles.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Bialystok, Poland, the city for which the bialy,
a round, flat bread roll, is named. He graduated from Warsaw
University, where he also earned a doctorate in philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, he was convicted of anti-Soviet activities for
protesting Soviet language policies in the Ukraine and spent nearly
three years in a Polish prison.
</P>
<P>
   He came to the United States in 1975 and was a visiting
professor at Harvard University until 1979, when he became a
research associate at the Harvard Ukrainian Research Institute,
where he remained until his retirement in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   He contributed to Polish and Ukrainian literary publications
such as ``Kultura'' and ``Suchasnist'' under the pen names A.
Skiwski and D. Bajurs'kyj.
</P>
<P>
   Though he bristled at the term Polish-American, he was
editor-in-chief of Zycie Polonii, a publication of the Eastern
Massachusetts division of the Polish-American Congress. In a story
published in the Polish American Journal on Jan. 1, 1994, he
described himself as a ``Polish citizen residing in America.'' He
denounced the Polish-American title ``because,'' he said, ``it
would suggest that I am only a vestigial Pole, still liking the
polka and kielbasa, but no longer a perfect speaker of Polish, with
all the cultural, historical and psychological consequences
thereof.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Kathleen M. Lestition; and a son, Igor of
Poland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7324 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-COURT-VETO     06-25 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-COURT-VETO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    SUPREME COURT STRIKES DOWN PRESIDENTIAL LINE-ITEM AUTHORITY
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Stripping President Clinton of the ability to cut
federal spending with the stroke of a pen, the Supreme Court struck
down his line-item veto authority on Thursday, ruling that the
practice violated Constitutional guarantees of the separation of
power.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 decision denies Clinton the ability to eliminate
specific spending provisions in bills that come to his desk, an
option he had exercised 82 times since the line-item veto authority
took effect 18 months ago. The White House immediately decried the
justices' decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am deeply disappointed,'' Clinton, who is visiting China,
said in a prepared statement. ''It deprives the president of a
valuable tool for eliminating waste in the federal budget.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled Congress approved line-item veto
authority for the president in 1996 as part of a larger effort to
reign in three decades of deficit spending. The provision took
effect in January of 1997, but was challenged in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Upholding an earlier finding by federal district court in
Washington D.C., the Supreme Court ruled that the special veto
power gave the president budget authority clearly assigned to the
Congress by the framers of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the justices ruled, taxation without representation
is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ''Money is the instrument of policy, and policy affects the
lives of citizens,'' wrote Justice Anthony Kennedy. ''The
individual loses liberty in a real sense if that instrument is not
subject to traditional constitutional constraints.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, wrote Kennedy, if voters can't force members of
Congress to keep taxes and spending in balance, it's the fault of
the people, not the process.
</P>
<P>
   ''Failure of political will does not justify unconstitutional
remedies,'' Kennedy wrote. ''Abdication of responsibility is not
part of the constitutional design.''
</P>
<P>
   The president may still propose, but not mandate, specific
spending cuts to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   And it is still the White House that sets the agenda for
taxation and spending by submitting its massive annual budget
proposal to Congress, which then uses those recommendations as a
starting point for the yearlong process of debating and
deliberating over taxes and spending.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's ruling shifts the balance of governmental power
slightly from the White House to Capitol Hill, but presidential
scholars differed over how much it would undercut Clinton's
influence on budgetary affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's lost power,'' said James A. Thurber, director of the
Center for Congressional and Presidential Studies at the American
University in Washington. ''He's losing the capability to control
the agenda on the Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, said the ruling would have a minimal effect on
White House authority.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's two kinds of power _ one is effective political power
and the other is formal constitutional power,'' said George C.
Edwards III, director of the Center for Presidential Studies at
Texas A&AMP;M University, in College Station, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   For the past century, Edwards said, presidential power, as
determined by the chief executive's ability to capture the national
spotlight and use image and rhetoric to help shape the public
debate, has been growing. That, said Edwards, means far more than
the loss of line-item veto authority. ''I actually don't think it
does very much in the short-term,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, moreover, Clinton used the line-item veto
sparingly.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it was ever a very powerful tool,'' said Robert
Bixby, policy director for the Concord Coalition, a Washington
advocacy group dedicated to a balanced federal budget. ''The
president didn't use it much and when he did use it, Congress
frequently overode his vetos.'' Of the 82 items Clinton had vetoed
using the authority, 38 were overridden in Congress _ all affecting
military spending _ and one other was later withdrawn by the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   The 43 remaining vetoes cut $869 million in projected spending
over five years, according to the White House Office of Management
and Budget , not a huge amount of money for a budget that, this
year alone, weighed in at $1.7 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   After three decades of spending more than it takes in, the
federal government is on track this year to raise more revenue
through taxes and fees than it spends. The budget surplus is
expected to top $40 billion, but the savings have resulted chiefly
from six years of lusty economic growth, not from line-item vetos.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the federal books balanced _ and paying off the $5.4
trillion federal debt amassed during a generation of deficit
spending _ will require political discipline, the Supreme Court
ruled, not extra-constitutional measures.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Framers of the Constitution could not command
statesmanship,'' wrote Kennedy. ''They could simply provide
structures from which it might emerge.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
