<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-98-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDOWS 98 ROLLOUT MAKES FEW WAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The introduction of Microsoft Corp.'s new Windows 98 operating
system might be the computer industry's biggest ``non-event'' of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the introduction of Windows 95 three years ago, Microsoft
chose a low-key approach to the Windows 98 rollout, with little
hype and few ads. Meanwhile, industry experts have belittled
Windows 98 as little more than a modest upgrade to Microsoft's
hugely popular Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Microsoft and computer retailers say that
consumers snapped up the new software in its first day on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's biggest computer chain, CompUSA, offered a host of
special bargains to attract customers to the midnight rollout of
Windows 98, including $98 computer systems for the first 10 buyers
in each store.
</P>
<P>
   It worked, according to CompUSA spokeswoman Carol Elfstrom.
``All of our stores had hundreds of people,'' she said. ``Some had
over a thousand. We had a great response. Sales of Windows 98 were
beyond our expectations.'' But Elfstrom refused to provide exact
sales figures.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday morning, there were no crowds at the Micro Center
computer store in Cambridge. Instead, a small, steady stream of
customers filed to balloon-decked displays to pick up their copies
of Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Cole, a Boston software consultant, hopes the software will
boost his computer's performance. ``It's supposed to reduce the
boot time and it's supposed to make disk access faster,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cole thought the $89 price tag was too high. ``I think they're
probably charging 20 percent more than they should but...I'm going
to buy it anyway, so I guess they can get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Matthew Brand, a dump truck mechanic, wanted to
replace the borrowed copy of Windows 95 on his home computer. He
figured $89 was a small price to pay, and he dismissed Microsoft's
critics as sore losers. ``I think other companies are just having a
hard time keeping up with Microsoft,'' he said, ``and that's what
they're complaining about.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft group product manager Rob Bennett said he was pleased
with the first few hours of sales, though he didn't know how many
units were actually sold. ``Even if the product was just half as
successful as Win 95, which was phenomenal, we'd be very
satisfied,'' said Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett will be a happy man, if the industry research firm
Dataquest is on target. Dataquest, of San Jose, Calif., estimates
that 5.5 million units of Windows 98 will be sold this year as
upgrades for machines with Windows 95. That's 37 percent lower than
the 8.8 million upgrade copies that Windows 95 sold in 1995.  &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   But the same study predicts Windows 98 will dominate the market
for operating systems that come pre-installed on new computers.
Dataquest estimates that of 106 million new computers to be sold
this year worldwide, 56.7 million will be equipped with Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   While the initial impact of Windows 98 seemed underwhelming, the
product did get a bump in publicity for an entirely different
reason: the antitrust war between the United States government and
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; On Tuesday, a federal appeals court threw out a lower court
injunction that had barred Microsoft from requiring computer makers
to bundle Microsoft's Internet Explorer Web browser with its
operating system. That issue is central to the Justice Department's
larger antitrust case against the Redmond, Washn. software giant.
The appellate decision made headlines around the world and handed
Microsoft a significant victory in its antitrust battles with the
government.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department could appeal to the Supreme Court to have
the injunction reinstated. But virtually every major computer maker
will now install Windows 98 on their machines, rather than Windows
95, making the injunction meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Microsoft's Bennett said the antitrust dispute may
actually have provided a boost to Windows 98 sales, simply by
keeping the product in the public eye. ``It's not the best kind of
publicity,'' he said, ``but it's certainly helped awareness.''
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 is also the last hurrah for MS-DOS, the operating
system that drove the original IBM Personal Computer in 1981 and
turned Microsoft into a computing superpower. Windows 95 and 98 are
both still largely based upon MS-DOS, an operating system that is
crude by 1990's standards.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, Windows 98 pales in significance to Microsoft's
Windows NT, its high-end product for serious business applications.
Microsoft will build all its future operating systems around
Windows NT, which is designed to run programs more efficiently and
break down less often than MS-DOS and its offspring.
</P>
<P>
   But after the initial buzz wears off, Dataquest analyst Chris
LeTocq predicted that many Windows 95 users won't bother to upgrade
their machines to Windows 98. LeTocq said that Windows 98 would
hold little appeal for business and professional computer users,
because it offers relatively little improvement over Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``If you have Windows 95 and it's working fine and you're not
the sort of person who likes to jump motorcycles over cars, then
there's no reason for you to buy Windows 98,'' said LeTocq. In
addition, he noted that many of the features of Windows 98 can be
added to Windows 95 for free, by downloading software add-ons from
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The real market for Windows 98, LeTocq said, are computer
hobbyists who enjoy tinkering with the latest hardware and
software. ``For those guys,'' he said, ``this is $90 of
entertainment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
