<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7329 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YEN-SLIPS-BOS &LR;      06-25 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEN-SLIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE YEN SLIDES AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Japanese yen slipped Thursday to its lowest level against
the dollar since the United States last week shored up Japan's
currency and attempted to bolster its economy.
</P>
<P>
   The yen fell a fourth straight day as world currency traders
grew pessimistic Japan's leaders would take the painful steps
needed to repair a disabled banking system, the only solution to
restoring an economy that contracted at a 5.3 percent annual rate
in the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In betting against the yen, currency traders played a role in
Japan's downward economic spiral: As the yen declines and the stock
market sinks, losses mount at Japan's banks _ heavy investors in
the Nikkei. As losses grow, banks are unable to make loans to
businesses that could recharge the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in a vicious cycle as the yen depreciates,'' says
Robert Litan of the Brookings Institution, a Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   The yen closed Thursday at 142.19 per US dollar, up 1.14. The
Nikkei barely moved, Thursdayedging up 9 points to close at
15,132.22 _ the market has been flat all year.
</P>
<P>
   The prescription recommended by US Treasury Department officials
in Tokyo last week was clear: Deal immediately, and decisively,
with the financial crisis. But America's desire to impose on Japan
a Texas-style bailout _ closing large, troubled banks _ is no easy
sell to political leaders afraid of taking costly measures before
elections next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese are floating down that great river in Egypt _
`denial,''' says Richard Katz, a reporter in New York for the
Oriental Economist Report, an English-language newsletter on the
region.
</P>
<P>
   There is much to be done.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government estimates _ economists say
conservatively _ that bad loans total $550 billion. That's more
than double the weight of all bad loans that pulled down financial
institutions in New England and Texas _ and Japan's crisis has
slammed an economy only half as big as the United States'.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Patrick, director of the Center on Japanese Economy and
Business at Columbia University who returned last week from Japan,
predicted that the world will ``start seeing, over the next few
months, additional newsworthy items _ banks merging, going under. I
view that as good news. Unfortunately, most ordinary people will
view it as bad news.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be costly for Japan. The country's bailout could
ultimately amount to nearly 8 percent of gross domestic product.
The US savings and loan crisis, which ultimately cost US taxpayers
more than $130 billion, was about 3 percent of US GDP.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Japan has a trove of riches that can be used to
shore up its banks. The Japanese are vicious savers, stashing $800
billion in one savings bank run by the country's postal service.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever course Japan chooses, economists and US bank regulators
say it will likely require a huge injection by the government into
a banking system that is bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for delay: Politics. ``There's a very strong
resistance to using public funds _ there's a taboo,'' said Steven
Vogel, a Japan specialist and assistant professor of government at
Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Policy makers face myriad dilemmas. For example, a move by the
Bank of Japan to help the economy by reducing already-low interest
rates would further pummel the yen at a time it is trading at
historic lows.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a week after US &UR;  &LR; Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers' trip to Japan, Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto said he
agreed to set up what is known as a ``bridge bank'' that would
provide government backing during a transition as sick institutions
are restored to healthy ones. The term ``bridge bank'' is even
borrowed from US bailouts.
</P>
<P>
   The reality, say US officials, is that the Japanese government
has hammered out few details of the &UR;  &LR; gargantuan bailout facing
them. The legislature, the Diet, has not yet approved the
establishment of a bridge bank. Now Japan's efforts to clean up the
banks are on hold until after national elections July 12.
Controversial issues are off limits for a Liberal Democratic Party
hoping to win a majority in the upper house.
</P>
<P>
   The government last spring appropriated $30 billion to a trust
fund that can be used to cover depositors or investors in
bank-issued bonds in the event banks fail, and to replenish healthy
banks. By comparison, the 19 banks that form the core of Japan's
financial system lost $28 billion in 1997, according to an estimate
from Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   William Seidman, who chaired the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
during the late-1980s bailouts and has consulted in recent months
to Japan's central bank and Diet members, believes Japan has only
one option: Roll up their sleeves and determine which banks are in
the worst financial condition. Next, he says, the government must
close or sell the sick ones infecting the entire system.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were really just getting into those tough problems,''
says Seidman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; While some Japanese banks have failed, rumors in Tokyo are
wild that one of the country's biggest banks, the Long Term Credit
Bank of Japan Ltd., is in serious trouble. Bank president Katsunobu
Onogi said at the annual shareholder meeting Thursday he would
consider a merger. Although Onogi did not disclose any names,
possible merger candidates include Nippon Credit Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But a merger with Nippon, a smaller bank in worse condition,
would create a bigger problem, said Tomishi Ishida, a Tokyo bank
analyst. ``It's bad,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
