<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, June 26. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-VETO (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules that the
president cannot cancel individual items of federal spending and
tax breaks approved by Congress because such ``line item vetoes''
circumvent the law-making procedure prescribed by the Constitution.
The ruling is a major blow to Congress and to President Clinton,
who, like many of his predecessors, coveted tax and spending powers
that he did not have. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-AIDS (Washington) _ People with HIV infection need not
have any symptoms of disease or obvious impairment to be covered by
the federal law that bars discrimination on the basis of
disability, the Supreme Court rules in a major victory for people
with the virus that causes AIDS. Voting 5-4, the justices agreed
with a federal appeals court's ruling that a woman with
asymptomatic HIV infection, who was refused care in a dentist's
office, met the definition of disability under the Americans with
Disabilities Act. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON (Xian, China) _ With the pageantry of thundering
drums and clanging gongs, President Clinton is welcomed to China,
the first U.S. president to visit this country in nearly a decade,
and he mildly rebukes critics in Washington who have attacked his
policy of engagement with the Beijing government. By John M.
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   MCDOUGAL _ A federal judge orders the release from prison of
convicted Whitewater figure Susan McDougal because she suffers from
a serious neck and spinal condition.
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN-LUTHERANS (Undated) _ In a decision that brings to a
close a divisive chapter of the Reformation, the Vatican says that
the Roman Catholic Church will sign a joint declaration with the
world's Lutherans that affirms that Catholics and Lutherans share a
basic understanding of how human beings receive salvation. The
document, approved last week by the Lutheran World Federation,
declares that Catholics and Lutherans have common ground to
overcome the issue that split the Western Christian world nearly
500 years ago _ the question of whether ``justification'' comes
solely through faith in God, as Luther held, or whether a person's
good works also play a role, as Catholics emphasized. By Gustav
Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   GM-STRIKE (Flint, Mich.) _ Like a large stone thrown in a pond,
the strikes at two General Motors' parts factories are producing
economic effects that are slowly rippling out across North America.
The first effects were felt immediately in this town when the
strike began, because GM accounts for more than half the employment
and taxes here. When 3,400 workers went on strike at a metal parts
stamping factory here on June 5, nearby restaurants lost half their
business immediately, while the pool table and bar stools at the
pub across the street have been deserted for the last three weeks.
The next ripples came over the last two weeks as the company has
closed 26 of its 29 assembly plants in North America and curtailed
production at nearly 100 parts factories. Now the effects are
reaching across the country, into communities and states where the
auto industry has been less visible than here in the industrial
Midwest. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEW-PLANETS (Undated) _ The discoveries of planets beyond
the solar system, stimulating renewed speculation of other possible
worlds throbbing with life, are now drawing closer in cosmic terms
to the world of their discoverers. The latest detection, made this
month by American astronomers, is of a planet about twice the mass
of Jupiter orbiting the star Gliese 876, one of the Sun's nearest
neighbors at a distance of only 15 light-years away. Previous
confirmed extrasolar planets have been observed at stars 40 to 80
light-years away. By John Noble Wilford. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-NY-YANKS-METS (New York) _ If the heavens cooperate, two
teams will gather on a swath of Queens County grass to demonstrate
how the game of baseball has particularly blessed New York City
this year with talent and character. An umpire will shout a
familiar demand, a Mets pitcher will fire a baseball to a Yankees
batter, and all will be right in one corner of an ever-churning
metropolis. By Dan Barry.
</P>
