<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-GERMANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY DEFEATS IRAN, 2-0, MOVES INTO SECOND-ROUND MATCH WITH
MEXICO  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELLIER, France _ On a patch of worn grass leading to La
Mosson Stadium, between two of the many police checkpoints in
Montpellier Thursday, a group of Germans sat with a handwritten
sign in French by their feet.
</P>
<P>
   The sign read, ``Sorry for Lens.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day Germany clinched first place in Group F with a 2-0
victory over Iran, there were many poignant gestures of regret from
German fans and officials for the French policeman, Daniel Nivel,
who was beaten by German hooligans in Lens, an attack that left him
in a coma after Germany's match against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   There were messages of apology for the attack on display in the
stands and on the official World Cup web site. German Foreign
Minister Klaus Kinkel visited Montpellier's famous square, la Place
de la Comedie, to express his regret over the incident and his
support of French police, who were out in force throughout this
peaceful city Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One German tabloid newspaper, the same that published graphic
photos of the beating, has opened an account to receive donations
for Nivel's family, and a poll conducted by German television
network RTL found that 62 percent of its viewers were in favor of
the German team giving the Nivel family its bonus money from the
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   In case of victory, that bonus would be approximately $3
million, but for now all that is certain is that Germany is in the
World Cup second round for the 12th consecutive time. It got there
by doing more than necessary _ it only needed a draw Thursday night
_ but by doing less than some of its German critics would like to
see. For the second consecutive match, it played a mediocre first
half, struggling with its transition from defense to attack, but
the Germans quickly found their rhythm in the second half: getting
goals on headers from Oliver Bierhoff in the 50th minute and
captain Jurgen Klinsmann in the 57th.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not the perfect team, but I haven't seen the perfect
team yet in this World Cup,'' said Klinsmann, one of eight German
starters over 30. ``We can improve, and we will improve.''
</P>
<P>
   The Germans, who will face Mexico in the second round in
Montpellier, finished with seven points in the group, taking first
place over Yugoslavia on goal differential. The Iranians finished
third with three points: all earned by the emotional 2-1 victory
over the United States that made their World Cup a success.''We
were a little tired tonight after running so much against the
Americans,' said Iranian defender Mohammed Khakpour. ``But the
Germans were the best team we played here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
