<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7339 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-US-YUGO-BOS &LR;      06-25 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-YUGO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US LOSES, BUT SALVAGES SOME PRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France _ The United States salvaged some pride and
Yugoslavia concentrated on self-preservation Thursday night. The
Yugoslavs took a 1-0 victory, coasting after an early goal by
Slobodan Komljenovic, but they were unable to turn this World Cup
match into a goalfest in an effort to overtake Germany for first
place in Group F.
</P>
<P>
   This translated into the smallest of accomplishments for the US,
which was eliminated by Iran Sunday and concluded the tournament
without a point and with one goal, its lowest scoring total since
the 1934 finals in Italy. Yugoslavia had hoped to avoid a
second-round meeting with Holland but will meet the Group E winner
in Toulouse Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The US had virtually nothing at stake, and the atmosphere was
much calmer in this city than it was in Lyon, site of Sunday's
match against Iran. But the US played conservatively in a 3-6-1
formation, demonstrating little creativity or inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   A US victory would have been as believable as a science fiction
work by Nantes's most famous author, Jules Verne. But it nearly
scored in the opening seconds as a Frankie Hejduk cross skimmed the
far post.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia appeared dangerous with a high-powered midfield and
Real Madrid striker Pedrag Mijatovic. But Mijatovic suffered a leg
injury and departed in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew from the outset this would be a very important
match,'' Yugoslav coach Slobodan Santrac said. ``We knew the US had
weaknesses and we were hoping to capitalize on them. Unfortunately,
we were unable to when we had chances for goals in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US played three strong matches. They didn't get the
results they hoped to get, but this is a team which will continue
to progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavs put the game away early as Mijatovic was held by
Mike Burns 35 yards from the goal and Egyptian referee Gamal
Ghandour awarded a free kick. Sinisa Mihajlovic, whose free kick
provided the difference in an opening victory over Iran, drilled a
shot to goalkeeper Brad Friedel's left. Friedel's punch went
directly toward the far post, where Komljenovic neatly headed past
Thomas Dooley.
</P>
<P>
   The US nearly scored in the first 25 seconds when Hejduk's cross
surprised goalkeeper Ivica Kralj and glanced off the far post.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Americans' chances came after the first goal, the
best after a Brian McBride cross was sent just wide of the far post
by Joe-Max Moore in the 31st minute. McBride departed after a clash
with Slavisa Jokanovic and returned two minutes later with his head
bandaged.
</P>
<P>
   Mijatovic went toward the bench in the 31st minute and might
have cost the Yugoslavs a goal as he left the exact place where
Milosevic's shot rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia appeared content to counterattack and remained
dangerous with Mijatovic's replacement, Perica Ognjenovic, who
combined well with Milosevic and Stankovic. But the Yugoslavs
struggled to find a midfield rhythm as Dragan Stojkovic was
repeatedly confronted by US players. Vladimir Jugovic supported
Stojkovic and put the US under pressure. Claudio Reyna retreated
into defense to break up a Stankovic counter late in the half, and
Burns got the best of a collision with Stankovic in the penalty
area.
</P>
<P>
   Preki entered 10 minutes into the second half in place of Moore
but had little influence on the game until late. Cobi Jones was
fouled by Jugovic, and Preki curled a 25-yard free kick just over
the bar in the 38th minute. Eric Wynalda and Marcelo Balboa, among
the veterans excluded from most of the action in the World Cup by
coach Steve Sampson, entered late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We proved we can play very good soccer against very good
teams,'' Sampson said. ``Again, our inability to finish was
crucial. Our lack of precision must be improved on as a national
team if we expect to get any kind of results in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will of course remember the quality of the opposition, what
I think was outstanding organization, also the tremendous fan
support of the Americans who traveled to France, the quality of
football we played at times, the numerous chances against Iran, and
of course, the missed chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we have already learned a lot from this. The first
half against Germany will be probably the greatest learning
experience for us. We had to very quickly learn to wake up to the
level of soccer at this level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
