<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKPLACE QUESTIONS FOR THE '90S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Two questions: Should any worker be exempt from
adapting to change?
</P>
<P>
   Change has a spot right up there with death and taxes. It is a
constant that cuts across all workplaces. It comes in new
technology, corporate reorganization, personnel realignment and
even forces of nature. Whatever the cause, it comes.
</P>
<P>
   So, should members of a union, who entered a workforce under one
set of agreements and expectations, be exempt from change when
their employer seeks to alter their labor agreement?
</P>
<P>
   Should a mentally retarded woman, who entered a workforce to do
only a single task, be exempt from change when her employer
restructures job definitions so that all workers must handle more
than one task?
</P>
<P>
   These are real questions. General Motors knows. It's dealing
with both of them in the arenas of law and public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, it's easy to say to those resisting change: Get
over it. Get with it. Only those who change will survive under the
new rules of global competition and investor expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But there's always another hand.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any reason for collective bargaining to exist any more,
if not for its ability to fulfill the quality-of-work expectations
of those it represents?
</P>
<P>
   Is there any reason for the Americans with Disabilities Act to
exist, if not for its ability to protect the quality-of-work
expectations of those it represents?
</P>
<P>
   These, too, are real questions. The answers aren't easy,
especially when what seems economically expedient to employers
clashes with the expectations of employees and others. It often
takes time and pain to bring to put those unaligned expectations in
sync.
</P>
<P>
   Will the United Auto Workers prevail in obtaining job security
guarantees?
</P>
<P>
   Will Denise Anderson win the right to return to a line job that
no longer exists?
</P>
<P>
   We'll wait for answers, knowing that unaligned expectations
sometimes never align.
</P>
<P>
   Should any worker stay in a job he or she hates?
</P>
<P>
   I happened to pass by two workers in conversation, one of whom
was saying this, ``I hate my job as much today as I did
yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not said in jest. It was said in the tone someone uses to
say, ``My cancer is not yet in remission.''
</P>
<P>
   The speaker was a stranger, but I wasn't sure whether I wanted
to slap him or hug him.
</P>
<P>
   What we do for a living takes up too much of our time and is too
much a part of our identity _ like it or not _ to hate it that
much.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a time of bread lines and soup kitchens. Jobs are
begging for people, not the other way around. Yes, there are people
who cannot find the job they want. Yes, a prolonged job search is
financially and emotionally painful.
</P>
<P>
   But there are alternatives. Maybe not the dream job, the perfect
job, the one equal to your experience and income expectations. But
skills can be adapted and used in many different ways. There are
temporary solutions and even long-range ones that are better, much
better, than the daily agony of dragging yourself to and through a
job you hate.
</P>
<P>
   Job security is a great thing. But, face it, it doesn't exist
any more for most people. Don't stay in a job just because you have
it. Security never outweighs misery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 1932EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
