<SLUG> BC-GUS-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DELICACY AMID THORNS AND PESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: People long familiar with that piece of country cannot
remember a year when the blackberries began coming ripe so soon, or
the canes were heavier with fruit.
</P>
<P>
   By middle June, a full two weeks early, the first were ready for
picking. Most still were red, so you had to search for the ripe
ones. But they were there low among the foliage _ plump and glossy
black, though a bit tart yet.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be sweeter this coming weekend. And sweeter still a bit
deeper into July. By then, nearly all will be mature, and the trick
in gathering will be to make the hand deliver them to the pail, not
to the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   I know of no gift that nature gives in more dependable
abundance. Only in a year when a late spring frost spoils the
blooming _ last year was such a one _ does the berry harvest fail.
And even then, there's usually some sheltered place whose
microclimate has preserved a few _ enough for a pie or a cobbler or
two.
</P>
<P>
   The gift is not entirely free, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Ticks and chiggers, in their inestimable numbers, await the
picker. When I was small, my mother dusted sulfur in my socks and
inside my trousers at the beltline to keep those pests away.
</P>
<P>
   It was useless. Then as now, no preparation known to man would
turn them, the chiggers especially. And it's said one also ought to
be careful of snakes in a blackberry thicket, though I've never met
one there.
</P>
<P>
   It's the clawing thorns that deliver the worst punishment. No
matter how cautiously you work, they catch the hand and lance
through sleeve and trouser leg. The swollen sun beats down, sending
salty rivulets of perspiration into the scratches.
</P>
<P>
   I can remember more than once getting so snagged and entangled
among the canes that there seemed no hope of ever getting loose
again.
</P>
<P>
   And I was tempted to cry out to my fellow pickers just to go on
and leave me, the way some northern tribes abandon their infirm
alone on the ice, to await the mercy of predators.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, in that country there are no predators of
sufficient size or savagery to finish the job.
</P>
<P>
   So there was nothing for it but to make my way to freedom in the
best possible way, whimpering and using what I believe is termed
/{adult/} language. And trying not to drop the part-full pail of
berries already picked.
</P>
<P>
   We understand perfectly the misery that waits, and yet we look
forward to this weekend and the next several of gathering.
</P>
<P>
   One fine year my daughter and her friend and I came home from
the country with enough berries to bake a dozen pies, or it could
have been more. Maybe 20. I think there may still be one or two in
the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, from time to time, we would take one out and thaw it
for the birthday of someone we knew, or some other special
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   By then, naturally, our wounds and welts had healed, the scars
had all but disappeared, so there was nothing to suggest the price
of suffering we'd paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tasty,'' the people would say.
</P>
<P>
   Only that. Then the conversation would pass on to something
else.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't want to sound bitter about it. But since then we've
gotten choosier about whom we share our berries with. What possible
joy can there be in giving, if the beneficiary doesn't understand
exactly how much your kindness cost?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
