<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-BUHL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUHL HOPING FOR ANOTHER COMEBACK WIN IN NEW ENGLAND 200 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robbie Buhl reflected on his first career Indy Racing League
triumph in last year's Pennzoil 200 at New Hampshire International
Speedway and remembered that it all happened, as things often do in
a feverish Indy car race, suddenly and dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   With three laps to go, Buhl inherited the lead from Eddie
Cheever but narrowly averted a rear-end collision when Cheever's
gearbox failed. Then, in another bit of last-lap drama, Buhl held
off a furious charge by runner-up Vincenzo Sospiri by .064 seconds,
the closest margin in IRL history.
</P>
<P>
   A 1986 graduate of New England College in Henniker, N.H., Buhl
could not think of a better backdrop for his first race back behind
the wheel of his Team Menard car after he suffered a severe
concussion during a test session at Pikes Peak, Colo., and was
sidelined for two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It couldn't have been scripted any better, especially with the
whole scenario and all that,'' he said during a media luncheon
Thursday at the Original Sports Saloon. ``That's what made it
pretty sweet _ that whole scenario of what had happened coming into
that race, with me spending the better time of my life around here
(in college) and racing up at that track when I paid 35 bucks on a
Thursday to go riding around up there.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, yeah, the timing of all that couldn't have been better,
that is for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhl, a 34-year-old native of Grosse Point, Mich., would like
nothing more than to duplicate his feat in Sunday's Pep Boys IRL
event, the New England 200, at NHIS. He will enter the race 15th in
the points standings with 58 after finishing only half of the four
races he's entered, including the last at Texas Motor Speedway,
where he recorded a season-best sixth place in the True Value 500K
June 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come back and win that event last year, that was as
gratifying as anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Buhl sported a new goatee and a renewed sense of
determination. But all he wanted, really, was to prove he was back.
Good as new. ``The reason I did (grow the goatee) last year was
that I was trying to do anything to confuse the doctors into
letting me drive,'' said Buhl, who arrived in Boston Thursday
sporting a goatee.
</P>
<P>
   Superstitious, Robbie?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not really. I'm not superstitious. I don't deal with
superstitions. The only routine I have is ... OK, the rabbit's
foot, the same gloves I've had since '81 ...'' he joked. ``Really,
the only thing I do is I get in a race car from the lefthand side.
It's not a superstition. I just always get in on the lefthand
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhl says he will not retrace his steps from last year, but he
will make a stop today at Children's Hospital as part of his
``Racing for Kids'' program. Still, nothing would change Buhl's
luck like another victory at NHIS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say I'm definitely as hungry as I was last year from
the standpoint that things have just not gone well for us this
year,'' he said. ``We've just had some unforeseen things happen to
us. So we really need a win to help us erase that and help us with
our momentum for the rest of the year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
