<HEADLINE>
BUST OF MISSOURI CONGRESSMAN UNVEILED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Emerson, the late congressman, was just a
teenager, not even old enough yet to drive, when he first carved
out a small place for himself on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1953, and he was fresh from Hillsboro, Mo., a wide-eyed
15-year-old with a love of history, roaming the marble halls as a
congressional page.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, 45 years later, Emerson's place in the
congressional firmament became permanently fixed.
</P>
<P>
   In a crowded ceremony in the Capitol's Statuary Hall, Emerson's
wife, friends and former colleagues unveiled a bronze bust of the
Missouri Republican that will be placed at the House's Page School
in the Library of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anything that's more perfect than for this
bust to reside at the entrance to the page school so that pages
will see that they too, can be anything they want to be,'' said
Rep. Jo Ann Emerson, who succeeded her husband as Missouri's 8th
District representative after his death of cancer two years ago
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Emerson, elected in 1980, was a conservative Republican who
built a reputation for pragmatism. While he championed issues that
affected Missouri, such as agriculture and public works, he also
cast a wider net to become a leading Capitol Hill voice on hunger
and congressional reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of his great strengths was that he was very unassuming,
very workmanlike,'' said House Speaker Newt Gingrich. ``He didn't
take himself seriously. He was able to cut through the baloney.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any person who kept the institution closer to
his heart,'' said Sen. Pat Roberts of Kansas. Roberts served with
Emerson in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration for a lasting memorial to Emerson came the day
of his funeral when Bill Coffield, Emerson's executive assistant,
and James Sharp, a friend from college, got together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to chatting, and Jim said what would really be a neat
thing, and of course, Bill would never ask for it, but to have a
bust of him somewhere special,'' Coffield said.
</P>
<P>
   So they formed a nonprofit group, raised money and hired
sculptor Michael Curtis, of Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   And Emerson Hall at the page school, so named after the
congressman just after his death, seemed to be the most fitting
place.
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager, Emerson wrote to every member of the House and
Senate but got little encouragement in his request to become a
page, his wife recalled. But in Washington for the inauguration of
President Eisenhower in 1953 _ a trip promised to him by his
grandfather _ Emerson stopped by the office of his local
congressman, Thomas Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're Billy Emerson from Hillsboro, Missouri.?'' Curtis'
receptionist said to him, Jo Ann Emerson recounted. ``We have been
looking all over for you!''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis hired the future congressman on the spot. His mother had
to send him his clothes by mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was truly a child of Congress,'' said Rep. Ike Skelton, a
Missouri Democrat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
