<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RECEIVES EMPEROR'S WELCOME IN ANCIENT CHINESE CITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   XI'AN, China _ Greeted by thunderous drummers and delicate
dancers, President Clinton received an emperor's welcome Thursday
in China's ancient capital city, where he began a nine-day tour
shadowed by controversy.
</P>
<P>
   China also displayed the tyrant's whim, as officials detained at
least three dissidents and stepped up surveillance of other
pro-democracy advocates throughout the country just hours before
Clinton's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Already stung by the host government's refusal to grant visas to
three Radio Free Asia reporters, Clinton again called human rights
vital to China's future as he became the first U.S. president to
visit the Asian nation since the bloody Tiananmen Square massacre
nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Xi'an is the first stop on a five-city tour that also will take
the president to Beijing to meet with President Jiang Zemin, to the
financial center of Shanghai, to the mountainous Guilin and to Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The trip comes at a sensitive time in U.S.-Chinese relations as
Asia faces an economic crisis and an nuclear arms escalation on the
Indian subcontinent. It also comes as Congress investigates China's
role in the 1996 U.S. elections and whether the Chinese also
received information that allowed the massive country to improve
its missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``A new day is dawning for the Chinese people, for China's
greatness lies, as always, with its people,'' said Clinton,
standing before the dramatically lit 14th-century fortress wall
that protected Xi'an's old central city from outsiders and
invaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this global information age, where both economic growth and
individual opportunity are based on ideas, a commitment to
providing all human beings the opportunity to develop their full
potential is vital to the strength and success of the new China as
well,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Chinese agents arrested Yan Jun, a Xi'an
dissident who was one of 70 people who signed a letter asking
Clinton to meet with democracy advocates. They also detained Li
Xiaolong in the southern Guangxi province, and Li Zhiying of
ChengCheng, according to wire reports.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry indicated it was unlikely
Clinton would meet with dissidents, for fear of triggering
government reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   China's leaders, President Jiang Zemin and Premier Zhu Rongji,
desperately want to present the nation's best face as Clinton's
tour draws international attention.
</P>
<P>
   But the detentions and the rejection of visas for Radio Free
Asia reporters cast a pall on the visit and bolstered the critics
who assailed Clinton for making the journey.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton twice ignored media questions about the dissidents'
arrests. Later, a White House spokesman said the administration was
aware of the detention reports and that U.S. Ambassador James
Sasser would raise the issue with Chinese officials Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also sent letters
protesting the rejection of visas for three people who work for
Voice of America's Radio Free Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president, in his meetings with President Jiang, will
encourage China to allow freer political dialogue so that all
Chinese citizens can be free to express their political beliefs
without government interference,'' said spokesman P.J. Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Xi'an turned out in droves to catch a glimpse of
the president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands, standing quietly, lined up 10 deep to watch
Clinton's 50-car motorcade pass through the city. A threatened
protest over inadequate housing in Xi'an never materialized, or at
least was not seen.
</P>
<P>
   Xi'an Mayor Feng Xucchu treated Clinton to the 8th-century Tang
Dynasty ``Emperor's Welcome'' in which 150 people dressed as
ancient warriors, horseback riders, drummers and dancers gathered
for an elaborate twilight ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the U.S. delegation walked down 200 yards of red
carpet before the South Gate of the 36-foot high fortress wall,
outlined by small yellow lights. As drummers banged on large kettle
drums, women dressed in white and bearing flowers danced before the
entourage. Afterward, the delegation walked across a drawbridge and
into the old city itself.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the invited guests that he hoped he would learn
more about China and that China would learn more about the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe both Chinese and Americans aspire to many of the
same things _ to provide for our families, to teach our children,
to build our communities, to protect our Earth, to shape our own
futures and pass brighter possibilities on to our children,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be those here and back in America who wonder whether
closer ties and deeper friendship between America and China are
good. Clearly the answer is yes,'' the president said. ``We have a
powerful ability to help each other grow. We can learn much from
each other. The steps we take over the next week can lead to far
greater strides for our people in the years ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
