<HEADER>
A7362 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEBANON-PRISONERS-ART     06-25 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-PRISONERS-ART-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI SOLDIER'S REMAINS EXCHANGED FOR BODIES OF GUERRILLAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The remains of an Israeli soldier killed in a failed
marine commando raid in Lebanon last September were flown to Israel
on Thursday in exchange for the bodies of 40 Lebanese guerrillas
and the freeing Friday of 60 prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Before the swap between Israel and the Iranian-backed Shiite
Muslim group Hezbollah, two more Israeli soldiers were killed in
the Israeli occupation zone in southern Lebanon in an attack
claimed by Hezbollah. But the exchange, reached after 10 months of
tortuous negotiations mediated by the Lebanese government, France
and the Red Cross, proceeded as planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Along with the war there are also human sides,'' said Maj.
Gen. Amiram Levine, the Israeli army's northern front commander.
``If this is a sign of feelers, humanity and dialogue, than it is a
very important step.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army said it had received the remains of Staff Sgt.
Itamar Ilya, 21, who was killed by explosives he was carrying when
his commando squad was hit by roadside charges while on a raid
north of the Israeli occupation zone Sept. 4. Twelve marine
commandos died in the botched operation, but all the bodies except
Ilya's were recovered. It was the highest single Israeli death toll
in Lebanon in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah said it had also returned body parts of at least two
other Israelis killed in the raid, but an Israeli army spokesman
declined to say whether other remains were received.
</P>
<P>
   Among the corpses of guerrillas turned over by Israel was that
of Hadi Nasrallah, the son of the leader of Hezbollah, Sheik Hassan
Nasrallah. The son was killed in a clash with Israeli troops, and
his body had been held by the Israelis as a bargaining chip for the
return of Ilya's remains.
</P>
<P>
   After Hezbollah and Amal, another Shiite guerrilla group,
transferred the remains to the Lebanese army, they were flown to
Israel on a French military transport plane.
</P>
<P>
   The plane landed at dusk at an Israeli air force base near Tel
Aviv, where it was boarded by the army's chief rabbi, Maj. Gen. Gad
Navon, for what was described as identification of Ilya's remains.
They were transferred to a simple wooden coffin that was carried
off the plane, draped in an Israeli flag, by comrades of the dead
soldier.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, soldiers moved 40 numbered wooden coffins of
guerrillas from flatbed trucks to the transport plane, which later
took off for Beirut. The bodies had been unearthed overnight from
cemeteries in northern Israel, where they had been kept for
possible exchanges for Israeli captives or war dead.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``For us, every combatant, every soldier in the army, every
missing soldier, every prisoner of war _ it is our obligation to
find him and return him to his country and to his family,'' said
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in a speech in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   In Beirut, Hezbollah put up banners welcoming ``the returning
martyrs'' and posters of Kalashnikov rifles on the route from the
airport into the city. Nasrallah said that he drew ``a measure of
comfort'' from the return of his son's body, and credited the
guerrilla ``resistance'' for making the exchange possible.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Israel is scheduled to free 60 Lebanese prisoners from
Hezbollah, Amal and other guerrilla groups. Ten will be released
from jails in Israel and 50 from a prison run in southern Lebanon
by Israel's militia ally there, the South Lebanon Army. An Israeli
military statement said that those to be released are ``without
blood on their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's violence, two bombs exploded near a group of
Israeli soldiers, killing two and injuring two in southern Lebanon.
Hezbollah is fighting to evict Israeli troops from a nine-mile wide
swath of territory there that is held as a buffer against attacks
on northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing deaths in southern Lebanon have set off a debate
among Israelis about whether the army should cut its losses,
withdraw from the area and defend Israel from its northern border.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has offered to pull out if the Lebanese army
guarantees security. But the Lebanese government and Syria, the
main power broker in Lebanon, have rejected the idea.
</P>
