<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM workers seek unemployment pay
 &HT;    By Kristi E. Swartz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Travis Brideman has been through this before.
</P>
<P>
   Brideman, who has been out of work a week because of a forced
shutdown of General Motors Corp.'s assembly plant, lined up with
fellow workers Thursday to file for unemployment benefits with the
Georgia Labor Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to prepare,'' said Brideman, who has been at the
Doraville plant for 19 years.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,000 Doraville workers have been off the job because
of a shortage of parts caused by United Auto Workers strikes in
Flint, Mich. Thursday was the first day they could file for
unemployment benefits, a maximum of $224 a week, about half their
GM pay. They got their last GM paycheck Thursday and could start
receiving unemployment checks in one to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Brideman said he hasn't been looking for temporary work yet but
said he will if the strike goes far into the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Department and union officials are helping workers fill
out applications Thursday and today at the UAW Local 10 building.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all of the idled workers are expected to file for
benefits, according to Labor Department spokesman Sam Hall and UAW
Local 10 President Bill Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they think they may be eligible, they should file because
each claim is decided on its own merit,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia law requires those filing for unemployment be out of
work through no fault of their own; actively seek full-time
employment; and be physically and mentally able to take a job if
one is offered.
</P>
<P>
   Because the shutdown was caused by a labor dispute, the labor
commissioner will appoint a tribunal from GM and UAW officials to
determine whether to grant benefits, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   GM will challenge unemployment claims because paying those
claims means the company would be financing a strike against
itself, said GM spokesman Gerry Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   If workers are denied benefits, they can receive strike pay of
$150 a week from the union.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
