<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPACT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT&AMP;T deal starts race among Net providers
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- AT&AMP;T's pending purchase of Tele-Communications has
sounded off like a starter's gun in the executive suites of the
telephone and cable TV industries.
</P>
<P>
   While both industries compete already for Internet and telephone
customers, the race among them will now begin in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   It's a race that will involve some of Atlanta's biggest
companies, including cable operator Cox Communications, BellSouth
Corp., Scientific-Atlanta and Hayes Microcomputers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them are doing what AT&AMP;T plans to do with TCI: offer
Internet access and local telephone service through cable's digital
two-way lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger is a good thing for the industry and a good thing
for Scientific-Atlanta,'' says Steve Necessary, a vice president
for marketing. His company's products include a set-top box that
enables the two-way features of cable's new digital lines.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, the number of households connected to the Internet
has grown 89 percent, according to a study by online consultant
Jupiter Communications. It projects the number of households will
reach 57 million by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   With 22.6 million customers, independent providers such as
MindSpring and America Online have the lead so far. Next come the
telephone companies, with 5.7 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   While far behind, cable operators such as Cox Communications are
growing. There are an estimated 200,000-plus households using cable
lines to reach the Net at speeds up to 100 times faster than
traditional telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   That number represents a tiny portion of the 68 million
households with cable TV. In part, it's because only about 15
percent of the nation's cable lines have been upgraded to provide
the service.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also true there isn't much demand yet for cable modems.
Most customers have fast connections at work and want the same at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cable has a great pipe but, will this service take off
tomorrow?'' says Bruce Leitchman, a media analyst with the Yankee
Group. ``The answer is no. Nor will it take off in the next four
years, but it is a great long-run play.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Atlanta companies are gambling big on the potential of
cable Internet access and telephone service. Cox Communications,
for example, now offers high-speed Internet connections through
cable modems in parts of its systems in Orange County, Calif., San
Diego and Phoenix. It also has begun offering telephone service in
some of these areas.
</P>
<P>
   And in metro Atlanta, cable operators MediaOne and Comcast are
offering the service. Less than 1,000 households have ordered cable
modems so far in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   While these numbers seem small, some industry observers are not
discouraged. ``Cable modems are doing better than anticipated,''
says Zia Daniell, a media analyst with Jupiter Communications.
``We're very bullish.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
