<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Takeover rumor springs MindSpring stock
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Speculation of a takeover bid sent shares of the
Atlanta-based MindSpring Enterprises soaring to an all time high
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring closed Thursday at $94.88 up $14.31. In early
trading, the stock reached an all time high of $96.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the speculation fueled by the news of the
AT&AMP;T-Telecommunications Inc. merger, the company announced a
three-to-one stock split aimed at attracting more individual
investors. The split will be the company's first, payable July 24
to shareholders of record July 9.
</P>
<P>
   The MindSpring stock surge has Wall Street analysts once again
speculating that the Atlanta Internet service provider (ISP) is
ripe for acquisition, something the company continually denies.
Rumors of a MindSpring takeover have been circulating ever since
the company's stock began to climb in early March.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McQuary, president and chief operating officer says the
company is open to offers, though acquisitions aren't a focus right
now. ``We are always talking to major players. If an interesting
offer came along we would consider it, but right now we are just
trying to build our own company. ''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is speculation that MindSpring is a target. It's that cut
and dry,'' said analyst Jeff Sadler of Robinson-Humphrey. Sadler
says a potential suitor would either be looking for a quality
provider or one with a large subscriber base. ``And America Online
has politely said they are not for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
