<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONATO, KHRISTICH COULD FACE TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ While the Bruins prepare for Friday's NHL expansion
draft and Saturday's entry draft, they are also mulling the future
of some players currently on their roster _ Ted Donato and Dmitri
Khristich, who will become restricted free agents Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be surprising to see Donato, 29, moved to another
team. His ice time diminished last season under first-year coach
Pat Burns, and president/general manager Harry Sinden said that
last spring, Donato asked to be traded if he wasn't going to be
used more.
</P>
<P>
   ``His role changed on the team this year,'' said Sinden. ``He
and Steve Heinze used to kill a lot of penalties. They didn't this
year. Then Donato wasn't a real regular among the first nine
forwards. His role changed, particularly in the last month of the
season. There's a possibility that for his sake and our sake, we
should be talking to teams about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Donato finished seventh on the club in scoring with 16 goals and
39 points, his fewest since the lockout-shortened 1994-95 season.
What could make him tradeable is that he can play all three forward
positions and makes a reasonable salary of $962,500, about the
league average.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time I talked to him, he was unhappy in his role,''
said Sinden. ``I said to him then that it might change. I told him,
`If your role doesn't change between now and the end of the season,
then we'll see what's available.' I don't think there's a lot of
sense to have Ted play another year here with the same amount of
ice time as he got the last couple of months of last year. He's
been a useful player and he probably could still be. If nothing
happens, he could still help us, but he's a guy we'd probably be
talking to other teams about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins expect that Khristich, who played most of the season
with center Jason Allison and rookie Sergei Samsonov and finished
second on the club in scoring with 29 goals and 66 points, will
exercise his option to take the team to arbitration in an effort to
increase his salary, which was $1 million last season. There was
speculation that Khristich might be moved because his play was
affected at times by his distraction over his contract, which
clearly aggravated Burns. But Sinden said the Bruins would like to
keep Khristich, who turns 29 next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a little moody, he sulks around a little bit, but he's a
good hockey player,'' said Sinden. ``That line was a pretty
effective line. I was sure that if we gave him what we asked for,
he'd be a lot happier. But I would think he'd go to arbitration and
put his case in front of the arbitrator. I wouldn't put him high on
our list of a guy we were going to try to trade unless we got a
very unreasonable arbitration award. We'd probably live with the
arbitrator's award.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the future of goalie Jim Carey, who, unlike Donato and
Khristich, was left exposed for the expansion draft, Sinden said
the Bruins haven't decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expansion is coming up next year, too,'' said Sinden,
referring to when Atlanta enters the league for the 1999-2000
season. ``Although we can't plan too far ahead, the same situation
is going to be here next year as far as goalies go. If Byron Dafoe
and Robbie Tallas have good seasons, we don't want to expose them
again. There's a chance Jim Carey can come back and play like he
did for a few years there.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, we've got to make a decision because it's a
lot of money for a guy who doesn't play ($2.2 million). I guess our
decision will be, do we go and trust he'll come back to form or
that he'll be available to go into the draft next year or do we
throw good money after bad? I think he's a pretty good gamble.
You're not the best goalie in the NHL for nothing. He got an awful
lot very quickly. He went from a minor league goalie to the Vezina
Trophy winner and got a huge, huge contract for a guy who had one
year's success. It might have had an effect on him. Maybe he's over
that now.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the entry draft, in which the Bruins have no first-round
picks, two seconds, a third, fifth, sixth, and ninth, Sinden said
there could be a surprise or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a couple of things in mind that we're reasonably
excited about,'' he said. ``I think we've got a couple of sleepers
there.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he doesn't expect a great deal from the later rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 10 years, there have probably averaged 20-22 teams
in the league each of those years,'' he said. ``After the third
round, there have been six rounds. If there were 22 teams drafting
for six rounds, that's 132 players a year times 10 years, which is
1,320. If 20 of them made it, I'd be surprised.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
