<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES RECOVER EARLY LOSSES; DOLLAR GAINS ON YEN
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury prices pared early losses and ended little
changed Thursday, as the dollar gained in currency trading against
the yen. Prices were also weakened by dealers' hedging Freddie
Mac's $4 billion global bond offering Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But trading volume in the Treasury market was nearly half of the
average for a Thursday in the second quarter, so price movements
are exaggerated somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year bond edged up 2/32, to 106 24/32. The
bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the price,
slipped to 5.65 percent, from 5.66 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices came under pressure as underwriters led by Bear,
Stearns &AMP; Co., J.P. Morgan and Salomon Smith Barney, sold the
five-year Freddie Mac note issue at a price to yield 5.77 percent,
or about 26 basis points over the new five-year Treasury note sold
Wednesday. (A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point.)
</P>
<P>
   Also weighing on the market was the slightly stronger than
expected housing data, early weakness in the dollar against the
Japanese yen, a strong stock market that gave back a good chunk of
its gains during the day, supply and technical factors.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said shorter-maturity bills were in strong demand for
the most part as the 3-month bill rate dropped below 5 percent on a
variety of factors, including end-of-the-quarter demand.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices fell early in the session after the Commerce
Department said gross domestic product increased at a seasonally
adjusted 5.4 percent annual rate in the first quarter, much higher
than its estimate of 4.8 percent a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management,
said ``despite still-booming home sales, the somewhat surprising,
upward revised 5.4 percent GDP, statistic, while subject to further
change with next month's annual revisions, certainly demonstrated
the economy's torrid expansion during the first quarter was likely
to slow substantially, due mainly to an inventory overhang.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Furthermore,'' he said, ``economic activity seems to be
encountering some head winds at the onset of the third quarter in
the forms of sagging durable goods orders, the GM strike, and an
ever-widening trade deficit.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine said he expected that Federal Reserve policy makers would
keep monetary policy unchanged at its two-day meeting next week
because of benign inflation, a growing budget surplus, strong
dollar and continued turmoil in Asia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
