<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7382 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NY-YANKS-METS-900     06-25 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NY-YANKS-METS-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NEW YORK'S TEAMS, IT'S PLAY BALL! BUT WHAT'S THE COST? 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAN BARRY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the heavens cooperate Friday night, two teams will
gather on a swath of Queens County grass to demonstrate how the
game of baseball has particularly blessed New York City this year
with talent and character.
</P>
<P>
   An umpire will shout a familiar demand, a Mets pitcher will fire
a baseball to a Yankees batter, and all will be right in one corner
of an ever-churning metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   As they say from Queens Boulevard to the Bronx River Parkway:
Yeah, right. If you want ``Field of Dreams'' fantasies, buddy, go
chase flies in some sandlot.
</P>
<P>
   The current issues and historic emotions woven through this
weekend's three-game series at Shea Stadium go far beyond the
typical smell-the-cut-grass baseball blather. There are fortunes at
stake here, as well as a borough's identity.
</P>
<P>
   There are the dueling political futures of a mayor and a city
council speaker at risk. There are two owners who chuckle through
gritted teeth and say that no rivalry exists. And there are the
fans who want nothing more than the right to brag.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain teams where the players really hate each
other,'' said David Halberstam, the author, who has written
extensively about sports. ``But this is a rivalry built up by the
fans. It's about who rules New York. Who rules the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, whose fashion sense permits him on
occasion to wear a Yankee warmup jacket and cap, said that he does
not even bother pretending that he likes both teams equally.
</P>
<P>
   ``One, it would be dishonest,'' he said. ``Two, I wouldn't get
away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time that the Mets and the Yankees are
encouraging the rivalry by playing some of the best baseball in the
major leagues, they are also seeking public subsidies in the
hundreds of millions of dollars to finance new ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   This has residents of their host city pondering answers to a
couple of questions: At what price baseball? And can New York,
given the shifts in everything from the economics of the sport to
the demographics of the city, continue to support two teams?
</P>
<P>
   Both teams see new stadiums as essential to their survival. The
Mets want an old-style park to be built alongside Shea that would
bring back eye-watering memories of Brooklyn's Ebbets Field but
sport the futuristic touches of a retractable dome and a
removable-grass playing field. The Yankees want to abandon the
Bronx landmark of Yankee Stadium for a ballpark on the West Side of
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the majestic skyline looming behind center field, Yankee
types say, their eyes as wide as silver dollars. And if you can't,
imagine the Yankees in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The public debate over the two proposals has been closer to a
hollering match between competing beer vendors than a dispassionate
evaluation on merit.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, the city council, the city's teachers, self-styled
defenders of good government and a medley of political candidates
and gadflies have all waxed apoplectic on the subject. It's enough
to make the musings of former Gov. Mario Cuomo _ who also made a
cameo appearance in the debate _ seem touchingly quaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to see guys who chew and never smile,'' said Cuomo,
himself a former minor-league ballplayer. ``And when they take off
their hat they're bald _ and they don't care. I love the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all the Mets and the Yankees have provided more than
enough moments, from the bravura to the bizarre, to help explain
the sellout crowds for this year's series, the second since
baseball instituted interleague play last year _ when the American
League Yankees won two of three from the National League Mets. In
that, they also offer some hope that baseball just might be able to
transcend city politics.
</P>
<P>
   Take Orlando Hernandez, who fled Cuba on a sailboat the day
after Christmas, spent a few days on a deserted island before being
rescued, and is now pitching for the Yankees with a poise that
suggests he commutes in from upscale Scarsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Or Rick Reed, the Mets pitcher who was ostracized for crossing
the picket line during a strike in 1995, but whose pitching
excellence has won over his colleagues. Or that day in May when the
Mets pulled off an old-fashioned blockbuster trade, acquiring Mike
Piazza, the all-star catcher.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there is David Wells, the Yankees pitcher with
the longshoreman's physique who once nearly came to blows with the
team's owner, George Steinbrenner. Last month he pitched a perfect
game, winning one for big lugs everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But the whiff of politics, not pretzels, envelops New York
baseball this year, and Wells' rare feat could not enter posterity
unmarked. Giuliani immediately arranged to present Wells with the
key to the city.
</P>
<P>
   The one person specifically not invited to the City Hall event
was Peter Vallone, speaker of the City Council, candidate for
governor and stubborn proponent of the notion that the city's
voters ought to decide the fate of Yankee Stadium. Thus the snub
had nothing to do with the speaker's Queens roots, and everything
to do with stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration feels that it cannot risk calling
Steinbrenner's bluff when he says that Yankee Stadium is too old
and inconvenient for the team to remain financially competitive. A
beam that fell from the stadium's rafters earlier this year
provided punctuation to that point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner has once again invoked his often-broken vow of
silence on the matter. Howard Rubenstein, his spokesman, said
Steinbrenner is studying the matter and will announce in the fall
``where he wants the stadium to be: that's the West Side, the
Bronx, or New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophisticated enough to recognize Steinbrenner's broad hints
that the Bronx will no longer do, the mayor raised the possibility
_ the conclusion, his critics say _ of dropping a stadium onto a
railbed along a moribund stretch of Manhattan's West Side.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed using the revenues of a business tax to pay for
the city's share of new stadiums for both the Yankees and the Mets,
and talked about the economic boost that would follow. And he
shrugged off allegations of being a Steinbrenner sycophant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would react the same way to the Mets and the stock
exchange,'' Giuliani said this week. ``It's purely business. I
don't conceive it as my job as the mayor to lose valuable New York
institutions. My job as the mayor is to get the public
understanding what is at stake, so they don't let emotions get in
the way of things that would be good for the city five or ten years
from now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even so, baseball in New York was no longer just about hitting
and pitching.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican mayor's proposal angered Vallone, a Democrat who
also happens to be running for governor. The speaker quickly framed
the debate in populist terms: the rich owner benefiting at the
expense of the taxpayer; the struggling Bronx losing out to
glittering Manhattan; the arrogant mayor ignoring the will of the
people.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone proposed a referendum on a Manhattan stadium, Giuliani
vowed to block it _ and suddenly the cordial deliberations between
the mayor and the council over the city's surplus budget became a
sort of screaming match between dysfunctional family members over a
Thanksgiving meal.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, in a sense, led the City Council to adopt its own
budget, in unprecedented defiance of the mayor. Baseball, in a
sense, now could lead to cuts in city funding for nonprofit
agencies, as a result of the budgetary crossfire.
</P>
<P>
   A recent radio commercial, paid for by the City Council's
political committee, used the familiar sound of a bat hitting a
ball to support the message that Little League _ not the Yankees _
had become ``part of the budget battle, the Giuliani administration
vs. your City Council, and your children.''
</P>
<P>
   And the other night the council held a public forum called
``Take Me Out to the New Ballpark,'' at which the 30-odd audience
members applauded any criticism of Giuliani and Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools are falling apart! Plaster is falling on students, but
that doesn't seem to bother Mayor Giuliani,'' cried a teacher from
the Upper West Side. ``We need to build new schools.''
</P>
<P>
   All because of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo, who generally supports the West Side proposal, said that
earlier this year he had urged the Yankees to tread carefully into
the turbulent world of public opinion. He said he had suggested the
team take several months to research the West Side proposal, and
then develop a clear-cut plan to the city _ after the fall's
gubernatorial elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you need is consensus,'' he said. ``If you don't have it,
the politicians won't agree with it. And politicians do nothing
that the polls say you don't want done.''
</P>
<P>
   The former governor's voice trailed off in disgust. ``I'm so
aggravated by what's happening here,'' he said. ``This is the
classic prescribed device for arriving at the wrong conclusions:
Start by ignoring the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   While Steinbrenner finds himself trying to downplay this year's
spike in attendance at Yankee Stadium, the Mets organization
quietly awaits city approval for a plan that, when compared to the
Yankees' desires, comes off as just another capital project.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Wilpon, the team's co-owner, said that the new stadium
would have better views of the ballfields, better concessions, and
other amenities that would encourage fans to return more often.
</P>
<P>
   And Jay Horowitz, the team's spokesman, sees a distinct and
elemental link between the quality of the team's play and
attendance. The Mets drew 3 million people when it won the World
Series in 1986, a number they matched by making the playoffs in
1987; since then, mediocrity has led to a plummet in attendance, to
1.7 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really turned it around the last two years, and we're in
an upswing,'' he said. ``It's a cyclical thing: when you play well,
you draw, and when you don't play well, you don't draw.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, the Yankees-Mets game draws big. But Steinbrenner
will not be in attendance for any of the three games at Shea. Prior
commitments require his presence in Tampa. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
