<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth unfazed by AT&AMP;T's likely inroads with mega-deal
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- BellSouth is betting that it will take years for AT&AMP;T
to realize the benefits from its purchase of the nation's
second-largest cable television company.
</P>
<P>
   The $48 billion deal to buy Tele-Communications Inc. could give
the long-distance company a direct link to millions of homes, as
AT&AMP;T offers Internet, phone, video and data services to business,
as well as consumers. But by the time, AT&AMP;T _ and other rivals _
get to where they want to be, BellSouth hopes to be somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the things you are seeing confirm the strategic view
BellSouth has had for several years,'' said Earle Mauldin,
president of BellSouth Enterprises, the unit that includes wireless
service, international operations and publishing. ``We are at the
front of the pack and we intend to stay in front of the pack.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years after passage of the Telecommunications Act, there is
little competition in local service. But AT&AMP;T this week gave clear
notice of plans to join the fray _ along with WorldCom and perhaps
others. When that happens, BellSouth will be facing rivals that are
not only larger, but are likely to offer a potent range of
services.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, BellSouth is lagging in the marketing of high-speed
data lines to business, a market where it has already lost
customers, said analyst Jeff Sadler of Robinson-Humphrey. ``That is
really the missing strategy. To defend yourself, you are going to
need the full quiver and they don't have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, BellSouth has in recent years branched out from its core
business in local phones to provide wireless service and Internet
access, as well as wireless delivery of cable television in New
Orleans and Atlanta. BellSouth this summer plans a roll-out of
digital subscriber lines _ DSL _ a high-speed alternative to cable
company modems that runs over regular phone lines. But DSL cannot
be delivered to all homes. And wireless cable cannot reach anyone
whose transmitter reception is blocked. Meanwhile, BellSouth's
trials of interactive cable remain quiet and limited.
</P>
<P>
   No company can use one route to reach all customers, Mauldin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, BellSouth has ``a targeted but ambitious'' plan to
expand its fiber optic lines, and is considering a partnership with
a satellite company that could fill the gaps in BellSouth cable
offerings, Mauldin said. ``We are investing in a variety of
approaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts expect competitors to ``bundle'' services
together, luring customers with the convenience of one-stop
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   What BellSouth lacks most conspicuously for a full bundle is the
right to offer long-distance _ a privilege it hopes to win from
federal regulators this year. BellSouth will argue that AT&AMP;T's
promise to compete in local service is another reason to grant that
right.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
