<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI0626-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State lab tests will confirm disease source
 &HT;    By Diane Lore and M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Thirteen children _ nine from Georgia and four from
out-of-state _ have been confirmed as infected with E. coli as part
of an outbreak linked to a Cobb County water park, public health
officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But ``several'' other children may also be infected, according
to Joyce Goldberg, spokeswoman for the state Division of Public
Health. ``I don't want to talk any specific numbers because in some
cases the evidence has been very weak and in other cases it's been
very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the confirmed cases, two are from Tennessee, one is from
Arizona and one is from Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the 13 cases have been proven to have the same genetic
signature as the strain of E. coli O157:H7 that appears to have
been spread through a kiddie pool area at the White Water amusement
park two weeks ago, Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   It will take at least two weeks for public health workers to
confirm whether all the cases belong to the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Bacteria that have been cultured from the sick and identified as
O157:H7 will undergo a third level of analysis to see if they match
the genetic fingerprint of bacteria found in stool samples linked
to the White Water outbreak. Those tests will be performed at the
new DPH lab on Clairmont Road near Decatur and confirmed by back-up
tests at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``A child can have clinical disease consistent with E. coli
O157:H7, but it may not be E. coli, it may not be O157:H7, and it
may not be the strain associated with White Water at all,'' said
Mel Ralston, a CDC public health advisor working with the state.
``So it's important for us to know.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the state is leading the investigation and has not
formally asked the CDC for help. CDC has, however, alerted other
state health departments through an e-mail network of the local
cases and asked them to send bacteria they isolate from patients to
regional labs or the CDC for analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The agency hopes to use a new network, called PulseNet, that
allows electronic comparison of the genetic fingerprints of
different bacteria. Those results could provide the final
definition of how far the outbreak reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``PulseNet can connect by phone line what's a match and what is
not,'' said CDC spokesperson Barbara Reynolds. ``It also sends out
alarms when there is a match. With PulseNet, we can really define
an outbreak better.''
</P>
<P>
   That precision is necessary because the cases now being looked
at could be E.coli 0157:H7 but have no relation to White Water. For
instance, two hospitalized sisters, aged 2 and 6, who were among
the first children found to be infected, have been confirmed as
O157:H7 cases but also have been proven to have no connection to
the park.
</P>
<P>
   It may never be clear who is responsible for the infection. It
may not be any of the children who are now infected, but rather a
child whose illness had not been noticed by parents or who showed
no symptoms at all. It's also possible, though less likely, that a
teen or adult who took a toddler into the pool could have been the
first case that caused the outbreak, Ralston said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, more than 1,000 calls have been logged at the state's
E. coli hotline, although Goldberg said the volume dropped slightly
Thursday. ``Our folks were able to take a little bit of a
breather,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At White Water park, attendance was only about 2,300 by 1:30
Thursday, a hot day in mid-season at an attraction that averages
6,000 to 8,000 vistors a day, according to figures released by park
officials.
</P>
<P>
   But new rules implemented did not have a serious effect on
operations, said park spokeswoman Deedie Dowdle. The park announced
Wednesday it will turn away children under the age of 4 who come
with groups such as day care centers or summer camps, but no one
was turned away Thursday, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another new policy requires children under the age of 3 to wear
plastic pants in the pools, and park officials said Wednesday that
the pants will be given to youngsters who come to the park without
them at no charge. About 30 plastic pants were handed out Thursday,
said Dowdle, who said most of the families who come to the park
already have them for the children that need them.
</P>
<P>
   The number of calls from season ticket holders asking about
refunds on their tickets was up around 100, a park manager said
Thursday. Park officials said Wednesday they had received about
eight such calls, and expressed their belief that most season
ticket holders will remain patrons of the water park. Officials
declined to say whether any season ticket holder had received a
refund.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, pool owners _ concerned about the safety of their
private and community pools _ were buying chlorine in an effort to
keep the water clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had more people coming in wondering how to keep (E.
coli) down,'' said Jennifer Wood, chemistry and sales for JC Pool
Supplies Inc. in Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   Seven children with confirmed E. coli infections remained
Thursday at metro Atlanta hospitals, although it was still unclear
which of the cases were related to White Water.
</P>
<P>
   Four children were at Scottish Rite Children's Medical Center.
Two girls, ages 2 and 4, were in critical condition. Braves
shortstop Walt Weiss's son, Brody, 3, was in serious condition. A
5-year-old boy was in good condition. Scottish Rite staffers were
caring for a fifth child with suspected E. coli infection, but that
child's lab tests had not come back yet Thursday, said hospital
spokeswoman Staci Flaxer.
</P>
<P>
   At Egleston Children's Hospital, three children with E. coli
infections were in good condition Thursday evening. Two sisters,
ages 2 and 6, were not infected at White Water park. They were
admitted to the hospital June 6, five days before officials believe
a park pool was contaminated with E. coli-laden feces, said
hospital spokeswoman Debbie Osborne. The other Egleston patient, a
3-year-old boy, apparently was infected at the swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
