   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   AMISH _ NEW HOLLAND, Pa. _ Eli's grandfather reckons that the
Amish are like other folks. ``We believe the best environment for
the Plain People is the farm,'' he explained, standing in a
well-ordered woodshop near fertile fields that his family has
cultivated for six generations. ``So just like you will save and
bend over backwards to send your children to college, we will save
and bend over backwards to help our sons and daughters buy a
farm.'' The problem for Eli's grandfather _ who does not want to be
identified further because of church strictures _ and the 36,000
other Plain Sect disciples in picturesque Lancaster County is that
developers are encroaching on farmland they have tended since
William Penn welcomed their persecuted forebears nearly three
centuries ago. (Dart 1480&AMP;insert).
</P>
<P>
   MOVED Monday in (a) National category for release Saturday, June
27.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-2000 _ FAIRFAX, Va. _ Fears about problems when
computers hit the year 2000 are global, said delegates from 93
countries this week at the World Congress on Information
Technology. Participants raniging from the president of the NASDAQ
stock exchange to executives from Pakistan admitted that they
aren't sure if their countries' attempts to avoid Y2K bug started
soon enough. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving Thursday in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
for release Saturday, June 27.
</P>
<P>
   FEDBUD-SURPLUS _ WASHINGTON _ Some fiscal conservatives are
nostalgic for the bad old days of budget deficits.Their concern is
that the celebration over the budget surplus is relaxing the
pressure for spending cuts. Moreover, the numbers show that the
surplus is almost all in the Social Security trust fund, which is
being used to mask shortfalls elsewhere. Story will include a
bulleted list of the biggest longstanding problems with waste and
duplication of spending that are not being discussed in the current
round of budget talks. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   FEDBUD-DATA _ Graph material on the size of the deficit/surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Both moving for release Saturday, June 27.
</P>
<P>
   TELEPHONE-TAX _ WASHINGTON _ Most Americans will be paying more
for their telephone service as of July 1 as part of a Clinton
administration effort to link up schools and libraries to the
Internet. After weeks of controversy, the Federal Communication
Commission cut back the program. But some legal experts and members
of Congress are saying this so-called ``Gore tax'' is still
unconstitutional. Story will tell how much the typical household
will be paying, and where the money will go (including some
Cox-area school applications). (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Monday, June 29.
</P>
<P>
   SWEDISH-BBQ _ WASHINGTON _ Lyndon Olson, the U.S. ambasssador to
Sweden, will hold a traditional Texas BBQ in Stockholm to celebrate
the Fourth of July. The Waco businessman will treat 1,500 guests _
including the king and queen of Sweden _ to 750 pounds of brisket,
300 pounds of ribs, 200 pounds of sausage, 375 chickens and 2,000
pickled jalapeno peppers. All the food and an insulated iron BBQ
pit about the size of a small car will be shipped over from Texas.
(Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   To move Thursday for release Saturday, June 27.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-FAMILIES _ Families whose children have contracted E. coli
015:H7 say it is an experience like no other. Their children
hovered between life and death for weeks, and they felt as helpless
as their doctors, waiting to see if dialysis, respirators and other
medical technology would help their children's bodies fight back.
We're talking to some of the families and personalizing the
experience. (Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-DAYCARE _ Checking with day care centers to see if parents
are telling them: don't take our kids to the pool. Also talking
with health experts about what the biggest danger is: whether day
care workers are washing their hands after changing diapers. (Lee,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FLAFIRES _ For decades North Georgians have weathered the Fourth
of July heat in Florida to take the kids to the beach while school
is out and the textile mills are shut down for a week and the
Firecracker 500 is being held at Daytona. But there will be no
firecrackers this Fourth in bone-dry, wildfire-burned Florida, and
in some places smoke is drifting out across the beaches and
blinding motorists traveling the interstate. What can Georgians
expect when they head south in the next few days, and is the
tourist industry worried that travelers might stay home?
(MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GALOTTERY _ As it reaches its fifth birthday, the Georgia
lottery has broad political support, strong sales, good leadership
and favorable national press _ thanks mainly to the support its
provided to education in the state and to Georgia families with
kids in college. But despite its ever-increasing level of support
among scitizens (62 percent in 1992; 75 percent now), the fact
remains that people who should not play the lottery _ including
poor people and gambling addicts _ are drawn into it, and suffer as
a result. (Mantius, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH _ Another recess begins for Congress Monday, and once
again Newt Gingrich is taking to the road. But the itinerary of
this trip seems more geared to helping vulnerable GOP candidates
than to furthering presidential ambitions, perhaps reflecting that
the fall races are tighter than the Republicans had expected.
(Sherman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SIERRACLUB _ The Sierra Club, one of the nation's leading
environmental groups, conjures images of California's pristine
mountains. But the tax-exempt foundation also strikes fear in the
hearts of many incumbents around the country as one of the most
aggressively negative issue advertisers in elections. This year,
the Sierra Club is targeting 18-20 districts around the country,
from North Carolina to California. New ads begin airing June 29.
(Foskett, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GOP-ENVIRONMENT _ Tired of their bad image on the environment,
Republicans are hoping to turn around public perception with the
help of a new group that intends to mount issue ads in the fall
elections. (Sherman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   OZONEALERTS _ From Miami to Nashville, ozone alerts have been
more frequent this year, as the South appears headed for a bad air
summer. And with new, more stringent ozone rules now being enforced
by the EPA, a number of metro areas in the Southeast could face the
same sort of restrictions on highway construction and smoke-stack
industries that Atlanta has felt for several years. But EPA also
has a plan to fight ozone in the South and the target is dirty
coal-fired power plants. (Harmon, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ALAVOTE _ Preview of Tuesday's runoff election between Fob James
and Winton Blount. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   LIGHTHOUSE _ CAPE HATTERAS, N. C. - Controversy is swirling
around the nation's tallest sentinel of the shore like the seas
beneath it in a nor'easter. The combatants all agree that something
must be done to save the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse from collapsing
on the beach where encroaching waves lap precariously close to its
brick and mortar base. It's the method of its salvation that has
tempers roiling. One side says the historic spiral-striped beacon
should be moved back from the advancing ocean. The other side says
leave it where it belongs and beat back the seas. (Finger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
