<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TOWN PUTS OUT UNWELCOME MAT FOR KKK, NEW BLACK PANTHERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ga.) 
(Eds.: kontinue in KKK internet quote is cq) 
(See optional ending) 
 
By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ They call their town the ``Jewel of the
Forest,'' and Chamber of Commerce officials usually are eager to
lure visitors. City leaders tout the fat bass in area lakes, the
beauty of the local forests and the quaint bed-and-breakfasts.
</P>
<P>
   But this weekend, locals are sending out a different message:
``Stay away.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the 8,000 townsfolk are putting out the unwelcome
mat for several Ku Klux Klan, New Black Panther and Muslim groups
that are planning to converge on the east Texas town Saturday to
rally on the tree-shaded lawn in front of Jasper's picturesque
109-year-old courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they cure all the problems in Dallas and it's safe for me
to walk the streets of Dallas, then they can come down here and
tell me what to do about Jasper,'' said George Miller, the
administrator of Jasper Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who is black, made that comment about the New Black
Panthers of Dallas. But he had the same sentiments for Klan groups
from the Texas cities of Vidor and Waco, and as far away as Georgia
who have announced plans to be in Jasper on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   KKK members say they're coming to express condemnation for the
June 7 murder of a 49-year-old black man, allegedly at the hands of
three white men who are accused of dragging him behind a pickup for
almost three miles along back country roads.
</P>
<P>
   Black militant groups say they'll be in Jasper to protest the
KKK and to protect local blacks from Klan members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect their right to congregate,'' said Muslim leader
Quanell X of Houston. ``But if they step out of line with one black
person, we'll be there to put them in check.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he will bring a group of black Muslims from Houston. A
group from the New Black Panther Party of Dallas announced it will
be on hand as well. The protesters, Quanell X said, will be armed
``with legal firearms,'' and plan to come into town ``right along
side the Ku Klux Klan.''
</P>
<P>
   A KKK spokesman said that while the Klan groups don't plan to
make a display of weapons, ``I am sure some members will have legal
firearms with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that, several hundred lawmen _ from local officers and
those from neighboring cities and counties to FBI agents, Texas
Rangers and state troopers _ will be on duty. One local businessman
said police informed downtown merchants that the streets around the
main square will be cordoned off.
</P>
<P>
   Officials aren't talking about their preparations publicly. But
about 200 officers were in Jasper, a city with a police force of
about 14 officers, two weeks ago when armed Black Panthers from
Dallas marched after the funeral of murder victim James Byrd Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be at least that many here Saturday,'' said Jasper
County District Attorney Guy James Gray.
</P>
<P>
   The real reason the Klan and militant groups are coming to
Jasper, said Sheriff Billy Rowles, is to get in front of all the
news cameras that have been in Jasper since Byrd's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you all would just go away,'' Rowles told members of the
news media this week, ``they would stay away. Jasper needs to have
time to heal.''
</P>
<P>
   That message was repeated throughout the community, about 140
miles northeast of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they think at least two of the men charged
with Byrd's killing may have ties to the Aryan Brotherhood, a
prison-based white supremacist group, or to Klan groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jewish-controlled liberal press has attempted to assign
blame and responsibility to the Ku Klux Klan and/or another Aryan
organization,'' the Vidor-based Knights of the White Kamellia said
on its Internet homepage. ``The truth is, neither the Klan nor any
other white organization would have anything to gain by such a
senseless act of unnecessary violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lowe, leader of a Klan faction based in Waco, said that
while the Klan condemns Byrd's murder, some question whether it was
a hate crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Byrd was an ex-felon,'' Lowe said. ``It might be a drug
deal gone wrong, not just a hate crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have said they see no indication that Byrd's death
involved drugs. Officials have characterized it as a random hate
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jasper's leaders, both white and black, said they
hope there is nobody around the county square Saturday to hear the
Klan and black militants except each other, law officers and the
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're encouraging everybody to stay away,'' said the Rev.
Bobby Hudson, an African-American pastor of Goodwill Baptist
Church. ``You've got to have somebody there to argue with, and we
don't want to give them anybody to argue with.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Billy Mahathay, proprietor of Billy's Old Fashion  &UR;  &LR; Barbecue,
agreed. ``I think that the Black Panthers and the Klan both need to
stay where they come from,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't raised like that,'' he added, looking at
photographs of he and his black sister and brother playing with
white friends as children. ``Jasper just isn't like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Snelson, past president of the Jasper Chamber of Commerce,
called Byrd's murder ``a cruel and savage atrocity committed by
misfits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We view this tragic incident as the difference between good
and evil, between right and wrong,'' he said. ``Not between white
and black.''
</P>
<P>
   Most citizens and public officials said they know of no
organized Klan groups in their county, but the Knights of the White
Kamellia Internet page claims otherwise. ``We have had a Klavern in
Jasper County since 1996 and will kontinue be active there,'' it
said.
</P>
<P>
   If so, most residents apparently find the group, which calls
itself part of the ``Invisible Empire,'' just that _ invisible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived here all my life,'' said Edith Lewis, 49, who is
white, ``and I've never seen the Klan. I saw the Black Panthers for
the first time the other day. I was not impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
