<SLUG> BC-COURT-FOSTERE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT REJECTS STARR EFFORT TO OBTAIN FOSTER-RELATED NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Supreme Court Thursday rebuffed Independent Counsel Kenneth
W. Starr's effort to obtain notes taken by a lawyer for a
now-deceased White House aide, ruling that conversations between
attorneys and their clients should be protected beyond the grave.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 decision, which was watched closely by the Clinton
administration and the legal community, overturned an appeals court
decision that sided with Starr. The high court said Starr's
argument was not persuasive enough to justify narrowing the
nation's oldest legal privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Starr wanted the court to force James Hamilton, the attorney for
Deputy White House Counsel Vincent W. Foster, to turn over three
pages of notes he took in 1993, nine days before Foster committed
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the majority in the first federal test of posthumous
attorney-client privilege, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist said,
``It has been generally, if not universally, accepted for well over
a century, that the attorney-client privilege survives the death of
the client in a case such as this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton hailed the ruling as as ``victory for the legal
profession. This case in importance transcended the facts of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr, in a written statement, said, ``Although we are
disappointed in the outcome of the Supreme Court's decision, we
understand and respect the care and expedition with which the Court
resolved the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr added, ``The issue has obviously proved to be of
considerable difficulty, as the divided opinions of the Supreme
Court and the Court of Appeals reveal. In all events, we continue
to pursue our investigations as thoroughly and expeditiously as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials are trying to sort out the ruling's
implications on Starr's effort to require Clinton confidant Bruce
Lindsey to testify about his conversations with the president in
the early days of the Monica Lewinsky investigation. The White
House has argued attorney-client privilege in that case, which is
currently moving through the appeals courts.
</P>
<P>
   One administration official called Thursday's ruling a
``setback'' for Starr. A White House official traveling with
President Clinton in China called it ``an important validation of
the vital issue of attorney-client privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr was seeking Hamilton's notes to help determine whether
Clinton aides commited perjury, obstructed justice or committed
other crimes in connection with Hillary Rodham Clinton's role in
the 1993 dismissal of employees from the White House travel office.
</P>
<P>
   She has said she had no role in the firings, but a draft memo by
a former White House aide given to Whitewater investigators in 1996
portrays her as being behind the dismissals. The memo also says
that Foster spoke to Hillary Clinton about the travel office issue.
</P>
<P>
   Starr subpoeaned Hamilton in December 1995 for the handwritten
notes he took during a two-hour meeting with Foster on July 11,
1993. Foster had come to him for legal represenation over the
dismissals in the travel office. Nine days later Foster was found
dead of a self-inflicted gunshot wound in a park in suburban
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton resisted the subpoena, and the appeals court later
ruled that the attorney-client privilege of confidentiality should
be waived when the information is important to a criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court said there was no case law holding that
the privilege applies differently in criminal and civil cases, and
that a client may not know when disclosing information to an
attorney whether it will later be relevant to a civil or criminal
matter.
</P>
<P>
   The case grabbed the attention of the legal community, with the
American Bar Association, National Association of Criminal Defense
Lawyers, American Corporate Counsel Association and National
Hospice Organization, all arguing that the legal privilege should
extend after a client's death. Ending that long-established rule
would be chilling to a lawyer's relationship with a client.
</P>
<P>
   While Rehnquist said Starr's arguments against the posthumous
privilege were not ``frivolous,'' he said Starr simply had not
satisified his burden of showing that ``reason and experience''
require the rule to be broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing that communications will remain confidential even
after death serves a weighty interest in encouraging a client to
communicate fully and frankly with counsel; posthumous disclosure
of such communications may be as feared as disclosure during the
client's lifetime,'' the court said.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist was joined by Justices John Paul Stevens, Anthony M.
Kennedy, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G.
Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Those dissenting were Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin
Scalia and Clarence Thomas. In the dissent, O'Connor wrote: ``In my
view, a criminal defendant's right to exculpatory evidence or a
compelling law enforcement need for information may, where the
testimony is not avaialble from other sources, overrride a client's
posthumous interest in confidentiality.''
</P>
<P>
   John Q. Barrett, a criminal law professor at St. John's
University School of Law and former associate counsel to the
Iran-Contra special prosecutor, Lawrence E. Walsh, said if the
ruling had gone the other way, the case would have minimal impact,
despite rhetoric about the horrors that would result from narrowing
attorney-client privilege. ``There just aren't many prosecutors who
happen to need something that happens to be in the hands of a
lawyer whose client has died,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the decision will likely end efforts to seek
long-sealed papers in the 106-year-old case of Lizzie Borden, who
was prosecuted but acquitted of the hatchet murders of her parents.
The notes of Borden's defense lawyer, George Robinson, are locked
in the offices of the Springfield, Mass., law firm he founded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
