<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7396 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-CLINTON-ART-840     06-25 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CLINTON-ART-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ARRIVES IN CHINA; DEFENDS POLICY OF ENGAGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-SCENE, CHINA-DISSIDENTS, CHINA-PEONY,
CHINA-GINGRICH) 
(ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   XIAN, China _ With the pageantry of thundering drums and
clanging gongs, President Clinton was welcomed to China on Thursday
night, the first American president to visit this country in nearly
a decade, and he mildly rebuked critics in Washington who have
attacked his policy of engagement with the Beijing government.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be those here and back in America who wonder whether
closer ties and deeper friendship between America and China are
good,'' the president said, speaking as much to his audience at
home as to the throngs of Chinese who poured into the streets of
Xian on Thursday to give Clinton a tumultuous welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the answer is yes,'' the president said. ``We can
learn much from each other. And as two great nations, we have a
special responsibility to the future of the world. The steps we
take over the next week can lead to far greater strides for our
people in the years ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-minute ceremony was a made-for-TV spectacle, replete with
warriors in Tang dynasty costumes, a score of maidens in flowing
white gowns bearing baskets of flowers and yellow-robed riders
astride strutting horses. Red paper lanterns hung from the
lampposts, and bright silk banners bearing images of mythical birds
of good fortune flapped in the breeze on a mild smoggy night.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds of factory workers, students, bankers and public
officials began vying for position at 9 a.m. on the sidewalks
around the square before the old city's South Gate, where the
president gave a short speech nearly 12 hours later. By evening,
the crowd extended for two miles down South Avenue out of the
square.
</P>
<P>
   Still two days away from the formal part of his trip, a one-day
summit conference with President Jiang Zemin in Beijing, Clinton
did not dwell here on any of the major, substantive differences
between China and the United States. Instead, he offered brief,
general remarks that stressed the positive aspects of the way the
Chinese-American relationship has developed since 1989, the year in
which President George Bush visited China and the Chinese
government used military force to crush pro-democracy protests in
Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his diplomatically indirect reference to the
political climate in the United States about China, recently
inflamed on Capitol Hill over questions about illegal campaign
contributions and the spread of nuclear weapons, Clinton offered a
gentle reminder of the gulf between the two countries on matters of
human rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Respect for the worth, the dignity, the potential and the
freedom of every citizen is a vital source of America's strength
and success,'' the president said as People's Liberation Army
searchlights played in the sky above him. ``In this global
information age, where both economic growth and individual
opportunity are based on ideas, a commitment to providing all human
beings the opportunity to develop their full potential is vital to
the strength and success of the new China, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, U.S. officials complained to the Chinese government
on Thursday over reports that several dissidents had been detained
and others harassed in connection with President Clinton's state
visit.
</P>
<P>
   But in Xian, which the White House chose for the first stop
specifically because it is a city without strong political
symbolism in modern times, the focus was on ceremony and on the
city's undeniably enthusiastic welcome for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The president and Hillary Rodham Clinton, showing the effects of
their 18-hour, 10,000-mile journey from Washington, made their way
down 150 yards of red carpet to the base of Xian's floodlit South
Gate, part of the fortifications that once guarded the city,
China's imperial capital for more than 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Xian's mayor, Fang Xichu, officially welcomed ``your excellency
Mr. President and Mrs. President,'' and presented Clinton with a
key to the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it a delight when friends visit from afar?'' Fang said,
quoting Confucius.
</P>
<P>
   The South Gate, also known as the Gate of Eternal Tranquillity,
was built in 1317, 400 years after the end of the Tang dynasty, a
period many Chinese regard as a high point in their civilization.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd in the large square facing the gate numbered only a
few hundred, limited by security concerns. But thick throngs lined
the route of Clinton's 50-car motorcade into the city from the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was a moment to be savored for many in the crowd, a
break from the routine and a sign of China's growing acceptance as
a weighty world player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived here more than 20 years and I've never seen as many
people gathered for anything before,'' said Chang Yingxiao, a
division chief in the Xian health bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Chen Tong, a 13-year-old boy came to the parade route to see
Clinton's car, and, perhaps, catch a glimpse of the president
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very much like President Clinton, I even worship him,'' he
said. Asked if he held any other Americans in such reverence, the
boy answered, ``George Washington and Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Controversy has raged in the United States over Clinton's
nine-day, five-city trip to China. Nearly a third of the members of
Congress had urged Clinton to delay the trip until charges of
illegal Chinese contributions to the 1996 Democratic campaign and
the transfer of missile technology to China had been resolved. Many
human rights advocates object to his rewarding the Chinese
government with a state visit while thousands of political
dissidents remain jailed.
</P>
<P>
   But The president's aides aides have hoped to use the trip to
project an image back to the United States of a prospering,
striving China that poses new challenges for economic competition,
not nuclear or ideological confrontation, and Clinton struck that
tone from the first moments of his visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, in this city famous for calligraphy, a new chapter in
China's story is being written,'' he said. ``We Americans admire
your accomplishments, your economy, your hard work, creativity and
vision, your efforts against hunger and poverty, your work with us
on peace and stability in Korea and South Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I believe both Chinese and Americans aspire to many
of the same things: to provide for our families, to teach our
children, to build our communities, to protect our Earth, to shape
our own futures and pass brighter possibilities on to our
children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
