<SLUG> BC-CHINA-BAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELITE MILITARY BAND TO PLAY FOR THE CLINTONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-SCENE, CHINA-CLINTON, CHINA-DISSIDENTS,
CHINA-PEONY, CHINA-GINGRICH) 
(ja) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Foreign presidents may come and go, Communist Party
leaders may rise and fall, but one thing has remained the same
throughout decades of state visits to Beijing: the People's
Liberation Army Military Band.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, on the plaza of a Defense Ministry compound
in west Beijing, the elite, 60-member brass band rehearsed snappy
renditions of ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' and the Chinese national
anthem, ``March of the Volunteers,'' which it will play on Saturday
at the official greeting for President Clinton in front of the
Great Hall of the People on Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   The band greets every visiting head of state, and also performs
at every state dinner as well as at various public affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was founded at the instruction of Mao Tse-tung in 1952,
the band has performed 48,000 times at important national and
international events, said Col. Fan Siting, who will conduct the
band for the Clinton festivities.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday, Cheng Yiming, Fan's predecessor,
reminisced about the first state visit by an American president,
that of Richard Nixon in 1972, which Cheng remembers with great
pride and clarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We chose the songs very carefully,'' said Cheng, now retired.
</P>
<P>
   For the welcoming dinner, the band made sure to play ``Home on
the Range,'' he said. ``This was recommended by the Foreign
Ministry, which told us this was a popular song in Nixon's hometown
and had been performed at his inauguration.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other American songs, in between Chinese favorites, was
``America the Beautiful,'' Cheng said. Later, after dinner and
toasts, Prime Minister Chou En-lai asked the band to play ``Home on
the Range'' again.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon thanked the band and said it was the best performance he
had ever heard, Cheng recalled. Nixon handed out a glass-encased
name card to everyone as a gift, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the most recent visit by an American president, that of
George Bush in early 1989, the band added ``Yellow Rose of Texas''
and ``Shenandoah'' to the evening repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what songs the band might play for Clinton and his wife,
Hillary Rodham Clinton, at dinner in the Great Hall of the People
on Saturday, the 12 officers assembled for the interview fidgeted,
as if worried about revealing secret information.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, one said: ``We don't know yet. The songs are chosen by
the protocol department of the Foreign Ministry, and they haven't
decided yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The band is ready to play many different American songs, the
officers said, but most are old standbys. ``There are not enough
cultural exchanges, and we expect the Americans to teach us some of
the newer popular songs,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   Though it is much less true today, a couple of decades ago the
People's Liberation Army band was one of the few paths available to
young aspiring musicians, providing quite a respectable career. To
join, those who pass a qualifying test must first spend three years
training in an army arts institute. Once in the band, musicians
usually spend their entire careers there.
</P>
<P>
   Now even this stodgy institution in the most stodgy of
ministries is trying to branch out. Several players formed a jazz
band, which played at a jazz festival here earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   A leading saxophonist from the band, who wants to become better
known and perhaps land side jobs playing at private parties,
recently rented out the Beijing Music Hall, the local equivalent of
Carnegie Hall, to put on a concert. He generated advance notices in
the press and, with the help of no little free ticket distribution,
played to a full house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
