<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-DENTIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULING BOLSTERS RIGHTS OF AIDS-INFECTED PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In its first AIDS-related ruling, the Supreme Court
Thursday found that a Maine woman infected with the virus that
causes AIDS is protected from discrimination under the Americans
with Disability Act.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-4 ruling sends the case back to a lower court to
reconsider whether a Bangor dentist, Randon Bragdon, violated the
anti-discrimination law by refusing to fill a cavity in Sidney
Abbott's tooth in his office because she was HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``HIV infection, even in the so-called asymptomatic phase, is an
impairment which substantially limits the major life activity of
reproduction'' and therefore qualifies for coverage under the
disability law, wrote Justice Anthony M. Kennedy for the majority.
He said a health-care professional could not assess the risk of
infection unless it was based on objective and scientific
information.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott, now 37, who works with developmentally disabled adults
in Bangor, said at a Boston news conference that she was
``gratified'' by the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to take legal action against Dr. Bragdon because
what he did was wrong,'' she said. ``And if Dr. Bragdon refused to
treat me just because I am HIV positive, I knew he would do it to
others.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a truly historic day for public health,'' said Dr.
Howard Koh, a member of the Massachusetts Commission Against
Discrimination. ``This decision upholds a cornerstone of public
health, that everyone has a right to basic health care without
being discriminated against.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragdon, a Tufts-educated dentist and lifelong Bangor resident,
said he had a ``mixed'' reaction. He and his lawyer, John McCarthy
of Bangor, said they were pleased Bragdon would have a chance to
argue that he should be allowed to rely upon his professional
judgment in deciding how to treat his patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about not treating,'' Bragdon said in a phone
interview. ``It's about being able to treat prudently. ...If we
really get to court and have a real trial, the science is on our
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Because AIDS is a fatal illness, Bragdon said health care
professionals should take special precautions in treating patients
who carry the virus. The ``universal precautions'' recommended to
dentists _ wearing a mask, gloves and protective glasses _ were not
foolproof, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Bragdon had offered to work on Abbott's tooth in
a hospital instead of his dental office and said she would have to
pay the additional cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an affirmation of Congress' intent to make sure that
people with all kinds of serious illness need protection from
discrimination regardless of how far the disease has progressed or
how they appear to people,'' said Bennett H. Klein, a co-counsel
for Abbott and a lawyer with the Gay and Lesbian Advocates and
Defenders, based in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Nan Feyler, an expert on AIDS and law at the University of
Pennsylvania Law School, said the decision set a new standard for
people with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole purpose of discrimination law is not to allow fear
to dictate,'' she said. ``Otherwise, people don't want to sit next
to blacks, don't want to eat food served by Hispanics, and don't
want medical exams done by women. No matter how sincere, fear
cannot be allowed to deny a service.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in a statement released by the White House,
said, ``This decision reinforces the protections offered by the
landmark Americans with Disabilities Act for Americans living with
HIV and AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   Public health officials estimate that more than 1 million
Americans are infected with the virus. Many now live for years
without symptoms and avoid development of AIDS because of advances
in medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The court found that Abbott, who has been HIV positive since
1986, qualified as disabled because the virus prevents her from
having children, because the likelihood of passing the virus to the
fetus and a sexual partner was so high that it effectively kept her
from reproducing or engaging in sexual intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, in his decision, said the dentist ``failed to present
any objective, medical evidence showing that treating respondent in
a hospital would be safer or more efficient in preventing HIV
transmission than treatment in a well-equipped dental office.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Kennedy in the majority opinion were Justices John Paul
Stevens, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg, and Stephen G.
Breyer. Dissenting were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Antonin Scalia, Clarence Thomas, and, in part, Sandra Day
O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist, writing for the minority, questioned whether
reproduction was a ``major life activity.'' The federal disability
law defines disability as an impairment that limits a major life
activity. ``There is absolutely no evidence that absent the HIV,
respondent would have had or was even considering having
children,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Bragdon vs. Abbott, 97-156.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe correspondent Daniel A. Grech contributed to this report
from Boston.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
