<SLUG> BC-GLENN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GLENN SWEATS IT OUT AS ASTRONAUTS GO THROUGH FLIGHT SIMULATION
</HEADLINE>
     &HT;     By SCOTT MONTGOMERY 
 &HT;     c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In the cramped metal compartments of the space shuttle
trainer, Ohio Sen. John Glenn and crew broke a heavy sweat Thursday
while they hurried through a simulation of the first hectic moments
in orbit.
</P>
<P>
   During the nearly four-hour training session, the seven-member
crew was clocked going through the laborious process of converting
the shuttle's two flight decks into laboratories by removing the
folding seats and storing their bulky pressurized launch suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was work. I was sweating,'' Glenn said afterward. ``My
underwear was soaked.''
</P>
<P>
   The crew wears blue thermal underwear beneath the orange launch
suits, and as part of the drill each member had to extricate
himself from the outer shell, emerging through a thick zipper along
the spine like larvae, before stowing the 100 pounds of gear. The
heavy suits only are used during launch and re-entry.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning less than 10 minutes after launch, the three crew
members on the mid-deck _ including Glenn _ will begin the
conversion process that must be completed within two and a half
hours so orbit experiments can be started on time.
</P>
<P>
   Computers must be set up, hatches must be opened, and launch
equipment must be stored so it can be retrieved easily for the trip
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big task for the first day,'' Flight Commander Curt
Brown said, ``and you don't want to get behind.''
</P>
<P>
   With the late October launch just four months away, the shuttle
Discovery's crew has moved into the meat of its crew coordination
training. Since the crew was named in February, most of the
training up to now has been individual work that involved either
learning shuttle equipment or learning about the experiments to be
conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the flight has more than 80 experiments scheduled. So
many, in fact, they're considering whether to they can keep them
all. ``We may have a little more than we can do in a nine-day
mission, realistically. So we may have to cut that down a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Two studies that won't be touched are those central to Glenn's
involvement in the space flight. At 77, Glenn will be the oldest
person ever in space and will be a prime subject of scientific
experiments on the erosion of muscle strength and the loss of sleep
associated with extended weightlessness.
</P>
<P>
   Both problems also plague elderly people on earth, and NASA
researchers hope that by sending a man of Glenn's age they will get
some hints about what triggers these physical changes. Several
other changes, including weakening of immune systems, also run
parallel between astronauts and the aged and could be subjects of
future study.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn was buoyant and smiling as the training wrapped up, even
as he and the crew, with the thin blue underwear pasted to their
bodies with sweat, ducked past a row of cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a good drill up there,'' Glenn said. ``Physically? I
feel great. Had a good sweat, I got a good workout.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's wife Annie also attended the session, as she has through
much of the training. After enduring the pioneering uncertainty of
Glenn's first space flight in 1962 she said her husband's role in
today's space program is easier to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, that he'll be 77 on launch day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He keeps me going,'' she laughed. ``He keeps me alert.''
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Montgomery is the Washington correspondent for the Dayton
Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For use by clients of The New York Times News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
