<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7411 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-AFLCIO-ENDORSE-BOS     06-25 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-AFLCIO-ENDORSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION GROUP BACKS HARSHBARGER FOR BAY STATE GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS AND JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Setting aside their reservations over his labor
credentials, the state's largest union organization Thursday gave
Attorney General Scott Harshbarger a major victory in his bid for
the Democratic gubernatorial nomination when they voted to endorse
him over his two opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger, who needed a two-thirds majority of the AFL-CIO
excutive council, won the union backing when 40 of the 56 union
leaders from around Massachusetts gathered behind closed doors to
consider which state-wide candidates to back.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger's victory came after strong lobbying from the
AFL-CIO's top officers, who are convinced he is the only Democratic
candidate who has the resources and organization to unseat Acting
Governor Paul Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tremendous boost to my campaign,'' Harshbarger said
after the union vote that further consolidates his position as the
Democrat's leading contender in the Sept. 15 primary. ``This is
part of the slow and steady road to getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, state labor leaders have been cool to
Harshbarger, particlarly since he beat one of their strongest
allies, former Attorney General James Shannon in 1990. The union
officials feel Harshbarger only recently reached out to them as he
runs for governor. They also are angry over what they feel is his
office's failure to enforce wage laws.
</P>
<P>
   But labor sources said the AFL-CIO leaders' strong argument to
some reluctant council members was that Harshbarger is a far
stronger candidate than his two rivals, former state Senator
Patricia McGovern and former US Representative Brian Donnelly, both
of whom trail far behind Harshbarger in the polls and in
fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Haynes, the AFL-CIO's secretary/treasurer, who lobbied
heavily for the 400,000 member labor group to back Harshbarger,
praised him as a ``strong and solid voice for working people with
the strength and conviction to beat the Republican Party in
November.''
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger's victory Thursday is a blow to his two rivals'
efforts to derail his increasingly strong, front-running status.
McGovern, the former Senate Ways and Means chairperson who angered
unions with her budget cuts during the state fiscal crises in the
late 1980's, had little support at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Donnelly, who had a strong labor record in Congress, had worked
with his supporters on the council to keep Harshbarger from getting
the necessary two thirds to win the endorsement, but failed in the
face of the union leadership's lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   ``This breaks the backbone of his opponents and eliminates the
rational of his opponents,'' said Lou DiNatale, a Democratic
political analyst. ``The political community has consistently
underestimated Harshbarger's ability to put together all the key
elements in a Democratic primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, both Donnelly and McGovern swore Thursday to continue to
seek the support of union members and locals, despite the vote for
Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won the first battle of the union leaders and we intend to
win the next of the union members,'' Donnelly said, touting his
20-year record of support for workers. ``This is far, far, far from
over.''
</P>
<P>
   McGovern also said she would take her case to the rank-and-file
union members around the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working men and women of Massachusetts deserve more than
slogans, they need a governor who can bring people together and
solve some of their problems,'' McGovern said. ``I'm confident that
a number of individual unions will be supportive and endorse me.''
</P>
<P>
   Haynes said he respected both Donnelly and McGovern, but said
Harshbager has embraced a strong union position and has
demonstrated this year and in past campaigns that he is a
formidable candidate.
</P>
<P>
   `Harshbarger's probably the most powerful campaigner in the
state,'' Haynes said. ``This guy is running an old-time grass roots
campaign and it is pretty impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO endorsement is the second major victory for
Harshbarger this month. On June 6 at the state Democratic Party
convention, he won a first ballot victory over McGovern and
Donnelly for the party's official endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO endorsement is also important because it provides
Harshbarger with the organization and campaign workers that played
key roles in recent Democratic victories. Haynes said the union
wanted to get behind a candidate now and not wait until after the
election in order to have enough time to pull together an effective
union campaign for the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Labor's energized efforts to bolster US Senator Edward Kennedy,
who was facing a serious Republican challenger in 1994, and its
strong backing of US Senator John Kerry in 1996 in his tough battle
with William F. Weld were seen as key elements in their victories.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger said the union backing will be key to any success in
the general election. He said he expected that the AFL-CIO's
endorsement was causing concern for Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul Cellucci would have been the happiest man sitting there
today if the AFL-CIO hadn't made an endorsement,'' he said. ``He's
got to be very seriously worried that the AFL-CIO has endorsed a
person who can unseat him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
