<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7413 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPACE-STATION-HNS &LR;      06-25 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-STATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL URGES FINANCIAL RESCUE PLAN FOR SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Concerned that Russia's worsening economy has
jeopardized that nation's key role in the U.S.-led international
space station, NASA's House oversight committee has asked the
Clinton administration to forge a financial rescue strategy within
30 days.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan request was included in a strongly worded letter
to President Clinton, signed by House Science Committee Chairman
James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., and Rep. George Brown of California,
the panel's ranking Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The International Space Station program is in trouble,'' they
warned. ``We face a situation in which there can be little
confidence that the Russian government will make adequate funding
available to meet its commitments ...''
</P>
<P>
   The committee's request followed a hearing on the station where
NASA administrator Dan Goldin acknowledged a mounting cost problem,
but said he was not prepared to propose a solution with a price tag
until the year 2000 federal budget is presented to Congress next
February.
</P>
<P>
   A recent agency-sought reappraisal, though, estimates U.S. costs
have escalated from $17.3 billion to nearly $25 billion since 1993,
the year Russia joined the project.
</P>
<P>
   Though invited, neither White House science policy nor budget
office representatives appeared before the committee. The White
House would not comment on the letter Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   However, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
remained steadfast in its plans to begin the orbital assembly of
the new station with the Nov. 20 launching of the first
U.S.-financed, Russian-built component from Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we are comfortable we can still go ahead with the
assembly,'' said Gretchen McClain, NASA's Washington-based
technical director for the program.
</P>
<P>
   The first of 33 U.S. shuttle assembly missions is tentatively
scheduled for a Dec. 3 liftoff. All told, about 90 launches will be
required to assemble and sustain the growing complex over at least
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, representatives from the United States,
Russia, Europe, Japan and Canada approved the third delay in the
start of assembly plans. It accommodated the latest in a series of
financially driven postponements in the construction of the
station's Russian service module, the first habitable component,
now scheduled for a late April liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   Space agency officials said Thursday that Russia's financial
difficulties now appear to pose the greatest threat to the
production of Progress and Soyuz capsules for the launch of fuel
and human crews to the station. Earlier U.S. concerns over Russian
finances were focused on the service module, which is nearly
assembled.
</P>
<P>
   Regular Progress fuel missions will be required after the
service module arrives in orbit to keep the massive station
circling at safe altitudes.
</P>
<P>
   The latest concerns over Russia's role arose in the spring when
new economic turmoil surfaced. Already in arrears to its station
program, the difficulties forced the Russian government to cut its
space budget.
</P>
<P>
   Its pledge of $340 million to the Russian Space Agency for
station work, much of it to come from unconventional financing
schemes, was cut to the U.S. equivalent of $160 million.
</P>
<P>
   The lesser amount was calculated to assure the launching of the
first component in November and the service module next year as
well as the earliest parts that will be necessary to make the
Progress capsules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardware they have in place we think, right now, can get
us through 1999,'' McClain said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
