<SLUG> BC-COCOLA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola case sales in line with outlook
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Coca-Cola said its second-quarter case sales are on
target to surge 9 to 10 percent worldwide, as analysts had
projected.
</P>
<P>
   But what caught some by surprise at the company's bi-annual
investment conference, held at Coca-Cola's headquarters on North
Avenue, was its expectation for a 7 to 8 percent rise in case sales
in its Middle and Far East division. That's where several countries
have been mired in a sharp economic downturn since last year.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the estimate is lower than the division's 11 percent
average volume increase over the last five years, Douglas N. Daft
told analysts and money managers. But it's equal to the 7 to 8
percent increase in case sales the company expects for North
America and ``would indicate that we are managing our business
through this current economic crisis,'' Daft said.
</P>
<P>
   Systemwide, the volume expectations exceed the 7 percent
increase in the year-ago period, and keep the company on track to
post annual earnings-per-share in the high $1.50s to low $1.60s
range, Chairman and Chief Executive M. Douglas Ivester said.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook includes volume increases of 10 to 11 percent for
Latin America and Europe, and 16 to 17 percent for Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The news created a feeding frenzy on Wall Street, where
Coca-Cola's stock hit a record high before closing at $84.87 1/2.
Nearly 5 million Coke shares traded, topping the three-month daily
average of 2.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Daft, whose division accounts for 20 percent of the company's
sales and 25 percent of profits, said Coca-Cola has revised
business plans for every country hit by the ``Asian flu.'' The
actions ``prevented business paralysis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will emerge with an even stronger business than we have
today,'' Daft said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester agreed, saying the climate has created investment
opportunities that otherwise might not have occurred. For example,
an estimated $450 million bottler deal in Korea ``could have easily
cost us twice as much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Through hedging, the company usually can limit the impact of
currency fluctuations on its earnings to about 3 percent, but
``1998 is not a year where we can do that,'' said Chief Financial
Officer James E. Chestnut. He stood by earlier estimates that the
impact would be in the 8 or 9 percent range this year. ``As far as
further out, things are just too volatile to say.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ivester was upbeat, painting a portrait of Coca-Cola as a
true growth company, despite its 112 years in business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty percent of our volume comes from places where 20
percent of the world's population lives,'' Ivester said. ``The
steps that we're taking today to grow and evolve the company will
lead to the company of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
