A7419 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-COX     06-25 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM prepares to close more plants
 &HT;    By Jim Dillon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio -- Thousands more local General Motors Corp.
employees will be sent home as the automaker prepares to literally
turn off the lights at nearly all of its North American plants.
</P>
<P>
   GM is using the massive shutdown, which will extend indefinitely
beyond GM's normal two-week summer break, to conserve cash while it
deals with a crippling strike by the United Auto Workers.
</P>
<P>
   The move would seem to signal that GM is anticipating a long,
drawn-out battle with the UAW.
</P>
<P>
   Strikes by about 9,200 UAW members at two GM plants in Flint,
Mich., have crippled the world's largest automaker, causing it to
lay off more than 147,900 workers throughout the U.S., Canada and
Mexico, and lose an estimated $1 billion in second-quarter profit.
</P>
<P>
   Another 80,000 or so of GM's North American employees remained
on the job Thursday. But only those workers making parts for other
automakers or working on GM's new full-size pickup truck, 1999
Oldsmobile Alero, Pontiac Grand Am and next generation of full-size
cars will escape immediate and indefinite layoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``This action is unparalleled and reflects the critical impact
that this strike is having on our company,'' said GM Vice President
Donald Hackworth in a taped message to GM employees. ``To protect
our company during this crisis, we must reduce all expenditures
that don't impact our future product programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackworth called the move a ``cold shutdown.''
</P>
<P>
   In a memo to plant managers, the automaker also urged them to
cut back on electricity and other utilities and limit any necessary
work to the day shift.
</P>
<P>
   GM's annual two-week shutdown of plants starts this weekend.
Normally, some skilled trades and maintenance workers stay on to do
annual maintenance and prepare for model changes. But that work
won't be done this year and plants will remain closed until a
settlement is reached, a GM spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Flint strikes are entering their third and fourth weeks
respectively. UAW leaders have predicted the strikes could last
into mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   UAW President Stephen Yokich, at his union's constitutional
convention in Las Vegas, said GM's latest actions were a public
relations gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all PR,'' he said. ``Since we went out on strike, they've
done nothing but spin PR instead of going to the bargaining
table.''
</P>
<P>
   GM and its parts subsidiary, Delphi Automotive Systems, employ
about 20,000 people in the Dayton area. More than 7,200 of those
workers already have been laid off as a result of the Flint
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming shutdown _ unmatched since the UAW's 67-day
national strike against GM in 1970 _ promises to put several
thousand more out of work.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how many more local GM workers will be laid off remains
to be seen because local Delphi plants make parts for other
automakers or are involved in future GM products, said Delphi
spokesman Jim Hagedon.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we will be taking advantage of the shutdown to minimize
costs as much as possible. Then as a general rule, we're going to
halt production except where we are working on critical customer
needs and essential future product programs,'' Hagedon said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, 910 of 3,900 laid-off workers at the Moraine truck
assembly plant were called back to work Thursday to ``clear the
line'' before it's shut down indefinitely, Hagedon said.
</P>
<P>
   A prolonged shutdown will create more havoc for GM's and
Delphi's many outside suppliers and vendors as well. Local
companies ranging from AK Steel to Jet Express count GM as a major
customer and have expressed deep concern about the strikes'
continuing impact on their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   GM also is cutting its $2 billion advertising budget for at
least the next six weeks, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   As another way to conserve cash, the company also has pledged to
challenge unemployment compensation to workers affected by the
strike.
</P>
<P>
   So far in Ohio, though, the company has not challenged
unemployment benefits granted to non-UAW members, said David
Garick, spokesman for the Ohio Department of Employment Services.
Most hourly GM employees in the Miami Valley are members of other
unions, including the International Union of Electronic Workers and
the United Steel Workers of America.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW does represent about 3,400 hourly workers at two GM
brake plants in Dayton. A hearing on whether those workers should
receive unemployment benefits is scheduled for Aug. 4 in Columbus,
Garick said.
</P>
<P>
   If GM eventually does challenge unemployment compensation paid
to non-UAW members and wins, those workers could be forced to pay
back that money.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 2,279 GM employees in Ohio, most of whom live in the
Dayton area, have applied for unemployment compensation, Garick
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
