u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOANSCAM-COX     06-25 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOANSCAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Canadian and Ohio officials unite to crackdown on fraudelent
loan companies
 &HT;    By Angela Townsend
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio -- Catherine Sloan thought she had finally found an
answer to her financial woes.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to get out of debt, the Kettering woman sent $443 to a
Canadian company as payment for insurance required to get a $5,000
loan.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan never saw a penny of the loan. The insurance she paid for
didn't exist. And when she tried to get her money back, she learned
the company's phone had been disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think I would have known better,'' said Sloan, an
accountant who holds down two jobs. ``I should have paid attention
to my first basic instinct, that it was too good to be true. When
you're desperate, you do desperate things.''
</P>
<P>
   The telemarketing fraud unit of the Ohio attorney general's
office has joined Canadian law enforcement agencies in
investigating bogus Canadian companies that lure people across the
country with empty promises.
</P>
<P>
   This week the two sides raided 27 ``boiler rooms'' of 40 fake
loan companies, arresting 15 people. The companies allegedly had
kept more than $1 million in fees. It's the third sting operation
in the past year in which Ohio officials have assisted.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Verble, spokeswoman for Attorney General Betty Montgomery,
said the company Sloan dealt with was not among those included in
this week's investigation. ``However, these organizations change
their name so fast that they could have ties to one of (the ones
investigated),'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Sloan, 44, spotted a classified ad in the Dayton Daily
News from a company promising loans to people with no credit who
needed money.
</P>
<P>
   It appealed to Sloan, saddled with huge medical bills due to a
lack of insurance. Forced to file for bankruptcy twice, she wanted
to avoid going down the same road again.
</P>
<P>
   She called the ad's 800 number and talked to a man claiming to
be a loan officer. The next day he called Sloan back. She was
approved for a $5,000 loan at 9 percent interest.
</P>
<P>
   Labeled a credit risk, she was told she had to buy long-term
disability insurance worth $443 before the company would process
her loan application.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was money I didn't even have. I had to borrow it,'' Sloan
said. No loan arrived in the four days promised. The explanation:
The company was behind on paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   On May 19, following a series of calls, Sloan was assured her
loan would be mailed in three days. It didn't come. This time she
was told an investor had pulled out. Her application would be
resubmitted after another investor could be found. That could take
up to a month.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan requested a refund of her money. It would take up to four
weeks, the company said. That was the last time she spoke with
them.
</P>
<P>
   When the four weeks passed without a loan check, Sloan called
again. The phones had been disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes people do get their money back. Last month, 38 states
distributed money to people tricked by a company named Uptown
Financial. More than 25 percent of the Ohio victims were from the
Miami Valley, Verble said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing more of a trend where telemarketers are not just
moving across state lines but international lines as well,'' Verble
said. ``They have a better chance of not getting caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to know that this is illegal and it's a scam,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio consumers who are victims of advanced fee loans are urged
to contact the attorney general's office at (800) 282-0515.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
