<HEADER>
A7421 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEAD-COX     06-25 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mead prepares for a major restructure
 &HT;    By Mike Drummond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio -- Mead Corp. will trim 500 workers over the next
three to five years and sell off $100 million of its non-essential
businesses and real estate holdings to out-maneuver a sluggish
paper market and cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton-based paper company also said Thursday it will take
an $80 million charge against its second-quarter earnings for
write-down of assets and losses associated with the sale last week
of its Zellerbach distribution business. Earnings will be released
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Mead, with annual earnings of $150 million last year on revenues
of $5 billion, will slash 250 salaried employees, including
executives, in the coming months as it restructures some of its
businesses and combines its coated paper divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Another 250 salaried employees will be cut from its total
workforce of 14,000 as the company replaces workers with new
``enterprise resource planning'' software in three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokeswoman said it was too early to say how many of
Mead's 600 local employees would be affected. However, she said
some of those layoffs would be through attrition.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mead predicted it will take a $10 million charge in the
upcoming third quarter and as much as $15 million in future
quarters, it expects the layoffs eventually will save the company
$50 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Also gone will be Mead Ink Products, a sawmill and 50,000 acres
of timber in South Ridge, Mich., undeveloped mill sites in
Tennessee, Kentucky and Michigan, and real estate in San Francisco
and Miamisburg _ 100 acres of land and a building at the Newmark
Center off Ohio 741.
</P>
<P>
   Mead expects to make $100 million off the sale of these assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not content to wait for the marketplace to rebound, and
for prices to rise,'' said Mead Chief Executive Jerome F. Tatar.
``The initiatives announced today are all part of our effort to
drive performance for shareholders regardless of the broader
industry cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Slumping paper prices, a glut of competitors and lack of
investor interest prompted Mead to make some of its boldest moves
since former Mead CEO Steve Mason cleaned house earlier this
decade. Mason discontinued two businesses, sold and bought sawmills
and unloaded Lexis-Nexis to Reed Elsevier plc for $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In the eight months as Mead's CEO, Tatar has proved he is not
content to coast. He oversaw the purchase this year of a small
specialty paper-producing mill in Potsdam, N.Y. Last week he
announced the sale of Mead's financially troubled Zellerbach
division to International Paper's xpedx division for $263 million,
affecting about 2,200 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't let a lot of grass grow under his feet,'' said
Kathryn McAuley, an analyst with New York-based Brown Brothers
Harriman.
</P>
<P>
   For decades Mead, one of only two Fortune 500 companies in the
Miami Valley, acquired non-essential pieces to its $5 billion
business. Tatar's housecleaning is a carry-over from Mason's
tenure, McAuley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mantra in the industry is to focus,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   To that end the company also announced Thursday that it is
combining its mills at Escanaba, Mich., Rumford, Maine, and
Chillicothe under one coated paper division.
</P>
<P>
   Tatar also is pulling the purse strings tighter on annual
spending for plant upgrades. After spending millions of dollars to
modernize its Stevenson, Ala., mill, Tatar is capping
capital-improvement spending to about $300 million in 1999 and
2000, down from its current cap of about $450 million.
</P>
<P>
   However, Tatar, as he has done in the past, has not ruled out
acquisitions
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
