   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-VETO (Washington) _ The Supreme Court says Congress
violated the Constitution's separation of powers rule when it
passed the Line Item Veto Act giving the president authority to cut
individual projects out of tax and spending bills. By MARK HELM.
(Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-ATTORNEY-CLIENT (Washington) _ The Supreme Court
sidetracks Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's effort to obtain
notes of a conversation between White House aide Vincent Foster and
his lawyer shortly before Foster committed suicide. The court
upholds the attorney-client privilege of confidentiality even
though Foster is dead. By MARK HELM. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-AIDS (Washington) _ HIV-infected people are protected by
a federal ban on discrimination against the disabled even if they
suffer no symptoms of AIDS, the Supreme Court says. The 5-4 ruling
ordered a lower court to reconsider whether a Maine dentist
violated the Americans With Disabilities Act when he refused to
fill an HIV-infected woman's tooth in his office. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ARTS (Washington) _ The government can deny cash grants
to artists because their work is considered indecent, the Supreme
Court rules, saying the policy does not violate artists'
free-speech rights. The 8-1 decision said the National Endowment
for the Arts can consider decency, as well as artistic merit, in
deciding who gets public money for the arts. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INVESTIGATION (Washington) _ Linda Tripp, whose secret
tape recordings of Monica Lewinsky triggered an investigation of an
alleged presidential affair and cover-up, is subpoenaed to testify
before a federal grand jury next week. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-TOBACCO (Washington) _ A week after the Senate killed
sweeping anti-smoking legislation, House Republican leaders outline
a much narrower bill that would include a national advertising
campaign to curb teen smoking but is unlikely to impose new
cigarette taxes. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   DELAY-RELIGION (Washington) _ House Majority Whip Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, joins with social and religious conservative Gary Bauer to
demand the reinstatement of Bronx teacher Mildred Rosario who was
fired for allegedly turning her classroom into prayer meeting. By
GREG McDONALD. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-TRENDS (WASHINGTON) _ Methamphetamine, an ``upper'' drug
long popular in California, is emerging as a problem for drug
enforcement officials elsewhere in the country, particularly on the
East Coast, a new report says. By NICOLE TSONG. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TIANANMEN (Beijing) _ President Clinton is walking a
political tightrope by accepting China's official welcoming
ceremony overlooking the 98-acre expanse of Tiananmen Square where
hundreds of unarmed pro-democracy activists were killed by army
troops in 1989. The welcoming ceremony begins at 9 p.m. EDT Friday.
By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   TIANANMEN-SQUARE (Beijing) _ What makes President Clinton's
reception in Tiananmen Square Friday in front of the Great Hall of
the People so sensitive is the historical resonance of this place
in the minds of the Chinese people. It has acquired something of a
split personality _ the figurative seat of state power, on the one
hand, and a place of dissent on the other. By ORVILLE SCHELL.
(Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-VILLAGE (Xian, China) _ A look at the rural village of
Xian that is one of the first stops on President Clinton's China
tour. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-JAPAN-U.S. (Paris) _ In dealing with the Japanese
financial crisis, America finds itself virtually alone, getting
little help from its European friends. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN.
(Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-STATION (Houston) _ The House oversight committee has
asked the White House to prepare a strategy within 30 days to bail
out the financially strapped international space station, a
U.S.-led project that is suffering largely because of Russia's
faltering economy. By MARK CARREAU. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-TEXAS (El Paso, Texas) _ In a warmup for their appearance
Friday night at the State Democratic Convention in San Antonio,
Vice President Al Gore joins gubernatorial candidate Garry Mauro on
a campaign stop designed to capitalize on the historic strength the
party in El Paso. But Republicans predict incumbent Gov. George W.
Bush will become the first GOP gubernatorial contender to carry
this border city. By JOHN GONZALEZ and R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   RACIAL-ATTACK (Jasper, Texas) _ Residents prepare for Saturday's
Ku Klux Klan rally in this East Texas town where three white men
are accused of the brutal killing of a black man. The Klan plans to
parade even though city officials have asked them not to. By
RICHARD STEWART. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   LUCAS-EXECUTION (Austin, Texas) _ The Texas Board of Pardons and
Paroles is to announce its decision on the fate of Henry Lee Lucas,
who is sentenced to die next week for the murder of an unidentified
woman. Gov. George W. Bush asked the parole board to review the
case because of doubts about Lucas' guilt. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ A new Time Magazine-CNN poll shows
that 65 percent of women do not consider themselves to be
feminists. One question is why? Another is what does the word
``feminist'' mean after decades of the women's rights revolution.
By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed; Marianne Means will be on
vacation for a week beginning June 29. Her column will resume July
6.)
