<SLUG> BC-MERGERS-ART-770-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BIGGER IS BETTER' PHILOSOPHY FUELS MERGER MANIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphics on top deals and top investment banks are being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another day, another dozen deals.
</P>
<P>
   On a single day in May, Office Depot, an eye on expanding
abroad, agreed to buy Viking Office Products in a $3 billion stock
swap; Nationwide Mutual Insurance Co. announced a $1.59 billion
hostile tender offer for Allied Group, an Iowa car and home
insurer; Dillard's, the Midwestern retailer, bought Mercantile
Stores Co. for $2.9 billion; and Cardinal Health, hoping to become
a one-stop service provider for pharmaceutical companies, paid $2.2
billion in stock for R.P. Scherer.
</P>
<P>
   And those were just the biggest fish. In all, 11 proposed deals
with a total value of about $17 billion were announced May 18. It
was a pace an almost unheard of _ or would have been last year or
the year before.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, though, it wasn't so unusual. The growing conviction by
corporations worldwide that bigger is better in the global
marketplace has generated a merger wave that has dwarfed anything
that has preceded it.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the value of mergers and acquisitions
announced through June 25 soared by 153 percent from the same point
a year earlier, to $910 billion, according to Securities Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that number is already just under the total for all of
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, deals doubled to $1.3 trillion, fast approaching the
$1.6 trillion record for all of last year. Acquisitions of
bargain-priced Asian concerns by United States companies are
running at a frenetic pace, and activity in Europe is approaching
record levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all surprised when we open the newspaper Monday
morning,'' said Mac Heller, global head of mergers and acquisitions
at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The push into foreign markets and the sense these days that no
company is untouchable, and practically no deal is impossible, are
driving many of this year's mergers. Daimler-Benz's $39 billion
merger agreement with Chrysler Corp. last month, for example, will
create a colossus employing 420,000 workers, giving the German
automaker easier access to American buyers and providing Chrysler a
formidable new base in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Even the general public is taking notice. Cyberinvestors swapped
rumors on Internet chat boards weeks before Tyco International and
U.S. Surgical Corp. announced their merger May 25.
</P>
<P>
   An e-mail message making the rounds this spring joked that
Sesame Street's Bert and Ernie were combining to become Bernie. And
two lawyers in a recent episode of ``The Practice,'' a popular
evening television drama, casually threw around terms like M&AMP;A as
they reminisced about their dreams in law school.
</P>
<P>
   The merger boom is driven in part by the exuberant U.S. economy.
Lower interest rates, of course, have made stocks an attractive
place to invest. But most companies are using their own shares to
make acquisitions, for several reasons, said Rick Escherich, a
managing director in the mergers and acquisitions group at J.P.
Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the accounting treatment on many stock deals is
tax-free. Companies that pay cash don't get such a break. Moreover,
low inflation and the sheer size of the deals being done today _
eight mergers in the past three months alone have exceeded $25
billion each, and three have surpassed $60 billion _ usually leaves
debt financing out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, institutional investors are more willing to take stock
as a way to stay fully invested in a given industry.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, there is a growing consensus among corporate
executives that in a global economy, the only choice is between
being one of the top two or three players in an industry or slowly
bleeding to death.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, several high-profile combinations _ including those of
Citicorp with Travelers Group, Nationsbank Corp. with BankAmerica
and Chrysler with Daimler-Benz _ have spurred a new sense of
urgency and a sense that almost anything is possible. Byron Wein,
head U.S. strategist for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co., says
companies are more pressed to grab friendly partners now or become
targets themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be a feeling out there that there were certain
trophy properties and that they'd never trade,'' Wein said. ``Now
the feeling is if Citicorp and Daimler can trade, anything can. If
something unique doesn't go to you, your second alternative may not
be all that desirable.''
</P>
<P>
   What a stretch from the 1980s, when many companies were acquired
in hostile takeover wars, disassembled and then sold in parts to
the highest bidder. Now it is a virtual love fest, with companies
strategically piecing themselves back together to create advantages
they say can only be achieved by merging.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Most people understand it's a game of scale and size,'' said
Jack Grubman, a telecommunications analyst at Salomon Smith Barney.
``Having a handful of players at the end of the day will be more
competitive then having thousands of fragmented companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The grab for assets will continue as long as current market
sentiment prevails. And even if the stock market crashes, many on
Wall Street believe, demand for acquisitions will remain strong as
financial buyers looking for bargains enter the fray.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, financial services deals _ including those
involving banks and insurance companies _ have led the way,
totaling $347 billion, or 38 percent of all activity, so far this
year. One reason is that the target companies have such high market
values. ``It used to be that a $3 billion to $5 billion deal was a
significant transaction,'' said Ralph Watts, co-head of mergers and
acquisitions at Salomon Smith Barney. ``That has been eclipsed by
the megadeal.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On April 13, for instance, two mergers _ between Nationsbank and
BankAmerica, and between First Chicago and Banc One _ were
announced and added up to $90 billion in value. Compare that with
last year, when all merger and acquisition activity in the bank and
insurance industry in the first six months tallied about the same
amount.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the sheer number of worldwide deals _ 10,401 so far,
according to Securities Data _ has given every firm on Wall Street
a reason to boast. Morgan Stanley was the adviser for the greatest
number, 182 to date, and aided Britain's Energy Group in its merger
with Texas Utilities Co. Salomon Smith Barney, which is owned by
the Travelers Group, helped engineer the largest merger this year,
the marriage of Travelers and Citicorp. Merrill Lynch often finds
itself across the table from Goldman, Sachs in bank negotiations.
And Credit Suisse First Boston had the ear of AT&AMP;T when it
announced the acquisition of Tele-Communications Inc. on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the real bragging rights belong to Goldman, Sachs. which not
only had a hand in eight of the 10 largest deals this year but also
advised on 160 transactions valued at $549 billion, the largest
dollar volume by far of any investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership's client list is a register of the world's
corporate elite. These include Monsanto, Ameritech, Daimler-Benz.
But this year's showing is due, in particular, to Goldman's
high-powered financial-institutions team, which represented, among
others, BankAmerica, First Chicago and Wells Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Heller of Goldman says he is puzzled by all the
attention given mergers these days. On a recent trip to his
hometown of Dayton, Ohio, he was cornered in a grocery store by an
old school chum who quizzed him on the hottest merger prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of made me sad,'' he recalled wistfully. ``The main
event for the economy is how good a job companies are doing in
delivering products and services. Not the merger business. Not Wall
Street. Not Goldman, Sachs.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a point. Despite this buoyant market, chief executives
still have some basic issues to address to insure success, said
Mark Maybell, an investment banker at Merrill Lynch. For one thing,
they have to deliver on promises made in announcing the deal or
their stock will take a hit later. Every combination has to pass
regulatory review. And management has to integrate the corporate
cultures successfully or both customers and staff will bolt.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is not an entirely new phenomenon, more chief
executives are merging their offices as well as their companies by
naming themselves co-chief executives. The arrangement keeps both
leaders in the spotlight and gainfully employed, although few such
marriages of convenience last between people who are not accustomed
to sharing power.
</P>
<P>
   In recent hearings before the Senate Judiciary Committee, Joel
Klein, head of the antitrust division of the Department of Justice,
said his agency would not restrict mergers based on size, but would
continue to scrutinize combinations for their effects on
competition and pricing. He warned, however, that he would look
with disfavor on any companies that plead the need to expand in a
global economy as an excuse to create entities that stifle
competition at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mere invocation of increased globalization as a purported
rationale for a merger does not result in a free pass from
competitive review,'' Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   The big question _ one that won't be answered for several years
_ is whether the 1990s will be remembered as a successful retooling
of larger, more competitive corporations or just another era of
Wall Street hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have a stable economy, people are going to say we did
smart things,'' said Gary Parr, head of mergers and acquisitions at
Morgan Stanley. But if the economy turns sharply down, he added,
``they are going to say these people got carried away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
