<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VATICAN-LUTHERANS-500(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLICS, LUTHERANS TO SIGN DECLARATION ON SALVATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a decision designed to resolve an issue that split the
Western Christian world nearly 500 years ago, the Vatican said
Thursday that it will sign a joint declaration with the world's
Lutherans affirming that Catholics and Lutherans share a basic
understanding of how human beings receive God's forgiveness and
salvation.
</P>
<P>
   The document, approved last week by the Lutheran World
Federation, declares that Catholics and Lutherans have found an
essential common ground on the issue of ``justification,'' the
action by which a human being is made worthy of salvation in God's
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The Reformation leader Martin Luther held that justification
comes solely through faith in God, while the Catholic church taught
that a person's good works play a role.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in agreeing that forgiveness and salvation come only
through God's grace but that good works flow from that, Catholics
and Lutherans have come to show a new appreciation for basic
elements in each other's teachings, as a result of years of
biblical scholarship, inter-church dialogue and a renunciation of
age-old stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the Vatican's position in Rome, Cardinal Edward
Cassidy, president of the Pontifical Council for Promoting
Christian Unity, said, ``I wish to stress that the consensus
reached on the doctrine of justification, despite its limitations,
virtually resolves a long disputed question at the close of the
20th century, on the eve of the new millenium.''
</P>
<P>
   But both Cassidy and the Vatican, in its official statement,
said that areas of considerable disagreement remained and required
further discussion between the two sides. The cardinal also said
the declaration ``has limits,'' in that it does not address major
differences between Catholics and Lutherans on such issues as
authority in the church and the ministry.
</P>
<P>
   But the cardinal said a formal signing would take place in the
fall, along with ``a celebration of the consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic-Lutheran declaration, a carefully-nuanced document
based on 30 years of discussions between Catholic and Lutheran
theologians, sets forth a ``common understanding of
justification.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Together we confess,'' the declaration states at one point,
``by grace alone'' human beings are ``accepted by God and receive
the Holy Spirit,'' which renews their hearts and calls them to good
works. It then goes on to acknowledge specific differences in
Catholic and Lutheran understandings of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   In accepting the document, called ``The Joint Declaration on the
Doctrine of Justification,'' Catholics and Lutherans agreed that
the anathemas they hurled at each other in the 16th Century, as
Europe slid into a devastating period of religious warfare, no
longer apply.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration's official acceptance by both the Vatican and
the Lutheran federation represents a triumph for supporters of the
ecumenical movement, which has urged closer cooperation among
different churches.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It comes at a time of growing awareness among Christians,
particularly in the United States and Europe, of the need to
respond to challenges posed by a growing religious pluralism, in
the emergence of faiths like Islam and Buddhism, as well as by the
rise of a secularism that is deeply wary of the public expression
of religion in society.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months ago, for example, the Evangelical Lutheran Church in
America, the nation's largest Lutheran denomination, entered into a
formal agreement for close cooperation with three smaller
Protestant denominations, allowing for exchange of clergy members
and sharing of communion among members.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Daniel Martensen, ecumenical officer for the
Evangelical Lutherans, said the moves toward closer cooperation
represented ``a change of mood'' among churches as the next
millenium approaches.
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms, Catholic and Lutheran officials said the
declaration will ease tensions between the two faith groups in
regions like Latin America and Eastern Europe, while encouraging
broader cooperation, such as in shared social service programs for
the poor, in nations like the United States where relations between
the churches are good.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Rome, Cardinal William Keeler,
archbishop of Baltimore, said, ``The big point is, we're announcing
consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an agreement that is solid,'' he said. ``Cardinal Cassidy
made it clear that this is something that the church is not going
to step back from.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeler said condemnations exchanged between Catholics and
Lutherans in the 16th Century were based partly on stereotypes and
caricatures of each other. ``When you get into a polarized
situation, and just are talking at each other, you don't really
hear what each other is saying,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Luther, a German monk born in 1483, became convinced that
salvation was a divine gift that humans could not earn, after an
inner struggle and a searching reading of St. Paul's Letter to the
Romans in the New Testament.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring that he felt ``reborn'' by this realization, Luther
also became fiercely critical of the medieval church's practice of
selling ``indulgences,'' by which believers understood they could
purchase a divine remission for their transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1517, he nailed his criticisms, in the form of 95 theses, to
a church door in Wittenburg, Germany, a gesture considered the
opening shot of the Reformation. Attempts by the church to
discipline him failed, his influence grew and he was
excommunicated.
</P>
<P>
   Brother Jeffrey Gros, a specialist in ecumenical affairs at the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops, said the joint declaration
would serve as an ``enormous encouragement'' to Catholics and
Lutherans already working together on various social and religious
projects in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he found it encouraging that the Vatican had
officially called for clarifications of parts of the declaration,
rather than raising outright objections.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from Cassidy's remarks, the Vatican's official statement
alternately praises and criticizes the declaration. Although the
statement says that ``a high degree of agreement has been reached''
in the Catholic-Lutheran dialogue, it points of out areas of
serious difference.
</P>
<P>
   The most important, according to the statement, is the Lutheran
belief that a person can be both justified by God and yet still a
sinner. The Vatican statement said it ``remains difficult to see''
how this doctrine ``is not touched'' by the 16th century anathemas
pronounced against Lutheran teachings by the Catholics' Council of
Trent.
</P>
<P>
   But in raising such questions, the Vatican statement also said
that the Catholic church wanted ``to contribute towards
overcoming'' differences between the two Christian groups.
</P>
<P>
   Lutherans gave final approval to the declaration on June 16, in
a unanimous decision of the governing council of the Lutheran World
Federation, meeting in Geneva, Switzerland. The federation
represents 124 churches in 69 nations.
</P>
<P>
   One council member, the Rev. Susan Nagle, pastor of First
Lutheran Church in Montclair, N.J., said that the work that went
into consideration of the joint declaration enhanced the role of
the federation among Lutherans worldwide. ``Within Lutheranism,
something monumental has happened here, not only with Roman
Catholics, but with our understanding,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're beginning to see the Lutheran World Federation as a
communion of churches with authority to speak for each other,''
Pastor Nagle said.
</P>
<P>
   Momentum for the joint declaration had been building for years.
The top policy-making body of the Evangelical Lutheran Church in
America, its Churchwide Assembly, voted overwhelmingly in favor of
the document last summer.
</P>
<P>
   But Lutheran and Catholic scholars in the United States had
reached substantial agreement on the issue of justification long
before. In 1983, on the 500th anniversary of Luther's birth, a
joint team of 20 scholars, sponsored by Catholic bishops and
Lutheran churches, issued a study declaring a shared view that
salvation came through God's grace and that old differences need
not be ``church-dividing.''
</P>
<P>
   That same year, Pope John Paul II gave the Catholic-Lutheran
dialogue a push by praising Luther in a letter to a German
cardinal. Luther, the pope wrote, was a man of ``profound
religiousness.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
