<HEADLINE>
TRIPP SUBPOENAED TO TESTIFY BEFORE GRAND JURY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Linda Tripp, who secretly recorded conversations
with Monica Lewinsky that triggered a criminal investigation of
President Clinton's sex life, has been subpoenaed to testify next
week before a federal grand jury investigating the case.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp, who turned over the tapes to independent counsel Kenneth
Starr, is scheduled to testify Tuesday, her attorney confirmed late
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Her appearance comes as Starr tries to negotiate an agreement
with Lewinsky's lawyers _ Jacob Stein and Plato Cacheris _ for her
to cooperate in the investigation into whether Clinton or close
associates engaged in a cover-up of his alleged sexual misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   The president and Lewinsky have denied under oath having sex.
Clinton has publicly said his relationship with Lewinsky was not
sexual and that he never urged anyone to lie.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's tapes reportedly tell a different story as Lewinsky
alleges in telephone conversations that she had an 18-month sexual
affair with the president and that he encouraged her to lie about
their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes also reportedly indicate that Lewinsky asked Tripp to
help cover up a White House encounter between Clinton and Kathleen
Willey, a Democratic activist who testified that the president
groped her and kissed her. Clinton has denied any improper behavior
involving Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the grand jury that subpoenaed Tripp heard Thursday
from White House adviser Sidney Blumenthal, who told reporters that
he provided the panel with details of conversations with the
president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton about Lewinsky. It
was the third appearance for Blumenthal, who earlier refused to
answer some questions on the grounds of executive privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president shared his account of the Lewinsky matter with
me unguardedly and freely under the assumption that we were
speaking in complete privacy,'' Blumenthal said. ``What I told the
grand jury under oath supports what the president has told the
American people and is contrary to any charge that the president
has done anything wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal's attorney, William McDaniel, again criticized
Starr's grand jury inquiry, calling it ``not only illegal but
unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Too many of the questions posed by Starr's deputies dealt with
how the president and his advisers wrestled with questions from the
news media and the independent counsel's office about Lewinsky,
McDaniel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is supposedly a serious investigation into the man who
occupies the highest office in the land,'' said McDaniel, who
characterized the questions put to Blumenthal as ``sophomoric,
silly, insulting to the grand jury and ... certainly insulting to
the president.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
