<SLUG> BC-SAKS-SALE-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAKS IS FOR SALE, BUT BUYERS APPEAR WANTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To the average New York shopper, Saks Fifth Avenue
might seem like the ultimate acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   There is the landmark name. The chic frocks. Tourists from
around the world flock to buy anything bearing the store's logo. A
first trip to Saks in search of a bridal gown or lipstick is a rite
of passage for New Yorkers who regard shopping as a serious sport.
</P>
<P>
   But for the average investment bank actually trying to sell the
retail legend, name and cachet do not so easily equal a deal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Saks Holdings Inc., the holding company for the retailer, said
Thursday that its board, as expected, had approved a sale or merger
of the company, and retained Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and Merrill Lynch
&AMP; Co. to assist.
</P>
<P>
   An acquisition or merger of the 97-store chain would end the
ownership of Investcorp International, the Bahrain-based investment
bank, which holds the majority stake in the retailer. Saks was
bought by Investcorp in 1990 for $1.6 billion, and the company sold
20 percent of Saks to the public in 1995 for $25 a share, or $425
million.
</P>
<P>
   Most retail analysts and investment bankers will not discuss
potential buyers, largely because they are hoping to get some
banking business of their own from one. But all the potential
acquirers are known to them because the department store universe
has gotten increasingly small as stores like B. Altman have closed
and others like Macy's have fallen under the umbrella of giant
chains like Federated Department Stores Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Federated, which owns Bloomingdale's, Macy's, Sterns and several
other chains, would seem like the biggest player in the game. But
the fit does not seem perfect. Federated has been focusing on every
place except New York in recent years, rolling out Bloomingdale's
in California and eyeing potential acquisitions in the Midwest,
where it has no presence.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the chairman of Saks, Philip Miller, has taken the
store on an interesting strategic journey. Miller tossed out the
clothing lines that are the bread and butter of Federated stores,
like Liz Claiborne, in favor of pricier lines like Dolce &AMP; Gabbana.
The move increased sales for Saks, but it also means that the store
has little in common with Federated or the giant May Department
Stores Co., which owns Lord &AMP; Taylor, another store less snazzy
than Saks.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there is Nordstrom Inc. ``It would be a real step up for
them,'' said Walter Loeb, the retail consultant. ``It would give
them greater access to name brands.'' But shares of Nordstrom are
held largely by the retailer's founding family, and it seems
unlikely that they would be willing to do a stock transaction to
acquire Saks.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows, of course, how much Saks could fetch, but luxury
retailers tend to be valued at roughly eight-tenths to 1{ times
revenues, which would put the price for Saks roughly between $1.8
billion and $2.5 billion. Few retail companies have that kind of
cash. Further, supplier synergies would be limited, especially
since Nordstrom has a totally decentralized regional buying
structure.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman Marcus, a unit of Harcourt General, is another potential
buyer. The two companies sell similar high-end merchandise and have
similar customers. They have been stomping around each other's
territory for a few years _ Saks has gone into Houston and Dallas,
Neiman has opened stores recently on the East Coast _ and have
privately expressed interest in each other in the past.
</P>
<P>
   But if the two were to get together, could an antitrust argument
result? Outside of Barneys New York, which is tiny compared with
those two, and dozens of small specialty stores around the country,
Saks and Neiman are truly the only national outlets for the Giorgio
Armani and Jil Sander's lines. Miller has also put an emphasis on
scaled-down Saks in small cities, like Greenwich, Conn., further
tightening the retailer's grip on the luxury market.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``If manufacturers feel they benefit from bargaining one of
these stores against the other,'' said Richard Steuer, an antitrust
lawyer at Kaye, Scholer, Fierman, Hays &AMP; Handler, ``they would have
the kind of argument the government would listen to.''
</P>
<P>
   Steuer pointed to the scuttled merger between Staples Inc. and
Office Depot Inc. last year, a union the government found a threat
to free trade. ``Even though this takes the issue from the mundane
to the sublime, the question of their ability to have a lock on a
certain universe of sellers remains,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   International retailers are another option. LVMH Moet Hennessy
Louis Vuitton is said to have already looked and moved on. Dickson
Concepts Inc. has been badly hammered because of the Asian
recession. Harrods Department Store in London is a good
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   And there is always the possibility that Saks executives could
try to raise enough cash to buy the retailer outright.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
