u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-IMF-230&AMP;ADD     06-25 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-IMF-230&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF'S NEW ECONOMIC PLAN FOR INDONESIA ADDS BILLIONS TO TAB 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The International Monetary Fund reached an
agreement Thursday that paves the way for resuming aid to Indonesia
for the first time since President Suharto resigned in May, but it
warned that economic conditions have worsened so quickly that the
country will need billions more in emergency aid.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing an economic reform plan Thursday, the fourth since
Indonesia's economic crisis began in October, IMF officials
predicted that the country's economy would shrink more than 10
percent this year. Independent economists expect the recession to
be much worse, and the World Bank predicted earlier this week that
by the end of the year 40 percent of the population would fall
below the poverty line, a huge setback for a nation that a year ago
seemed to be a model for developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   When the IMF first put together an economic aid plan for
Indonesia, it estimated that the country would need $43 billion in
emergency loans, some from the IMF, some from the World Bank and
the Asian Development Bank, and some committed by individual
countries. That figure included a $3 billion commitment from
Washington, none of which has yet been sent to Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   But in a statement Thursday, the IMF said $43 billion would not
be enough. It called for an additional $4 billion to $6 billion,
though it did not indicate where the money might come from.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``At this critical moment, we are seeking further support of the
international community to insure the success of our economic
program,'' said the country's new agreement with the IMF It was
made public after Hubert Neiss, the Asia-Pacific director of the
IMF, met with Indonesian President B.J. Habibie on Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Neiss also announced that the Asian Development Bank approved a
$1.5 billion loan Thursday to strengthen the crippled banking
sector and help close the budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The new economic plan is similar to the last three: It calls for
government austerity and high interest rates to contain inflation
and support Indonesia's currency. But there are growing fears that
the strategy is failing, with most Indonesian businesses unable to
borrow money or pay back previous loans.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF now projects that inflation will run at about 80 percent
over the next year, largely because the price of imported goods has
soared as the value of Indonesia's currency, the rupiah, has
dropped. The plan optimistically calls for the rupiah to stabilize
at a rate of about 10,000 to the dollar by year's end, compared
with about 2,400 to the dollar before the crisis began.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, however, the rupiah is trading at about 16,000 to the
dollar, weaker than it was in the days leading up to Suharto's
forced resignation. That reflects a growing skepticism among
investors that the country can recover anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Neiss said the decision on whether to release the next
installment of aid, about $1 billion, will come at the next meeting
of the IMF's executive board July 8. He said he expected it to be
approved. Aid was suspended during the political turmoil in late
April and May that led to the end of Suharto's 32-year rule.
</P>
<P>
   Release of the aid is regarded as a crucial step in restoring
some degree of confidence in the Indonesian economy, which has seen
trade come to a virtual standstill, record unemployment and a
currency worth one-sixth what it was worth in August.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new agreement, the government will continue subsidies
for food and fuel to minimize the burden on the poor. But those
subsidies are costing the government billions at a time when
revenues have fallen to nearly zero. That is why the IMF sought
additional aid Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It remains our objective, however, to phase out subsidies as
output and household incomes recover,'' the IMF's statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Daragh Maher, an analyst at ING Barings in Singapore, described
the concessions to the poor as necessary to give the Indonesian
economy a chance to recover. He described the assumptions in the
agreement as ``falling on the optimistic end of expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwik Kian Gie, a prominent Indonesian economist, said the
figures in the latest agreement were ``daring'' given that other
economists expect the economy to shrink by 15 percent to 20 percent
this year. ``Nobody, including the IMF, can make assumptions in
times of uncertainty,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
