<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI SERVES HIMSELF OUT OF TOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ It was another four seasons in one day at
Wimbledon, with things a warm, bright, rainy, chilly step away from
the surreal. No wonder 28-year-old Andre Agassi, dressed in a
billowing white smock of Byronic vintage above black undershorts
that smacked of 21st century technology, discovered himself out on
Centre Court locked in a May-December entanglement.
</P>
<P>
   His opponent was none other than Tommy Haas, the 20-year-old
German who replaced the Las Vegan in the role of teacher's pet at
Nick Bollettieri's tennis think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the last best thought, and shot, in a roller coaster
duel that had been halted by darkness on Wednesday night, belonged
to the 44th-ranked Haas, who remained calm and directed and pulled
off a 4-6, 6-1, 7-6 (7-4), 6-4 upset that provided the floundering
Agassi with yet another setback.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Agassi, who commandeered this slam six years ago, the
brand new French Open champion, Carlos Moya, and the 1989 French
Open champion, Michael Chang, also made premature departures from
Wimbledon Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On the women's side, both of the teen-aged Williams sisters, the
seventh-seeded Venus and the 20th-ranked Serena, stayed on target
for a sibling spat in the fourth round by posting straight-set
victories over their overwhelmed opponents. Serena clobbered
16-year-old Mirjana Lucic, 6-3, 6-0, and Venus set a women's record
with a 125-miles-per-hour serve in the course of her 6-1, 6-2
demolition of Austria's Barbara Schett.
</P>
<P>
   But Jennifer Capriati's wild-card bid to reassert herself at
Wimbledon was thwarted, 4-6, 6-4, 6-2, by another wild card, Lori
McNeil. ``I'm pretty heartbroken, especially because I think I
really had the match, should have won it,'' said Capriati, who
controlled the opening set but failed to adjust to the windy
conditions, as well as McNeil's chipping-and-charging, when the two
returned to court after an hour-long rain delay. Capriati was a
serve away from leveling the second set at 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions changed, I hit a few shaky shots, and she
gained confidence,'' said Capriati, who wasn't the same player in
the latter stages of the match.
</P>
<P>
   Like Capriati, the new French Open champion, Moya, failed to
handle the rain delay with the requisite resilience.
</P>
<P>
   Moya, who said he'd be king of the world for the space of the
two weeks that separate Roland Garros from Wimbledon, failed to
receive the royal treatment from Morocco's 59th-ranked Hicham Arazi
and made a humble exit from the same Centre Court where he had
hoped to hold court long enough to make Pete Sampras fear for his
No. 1 ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the break, I was a completely different player; I don't
know what happened, but nothing worked anymore,'' lamented the
fifth-seeded Moya, after he was ousted 4-6, 6-4, 6-3, 6-4. He had
been considered the likeliest of the quartet of seeded Spaniards to
adjust his game to these unpredictable lawns.
</P>
<P>
   But Moya's demise wasn't as surprising as Agassi's. After all,
this was only Moya's fifth match at Wimbledon, but the selective
seeding committee was so certain that Agassi's prior laurels here
presaged a possible breakthrough performance that they upgraded him
from his ranking of 19th to the No. 13 slot. To his own dismay, he
didn't play like a man who deserved the promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't deserve to win today, didn't do what I needed to
do,'' said Agassi, whose killer instinct isn't what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   As if he hasn't had enough trouble re-inventing himself as a
slam contender after last year's nosedive to 141st in the computer
rankings, here was Agassi face-to-face with just the sort of
strapping, scrapping player designed to make has-beens of the older
generation. Not to mention this was an upstart whose mission was
personal, not generic: Haas was out to prove a point _ that he's
graduated from the ranks of potential threats to present threats.
He convinced Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not out there for my health, but it even took Michael
Jordan a year before he was playing his best again,'' Agassi said.
``Right now I feel like I have a lot more to do with some of these
defeats than my opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi doublefaulted in the sixth game of the final set to lose
the service break he'd gained in its opening game, the first game
of this heldover match. Another Agassi doublefault gave Haas a
first match point to practice on, and an errant backhand gave the
underdog his second match point chance, a chance he converted when
Agassi pumped a forehand wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this road real well,'' said Agassi, who lost in the
first round to another of tennis' young Turks, 18-year-old Marat
Safin, earlier this month at the French Open.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Chang, unseeded at a slam for just the second time in a
decade, was upset by Sweden's Magnus Gustafsson, 6-2, &UR;  &LR; 5-7, 6-2,
1-6, 6-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
