<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-FOSTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES UPHOLD ATTORNEY-CLIENT PRIVILEGE, DEAL SETBACK FOR STARR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Thursday rejected independent
counsel Kenneth Starr's effort to see a lawyer's notes from
conversations with White House aide Vincent Foster shortly before
his death.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 ruling affirmed the long-held principle that
conversations between a client and his attorney are confidential,
even after the client is dead.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's decision was a setback for Starr, who wanted
access to three pages of notes taken by lawyer James Hamilton
during his July 11, 1993, meeting with Foster, a deputy White House
counsel who committed suicide nine days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been generally, if not universally, accepted for well
over a century that the attorney-client privilege survives the
death of the client in a case such as this,'' Chief Justice William
Rehnquist wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was whether Starr could use Hamilton's notes in the
investigation of staff firings at the White House travel office and
whether first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton lied when she denied
playing a role in the dismissals.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, a long-time law partner of the first lady, would have
been a key witness in the travel office inquiry. Seven employees
were fired shortly after President Clinton took office and a
relative of the president's was put in charge of the travel
operation.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady and presidential aides have said she played no
role in the firings _ a position contradicted in a memo by White
House staffer David Watkins. The memo says Foster ``regularly
informed me'' of the first lady's ``insistence'' that the travel
office employees be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to working with Hillary Clinton at the Rose Law Firm
in Little Rock, Ark., Foster did legal work for the Clintons on the
Whitewater development, a failed land deal that four years ago
triggered Starr's investigation of the president
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry was expanded to include the White House travel
office firings and, earlier this year, the Monica Lewinsky
sex-and-perjury allegations involving the president.
</P>
<P>
   Starr issued a statement saying he was disappointed by
Thursday's ruling but would push forward with his investigations of
the Clinton White House. ``Although we are disappointed in the
outcome of the Supreme Court's decision, we understand and respect
the care and expedition with which the Court resolved the case,''
Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton called the ruling a victory not only for him and his
late client but for all Americans who consult with an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day we tell our clients what the law is and instruct
them to obey it; we tell them to settle; we tell them to plead; we
tell them to obey subpoenas; we tell them to tell the truth,''
Hamilton said. ``Without candid information from clients, we can't
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton met with Foster only once and assured him that their
conversation would be confidential.
</P>
<P>
   In his pleadings before the Supreme Court, Starr argued that
Hamilton's notes could provide key information about the travel
office firings and the roles played by various people at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist said Starr's arguments were not ``frivolous'' but that
he failed to satisfy the court that his need for information was
sufficient to breach the traditional confidentiality rule. The
chief justice said knowing that their discussions will remain
secret even after their death will encourage clients to confide
``fully and frankly'' with their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist rejected Starr's arguments that disclosure after death
would have a chilling influence only on clients intent on
committing perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, joined by Justices Antonin Scalia
and Clarence Thomas, dissented saying that in criminal cases a
narrow exception should be carved out to the rule that
attorney-client privilege survives a client's death.
</P>
<P>
   If testimony is unavailable from any other source, O'Connor
said, the confidentiality rules would not apply in cases ``where
the exoneration of an innocent criminal defendant or a compelling
law enforcement interest is at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   At Starr's request, the Supreme Court agreed to expedite the
Foster notes case rather than hold it over until the court's new
term, which begins in October.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The court refused a similar effort by Starr to get a speedy
review and decision from the justices on whether Bruce Lindsey,
President Clinton's most trusted legal adviser, and three Secret
Service employees must testify before a federal grand jury in the
Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
