<HEADER>
A7453 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-NYT &LR;      06-25 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CHINESE SEE IT, TAIWAN REMAINS THE MOST IMPORTANT ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-SCENE, CHINA-CLINTON, CHINA-DISSIDENTS,
CHINA-PEONY, CHINA-GINGRICH) 
(JT) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From China's point of view the most explosive issue
in its relationship with the United States is Taiwan. Chinese
officials consistently argue that the level of American arms sales
to the island violates Washington's pledge to reduce and,
ultimately, phase out such sales.
</P>
<P>
   To press its point, Beijing contends that its help to Pakistan
and Iran's military and missile programs, which Washington is
trying to limit, is comparable to Washington's military assistance
to Taiwan. In negotiations Beijing has suggested trading off its
missile cooperation in the Middle East for American commitments to
cut arms sales sharply to Taiwan, a possibility criticized by
American Republicans like the former American ambassador to China
and representative to Taiwan, James Lilley.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has argued that Chinese missile assistance to
countries like Iran, which may use the weapons offensively, is
quite different from its select supplies of defensive weaponry to
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1979, when Washington recognized Beijing as the sole legal
government of China and acknowledged that Taiwan is part of China,
Washington has been committed to sell Taiwan whatever it needs to
defend itself, language in the 1979 Taiwan Relations Act and passed
by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But in August 1982, in what became known as the third
communique, President Ronald Reagan agreed that the United States
would gradually reduce arms sales to Taipei from the levels of that
era, $830 million a year. For a time the administration cut
spending $20 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Although administration officials, then and now, argue that
nothing in the 1982 communique contradicts the 1979 law, ``the
problem is that the two are not consistent, and it's not hard to
find ways in which they are in conflict,'' said Professor Kenneth
Lieberthal of the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The 1979 act, which Congress regards as pre-eminently the law of
the land, speaks of no reductions. The communique, which China
regards as superseding the law, promises reductions of sales to
Taiwan, ``leading over a period of time to a final resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue was not prominent, however, until 1992. Then, in the
midst of his campaign for re-election, President George Bush agreed
to sell Taiwan 150 advanced F-16 fighters, worth more than $5
billion and produced in the pivotal state of Texas. That one sale
drove the fiscal 1992 arms sales to Taiwan of $478 million, to
$6.275 billion for fiscal year 1993, before falling back to figures
below $500 million each year since then, according to unclassified
congressional notifications under the Export Control Act and
assembled by the Congressional Research Service.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years the Clinton administration has also
notified Congress of some major sales, including, in January, three
Knox-class frigates and antisubmarine missiles and launchers worth
$300 million; last year 21 AH-1W Super Cobra attack helicopters
worth $479 million, and, in 1996, two sales of Stinger
ground-to-air missiles and launchers that totaled 1,764 missiles
for $885 million.
</P>
<P>
   China has been particularly concerned about past sales of
Patriot-equivalent air-defense systems and wants to forestall
future American sales of a ``theater missile defense system'' to
Taiwan, a system that has not been developed yet.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1982 communique Beijing promised a peaceful resolution of
the question of Taiwan, which Washington interprets as directly
linked to its promise to reduce arms sales, an assumption that
Beijing rejects. Some officials here have argued that China's
severe reaction to pressure by President Lee Teng-hui of Taiwan for
independence, including Chinese missile launchings that bracketed
Taiwan before its elections in March 1996, was also a violation by
Beijing of the communique.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a legal and moral obligation to provide for Taiwan's
security, and if Taiwan feels secure there's more likelihood for a
real cross-straits dialogue between Beijing and Taipei about the
future,'' said Winston Lord, former Assistant Secretary of State
for East Asia and a former ambassador to China.
</P>
<P>
   Even the sales of F-16's, Lord argued, ``though a stretch,''
were nonetheless legitimate, given China's growing military
capacity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
