A7456 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-LOANS-NYT &LR;      06-25 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-LOANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMANITARIAN AID PACKAGE OK'D FOR INDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Thursday, only six weeks after India conducted nuclear tests,
prompting economic sanctions by the United States, the World Bank
resumed its lending program to New Delhi with the endorsement of
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Washington said the aid, $543 million in loans, is chiefly
humanitarian and thus exempt from its sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's decision suggested that despite Clinton's
warnings about the harm that economic sanctions would do to India
and to Pakistan, which later conducted tests of its own, most World
Bank projects will probably move ahead. The bank focuses most
programs on health, nutrition, education and rural development; it
is unclear whether the administration will seek to block electric
power projects, which are often part of development programs.
</P>
<P>
   The new loan is for Andhra Pradesh, a state that has been a
leader in economic reform. The state has 73 million people, and the
bank said about 30 percent of the children suffer from
malnutrition. The literacy rate is 44 percent, lower than India's
average.
</P>
<P>
   The package the bank approved is directed at those problems,
including projects to insure that more childen complete primary
school, to train health workers and to pay for immunization and
nutrition services for preschool children and pregnant and nursing
women. Money for irrigation systems and the maintenance of rural
roads is also included.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department, which enforces Washington's sanctions,
said all the programs fall under an exception in the 1994 Nuclear
Nonproliferation Act. That law requires Washington to cut off
virtually all direct aid to nations that conduct nuclear tests; it
also bans American banks from making loans to their governments and
mandates that the United States vote against aid to those countries
by the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   But the law exempts aid for ``basic human needs,'' a category
that is not defined in the legislation. It is up to the
administration to devise a definition, and it appears to have
chosen a relatively broad one, especially after it became clear
that other industrialized countries would not join in voting
against most World Bank programs for the poor. The United States
has about 18 percent of the voting power in the bank, not enough to
block a program by itself.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's decision signals that the economic pain from the
sanctions will be less than India and Pakistan first feared. India
is the largest borrower from the bank, receiving $1.5 billion this
year, not counting Thursday's program. Pakistan receives less from
the bank, but the aid is a larger portion of its economy.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear what will happen to aid for India's national power
projects. A loan of $450 million, part of a $5.7 billion program
for a power-distribution network, was put on hold a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most severe sanction against both countries,
however, is being meted out by the currency markets.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of the nuclear tests and an unpopular budget
have scared investors away from India, sending its currency
plunging. That has forced leaders of the ruling Bharatiya Janata
Party to draw up new economic reforms, to end state monopolies in
insurance and to make it easier for foreigners to buy real estate,
in the hope of drawing in foreign investment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
