A7457 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNBEAM-MARKETPLACE-5     06-25 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNBEAM-MARKETPLACE-595&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: PLUG COULD FALL OUT AS SUNBEAM STOCK PLUMMETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How much worse can it get for Sunbeam Corp?
</P>
<P>
   Since the board of directors dismissed Albert Dunlap as chairman
and chief executive nearly two weeks ago, the stock has continued
to plummet. By all accounts, the financial outlook for the rest of
the year looks bleak.
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting the situation is even more dire, the company said
Thursday that there were unanswered questions about its 1997
financial results and confirmed that the Securities and Exchange
Commission is investigating its accounting practices.
</P>
<P>
   The company, while saying it is conducting an internal review of
its financial statements, reversed its position of just a week
earlier when it said questions about last year's numbers were
without merit.
</P>
<P>
   There is more. Sunbeam said Thursday that it would have to delay
registration of a bond offering with the SEC. The problem: its
independent accounting firm, Arthur Andersen LLP, is withholding
its opinion, needed to complete the filing, until the company
concludes its financial review.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the company said that Arthur Andersen had conducted
a review earlier this month at the request of Sunbeam's board and
had found no problems. Sunbeam and Arthur Andersen declined to
comment on the about-face.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to sorting out any problems with last year's
results, Sunbeam will soon be in violation of loan covenants that
put it at risk of defaulting on $1.4 billion owed to Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter &AMP; Co., Bank of America and First Union.
</P>
<P>
   The lenders require the company to meet certain financial tests,
such as maintaining a cash flow of at least two and a half times
the amount of its interest payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company will not meet these tests as of June 30, 1998,
because of its anticipated loss for the second quarter,'' Sunbeam
said in a statement. The company added that it was negotiating with
the lenders to waive the requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunbeam is seeking the waiver to give its new management time
to complete a full review of Sunbeam's business and develop a new
operating plan,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam has drawn down about $1.4 billion of its $1.7 billion
credit line, with Morgan Stanley providing about $680 million of
the total and each of the banks about $510 million.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the lenders could demand immediate repayment of the
loans, but that seems unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The company ``is worth more alive than dead,'' said Joe
Kinnison, a money manager with American Express Financial Advisers,
which holds 3.8 million Sunbeam shares. ``There is no incentive for
the banks to liquidate.''
</P>
<P>
   For investors who wonder if the news can only get better from
here, Kinnison and other stock analysts urge extreme caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a difficult time coming up with a valuation for it at
this time,'' Kinnison said.
</P>
<P>
   A lingering concern is the inventory of barbecue grills and
electric blankets sitting in warehouses, an unknown quantity for
now, Sunbeam concedes.
</P>
<P>
   William Steele, a financial analyst who follows the company for
Buckingham Research Group, said: ``Given the uncertain earnings
outlook, as well as a lack of information regarding the magnitude
of problems the company will face, in conjunction with the
possibility of significant financial restraints placed on the
company based on covenant violations, we would continue to avoid
adding to or initiating positions on Sunbeam.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the loss of investor confidence, the company's stock
price has declined sharply from its $52 high in March. The shares
closed at $10.4375 each Thursday, down 13 percent, or $1.5625.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first hit was in March when Dunlap warned of slowing sales.
A couple of months later, he stunned Wall Street with a $44.6
million first-quarter loss.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, at the same time the board dismissed Dunlap, it said
that his earnings forecasts for the second quarter and full year
were far too high. Sunbeam had been expected to earn 5 cents to 10
cents a share for the quarter ending June 30 and $1 for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The company now says it will report a loss for the quarter and
will not meet the $1 earnings target.
</P>
<P>
   Investor losses, meanwhile, are mounting. Dunlap himself has
suffered a huge paper loss. At the stock's peak, he owned 1.4
million shares worth $77.4 million. Thursday, those shares were
worth $15.5 million. Some of the stock he purchased at market
prices, but most of it was a stock award by the board.
</P>
<P>
   His investment was about $5 million. (The figures exclude
millions of stock options granted by the board that were based on
stock performance and are currently worthless.)
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Sunbeam factory workers and lower-level managers
have fared even worse. They bought shares under a payroll deduction
plan and many have retirement funds invested in the stock. Some of
them, who survived Dunlap's ax, may wonder if the ones who lost
their jobs and took their funds with them were the lucky ones after
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large percent of their net worth is probably involved in
their investment, so that is more tragic,'' said Sarah Teslik,
executive director of the Council of Institutional Investors in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Dunlap, whose net worth was more than $100 million even
before arriving at Sunbeam in July 1996, ``they were not investing
just to make money but to protect their homes and families, and
that makes it sadder,'' Ms. Teslik said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
