<HEADLINE>
MASON OF HORNETS GUILTY OF 2 MISDEMEANORS  
 (JT)  
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anthony Mason pleaded guilty Thursday to two misdemeanor counts
of endangering the welfare of a child in connection with an
incident last February in which Mason, the Charlotte Hornets
forward and former Knick, and a cousin were accused of having
consensual sex with two girls at a house in Queens, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, who had been visiting his native Queens during the
National Basketball Association's All-Star Game break, admitted to
having placed sisters age 14 and 15 ``in a position where they
would be subjected to sexual contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Appelbaum, an assistant district attorney, told Queens
Criminal Court Justice Sheryl Parker Thursday that charges of rape
and sexual abuse were being dismissed because the DNA testing did
not link Mason to the victims serologically.
</P>
<P>
   Mason was ordered to serve 200 hours of community service
working with the homeless at the Progressive Baptist Church in
Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   William Duggins, Mason's co-defendant and cousin, in whose
apartment the incident occurred, pleaded guilty to statutory rape
and to endangering the welfare of a child. Duggins, 24, of Queens,
was sentenced to five years probation and 800 hours of community
service. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
