A7463 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEAMSTERS-ELECTION-NY     06-25 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNDING STALEMATE COULD DELAY TEAMSTERS' VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (mk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal monitor who was appointed to supervise the
Teamsters' election said Thursday that, because of a stalemate over
funding, he might have to close his operations and the election
might have to be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   The monitor, Michael Cherkasky, told a U.S. judge that his
office might run out of money within weeks because Congress has
barred using government money to supervise the election, insisting
that the union pay for the election itself.
</P>
<P>
   Cherkasky asked the judge, David Edelstein of U.S. District
Court in Manhattan, to order the government and the International
Brotherhood of Teamsters to work out an agreement to fund his
office so it could oversee the election.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual standoff, Congress has barred federal money from
helping conduct the election, while the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals has ordered the federal government to pay for the election.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court said that a 1989 consent decree states that if
the federal government chooses to supervise the election then it
must pay to conduct and supervise the election. The election is
scheduled for September and October.
</P>
<P>
   Cherkasky said his office needed $8.6 million to conduct the
election, saying that some contractors, like the company that would
print the ballots, were refusing to sign a contract until adequate
funding was guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   The funding dispute, Cherkasky said, could undercut the
longstanding federal effort to root out Teamster corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Cherkasky wrote Edelstein, ``It would be astounding, and a
stunning waste of decades of effort spent fighting organized crime
and labor racketeering, if the current paralysis over funding
resulted in the abandonment of this law enforcement effort and left
the rerun election in limbo.''
</P>
<P>
   In the union's 1996 presidential election, Ron Carey, the
incumbent, narrowly defeated James Hoffa, but federal monitors
threw out the election and ordered a new one because Carey aides
siphoned more than $700,000 of union funds into his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Pazzi, Hoffa's campaign manager, voiced concern Thursday
about the funding stalemate, saying that Hoffa, now the
front-runner, stands to be hurt if the election is delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Cherkasky suggested that even if there was no funding agreement,
Edelstein should order the union to conduct the election, with the
funding to be worked out later.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter Hoekstra, R-Mich., the point man in Congress on the
funding issue, criticized Cherkasky for not having set up stricter
controls to stop Teamster officials from using union resources to
support their candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we get some of those issues addressed, it's pretty
difficult to work out the funding issues,'' Hoekstra said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0457 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-365&AMP;ADD     06-25 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-365&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDE SAYS HIS TESTIMONY BACKED CLINTON'S DENIALS ON LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sidney Blumenthal, a senior White House aide, said
Thursday that he told a grand jury here that Clinton's private
comments to him about Monica Lewinsky did not contradict his public
denials of a sexual relationship with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they really liked the story that I had to
tell,'' Blumenthal said of the prosecutors investigating the
president, describing in an interview Thursday night his appearance
before the grand jury Thursday and one on June 4.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Clinton tried to exert executive privilege to prevent
Blumenthal's testimony. The president dropped his claim after a
federal judge rejected it.
</P>
<P>
   But Blumenthal said Thursday night that his testimony supported
Clinton's denials. ``What I told the grand jury, under oath,
supports completely what the president has told the American
people, and is contrary to any charge that the president has done
anything wrong,'' Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said that prosecutors told him he was done for now,
but that he might eventually be called back. Tuesday, prosecutors
plan to call Linda Tripp, the Pentagon worker whose surreptitious
taping of Ms. Lewinsky and contacts with the office of Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr helped entangle Clinton in charges of perjury
and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from Blumenthal's account, prosecutors are looking into
whether the White House has tried to obstruct the investigation
since the charges were disclosed in January.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said that many questions centered on the twice-daily
strategy sessions that some senior White House aides and lawyers
have held for the last five months.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were on to a new fantasy plot of obstruction,'' scoffed
Blumenthal, who is a communications adviser to the president. ``In
the new fantasy plot, the obstruction was taking place in White
House strategy meetings, and we were receiving orders and carrying
them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr spokesman Charles Bakaly declined to comment on
Blumenthal's description of his testimony, saying that while
witnesses were free under grand jury rules to discuss their
testimony, ``the prosecutors cannot do so, even to respond to
inaccurate statements.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Starr has indicated that exploring discussions among White House
aides was important to determining whether there has been
obstruction. In oral arguments opposing the White House claim of
executive privilege, Starr said, ``If there is no evidence of White
House involvement in obstruction of justice, or if there is, it is
not going to be on paper and it's not going to be on tapes. It will
be conversations, talk between human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   William Alden McDaniel, Blumenthal's lawyer, said that
Blumenthal declined to answer one question Thursday on what he
called ``a minor topic,'' which he did not describe. He said that
Blumenthal ``would be happy to answer if he is so instructed by the
judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said that he was asked whether President Clinton or
Mrs. Clinton issued orders to participants at the strategy
meetings, and answered no. He said that he told the jurors that
during the meetings, ``We talk about what's in the media, and we
talk about politics and tactics and strategy.'' The Clintons do not
attend the meetings, aides have said.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said that he was also asked who was permitted to
speak in the strategy meetings, and replied that anyone could.
``They said to me, `You mean to tell us that Mike McCurry just
doesn't follow orders, he's allowed to speak in meetings?''' said
Blumenthal, in a reference to the White House press secretary. ``I
said, `Yes, he's allowed to speak, and he has a lot of opinions.'''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, who has framed his subpoena to testify on his office
wall, has made no secret of his contempt for Starr and some of his
team. He said he had run up about $50,000 in legal fees because of
the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said that he was asked both Thursday and three weeks
ago about a private talk he had had with the president in the Oval
Office early in the evening of Jan. 21, as the accusations
involving Ms. Lewinsky erupted. Blumenthal said that he described
the conversation to the grand jury, but he declined to describe it
publicly. ``I still regard this as a confidence from the
president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said that the jurors themselves asked a few
questions. He said that their questions were ``more personal,''
saying that one asked, ``Why did the president confide in you?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
