<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7466 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-FINLAY-ART-NYT     06-25 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-FINLAY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT'S RULING ON INDECENCY PROMPTS FEARS OF A CHILLING EFFECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SCOTUS-RDP) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By MEL GUSSOW    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Performance artists whose lawsuit led to Thursday's
Supreme Court decision on indecency in the arts expressed
disappointment at the ruling, saying they feared it would have a
chilling effect on creativity and freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
   For Karen Finley, whose performance in a New York theater as a
chocolate-covered nude was at the heart of the case, the decision
was a personal defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm stunned and saddened by it,'' she said. She had listened
to the oral arguments made before the Supreme Court and thought
that the court would rule in her favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your child falls down a well: what's your reaction?'' she
said. ``I spent years on the case, and I lose. It's a major
tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Endowment for the Arts, which gives money to
encourage development of the arts, rescinded grants awarded to Ms.
Finley and three other performance artists _ Tim Miller, Holly
Hughes and John Fleck _ after protests from members of Congress,
led by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C. The artists filed a lawsuit, which
ultimately led to the Supreme Court case.
</P>
<P>
   The court, in an 8-1 ruling, upheld a 1990 law requiring the NEA
to consider decency standards when deciding which artists should
get grant money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take it that the Supreme Court has decided that my work is
indecent,'' Ms. Finley said. Alluding to the title of one of her
first shows, ``We Keep Our Victims Ready,'' she said, ``No matter
what you do you're still a victim. I think it's very sexist.''
</P>
<P>
   In her performance, Ms. Finley uses her body, sometimes
appearing nude and covered only with chocolate, to make a statement
about the abuse of women. ``My work was taken out of context and
eroticized by Helms on the Senate floor,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Finley said that the impact of the decision will be felt in
other areas of the arts and predicted that museums and foundations
will be more reluctant to offer support to artists with unpopular
views.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is going to be the decider of what's decent and what
isn't?'' she said. ``It will be a free-for-all. The witch hunt can
happen anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Finley is appearing Off Off Broadway at the Flea Theater in
``The Return of the Chocolate-Smeared Woman.'' She said she would
continue her performances, but she might look for alternatives to
performing, although she feels she may have to confront repression
even as an author and visual artist.
</P>
<P>
   For Miller, the court decision is ``a further nail in the coffin
of freedom of ideas and images in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a chilling effect,'' Miller said, adding that the
decision will not only affect established performers like himself
and Ms. Finley, but also limit opportunities for emerging artists.
He was concerned about the effect of the decision on such
institutions as the National Science Foundation, the National
Endowment for the Humanities, the Smithsonian Institution and the
academic world itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you express an unpopular opinion, it would seem to be a
pretty serious breach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller said he views the case as an ``ongoing battle,'' and
prefers to take a long view: ``One hundred years from now, the
decision will seem as absurd as the Dred Scott decision.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
