<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-ARTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES UPHOLD DECENCY LAW FOR ARTS GRANTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court ruled Thursday the constitutional
right to free speech and expression does not automatically prevent
the federal government from limiting its arts funding to works that
meet general decency standards.
</P>
<P>
   A controversial 1990 federal law requires the chairman of the
National Endowment for the Arts to consider ``general standards of
decency and respect for the diverse beliefs and values of the
American public'' before awarding government grants.
</P>
<P>
   In an 8-1 decision, the high court upheld that standard for
allocating federal resources for artists, many of whom rely on such
support for their work.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court said the law _ as written _ neither prevents
artists from speaking nor does it necessarily require NEA to
discriminate against a work of art because of the opinion it
expresses.
</P>
<P>
   However, the court said the NEA could run afoul of the First
Amendment if it applies the standards in a way that discriminates
based on viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``That the statutory standard admonishes the NEA merely to take
`decency and respect' into consideration, and that the legislation
was aimed at reforming procedures rather than precluding speech,
undercut argument that the provision inevitably will be utilized as
a tool for invidious viewpoint discrimination,'' Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor wrote for the majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the NEA were to leverage its power to award subsidies on
the basis of subjective criteria into a penalty on disfavored
viewpoints, then we would confront a different case.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice David H. Souter, the sole dissenter, assailed the court
for failing to see the ``clear legislative purpose, so plainly
expressed'' that Congress, through the NEA, intended to suppress
artistic expression that lawmakers find offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``A statute disfavoring speech that fails to respect America's
`diverse beliefs and values' is the very model of viewpoint
discrimination; it penalizes any view disrespectful to any belief
or value espoused by someone in the American populace,'' Souter
wrote. ``Boiled down to its practical essence, the limitation
obviously means that art that disrespects the ideology, opinions or
convictions of a significant segment of the American public is to
be disfavored ...''
</P>
<P>
   Four performance artists, who believe their scatological work
might not pass NEA muster, challenged the agency's standard as a
violation of the First Amendment's right to speak and express
oneself without governmental interference.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Finley, John Fleck, Holly Hughes and Tim Miller sued the
government, seeking a judicial ruling that the standard is
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   They won in the U.S. District Court for Central California and
again in the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals before losing in the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the high court rejected the artists' argument
that the NEA standards are unconstitutionally vague, giving
government officials free reign to determine what the standards
mean.
</P>
<P>
   The justices likened the standards to valid, equally subjective
evaluations the government uses in awarding scholarships based on
``excellence'' and similarly ill-defined criteria. ``To accept the
vagueness argument would be to call into question the
constitutionality of these valuable government programs and
countless others like them,'' O'Connor wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Stephen G.
Breyer, Ruth Bader Ginsburg, Anthony M. Kennedy and John Paul
Stevens joined O'Connor's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia, writing separately, not only agreed
NEA's standards pass constitutional muster but added that the
Constitution allows the federal government to consider the opinions
expressed in deciding whether to fund an artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who wish to create indecent and disrespectful art are as
unconstrained now as they were before the enactment of this
statute,'' Scalia wrote in an opinion joined by Justice Clarence
Thomas. ``They are merely deprived of the additional satisfaction
of having the bourgeoisie taxed to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The socially conservative Family Research Council hailed the
court's decision as sending a ``strong message'' to artists whose
work shows disdain for religious symbols or celebrates homosexual
love.
</P>
<P>
   ``If government's in the art business, it has every right to
call the tune,'' said Robert Knight, the council's cultural
director. ``No individual has a right to be granted tax dollars
with no strings attached.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the liberal civil rights group People for the American
Way called the court's decision ``troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Allowing the government to attach strings and apply vague
criteria to its funding will cast a chill over First Amendment
rights by encouraging the institutions that rely on government
funding to shy away from controversial topics or viewpoints,''said
Elliot Mincberg the group's legal director.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
