<SLUG> BC-IRAN-U.S.-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MUST ALTER BEHAVIOR, IRANIAN OFFICIAL SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ Iran on Thursday reiterated its rejection of a
political dialogue with the United States, as a deputy foreign
minister praised the Clinton administration for softening its
hostile tone but sharply criticized Washington for not abandoning
its punitive policies against his country.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, the minister, Mohammed Javad Zarif, offered the
most detailed official Iranian reaction to a speech last week by
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright calling on the Iranian
government to help formulate a ``road map'' to normal relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a move at least in rhetoric on the part of the United
States to better understand the realities of the Islamic Republic
as well as of our region,'' Zarif said. But, he added, ``Where it
matters, where it will be taken seriously by Iran _ regarding the
policies of the United States, the behavior of the United States _
we see the remnants of a Cold War mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other issues, Zarif cited the continuation of an American
trade embargo against Iran and American opposition to the building
of a pipeline through Iran to transport oil from the Caspian Sea as
proof of American ill will toward his country.
</P>
<P>
   Zarif, who studied at Columbia University and San Francisco
State University and holds a Ph.D. in international relations from
the University of Denver, served as a diplomat at the United
Nations for nine years, and is known for his conciliatory tone,
even when it comes to discussing the Ujited States.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks amplified those made by Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi in Spain last week in which he said that if the United
States is serious in improving relations with Iran, it must prove
it with ``facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither President Mohammed Khatami nor Iran's spiritual leader,
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, has reacted publicly to Albright's speech,
which was the result of long deliberations within the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed Ali Nateq Noori, the speaker of the Parliament who was
defeated by Khatami in last year's presidential election, did not
refer to Albright's remarks in a speech on Tuesday, but said, ``It
is a mistake to imagine that America has given up mischief.''
</P>
<P>
   Iran is embroiled in a high-stakes political battle between
supporters of Khatami, who has pushed for the creation of a civil
society and the rule of law, and conservative supporters of
Khamenei, who are determined to uphold revolutionary values.
Improving relations with the United States is not high on the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Zarif also faulted Albright for repeating
charges against Iran that it sponsors terrorism and is developing a
dangerous program of nuclear, chemical and biological weapons and
ballistic missiles. ``She made a big mistake, big mistake,'' Zarif
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the American call for an official dialogue between the two
countries, Zarif said, ``We don't believe that the behavior of the
United States shows yet that it is ready for a dialogue based on
mutual respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, some Iranian officials have expressed concern that
even if they proceed down the road with negotiations with the
United States, they could end up empty-handed. Three years ago,
Rafsanjani, as president, said that the United States had missed a
signal to improve relations with Iran when it forced the
cancellation of a $1 billion deal that Iran had made with an
American oil company.
</P>
<P>
   Zarif acknowledged that even Iran's modest opening of the
country to American scholars and political analysts had been
criticized in news reports and in Parliament. ``To put it mildly,
there is a diversity of views regarding that exchange,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Iran has rejected requests for visas by a number of American
lawmakers and at least one former hostage who applied for a tourist
visa, Iranian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's remarks have reignited a debate in Iran's
increasingly outspoken news outlets over policy toward the United
States, with some newspapers voicing suspicion of the United
States, while others have suggested that improved relations with
Washington are possible.
</P>
<P>
   One sign that the mood in Tehran toward the United States is
less uniformly hostile than it has been in the past came after Iran
beat the United States in a World Cup soccer match last Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   In Vali Assr Square in central Tehran a group of men raised an
American flag and showered onlookers with leaflets denouncing the
United States. As soon as the group began to set the flag on fire,
it was pulled down into the crowd. Other onlookers tore up the
leaflets.
</P>
</TEXT>
