<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-AIDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
DIVIDED COURT RULES DISABILITIES ACT COVERS HIV-INFECTED PEOPLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A sharply divided Supreme Court ruled Thursday that
people who suffer from the virus that causes AIDS enjoy the same
federal protection from discrimination as other disabled
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-4 decision, the high court said the Americans with
Disabilities Act covers people with the human immunodeficiency
virus, or HIV, regardless of whether they show symptoms. The law
protects people with disabilities that ``substantially'' limit
their ability to perform a major life activity; HIV sufferers are
restricted from engaging in the major activity of reproduction
because of the danger the disease presents to a victim's sexual
partner and offspring, the justices said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The act addresses substantial limitations on major life
activities, not utter inabilities,'' Justice Anthony M. Kennedy
wrote in the court's majority opinion. ``Conception and childbirth
are not impossible for an HIV victim but, without doubt, are
dangerous to the public health. This meets the definition of a
substantial limitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Justices Stephen G. Breyer, Ruth Bader Ginsburg, David H. Souter
and John Paul Stevens joined Kennedy's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   In their decision, the justices sent the case back to a federal
appeals court to decide whether a dentist was justified under the
law when he refused to treat a patient who suffers from HIV in his
office.
</P>
<P>
   Randon Bragdon of Bangor, Maine, offered to fill Sidney Abbott's
cavity in a more antiseptic hospital room, where the doctor said
his chances of contracting HIV from his patient were much less than
they were in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott sued Bragdon, alleging discrimination under the law. The
U.S. District Court in Maine and the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals agreed with the patient. The 1st Circuit now must determine
whether Abbott's HIV presented what the law calls ``a direct threat
to the health or safety'' of Bragdon or his assistants in the
office.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, in a concurring opinion Breyer joined, said the high
court should have taken the additional step and ruled that Bragdon
was not justified in refusing to treat Abbott in the office. The
1st Circuit has already ruled Abbott's HIV presented no direct
threat, Stevens added.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, however,
disagreed with the court's conclusion that reproduction is a major
life activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can deny that reproductive decisions are important in a
person's life,'' Rehnquist wrote. ``But so are decisions as to who
to marry, where to live and how to earn one's living.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief justice said major life activities are those that are
``repetitively performed and essential in the day-to-day existence
of a normally functioning'' person. ``They are thus quite different
from the series of activities leading to the birth of a child,'' he
wrote in a dissent joined by Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate dissent, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor said neither
the law nor federal regulations intended for reproduction to be
considered a major life activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, the act of giving birth to a child, while a very
important part of the lives of many women, is not generally the
same as the representative major life activities of all persons _
`caring for one's self, performing manual tasks, walking, seeing,
hearing, speaking, breathing, learning and working' _ listed in
regulations relevant to the Americans with Disabilities Act of
1990.``
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights supporters and the dentist's attorney hailed the
decision as a victory for their respective positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court unequivocally recognized the right of people
with HIV and other disabilities to full protection from
discrimination,`` said Catherine Hanssens, AIDS project director
for the gay rights group Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund.
``I am heartened the court saw that Congress intended the ADA to
provide such broad protection _ that irrational discrimination
should not be allowed to keep people with HIV from health care and
services.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney John W. McCarthy said he and Bragdon are ``ecstatic''
about the Supreme Court's decision after his client lost in the
lower federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He Bragdon believes he should be able to exercise his
professional judgment'' when treating patients with HIV, McCarthy
added. ``We're going to have another chance to file briefs and
argue the issue all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
