</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAGAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New details emrge at Fagan's arraignment
 &HT;    By John Holland
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Stephen Fagan fled to Florida carting not
just his two confused, ``shell shocked'' daughters, but also a
detailed plan to elude capture and deceive his children,
prosecutors said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Outlining their case at Fagan's arraignment, prosecutors said
Fagan secured false passports for himself and daughters Rachael and
Lisa, then 5 and 2, just days after he kidnapped them during a 1979
custody dispute. Within two weeks he had obtained two phony Social
Security numbers for himself, a driver license and a new identity
as William Stephen Martin, grieving widower, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan picked up the girls for a weekend visit on Oct. 25, 1979,
and never returned them to his ex-wife, Barbara Kurth. Fagan claims
Kurth was an unfit mother, although state investigators and a judge
found the allegations baseless.
</P>
<P>
   Rachael and Wendy strongly support their father and have refused
to be reunited with their mother. Thursday, the girls and Fagan's
fourth wife, Harriet, again stood with him as he pleaded not guilty
to kidnapping and contempt of court charges.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the group stood arm-in-arm before a phalanx of
photographers and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan's life as a fugitive began at the Key West home of Carolyn
Garrison, an old friend from his days as a bartender at one of
Boston's most notorious nightclubs, according to a statement
released by Assistant District Attorney Lynn Reilly. Fagan told
Garrison and the girls that their mother had died, apparently from
a car accident, Garrison testified at a grand jury hearing earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendant arrived (in Key West) with Rachael and Wendy,
who were, as Ms. Garrison describes, shell shocked,'' prosecutors
said in a court document filed Thursday. ``(Fagan) told Ms.
Garrison that the police had found Barbara's car by the side of the
road and they believed her to be dead.''
</P>
<P>
   He then changed Wendy's first name to Lisa. ``When Wendy asked
why, he simply said that it was her middle name and that was what
he intended to call her,'' prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan was arrested on April 16, but under Massachusetts law had
to be arraigned again in Superior Court, where the two felony
counts of kidnapping carry sentences up to 10 years each. He
remains free on $250,000 cash bond, although prosecutors and a
judge added a new stipulation to the bail.
</P>
<P>
   A judge sealed the new bond provision from the public.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, prosecutors tried to show Fagan planned the escape in
advance. They noted that he transferred ownership of his home to
his parents nearly a year before he fled. Then, just a week after
disappearing, they sold it to Boston attorney Richard Egbert.
</P>
<P>
   Egbert now represents Fagan, though he said the sale was just a
``historical coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
