<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-RDP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES UPHOLD DECENCY TEST IN AWARDING ARTS GRANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: SCOTUS-VETO, SCOTUS-AIDS, SCOTUS-STARR,
SCOTUS-VETO-TEXT, SCOTUS-STARR-TEXT) 
(ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(sw) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court upheld a congressional decency
test for awarding federal arts grants on Thursday, but only after a
majority of the justices interpreted the 1990 law as containing
only ``advisory language'' that did not actually prohibit federal
subsidies for indecent art.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the court strongly suggested, in a majority opinion by
Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, that if the law was invoked to impose
``a penalty on disfavored viewpoints,'' it would violate the First
Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 8-1 to uphold the disputed provision, which
requires the National Endowment for the Arts to take into account
``general standards of decency and respect for the diverse beliefs
and values of the American public'' when making grants. But the
court was more divided than the vote indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Two members of the majority, Justices Antonin Scalia and
Clarence Thomas, objected strenuously to their colleagues'
interpretation of the statute as basically toothless. ``The
operation was a success, but the patient died,'' Scalia said of the
majority's work in a separate concurring opinion that took a very
different view of a law.
</P>
<P>
   The law as properly interpreted ``unquestionably constitutes
viewpoint discrimination,'' Scalia wrote, saying there was no
problem with such discrimination in the selective disbursement of
federal subsidies. He added that even an outright ban on federal
financing of indecent art would be constitutional as well.
</P>
<P>
   He said the majority had regrettably upheld the law only by
gutting it. ``The most avid congressional opponents of the
provision could not have asked for more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Only Justice David Souter, in a lone dissenting opinion,
interpreted the provision both as having real force, and as
violating the First Amendment. ``A statute disfavoring speech that
fails to respect Americans' `diverse beliefs and values' is the
very model of viewpoint discrimination,'' Souter said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came in a case originally brought against the
national endowment by the performance artist Karen Finley and three
other non-mainstream artists, who were initially denied grants as
the dispute over financing indecent art was heating up but shortly
before Congress adopted the provision currently at issue.
</P>
<P>
   They then amended their lawsuit, added more plaintiffs, and won
both in the Federal District Court in Los Angeles and the 9th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, in San Francisco. The provision has been
legally unenforceable since 1992 under an injunction that the
ruling on Thursday has the effect of lifting.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, National Endowment for the Arts vs. Finley, No.
97-371, amounted to something of an inconclusive stand-off with an
odd twist: it was the Clinton administration, appealing the lower
court decision and seeking to defend the law, that put forward the
interpretation of a provision with essentially no bite or practical
effect, while the challengers described the law as far-reaching and
constitutionally intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   In the years it took the case to reach the Supreme Court, the
controversy over federal subsidies for indecent art has raged on
and, to some extent, moved on. Congress has slashed the endowment's
budget and has come close to eliminating the agency entirely, while
the endowment itself has basically stopped making grants to
individual artists.
</P>
<P>
   Two relatively small grants in 1989, $30,000 for a retrospective
of sexually explicit photographs by Robert Mapplethorpe and $15,000
to the artist Andres Serrano, who photographed a crucifix immersed
in his own urine and called the work ``Piss Christ,'' ignited the
furor that has never completely died down.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the ruling on Thursday permitted both the
Endowment and House Speaker Newt Gingrich to praise the court and
claim victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the Supreme Court validated the right of the American
people to not pay for art that offends their sensibilities,'' the
speaker said.
</P>
<P>
   William Ivey, chairman of the National Endowment for the Arts,
said the ruling was ``a reaffirmation of the agency's discretion in
funding the highest quality art in America'' and would not affect
``our day-to-day operations.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Justice O'Connor's opinion was joined by Chief Justice William
Rehnquist and by Justices John Paul Stevens, Anthony Kennedy,
Stephen Breyer and Ruth Bader Ginsburg. Justice O'Connor said that
in adopting the requirement that decency be taken into
consideration, Congress imposed ``no categorical requirement'' and
``declined to disallow any particular viewpoints.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not perceive a realistic danger'' that the law will
``compromise First Amendment values,'' she said. But she added,
``If the NEA were to leverage its power to award subsidies on the
basis of subjective criteria into a penalty on disfavored
viewpoints, then we would confront a different case.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM CAN BEGIN HERE)
</P>
<P>
   While the justices disagreed on whether the law imposed
viewpoint discrimination, all nine were in agreement on one point:
that the law was not unconstitutionally vague, as the plaintiffs
had argued and the Ninth Circuit had concluded. While the
provision's ``undeniably opaque'' terms might raise constitutional
questions if they appeared in a criminal statute, O'Connor said,
``when the government is acting as patron rather than as sovereign,
the consequences of imprecision are not constitutionally severe.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the government awarded fellowships on the basis of such
inherently subjective criteria as ``excellence,'' adding that to
strike down the decency provision as vague ``would be to call into
question the constitutionality of these valuable government
programs and countless others like them.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Overshadowed in the court's burst of activity were these other
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Self-Incrimination
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled, 7-2, that the Fifth Amendment does not provide
a right against compelled self-incrimination for a person who fears
prosecution in a foreign country. The decision resolved a split in
the lower federal courts in cases involving suspected wartime Nazi
collaborators who are being investigated by the Justice Department
for possible deportation.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, United States vs. Balsys, No. 97-873, the 2nd U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, in New York, had ruled last year that a
Lithuanian immigrant could refuse to testify in the preliminary
investigation due to his fear that if he were deported to
Lithuania, Israel or Germany, his testimony would be used against
him in criminal prosecutions. In an opinion on Thursday by Souter,
the court overturned that ruling and held that ``concern with
foreign prosecution is beyond the scope of the Self-Incrimination
Clause'' of the Fifth Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Deportation is a civil proceeding, and because the Fifth
Amendment applies only in the criminal context, the immigrant,
Aloyzas Balsys, has no basis for claiming the privilege in the
domestic case. He claims to have been in hiding during the war, but
the government now suspects that he actively participated in
persecuting Jews in Lithuania and that he lied on his application
for a visa to enter the United States in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Souter said the court had to take seriously the government's
view that ``domestic law enforcement would suffer serious
consequences if fear of foreign prosecution were recognized as
sufficient to invoke the privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg and Breyer dissented. ``The basic values which this
court has said underlie the Fifth Amendment's protections are each
diminished if the privilege may not be claimed here,'' Breyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Retroactive Liability
</P>
<P>
   Voting 5-4, the court declared unconstitutional a 1992 law that
required companies that had once been in the coal mining business
to assume retroactive liability for lifetime health benefits for
miners and the survivors and families of miners who had worked for
them decades earlier. The law was enacted to address a crisis in
coal industry health benefits, partly due to the departure of many
companies from the mining business.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, Eastern Enterprises vs. Apfel, No. 97-42, would
have had potentially sweeping constitutional implications had a
majority been able to agree on a rationale for striking down the
Coal Act. But only a plurality of four justices, in an opinion by
O'Connor, found that the law imposed an unconstitutional ``taking''
of the companies' property. The other three were Rehnquist, Scalia
and Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth member of the majority, Kennedy, said the takings
clause of the Fifth Amendment was inapplicable, because only a
general financial liability, and not property, was involved.
Rather, he said, the law violated the companies' right to due
process.
</P>
<P>
   The dissenters, Breyer, Stevens, Souter, and Ginsburg, agreed
that the due process analysis was the correct one, but said there
was no due process violation.
</P>
<P>
   The most unusual opinion _ perhaps of the entire day _ was a
one-paragraph separate concurring opinion by Thomas. He said the
law should be seen as violating the constitutional prohibition
against ex post facto legislation, and called for reconsideration
of a 200-year-old Supreme Court precedent that had limited the ex
post facto clause to criminal laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
