<SLUG> BC-CHINA-GINGRICH-ART-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GINGRICH CLARIFIES GOP STANDS ON TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-SCENE, CHINA-CLINTON, CHINA-DISSIDENTS,
CHINA-PEONY) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton arrived in China, House
Speaker Newt Gingrich suddenly stepped forward Thursday to polish
Republican credentials on an array of international issues, from
trade relations with China to long-stalled financing for the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, a Georgia Republican, promised that Congress would try
again this September to give President Clinton expanded ''fast
track'' trade negotiating authority _ an issue that sharply divides
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only country economically strong enough to keep the world
economy moving forward is the United States,'' Gingrich said. ``The
trick is for us to send a signal that we want a stronger and more
vibrant world market, and that means a strong vote on fast track.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich made his announcement standing with a bipartisan group
of lawmakers from farm states who have come under increasing
pressure from agricultural and business groups on issues affecting
global trade, particularly the economic crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Some corporate leaders complain that Republicans are threatening
American competitiveness by opposing satellite deals with China and
supporting sanctions against countries charged with religious
persecution. The House has also been holding up an $18 billion
contribution to the IMF, which the administration says is needed to
maintain economic stability in Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of discontent, Charles Mack and Bernadette Budde of
the Business-Industry PAC, which makes recommendations to corporate
political action committees, wrote to members in March, ``How
ironic that, after decades of GOP rhetoric pledging fealty to free
enterprise, global competition and less government interference,
business cannot rely on a Republican Congress to advance these
principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's stance Thursday won instant praise from the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce and allowed farm state lawmakers to go home for
the Independence Day recess with promises of action to lift farm
exports. But the speaker's move seemed aimed at seeking partisan
advantage at least as much as resolving the disputes festering in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fast track'' legislation would grant the president the right
to negotiate trade agreements that Congress can approve or reject,
but not amend. In a severe setback for Clinton, such legislation
was pulled from the House floor last November because it failed to
garner enough votes for passage. The opposition was led by House
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., who carried the majority of
House Democrats with him.
</P>
<P>
   Granting such presidential powers over trading agreements is
considered even more difficult to pass in an election year, and the
White House already indicated it would not seek another vote on the
issue before the mid-term elections. By scheduling a vote in
September, the Republicans would split the Democrats at the moment
when they most need Clinton to be campaigning for them in the
midterm election.
</P>
<P>
   Both the White House and Gephardt on Thursday called the
financing of the IMF more pressing than ``fast track.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think from an economic point of view, the financial crisis
in Asia has a much more direct impact on the economic well-being of
Americans and that issue needs to be dealt with first,'' said Joe
Lockhart, a spokesman for Clinton. As for the fast track, Gephardt
called a new debate ``simply irrelevant at this juncture.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gingrich said he thought ``fast track'' legislation could gain
more votes this year because of the Asian crisis and a decline in
farm prices. ``My instinct is that a lot of members who were
wavering last fall now realize that it's very important for us to
pass this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the IMF, Gingrich said he was looking for a bipartisan
agreement, with strings attached. ``We think that it's very, very
important that we have legitimate oversight and legitimate checks
on exactly what the IMF is doing, where it's been successful, and
where it's frankly just caused more problems than it's helped,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted 84-16 in March to provide the IMF with the full
$18 billion sought by the Clinton administration, provided certain
conditions were met by the lender. But the House demanded far
greater changes in the way the agency operates. And last year it
tied IMF financing to an abortion dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich did not indicate Thursday what level of funding he
would support or what conditions the House would impose on the
agency. But he acknowledged that the problems in Asia and Russia
have heightened the need for Congress to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the kind of changes you have in Indonesia, in Russia and
in South Korea, and the potential challenges in Japan, we have an
obligation to work with the International Monetary Fund,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the difficulties Gingrich could face from other
Republicans, however, Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the House Majority
Whip, immediately denounced the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giving the IMF more money is not a panacea for all the
troubles that bedevil the Asian economy,'' he said. ``In fact, in
many instances, the IMF is the problem, not the solution.''
</P>
<P>
   On another issue that Gingrich termed of ``critical
importance,'' the House Ways and Means Committee on Thursday came
out strongly in favor of giving China the normal trade status
accorded most other nations.
</P>
<P>
   The president has called for an annual renewal of such ties,
over objections from critics who cite China's human rights abuses,
its occupation of Tibet, and allegations that China tried to
influence elections in the United States through campaign
donations. To stop Clinton from giving the renewal, Congress would
have to pass a resolution of disapproval. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
