<HEADER>
A7487 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOTORCYCLE-ART-REVIEW     06-25 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTORCYCLE-ART-REVIEW-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: MACHINES AS ART, AND ART AS MACHINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs 6th graf for wording change, 7th graf to correct number of
motorcyles)  (See related story, MOTORCYCLE-ART-FONDA) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One good thing about ``The Art of the Motorcycle,''
opening Friday at the Guggenheim, is that by the time it's over
everyone should finally be sick and tired of jokes about the museum
as a big parking garage ramp.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Lloyd Wright know-it-alls, upon reading this sentence, are
probably already preparing letters to the effect that the
Guggenheim's design originated in a plan of Wright's during the
1920s to build a planetarium encircled by a kind of double-helix
system of ramps, a ziggurat for cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you see,'' these letters will no doubt say, ``the idea of
motorcycles in the Guggenheim is, in fact, a fulfillment . . . ''
Blah, blah, blah.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the record, as far as motorcycles go, I drove a scooter
in Cozumel, Mexico, once, and as a boy I pedaled around Manhattan
on a banana bike, the kind that had the ``Easy Rider'' handlebars _
or in the biker lingo of the Guggenheim's He-man-size exhibition
catalog, ``ape hanger'' handlebars.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and I have visited the Henry Ford Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Having thus firmly established my bona fides, let me make the
following observations:
</P>
<P>
   1. The show, historically speaking, covers the ground between an
1868 French velocipede with a steam engine beneath the seat (ouch!)
and a sleek new MV Agusta. With 113 motorcycles, it is much too
big, but many of the bikes in it really are great to look at, and
you don't have to have a tattoo or know what a single-overhead-cam
valve gear with enclosed rockers is to admire them. I suspect that
men who have been dragged to Monet exhibitions over the years will
seek revenge here, though anyone with design sense will do fine in
it.
</P>
<P>
   2. Frank Gehry's installation of the exhibition, which includes
shiny stainless-steel panels along the rotunda side of Wright's
ramp, miraculously dematerializes the rotunda and suddenly makes
the inside of the museum resemble a machine: an apt metaphor. At
the same time, the panels nod to Gehry's Wright-influenced,
titanium-clad Guggenheim in Bilbao, so the whole effect is a kind
of spiral of allusion.
</P>
<P>
   3. Yes, it is weird to find motorcycles in the Guggenheim, which
has never done anything quite like this before, but American art
museums have always shown objects of design. And anyway, much of
the art in the Metropolitan, never mind the Modern or the
Cooper-Hewitt, originally had a practical purpose, whether it was a
bowl or a chariot. Motorcycles, better than many things, illustrate
technology and taste as they have evolved together in the 20th
century, which is an issue basic to modern art. Looking at one of
the earliest bikes here, an 1893 Millet from France, I thought of
``Ballet Mecanique,'' the machine age film that Leger, Gerald
Murphy, Man Ray and George Antheil made in the 1920s. It made
abstractions out of close-ups of churning engines like the
Millet's.
</P>
<P>
   4. Besides, the Guggenheim under Thomas Krens, to the
consternation of many people, has been stretching in new
directions, which isn't bad. Listed as the main curator for this
show, he has lately been tooling around on a BMW motorcycle, so he
can now officially be regarded as the biker outlaw of museum
directors.
</P>
<P>
   5.. Apropos of BMW, there have been complaints in the press
about the company's sponsorship of ``The Art of the Motorcycle'' _
and one can't help wondering which came first, the idea for the
exhibition or the realization that money would be available for
such a show. The museum is quick to counter that among the bikes on
view, 6 are BMWs, 10 are Harley-Davidsons, 9 are Hondas. OK,
corporate support doesn't necessarily mean corporate noodling in
curatorial decisions. But the true test of any show's credibility
is what it adds to the sum of human knowledge and happiness. Which
brings me to:
</P>
<P>
   6. The catalog, a curious document. Clearly it wants to be
scholarly. One essay informs us that: ``Neither writing nor riding
is possible without a certain violence. As the writer inscribes
paper with ink and words, so the motorcyclist cuts a line through
sheer space using angles and velocity as letters and punctuation.''
</P>
<P>
   And: ``The pipes are to the motorcyclist's identity what the
unconscious is to the Freudian subject: a large inaccessible
reservoir of feeling and meaning, which is a remainder of a
collective spirit. In both cases, one must listen at least twice
for the significance of the utterances.''
</P>
<P>
   At least.
</P>
<P>
   As for the catalog entries on each bike, some are good, some are
like this: ``The geared primary drive and multi-plate clutch, which
were on the left side, transmitted power to a four-speed gearbox.
The full-circle crankshaft featured a roller big-end bearing, with
a bronze small end bush. Lubrication was wet-sump, with a gear-type
oil pump.''
</P>
<P>
   I can only assume that this makes sense to mechanics and,
perhaps, sexologists.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the photographs are cool.
</P>
<P>
   So we take this show seriously at a certain peril, which is
fitting because motorcycles are frivolous to begin with: they're
about irresponsibility, about not conforming, about getting away.
Or at least they're about embracing the image of nonconformity.
Motorcyclists are also famous for riding in packs and dressing
alike. Every society has its rules, even Hell's Angels.
</P>
<P>
   That's just one cultural cliche motorcycles neatly reflect. An
early American bike, the bright orange and white 1911 Flying
Merkel, summons to mind tinted postcard images of barber shop
quartets, brass bands and summer fairs. I picture a snake-oil
salesman, in boater hat and high collar, riding one. The huge 1948
Indian Chief, the apex of mid-century kitsch (pinstripes, decals,
big red swooping fenders), in the same way encapsulates America's
extravagant postwar spirit. It's the motorcycle equivalent of the
Fontainebleau Hotel in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   For another reason I like British bikes. They tend to be black
and practical, with sturdy engines and no frills, and, so I'm told,
they're a pain to kick-start. They evoke the ethos of tinned food
and vast unheated manor houses. Take the 1926 Brough Superior
SS100, massive and not obviously beautiful but very elegant on its
own terms. (It's T.E. Lawrence's bike.) Likewise, the classic 1939
Triumph seems to embody pragmatism on two wheels.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition has sales brochures and magazine ads to
illustrate the marketing of bikes in different countries to suit
diverse tastes. In the early 60s, for instance, Japanese companies,
in the wake of similar efforts by British manufacturers like
Triumph and American makers like Harley-Davidson, made a mark with
bikes geared to a growing affluent populace of anti-outlaws.
</P>
<P>
   Honda's ads showed clean-cut families with efficient little
vehicles like the Super Cub. The company's famous slogan was ``You
meet the nicest people on a Honda.'' Then it became ``The new
American motorcycle gang.'' The standard view of Japan is that it
has always adapted other cultures, then often surpassed them.
That's what you see here in later years, as well, when Japanese
manufacturers mimicked stripped-down American muscle bikes of the
'70s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   These muscle bikes are ugly, but that's the point, I suppose.
Esthetically, I prefer a stylish eccentric like the streamlined
1930 French Majestic 350, canary yellow and blue, the engine and
wheels wrapped in bullet-shaped fairing with vents on the sides.
Tres chic. Even when the French tried to imitate American swagger
they remained French. The 1933 Dollar is a tough, compact bike with
an Indian-head gas cap and decal, but the Jaeger clock with its
dandyish Roman numerals is a Gallic giveaway.
</P>
<P>
   I must mention the show-stopper, a 1925 Boehmerland, a Czech
novelty resembling a circus prop. Red and yellow, it has a wooden
sidecar in the shape of a rocket and is bigger than many
automobiles. The museum label says the bike carries six people.
That seems like a small exaggeration. Six clowns maybe.
</P>
<P>
   In the end the Italians, naturally, make the really
memorable-looking motorcycles. Check out the enveloping shape of
the 1958 Aermacchi Chimera; the surreal 1995 Aprilia Moto 6.5,
designed by Philippe Starck, which resembles a wasp, and the MV
Agusta F4, whose frame and exposed machinery can bring to mind the
body of a sleek swimmer. These are truly beautiful objects.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the Vespa. Sophia Loren. The Via Veneto.
``Roman Holiday.'' ``La Dolce Vita,'' and that unmistakable drone
of the Vespa's engine, like a throaty laugh. I recall the famous
1953 photograph by Mario De Biasi of a woman striding toward a
group of goggle-eyed Italian men. The man nearest to her sits on
(what else?) a Vespa.
</P>
<P>
   To anyone who really knows motorcycles, it's probably one of the
least exciting bikes in the show. But I don't care. It's the one I
want.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Art of the Motorcycle'' remains at the Guggenheim Museum,
Fifth Avenue at 898th Street, through Sept. 20. ``The Motorcycle on
Screen,'' a program of about 40 films and videos, begins Friday and
runs through July 31. Screenings in the museum's theater are on
Wednesdays at 2:30 and 6 p.m. and on Fridays and Saturdays at 2:30
and 7:30 p.m. Tickets are free with admission to the museum.
Screening information: (212) 360-4321. On Tuesday at 7 p.m., Dennis
Hopper will discuss the making of the film ``Easy Rider.''
Admission: $15; $10 for students and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, which is sponsored by BMW, moves in November to
the Field Museum of Natural History in Chicago, and in the fall of
1999, to the Guggenheim in Bilbao, Spain.
</P>
</TEXT>
