<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7489 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-TCI-NYT &LR;      06-25 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-TCI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: REGIONAL BELLS SEE BENEFITS IN AT&AMP;T-TCI DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After AT&AMP;T said Wednesday that it had agreed to acquire
Tele-Communications Inc. for $31.8 billion, the stock of the five
regional Bell telephone companies dropped by almost 4 percent on
average, shaving about $11 billion from their combined market
value.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, the thinking went, had lessened its need to use the Bells'
networks to reach local customers. By linking to consumers through
TCI's extensive cable television system, which reaches 10.5 million
homes, AT&AMP;T could reduce the amount it pays the Bells to begin and
end long-distance calls, while building a platform to offer local
phone service and high-speed access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Bells' reaction Thursday: good riddance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who had the bigger celebration _ them or us,''
said James Ellis, general counsel of SBC Communications Inc., which
groups Southwestern Bell and Pacific Telesis.
</P>
<P>
   In the long-running battle between the Bells and the nation's
big long-distance companies, spin tactics have become almost as
valuable as a powerful friend in Washington. But the Bells on
Thursday seemed genuine in welcoming the deal, or at least in
declining to condemn it. The Bells think that AT&AMP;T's acquisition of
TCI can ultimately help them reach their pot of gold at the end of
the optical fiber: the $80 billion long-distance market. They may
be right.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly in the direction that the FCC wanted,'' said
Stephanie Comfort, chief telecommunications analyst for Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter. ``As the alternative pipe becomes available,
that helps the Bells.''
</P>
<P>
   The Telecommunications Act of 1996 said the Bells would be
allowed to sell long-distance service only after convincing
regulators that they had opened their local networks to potential
competitors. The act carried a checklist of technical requirements
the Bells must meet before winning long-distance approval.
</P>
<P>
   No Bell has yet won that approval, in part because AT&AMP;T, MCI
Communications and other big long-distance companies have
vigorously maintained that they have been kept out of local markets
by recalcitrant Bells. The Bells have generally said that their
networks are open but that AT&AMP;T and MCI are dragging their heels in
order to protect their long-distance businesses.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T chairman C. Michael Armstrong had a strong case Wednesday
when he said that argument ought to be laid to rest. But by doing
that, he may also given the Bells a boost in their quest for
long-distance glory.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to concerns that local markets are not open to
competition, Bell Atlantic Corp. chief executive Ivan Seidenberg
said Thursday, ``This puts a fire under everyone suggesting those
concerns should come down fast now that King Kong and Godzilla just
got together.''
</P>
<P>
   Sid Boren, BellSouth Corp.'s executive vice president for
planning, development and administration, said, ``It gives us
leverage to use on the long-distance applications.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This returns the telecom act to where everyone thought it
would be in 1996,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Bells believe that the presence of competition from a
cable-based phone system would be a huge factor in their favor when
they petition the Federal Communications Commission for permission
to sell long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, which advises the FCC on the petitions,
has said that it will recommend approval only for Bells that
demonstrate that their markets are ``irreversibly open'' to
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The concern has been that after allowing a competitor to gain a
local foothold using a Bell network (and winning entry to the
long-distance market), the Bell could backslide and unfairly
eliminate the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Boren said AT&AMP;T's deployment of a cable-based phone system would
not depend on the Bells in a major way and so any offering of
service using a cable system could fairly be deemed irreversible
and not vulnerable to potential Bell ``backsliding''.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Bells which, during drafting of the
telecommunications act, argued against a strict market test for
determining when they could sell long-distance service. The
long-distance companies floated plans that would have allowed the
Bells to sell long-distance service once they had lost a certain
percentage of their local markets, regardless of the state of the
Bells' networks.
</P>
<P>
   The Bells refused. And so the checklist of conditions was put in
place. AT&AMP;T argues that the Bells still have to meet the checklist
before getting into the long-distance market, even if AT&AMP;T is
making inroads in the market.
</P>
<P>
   A high-ranking FCC official agreed with AT&AMP;T in principle. The
official indicated, however, that in areas where AT&AMP;T offered
service through cable TV wires, local Bells would not have to meet
as rigorous a test.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the market is looking competitive, and there's real
facilities to bypass the Bell company network, then it just sort of
changes the way you look at the item,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   That is just what the Bells are counting on.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T has always said we need an industrial-strength OSS
system,'' said Mark Roellig, U S West's executive vice president
for pubic policy, human resources and law, referring to one of the
systems that would allow other companies to link to a Bell's
network. By working through TCI's system, Roellig said, ``They
clearly don't need industrial strength OSS because they will be
proving most of the services over their own network.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest hurdle between the Bells and the
long-distance market over the next few years could be AT&AMP;T's
stumbles in upgrading TCI's cable networks to offer widespread
phone and data service. AT&AMP;T has not offered any technical details
of its plans and has not said how much it intends to spend to make
new services available.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rosenblum, AT&AMP;T's vice president for law and public policy,
said the Bells ought to be let into the long-distance arena when
there is widespread competition for local service. But he added
that that day may not be near and said the Bells were jumping the
gun in using the merger announcement as a platform to press for
quicker long-distance approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're offering a lot of good things to give people choice,''
he said. ``But it is going to take a while for those good things to
actually hit the ground for consumers. What the Bell companies
continue to do is confuse plans and realities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
