<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-SCHOOLS-ART-580(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON MULLS RETURN TO SCHOOL PLAN THAT IGNITED BUSING CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``Neighborhood schools'' is a fraught, to some even
frightening, phrase here.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a quarter-century ago, it was the rallying slogan of
those who opposed forced busing to achieve school integration;
today, it can still conjure up images of angry protesters and
nightstick-swinging police officers in the white enclaves of
Charlestown and South Boston, of saucer-eyed children watching
adult violence from their school-bus windows.
</P>
<P>
   For all that historical baggage, however, the Boston School
Committee on Wednesday night is scheduled to take up the issue of
whether to move back toward neighborhood schools, reopening the old
debate despite any trepidation because, backers of the proposal
say, it simply seems time. The court-decreed busing ended more than
a decade ago, but the system that replaced it has kept many
children from attending the school nearest their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The basic issue sounds much the same as 25 years ago, but the
city and its school system have changed tremendously _ from a
public-school population that was nearly 60 percent white to one
that is nearly 85 percent minority; from largely segregated black
and white neighborhoods to more melanges of black, white, Hispanic
and Asian areas; from an explosive focus on race to more of a focus
on basic quality in the perennially troubled Boston schools.
</P>
<P>
   Along with those changes, political pressure from advocates of
neighborhood schools has mounted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's at the point where you can't ignore it anymore,'' said
Peggy Davis-Mullen, a member of the Boston City Council who has
been pushing for neighborhood schools for nearly a decade and
almost got the issue put on the city ballot last year. ``It was a
taboo thing to talk about; politically, people were just terrified
and would not talk about it, and I think that people have seen that
you can survive and make this political argument _ it doesn't mean
you're a racist.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan to be discussed at the Wednesday meeting, still
tentative in its particulars and not likely to be voted on for
months, is actually called not ``neighborhood schools'' but a
``cluster model,'' and it would offer only a partial return to the
pre-busing system in which students mainly went to the schools
nearest their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed plan would divide the city into 10 geographical
clusters, and students would generally attend schools within their
cluster. They would choose from a narrower array of schools than
now, but have a greater guarantee of being able to attend a school
near home.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Schools Superintendent Thomas Payzant is presenting the
plan in response to a school committee study group's
recommendations. Payzant said he was withholding judgment on it
until he could determine how it would play out, and whether it
would keep schools racially as diverse as now.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the plan offers some promise, the superintendent said,
including the prospect that it would cut students' traveling time
to school and some of the transportation costs that now take up $42
million in the school system's total annual budget of $547 million.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he thought issues of race would hamper the
plan, Payzant said, ``I really don't think it will be the major
question.'' Rather, he said he expected the debate to pit advocates
of maximum school choice who do not want their children's options
limited against advocates of neighborhood schools who value
proximity.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But others, including integration experts and some parents, say
they still worry about the potential rise in racial tensions and
the possibility that the city's 63,000 public school pupils will
become resegregated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston students have been going to school peacefully as far as
race is concerned for a decade,'' said Charles Willie, the Harvard
urban sociologist and school integration specialist who helped
design the school assignment system now in place, ``and there's a
question, Why return to what was a source of a great deal of strife
in the past?''
</P>
<P>
   Boston's court-ordered busing system, the forced desegregation
that spawned such conflict in the 1970s that the city became a
symbol of Northern urban racism, began when a U.S. District Court
ruled that the schools had been intentionally segregated. Students
were bused so that the enrollment in each school would more closely
reflect the racial makeup of the city.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the schools were deemed sufficiently integrated to to
allow the court-ordered busing system to be ended. In 1989, it was
replaced by a system called ``controlled choice,'' in which the
city was divided into three big zones and students were allowed to
choose among about 27 schools in their zone, as long as all the
schools remained well-integrated. The cluster plan would reduce
that choice to 7 to 10 schools.
</P>
<P>
   Race may not be a central focus of the new plan, but it already
permeates the emerging debate.
</P>
<P>
   There is, for example, the plan's greatest practical rub: Among
the things that have changed over the last 25 years, one is that
scores of Boston schools have been closed or converted into housing
complexes for the elderly or offices, reducing the total to 128
from 208. And the closed schools have tended to be in predominantly
poor and minority areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm against it only in that there are neighborhoods that do
not have schools,'' said Hattie McKinnis, executive director of the
Citywide Parents Council, which is an advocate for parents in the
school system, ``and that's basically in communities of color _
Roxbury, Mattapan and Dorchester _ so it would be unfair. It means
these kids will constantly be getting on a bus to go to somebody
else's school.''
</P>
<P>
   The cluster plan appears politically unstoppable, Ms. McKinnis
said, adding that she hoped the city would not fall back into its
old habits of shortchanging minority children.
</P>
<P>
   There is also what some see as the racially tilted side-agenda
of the cluster plan: To lure back into the school system the
whites, and in general the working and middle classes of all races,
who have fled it in such prodigious numbers. The city over all is
still almost 60 percent white; but half its white students _ and
one-quarter its black students _ go to parochial or other private
schools.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is there aren't enough white kids in the
Boston public school system anymore to have any kind of racial
balance,'' said James Kelly, president of the Boston City Council,
who believes the cluster model does not go far enough toward
neighborhood schools.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of neighborhood schools argue that white students are
bused to distant schools disproportionately to fill racial quotas.
Many minority students are also bussed to distant schools attended
mainly by other poor minority students to fill seats when, cluster
proponents say, they would be better off staying in schools nearer
their homes, where it is easier to attend after-school programs.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities in similar situations have been moving away from
busing to end segregation as court orders have expired, prompting
concerns from some scholars of integration that some schools are
becoming resegregated.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, a federal judge accepted an agreement for Indianapolis
to phase out the city's 1981 court-ordered desegregation plan,
which involved the busing of several thousand black students to
schools in the city's suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, parents appear split on the cluster proposal. Some
said they preferred the option of choosing among more schools and
seeing their children bused rather than walking city streets to
schools nearer home; others, like Estelle Reason, who was picking
up her granddaughter, Chandra, at a Roxbury school the other day,
said she thought that children should stay close to home and that
busing money be plowed directly into education instead.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Reason, who is black, remembers being forced to send her son
to school in all-white Charlestown at the height of the busing
tension. ``That put me in bed for a week,'' she said. ``I had to go
up on the school bus with my kids. They were fighting and fighting;
they were just looking to fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
