A7495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGS-AD-COLUMN-NYT     06-25 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: TWO MAGAZINES TRYING UNCONVENTIONAL SUPPLEMENTS
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two magazines are supplementing their appeals to
readers and advertisers with unconventional supplements that are
appearing in issues now coming out.
</P>
<P>
   Out magazine teamed up with the Seagram Americas unit of the
Seagram Co. for an advertising supplement, called Out to Party,
that promotes summer entertaining as it sells seven Seagram liquor
brands like Chivas Regal Scotch whisky and Captain Morgan's rums.
And Wallpaper magazine published its first editorial supplement
ever, called the Stockholm Design Guide, which is all Sweden all
the time, from the subjects of the articles to the advertisers to
even the paper stock.
</P>
<P>
   The projects have more in common than sharing Absolut vodka as
an advertiser; Out's because Seagram imports the brand and
Wallpaper's because the distiller, Vin &AMP; Sprit AB, is Swedish. They
are both emblematic of the ambitious efforts by print media to find
nontraditional ways to attract and keep advertisers as competition
for marketers' dollars intensifies. The ferocity of that battle was
underscored in recent days with the closings of magazines including
Inside Sports, Financial World and Living Fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most magazines haven't asked themselves a fundamental
question: `What business am I in?''' said Arthur Shapiro, executive
vice president for marketing at Seagram Americas in New York.
``They're not in the business of selling ad space, but of building
relationships with advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a handful are good at doing that,'' he added, ``but it's
incumbent upon them to market themselves, to come to us and say,
`Hey, I've got an idea for you,' because print is very cluttered.
Unless I can cut through the clutter, I'm not going to meet our
needs for brand development.''
</P>
<P>
   Seagram is the principal sponsor of the 32-page guide, which has
nine ad pages and a ``Brought to you by'' credit on the cover.
Other advertisers include Levi Strauss &AMP; Co., for Dockers khakis,
and Rhino Records, for a ``party pack'' of soul music compact
disks.
</P>
<P>
   The guide may be the first Seagram magazine insert that
advertises multiple brands, Shapiro said; while the recipes feature
Seagram brands by name, there are also some drinks with ingredients
not sold by Seagram like Triple Sec.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to spend money to say, `Hey, instead of Captain
Morgan's, use Bacardi,''' Shapiro said, laughing, ``but it does go
beyond our brands.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad supplement appears in the July issue of Out, which is the
first to be revamped by the magazine's new editor in chief, James
Collard. In addition to 140,000 copies bound into the issue,
260,000 copies are to be distributed at Gay Pride events, including
those this weekend in New York; at bars, clubs and restaurants in
20 large markets, and as an insert in the Tzabaco catalog, which
sells merchandise aimed at gay men and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was more planned out than D-Day,'' said Louis M.
Fabrizio, publisher at Out in New York, a unit of Out Publishing
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the idea in October 1996 and discussed it with another
company, but it never really got off the ground,'' he added.
``There are a million reasons why people can't do something, but
I've never heard them from Seagram.''
</P>
<P>
   The guide is among several alternative ad vehicles offered by
Out. For instance, the magazine runs a corporate image advertising
feature, called Companies That Care, in which marketers purchased
space to promote their diversity policies. Sponsors have included
the Eastman Kodak Co., Gap Inc., Honeywell Inc. and the Prudential
Insurance Co. of America.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the Wallpaper project, the Stockholm editorial
supplement, which runs 68 pages, is being bundled with the
magazine's first single-theme issue, titled ``Wanderlust 1998'' and
focusing on worldwide travel.
</P>
<P>
   The supplement covers ``all the fields that fit into the realm
of Wallpaper,'' said Tyler Brule, editorial director of Wallpaper
in London, a youthful life-style magazine owned by the Time Life
Entertainment Group Ltd. unit of Time Warner Inc. ``And it allows
us to attract a number of advertisers who normally wouldn't come
into our book.''
</P>
<P>
   There are articles on Swedish design, architecture, fashion,
media, shopping and reklam nyheter (ad agency news), including
brief reports about shops like Lowe Brindfors, part of the Lowe
Group unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies, and two Omnicom
Group units, TBWA Sweden, part of TBWA Worldwide, and Paradiset
DDB, part of DDB Needham Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we wanted to say is that Wallpaper, a magazine based in
London with an American parent, is a global magazine sold in almost
50 countries, and Stockholm, the 1998 European capital of culture,
is a great place to start,'' Brule said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were moments,'' he added, ``when I thought: `What have I
got myself into? It can't be Danish, Norwegian or Finnish; it has
to be Swedish.' But we're getting all these fantastic mentions in
Swedish papers _ not that I can read any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Three organizations accounted for about half the 23 ad pages in
the supplement: Food from Sweden, the Stockholm Information Service
Convention and Visitors Bureau, and the Swedish Travel and Tourism
Council. In addition to Vin &AMP; Sprit, the Absolut distiller, which
took the back cover, advertisers include Ericsson AB, Victor
Hasselblad, Orrefors and Saab, jointly owned by Investor AB and the
General Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agency scene is so hot in Stockholm, it's such a great
advertising town that people pulled out the stops for us,'' Brule
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wallpaper printed almost 200,000 copies of the supplement, which
is the magazine's regular press run. In addition to distribution
with newsstand and subscription copies of Wallpaper, the supplement
is to be available in most airport lounges of SAS, the Scandinavian
airline.
</P>
<P>
   For the next supplement, ``I'd like to look at North America,''
Brule said. ``Much as I would love to do my home country of Canada,
it will probably be about somewhere in the United States.''
</P>
</TEXT>
