<HEADER>
A7497 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC--ROBERTSON-HNS &LR;      06-25 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC--ROBERTSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rich get richer; &QL; 
poor head home
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NANTES, France _ Things are normal. It remains a petit monde as far
as the current coupe thereof is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, 162 teams sought spots in France's World Cup
'98. Every continent except Antarctica, where the penguins are
still soccer-ignorant, would send its best to the planet's biggest
sporting fete. But with futbol's Sweet 16 almost set, it's pretty
clear the balance of power hasn't shifted in the 68-year history of
the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Every champion has come from Europe or South America. And
whatever happens today in Lens, where England and Colombia go to
war _ perhaps literally in the streets outside the stadium _ to lay
claim to the final spot in the knockout round of the tournament,
the two land masses will account for seven-eighths of the elite
field.
</P>
<P>
   Asia was shut out. North America and Africa, in turn, will be
represented by the lonely interlopers from Mexico and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   And the former barely survived. Somehow, Mexico's hombres dug
deeply enough to forge a dramatic late tie against the Netherlands
on Thursday, good enough to obtain a second-round place, with help
from a Belgian draw with South Korea. But you can't take Mexico's
chances to make it to the Stade de France in Saint-Denis on July 12
too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Their compadres north of the Rio Grande did them no favors.
Because of the hapless Americans' 1-0 defeat at Yugoslavia's hands,
Mexico must confront Germany, Cup holders in 1990 and '98's most
hardened entry.
</P>
<P>
   Europe, South America rule
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria? The Lions have the athletes and the wiliest of coaches
in Bora Milutinovic, a mercenary Serb who took the Americans into
the second round in 1994 and might be able to keep the
temperamental Nigerians tugging on the same rope, but they haven't
escaped sleeper's status in a draw that tilts ponderously toward
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Like always.
</P>
<P>
   If England, the birthplace of soccer, pulls through with a win
or a tie, 10 European nations will be alive and, of course, kicking
when the second round begins Saturday. Of the major Western powers,
only the doggedly disappointing Spanish team will be conspicuously
absent. A Colombia victory, in turn, would give South America a
fifth entry.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, a team in dire trouble until virtually the final touch
of the afternoon in Paris' Parc de Princes Stadium, ousted Belgium
and defended our continent's honor, although the U.S. team's
modestly redemptive showing in the inconsequential loss here
against Yugoslavia saved an additional measure of face for us
out-of-the-loop Norte Americanos.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Matador,'' Luis Hernandez, got his bull when he beat the
Dutch goalkeeper in the fifth minute of second-half injury time,
snatching a second consecutive 2-2 tie from the teeth of
you-know-what. The Mexicans had penned the same improbable
0-2-to-2-2 script against the Belgians in their previous game.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, meanwhile, showed up in the quaint old Loire
River port town shattered by the 2-1 defeat to Iran in Lyon on
Sunday night. Many had 6 a.m. flights booked to the United States
today. They couldn't escape coach Steve Sampson or each other
quickly enough. The bickering and blame-placing had become nasty.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. team nearly disgraced
</P>
<P>
   If ever a result appeared destined to be ugly, it was this one,
particularly because the Yugos had the incentive of improving their
second-round draw by overtaking Germany in the Group F standings
with a gob of goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans showed a modicum of pride, though, if little else.
They rewarded their boisterous fans, who turned out in respectable
numbers, bedecked in the obligatory flags and face paint _ one guy
made himself up to be the Statue of Liberty _ with a frantic
defensive effort despite the irrelevancy of the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Sampson's Oh-Fers will leave France having scored
just one goal in 4{-plus hours of competition. When Preki
Radosavljevic's free kick sailed high over the net in the 86th
minute Thursday night, it ensured another shutout.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 32 teams in France, only Tunisia and Japan have
mounted more feeble offensive showings. But both have games today
to try to throw off their goose eggs. The Americans' gander is
cooked, its liver sacrificed to the foie gras trade.
</P>
<P>
   Where the U.S. program goes from here is anyone's guess, but you
suspect that until NBA point guards, NFL cornerbacks and
major-league shortstops are dragged off to a soccer gulag, our
entry shall remain a World Cup nonentity into the foreseeable
future.
</P>
<P>
   But we have Mexico to embrace. They're neighbors, so why not?
</P>
<P>
   Ol!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
