<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LEITER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL INCENTIVE FOR LEITER AGAINST THE TEAM THAT TRADED HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also BBO-NY-YANKS-METS)  
 (JT)  
 By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Al Leiter walks out to the mound at Shea Stadium
Friday night in the emotionally charged atmosphere of a house
packed with Mets and Yankee fans, he will be excited as ever.
</P>
<P>
   But not because of some personal vendetta Leiter has against the
Yankees, the team that traded him to the Toronto Blue Jays nine
years ago after a 162-pitch outing in damp weather that Leiter
believes contributed to his ensuing arm trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old left-hander simply gets pumped up every time he
takes the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to stick it to every team I pitch against, not just the
Yankees,'' said Leiter, who will bring an earned-run average of
1.60, the best in the major leagues, into Friday night's opener of
this much-anticipated three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   If this were 1989, or even some time in the early 1990s, Leiter
admitted, he might feel a little differently.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Toms River, N.J., Leiter was touted as the next Ron
Guidry or Dave Righetti when he made his major league debut in
Yankee pinstripes in 1987 as a skinny 21-year-old kid who was prone
to blisters on his pitching hand. Since then, he has been through
so much that he has put behind him that cold spring evening in 1989
when Dallas Green, the Yankee manager then, left him out for 162
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   After one more start as a Yankee, Leiter was dealt to the Blue
Jays for Jesse Barfield. After another start, Leiter began to
develop the arm troubles that derailed his career for the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``I could say, `I shouldn't have stayed in that game. I
should have mentioned something to the pitching coach.' But I
really try to base my life on right now, today. And I think I've
always been that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then Leiter has won three World Series rings: two with the
Blue Jays, one last season with the Florida Marlins, when he
started Game 7 and gave his team a chance to win _ which it did in
extra innings. He has pitched a no-hitter. He has pitched in an
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   His redemption extends beyond the baseball field, too. Leiter
has also watched his older brother, Mark, recover from the
devastating tragedy of losing an infant son in the spring of 1994
to resurrect his career as the Phillies' current closer at the age
of 35. It was Al Leiter who helped resuscitate his older brother's
career when he persuaded the Yankees to take a look at Mark and
give him his second chance in baseball after Mark, too, had arm
troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``By all rights, he's lucky to be playing,'' said the younger
brother. ``And here he is having a career year.''
</P>
<P>
   They both are. Leiter not only leads the majors in ERA, but he
takes a 9-3 record and a six-game winning streak into Friday
night's game.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Leiter has faced the Yankees nine times in his career.
And he has more than a little mixed emotions about the storied
organization that he began his career with and that he will face
again Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so far removed from my initial signing with that
team,'' Leiter said. ``It's a bit more of a job to me now. I look
at it like a professional. I don't feel like they dissed me or like
it was any kind of raw deal. If anything, I don't feel like I did
as well as you are supposed to do as a Yankee.''
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed the pressure that will inevitably be present when
he takes the mound against the best team in baseball in such a
highly visible game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting a game, Friday night against the Yankees and I'm
going to be as excited as hell,'' he said. ``If there was pressure,
there's no more pressure than to start Game 7 of the World Series.
Here I was, a guy who really didn't have a good year. Our ace
pitched Game 6 and lost. And three-quarters of the media and fans
were thinking we had no chance because I was pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a game in mid-season against a very good team. And
then you bring in what my brother's been through, come on. It's a
baseball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter's future with the Mets is uncertain. Obtained by the Mets
during the Marlins' offseason dismantling, Leiter is in the final
year of a 3-year, $8.6 million contract that will pay him $3
million this season. His representatives, Alan and Randy Hendricks,
are in New York through the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a team really wants a player, don't let him go through the
free agent market,'' Leiter said. He recalled what he told the Blue
Jays: `` `Had you guys come to me in August, I would have signed
with you guys.' I went from a first-time ever free agent making
$900,000 to teams offering me $3 million. I would have signed for
less in August.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Mets, Leiter said: ``I don't know what they're
thinking. I would like for it to work here. You just never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter has major league pitches, that was never an issue. But
until this season he had never really harnessed his control, not
even in 1996, when he went 16-12 with a 2.93 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   A knee injury dogged Leiter all of last season. But after that
Game 7, when he decided to use other pitches and all of the plate,
Leiter has blossomed into a complete pitcher and not just a
thrower. He will almost certainly be named to his second All-Star
Game in less than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I could think of what could of been,'' said Leiter,
when asked if he ever looks back to the years of arm trouble and
when he sometimes could not find home plate. ``But the two most
wasted emotions are regret and worry. Neither deals with the
present moment.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
