<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TRUMPETS-470&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHEN TRUMPETS FADE': A SOLDIER STUCK IN COMBAT AND A TIME WARP 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The years since 1944 intrude too heavily on the attitude and
even the language of ``When Trumpets Fade,'' an otherwise
impressive World War II movie that premieres Saturday on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the first hint that something is chronologically amiss is
the use of ``Over There,'' a popular World War I song, in the
opening credits. Then comes the film itself, with an emotional
center of gravity that seems to lie somewhere between Korea and
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Director John Irvin (``Hamburger Hill'') and screenwriter W.W.
Vought use the film to convey a sense that battles are bloodily
futile exercises to be survived rather than fought. Then they mix
in the irony _ the god of war applies no rational method to the
grim task of choosing corpses.
</P>
<P>
   These themes aren't unknown to World War II, but they're far
more common to Vietnam or, for that matter, the peculiar horrors in
the Great War of 1914 to 1918.
</P>
<P>
   So Pvt. Manning (Ron Eldard) of the U.S. Army seems a little out
of place in the mud and underbrush of the Hurtgen Forest, bordering
Belgium and Germany, late in 1944. He's a guy who just wants to
keep a low profile and live another day amidst the madness.
</P>
<P>
   Vought's story _ it's fictional, though the Battle of Hurtgen
Forest was a real prelude to the Battle of the Bulge _ has other
things in store for Manning.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its shaky moorings, the movie keeps getting better as
Manning's knack for survival wins him two unwanted promotions, up
to lieutenant, in three days.
</P>
<P>
   Eldard, whose own survival skills got him past ``Men Behaving
Badly,'' is stunningly good as a jaded, battle-hardened soldier who
just wants out but instead finds himself mired deeper and deeper in
what one of his comrades calls ``the death factory.''
</P>
<P>
   Pvt. Manning is essentially a victim of his own competence. His
superiors are forever increasing the odds against him as they
persist in sending him back into the damp forest to face German
tanks and 88 mm guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Trumpets Fade'' re-creates the deadly chaos of pitched
battle as well as, and possibly better than, anything ever produced
for the television screen.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers who adore pyrotechnics in their war movies _ hey, guys!
_ won't feel shortchanged. The tanks, guns and troops, by the way,
are mostly Hungarian. The production was filmed in Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   The film is also unusually suspenseful. When Eldard leads a
patrol of terrified reinforcements into the woods behind the German
line, the dense fog, wind and snapping twigs might catch you with
your eyes wide and your breath short.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're squeamish about foul language, ``When Trumpets
Fade'' could leave you sputtering with rage. There's barely a
phylum or genus of profanity that isn't bandied here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   _ Which is no way to bring us to Mary Tyler Moore, the host of
``Three Cats From Miami ... and Other Pet Practitioners,'' showing
Sunday on the very same HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Taped in Atlanta, the thing is an unabashedly schmaltzy awards
show for animals. More exactly, for animals that perform some sort
of therapeutic job for their human friends.
</P>
<P>
   Among the winners are Dusty, a rabbit who sits still while
juvenile burn victims pet him; Frosty, a horse used to give rides
to disabled children, and Buster, Flame and Flashback, the three
Miami cats that are regular visitors to a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   Moore (``In my long career in show business, I've been asked to
do many things, but ...'') appears a tad nervous but comes through
gamely (excuse the word) as she adorns the animals' necks with
ribbons and medals. The barks of approval are from the studio
audience, where dogs lounge in the aisles and occupy several seats.
</P>
<P>
   You could look at it this way: There isn't a single lengthy
acceptance speech, and Harley D. Swine, a potbellied pig, doesn't
squeal, ``You like me! You really like me!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
