<SLUG> BC-IRS-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES BILL TO REVAMP TAX COLLECTION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Mo.)   (ja) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By a resounding majority, the House Thursday
approved a compromise bill to revamp the Internal Revenue Service,
moving the country one step closer to the biggest make-over of its
tax collection system in nearly 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Voting 402-8, the House accepted legislation worked out by
House-Senate negotiators that would lead to an internal
reorganization of the IRS, create an independent board to oversee
its operations and give taxpayers more rights and powers in
disputes with the tax agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about putting the taxpayer first and the IRS second,''
said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who heads the House Ways and Means
Committee. ``It's been the other way around for too long.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to pass the measure after it returns from
its July Fourth recess. President Clinton has said he will sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Although the measure rolled through the House, there was some
grumbling about a provision tacked on near the end of negotiations
between the House and Senate that gives those who sell stocks or
other property a break on their capital gains taxes. Under that
provision, the time an asset must be held for its profits to
quality for a low, 20 percent tax rate would be reduced to 12
months from the current 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   The change in capital gains taxes was condemned by Rep. Dick
Gephardt of Missouri, the House minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that some in the majority in this House can't resist
any opportunity to try to put a tax break in tax legislation for
the wealthiest of the wealthy,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   But though he criticized the new provision on capital gains,
Gephardt, along with virtually all of his Democratic troops, voted
for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Archer said Thursday that the bill would create 74 new rights
for taxpayers, but some experts say that bill would have minimum
impact on the vast majority of taxpayers who never run afoul of the
IRS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us don't have (a) fight with the IRS,'' Clinton
Stretch of Deloitte &AMP; Touche said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, the burden of proof would shift from the
taxpayer to the government in civil court tax cases as long as the
taxpayer met certain threshold requirements, like maintaining good
records. Another provision would protect ``innocent spouses'' _
generally divorced or separated women _ from being liable for taxes
owed by their former partners. Under the provision, such spouses
would owe taxes only on their portion of the joint income.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also suspend interest and some penalties on
recalcitrant taxpayers if the IRS failed to notify the taxpayer
within 18 months that taxes were owed. Starting in 2004, the IRS
would have to notify the taxpayer within 12 months or it could not
collect interest and penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, if passed by the Senate and signed by Clinton as
expected, would cost the government $13 billion over a 10-year
period as a result of fewer taxes' being collected. Lawmakers said
the loss to the Treasury would be made up by permitting people over
the age of 70{ to shift money from regular individual retirement
accounts into so-called Roth IRAs, which allow for easier
withdrawal, and pay taxes in the process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
