<HEADER>
A7506 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOWLING-VOSS-COX     06-25 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOWLING-VOSS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Voss sets his sights on Anthony's mark
 &HT;    By Michael Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Brian Voss has made a Hall of Fame career out of a
sport typically personified by paunchy men in need of more aerobic
activity.
</P>
<P>
   Voss certainly doesn't fit that description. He has appeared in
a couple of movies, and his striking good looks spawned actress
Lauren Bacall's interest in professional bowling. Chances are,
though, few in Atlanta have ever heard of the guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind that,'' the 39-year-old Roswell resident said.
``I love what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's win.
</P>
<P>
   Voss holds a winning streak that just keeps on rolling, much
like the bowling ball he slings down the lane to knock down 10
pins. He extended his run of one title per year to 12 by claiming
the Professional Bowlers Association Tour's Brunswick Johnny
Petraglia Open in May.
</P>
<P>
   His 12 straight years with at least one title is the best among
active players and ties Don Johnson for second all-time behind PBA
legend Earl Anthony, who won titles in each of his first 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   And you better believe this record means something to Voss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go in the books. I want people to set themselves to
me,'' said Voss, who has won 19 PBA titles. ``I want to set new
barriers.''
</P>
<P>
   With Voss tip-toeing in on his record, Anthony expressed more
praise than fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish him well. I hope he wins for 25 years in a row_good for
him,'' Anthony said. ``I didn't even know about records. All I did
was bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Voss started bowling when he was six years old. His father,
Dale, bought a bowling center in Anchorage, Alaska, which led to
countless hours of practice and competitions with his four
siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Although his brother Mike tried a career in bowling, Brian was
the one who stuck with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say he was a natural; he worked hard, `` his
mother, Diane Shea, said from her home in Grand Junction, Colo.
``But some people have more of a flair for things than others.''
</P>
<P>
   Professional bowling wasn't always the plan. Voss tried college
for a semester and a half before quitting. After getting fired from
a job at a bowling center and breaking up with his girlfriend, Voss
joined the Army in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after, he was transferred to Germany where word got out
about his prowess in the lanes. He became a member of the all-Army
bowling team and was all-Army champion for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were the best years of my life,'' said Voss, who
competed throughout Europe.
</P>
<P>
   He left the military in 1981 to start his life as a professional
bowler. Voss claimed his first title in 1983, a sign of things to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Cupid struck in 1987, when Voss met Anderia Gough at a
tournament in Las Vegas. One month later, the streak began with a
victory at the Quaker State Open in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, he moved to Florida to be closer to his future wife.
That was also the year he was named PBA player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Voss' exchanged vows the day after one of Brian's biggest
victories, the Budweiser Classic in Sunrise, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Voss is the first to admit it doesn't come as easy anymore,
however.
</P>
<P>
   Before claiming that title in May, Voss went through one of the
biggest slumps of his career. For four weeks, he barely missed
cuts, and he felt he was just throwing away the $1,200 a week it
costs him to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel the same as I did. I need to practice more,''
said Voss, who was inducted into the PBA Hall of Fame in 1994.
``Things have changed a lot. I didn't have a wife and kids. If I
wasn't out partying, chasing girls or whatever, I was practicing.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, Voss got a scare when he thought his
seven-year-old son, Joshua, didn't come home from school. He later
found out that Joshua hid under the bed because he got in trouble
at school.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of being a parent, I guess,'' said Voss, who also
has a six-year-old son,Cameron. ``I wish I could be with them all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But he knows that only comes when the tour stops for its annual
three-month break.Although his earnings surpassed $1 million in
1992, Voss realizes that continued success edges him closer to the
record and a more comfortable future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it's like to have a real job,'' Voss said.
``I'm doing this until they stop making Advil.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
