<SLUG> BC-FINAL-FOURSITES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another coup: Atlanta lands '07 Final Four
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The qualities that made it the host city for the '96
Olympics continued to pay off Thursday, when the NCAA Men's
Basketball Committee awarded the 2007 Final Four to Atlanta and the
Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Also receiving Final Fours on Thursday were New Orleans (2003),
San Antonio (2004), St. Louis (2005), and Indianapolis (2006).
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA originally had planned to award only three Final Fours,
with five cities competing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But all the bids were so impressive that it would have been
difficult to get it down to three,'' said Kentucky athletics
director C.M. Newton, committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta already has the 2002 Final Four. The only other Final
Four here was in 1977 at the Omni.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are absolutely thrilled,'' said Charlie Shaffer, president
of the Atlanta Sports Council, which put Atlanta's bid together.
``There were a lot of good things about our bid, but more than
anything, the city of Atlanta won it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's bid for the Final Four was presented to the NCAA on
Monday by Shaffer; Dave Braine, the athletics director of Georgia
Tech, the host school; and Kahlil Johnson of the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Some highlights of Atlanta's bid:
</P>
<P>
   Transportation: Eighty-three percent of the nation's population
can reach Atlanta by plane in two hours or less. Over 2000 flights
leave Atlanta each day, more than from any competing city.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels: The NCAA wanted a minimum guarantee of 8,000 hotel
rooms. Atlanta offered 8,400 within 10 minutes of the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Centennial Park: The Olympic park will serve as the major
gathering and recreation area for the 40,000-plus fans that will
attend each session of the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you looked at the bid and the history Atlanta has of
hosting these kind of events, it was really a no-brainer,'' Newton
said.
</P>
<P>
   After making improvements to the Superdome, New Orleans will be
getting its first Final Four since 1993. San Antonio drew rave
reviews after hosting the event this March and was rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis built the TransWorld Dome and will get its first Final
Four since 1978. Indianapolis, which had the Final Four in 1997,
will get it again in 2000 and 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
