<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAWKS-DRUGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks center indicted for drugs
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Atlanta Hawks backup center Greg ``Cadillac''
Anderson has been indicted by a federal grand jury in Jackson,
Miss., on drug and money-laundering charges.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was accused of two counts of possession of cocaine with
intent to distribute and one count of money laundering, according
to U.S. Attorney Brad Pigott. Authorities refused to say whether
Anderson was in custody or was being sought by FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am shocked,'' Hawks general manager Pete Babcock said
Thursday night. ``Absolutely shocked. For his sake, I hope it's not
true. If it is, it's a huge disappointment. It's a tremendous
disappointment that there is even the accusation.''
</P>
<P>
   Babcock said he was first apprised of the situation by an FBI
agent during Wednesday's NBA Draft. The agent granted Babcock a
``courtesy'' and revealed that Anderson was the alleged culprit.
</P>
<P>
   But because the indictment was sealed, Babcock would not reveal
Anderson's name early Thursday after a press conference introducing
first-round draft choice Roshown McLeod.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in Jackson, Miss., also refused to comment until a
federal judge agreed late Thursday to unseal that part of the
indictment identifying Anderson and the charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   With the bulk of the indictment remaining under seal, officials
refused to say if others had been charged by the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA has been hit by player arrests for drug possessions, but
nothing on this level.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it turns out that he is guilty,'' Babcock said, ``he has
absolutely no place in our organization whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, a 6-foot-10, 250-pound free agent, has played for five
NBA teams. He has career averages of 7.3 points and 6.2 rebounds a
game. Last season with the Hawks, he played in 50 games, averaging
1.8 points and 2.4 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
