<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBA-FORMAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PBA going back to raucous roots
 &HT;    By Michael Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- During the Professional Bowling Association tour's
36-year run on ABC, professional bowlers approaching their pins
were like doctors in the operating room _ the slightest
out-of-place sound wasn't tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   No more.
</P>
<P>
   Since moving to CBS this year, the tour, which ranks behind only
college football as the longest-running sports series on network
television, has taken on a completely new ``Generation X'' look,
full of state-of-the-art graphics and a loud, raucous atmosphere
reminiscent of most bowling alleys.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at sports, I want to be entertained,'' PBA
commissioner Mark Gerberich said. ``In the days of the remote
control, we need to put more energy in the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   To do just that, the new format includes a ``mini-arena'' set-up
in which fans are seated in a horseshoe arrangement to surround the
bowlers, permitted to cheer at all times _ even when a player
prepares to make a delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players were being unfairly criticized as being
primadonnas, where they need quiet,'' Gerberich said. ``Bowling's
supposed to be fun. Our players perform in noise all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The PBA experimented with the format last season on ESPN, where
the tour is still televised, and Tom Baker likes the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been so excited,'' said Baker, who has bowled
professionally for 22 years. ``The people get your heart racing. It
was a little too quiet. Now, players show a lot more emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Other changes to the telecasts include a super-slow-motion
camera to capture pin action and ball spinning and a moving camera
that follows the ball down the lane.
</P>
<P>
   Championship rounds feature gold-colored Pro-Pins that are four
ounces heavier than the standard pins. Also, with airtime cut from
90 minutes to one hour, the five-man step-ladder tournament has
been reduced to four. Although there has been a 15 percent increase
in ratings on ESPN, the audience on CBS has dropped slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my hometown of Buffalo, they don't like the format,'' Baker
said. ``For me, it doesn't make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to knock down pins.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
