A7510 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUCKUS-COX     06-25 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUCKUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New owners to revamp RuckusText
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The new owners of the Atlanta Ruckus _ the fourth
group of people to hold that title in as many years _ are using an
adage familiar to local soccer fans as they pledge to reverse a
pattern of neglect by their predecessors:
</P>
<P>
   Trust us.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney John Latham and banking executive Robert Glustrom have
been in charge for less than a week, but their first act was to
alter the team's identity. For the time being, the Ruckus will be
referred to only as ``A-League Atlanta'' until a new nickname is
unveiled, probably by the start of next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ruckus just doesn't have positive connotations,'' said
Glustrom, chairman of AmTrade International Bank in Atlanta and the
father of three soccer-playing sons. ``We want to develop an image
and a brand and decide what we're going to stand for.''
</P>
<P>
   So tonight in Richmond, Va., the team formerly known as the
Ruckus (2-10) plays its first game since the A-League revoked the
franchise rights of former owner Vincent Lu last week for failing
to abide by operational guidelines. Head coach David Eristavi has
been retained, and several current players are being approached
about staying on.
</P>
<P>
   Latham, a partner in the prominent Atlanta law firm of Alston
and Bird and counsel to soccer apparel maker Umbro, the A-League's
main sponsor, said he and Glustrom, a longtime personal friend,
didn't have to be persuaded to step in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled to be in this position,'' Latham said. ``Bobby
and I had been talking about doing this if the opportunity came
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Atlanta Chiefs player Mike Balson, an A-League
consultant, will serve as general manager for the rest of the
season and will help implement a long-term business plan.
</P>
<P>
   Lu refused to promote and market the team and failed to pay
employees and work with sponsors as well as the league. Attendance
has plummeted from an average of 2,406 last year to barely 500 a
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the last home game (a 2-0 loss to Richmond on June
9), and I counted only 126 heads,'' Glustrom said. ``I almos
cried.''
</P>
<P>
   The franchise nearly folded in June 1996 when Lu, who owns a
tennis racquet business, promised to turn it around and move home
games to property he owns on the old Roswell High School site.
</P>
<P>
   But Lu's interest diminished rapidly. A week before the current
season began, he switched home games to Adams Stadium after feuding
with the city of Roswell on several legal and financial issues. On
June 13, he refused to send a team to a road game on Long Island,
prompting the league to act.
</P>
