<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Galarraga gets extra day to heal
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- What a strained groin could not do, what a crushed
little finger could not achieve, a wrenched back has done to Andres
Galarraga. The first baseman hopes to be back in the lineup tonight
for the start of the Toronto series after missing his first two
starts as a Braves. Look quick. Since re-establishing his career,
Galarraga does not sit down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big improvement from yesterday,'' he said Thursday. ``I don't
want to play like this. I'd rather not play today and play and then
miss two weeks. If I keep getting better like I have, in a few days
it will be all better probably.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Galarraga missed eight games _ three while serving a
suspension for charging the mound, four after breaking a bone in
his right hand when hit by a pitch. When he came back, he went on a
nine-game hitting streak. He missed just three starts in all of
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox believed. He had two lineups posted on the
clubhouse wall _ one with Galarraga, the other with Javy Lopez
batting clean-up. But after a day of whirlpool, heat and
ultra-sound therapy, Galarraga skipped batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays hurt all the time,'' said Cox. ``He played with that
bad finger (after being hit by a pitch June 13 by Montreal's Jesus
Vazquez). It's already been broken once. And he's still soaking it
every day in the whirlpool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he played through his groin injury, when he could barely
walk. And he was still hitting like crazy. Now, he could run pretty
good so he played through both of those. This thing, a back injury,
you can forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga felt a twinge in the left side of his lower back while
taking batting practice at Yankee Stadium Tuesday night and thought
nothing of it, until he tried to get out of bed the next day. ``I
couldn't even put on my clothes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga had gone hitless in eight at-bats in New York while
his average dropped to .306, the lowest in eight weeks. He has not
hit a home run in his last 11 starts, his longest stretch of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss scare
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Walt Weiss and wife Terri had a scare Thursday when
Bo, the couple's 11-month-old son, began running a fever and was
taken to Scottish Rite Children's Hospital for examinatin. Like
Brody, the couple's 3-year-old who is fighting a serious E. coli
infection, Bo had tested positive for the bacteria, but not for the
same strain that has infected his brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's clear so far,'' Weiss said. ``We got nervous when he ran
a temperature. We'll keep an eye on him for another two days and if
he's still clear, then he'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss reported Brody was unchanged, ``which is good. He's at the
stage right now where things can change quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Oz-man walking
</P>
<P>
   With 11 walks in his first 85 at-bats as a Brave, Ozzie Guillen
has already surpassed his season total of 10 from 1996, when he
batted 499 times. At this rate, he could surpass his career high
(28 in 1990) by the end of July. The transformation _ prompted by
Guillen's leadoff role and adapting to a new league _ has been
radical. In his 13 seasons with the White Sox, Guillen walked an
average of once every 31.4 at-bats. As a Brave, that rate is 7.7
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a free swinger,'' he insists. ``But I'm going up there to
have a good at-bat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ozzie's smart,'' said Cox. ``He knows situations and he can
have real good at-bats with men on. No easy out with him. I never
like to see a guy like that come up with men on. They're not going
to hit a home run but they'll get wood on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Pride could not have played in the field if he had to
Thursday, after taking a David Cone fastball to the right kneecap
the night before. ... Dugout coach Jim Beauchamp is back in the
clubhouse after surgery to repair tendon damage in his right knee.
He faces some extensive rehab time before being able to resume his
regular duties. ... Stat corner: Kevin Millwood went to 3-2 counts
to nine of the first 11 men he faced Wednesday night en route to a
93-pitch count in just 3 1/3 innings. ``That's not his game,'' said
Cox. ``His game is get 'em out quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
