<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ON DECK:TORONTO BLUE JAYS
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: Tonight at 7:40 p.m., Saturday at 7:10 p.m. and Sunday at
1:10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   TV/radio: TBS and 750-AM will broadcast all three games.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: Tonight, RHP John Smoltz (5-1, 3.42;
0-1, 6.43 lifetime vs. Blue Jays) vs. RHP Pat Hentgen (8-4, 4.32;
first appearance vs. Braves). Saturday, RHP Greg Maddux (10-2,
1.75; 1-0, 4.50 lifetime vs. Blue Jays) vs. RHP Juan Guzman (4-9,
5.44; first appearance vs. Braves). Sunday, LHP Tom Glavine (10-3,
2.72; first appearance vs. Blue Jays) vs. RHP Chris Carpenter (4-2,
4.65; first appearance vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Series history: Rivals in the 1992 World Series, the Braves and
Blue Jays meet for the first time in Atlanta since then. The Braves
lead the all-time regular-season series 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Past meetings: The Braves took two of three at SkyDome last June
16-18, a series highlighted by Denny Neagle out-dueling Roger
Clemens 3-0 in the first game.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jays leaders: Avg. _ Carlos Delgado (.295); HR _ Jose
Canseco (22); RBIs _ Canseco (45); SB _ Canseco (21). W _ Roger
Clemens and Pat Hentgen (8); ERA _ Paul Quantrill (2.66).
Strikeouts _ Clemens (102). Saves _ Randy Myers (21).
</P>
<P>
   Quickly: The Blue Jays attempted Thursday night to sweep four
games from Canadian rival Montreal. The team is still trying to
recover from one of its worst starts in history in a record-tying
16-loss April. The Blue Jays came within one victory of tying the
franchise record for May wins with 18 and were 10-10 in their last
20 games entering Thursday night. ... Canseco has stunned the
league by reclaiming his career at age 33. He has reached the 20-20
mark for the third time in his career and continues to pace the
club offensively, even though he has hit just .207 over the past 10
days.Who's hot: Catcher Darrin Fletcher, who came off the DL June
14 after a hamstring problem, has hit .400 since with seven RBIs in
35 at-bats. DH Mike Stanley had a six-game hitting streak and was
batting .426 with five homers in his previous 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Who's not: Canseco, despite strong production numbers, is
hitting .207 over his last 10 games. Veteran Juan Samuel is hitting
just .200 in a reserve role.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
