<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEATH-SENTENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL RECOMMENDS COMMUTING A DEATH SENTENCE
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By CAROL MARIE CROPPER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Texas State Board of Pardons and Paroles
recommended Thursday that one of the United States' most notorious
mass murderers not be executed for a killing that evidence suggests
he did not commit.
</P>
<P>
   It is now up to Gov. George W. Bush to decide whether the
killer, Henry Lee Lucas, should have his death sentence commuted to
life in prison, as the board suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an unusual case,'' Bush said after the ruling. ``I
will give it careful consideration and announce a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas is also serving six life terms, two 75-year terms, and one
60-year term for nine other killings, but the case for which he was
sentenced to death, the rape and murder of a hitchhiker 19 years
ago, is the only one in which there is serious doubt about his
guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, 61, was scheduled to be executed by lethal injection at
6:01 p.m. on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas' lawyers said they expected the governor to honor the
board's recommendation, since he had publicly asked the board to
review the case. But, one lawyer added, it would be the first time
Bush has commuted a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, who in the 1980s asserted that he had committed as many
as 600 murders across the country, told officials that the
unidentified slain woman, known only as Orange Socks, was one of
his victims. But he later recanted his confessions and work records
and other evidence now suggest that he was in Florida at the time
of the killing in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The case came to the public's attention after former state
Attorney General Jim Mattox, a supporter of the death penalty,
reviewed Lucas' case and concluded that there was compelling
evidence he was not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the state that easily leads the nation in executions,
Lucas' lawyer Danny Burns said he had not expected the board to
give his client a reprieve. It is the first time the Texas board
has, without a court decision, recommended the commutation of a
death sentence since 1976, when the death penalty was reinstated,
Burns said.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Rodriguez, chairman of the parole board, said he could
not confirm that but added, ``I know it is the first in recent
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Rita Radostitz, another lawyer for Lucas, said he was, ``very
emotional'' when told of the board's recommendation. ``He was
definitely pleased, relieved I think.''
</P>
<P>
   The board did not call for overturning Lucas' conviction. In a
letter to Bush, Rodriguez said, ``It is important to note that this
person remains convicted of this offense and as such should remain
incarcerated for the rest of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether the board's recommendation meant that it had
decided there were reasons to doubt Lucas' guilt, Rodriguez said:
``I felt that he had raised enough questions. When you're deciding
life and death, enough questions is enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
