<SLUG> BC-BKN-CAMBY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBY WILL HAVE TO EARN KNICKS' SUPPORT ON THE COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first hurdle Marcus Camby faces in New York will probably be
in his own locker room. The former University of Massachusetts star
was traded from the Raptors to the Knicks Thursday for Charles
Oakley, one of the most popular players in team history. Oakley's
teammates won't be thrilled about the deal. But one thing can
change their opinions: Camby on the court.
</P>
<P>
   While New York may have lost a layer of toughness by trading the
34-year-old Oakley _ a Knick since 1988 _ it acquired a man 10
years younger who led the NBA in blocked shots (3.65 per game) last
season. So now the Knicks can have two 7-foot shot-blockers in
their frontcourt, Camby and Patrick Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us more flexibility, makes us more intimidating in
the defensive end and more athletic than we've been in the past,''
general manager Ernie Grunfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   It also helps bankroll the cash-strapped Raptors. In addition to
Oakley, they received second-round draft pick Sean Marks and cash.
Part of the money undoubtedly is to help fund the $10 million
balloon payment Oakley is due at the end of next season. The
Raptors also received cash from the Warriors when they traded
Antawn Jamison to them for guard Vince Carter. The team that was
once seen as a young group on the way up after drafting Camby
second overall in 1996 now boasts a strange mix of youth and
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley is 34. Kevin Willis, acquired earlier this month, is 35.
Chauncey Billups, Carter, and Alvin Williams are all 22 or under.
</P>
<P>
   ``As one of the NBA's best defenders and rebounders, Charles
Oakley gives us a physical presence and mental toughness that is
unsurpassed in our league,'' Raptors GM Glen Grunwald said.
</P>
<P>
   Camby had been either injured or out of place in Toronto. Most
observers agree that he has only scratched his potential. Still, he
had decent numbers with 12.1 points and 7.4 rebounds per game last
season. The flip side is that he has missed a total of 38 games in
two pro seasons. The Knicks will miss Oakley's durability and
hustle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tremendous respect for Charles and what he has meant
to the franchise,'' Grunfeld said. ``It was a difficult thing to do
because of what he has meant to the franchise. You have very strong
feelings. We grew up together and we've been through a lot of
battles together. It's never easy to part with someone of his
character.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley's fan base at Madison Square Garden was diverse because
all could relate to the gritty play that often led to hard fouls
and discipline by the NBA. Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy often
defended the aggressiveness of Oakley. Thursday the coach joked
about the man who will be an opponent. ``I want to make it clear,''
he said, ``Charles Oakley does flagrantly foul now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 2131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
