<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7519 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMEX-NASDAQ-385&AMP;ADD-N     06-25 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMEX-NASDAQ-385&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMEX MEMBERS VOTE TO JOIN NASD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The American Stock Exchange, one of the nation's
oldest and sleepiest financial exchanges, said Thursday that its
members had voted overwhelmingly to join the the parent
organization of the Nasdaq stock market, the fast-growing exchange
that favors high-technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   More than two-thirds of the 828 members of the American Stock
Exchange, which includes floor brokers, specialists and others who
operate on the trading floor, voted for the merger, intended to
create a vastly more competitive rival to the New York Stock
Exchange, which has long been the nation's preeminent marketplace
for buying and selling stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq stock market, the nation's second largest stock
exchange, and the American Stock Exchange, the third largest, will
continue to operate as separate entities. While the Amex offers the
traditional ``open outcry'' market, the Nasdaq is an electronic
exchange where all the trading is done by telephone and computer
links. But by combining, the Amex is expected to get a new
technology platform to enhance its trading floor.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, by sharing technology and regulatory resources and
offering companies around the world a choice of listing on an
electronic exchange or one that operates as an open-air auction
market, where brokers shout out bids and offers on stocks, the
National Association of Securities Dealers, which will oversee both
exchanges, hopes to create a cheaper and more efficient global
``market of markets'' that might some day overtake the Big Board as
the world's leading marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The promise to investors, big and small, is the prospect of
lower trading costs for the thousands of stocks listed on the two
exchanges, everything from MCI Communications and Starbucks Coffee,
which trade on the Nasdaq, to Viacom and Cablevision, which are
listed on the American Stock Exchange. The combination could allow
the two exchanges to lure companies with more global heft.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the agreement, which still must be approved by the
Securities and Exchange Commission, the NASD, Nasdaq's parent, said
it would commit at least $110 million to the Amex over the next
five years, to upgrade its technology, and spend an additional $30
million on marketing and advertising for both exchanges.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The vote, 622-206, more than the two-thirds majority required,
was a huge victory for NASD chairman Frank Zarb and Amex chairman
Richard Syron.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the results of the vote, Syron said in a telephone
conference call that there was little dissent before the vote. ``It
was a very orderly, very calm meeting,'' he said. ``This really is
an overwhelming vote in favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some members had been expected to oppose the merger
Thursday night over concerns that seat prices would decline and
that the traditional auction market would be changed, those who
attended the meeting said that many of those issues had been
addressed by the NASD and Amex leaders, who traveled the country,
lobbying for a merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once people had a stake in the negotiating process, once they
were participating in it, then they became comfortable with the
transaction and were willing to support it,'' said Lewis Lowenfels,
a former member of the board of governors of the Amex who
represented the floor brokers in the merger.
</P>
<P>
   While the Nasdaq has managed to surpass the Big Board in daily
trading volume in recent years, it continues to lose companies to
the more established exchange. And a series of investigations into
improper trading practices surrounding Nasdaq companies in the
1980s and 1990s sullied the electronic market's reputation. More
than 30 Wall Street firms agreed in December to pay about $1
billion to settle price-fixing charges that they kept the spreads
on trades artificially wide. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Amex, on the other hand, has suffered less from scandal than
from a diminishing position relative to the high profile Big Board.
The junior exchange fell to third place behind the Nasdaq in
listings and trading volume in the 1970s, and managed to stay just
ahead of the smaller regional exchanges in the 1980s and 1990s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, though, the Amex has developed a strong
business in options and other derivatives, particularly those that
track the fortunes of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, known as
Spiders, and the Dow Jones industrial average, or Diamonds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet just as the Nasdaq seemed to be losing momentum, and the
Amex seemed to be losing hope of ever being a market leader, the
boards of the two exchanges agreed last April to a merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great boon for companies listed on the American
Stock Exchange because it was a back-water, a no place,'' said
Samuel Hayes, a professor at Harvard University, after the merger
proposal was announced in March. ``This also gives the Nasdaq a
platform for higher visibility vis-a-vis the New York Stock
Exchange.''
</P>
<P>
   The combination also helped lure the Philadelphia Stock
Exchange, the nation's oldest exchange and one that is rich in
stock and options listings, into the merger talks.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Stock Exchange, meanwhile, has been making great
strides in the listing of large international companies, and
basking in the glow of record revenue and trading.
</P>
<P>
   But few on Wall Street are expecting anything less than an
all-out brawl between the exchanges. And with the vote over, Zarb
said, ``Now it's time to forge a single front.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
