<SLUG> BC-BOYS-ABUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1 IN 8 BOYS OF HIGH-SCHOOL AGE HAS BEEN ABUSED, SURVEY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TAMAR LEWIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new study of adolescent boys' health has found that more than
one in eight high-school-age boys said they had been physically or
sexually abused, with Hispanic and Asian-American boys reporting
the highest rates of both kinds of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised by these differences between ethnic
groups,'' said Cathy Schoen, an author of the study. ``We didn't
find those ethnic differences when we looked at abuse among girls,
and most of the studies of abuse look at girls, because they have a
much higher rate of sexual abuse. But boys and girls have similar
rates of physical abuse, and it does look like boys within some
ethnic families are more at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted by Louis Harris and Associates Inc. for The
Commonwealth Fund, found that the physical abuse of boys was far
more common than sexual abuse, and that two-thirds of the physical
abuse was by a family member and took place in the home.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who were sexually abused, about one-third reported
that the abuse had happened at home, and 45 percent said the abuser
was a family member. Most of the boys said the sexual or physical
abuse they experienced was a recurring pattern.
</P>
<P>
   The study, based on questionnaires completed by 3,162 boys in
grades five to 12 in nearly 300 schools across the country,
compared the boys' responses with those collected in a matching
sample of adolescent girls, analyzed in a report last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half the abused boys said they had not talked to anyone
about it, compared with 29 percent of the abused girls. And among
the boys, abuse was more strongly linked to thoughts of suicide: 15
percent of the abused boys said they wanted to kill themselves,
nearly double the rate of the abused girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's striking how many boys have no one to talk to, and keep
their problems to themselves,'' Ms. Schoen said. ``Another thing
that struck me about boys who said they had been abused is their
much higher rate of bulimia, which is so rare among boys generally
that doctors could almost look at it as an early warning sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, boys were more likely than girls to say that they did
not usually talk to anyone when they were stressed, overwhelmed or
depressed. Boys with symptoms of poor mental health were
particularly likely to lack a support person.
</P>
<P>
   Four in 10 of the boys with severe symptoms of depression had no
one to talk with, more than twice the ratio of the girls. Among
boys and girls alike, mothers were the most frequently named source
of support.
</P>
<P>
   The questionnaires did not define abuse, asking simply whether
the respondent had ever been sexually or physically abused. Among
Asian-American boys, 9 percent reported sexual abuse and 17 percent
reported physical abuse. Among Hispanic boys, 7 percent said they
had been sexually abused and 13 percent said they had been
physically abused. Among blacks and whites, the sexual abuse rate
was 3 percent; 10 percent of the blacks and 8 percent of the whites
said they had been physically abused.
</P>
<P>
   While three-quarters of boys and girls alike said they turned to
television when they were stressed, girls were far more likely than
boys to say they would call a friend, while boys were more likely
to spend time on the computer or exercising.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted from December 1996 through June 1997
and had a margin of sampling error of plus or minus three
percentage points for the boys overall; the percentage was higher
for the individual ethnic groups.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The survey examined several areas of boys' health:
</P>
<P>
   _ Eight in 10 boys exercised at least three times a week, but
Hispanic and Asian-American boys were less likely than black or
white boys to participate in organized sports.
</P>
<P>
   _ While boys were generally much less likely than girls to
report eating disorders _ 8 percent of the boys said they had
binged or purged, compared to 16 percent of the girls _ abused boys
were four times more likely to have binged or purged than those who
had not been abused, and eight times as likely to do so frequently.
</P>
<P>
   _ While high school boys and girls had similar rates of
drinking, smoking and using drugs, boys in grades five thorough
eight were more likely than girls to drink, smoke or use drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, one in five adolescent boys said there had been a
time when he needed medical care but did not get it, and uninsured
or abused boys were especially likely to have been in that
situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
