<SLUG> BC-INTEL-CHIP-FLAW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL CONFIRMS FLAW IN NEW CHIP
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Intel Corp. confirmed Thursday that a bug would
delay shipments of its 450NX chip set, which is to be used with its
new Xeon microprocessor in high-powered servers.
</P>
<P>
   Xeon will sell for $1,100 to $2,800, depending on the level of
memory included with the chip. The Xeon is Intel's first entry into
the area of high-performance computing, which has been dominated by
chips like Sun Microsystems' Sparc, Hewlett-Packard Co.'s PA-RISC
and Silicon Graphics' MIPS.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said the flaw only affected the Xeon when it is used with
the 450NX chip set, the set of parts surrounding the
microprocessor, which is intended for large servers using up to
four processors at a time. Further testing will delay shipment of
that combination by about three weeks, Robert Minetta, an Intel
spokesman, said. There is no problem when Xeon is used with the
440GX chip set, which will commonly be used in work stations and
smaller servers, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Intel did not disclose the nature of the flaw in the 450NX, but
Minetta said it would be published shortly. Such problems are
common in new microprocessors and are usually of little consequence
to most users. But Intel's experience with the original Pentium in
1994, when it denied the significance of a flaw, only to later
issue a recall of thousands of chips, has prompted the company to
disclose such problems as they become known.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
