<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-COLUMNIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS GROUP RESCINDS COLUMNIST'S WRITING AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Society of Newspaper Editors has rescinded the 1998
Distinguished Writing Award it gave to former Boston Globe
columnist Patricia Smith, citing her admitted fabrication of people
and quotations in four columns.
</P>
<P>
   Although none of Smith's 1997 columns submitted for the award
contained fabrications, the society board said in a statement
Thursday, ``There is no place in journalism for fabrication of any
kind.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the society withdrew an award since it
instituted the prizes in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Smith did not return a call to her home Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Globe editor Matthew V. Storin had urged the society
Wednesday to withdraw the award.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 43, resigned from the paper June 18 after admitting that
she had invented characters and quotes. Before her resignation, she
had written a Metro column twice a week since 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
