s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-ROTH-IRA-ART-2     06-25 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-ROTH-IRA-ART-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ESTATE PLANNING, A ROTH IRA SHINES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Minn., Md., Ohio)  (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
(af) 
 By VIRGINIA MUNGER KAHN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors seeking to take advantage of the single most lucrative
feature of the Roth individual retirement account will have to pay
a substantial penalty. The ultimate one.
</P>
<P>
   Though bushels of marketing materials for the new Roth IRA have
been thrown at young savers, the fact is that Roth IRAs are of far
greater benefit to a very different age group _ older investors
seeking to transfer wealth to the next generation after they die.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Roth IRAs so attractive for estate planning? Two big
things.
</P>
<P>
   First, unlike a traditional IRA, the Roth version does not
require distributions to begin at age 70{. This means that if a
retiree does not need the money in an IRA, the assets can keep
accumulating tax free.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the assets can be passed on to heirs without any
additional income taxes being owed. Unlike traditional IRAs, the
Roth variety offers tax-free distributions as long as the assets
are held in the account for five years.
</P>
<P>
   That one-two combination can yield enormous advantages for
beneficiaries. ``It's like a perpetual gift,'' said Christine
Fahlund, a certified financial planner at T. Rowe Price Associates
in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   For the majority of people, only income taxes need to be
considered in doing this planning. For the more affluent, however,
estate taxes are also a factor. Estate taxes kick in when the
assets in an estate exceed $625,000 (the amount will gradually rise
to $1 million by 2006), and the tax rates go as high as 55 percent.
But estate taxes can often be minimized by dividing assets between
spouses and sometimes by careful use of trusts.
</P>
<P>
   What can switching into a Roth IRA mean to heirs? Consider this
example from T. Rowe Price: Harry and Jane are each 70{ years old
and have a son, Andy, 40. Harry has $100,000 in a traditional IRA
that he wants to convert to a Roth IRA. He has $32,000 available in
a separate, taxable account to pay the taxes on the conversion.
Jane, the beneficiary, dies at age 80, Harry at age 85. Assuming an
8 percent return, that leaves Andy with a Roth IRA of $326,000 upon
Harry's death.
</P>
<P>
   What would have happened if Harry had kept his money in the
traditional IRA? First, the $32,000 he would have used to pay taxes
would have stayed in the taxable account, earning 5.4 percent
annually after taxes. Good. But he would have had to make mandatory
withdrawals from the traditional IRA.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, upon Harry's death, the traditional IRA would have
shrunk to $60,500 after taxes. But, the taxable account would have
grown to $223,500, assuming that the money withdrawn from the IRA
was added to it. Thus the total pot, using the traditional IRA, is
$284,000, or $42,000 less than the Roth IRA.
</P>
<P>
   That is a tidy difference for Andy, but not enough to quit his
job over.
</P>
<P>
   The big payoff comes when the two accounts are converted to a
stream of income over Andy's remaining life expectancy, 28 years.
If he takes distributions from the Roth IRA over that time,
assuming the 8 percent return, he will receive a total of $1.1
million, tax free.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the pot of money from the traditional IRA, earning
an after-tax rate of 5.4 percent, would give him $475,000 in
payments over his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   The big gap in payouts results from the fact that Harry and Jane
did not have to take minimum distributions from the Roth IRA. while
they were alive, and earnings are distributed to Andy tax free, Ms.
Fahlund said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got two buckets of a very different nature,'' she said.
``In one, you've got a bucket full of money that's completely tax
free for years to come and in the other you've got totally taxable
assets.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There are other perks, too. The Roth IRA lets you avoid having
to deal with beneficiary selections, irrevocable decisions that can
have nasty tax consequences.
</P>
<P>
   How? Most IRA holders are unwilling to name their children as
beneficiaries, preferring to name their spouse instead. That is
fine as long as the owner of the IRA dies first: the spouse takes
the money and names his or her children as beneficiaries. When the
spouse dies, the children either take the money out over five years
or over their life expectancy.
</P>
<P>
   But if the spouse dies before the account owner, the money in
the account must be distributed by the end of the year after the
latter's death. That means a big payment of income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tax nightmare,'' said Bruce Steiner, tax and estate
attorney at Kleinberg Kaplan Wolff &AMP; Cohen in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, a Roth IRA lacks such complications. The more
tax-efficient long-term payout is available regardless of which
spouse dies first. In fact, converting to a Roth IRA can be a great
way to get out of a distribution choice you've committed to.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a Roth IRA is not for everyone. First, to be
eligible, individuals must have adjusted gross income of less than
$100,000 a year. Second, they need to come up with the cash,
separate from the IRA, to pay the income taxes on the conversion
amount.
</P>
<P>
   Do the estate planning benefits of Roth IRAs sound to good to be
true? They may well be. Some planners doubt whether Congress, over
time, will keep allowing this tax-sheltered pool of national assets
to balloon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel it is too great a benefit for Congress to watch it
grow,'' said R. Mark Hochberg, an estate tax lawyer at Schanker &AMP;
Hochberg in Huntington, N.Y. ``I tell anyone to do a conversion or
set up an account now, because there's no assurance the Roth will
remain part of the law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors should also consider the state of the markets. If they
convert this year and stock prices plummet, they will have paid
taxes on inflated asset values.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the potentially limited window of opportunity,
financial advisers say investors would be wise to do a conversion
analysis soon, either with the help of a professional or an IRA
conversion software program or workbook. Most programs available to
consumers, however, focus on the lifetime of the owner and spouse _
not on estate planning.
</P>
<P>
   Why aren't more people making the switch to a Roth? ``In
general, the mistake people make is not being predisposed to doing
the conversion because of the immediate tax implications,'' said
Ross Levin, a certified financial planner and president of
Accredited Investors in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Some advisers are becoming far more direct.
</P>
<P>
   In what he volunteers is ``an extraordinary act of enlightened
self-interest,'' James Budros, a certified financial planner and
principal at Budros &AMP; Ruhlin in Columbus, Ohio, has offered to pay
the cost of converting his parents' $100,000 traditional IRA to a
Roth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm willing to pay taxes now,'' he said, ``to get big bucks
later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
