<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GM STRIKE STARTS TO AFFECT WORKERS ACROSS THE NATION
</P>
<P>
   The strikes at two General Motors factories have forced the
automaker to curtail production at 100 parts factories, close 26 of
its 29 assembly plants in North America and temporarily lay off
147,900 workers.
</P>
<P>
   And now the effects are reaching across the country to other
companies. A windshield-wiper factory in Rochester, N.Y., has laid
off 1,200 workers and Lear Corp.'s car-seat factories from Delaware
to Texas have laid off 2,800 employees. Economists are also
reducing their estimates of the annualized growth rate of the
nation's economic output for the second quarter because of the
strike.
</P>
<P>
   SUNBEAM FACING A BLEAK OUTLOOK
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Sunbeam have plummeted 42 percent since the board of
the appliance maker dismissed its chief executive, Albert Dunlap
two weeks ago. Now the company has confirmed that the SEC is
investigating its accounting practices and Sunbeam is delaying
registering a planned bond offering.
</P>
<P>
   POWER CUTBACKS IN MIDWEST
</P>
<P>
   Utilities throughout the Midwest asked customers to cut the use
of appliances because of a heat wave that has resulted in a surge
in demand for electricity. Many industries in the region also
reduced their power consumption, canceling shifts and sending
workers home early.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE APPROVES OVERHAUL OF IRS
</P>
<P>
   The House approved legislation worked out by House-Senate
negotiators that would lead to an internal reorganization of the
Internal Revenue Service, create an independent board to oversee
its operations and give taxpayers more rights and powers in
disputes with the tax collection agency.
</P>
<P>
   STRONG GROWTH IN FIRST QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   The economy grew at a 5.4 percent annual rate during the first
three months of this year, stronger than originally estimated.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER ISSUES LEAD STOCKS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Concern about profits for the computer industry's bellwethers
sent the Nasdaq and Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock indexes down. The
Dow Jones industrial average rose 11.71, to 8,935.58.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on the 30-year Treasury bond fell to 5.65 percent, from
5.66 percent Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   SAKS HIRES ADVISERS FOR ITS SALE
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the holding company for Saks Fifth Avenue has
approved a sale or merger of the 97-store chain. It retained
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. to assist with a deal
that would end the ownership of Investcorp International.
</P>
<P>
   OIL FALLS ON DOUBTS ABOUT CUTBACKS
</P>
<P>
   Oil futures snapped a four-day rally and fell almost 4 percent,
to $14.03 a barrel, on skepticism that oil producers would follow
through on promises to cut production sufficiently to reduce a
supply glut.
</P>
<P>
   GOP's LOW-BUDGET TOBACCO BILL
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in the House of Representatives offered a
one-page outline of the kind of tobacco legislation they prefer as
an alternative to the ambitious anti-smoking bill shelved by the
Senate last week. The Republicans favor an advertising campaign to
discourage teen-age smoking, no increase in tobacco prices and
diminished authority of the Food and Drug Administration to
regulate tobacco products. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
