<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BITTERNESS MARKS END TO US EFFORT AT WORLD CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France _ Tab Ramos said the whole tournament had been a
mess, that he couldn't wait for it to end. Alexi Lalas said it was
a nightmare. Eric Wynalda called it tragic.
</P>
<P>
   Thus did the World Cup end for the Americans here Thursday
night, with finger-pointing and second-guessing and bitterness. The
coach had the wrong people on the field in the wrong formation. The
right people never got to play. The players who didn't play weren't
mature about it, weren't professional. Et cetera, et cetera.
</P>
<P>
   This is what three-and-out is like when you expected something
more, and the Yanks clearly did this time. ``At the end of the day,
it's the result that counts,'' US Soccer Federation president Alan
Rothenberg said after the Americans were blanked, 1-0, by
Yugoslavia in their group finale at the Stade de La Beaujoire.
``Three-and-out is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   The three might have been a surprise _ the Yanks were convinced
they would beat Iran _ but the out never was. Nobody outside their
camp thought they would survive the first round this time, and
everybody inside it conceded it would be a long shot. This is the
team, after all, that couldn't beat the Mexicans or the Jamaicans
in its regional. ``And there is no Germany or Yugoslavia in our
confederation,'' Rothenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The finger-pointing and the second-guessing and the bitterness,
finally, were irrelevant. The Yanks were 150-1 shots here, and
150-1 shots watch the second round on TV in their rumpus rooms.
They are going home because they were in awe of the Germans. They
are going home because they are The Gang That Couldn't Shoot
Straight. They are going home because they scored one goal in 270
minutes and gave up five.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a good World Cup, and that's why we're going
home,'' said defender Marcelo Balboa, who got a token eight minutes
here after playing every minute four years ago when the host US
advanced to the second round. ``We didn't do what we did in 1994.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans were younger in 1994. They were playing at home in
1994. They had an easier draw in 1994. They had been together in
camp for months in 1994. They had an experienced coach in 1994. And
they didn't do as well in 1994 as it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a poor game against Switzerland and we saved it with a
spectacular shot,'' Rothenberg said. ``We had a great game against
Colombia. We had a horrible game against Romania. We held the score
down against Brazil, so people thought it was a better effort than
it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything was different about 1998. The Americans had to play
16 qualifying matches. They had some players in Major League
Soccer, others scattered throughout Europe. They could rarely put
the same starters on the field more than two matches in a row. They
had half a dozen players over 30. They had a coach who was learning
on the job, whose fate was undecided until the team had already
qualified. They were playing overseas against a three-time champion
and one of the most explosive teams in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, the Americans were a team in transition, split
between old boys like Wynalda and Ramos and Balboa and rookies like
Chad Deering, Brian Maisonneuve, and David Regis. ``The team that
played in the World Cup is very different than the team that
qualified,'' said Wynalda, who was pulled midway through the opener
and never started again. ``That's not a criticism. That's a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the team that qualified might have done better here. Odds
are it would not have. Ramos, who didn't play Thursday night after
starting against Iran and coming off the bench against Germany, had
missed most of the last 18 months after tearing up the same knee
twice. Wynalda, who had scored only one goal all year, had knee
surgery in April and did little when he did play here. Lalas and
Balboa weren't as young or as quick as Regis or Eddie Pope, who
took their places.
</P>
<P>
   So they got part-time minutes here, or none at all, and as loss
followed loss, they sounded off. Word from within the camp, never
substantiated, was that Sampson had threatened to send four
veterans home for their sour attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   The veterans, three of whom were playing in their third Cup,
felt they had carried the team for a decade and deserved better. So
when the wheels came off here with them sitting on the bench, they
blamed Sampson, who had dumped captain John Harkes, their blood
brother, in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous disappointment, and there has to be
accountability,'' said Lalas, who played every minute in 1994 and
no minutes here. ``There's blame that'll go around.''
</P>
<P>
   The blame game is standard procedure among the three-and-outs.
The Saudis, South Koreans, and Tunisians dumped their coaches
before the first round was even over. The Spanish and Belgians and
Bulgarians are going home to a national chorus of hand-wringing and
derision. The Yanks are just going home, as 150-1 shots usually do.
Call it a mess, call it a nightmare, call it tragic. The French
merely called it ``la illusion Americaine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
