<SLUG> BC-HKN-OWNERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL OWNERS ADD SOME BALANCE TO OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The National Hockey League began tweaking its rules
Thursday to increase the offensive balance of the game. Measures
passed by the board of governors included a move of the goal line
farther out from the boards; the use of two referees, instead of
one, for a limited number of games; and the trimming of the goal
crease by two feet on each side to allow attackers to get closer to
the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   But the board tabled a proposal that would have made
regular-season games worth 3 points, instead of 2 points, in the
standings. The idea was suggested by Commissioner Gary Bettman in
an effort to reduce the number of tie games and to discourage
conservative play. Under the proposal, games decided in overtime
would be worth 2 points to the winning team and 1 point to the
loser, while a regulation victory would mean 3 points for the
winner.
</P>
<P>
   The board also amended the league constitution to limit
ownership interests by the same investors in more than one team.
This could immediately affect the Fox Group, which indirectly owns
a stake with the Rangers and has an option to buy a piece of the
Los Angeles Kings. ``We're going to have to sit down with them,''
Bettman said.
</P>
<P>
   No decision was made on future Olympic participation, which
resulted in mixed reviews after the Nagano Games, Japan. Some
owners, players and fans were unhappy with the length of the season
and a perception that interest waned in the league schedule and the
Stanley Cup playoffs after the 17-day break in February. One of
those owners was Bill Wirtz, of the Chicago Blackhawks and former
chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitting out 17 days and they wonder why,'' Wirtz said
Thursday. ``It was stupid. It was ludicrous. They got taken.''
</P>
<P>
   In other rules changes, Bettman vowed longer suspensions against
a player who delivers blows to the head of an opponent. And he said
the board approved the use of two referees, instead of one, for a
limited number of games, along with two linesmen. Punishing stick
or elbow blows to the head could cut down on the alarming increase
in concussions sidelining stars such as Anaheim's Paul Kariya.
Using two referees could help detect obstruction fouls behind the
play while extending careers of veteran referees who become more
experienced but less athletic with age.
</P>
<P>
   Bettman said tests in Canada have shown that, under a
two-referee system, a referee skates 6 miles per game, instead of 9
and that heart rate is reduced by 20 beats per minute. The
goal-line movement and the reduction of the crease size could
improve the flow of attack.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the line is 11 feet from the backboards. Next season,
it will be 13 feet. The two feet will be taken away from the
neutral zone, two feet on each side of center ice. With more room
behind the net, it is hoped that goalies will be less able to clear
or hold pucks that are shot in by attackers. Combined with
increased enforcement of anti-obstruction rules, it is thought that
attacking forwards will have more opportunities to create scoring
chances.
</P>
<P>
   By trimming the crease by two feet on each side, attacking
players can get closer to the net for deflections, rebounds or
setting screens. Goals will still be nullified if attackers have
skates in the blue-painted crease. But the crease will now take up
less space. On the matter of crease interference, the board also
closed a loophole that prevented the video-review judge from
informing the referee if an attacker's skates were in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   The board also approved establishment of the Maurice Richard
trophy to honor the leading goal-scorer each season. The Art Ross
trophy already honors the overall points producer, goals combined
with assists.
</P>
<P>
   Richard, the former Canadiens great, has cancer but has been out
and about recently. He is believed to be currently on a fishing
trip, the kind of thing hockey people used to do in the summer,
back when Richard played, when the playoffs ended in April and the
league had a longer off season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
