<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RULES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNORS VOTE RULES AIMED AT SPEEDING UP THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Every NHL coach reminds his players to keep their feet
moving, and Thursday the league's Board of Governors did the same,
ratifying a number of rule changes aimed at making the game faster
_ including the addition of a second referee in the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   Not all games next season will have a second ref on duty,
according to commissioner Gary Bettman, but perhaps 10 or 20 games
in every NHL rink will have the extra whistle-blower added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some studies have shown that one referee skates 9 miles per
game and the addition of a second ref cuts that down to about 6
miles,'' said Bettman. ``And a study by a Canadian college showed
that a second ref out there cuts a ref's average heart rate down by
20 beats per minute.''
</P>
<P>
   The reduced miles and heart stress could help referees stay
longer on the job. NHL referees now typically are labeled for
retirement by their mid-40s. A second ref, the league hopes, will
enable some of its best arbiters to stay on the job into their 50s.
Another major advantage of a two-referee system: faster games.
Preseason experiments with two refs pared some 16 minutes off the
length of games.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on the recommendation of their general managers, the
Lords of the Boards also approved pulling the nets closer to the
neutral zone, clipping the wings off the crease area, and allowing
the video goal judge to call down to the surface and inform
referees that a man was in the crease when a goal was scored.
Previously, the referee had to initiate the call upstairs, a move
that became all too familiar to Bruins fans last spring when Tim
Taylor's toe in the crease negated a P.J. Axelsson overtime goal in
Game 3 of the playoffs against the Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   A closer look at the rule changes:
</P>
<P>
   _The goal lines, previously 11 feet from the end boards, will be
placed 13 feet out, reducing the neutral zone from 58 to 54 feet.
The increase of some 20 percent in room behind the net should allow
for more playmaking and discourage goalies from handling the puck.
Overall, there should be more skating and passing and less room in
the middle of the ice for trapping defenses.
</P>
<P>
   _The arc of the crease's blue zone, which previously extended 3
feet from the side of each post, will be cut back by 2 feet.
Attacking forwards now can muscle within 12 inches of the post and
within about a boot length from the top of the crease. The change
should make it easier for players to score and, more important, cut
down significantly on interference calls. Note to Bruins fans:
Taylor's skate would not have been in the blue paint if the smaller
crease had been used this year. Tell that to the hockey gods.
</P>
<P>
   _The video goal judge doesn't have to bite his lip if he clearly
sees a crease infraction. However, the referee maintains the right
to allow a goal in such circumstances if he believes the attacking
player was pushed into the crease by a defending player.
</P>
<P>
   _If the addition of a second referee brings the desired results,
there is an outside chance that all of next year's playoff games
will have four on-ice officials on duty: two referees and two
linesmen. The league will have to hire a handful of full-time
referees for the phase-in period this year and upward of 16 more if
it becomes a 1,107-game (27 cities, 41 home games per team)
proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Bettman also said the league will levy stiffer suspensions to
players who deliberately use sticks or elbows that result in head
injuries to opponents. During the preseason, the league also will
experiment with the elimination of the center-ice red line in
regard to two-line (offside) passes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
