<HEADLINE>
KING LAWYER ERRS DURING TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don King's lawyers were recovering Thursday from a strategic
error that led a federal judge to throw out two days of key
testimony in the promoter's criminal retrial for allegedly
defrauding a Lloyd's of London syndicate by faking expenses after a
Julio Cesar Chavez fight was canceled in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   King's defense chose a risky path to question Donald Cayea, a
syndicate lawyer. Peter Fleming Jr. and King's other lawyers were
barred by U.S. District Judge Lawrence McKenna from identifying
themselves as the same King team at the settlement talks, lest they
be recast as unsworn witnesses, and possibly dispute testimony by a
sworn witness. But late Wednesday, Fleming said, ``I was there,''
while questioning Cayea.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming called the slip-up a mistake, and McKenna believed it
was inadvertent. Fleming said the loss of the testimony did not
kill the defense's case.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna ordered the jurors to disregard the testimony, without
saying that Fleming had violated a court order.
</P>
<P>
   Cayea's most contentious testimony, that King's defense offered
money to settle the civil fraud case to get potentially exculpatory
evidence for the criminal trial, led King's lawyers to ask for a
mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   King's defense said no such offer occurred, and accused Baruch
Weiss, an assistant U.S. attorney, of eliciting testimony he knew
was wrong. McKenna did not rule on the mistrial application. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
