<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Friday, June 26. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANDARDS (Phoenix) _ Fordham foundation rates Arizona's
academic standards as the best in the nation. By CATHERYN CRENO.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AHCCCS (Phoenix) _ Beverly HIlls millioinaire and Valley apartment
mogul Michael Phillips recently got an operation here. Trouble is,
authorities say, he claimed he was destitute and conned
AHCCCS,Arizona's healthcare system for the indigent, into paying
for the knifework. Phillips was arrested Thursday, but AHCCCS
officials say there are hundreds like him out there and they may
have nicked the state for as much as $250,000,000 just in the last
year.By SUSAN STECKNER and WILLIAMHERMANN. Story will move in the
``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   VETO (Washington) _ The US Supreme Court onThursday struck down
what John McCain and congressonal republicans had hoped would be
their legacy: a law giving the president authority to curb
pork-barrel spending through limited veto authority. The court's
6-3 decision (with Arizona's O'Conner dissenting) capped a rough
fortnight for McCain, who had worked for this for 10 years.
McCain's tobacco bill was defeated last week, and at the same time
he came under fire for making a crude joke about the president's
daughter. By JEFF BARKER. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   DIRTYAIR (Phoenix) _ Coal-fired power plants built before 1977
are the dirtiest, are exempt from new clean-air standards and could
hold an unfair economic advantage _ and never be cleaned up _ under
efforts to deregulate the electric-utility industry. Ending this
regulation ``loophole'' from six plants in Arizona, for example,
would reduce as much air pollution as removing 2.3 million cars
from the road, or every car in Maricopa County. A
consumer-environmental group, U.S. Public Interest Research Group,
calls on Congress to eliminate the loopholes for older plants. By
STEVE YOZWIAK. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
