<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7552 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPECTOR-SUIT-ART-700(     06-25 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECTOR-SUIT-ART-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RONETTES' SUIT SAYS PHIL SPECTOR OWES THEM $10 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
 (JT)  
 By GLENN COLLINS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; So won't you say you love me,  &LR;   &UR; I'll make you so proud of me,
 &LR;   &UR; We'll make 'em turn their heads  &LR;   &UR; Every place we go.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As it had to, it all began with a love song, and
those were the words: the lyrics of ``Be My Baby,'' co-written by
Phil Spector and sung by his future wife, Ronnie, and the other
Ronettes.
</P>
<P>
   They were the first of the great bad-girl groups, and with their
architecturally unstable black beehive hairdos and provocative dark
eye makeup, they whu-oh-oh-oh'd their sultry way to stardom. ``Be
My Baby'' sold more than 2 million copies in 1963, even more than
their other hits like ``Baby I Love You'' and ``Walking in the
Rain.''
</P>
<P>
   But now the music is over, and in a civil lawsuit in the cramped
chambers of State Supreme Court in Manhattan, 24 years after her
divorce, Ronnie Spector Greenfield and the two other Ronettes are
suing the rock legend for $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is a spectacle that has provided further evidence, as
if more were needed, that the Golden Oldies age expired not with a
bang, or a whimper, or even a doo-wop, but with a bleat of lawyers.
Echoing an increasingly popular refrain among performers from that
era, the Ronettes contend that they were cheated by a conniving
producer who took advantage of their naivete, exploited their
talent and left them with little to show for their stardom but
memories.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs claim that after recording 28 songs with Spector,
they were paid a pittance in the early 1960s, and that Spector has
wrongly deprived them of millions, not only from the sale of their
records but also from the licensing of their hit songs in
commercials and television shows like ``Moonlighting,'' and in
films like ``Dirty Dancing'' and ``Goodfellas.''
</P>
<P>
   Spector says the Ronettes were simply hirelings, rock 'n' roll
elements in the complex mini-symphonies he conceived and recorded,
and that the success of the records was attributable to his
production wizardry. Furthermore, his lawyers contend, Mrs.
Greenfield signed away all her rights to royalties in their 1974
divorce settlement.
</P>
<P>
   This week, as Spector has defended himself in the witness box,
spectators have swarmed the courtroom for a glimpse of the creator
of the Wall of Sound: Spector's much-imitated recording technique
of overdubbing squadrons of guitars, pianos and percussion
instruments in a wave of hormone-thrilling noise.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, visitors have often experienced the sound of
silence. Long pauses have punctuated the 58-year-old Spector's
sometimes inaudible answers to lawyers' questions.
</P>
<P>
   In his frequently affectless testimony, there is little evidence
of the rocker who played guitar in the Rolling Stones recording of
``Play With Fire.'' At times he has seemed positively elfin as he
slyly parried questions from the plaintiffs' lawyer. At other
times, his demeanor was so dour it recalled the drug-pusher
character he played in a cameo appearance in the 1969 film ``Easy
Rider.''
</P>
<P>
   With his pale visage shrouded as ever by inky shades and framed
by dark shoulder-length hair, Spector has favored black shirts,
black and blue silk ties and black platform shoes, set off by a red
AIDS ribbon and a diamond earring in his left ear.
</P>
<P>
   In her turn on the witness stand, the 54-year-old Mrs.
Greenfield has described her life as a Ronette from Spanish Harlem
who toured the world as a star, and has told horror stories of her
marriage of nearly six years to Spector.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the drama inherent in these revelations of an
ooh-wah donnybrook, the testimony has at times put observers to
sleep with technical discussions of ``synchronization rights'' and
``recording masters,'' not to mention long evidentiary
presentations of records and discs referred to by the lawyers as
``product.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the nonjury trial came to a temporary hiatus after
hours of legal wrangling; due to Judge Paula Omansky's crowded
court schedule, trial proceedings will resume on July 13.
</P>
<P>
   His former wife's case ``is all a lot of nonsense,'' said
Spector after he stepped down from the stand. ``Some people, after
30 years, maybe they could realize that they have something to do
with the fact that they're not Tina Turner or Diana Ross.''
</P>
<P>
   Out in the hallway, signing autographs and wearing sunglasses
even darker than Spector's, Mrs. Greenfield said, ``I'm stunned
that this has finally come to trial.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``He owes me big time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Ronettes _ Ronnie, her sister and their cousin _ had started
performing in 1959, but first won music-mogul attention in 1961 as
singing go-go dancers in the Joey Dee Review at the Peppermint
Lounge in Manhattan during the frenzy over Chubby Checker and the
Twist. Soon they were recruited as live performers in Murray the
K's rock shows; Spector took notice and tried to sign their lead
singer, Veronica Bennett _ Ronnie _ to his Philles record label.
</P>
<P>
   But the group loyally stuck together, so Spector signed them
all, first as background vocalists for Darlene Love and other
Spector stars, and then as the centerpiece of their own Wall of
Sound recordings. By 1964, Spector became their manager, but by the
time he married Ronnie in 1968, the group had disbanded.
</P>
<P>
   The two divorced in 1974. In his testimony, Spector described
his relationship with Ronnie as ``a good strong loving
relationship,'' though he noted, over the Ronettes' lawyer's
objection, that ``Veronica had a lot of problems with drinking and
mixing medication.''
</P>
<P>
   In court and in her 1986 autobiography, titled, not
surprisingly, ``Be My Baby,'' Mrs. Greenfield has alleged that
Spector engaged in bizarre and psychologically abusive behavior in
their 23-room Los Angeles mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Spector's reputation as a top-of-the-charts cut-up dates back to
the late 1950s, when he told interviewers that the theme of his
first big hit, ``To Know Him Is to Love Him,'' was taken from the
inscription on his father's gravestone. Soon he was being profiled
as ``the First Tycoon of Teen.''
</P>
<P>
   But during the trial, Mrs. Greenfield testified that Spector
frustrated her singing career and held her as a virtual prisoner,
confiscating her shoes and surrounding her with guard dogs.
</P>
<P>
   She also testified that she had signed their 1974 divorce
settlement, including a clause forfeiting all future record
profits, because ``Phil threatened me several times.'' She added:
``He told me `I'll kill you' and said, `I'll have a hit man kill
you.'''
</P>
<P>
   On the witness stand, Spector denied that he kept his wife as an
involuntary prisoner and he rejected the hit man allegations,
saying rather joylessly, ``I've heard them over the last 20
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The divorce allegations are irrelevant to the case, said Andrew
Bart, Spector's lawyer. But Alexander Peltz, the Ronettes' lawyer,
said, ``The marital testimony goes to the issue of what she gave up
in the divorce settlement, and what feelings he had against her,
and why he prevented her from getting any money all those years.''
</P>
<P>
   Peltz is seeking damages for breach of contract as well as
former and future earnings, and he says the Ronettes are entitled
to share in profits from the original recordings.
</P>
<P>
   Bart says that it is ``a simple case,'' since Mrs. Greenfield
signed away all her rights to the group's recording earnings in her
divorce settlement and thereby invalidated a 1963 contract signed
by the Ronettes. ``She released Phil and all of his companies from
claims, contracts and legal action,'' Bart said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Greenfield ``is trying to build a case out of sympathy
instead of legal principle,'' Bart contended.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to make Phil look like an ogre,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Including the preliminary maneuvering, the legal action has
dragged on for 13 years. Mrs. Greenfield has remarried and had two
children, and lives in Connecticut. Her husband, Jonathan, her
manager, hovered protectively on Wednesday when she joined the
spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Spector has been sporadically active in the music business since
the appearance of his magnum opus, ``Phil Spector: Back to Mono,''
a boxed collection of his work from 1958 to 1969 that appeared
early this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The other plaintiffs are Mrs. Greenfield's sister, Estelle
Bennett Dong, and her cousin, Nedra Talley Ross. ``He's totally
cheated us for 35 years,'' said the 52-year-old Mrs. Ross, who runs
a restaurant and an importing business these days in Virginia
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Love, the rock diva whose classic ``(Today I Met) The Boy
I'm Going to Marry'' was a 1960s Phil Spector hit, is attending the
trial ``in a show of support'' for the Ronettes, she said from her
seat in Courtroom 205. She has known Mrs. Greenfield since 1962,
when they met at a Murray the K show at the Brooklyn Fox Theater.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't easy getting money out of rock 'n' roll icons. A jury
in New City gave Ms. Love a $260,000 judgment against Spector for
unpaid royalties last year, but the judge ordered it reduced to
$130,000; the judge's ruling is on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Others have sat in the audience to behold the sheer spectacle of
what they've called the ``Spector Show,'' notching a life sighting
of the man who was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in
1989. ``He's a go-see,'' said Don Chaisson, a video promoter from
Hempstead, of Spector. ``He rarely makes appearances.''
</P>
<P>
   Spector himself, during his testimony, summed up the story in a
phrase worthy of the Wall of Sound. ``It's so sad to see good love
go bad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
