<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-ASSASSINATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO LIKELY TO AUTHORIZE LIMITED INQUIRY INTO KING ASSASSINATION
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno's aides have advised
her to go forward with a review of key pieces of evidence in the
assassination of Dr. Martin Luther King. But law enforcement
officials said they had no reason to believe that that James Earl
Ray was wrongly convicted of the murder, law enforcement officials
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has been under pressure from the family of the civil rights
leader to reexamine evidence in the case in light of more advanced
forensic techniques than those available in 1968 when King was
killed. These tests could be used to examine the bullet that killed
King and the rifle which bore fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   Reno met with advisers on Thursday in an effort to reach a
decision, which could be announced as early as Friday. After an
evening discussion, officials said, she seemed unlikely to
authorize the creation of the broad fact-finding body sought by the
King family and appeared to favor a much narrower inquiry into a
few details of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the effort to reexamine the case is a belief among some
of King's family members, including his widow, Coretta Scott King,
that Ray might not have acted alone. Mrs. King met with Reno in
April saying she had presented new evidence to the attorney
general, but did not elaborate on the nature of the information.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has left Justice Department officials in an awkward
spot. They are reluctant to avoid offending a prominent family with
powerful Democratic allies in Congress and the White House. Yet
Justice Department officials are unwilling to reopen the case and
remain skeptical that a fresh review would yield significant new
information.
</P>
<P>
   Most investigators who have examined the case in the 30 years
since King's death have long concluded that King was shot to death,
as he stood on the balconey of the Lorraine Motel in Memphis, by a
single bullet fired from a deer rifle by Ray, a loner with powerful
racist motives.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, who died in April, was serving a 99-year sentence for the
1968 shooting. He confessed to the shooting and pleaded guilty, but
quickly recanted his confession. Until his death, he suggested that
a shadowy conspiracy, for which he offered no evidence, was behind
the killing.
</P>
<P>
   The most thorough examination of the case by the House Select
Committee on Assassinations, found that Ray fired the fatal shot
and that if co-conspirators existed they were probably limited to
family members and some racist militants in St. Louis who were
known the Ray family and had put a bounty on King's life.
</P>
<P>
   A recent book on the subject, ``Killing the Dream,'' by Gerald
Posner, which some reviewers said was a definitive study of the
assassination, found no credible evidence to support Ray's
contention that he was manipulated into a conspiracy, or that the
FBI or CIA covered up evidence in King's murder.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a retired FBI agent said that he had found
two slips of paper in Ray's car that were said to bear the named
``Raul'' on them. One slip contained list of payments to
unidentified people and organizations. The FBI said the agent was
not part of the search team and dismissed the assertion as a
``total fabrication.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the case stirred such deep passions, that it has
never been fully brought to rest. Ray repeatedly tried and failed
to win a new trial, saying he was set up and that someone else
fired the fatal shot. During prison interviews he spoke of taking
orders from a man he identified as Raoul, or at other times as
Raul, whose identity has never been positively established.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the King family avoided being drawn into Ray's legal
maneuvering. But last year the King family began publicly voicing
doubts that Ray acted alone and Mrs. King, in an emotional court
proceeding pleaded with a federal judge to grant Ray a new trail.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of reexamining the case has divided some of King's
admirers. On one side were those who complained that the effort was
a said that waste of time, But Mrs. King had pleaded with the
federal courts to grant Ray a new trial as an opportunity to
examine new facts and explore the nature of racism that led to the
crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
