</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDWEST-POWER-CUTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILITIES URGE SAVING POWER IN HOT MIDWEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Ill., Wis.)   (af)  
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Utilities throughout the Midwest asked millions of customers
Thursday to cut the use of appliances, including air conditioners,
because of a heat wave that has resulted in a surge in demand for
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Major industries also reduced operations in the Midwest on
Thursday, canceling shifts or sending workers home early, to
conserve power.
</P>
<P>
   Most utilities have been able to avoid blacking out parts of
their service areas. But some utilities have warned that they will
impose blackouts if voluntary cuts in power use are insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Although a heat wave is the main cause of the power shortages,
they have been compounded by severe storms in recent days that
knocked out important transmission lines in Ohio. And many nuclear
power plants have been closed for the summer for maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   ``A serious electric power problem has developed,'' said
American Electric Power Co., a leading utility based in Columbus,
Ohio, in a warning to its 7.5 million customers in areas that cover
parts of seven states. Utilities in the region scrambled Thursday
to buy surplus power, causing prices to soar temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases power sold for $4,000 per megawatt hour, the
standard unit of measurement. Normally a megawatt hour sells for
$25 to $50.
</P>
<P>
   ``These prices are astronomical,'' said Jim Owen, a spokesman
for the Edison Electric Institute, a trade group for the utility
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Many major industrial customers in states like Ohio, Illinois
and Wisconsin complied with voluntary agreements made with their
utilities to reduce consumption in periods when demand outruns the
capacity of the utilities' power plants.
</P>
<P>
   LTV Corp., a steelmaker, closed a plant in Cleveland and reduced
production at others in the Midwest. Sun Oil Co. said it had shut
its refinery in Toledo, Ohio, because of storm damage to power
supply equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Warnings issued by ComEd, a utility that supplies 3.4 million
customers in northern Illinois, were typical of how Midwest
utilities sought to weather the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ComEd asked residential customers not to run major appliances
until after 7 p.m. It asked 300 of its large commercial customers
to cut back to save about 800 megawatts of power, which caused some
to shut operations for a shift.
</P>
<P>
   The utility also asked about 100 municipal governments to shut
off appliances and lights at buildings. Many complied.
</P>
<P>
   Don Kirchoffner, a spokesman for ComEd, said the voluntary cuts
and the purchase of power at high prices allowed the utility to get
through the day without shutting off power.
</P>
<P>
   Kirchoffner said the utility was forced to buy power from
outsiders, paying about $4 million for what normally would have
cost $100,000 to $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Cinergy, the parent of Cincinnati Gas &AMP; Electric Co., also
beseeched customers to conserve power, as did some utilities in
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   John Procario, the vice president of the electric system of
Cinergy, said ``the growing demand could strain the system to the
point that we would need to implement rotating blackouts to prevent
a failure of the entire system.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts said the danger of major blackout was remote and
that the utilities will be able to get through.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
