   HOWIE-COX (Undated) _ You know him as Howie Mandel, the standup
comic who's championed bullhorn-style wackiness for years. Today,
meet Howard Mandel, TV's newest daytime talk show host.
</P>
<P>
   PHIL-COLLINS-TEX (Houston) _ Take a look at him now. Phil
Collins, the venerable 47-year-old pop icon, is trying to reinvent
himself _ and his music. And not everybody is happy. By Andy Summa.
</P>
<P>
   MARIO-LANZA-NYT (Undated) _ The renewed popularity of the late
Mario Lanza. By Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   SENEGAL-SINGER-NYT (Dakar) _ This West African capital has been
throbbing for years with nightclubs. Walls are pasted with concert
posters, and street merchants peddling cassettes can talk
knowledgeably about musicians from across the region. So it's no
surprise that any taxi driver can point to a landmark on the the
city's corniche, or seaside road: the home of Youssou N'Dour, one
of the world's best-known African singers. By Vivienne Walt.
</P>
<P>
   BRANDY-MUSIC-$ADV28-NYT (Undated) _ Imagine cruising along a
coastal road at sunset in a cherry-red sports car with the top
down. Sure, the image is a cliche. But does every experience have
to be original to be fun? The appeal of ``Never Say Never,'' the
second album by the teen-age rhythm `n' blues singer Brandy, lies
not in her inventing anything new but in her delivering familiar
pleasures with all the accessories. And she can really sing. By
Dimitri Ehrlich.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-MCLACHLAN-SPI (Undated) _ Sarah McLachlan is bright,
thoughtful and quick to make fun of herself, wasn't out to prove
anything. But the success of Lilith Fair erased any doubts about
the commercial viability of a large-scale all-women tour. By Gene
Stout.
</P>
<P>
   SPICE17-COX (West Palm Beach) _ As the group launches its first
American tour and as ``Spice World'' makes its way to video stores,
it's increasingly obvious that determination is the only true
factor in the Spice Girls' remarkable success story. By Charles
Passy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOGS-AND-PEOPLE (New York) _ ``Don't eat the eyes.'' Now there's
a sentence to consider. You could either be having dinner in
Chinatown _ or talking to a dog. In this case, Caroline Knapp, the
author of the best-selling memoir, ``Drinking: A Love Story'' (Dial
Press, 1996) is addressing Lucille, her 3-year-old German shepherd
mix, who has been systematically gutting a stuffed animal _ a
lemming, to be exact. Ms. Knapp remains calm in the face of
annihilation. She has written a new book, ``Pack of Two: The
Intricate Bond Between People and Dogs'' (Dial Press), a
thoughtful, sensitive analysis of the all-out love affair she
unexpectedly found in her relationship with Lucille and that other
people, especially women, find with their own dogs. By Alex
Witchel.
</P>
<P>
   SHEEHY-COX (Atlanta) _ Author Gail Sheehy has some news for
middle-aged men who think Viagra is going to solve all their
problems. By Don O'Briant.
</P>
