<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton says rural areas ``cannot rely on agriculture alone
to sustain their economy.'' Right. They also need a cafe with
homemade pies.
</P>
<P>
   ``American farmers have become so productive and so advanced,''
Mr. Clinton says, ``that agriculture should be considered another
high-tech industry.'' We'll watch for Winnows 98.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if watermelon is a fruit or vegetable,'' says Mr.
Clinton. ``I think it's something in between.'' One thing's sure _
watermelon is Democratic. The GOP has watermelone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come a long way from the days when Thomas Jefferson
thought every American should be a farmer,'' the president says.
Right. Now most Americans think they're Thomas Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   ``American agriculture,'' says Mr. Clinton, ``is one of our most
powerful export engines.'' Yes, but along with food off the farm,
could we also export some of the smell?
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that our nation's core values in many ways have
their deepest roots in rural America,'' Mr. Clinton says. Like
``Watch where you step.''
</P>
<P>
   The president calls the Census ``the single most important
source of information about the American people.'' The Census? Not
Rush Limbaugh?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's likely I will run for president in the year 2000,'' Dan
Quayle says. No word what he'll do in 2001 and on.
</P>
<P>
   A national commission says America is becoming a ``nation of
spectators.'' Yes, and we're often willing to pay scalpers' prices
for the privilege, too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HERE LIZARD, LIZARD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DAVID GRIMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune &LR;
</P>
<P>
   As if the prospect of coexisting with tens of millions of pink,
sterile medflies were not daunting enough, we Floridians are now
being threatened by mobs of six-foot, tail-whipping iguanas.
</P>
<P>
   As is so often the case, this particular problem originated in
California. Back in the late '80s and early '90s, South American
green iguanas were considered trendy pets and were being imported
to this country by the tens of thousands. What people didn't
realize - and weren't told - was that the cute little lizards
quickly grow into dragon-size creatures that carry disease, tear up
the house and wield their heavy tails like broadswords
</P>
<P>
   Life is unpleasant enough in California what with earthquakes
and Starbucks and everything, so people began abandoning their pets
faster than you can say, ``Run for your life! Another bad Godzilla
movie!''
</P>
<P>
   Animal shelters were soon up to here with the little darlings
and stopped accepting castaways. Finding foster homes for
columnist-size creatures that run like a deer and have an annoying
habit of leaping through your screen door or pool cage has been no
easy matter, either.
</P>
<P>
   All of which would be nothing more than another good reason not
to visit Los Angeles were it not for the fact that iguanas are now
becoming a problem in Phoenix and, yes, Florida.
</P>
<P>
   If you are the kind of person who only ventures outside long
enough to hose the malathion off your car, then chances are good
that you will escape being impaled on the sharp tail of an angry
six-foot iguana, at least for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida is nothing if not conducive to biodiversity, so I
predict it will not be long before iguanas are thicker than love
bugs here, and considerably more trouble to scrape off your
windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly we need some sort of long-term strategy, something more
clever and cunning than a bumper sticker campaign urging iguanas to
go back where they came from. (This didn't work with people from Up
North, so I see no reason why it would work on iguanas, which, from
what I've read, are even more cantankerous than New Yorkers, if you
can imagine such a thing.)
</P>
<P>
   One possible strategy - and it is not an appealing one, I admit
- is to simply learn to get along with the iguanas. According to
the Reuters story I read, iguanas get jumpy when they do not get
enough affection, and a jumpy iguana is the kind of iguana that
turns its owner into shish kebab. The story recommends that you
take your iguana into the shower with you as the mist is good for
the lizard's skin. The story did not say anything about bubble
baths, but I presume iguanas would like that, too, though you
probably ought to take care where you sit.
</P>
<P>
   While you are bathing with your iguana, you might want to engage
it in conversation, as that would help relax it, and a relaxed
iguana is less likely to poke a hole in your liver with its tail.
One thing you definitely want to avoid discussing is that iguanas
carry salmonella bacteria on their skin and are sometimes infested
with ticks. Iguanas do not respond well to having their personal
hygiene called into question, so you probably ought to talk about
something more innocuous, like the weather, unless you want to end
up like that unfortunate housewife in ``Terminator 2.''
</P>
<P>
   If possible, you might want to chat with your iguana about how
nice Central America is this time of year, as there is a chance
that will make it homesick for the jungles of its native Guatemala
or El Salvador or wherever it came from. Do not discuss any
political unrest that might be occurring in that region as iguanas
get fidgety when the talk turns to politics and a fidgety iguana is
an iguana that skewers your pancreas as if it were a martini olive.
</P>
<P>
   While you want to be affectionate with your iguana, you do not
want to be too affectionate because then the iguana will have no
reason to leave. For that reason, candlelight dinners are out, as
are foot rubs and back rubs.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Sarasota (Fla.)
Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
