<SLUG> BC-HKN-AWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' BURNS, SAMSONOV HONORED BY LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Bruins scored twice here Thursday night, with
Sergei Samsonov officially named the NHL's new kid on the block and
Pat Burns crowned again as king of the turnarounds.
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov, who began last season just days shy of his 19th
birthday, became the sixth Bruin to be named the league's Calder
Award winner as rookie of the year. And the 47-year-old Burns, who
only last May inherited a Bruins' team fresh off finishing dead
last in the standings, was named the Adams Award winner as coach of
the year, his third time capturing the award.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our Academy Awards,'' said a beaming Burns, who
earlier in the day said he was convinced that Dallas' Ken Hitchcock
would win the award. ``We've directed films all year long, and
there are stars of the movies...and you have the directors who are
coaches--it's almost like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov, near tears on the podium, rattled off the customary
list of thank yous, including his teammates, club managenent, even
his agent. He then gestured to his father and said, ``Dad, this
one's for you.'' Viktor Samsonov sat stoically in the crowd, his
sapphire eyes watering.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one who brought me up to hockey,'' said Samsonov, the
first Bruin since Ray Bourque in 1980 to capture the Calder. ``He
helped me the most. He deserves it as much as I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns was the first Bostonian named coach of the year since Don
Cherry won it 1976. Cherry was also a runnerup in '78, as were Mike
Milbury in 1990 and Brian Sutter in '93. Burns won the Adams in '93
with the Maple Leafs and in '89 with the Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was question of, I think, they needed leadership,'' said
Burns, referring to his arrival in Boston last spring. ``I was
fortunate to have Ray Bourque there for his leadership, but I think
the players were looking for other leadership, too, and that came
from me, Jacques Laperriere and Bobby Francis.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns was a busy man earlier in the week when the Bruins'
protected list for today's expansion draft was made public. Two
players he helped steer to the Bruins as free agents last summer,
Dave Ellett and Ken Baumgartner, were left left unprotected for the
draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of them called me and wanted to know what was up,'' said
Burns. ``I told them I didn't know, but I'd find out and get back
to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he then promptly called Boston general manager Harry
Sinden and assistant GM Mike O'Connell for an explanation. He was
told, esssentially, that business was business and the Bruins were
opting to protect younger players, including the likes of Darren
Van Impe and Landon Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Mike and Harry to call both of them and explain it,''
said Burns. ``I think (Baumgartner and Ellett) both understand it's
a business, but I think it was important for them to have it
explained to them, that's all. I didn't know it was coming. I said,
`Guys, I don't know, but I'll look into it.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's highly unlikely that either Ellett or Baumgartner will be
taken in the draft. The Predators are expected to take checking
center Mike Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what free agents he thinks the Bruins might persue this
summer, beginning next week, Burns said any coach would like to
have the likes of Doug Gilmour or Ron Francis--two of the premier
unrestricted free agents available--on his roster. However, Burns
didn't sound as if either Gilmour or Francis would be heading to
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me a long time ago, `You'll have to do the best with
the guy you have,''' said Burns. ``And, hey, that's fine, I accept
that. We have a good bunch of guys and I wouldn't want to see that
chemistry changed. There are bargains and bandits in free agency,
and you have to look out for the bandits.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's superstar goalie, Dominik Hasek, won the Hart Trophy
as the league's MVP for the second straight season--the first
goalie to take the award in consecutive seasons. The star of the
gold-medal-winning Czech Olympic team also won his fourth Vezina
Trophy in five years, again chosen the game's top netminder. The
Kings' Rob Blake won the Norris Trophy as the game's top
defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas right wing Jere Lehtinen was the Selke Trophy winner as
the game's top checker. St. Louis netminder Jamie McLennan won the
Masterton Award, for perseverance and sportsmanship, battling back
after a life-threatening bout of bacterial meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov, with 43 of 54 first-place votes, bested a field that
included fellow finalists Mattias Ohlund (D, Vancouver) and Patrik
Elias (F, New Jersey). Burns collected 48 of 87 first-place votes,
finsihing ahead of Larry LA's Larry Robinson and Hitchcock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
