<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-ASSEMBLY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING PREPARES FOR NEW ASSEMBLY LINE IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KAREN WEST  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As part of its preparations to establish a new
assembly line in California, Boeing is sending by rail a mock-up
fuselage section of its longest 737 aircraft from its factory in
Wichita, Kan.,to Long Beach, according to an internal company memo
to managers.
</P>
<P>
   While a final decision has not yet been made on the California
assembly line, the experimental train trip is being conducted to
make sure the 125-foot-long 737-900 fuselage isn't too big for the
route and to determine how long the journey will take.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any project of this scope, there are certain steps we
need to take in order to prove the feasibility of the project and
protect our ability to move ahead,'' Fred Mitchell, Boeing's
executive vice president for airplane production said in a June 22
company bulletin sent to managers. ``In a sense, we are buying
insurance so that if we do make the decision to locate an
additional next-generation 737 line at Long Beach, we can do so
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing officials are hoping the ``simulated rail-car
transfers,'' which will be made in the next few weeks, will help
them decide whether it makes good business sense to create a new
production line to build certain 737 models at its Douglas Products
Division. Because it's a new model, another fuselage mock-up _ a
wooden shell of the aircraft's body section _ also will be sent by
rail to Boeing's Renton factory, where the 737 and 757 airplanes
are currently built.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure everything goes smoothly,'' Boeing
spokesman Sean O'Donnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also is preparing for the new line by clearing out an
aircraft production bay now used to build MD-11 jets at the Long
Beach factory. In addition, the company is upgrading the assembly
area, installing electrical power supplies and appointing teams to
head up 737 production work at the Southern California plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get a sense of space and proportions,'' O'Donnell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing announced in May that it is sending some 737 aircraft to
its Douglas Products Division for finishing work.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the company said its Renton aircraft factory was
overloaded with work and that it had nearly run out of room to
build all of its 737 models there.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing hasn't been able to keep up with demand for its
airplanes, and as a result, many of its airline customers have been
left waiting impatiently to take delivery of their jets, mainly the
next-generation 737 models.
</P>
<P>
   The plan to shift finishing work, and a study to establish a new
737 assembly line in California has had leaders of Boeing's largest
union threatening legal action or a possible strike when their
contract expires in December 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Johnson, president of District Lodge 751 of the
International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers in
Seattle, has said he would do everything he could to prevent 737
assembly from moving to Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   But after a meeting earlier this month with Boeing Chairman Phil
Condit and other company executives, Johnson said he would hold off
on recommending legal action or walkouts as long as dialogue with
the company continues.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, whose union represents 39,000 Boeing workers, could not
be reached for comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, leaders of the separate United Aerospace Workers
union at the underused Long Beach commercial jet factory, which
employs about 10,000 people, welcomes the move.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said a decision on the new assembly line will be made
in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   The company has said that the Long Beach plant ``can provide
some relief because we don't have enough people or space for all
the work.''
</P>
<P>
   If a 737 assembly line were established in California, it would
focus on final assembly of airplanes such as the Boeing Business
Jet and the cargo version of the jet, which have significantly
different configurations from the next generation 737s ordered by
most airline customers. In addition, Boeing would consider doing
assembly work on the 737-900 model in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the decision, Mitchell said Boeing will still use
its Renton factory as the primary final assembly location for 737
and 757 airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   In an inhouse memo sent to managers last month, Boeing said that
a new next-generation 737 assembly line in Long Beach would account
for about 17 percent of the production hours for each 737 built
there.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the work _ such as wings, fuselage, aircraft systems
and interiors _ would continue to be done at Boeing facilities by
members of the local Machinists union.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing announced earlier this year that it will phase out
production of the MD-80, MD-90 and MD-11 airplanes, leaving only
the Boeing 717 _ formerly the MD-95 _ left at the California plant.
</P>
<P>
   If the company goes ahead with a new production line in Long
Beach, it would be the first time Boeing has ever established
commercial aircraft
</P>
<P>
   final-assembly operations outside the Puget Sound area.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing inherited the Long Beach factory when it acquired
McDonnell Douglas last year in a $16.3 billion stock deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
