<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-MIATA-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIATA CLUB HOLDS ANNUAL MEETING IN POCONO MOUNTAINS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Del.)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first redesign of the Mazda Miata sports car since it was
introduced in 1989 has helped make the Miata Club of America's
annual gathering this week in the Pocono Mountains of Eastern
Pennsylvania a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 owners of the two-seat roadsters from the United
States, Canada and Europe will descend on the Split Rock Resort in
Lake Harmony to speed around the Pocono Raceway, caravan through
winding mountain roads, participate in road-rally scavenger hunts
and shop for accessories sold by the companies that are acting as
sponsors, including Michelin and Mazda's marketing arms in Canada
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more excitement for the event this year because the
new car has just come out,'' said Dave Thomas, the organizer of
Miata Mountain Madness and a former president of the Delaware
Valley Miata Club, the host of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Tidwell, the president of the Miata Club of America, said
of the club's eighth annual convention: ``This is about as big as
it gets. ``It's not bigger because we are limited in the number of
people who can attend.''
</P>
<P>
   From bank executives to United Parcel Service drivers, the
thread linking those who will gather in the Poconos from June 30 to
July 3 is ownership of a Miata. Some are young professionals; most
are in their mid-40s with children who are already grown.
</P>
<P>
   Many, like Thomas, an executive at a Philadelphia direct-mail
company, are former owners of the British sports cars after which
the highly successful Miata was patterned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owned a Triumph Spitfire as a teen-ager, and a lot of the
club members owned MGs and Alfa Romeos,'' said Thomas, who lives in
Gulph Mills, Pa., and owns one of the 350 Laguna blue and tan
Miatas that were made in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Miata offers the same kind of fun as those British sports
cars but without the oil spot in your driveway,'' he said,
referring to the notoriously unreliable vehicles of an earlier
generation. ``And it cranks up every time you turn it on, unlike
some of the British cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Formed on Nov. 1, 1987, the Miata Club of America existed even
before there was a car or a name for the car then known to be under
development at Mazda. Since then, more than 65,000 people have been
members. There are 25,000 people on the rolls now.
</P>
<P>
   The $29-a-year membership fee covers a subscription to Miata
magazine, which is filled with advertising for Miata products like
tires, wheels, car covers and floor mats.
</P>
<P>
   While this week's convention has a lengthy list of scheduled
activities, most people come to socialize. ``This is largely a
social club that brings people from all walks of life together
because of this little car,'' Thomas said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
