A7585 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-FOLLOW-HNS &LR;      06-25 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-FOLLOW-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NBA draft results in agony and ecstasy
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two things were clear after the NBA draft Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   First, few people were happier than the Rockets after taking
their three first-round selections. They literally danced in their
war room when they saw how the picks in front of them unfolded,
leaving their prime choices on the board.
</P>
<P>
   Second, few people were sadder than the high schoolers, present
and future.
</P>
<P>
   While the Rockets rejoiced in their good fortune and their
tireless evaluation of talent that yielded Michael Dickerson, Bryce
Drew and Mirsad Turkcan, high schoolers Al Harrington, Rashard
Lewis and Korleone Young _ and perhaps a legion of future prep
stars weighing the NBA as an option to college _ were sent a
tough-love message by the league: Stay in school for at least one
year of college.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington was the only high school player taken in the first
round, chosen 25th by the Indiana Pacers. Lewis, the Elsik High
School standout, went at No. 32 to the Seattle SuperSonics. Young
was the last of the trio taken, going 40th to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was the third pick of the second round, Young the 11th.
That means the money they sought by jumping from high school to the
pros won't be guaranteed. Only first-rounders sign guaranteed
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this doesn't get the message across to them, nothing
will,'' said NBA scout Marty Blake.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Harrington and Lewis were projected as solid first-round
material. But team after team _ including the Rockets _ passed on
the teen-agers to take players who had college experience or
Europeans who have played professionally.
</P>
<P>
   It might not stem the tide of players who try to make the jump
to the pros from high school. But it might be the start of the
pendulum swinging back toward the top high school players going to
college, even if for just one year of seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' case was particularly difficult. He was flown to the
draft by the NBA with the expectation he would be shaking hands
with David Stern at the podium as a first-round pick. Then, he
proceeded to say he felt betrayed by the hometown Rockets, thinking
they had given him assurances they would draft him with one of
their three first-round selections.
</P>
<P>
   All that did was compound the tough situation. Lewis is too
young and too talented to burn bridges with any team, let alone the
one that scouted him as much as any in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets did what they thought was best for their team. Their
three first-rounders, along with second-round pick Cuttino Mobley,
left them thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second leg of their offseason renovation of the
roster. The only sure holdovers from last season appear to be
Hakeem Olajuwon and Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   The first maneuver was to get two extra first-round draft picks
for Kevin Willis in a trade with Toronto. Now, the Rockets have
used those picks to the best of the team's ability.
</P>
<P>
   Their next task will be to dive into free agency Wednesday, or
whenever the NBA's dicey labor situation is resolved. It is likely
the league will lock out the players Wednesday, meaning no teams
can sign or have contact with free agents or their agents.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Rockets are expected to make a splash, with
perhaps as much as $10 million available under the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen, Tom Gugliotta, Kevin Johnson, Rod Strickland,
Damon Stoudamire, Jayson Williams, Antonio McDyess, Cedric
Ceballos, LaPhonso Ellis and Joe Smith are some of the top free
agents available.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets cannot talk to or about free agents until Wednesday
or whenever the lockout is lifted. But Pippen is believed to be No.
1 on their wish list.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rockets have as much luck in free agency as they did in
the draft, Pippen should be a Rocket before training camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
