<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-OAKLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR YOUTH-OR-BUST KNICKS, OAKLEY IS NO. 1 VICTIM 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marcus Camby is not known for breezing by in
olive-colored shoes with a Derby to match or for retrieving a loose
ball three rows back. He is not one to mangle metaphors, jumble
cliches or mix it up with an elbow.
</P>
<P>
   He is not Charles Oakley at all. Not in style, effort or
attitude. And the Knicks have decided Oakley is not their type
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   It's youth or bust now. The Knicks traded Oakley's savvy and
heart to Toronto for the athletic ability and unfulfilled potential
of Camby in a deal that was completed late Wednesday night.
Acquiring Camby does not fill the Knicks' most urgent need _ point
guard. So the team could still use Camby in a deal to secure that
position in the next week.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Knicks are claiming the 24-year-old Camby as their
own after giving the cash-poor Raptors their 44th pick in the
draft, Sean Marks, and an eye-catching $5 million to help offset
the $10 million that Oakley is scheduled to receive as a balloon
payment in the last year of his deal.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a trade that was welcomed by all within the Knicks'
organization. Although Patrick Ewing, who benefited from the
barbed-wire protection he received courtesy of the aggressive
Oakley for 10 years, gave his OK for the deal, there were those who
questioned whether it was wise to disrupt the makeup of the club by
sending their role player away.
</P>
<P>
   The anxiety of this decision was not lost on the Knicks' brain
trust. But one thing kept them focused on Camby. There was the
Indiana series, and the lasting images of how a tandem of young and
athletic forwards _ Antonio Davis and Dale Davis _ left the Knicks
looking more outdated than ever before as they bowed out in the
second round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What drove this was, `Are we a step behind or a step ahead of
Indiana?' I asked Jeff and Ernie this question,'' said Dave
Checketts, the president of Madison Square Garden, referring to
Coach Jeff Van Gundy and the team president Ernie Grunfeld. ``As
much as Knick fans are going to miss Oak, they have to ask
themselves that question, too. We agonized over this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the decision was also contract related. Oakley made it
no secret that he wanted to re-sign for another three or four years
after his deal expired next year, leaving the Knicks in a situation
where they would have had to pay a 35-year-old forward in the
sunset of his career. Camby, who also has a year left on his deal,
gives the Knicks more options for the future. And more flexibility
on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the trade changes the image of a team that has been to
the playoffs each of the 10 years that Oakley was there to grab
rebounds and strike fear into anyone foolish enough to look for an
easy layup. Oakley was the Knicks' interior defense enforcer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the trade injects some youth and flexibility,'' Buck
Williams said. ``But I think that with Oak gone, the Knicks can't
be looked at as this hard-nosed, bump-and-grind, dive-on-the-floor
type of team anymore. That image was carved from what Oak did.
Charles Oakley is irreplaceable.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby has to forge his own identity. He will arrive as the
former second-overall pick in the 1996 draft out of UMass with a
trail of off-the-court problems. When he was a student, Camby
violated National Collegiate Athletic Association rules when he
accepted cash and gifts from an agent. Last summer, he was charged
with possessing a small amount of marijuana, a charge that was
later dropped.
</P>
<P>
   In a turbulent two years in Toronto, Camby alternately wowed and
disappointed those with high expectations of him. The
6-foot-11-inch Camby has been fragile, missing more than 15 games
each season with foot and ankle injuries. And while the Knicks
intend to add weight to his spindly frame, it is likely that Larry
Johnson will move over to power forward, while Camby fills the
small forward position.
</P>
<P>
   Camby gives the team a jolt of energy, fresh legs and someone
who can take off in the open court. He adds speed to a team of
plodders. And he is a shot-blocking force who led the league with
230 blocked shots this season. Other than this, his other numbers
were down from his rookie year. He averaged 12.1 points a game,
shot 41 percent from the field and 61 percent from the line.
</P>
<P>
   It was a curious downswing from a player that has been viewed as
unmotivated by some general managers in the league. But maybe it
was the environment of losing in Toronto that dampened Camby's
finesse game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes young players longer to develop in certain
situations,'' Grunfeld said. ``He was in a situation where the team
was losing in Toronto. We want to put him in a good environment,
around veteran leadership and get the most of out him.''
</P>
<P>
   The very veteran who could help Camby's most would have been
Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate it so bad for him,'' Oakley's mother, Corine, said when
phoned at her home in Cleveland. ``He'll be disappointed, I know.
But he'll be fine. He'll adjust. He'll say something like,
`whatever ... nothin' you can do,' and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We would never give up a guy who has done so much for this
team and is still a very capable player to trade for someone we
didn't feel could help us win now,'' Van Gundy said. ``We're not
about winning down the future. So I don't think this is about
potential.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
