<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREACHER-TEACHER-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHER FIRED FOR PRAYING IN CLASS BECOMES A CAUSE CELEBRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Texas)   (bl)  
 By JACQUES STEINBERG with MACARENA HERNANDEZ   c.1998 N.Y. Times
News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The dismissal of Mildred Rosario would seem to be
clear cut.
</P>
<P>
   A substitute public school teacher in the Bronx, Ms. Rosario
readily admitted to school officials that she had led her sixth
graders in prayer on June 8, asking ``if anyone would like to
accept Jesus as their savior'' and then laying her hands on their
foreheads.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education saw this as a clear violation of the
separation of church and state and dismissed her four days later.
As a temporary worker, she was not entitled to the lengthy
disciplinary process mandated by the contract with the teachers'
union.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Rosario has since emerged as an unlikely cause celebre,
drawing the attention of not only religious-minded parents and
clerical leaders in New York City but also House Speaker Newt
Gingrich and the conservative Rutherford Institute, which
underwrote Paula Jones' suit against President Clinton and is
offering to fund any legal action Ms. Rosario may pursue.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, House Majority Whip Tom DeLay convened a news
conference on Capitol Hill attended by Ms. Rosario and other House
members to condemn her dismissal. Later, at a closed-door meeting
of House members known as the Values Action Team, Gingrich spoke of
Ms. Rosario's plight as ``important,'' DeLay's spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Gingrich's office said that while he was ``not
familiar with the details of this case,'' the speaker believed that
``praying'' was not an ``appropriate reason'' for a teacher to be
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   However much the letter of the law may be on its side, the Board
of Education has touched a raw nerve among those who feel that the
barriers against bringing religion into the classroom have been
maintained with far too much rigidity.
</P>
<P>
   But parents, politicians and others who support Ms. Rosario say
they also view her dismissal as an opportunity to lament the moral
decline of public education _ the same concerns, some of them add,
that have prompted them to support the introduction of publicly
financed vouchers to parochial schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. DeLay is interested for one very simple reason,'' said
Michael Scanlon, an aide to the Republican congressman. ``Our
public school systems are overrun with drugs, crime and guns, and
several undesirable influences. And while these children are
offered condoms and needles, they are denied the opportunity to
reach out to their teachers in times of grief and confusion because
it might strike up a conversation that deals with faith and
morality.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rosario, 43, a member of a Pentecostal church who is
weighing filing a grievance against the board, was quoted by The
Associated Press as telling the news conference: ``I am just a
simple schoolteacher from the South Bronx. I believe this is an
injustice and I hope that with the support gathered here I can get
back and teach my students.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That Ms. Rosario found herself in front of a classroom last fall
says much about the pressures on urban school systems. The school
in which she taught, Intermediate School 74, lies in District 8 in
the Hunts Point section of the South Bronx, an overcrowded district
that is short hundreds of licensed teachers. In September 1997, the
school, among the lowest-performing in the city, was shifted to a
special district, called the Chancellor's District, overseen by
Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rosario, who speaks Spanish and has worked in the system, on
and off, as a substitute since 1993, was hired last fall to teach
bilingual education. There is such a shortage of bilingual teachers
that half of all bilingual teachers citywide do not have state
certification. But because Ms. Rosario had taken courses in
education and Spanish at the College of New Rochelle, from which
she graduated in 1991, she was granted a temporary bilingual
teaching certificate, school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the school year, the chancellor's aides said,
Ms. Rosario compiled a checkered record, with three unsatisfactory
evaluations of her teaching from February to April. By May, the
principal of School 74 had already decided that she would not be
invited back next year, said Barbara Byrd-Bennett, the supervising
superintendent of the Chancellor's District.
</P>
<P>
   But parents say that Ms. Rosario was beloved by the children and
that any discussion by school officials about poor teaching is only
being used as justification to support her dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   One parent, Eva Santos, recalled how Ms. Rosario stopped by her
home for an hour, every day for a week, after her son, Juan, 13,
broke his arm. Since his sixth-grade teacher's dismissal, Ms.
Santos said she had found her son holding a newspaper clipping of
his teacher and crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as parents are not upset with what she did,'' Ms. Santos
said. ``Actually, we applaud what she did with the children. We
don't know why the Board of Education took such drastic measures.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least one child, and her guardian, were less
complimentary, particularly when discussing the events of June 8.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, some of her students said in interviews, Ms.
Rosario began talking about God after the principal had called over
the intercom for a moment of silence in memory of Christopher Lee,
a schoolmate who had recently drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Luisa Corporan, 11, said Thursday that she recalled asking her
teacher the first question, ``Where is Christopher Lee?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rosario replied that he was in heaven, Luisa said.
</P>
<P>
   The students then began asking questions, such as ``What is
heaven like?'' or ``What does God look like?''
</P>
<P>
   In a five-page written statement, which she submitted to the
board as part of a disciplinary hearing, Ms. Rosario said she had
then asked how many of the children ``would like to hear about
God?'' Juan, the boy with the broken arm, said his teacher was
emphatic that anyone who did not want to engage in the conversation
could read a book in the back of the classroom, by the computers.
</P>
<P>
   One, or perhaps two boys, left their seats, the children said.
</P>
<P>
   After imploring the children that ``this is something
voluntarily free will,'' Ms. Rosario wrote in her statement, she
then asked ``if anyone would like to accept Jesus as their personal
savior.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They all raised their hands,'' wrote Ms. Rosario, in an
account later confirmed by Juan and Luisa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started praying in Spanish,'' Ms. Rosario wrote, ``then I
went to each one of them. I put my hand in their forehead asking
Jesus to take care of them and their families.''
</P>
<P>
   The children asked their teacher ``if they could pray for
them,'' Luisa said. ``She didn't force nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   But after class, school officials said, one girl called home to
say she had been frightened by what she saw and asked that her
older sister, her guardian, pick her up at school. It was in a
meeting with the school principal, Leroy Johnson, that the girl and
her sister described what had happened. Several other parents also
called, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   At a disciplinary hearing four days later on June 12, school
administrators asked Ms. Rosario if she felt she could refrain from
``preaching'' in class through the end of the school year, Dr.
Byrd-Bennett, the district administrator, said. She recalled that
Ms. Rosario was emphatic that she could give no such assurance, and
was informed that she was being dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   After a lengthy account of her dismissal was headlined on the
June 16 cover of The New York Post, and in shorter articles that
day in The New York Times and The New York Daily News, Ms. Rosario
began receiving an outpouring of support.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, before marching in an evangelical parade, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani said Ms. Rosario should have received a warning
for her actions, but not a dismissal. Tuesday, several hundred
people, including neighborhood parents and ministers, rallied
alongside her outside the Board of Education headquarters in
downtown Brooklyn, pleading that she get her job back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
