</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-OAKLEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KNICKS TRADE TAKES THE HEART OUT OF GARDEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saralene Oakley received the disturbing news Thursday afternoon
at Nails, Etc., the beauty salon her sibling helped her get off the
ground in their hometown of Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``They traded my brother?'' Charles Oakley's big sister said.
``What are the Knicks doing? Who do they get? What could they be
thinking after all these years? I'm just in shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a friend had tickets to one game in two years, and you
remembered Oakley's tenacity. Maybe you were the regular, the guy
who thought it was Take a Knick Home Night as he plunged into your
lap hunting down a loose ball. Perhaps television was your only
link to Oak.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. At some point, all who have had the honor of seeing
him play have expressed a shared community of everymanness. He was
the hod carrier at the construction site, the assembly-line worker
at General Motors. Oakley punched in, punched out, complained under
his breath and poked fun at the blue blazers hurdling each other
for power and position.
</P>
<P>
   Now the familiar face in the lunch room is gone, the 10-year
company man replaced by a younger, cheaper kid two years removed
from college.
</P>
<P>
   It happens every day in America. Yet you never expected the
hardest-working man in basketball to be told he was not useful
enough, that his grit and perseverance were tapped out.
</P>
<P>
   Trading Oakley to the Toronto Raptors on Thursday for Marcus
Camby, a frail 24-year-old, saved the shop-till-they-drop Knicks
slightly more than $2 million, and now they have to consider
whether it was worth it.
</P>
<P>
   If Oakley has a moment, maybe he can provide the answer the way
he did by teasing a Charlotte ball boy after Alonzo Mourning had
been traded to Miami in 1996, leaving the Hornets depleted in the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``How y'all going to cook without a stove in the kitchen?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the obvious questions of who will terrify Chris Webber
into making 2 of 20 shots and how Patrick Ewing will guard anyone
over 250 pounds in the post, is this question: How many times can
Madison Square Garden let go of an aging warrior who elicits such
strong emotions in his teammates and fans?
</P>
<P>
   If Camby falters or the Knicks fall apart, Dave Checketts and
Ernie Grunfeld are going to have to deal with the fact that they
may have taken the passion and desire of a proud veteran for
granted, that Oakley's departure mirrored the erosion of New York's
competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the toughest trade I've ever made,'' said
Checketts, the Garden president.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we all get a little sentimental on the subject of Oakley,
enough to forget that he was outplayed by Antonio Davis two months
ago in Indianapolis. But he, John Starks and Ewing were the Knicks
the last decade, the way Willis Reed, Walt Frazier and Dave
DeBusschere were once the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley was never part of the Starks-Ewing clique. He resented
Starks' poor work ethic at times and wondered why everyone was so
concerned about Ewing wearing an ice pack around his knees when
Oakley was getting stitches in his brow and a cast on his foot.
</P>
<P>
   But do you know who tied Ewing's ties for him when his wrist was
in plaster for five months last season, or who always jumped in
when Starks was in a scrap on the floor? He was ornery and
irritable sometimes. But he was family.
</P>
<P>
   He was stylish without being gaudy _ no other Knick could pull
off wearing a lavender silk suit on game nights. He scowled when he
was playing, but after the buzzer sounded he was just plain Oak.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1997, several of the writers covering the Knicks
half-kidded Oakley about showing them around Cleveland during the
All-Star Game. Oakley nodded and told everyone to be in front of a
hotel at a certain time.
</P>
<P>
   He showed up that Friday night in a wide-brim fedora and a
pin-striped suit, opened the door to a limousine he owned and
ushered everyone in. First stop was Club Togo in Oakley's old
neighborhood, where high school friends told of a young, spry,
Gheri-curled Oak dunking and blowing kisses to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop was his mother Corine's house for a spread of sweet
potato pie, ham hocks and collard greens _ and framed pictures of a
smiling kid who made a mother very proud. Of his beautiful prom
date, he shrugged and said, ``Someone had to take her.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit was not written about and Oakley never once brought it
up as leverage for less-critical stories about him. He simply
wanted to show the people who wrote about him who he was _ the way
he showed Knick fans every night, collecting rebounds, shooting his
medium-range jump shot, beating quicker players down the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave his heart to New York,'' Saralene said. ``This is
almost the end of his career. It's crazy. It's not right. He was
supposed to finish his career there.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no silver lining, no cake or retirement gift. Most
likely, Charles Oakley will finish his career with the worst team
in the Eastern Conference. The Employee of the Decade was just let
go.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are about business and looking toward the future.
Oakley is about sentiment and living for today. They really don't
deserve him anymore. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
