</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CURRY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY LOOKS BACK FONDLY AT THOSE SWAGGERING METS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There was a gray Yankees uniform hanging in Darryl
Strawberry's locker, a blue Yankees cap resting on the floor and
several teammates sprinkled throughout the visiting clubhouse
Thursday, but Strawberry plopped himself inside a baseball time
capsule and went exploring. He journeyed away from the Bronx and
back to Flushing. For 30 glorious and gleeful minutes, it was 1986
again.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from Strawberry's perpetual smile, his continual
giddiness and his sudden expertise as a storyteller, this was a
trip down memory lane that he has wanted to take for a long time.
With Strawberry's return to Shea Stadium to play the Mets at hand
Friday night, the only player this weekend who can wear World
Series Championship rings from both teams oozed with enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   This was fun to hear and fun to watch. For everyone who is tired
of hearing the cliches and tired of hearing how this three-game
series has been too hyped, make friends with one of the eight beat
reporters who covers the Yankees and beg him for a tape of
Strawberry's interview. It was that engaging. Darryl, the current
Yankee and former Met, first sounded like Sybill. But the more he
spoke, the more he sounded like Mr. Met.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're a lot like we were in '86, knowing how to win
and always finding a way to win,'' Strawberry said. ``That's
special. You don't always get to play on teams like that. I've been
able to do it twice. Here I am on my third one. I've been pretty
fortunate to have a career where I came back in New York and was
successful. Those are great stories no matter how you look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry is right. He was in the middle of those arrogant Mets
of 1986 and was in the middle of those lovable Yankees of 1996 and
these respected Yankees of 1998. And he fit snugly every time. He
shared beers with Lenny, Doc and Darling, then switched teams,
changed his life and shares Bible classes with Pettitte, Girardi
and Curtis. But, the mature Strawberry of the Yankees became the
brazen Strawberry of the Mets when he was asked who would win
between the two champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different personality over here,'' Strawberry said.
``Over there, we had a lot of egos and arrogant people that didn't
care. If we had played these guys, we would have probably been
yelling at these guys and calling them wimps. That's just the way
we were.''
</P>
<P>
   Notice that Strawberry used ``we'' to refer to the Mets and
``these guys'' to refer to the Yankees. Informed of this
revelation, he stammered to explain himself before relenting in an
avalanche of laughter. Strawberry, who watched last year's
Mets-Yankees series on television because of knee surgery, did not
even try to be coy when the topic switched to which team he would
align himself with in a grudge match between 1986 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have to play for them because I had that type of
personality back then,'' said Strawberry, using ``them'' to
describe the Mets. ``I would have to be a part of that. I can't
deny something that was there. I was right in the middle with the
rest of them.''
</P>
<P>
   So would the 1986 Darryl call the 1998 Darryl a wimp?
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably so,'' Strawberry said.
</P>
<P>
   And how would the 1998 Darryl react to the insult?
</P>
<P>
   ``He would be like, `Whatever,''' Strawberry said. ``Not much I
can really say about it. I'd rather be this than what I was then.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry said that once, but for most of the 30 minutes, he
did not express that. He was in 1986 and delighted in reminiscing
about how the Mets played hard and partied harder, how Davey
Johnson created an arrogant club by imploring players to walk with
a swagger and be the intimidators, not the intimidated, and how
most fans considered them ``pond scum.'' With each memorable tale,
each smile, the trip got better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was afraid of us,'' Strawberry said.
</P>
<P>
   Would the Yankees be afraid?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said Strawberry, a startling non-answer since
the Yankees are on pace to win 119 games, 11 more than the 1986
Mets won. ``National League teams were afraid of us. We were a
fighting team. We were a hated team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' fans should not hate Strawberry, the player who has
more homers at Shea Stadium than anyone. They should be thrilled
that a 36-year-old who has endured tax, marriage and
substance-abuse problems is as excited about the three games as
they are. Strawberry will be wearing a Yankee uniform Friday, but
Thursday he leaped in a time capsule and was a Met again. It was a
pleasant ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being successful in New York is like being on top of the
world,'' Strawberry said. ``I don't think a lot of people
understand that. I do. I've been there and I understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
