<HEADER>
A7595 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-ATHLETES-ART-$     06-25 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-ATHLETES-ART-$ADV28-885&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIGGER LEAGUE IS PLAYING TO THE PLAYERS 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By PAUL SWEENEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wall Street's competitive culture has always been populated by
more than a few sports fans. But now the institutions themselves _
banks, brokerage firms, money managers and mutual fund companies _
are developing a love of the game. Or, more exactly, a love of the
players and their substantial paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   In a period when skyrocketing salaries and signing bonuses,
multiyear contracts and lucrative endorsements can push annual
incomes well into the millions, professional athletes as a group
have become highly desirable and actively courted clients.
</P>
<P>
   A few institutions have gone as far as setting up separate
departments just to serve athletes. For example, Star Banc Corp. in
Cincinnati opened such a division three years ago and put two
former college football players and current vice presidents,
Jonathan Hayes and Earl Layne, in charge of managing money for some
80 professional athletes.
</P>
<P>
   State Street Research and Management, the United States'
second-oldest mutual fund manager, which has guarded the fortunes
of generations of patrician Bostonians, inaugurated its Athletes
fund last autumn and hired a retired Bruins hockey star, Derek
Sanderson, as resident rainmaker. Others, like Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.,
have tried to make their sales forces more athlete-savvy.
</P>
<P>
   These companies are charging onto a field once used only by a
handful of boutique money managers, like CSI Management in San
Francisco or Investment Advisors International in Cleveland. (IAI
is a division of the International Management Group, which got its
start representing golfers and tennis players in the 1960s.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing a lot more competition, especially from
traditional Wall Street houses and even Big Six accounting firms,''
said Leland H. Faust, president of CSI.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, most professional athletes were considered
anything but the carriage trade. Just ask John Havlicek, the
legendary Boston Celtic and 13-time National Basketball Association
all-star. Havlicek earned only $15,000 as a rookie in 1962,
equivalent to about $80,500 today, and even worked in the
off-season as a representative for a hardware and home-appliance
company.
</P>
<P>
   He and a couple of other Celtics tried to pool their money and
buy a few hundred dollars' worth of stock, but had trouble finding
a broker who would take them on as clients, Havlicek recalled.
</P>
<P>
   According to Faust, ``When the top salary in major league
baseball was $700,000, it wasn't chump change, but there were still
a lot of higher-paid people around.'' Now, when the median salary
in major-league baseball is $1.3 million, he said, ``you have a
bigger market.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletes now ``qualify as bona fide clients,'' Faust added.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, however, athletes are very different from other
clients in their income bracket, like corporate executives, doctors
or lawyers. They are typically much younger and suddenly wealthy _
often signing fat bonus contracts in their teens _ and have spent
their lives learning to excel in their sport, not in finance.
</P>
<P>
   Many are from small-town or working-class backgrounds, and few
have had much exposure to money management. They have too often
been prey to dubious advice from flamboyant agents or hangers-on.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, institutional money management for professional
athletes has become a specialty that combines private banking and
trust-department functions with the roles of coach, psychologist
and even guardian.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers find themselves steering clients clear of risky
ventures like nightclubs and restaurants, car-wash franchises and
oil-and-gas partnerships that are often pitched to athletes and
other celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I see guys lose money on bad investments,'' said
Victor Green, a defensive back for the New York Jets who recently
signed a three-year contract for a total of $3 million and keeps
his money with Star Bank, a unit of Star Banc.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes and their advisers also face the challenge of planning
for a lifetime around a peak earnings period that can be
agonizingly brief.
</P>
<P>
   John L. Macklin, president of IAI, which has $1 billion in
assets under management and counts Havlicek and the retired tennis
champion Martina Navratilova among the firm's clients, says he
invests an athlete's money as if it were the portfolio of a
58-year-old executive just a few years shy of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Such an outlook calls for a fairly conservative strategy. Star
Bank's portfolio managers typically suggest a mixture of about 60
percent large-cap equities, 30 percent bonds and the remainder in
money market funds. Specific stocks that Star Bank recommends to
athletes include Walt Disney; Sofamor Danek, a medical-supply
company, and Clear Channel Communications, which operates a large
chain of radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   At State Street Research, Gardner Jackson Jr., a portfolio
manager, says the firm's new Athletes fund, which requires a
minimum initial investment of $500,000, is mainly invested in
large-cap growth stocks, and performs like a State Street
institutional mutual fund that had a 47.4 percent total return for
the 12 months ended April 30, a bit better than the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index during the period.
</P>
<P>
   The fund holds stakes in 55 companies including General
Electric, DuPont and two hot drug companies, Warner Lambert and
Pfizer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Advisers often find themselves helping their athlete clients
with day-to-day money matters. Surrounded by temptations to spend
heavily on luxury clothes and cars, multiple homes and late nights
on the town, professional athletes sometimes need reminding that
succumbing would mean robbing their own future, the advisers say.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Ready of the Denver office of Prudential Securities, who
has about 50 football players as clients, said one player called
him from Las Vegas to ask for more money after he had lost $4,000
gambling. ``I told him no and he got mad, but when he got back to
Denver he gave me a big hug,'' Ready said.
</P>
<P>
   At Star Bank, Layne, who played football at Liberty University
while earning a degree in finance, has attracted many players as
clients with similarly personalized service. He and Hayes, who
founded the bank's pro sports division, routinely take care of
extracurricular tasks like seeing that clients' bills are paid and
that their insurance policies are renewed on time.
</P>
<P>
   Not all clients, of course, need or want such help. And advisers
say it is often hard to persuade naturally aggressive athletes to
play it safe with their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell the guys that they are already on third base and don't
need to hit a home run,'' Layne said. ``All they need to do is hit
singles and doubles, and that will get them home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
