<SLUG> BC-NY-PROTEST-PERU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS ASK PERU'S LEADER TO FREE A NEW YORK WOMAN
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The worlds of Mark and Rhoda Berenson, the parents of
a New York woman who has been imprisoned in Peru, and President
Alberto Fujimori, the Peruvian leader who has rejected calls for
her release, intersected Thursday night at the Hilton hotel in
midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the hotel, the Berensons and about 30 others
demonstrated for two hours, demanding the release of Lori Helene
Berenson, a 28-year-old former Manhattan resident who is serving a
life sentence in a Peruvian prison after being convicted on
terrorism charges. Inside, Fujimori attended a conference on
financial services for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   But the two sides never met; security guards made sure of that.
They had plenty to say about one another in stoking a case that has
cast a spotlight on the activities of Americans living abroad and
on the methods of the Peruvian courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a coward,'' Berenson shouted, speaking as much to the
Peruvian cameras as he was to the local media. ``Give Lori what she
deserves. I'm getting impatient.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori, meanwhile, spoke about Ms. Berenson at a brief press
conference, branding her a terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be just. We must make justice,'' he said in halting
English. ``Peru has the right as the United States to have a
peaceful country. You don't have want to have more World Trade
Center problems,'' he said, referring to the 1993 bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berenson's plight returned to the headlines this week after
Javier Valle Riestra, Peru's new prime minister, said she should be
freed or given a new trial. Fujimori rejected that suggestion.
Valle Riestra then offered his resignation, but Fujimori would not
accept it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berenson has been held in a prison high in the Andes since
her conviction in January 1996 by a tribunal that did not permit
her lawyers to question the evidence or to cross-examine witnesses.
She was accused of assisting the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary
Movement, a Marxist guerrilla group, in a plan to take the Peruvian
congress hostage.
</P>
<P>
   This last weekend, Ms. Berenson's father and uncle visited her
in prison. She was frail, they said, with her eyesight failing, her
voice hoarse and her complexion purple from the cold temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   The Berensons found out only Wednesday night that Fujimori was
scheduled to be in New York this week. They hastily made
arrangements to get as close as possible to the man who controls
their daughter's fate. They distributed placards and chanted
slogans. They played, over and over, a folk song called ``A Voice
in the Distance'' that had been written for their daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything went as planned. Shortly after the demonstration
began at 5 p.m. on the southeast corner of the Avenue of the
Americas and West 54th Street, several police officers ordered the
protesters to first move to the northwest corner, then to the
northeast one.
</P>
<P>
   And the protesters could not gain access to the air-conditioned
and carpeted confines of Fujimori's press conference at the
Microcredit Summit Meeting of Councils.
</P>
<P>
   That did not prevent Mrs. Berenson from thinking about
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went into the hotel earlier just to see where the meeting
was,'' Mrs. Berenson said. ``I said, `Gee, what happens if I see
him?' I would say, as a mother, parent to parent, `Why are you
doing this? Please have some humanity.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
