A7609 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-MAIN26-COX     06-25 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves just not 'sharp' Klesko says
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- This is not October. The interleague schedule is for
freaks. Half the starting infield is out. Explain it away however
you want, then explain this:
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have lost five times in seven games, and what
happened to them Wednesday night usually happens out behind the
barn.
</P>
<P>
   Spotting Atlanta an early two-run lead, the Yankees pounded five
Braves pitchers for 13 hits and won a walkover 10-6, taking their
second of three games from the Braves this week. Atlanta made three
errors that led to four unearned runs, and Yankees starter David
Cone (10-2) held the Braves to two earned runs and five hits
through seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Millwood (9-4) never got out of the fourth, yielding five
runs and losing his second consecutive game for the first time
since his first two major-league starts last July. Javy Lopez's
17th homer, a three-run job off Mike Stanton in the eighth, spruced
up the score, but it came after half of the 48,980 assembled had
departed Turner Field. They saw the nastiest home performance of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of our tops, that's for sure,'' said Ryan Klesko,
an emergency fill-in at first base after Andres Galarraga was
scratched with a stiff back. ``Just one of those things where we
weren't very sharp for the game. Errors put us under. What cost us
the game was defense today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves led 2-0 after two innings, after which the Yankees
worked Millwood over. Paul O'Neill homered in the third and New
York sent eight men to the plate in the four-run fourth. After a
9-2 start this year, Millwood in his last two starts has thrown a
combined 4 2/3 innings, giving up 14 hits and 12 runs while his ERA
has soared to 4.78.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around the fourth, he started throwing the ball around the
middle of the plate instead of using the corners,'' said Lopez.
``That's when the other team gets the advantage. Then he started
walking a few people. ``Also,'' added Lopez, whose throwing error
hurt in the decisive fourth, ``we didn't play defense at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's bullpen gave up another five runs (just two earned)
and the Braves were simply not built for an American League
three-hour slamfest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ahead in the ballgame,'' said manager Bobby Cox. ``We
have to pitch a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   With shortstop Walt Weiss at his son Brody's bedside, with
Galarraga questionable tonight with a back so sore he was barely
able to dress, the prognosis for tonight's fourth game with the
Yankees is hardly bright.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything bad is happening right now,'' said Galarraga, who
missed his first start as a Brave. ``We know we can get better.
We're kind of struggling, myself too.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa breaks record
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa broke the major league record for home runs in a
month Thursday night, hitting his 19th of June in the seventh
inning of the Chicago Cubs' game against the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who has 32 homers overall, broke the mark set by Detroit's
Rudy York in August 1937.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
