<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reno may order limited probe of King assassination evidence
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Attorney General Janet Reno is expected to announce
today that she has approved a new investigation into the
30-year-old assassination of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   According to news reports Thursday, Justice Department officials
told some members of Congress that Reno will authorize a limited
inquiry rather than the full-scale probe that the King family has
requested.
</P>
<P>
   Reno also is likely to reject the King family's request that she
empanel a national truth and reconciliation commission that would
have the authority to grant immunity in return for testimony, The
Associated Press said, citing unnamed Justice Department officials.
</P>
<P>
   The King family had not heard anything from the Justice
Department as of late Thursday. Coretta Scott King, the slain civil
rights leader's widow, said she would not comment until she
receives official notification.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said Reno had not reached a
decision yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is definite,'' said spokeswoman Lauren Varien.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. King and three of her children met with Reno in April and
with President Clinton last week. They cited new evidence in their
request for a probe.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings tried last year to obtain a new trial for James Earl
Ray, who pleaded guilty in 1969 to the April 4, 1968, murder but
recanted within days. Ray died in April at age 70.
</P>
<P>
   Former FBI agent Donald Wilson came forth in March with two
pieces of paper he said he found in Ray's abandoned car 30 years
ago in Atlanta. Both papers contain the name Raul.
</P>
<P>
   Ray maintained he was set up by a shadowy smuggler he knew only
as Raul.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said Thursday he has not been contacted by anyone from
the Justice Department but is concerned about turning the evidence
over to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bureau called it a fake without having seen it,'' Wilson
said. ``My concern is what would become of it. Would it be received
and preserved with the best of intentions?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
