</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-STARR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-435&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SETBACK TO STARR, COURT AFFIRMS LAWYER-CLIENT PRIVILEGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs lede graf to insert Kenneth Starr's name) (See related stories: SCOTUS-VETO, SCOTUS-AIDS, SCOTUS-RDP) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(JT) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Thursday broadly affirmed the
rights of clients to take to their graves their consultations with
lawyers. The ruling was a legal setback for the Whitewater
independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, who was seeking the notes of
the lawyer who had represented Vincent Foster, the deputy White
House counsel who committed suicide nearly five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the 6-3 decision was an important victory for a prominent
array of lawyer organizations and groups representing the
terminally ill and psychiatrists. They had argued that any erosion
of the lawyer-client privilege would have a devastating impact on
the relationship between lawyers and their clients, leaving hollow
a well-grounded doctrine of confidentiality that is the cornerstone
of modern law practice because it provides the fundamental
incentive for clients to be speak candidly with their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The justices ruled that three pages of notes taken by Foster's
lawyer, James Hamilton, at a meeting of the two did not lose its
protection under the lawyer-client privilege when Foster died nine
days later.
</P>
<P>
   In issuing a subpoena for the notes, Starr had maintained that
Foster's death extinguished the privilege. He had claimed that the
lawyer's notes were central to the inquiry into the circumstances
of Foster's death and the dismissal of the staff of the White House
travel office in 1993, an event which, by all accounts, had
contributed to Foster's deepening depression.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton had argued that the notes of his consultation with
Foster were protected, even posthumously, by the privilege.
Thursday the high court, reversing a federal appeals court
decision, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been generally, if not universally, accepted, for well
over a century, that the attorney-client privilege survives the
death of the client in a case such as this,'' Chief Justice William
Rehnquist wrote for the court. ``While the arguments against the
survival of the privilege are by no means frivolous, they are based
in large part on speculation _ thoughtful speculation, but
speculation nonetheless _ as to whether posthumous termination of
the privilege would diminish a client's willingness to confide in
an attorney.''
</P>
<P>
   The justices rejected Starr's claim that any effect on the
client-lawyer relationship would be minimal. Starr had argued that
when clients seek advice from lawyers, they do not give much
thought to what happens after they die.
</P>
<P>
   But the court said many clients have an abiding interest in
posthumously preserving their reputations and protecting their
survivors from the intrusions of investigators.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Knowing that communications will remain confidential even
after death encourages the client to communicate fully and frankly
with counsel,'' the court said. ``While the fear of disclosure, and
the consequent withholding of information from counsel, may be
reduced if disclosure is limited to posthumous disclosure in a
criminal context, it seems unreasonable to assume that it vanishes
altogether. Clients may be concerned about reputation, civil
liability, or possible harm to friends or family. Posthumous
disclosure of such communications may be as feared as disclosure
during the client's lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the justices speculated, it was ``quite plausible that
Foster, perhaps already contemplating suicide, may not have sought
legal advice from Hamilton if he had not been assured the
conversation was privileged.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr, who has repeatedly criticized the administration for
invoking a variety of privileges to limit testimony in his inquiry,
on Thursday issued a brief statement that expressed disappointment
in the outcome of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue has obviously proved to be of considerable
difficulty, as the divided opinions of the Supreme Court and the
Court of Appeals reveal,'' he said. ``In all events, we continue to
pursue our investigation as thoroughly and expeditiously as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to know what impact the decision in the case
will have on the long-running inquiry by Starr because it will
probably never be known whether Hamilton's notes contained anything
useful to investigators. While Foster was a close confidant of
President Clinton and a former law partner of Hillary Rodham
Clinton, Starr has won other legal fights over privilege issues
only to obtain relatively unimportant evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But as a matter of law, the ruling Thursday was a decisive
defeat for Starr, who had asked the court to put the case on a fast
track.
</P>
<P>
   Even the court's three dissenters _ Justices Sandra Day
O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas _ refused to go as far
as Starr had sought in his argument that in criminal cases, the
privilege dies with the client.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the dissenting justices proposed that there be a new and
narrow exception to the privilege after death allowing for a lawyer
to turn over material to criminal investigators only in exceptional
circumstances and when the information is not generally available
elsewhere. They cited the compelling example of when a client,
before dying, confesses to a crime for which another person is
being tried.
</P>
<P>
   In a footnote, the majority dismissed the dissent's concerns
about such cases, saying that issue was not squarely before the
court in the case decided Thursday, Swidler &AMP; Berlin vs. United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The court refused to extend the main exception to the
lawyer-client privilege after the death of a client _ in disputes
between heirs. In those cases, most state courts have found that
the disclosure of confidences is permissible because it furthers
the client's intent in disposing of an estate.
</P>
<P>
   But the court declined to adopt the argument by Starr that that
exception to the privilege should be expanded to include criminal
inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason to suppose as a general matter that grand
jury testimony about confidential communications furthers the
client's intent,'' the court said.
</P>
<P>
   The case began in 1995, when a federal grand jury, at the
request of Starr, issued a subpoena to Hamilton for the notes. A
district court judge, after privately examining the notes,
concluded that they were protected by the lawyer-client privilege.
Last year a divided three-judge panel of the District of Columbia
U.S. Court of Appeals reversed, finding that the need of the
investigators for the notes outweighed the policy reasons behind
confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980625.0548 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-POLICE-BEARDS-NYT &LR;      06-25 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-BEARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEARD-BAN DISPUTE TURNS INTO CONSTITUTIONAL DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ The seemingly simple and harmless matter of
growing a beard may be neither, judging by the constitutional
arguments Thursday before a federal appeals court panel. At issue
is whether Newark can dismiss two police officers who wear beards
because of their Sunni Muslim beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The two officers, Faruq Abdul-Aziz, who has been on the force
for nine years, and Shakoor Mustafa, who has been an officer for 12
years, face dismissal under a 1971 department regulation that
requires officers to be clean-shaven unless medical reasons prevent
them from complying.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. District Court judge last year blocked the dismissal of
the officers, maintaining that their right to religious expression
outweighed the department's authority to enforce a management
directive that city officials said was intended to promote
discipline and order.
</P>
<P>
   It is a case that has yoked together uncommon allies and
seemingly incompatible ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for both sides in the case said there was little settled
law on the intersection of beards, religious observances and
management prerogatives, and court rulings in recent years have
gone both ways. In fact, the entire issue of how and which
religious practices are protected has been in question since last
June, when the U.S. Supreme Court re-established itself, not
Congress, as the arbiter of such questions.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, lawyers in the case predicted that regardless
of the decision by the three-judge panel in Newark, the case was
likely to end up before the United States' highest court.
</P>
<P>
   As the arguments unfolded in the old federal courthouse, the
case presented a host of incongruities. For one, it involves two
black police officers who are asserting their individuality in a
predominantly black city with a black political leadership while
being defended by the predominantly white leadership of the
Fraternal Order of Police, the officers' union.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, their case is supported by an uncommon alliance of
the American Civil Liberties Union; the Anti-Defamation League, a
Jewish organization; and the Becket Fund for Religious Liberty, a
public-interest law firm that argues for wider expression of
religious, and generally Christian, traditions.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's arguments, the city of Newark defended a rule that
was originally intended to prevent the wearing of long hair and
beards as emblems of protest in the 1960s and '70s. The department
does not enforce the rule, which permits mustaches, for about two
dozen officers who have presented doctors' letters saying that the
men have a skin condition that prevents them from shaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am amazed that the city of Newark with its large minority
population is fighting to do this,'' said Jack McEntee, president
of the Fraternal Order of Police. ``If this was happening in a
small, mostly white town anywhere, you would have busloads of
people here to protest.''
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Saunders, who represented the city, said Thursday that
the regulation prohibiting beards was essential to the ``esprit de
corps'' of the police department and to maintaining a professional
atmosphere. To allow the department's Muslims to wear beards, he
said, would create ``a superior religious right'' that no other
religious group had.
</P>
<P>
   In a spirited exchange with the lawyers, the three judges _
Samuel Alito Jr., Morton Greenber and Theodore Mckee _ asked
whether the department was stifling ``a legitimate uniqueness''
that the Constitution sought to protect and whether the department
was asserting that there would be order from uniform grooming when
this result was not supported by any studies.
</P>
<P>
   The judges also questioned whether the city was trying to
enforce a uniformity that was impossible and even unwise in a
multicultural society.
</P>
<P>
   There was even a joke from Mckee, who is black and has a beard.
``So you say that we should, and pardon the pun, accept as gospel
the police director's view that beards are unprofessional,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The judges said they would consider the case and rule later.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Cannan, the lawyer for the two men, quoted passages from
the Koran and statements from the men's imam, or spiritual leader,
supporting the religious significance of beards and their
obligation to wear beards.
</P>
<P>
   Cannan contended that their beards were protected by the
Constitution not only as a sincere religious expression, but also
as an expression of free speech. He said that Newark was required
to show ``a compelling interest'' to justify its grooming
regulations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
