<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-25 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7619 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-VILLAGE-HNS &LR;      06-25 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-VILLAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TALKS TO CHINESE VILLAGERS WHO VOTED IN LOCAL ELECTIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Friday is cq in lede; also notice dateline change from
budget) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   XIA HE, China _ Hoping to put an early positive spin on his
controversial China journey, President Clinton traveled Friday to a
well-scrubbed village where the locals said rudimentary elections
had made a difference in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton talked for about an hour with a handful of villagers
seated under a shady tree, then addressed more townsfolk in the
courtyard of a primary school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to show early on that the president's talk about
progress in China was not a pipedream,'' said an administration
source involved in laying out Clinton's nine-day state visit. The
journey is the president's first trip to the world's most populous
nation and most important remaining authoritarian regime.
</P>
<P>
   Planners selected the village not only because it is just off
the road to one of China's biggest tourist attractions, the buried
army of Qin dynasty terra-cotta warriors, but also because it has
held elections under a 10-year-old draft law, which is the first
test of democracy in the nation's many millennia.
</P>
<P>
   Huang Xiang Li, a 31-year-old villager, said local elections in
1995 had resulted in some changes in government, including the
defeat of ``some old people,'' whom a U.S. source said were
apparently long-serving Communist Party hacks.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear if they had been replaced by other members of
the only political party allowed in China, or local people not
affiliated with the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   Villages are the basic governmental unit in China's countryside,
where 70 percent of the 1.2 billion population lives, and the only
level where direct elections are allowed. No plans have been
announced for taking the electoral experiment to a higher level of
government, and a Western scholar said, ``to connect the dots to
higher levels ... is problematic.''
</P>
<P>
   Huang, a mother of two who works in the thriving tourist
industry, expressed satisfaction with the elections, as did Wang
Xiang, who is now 21 and had just become eligible to vote in the
elections three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have changed for the better,'' Wang said Thursday, as
final preparations for Clinton's visit proceeded. She cited
improvements in overall living standards and in the quality of the
local schools.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin O'Brien, a visiting professor at the University of
California at Berkeley who has studied China's embryonic elections,
said the process was a one-on-one affair _ a comment that Wang
backed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for people whom I really trusted,'' she said, ``some
old, some new.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said Clinton's visit could provide ``a really big
boost'' for the election process, which the national government has
said will be made permanent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motive (for Clinton's visit) may be propaganda and public
relations, but the effect could be real,'' O'Brien said in a
telephone interview from California. He added, however, the
elections should not be viewed as fully democratic, given the
prohibition on organized opposition to the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese are very committed to making it a success _ as
they understand it,'' O'Brien said. If a non-Communist is elected,
he said, the party would quickly attempt to recruit the winner, who
is ``obviously an up and coming young elite.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said a principal effect of the elections has been that
they ``allow the most unpopular (Communist) cadres to be kept from
running villages.''
</P>
<P>
   A Clinton administration official said that White House
personnel scouted several villages and eliminated some because
their elections had seemed less than genuine.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the village votes have been observed by teams from the
Atlanta-based center sponsored by former President Carter, and
their reports have been generally supportive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the lack of a democratic tradition and limited
education, villagers were quite capable of making intelligent
choices,'' Tan Qingshan, a political scientist at Cleveland State
University and a Carter Center observer, wrote in an article for
the English-language China Daily.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made a point of stopping in Xia He before going on to
view the pottery warriors, the tourist highlight of his first full
day in China.
</P>
<P>
   The president flies to Beijing on Friday night to be formally
welcomed Saturday morning at a ceremony in Tiananmen Square, where
Chinese army troops killed hundreds of protesters in putting down a
1989 pro-democracy movement.
</P>
<P>
   Xia He is an old farming village whose fortunes took a dramatic
upturn when the 2,000-year-old terra-cotta army was discovered
nearby in 1974. The village makes enough money off a
government-owned souvenir factory that all the 374 residents have
cable television.
</P>
<P>
   Wang has watched enough international news to know that Clinton
defeated incumbent President Bush in 1992 because the U.S. economy
was in a slump, ``but now the economy has gotten better.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang said locals were also familiar with Clinton's ``troubles''
back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we know,'' she said smiling, but refused to be drawn into
specifics. ``That's the American people's affair.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite some modern technology, old-fashioned touches abound in
Xia He, including big haystacks in front of most houses that
provide fuel for cooking. A peasant towing a hand-pulled cart
scattered visitors on the narrow main street the day before
Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
   The village is a neat collection of red-brick houses, many in
the traditional style with walled courtyards and some with a second
story, suggesting a touch of relative affluence. Many renovations
were in evidence, in addition to the recent sprucing up for
Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
   It was also clear that White House advance staff had thoroughly
prepared the way for the Clintons: a baby just learning to walk
clutched its mother's hand while teething on a color picture of
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In the schoolyard, colorful banners _ from a decorating company
in Xi'an _ fluttered with welcoming messages for the U.S. party,
including: ``Although far away, if you have close friends, you are
like neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
