<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 6/25/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) FLINT, Mich. -- June 25, 1998 -- GM-STRIKE, 6-25 -- The
owners of the Capitol Coney Island Family Restaurant, Philip Kosman
2d, left, Vasilios Kosman and Philip Kosman, have lost customers
because of the strike at a nearby GM plant in Flint. When 3,400
workers went on strike at a metal parts stamping factory on June 5,
nearby restaurants lost half their business immediately, and the
pool table and bar stools at the pub across the street have been
deserted for the last three weeks. (Peter Yates/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) BEIJING -- June 25, 1998 -- CHINA-BAND, 6-25 -- Col. Fan
Siting, right, leads the People's Liberation Army Military Band in
a dress rehearsal Thursday in Beijing for the state dinner to be
held Saturday in honor of President Clinton and Hillary Rodham
Clinton. Since the band was founded at the instruction of Mao
Zedong in 1952, it has performed 4,800 times at important national
and international events. (Hilary Smith/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- June 25, 1998 -- SCOTUS-VETO, 6-25 -- The
Supreme
</P>
<P>
   Court rejected Thursday an effort to strengthen the hand of the
President, ruling that the President could not veto single items in
a bill. President Clinton used the Line Item Veto Act in August
1997. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- June 25, 1998 -- SCOTUS-STARR, 6-25 --
James Hamilton argues that the notes of his consultation with
Vincent Foster are protected, even posthumously, by the privilege.
The Supreme Court on Thursday broadly affirmed the rights of
clients to take to their graves their consultations with lawyers.
The ruling was a legal setback for the Whitewater independent
counsel, who was seeking Hamilton's notes. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1998 -- SPECTOR-SUIT, 6-25 -- In a
civil lawsuit in the cramped chambers of State Supreme Court in
Manhattan, 24 years after her divorce, Ronnie Spector Greenfield
and the two other Ronettes are suing rock legend Phil Spector for
$10 million. Ms. Greenfield, left, and performer Darlene Love seen
during a break in court proceedings. Last year, Ms. Love won a
$260,000 judgment against Spector for unpaid royalties but the
judge ordered it reduced to $130,000; the judge's ruling is on
appeal. (Marilyn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- June 25, 1998 -- CHINA-GINGRICH, 6-25 --
Speaker Newt Gingrich, enroute to a press conference at the
Capitol, announced his support for an extension of trade status for
China. Gingrich, a Georgia Republican, promised that Congress would
try again this September to give President Clinton expanded ``fast
track'' trade negotiating authority - an issue that sharply divides
Democrats. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BOSTON -- June 25, 1998 -- BOSTON-SCHOOLS, 6-25 -- After
nearly a quarter-century of busing, Boston officials are going to
discuss moving back toward neighborhood schools. Pupils arrived at
the Ellis Mendell School in the Roxbury neighborhood on Tuesday.
``It's at the point where you can't ignore it anymore,'' says Peggy
Davis-Mullen, a member of the Boston City Council who has been
pushing for neighborhood schools for nearly a decade and almost got
the issue put on the city ballot last year. (Evan Richman/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NYACK, N.Y. -- June 25, 1998 -- SCOTUS-FINLEY, 6-25 --
The Supreme Court upheld a 1990 law requiring the National
Endowment for the Arts to consider decency standards when deciding
which artists should get grant money. For Karen Finley, whose
performance in a New York theater as a chocolate-covered nude was
at the heart of the case, the decision on indeceny in the arts was
a personal defeat. ``I'm stunned and saddened by it,'' she says.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SICILY, Italy -- June 25, 1998 -- SICILY-MAFIA, 6-25 --
An Italian soldier keeps a lookout Thursday as his jeep moves
through rush-hour traffic in Palermo, as the army begins to pull
out to hand over its six-year anti-Mafia operation to the civilian
authorities. ``For those of us who have lived it, the emergency is
not over,'' complains Rita Borsellino, a pharmacist whose brother,
a prominent anti-Mafia prosecutor, was killed by a car bomb in
1992. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1998 -- MEDIA-BRILL-BOS, 6-25 --
Steven Brill, editor and publisher of Brill's Content, in his
Manhattan office. In starting a magazine of media criticism, Brill,
47, obviously wanted to watch the watchers. The grand irony is that
he is now the most scrutinized man on the media radar screen. ``No
more Mr. Nice Guy,'' he says with a sly smile. (Tom Herde/Boston
Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 28 --
PILOBOLUS-DANCE, 6-25 -- Joyce Coyoc, middle, at the Pilobolus
Dance Theater audition. Pilobolus is a company famous for its wit
and sensuality. These qualities will be on display in the three
programs being presented during the group's annual monthlong season
at the Joyce Theater, which opens Tuesday night with the New York
premiere of ``The Hand That Mocked, The Heart That Fed,'' a new
dance featuring an original score by the noted jazz composer Maria
Schneider. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 28 --
KAUFFMANN-FILM-CRITIC, 6-25 -- Stanley Kauffmann in the Walter
Reade Theater. At age 82, Kauffmann is celebrating his 40th
anniversary as film critic at The New Republic this month. He, as
always, remains afloat, buoyed by an old-fashioned commitment to
the art, not the business, of film. (Jack Manning/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1998 -- THEATER-NOTES, 6-25 -- Jack
Klugman, left, and Tony Randall in ``The Sunshine Boys.'' Klugman
gives a seriously funny performance in the revival of Neil Simon's
1972 comedy, while Randall, who was Klugman's co-star on the sitcom
version of ``The Odd Couple,'' adds inescapable resonance. (Sara
