dance featuring an original score by the noted jazz composer Maria
Schneider. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 28 --
KAUFFMANN-FILM-CRITIC, 6-25 -- Stanley Kauffmann in the Walter
Reade Theater. At age 82, Kauffmann is celebrating his 40th
anniversary as film critic at The New Republic this month. He, as
always, remains afloat, buoyed by an old-fashioned commitment to
the art, not the business, of film. (Jack Manning/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1998 -- THEATER-NOTES, 6-25 -- Jack
Klugman, left, and Tony Randall in ``The Sunshine Boys.'' Klugman
gives a seriously funny performance in the revival of Neil Simon's
1972 comedy, while Randall, who was Klugman's co-star on the sitcom
version of ``The Odd Couple,'' adds inescapable resonance. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1998 -- MOTORCYCLE-ART, 6-25 -- This
Indian Chief motorcycle with wide leather seat is just one of the
motorcycles in the ``The Art of the Motorcycle,'' exhibit at the
Guggenheim Museum. Frank Gehry's installation of the exhibition,
includes 113 motorcycles ranging from an 1868 French velocipede
with a steam engine beneath the seat to the current BMWs and Harley
Davidsons. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1998 -- NAUGHTON, 6-25 -- James
Naughton stands outside a brownstone in Manhattan's theater
district. Naughton is performing at the Manhattan Theater Club with
a one-man musical revue. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LANCASTER COUNTY, Pa. -- June 25, 1998 -- A buggy
traveling on Route 340 in Lancaster County, Pa. The Amish have a
complicated relationship with the tourists who make their roads
impassable in summer yet spend $400 million a year in Lancaster
County, much of it on Amish-made products. (Marty Katz/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) INTERCOURSE, Pa. -- June 25, 1998 -- AMISH-COUNTRY-1,
6-25 -- An Amish farmer works the fields with a teams of horses.
Lancaster County's Amish are Old Order Amish, the most distinct in
their customs and the fastest growing and one of the largest groups
of Amish in the United States. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
