A7644 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUCAS-EXECUTION-HNS &LR;      06-25 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCAS-EXECUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS PAROLE BOARD RECOMMENDS LUCAS BE SPARED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In an unprecedented move, state parole officials
voted 17-1 Thursday to recommend sparing the life of Henry Lee
Lucas, once considered the most heinous serial killer in the nation
after he confessed to hundreds of murders.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles also voted to recommend
Lucas be granted a 270-day reprieve from his death sentence,
scheduled to be carried out Tuesday. It was unclear whether the
reprieve was recommended as an alternative to commutation.
</P>
<P>
   The matter now goes to Gov. George W. Bush, who can accept or
reject the board's recommendations. Bush, who was in Brownsville
for a meeting of U.S. and Mexican border state governors, said he
will ``carefully review and consider the recommendation'' and would
make his decision soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take every death-penalty case very seriously,'' Bush said.
``The first question I have in each death-penalty case is whether
there is any doubt about whether the individual is guilty of the
crime. While Henry Lee Lucas is guilty of committing a number of
horrible crimes, serious concerns have been raised about his guilt
in the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the board gave no specific reason for making its
recommendations, board Chairman Victor Rodriguez said a 1986
investigative report by then-Attorney General Jim Mattox carried
significant weight in swaying the board.
</P>
<P>
   That report, among other things, raised serious doubt about
whether Lucas is guilty of the Oct. 31, 1979, rape and
strangulation of an unidentified woman known only as ``Orange
Socks.'' &UR;  &LR; The case was named for the only item of clothing the
victim was wearing when her body was found in a ditch near
Georgetown, north of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas confessed to the crime and was convicted in 1984. It is
the only case in which he received a death sentence, although he
has been convicted of 10 other murders and received life sentences
in six of those. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Although the parole board technically did not recommend what
lesser punishment Lucas should receive, Rodriguez wrote in a letter
to Bush that the murderer should never be released from prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to note that this person remains convicted of
this offense and as such should remain incarcerated for the rest of
his life,'' Rodriguez wrote Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe this person will ever be a free man,''
Rodriguez told reporters later. He added that he has informed
Lucas' lawyers that they fell far short of proving Lucas should be
pardoned.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's vote is believed to be the first time in the modern
era of the death penalty that the Texas parole board has
recommended a commutation of a death sentence on its own
initiative. Previous commutations have been granted only after
major changes in law or, in a few instances, after prosecutors
recommended the action because of trial flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson County District Attorney Ken Anderson, whose
predecessor prosecuted the ``Orange Socks'' case, called Lucas ``a
monster'' and said he is disappointed by the parole board's action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucas was proved guilty beyond a reasonable doubt to 12
citizens. The case has been reviewed by 23 judges over the past 14
years,'' Anderson said. ``The only other reason to grant clemency
is for reasons of mercy. There is no one less deserving of such
than Lucas.''
</P>
<P>
   Rita Radostitz, one of Lucas' attorneys, said she was heartened
by the board's vote and hopes the governor follows the
recommendation. She agreed with Rodriguez' assessment that the
Lucas case is not likely to set a precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lucas case is unique in that the attorney general's office
investigation weighed heavily in it, and I don't think there will
be very many other cases in which the attorney general's office is
going to come out and say, `We think this guy is innocent,''' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mattox began his investigation into Lucas after news reports
questioned the veracity of some 600 killings around the country to
which he had confessed. They pointed out, for example, that work
records indicated Lucas might have been in Florida at the time of
the ``Orange Socks'' slaying. In other cases, investigators found
that Lucas was actually incarcerated at the same time he was to
have killed someone. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Lucas, who had gained national notoriety for his confessions,
later recanted most of them. He said law-enforcement officials fed
him details about crimes and let him read investigative reports
that allowed him to give explicit confessions, and in some cases,
point out where bodies had been recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't view this as a win for Henry Lee Lucas,'' said Mattox,
who is seeking to be re-elected to the attorney general's post in
the November election. ``I view it as a win for our system of
justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the governor chooses to commute this sentence,'' he added,
``I'll be willing to stand up beside him (the governor), to defend
him any time, because it's the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Mattox believes it's unlikely Lucas committed the
murder for which he was sentenced to die, he also said Lucas is
guilty of other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a child molester, a thief. He's a murderer and he's also
a liar,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of people associated with this case at the
first, the task force and the first prosecutor, who kept saying
they thought they were handling the greatest mass murderer in the
history of the world,'' Mattox added. ``He was not.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattox says he now hopes that many of the cases that were
cleared based on Lucas' confessions will be reopened so
law-enforcement officers can find the real killers.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of some of the victims whose murders were attributed
to Lucas agreed. Joyce Lemons, whose daughter was murdered in
Lubbock on Aug. 24, 1975, two days after Lucas was released from
prison in Michigan, said it took her and her husband four years to
get their daughter's case reopened after Lucas confessed to it in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   Records in the case show that Lucas could not have been in
Lubbock at the time of the murder. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Now we need to turn to the creators of Henry,'' Lemons said
Thursday, referring to the Texas Rangers task force that
coordinated Lucas' confessions. ``They belong behind bars.''
</P>
<P>
   Prison spokesman David Nunnelee said Lucas was ``upbeat''
Thursday and quoted him as saying the parole board's decision
``shows there's some justice in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas will remain housed on death row near Huntsville, pending
Bush's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Radostitz, Lucas' lawyer, described him as emotional after the
parole board's announcement, and said he sounded as if he were
crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he wasn't, but as I said, you can never believe
anything Henry says,'' Radostitz said in what may be a classic
understatement. ``It sounded like crying to me. He sounded tired
and he sounded a little bit like he didn't believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporters R.G. Ratcliffe, Allan Turner and Jim Henderson
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
