<HEADER>
A7647 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN--Astros-Rockies-H     06-25 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--Astros-Rockies-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros' tour of Coors 
comes to a rocky end
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DENVER _ Leave it to Derek Bell, who probably could find something
positive to say about an ingrown toenail, to find the silver lining
in the Astros' latest run of bad luck at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we don't have to come back here this year,'' Bell
said.
</P>
<P>
   That's about the only bright spot the Astros could take from
Denver after stubbing their toes yet again in a 6-5 loss to the
Colorado Rockies on Thursday. This one took 12 innings, but the
results were no different: thin air, dry heat _ Astros lose again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is,'' a frustrated Jeff Bagwell said.
``It's not like we get overmatched up here. We just don't seem to
get any breaks. I do know one thing: Five or six runs is not enough
for us to win at this ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially when the Rockies trot to the mound a pitcher who is
making his major-league debut. Mike Saipe is no Kerry Wood, and his
5-5 Class AAA record and 4.06 ERA were hardly intimidating. But
dress him in a white baseball uniform with black pinstripes and
purple trim, and he gets a whole new set of credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Saipe didn't beat the Astros. But they didn't beat him either,
and that's what seemed to frustrate players and manager alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought we would be able to score some runs off
him,'' manager Larry Dierker said. ``He looked a little nervous,
and he wasn't throwing particularly hard. But for some reason, we
just couldn't get to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Saipe's debut overshadowed Lamar, Colo., native Scott Elarton's
first start in Coors Field, but it was utility player Kurt Abbott
who upstaged both rookie pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott's 12th-inning double off Mike Magnante drove home Vinny
Castilla for the winning run before 48,046 fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros lost both games in the two-game series, marking the
first time all season they have been swept in a series. While the
Astros have lost three in a row just once all year, they have lost
four of five at Coors Field and are 6-23 in Denver since the
Rockies entered the league.
</P>
<P>
   Saipe held the Astros to three runs in six innings and appeared
on his way to victory until Bell rejuvenated the Astros' hopes with
a game-tying two-run homer off Dave Veres in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trying to change our luck here with one swing,'' Bell
said. ``I was just trying to help us win the game. I wasn't
thinking that might be the turning point for us, because I know how
bad our luck is in this park, and I knew the game wasn't over
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   It was over for the Astros' bats, which managed just one hit
after Bell's 10th home run denied ex-Astro Veres a second save in
as many days.
</P>
<P>
   Veres and Curtis Leskanic combined for three scoreless innings
after regulation, when the Astros put only one runner in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like runs are easy to score here until you need
them,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros took a 2-0 lead in the third inning on Craig Biggio's
controversial two-run homer. The ball hit a fence behind the
outfield wall, and right fielder Dante Bichette played it off the
carom. Biggio thought it was a double until umpire Gerry Davis gave
the home-run signal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a perfect view of it,'' said Magnante, who was seated
in the bullpen. ``It was definitely a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Bichette's RBI double got a run back for the Rockies in the
bottom of the inning, and Kirt Manwaring doubled home the tying run
in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros reclaimed a one-run lead when Saipe hit Moises Alou
with the bases loaded in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker was ripe for second-guessing in the sixth inning when
Elarton, who threw 113 pitches, allowed the first two batters to
reach base before he struck out Manwaring.
</P>
<P>
   Rockies manager Don Baylor sent lefthanded pinch-hit specialist
John Vander Wal to the plate to hit for Saipe, and Dierker could
have countered with lefty C.J. Nitkowski, who was warming up.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker decided to stick with Elarton, and the non-move
backfired when Vander Wal, who was hitless in his previous 18
pinch-hit at-bats, crushed a 1-1 changeup into the right-field
seats.
</P>
<P>
   The three-run homer and 5-3 lead held up until Bell's shot in
the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I considered C.J.,'' Dierker said. ``But he (Elarton) had
struck out the guy before Vander Wal and he was still throwing
hard. I thought he still had plenty of stuff left to get Vander Wal
out. The last time I took him out, the bullpen gave it (the lead)
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, I decided to leave him in there and see if he could
get out of it. If this guy is going to be a horse for a while, he's
going to have to pitch 110 or so pitches sometimes. A lot of times,
you're going to pitch deep into games and you're not going to win.
But sometimes, you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just didn't work out this time, but I still thought Scott
pitched a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies' final push started with a perfectly executed
swinging bunt by slugging third baseman Vinny Castilla, of all
people.
</P>
<P>
   One batter later, Abbott smashed a pitch from Magnante off the
center-field wall. Carl Everett made a mad dash for the wall but
slipped at the warning track, ending any chance for a play at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker didn't think Everett had a chance, but the Astros center
fielder wondered if things might have gone differently had he taken
a more cautious approach to the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I should have sat back and played it off the wall,''
said Everett, who has the strongest arm among the Astros'
outfielders. ``I was probably a little too aggressive. This is a
tough place to play defense because the gaps are so huge. But I
think if I could have gotten it cleanly off the wall, it might have
been a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was the same old story for the Astros at Coors
Field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
