<HEADLINE>
BUS FARES FROM NEW JERSEY TO NEW YORK MAY RISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Under increasing pressure from New York officials,
the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey is edging toward
moves that could increase fares for bus and PATH train commuters
from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 15 years, the authority is studying
whether to increase the fees charged to local buses arriving at its
bus terminal on Eighth Avenue. Officials at the authority, which is
known for being guarded about its intentions, hinted that the time
might be near for an increase in the PATH fare, which has stood at
$1 since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey officials bristled at any talk of raising the fares,
as they have since 1994, when New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani began
calling for the two-state authority to cut its subsidies to
operations that primarily benefit New Jersey residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the wrong time to talk about an increase in fares,'' said
Julie Plocinik, a spokeswoman for Gov. Christie Whitman of New
Jersey. ``It's a time when we should be encouraging more people to
use mass transit to take the strain off our already congested and
aging infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's transportation commissioner, John Haley Jr., who also
sits on the authority's board, said he would recommend that she
veto any increases. Whitman and Gov. George Pataki of New York have
veto power.
</P>
<P>
   In March, as part of a review it began last year of all its
operations, the authority began looking at the fees at the bus
terminal, which lost $50 million last year. The possible fee
increases were reported in The Star-Ledger of Newark on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Commuter buses, nearly all of them from New Jersey, make up
nearly two-thirds of the buses that come into the terminal, but
provide less than a quarter of its bus revenue. While local buses
pay a base fee of $1.74 per bus, medium- and long-distance buses
pay additional surcharges of up to 15 percent of their ticket
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Authority officials said the low fee charged to local buses was
meant to encourage mass transit. It has helped New Jersey Transit,
which runs more than half of the buses that come into the terminal,
to avoid a fare increase since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Port Authority officials said Thursday that they were preparing
a study to predict how many people would continue to ride buses
under several possible pricing plans.
</P>
<P>
   John Orcutt, associate director of the Tri-State Transportation
Campaign, a watchdog group, said that the Giuliani administration's
repeated calls for a fee increase, at a time when traffic in New
York is at record levels, are ``another absurd attack by New York
politicians on the cost of commuting from New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Kalikow, an authority commissioner from New York City,
said that even if the authority increased its fees, New Jersey
Transit could avoid a fare increase by asking for more money from
the state.
</P>
<P>
   And Anthony Coles, a lawyer on Giuliani's staff, said that even
if buses became more expensive, ``It's a little silly to think that
a reasonable adjustment in the New Jersey Transit fare will cause
somebody to buy gas, pay a $4 toll and park in a garage at New York
City rates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
