<SLUG> BC-SALMON-SAVE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS BOOST EFFORTS TO SAVE PUGET SOUND SALMON RUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY, ROB TAYLOR and MICHAEL PAULSON.   
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Efforts to save endangered Puget Sound salmon runs have gotten a
boost from Washington's two U.S. senators, who have lined up almost
all of the $30 million in federal money that Washington Gov. Gary
Locke requested for a restoration effort.
</P>
<P>
   But under an appropriation bill that includes much of that $30
million, the federal government would be severely limited in what
it can do at dams on the Columbia and Snake Rivers to restore
endangered salmon runs _ largely because of efforts by Sen. Slade
Gorton, R-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   And the entire Interior Department appropriations bill, approved
Thursday by the Senate Appropriations Committee, is so loaded with
controversial measures that three Cabinet secretaries are
recommending that President Clinton veto it.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the bill is changed in conference committee, or
rewritten after a veto, the money for Puget Sound salmon is likely
to remain, Gorton indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gorton and Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., have been praised
for their efforts in obtaining the $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although providing money for Puget Sound efforts, the bill also
reflects Gorton's skepticism about salmon recovery upstream in the
Columbia River rystem, and particularly on the Snake River in
Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton, chairman of the Interior Appropriations subcommittee,
has continued his crusade to see that power generation, irrigation
and barge transportation are not damaged by measures designed to
get young salmon past a string of dams on the Columbia and Snake
rivers.
</P>
<P>
   The bill contains language that forbids the federal government
from taking any action that would ``remove, breach or diminish''
current uses at dams on the two rivers.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill also reflects an aggressive, bipartisan optimism
about moving to restore fish runs on rivers in the Puget Sound
basin and in southwest Washington. The National Marine Fisheries
Service proposed in February that Puget Sound chinook be listed
under the Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unlike the spotted owl. We are working ahead of the
curve to make sure that the endangered species listing doesn't come
down in a way that's detrimental to everybody,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   King County Executive Ron Sims said he has secured agreement
from the Clinton administration to put additional money for salmon
recovery into its budgets for fiscal years 2000 and 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen the federal government work this well,''
Sims said. ``They are very concerned as to how a metropolitan area,
one of economic vitality, can respond to the Endangered Species Act
without sapping its growth and life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sims drew contrasts between the bipartisan unity seen in western
Washington and unending conflicts over the conflicting uses _
hydropower, irrigation, shipping and salmon _ on the Columbia
River.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Columbia you have never been able to get a common
ground,'' he said. ``Over here the common ground was established
very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The money in the Interior bill would go to the state, and then
be sent back to local governments and Indian tribes. It would go
directly and immediately to improving habitat and fish passage.
</P>
<P>
   In King, Pierce and Snohomish counties, federal money would go
for currently identified projects to restore critical streamside
habitat, marine wetlands, tidal fresh water wetlands, estuary, wide
channel and floodplain habitats, and to replace culberts.
</P>
<P>
   Money would be spent for habitat acquisition to protect key
streamside areas along major salmon streams, the Cedar and
Snoqualmie rivers as well as the Bear and Issaquah Creek
tributaries of the Sammamish River.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan support for the Puget Sound effort gives it a
strong chance of remaining in any final measure.
</P>
<P>
   In another area of cooperation, Gorton has talked repeatedly
with Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt over ways of clearing up
disagreements on how to go about removing the Lower Elwha and
Glines Canyon dams from the Elwha River. Built more than 60 years
ago, without fish ladders, the dams destroyed the Olympic
Peninsula's greatest salmon fishery.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton has removed his previous insistence that the federal
government wait at least 12 years after removing the lower dam
before taking down the 210-foot-high Glines Canyon project, which
is the major barrier to miles of unspoiled salmon spawning habitat.
</P>
<P>
   But other provisions are highly controversial, and have led to a
veto threat by the Clinton administration. ``Unless this bill sees
some major revisions, it isn't going to make it through the
process,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt, Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, and Energy
Secretary Federico Pena all would recommend Clinton veto the bill
as currently written, according to a letter sent from Acting Office
of Management and Budget Director Jacob Lew to Senate
Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The Cabinet secretaries objected to what they saw as not enough
money for endangered species programs, land acquisition, Bureau of
Indian Affairs education operations, the Clean Water Action Plan,
and a program to protect artifacts of national heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The administration said it ``strongly objects'' to a number of
riders, many of which concern policy in Alaska. They include
provisions that would mandate a high level of timber sales in the
Tongass National Forest, establish an easement to build a road
across the Izembek National Wildlife Refuge, prohibit the
regulation of commercial fishing in Glacier Bay National Park, and
place new limits on federal land acquisitions in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Another controversial area is the spending bill's provision to
terminate the Interior Columbia Basin Ecosystem Management Plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Columbia Basin Ecosystem Management Project aims to
use an exhaustive scientific assessment of the vast basin to help
determine how much grazing, logging, mining and other uses federal
lands can bear.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials say that without such broad, science-based
planning, their agencies run the risk of having logging, mining and
grazing shut down by lawsuits to protect endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   But rural industries are willing to take that chance. They fear
the ecosystem project will curb their use of federal lands and,
despite federal denials, might impact private land.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton said that even federal officials believed that the
ecosystem project was ``moving up a dead-end street.'' He said the
Senate bill would ``demand much more attention to local input.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray said she is concerned that the Interior spending bill _
by locking in current uses of dams _ would jeopardize one
successful effort to bring longterm peace to fisheries and power
management along the Columbia River.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the Clinton administration is due to sign a Habitat
Conservation Agreement with the Chelan and Douglas County public
utility districts. The utilities own three big power dams on the
mid-Columbia River.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement mandates that more than 90 percent of young salmon
survive passage through dams and reservoirs. But it leaves the
utilities with wide latitude on measures they will take at the dams
to assure salmon survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked very hard to put together the mid-Columbia habitat
conservation plan, and many people fear this bill's language (on
dams) could preclude the agreement from being implemented,'' Murray
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
