<HEADLINE>
TO RUSSIA, WITH LOVE AND NOSTALGIA  
 IT'S A NICE SONG IF YOU CAN GET IT  
 BREAKING EDINA'S MOLD  
 CAMPFIRE WITHOUT FIRE  
 AN UPDATED RHETT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The chief rabbi of Moscow, PINCHAS GOLDSCHMIDT, is
taking home $3,600 to help rebuild Moscow's Lubavitch synagogue,
which was damaged by a bomb last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gift is somewhat nostalgic,'' said RABBI MARC SCHNEIER,
the president of the New York Board of Rabbis, who gave the money
for the Marina Roshche synagogue to Goldschmidt on Thursday. ``It
conjures up all these memories for me of 26 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneier had a bar mitzvah in 1972 at Moscow Choral Synagogue,
the only synagogue in operation there at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember after speaking to the congregation and seeing many
of these congregants just overwhelmed by a 13-year-old young man
who was well versed in Hebrew, in Jewish learning,'' Schneier said.
``Twenty-six years later, that's commonplace there, a daily
occurrence in Moscow.'' Goldschmidt said that Moscow has 13
synagogues now.
</P>
<P>
   It's a Nice Song If You Can Get It
</P>
<P>
   BOB MERRILL is crazy for voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill, a trumpeter and bandleader, had been hired to play at
the wedding of REGEN HORCHOW and JEFF FEARON on Nantucket, Mass.
The requests for Gershwin tunes started coming even before he left
New York _ no surprise, considering that Ms. Horchow's father,
ROGER HORCHOW, was a producer of the all-Gershwin musical ``Crazy
for You.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted `I Can't Be Bothered Now,' which was a
stump-the-band thing for me,'' Merrill said. ``I was going to try
to get the music, but Sam Ash was closed for the day.''
</P>
<P>
   So he called ERIC COMSTOCK, a singer and cabaret historian, and
left a message.
</P>
<P>
   Comstock returned the call, telling Merrill's answering machine
that he did not have sheet music for ``I Can't Be Bothered Now.''
``I learned it by ear,'' Comstock said. ``From an Astaire movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill called and left this message: ``Call back and play it on
my machine.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Merrill landed on Nantucket, he checked his machine.
Sure enough, there was a message from Comstock. In fact, there were
two. ``The first time he did it, he got cut off,'' Merrill said,
who transcribed the melody and arranged it.
</P>
<P>
   The review? ``They loved it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking Edina's Mold
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She's sweet, she's darling, but don't call LYNNE
FRANKS ``sweetie darling.'' At least, not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Franks is the pioneering English fashion publicist who
claims to be the prototype for Edina, the pioneering English
fashion publicist on the BBC sitcom ``Absolutely Fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Ms. Franks has written a book, ``Absolutely Now: A
Futurist's Journey to Her Inner Truth'' (Overlook Press), a
blueprint for entrepreneurs who want to follow in her footsteps. As
she explained it at a party at a Benetton store at 597 Fifth Ave.,
it advises simplifying one's life and sharing one's expertise.
</P>
<P>
   The similarities between Ms. Franks and Edina are, as one or the
other (but probably Edina) might say, really quite freaky, darling.
Both hobnobbed with fledgling fashion designers and British
nobility in the 1980s. Both are divorced, with children. Both
became followers of Buddhism. And both possess whatever the English
call chutzpah.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one striking difference: Edina remains trapped in
cable reruns. Ms. Franks fled, divorcing her husband, selling her
business and moving to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   JENNIFER SAUNDERS, the sitcom's creator and a former client of
Ms. Franks, did not return calls for comment. She has been quoted
as saying that Edina was not modeled on Ms. Franks. ``She has to
say that or I could sue,'' Ms. Franks said. ``Not that I would, of
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Campfire Without Fire
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ PETER, PAUL and MARY are scheduled to perform at a
``campfire sing-along'' for the New York City Parks Foundation on
Monday evening in Central Park. Don't look for a real campfire.
What will be blowing in the wind will be a ``faux fire,'' as their
spokesman describes it. The flames will be made of orange silk and
will be fanned by an electric fan. ``Fire Department regulations,''
the spokesman, ANDY MORRIS, explained.
</P>
<P>
   An Updated Rhett
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone With the Wind'' has gone high-tech, with a Web site
(www.franklymydear.com). ``In trying to get someone who would see
`Pulp Fiction' to come and see `Gone With the Wind,''' said GORDON
PADDISON, who oversees the site for New Line Cinema, ``we tried to
translate it into this medium and break it to a new, young, hip,
edgy audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of long, tedious paragraphs, the site offers Rhett
Butler and Scarlett O'Hara postcards that users can send by e-mail.
Visitors to the site can also vote on which actors they would cast
if ``Gone With the Wind'' were being remade. As of Thursday, TOM
SELLECK was leading HARRISON FORD by 700 votes in the balloting for
Rhett, and NICOLE KIDMAN was 173 votes ahead of KATE WINSLET. And
91 people had voted for RUPAUL.
</P>
</TEXT>
