<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-IMMIG-SLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEAR OF DEPORTATION CITED IN IMMIGRANT'S DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Philippines)  (ja) 
 By DAVID ROHDE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An illegal immigrant who may have been afraid to report to the
police that she was being abused by her former boyfriend was found
dead in the basement of her Englewood, N.J., apartment Thursday,
officials said. Prosecutors say that they believe the man killed
her, but that he has apparently fled the country.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the woman, Alena Gonzales, a 36-year-old mother
of two from the Philippines who disappeared Saturday night, had
tried to break off her relationship with the man, 32-year-old Fredy
Bustamanti, and was engaged to another man, Peter Bartells.
Bartells reported her missing to the Englewood police on Sunday
after she failed to show up for a date Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Ms. Gonzales said that Bustamanti repeatedly beat her
over the course of an eight-year-relationship and threatened to
report her to immigration officials if she reported his actions.
They said that after Ms. Gonzales began seeing another man,
Bustamanti repeatedly threatened to kill her, her boyfriend and
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fredy was always physically abusive and violent with her,''
said Susan Goodman, a friend of Ms. Gonzales. ``She is illegal
herself and she always had this fear of being deported.''
</P>
<P>
   After receiving a tip Thursday, the police discovered Ms.
Gonzales' body in the basement of the apartment building in which
she and Bustamanti lived at 26 W. Palisades Ave., Englewood's main
commercial thoroughfare. The Bergen County prosecutor, William
Schmidt, said the autopsy results showed that Ms. Gonzales was
strangled to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``An object was used to effect the strangulation and the
asphyxiation,'' he said, adding that the police were not sure
exactly where Ms. Gonzales was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said investigators believe Bustamanti, who worked for
Campoli Construction in Cresskill, N.J., flew to his native
Guatemala on Saturday. He said Bustamanti's estranged wife had once
filed a domestic abuse complaint against him.
</P>
<P>
   Violeta Hernandes, 30, the landlord of the Palisades Avenue
building, said Bustamanti had moved in about three years ago. He
then asked her if Ms. Gonzales, the mother of twin 12-year-old
girls still in the Philippines, could move into a $250 room in the
building.
</P>
<P>
   She said the couple looked ``happy'' and that she never saw any
hitting in the relationship, and added that she was ``very
surprised'' by the allegations against Bustamanti.
</P>
<P>
   But Schmidt said Ms. Gonzales' friends told prosecutors the
relationship was ``not a good one.'' When asked whether the
relationship was violent he said yes.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said ``the vast majority'' of homicides prosecutors see
in Bergen County are the result of ``violent relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that Ms. Gonzales' plight was not unusual and that
illegal immigrants frequently hesitate to report domestic abuse.
They are also threatened with exposure to immigration officials by
bosses or people with whom they get involved in disputes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very common,'' said Mimi Kuo, a counselor who has dealt
with issues of sexual assault in the Asian community. ``There's a
lot of silence around this issue. It's only when something as
drastic as this happens that the issue gets the attention it
deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gonzales' friend Ms. Goodman said that Ms. Gonzales had
arrived in the United States about 10 years ago and had held a
variety of jobs as a housekeeper. Her earnings here went primarily
to supporting her two daughters and her 65-year-old mother in the
Philippines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
