<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILDREN-SLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER CHARGED WITH KILLING TWO OF HER CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By DUAYNE DRAFFEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMITYVILLE, N.Y. _ Two children were found dead in their home in
this Suffolk County village by the police early Thursday morning,
and their 31-year-old mother has been charged with killing them.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said that the mother, Debra Roberson, 31,
called relatives shortly after midnight and told them the children
were dead. Her relatives called the police, and two police officers
went to Ms. Roberson's apartment at 505 Broadway about 1 a.m. When
no one answered repeated knocks and calls, they broke in the door,
the police said. In one room of the three-room apartment, they
said, they found Ms. Roberson standing over her dead children,
Melvin King, 5, and his sister, Delvin King, 6.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, the police said the cause of death seemed to be
burns from scalding hot water. Both children had extensive burns on
their bodies and arms, and Melvin had burns on his face and head as
well, the police said. The children had been dead ``for some time''
before the police arrived, said Detective Lt. John Gierasch,
commander of the Suffolk County Homicide Squad. Ms. Roberson's
7-month-old son, Hasson, was found sleeping and unharmed in another
room, the police said, and he is now with relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Gierasch said Ms. Roberson would be held overnight at the Fourth
Precinct headquarters in Hauppauge and would be arraigned Friday
morning in First District County Court in Central Islip on two
second-degree murder charges. She had no previous police record, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said that there had been a few complaints about
drug sales from another apartment in the three-story house, but
that over all there had been very little crime in that area of
Amityville.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roberson had moved into the front apartment of the well-kept
white house with green trim just north of the Sunrise Highway about
four months ago, the police said. Neighbors said her children were
always nicely dressed and seemed well cared for.
</P>
<P>
   One neighbor, Frances Taylor, said that she often saw Ms.
Roberson playing outdoors with her children and that they seemed
happy. ``She was always with them, laughing and having little
picnics in the front yard,'' Ms. Taylor said. ``There was no sign
of something like this about to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   A next-door neighbor, who said her children often played with
Melvin and Delvin, said: ``They were good kids and didn't get into
trouble. They never said anything bad about their mother, either.''
The woman, who refused to give her name, said she had not seen the
children for about a week, and some of their classmates at
Northeast Elementary School said the King children had not been in
class for about that length of time.
</P>
<P>
   The police said they were investigating reports by at least one
neighbor that Ms. Roberson had been acting strangely in the last
two days, keeping her blinds down and repeatedly crossing herself
as she stood at a window.
</P>
</TEXT>
