<SLUG> BC-NJ-GASOLINE-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR FACES OPPOSITION TO PROPOSED GAS-TAX RISE
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JENNIFER PRESTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Republican lawmakers in the General Assembly are
considering tapping the state's $661 million budget surplus to help
pay for transportation projects rather than support Gov. Christie
Whitman's proposal to raise the gasoline tax by 5 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The growing opposition among Whitman's fellow Republicans in the
Assembly to an increase in the gasoline tax for transportation
improvements comes less than a week after lawmakers rejected her
plan for a 2-cents-a-gallon increase to help pay for the
preservation of open space and farmland.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman has proposed putting the question of the gasoline tax
increase on the ballot for voters to consider this fall. Lacking
legislative support for a tax increase for open space, Whitman and
legislative leaders are now planning to borrow more than $1 billion
over the next 30 years to help preserve 1 million acres of open
space in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said Thursday, however, that she remains firmly
committed to a 5-cents-a gallon gasoline tax increase for
transportation projects. But some Republican lawmakers are now
saying the state should consider other options to pay for mass
transit and highway improvements, including borrowing money and
paying for the borrowing out of the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Assembly is currently looking for alternatives to the
governor's plan,'' said Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, R-Salem
County. ``That doesn't mean that the governor's plan is not the one
we are going to end up with.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said that he believed that there was strong support in
the Assembly for spending more money on transportation projects
despite opposition from some Assembly members over putting a
gasoline tax on the ballot this year.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican-controlled state Senate, there is more support
for the governor's proposal for a gasoline tax referendum. A bill
has been introduced with bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it could pass the Senate to put it on the ballot,''
said Senate President Donald DiFrancesco, R-Scotch Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said Thursday that she was continuing to push for the
nickel increase. She described the proposal to use the budget
surplus, a ``Band-Aid approach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a time for leadership and the acknowledgment that we
have needs,'' Whitman said. ``We have infrastructure needs in the
state of New Jersey that should not be addressed in a piecemeal
fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Richard Bagger, a Republican and the chairman of the
Assembly Budget and Appropriations Committee, said that Republican
members of the caucus were deeply divided over the issue. ``There
is a wide divergence of opinion,'' said Bagger, who supports the
governor's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the General Assembly are up for re-election next
year, causing some to worry that supporting a gasoline tax increase
could hurt them at the polls with tax-weary voters. Senators are
not up for re-election until 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
