<HEADLINE>
GORE, MAURO WARM UP FOR TEXAS DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ In a warm-up for their joint appearance Friday
night at the State Democratic Convention, Vice President Al Gore
joined gubernatorial candidate Garry Mauro on a campaign stop
Thursday designed to capitalize on the historic strength here of
Mauro and his party.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Republicans said the Democrats' visions of a Mauro victory,
either statewide or in El Paso, were just another desert mirage.
They predicted Gov. George W. Bush would become the first
Republican gubernatorial contender to carry this west Texas border
city, despite Bush's controversial stances on hot-button topics
involving gambling and radioactive waste.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who spent part of the day in Houston, met with El Paso
educators and dignitaries before rallying Mauro supporters at a
$500-per-person dinner. That event was expected to generate
$150,000 for Mauro's campaign, which earlier this week got an
estimated $250,000 boost from a Washington, D.C., event attended by
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While the incoming dollars could help Mauro buy media exposure
for his underdog campaign, aides said Mauro will tell party
loyalists at the state convention that it's time for Democrats to
think in unconventional terms about capturing November votes.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic convention opens Friday in San Antonio, with
6,500 delegates and 2,200 alternates gathering to elect a new
chairman, adopt a campaign platform and listen to speeches from
statewide candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the list of speakers are Gore, civil rights leader Jesse
Jackson and Houston Mayor Lee Brown, who was elected in a
nonpartisan election. But Brown, an African-American who served in
the Democratic Clinton administration, is expected to discuss his
winning campaign strategy to the black and Hispanic caucuses of the
state party.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing a successor to outgoing state party Chairman Bill
White of Houston, Democrats will choose between Molly Beth Malcolm
of Texarkana, a former Republican who joined the Democrats with a
convert's fervor and now leads Texas Democratic Women; and San
Augustine County Judge Curt Goetz, who made his first Democratic
political speeches as a child campaigning in his father's state
representative race.
</P>
<P>
   In El Paso, Mauro has pointed out that Bush has criticized the
Speaking Rock Casino, operated by the Tigua Indians, and that Bush
supports plans of the Texas Low-level Radioactive Waste Disposal
Authority to open a facility near Sierra Blanca.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro aides claimed Bush is threatening 900 jobs at the casino
and is endangering the environment in Texas and Mexico by
supporting the disposal site. Mauro's camp also accuses Bush of
having only a superficial interest in El Paso, as opposed to the
long-standing ties Mauro developed as land commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Governor Bush and his political operatives to talk about
winning El Paso is a little like Garry Mauro saying he's going to
win The Woodlands,'' Rogers said. ``The bottom line is Garry has
always done well in El Paso. He's always done 60 percent-plus and
he'll do 60 percent-plus again. He will do much better than Ann
Richards did last time,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   El Paso County was one of the few bright spots for Richards in
her 1994 defeat by Bush. She outpolled Bush 50,560 to 40,011.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro is hoping that his role in advocating veterans' housing
and land programs will help him in this community of more than
600,000 people, which has sizable military populations because of
nearby Fort Bliss. The county has 325,127 registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat also hopes voters associate him with clean-burning
fuels, which he likewise has promoted as land commissioner since
1983. Air pollution _ much of it wafting across the Rio Grande from
Ciudad Juarez, Mexico _ is a major annoyance in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Bush predicts he will dominate in November here, and a
Texas Poll earlier this month gave his prediction credence. In the
55-county West Texas region, 78 percent of the respondents backed
Bush compared to 13 percent for Mauro. It was Bush's best regional
performance in the state _ and Mauro's worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should whup me in El Paso. It's been a Democratic
stronghold a long time,'' Bush said. ``But I feel like I've got a
good chance to do well this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of El Paso know I care about their community,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Mauro's aides are wrong that he wants to close down
the Tigua casino, although he is opposed to outlawed games known as
8-liners.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to do is enforce the law, and if the law says that
a game is illegal, then I think we ought to make sure the game does
not go forward. I've never said I want to shut down the casino,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also bristled at Mauro's suggestion that the low-level
waste site 60 miles southeast of El Paso will harm Texas and
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the site is deemed safe, I support it,'' Bush said, noting
that the site's licensing process is incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
