<SLUG> BC-FBC-BARNHOUSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSE BOWL DIALS AT&AMP;T FOR SPONSOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Granddad looks different. Nose ring. Watching the X-Games. He's
running with a different crowd, too. A big-money bunch. Now we find
out he's seeing another woman. Name used to be Ma Bell. It's not
love, but a match of convenience.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Bowl nobly calls itself the Granddaddy Of Them All.
And, with a tradition that dates to 1902, the title is appropriate
and correct. But in the past decade the Old Guy has been through
more changes than a Las Vegas showgirl.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Bowl and ABC Sports, its television partner, announced
Thursday that AT&AMP;T will be the game's corporate sponsor for four
years. That announcement should be no surprise given the computers,
cars and cellular phones whose names litter college football's
postseason marquee.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fact that the Rose Bowl has given in to crass
corporate culture is yet another sign of changing times in the bowl
business. The group that runs the Rose Bowl is second only to The
Masters when it comes to equal parts hallowed tradition and snooty
arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rose Bowl has been forced to change. Ten years ago, it
switched from NBC to ABC for more money. Two years ago, it agreed
to join the Bowl Championship Series when Big Ten and Pacific-10
coaches claimed a recruiting disadvantage because they felt locked
out of the national championship picture created by the bowl
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Rose steps down off its pedestal to join the
Fiesta, the Orange and the Sugar in the Bowl Championship Series
rotation. If a Pac-10 or Big Ten team has a shot at the national
championship, which has been the case the past two years, the Rose
won't have its traditional game between the Big Ten and Pac-10
champs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud to be part of giving the public what it wants, No.
1 vs. No. 2,'' said Harriman Cronk of the Rose Bowl executive
committee, which will play host to the championship series title
game in 2002. ``I think we have the best of both worlds. Can you
imagine what it would be like to invite Notre Dame? It will be very
exciting the first time we have an opportunity to bring in somebody
different.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Rose joined the series fold two years ago, it was
apparent that a corporate sponsorship was necessary. Ticket prices
for the Rose Bowl have nearly doubled in recent years. The prices
will increase from $75 this year to $110 for the 1999 game,
increasing revenue to about $11 million.
</P>
<P>
   But with the series bowls paying about $12 million per team, the
Rose and ABC needed another revenue stream.
</P>
<P>
   ``A corporate sponsorship wasn't a condition of the Rose Bowl
becoming part of the Bowl Championship Series,'' ABC Sports
executive vice president Brian McAndrews said. ``It was more
something that needed to be worked out to make the economics
work.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T was in the news this week with its $38 billion purchase of
TCI, the cable outfit. Writing another check for a million or two
for a corporate sponsorship was no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The TCI deal was a strictly business deal,'' AT&AMP;T spokesman
Burke Stinson said. ``The Rose Bowl deal is good for AT&AMP;T's image
and is a plus for us. We hope to bring class not crass to the Rose
Bowl proceedings. We're not looking to plaster the place with AT&AMP;T
logos, on the field or on the players' uniforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh huh. Sure.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Rose is retaining some of its haughtiness. ``We
have consistently said we would not accept a title sponsor, just a
presenting one,'' Cronk said.
</P>
<P>
   It might be the ``Tostitos'' Fiesta Bowl and the ``Nokia'' Sugar
Bowl and the ``Federal Express'' Orange Bowl, but a Rose is Rose is
a Rose Bowl ... presented by AT&AMP;T.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-98 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
