<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SIDEWALK-VENDORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR ABANDONS PLAN TO BAN SIDEWALK VENDORS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's administration on Thursday
moved further away from its plan for a widespread ban on sidewalk
vendors in Manhattan, announcing that it would work with the City
Council to instead regulate the number of people who sell food,
tube socks, comic books and paperbacks on busy streets.
</P>
<P>
   City officials insisted that they still wanted to end vending on
many sidewalks to reduce congestion, though they said they had not
decided how many. But it was clear from testimony before a City
Council committee Thursday that the mayor was seeking a compromise
in his aggressive campaign to combat clusters of food carts and
street artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a middle ground between having no vendors entirely on
a street as opposed to a limited number _ perhaps one, perhaps two
is something that is manageable,'' Joseph Rose, the city's planning
director, said after an appearance before the council's
Transportation Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rose's comments marked the second time in just over a week that
the administration had scaled back what was once an ambitious plan
to ban vending on 144 blocks in Manhattan. And together, the moves
amounted to an unusual concession for the mayor, who has seemed to
revel in fighting what he considers quality-of-life offenders like
reckless cab drivers, turnstile jumpers, ``squeegee men'' and, most
recently, sidewalk vendors.
</P>
<P>
   But while the public has been largely supportive of much of
Giuliani's quality-of-life crusade, the planned vending crackdown
produced little enthusiasm. Thousands of customers signed petitions
opposing the bans and applauded when vendors shut their carts for a
day and marched down Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, lawyers for the city have voiced concerns about
fighting lawsuits by vendors and street artists. Rose said the
administration was now willing to replace or reshape the Street
Vendor Review Panel, a body dominated by mayoral appointees. The
panel's charter limits it to all-or-nothing decisions about whether
to close streets to vending.
</P>
<P>
   Rose told the committee that the administration now favored a
more flexible approach that could put caps on the number of vendors
in certain locations rather than a wholesale ban on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of its limited authority, the panel does not have the
ability today to reconcile street vending with congestion and other
streetscape concerns in the most successful manner,'' Rose
testified. ``Additional legislation is warranted to achieve a more
balanced result.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose testified in a respectful, conciliatory tone that
contrasted sharply with the brusque indignation that many of the
mayor's appointees have expressed in recent testimony before the
council, which has so bitterly fought the mayor over the city
budget and other matters that the two sides have barely been
talking in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   So council members were delighted, if stunned, to find the mayor
enlisting their help in regulating street peddlers, who have
bedeviled mayors for most of this century. ``New York City's
pushcart wars have now raged longer than the Cold War,'' said
Councilman Noach Dear, D-Brooklyn, the chairman of Thursday's
hearing. ``It appears an elusive cease-fire could be at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the administration's sudden turn to diplomacy,
Colleen Roche, the mayor's spokeswoman, said, ``The administration
is always open to discussing rational and thoughtful proposals.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Vallone, the City Council speaker, called Rose's statement
``a major step in the right direction'' of defusing the controversy
over the mayor's efforts to ban sidewalk vendors on 144 Manhattan
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how well intended, the way you do things makes a big
difference in how the public is going to receive it,'' Vallone
said. ``They were trying to do this by coming down with fiats and
orders.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite City Hall's conciliatory posture, spokesmen for the
city's best-organized group of vendors, the Big Apple Food Vendors
Association, said they remained suspicious of the mayor. ``If you
tell me you're going to help me but you keep grinding me down and
keep putting the knife in my back, you're not helping me,'' said
Jeffrey Cicio, the group's president.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday night, Deputy Mayor Rudy Washington
seemed to indicate that the group had good reason to be concerned,
saying he hoped that about two-thirds of the 144 streets would be
off limits to vending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a congestion problem on certain streets in this
town and vendors cannot go anyplace they want to go,'' Washington
said. ``By the very nature of their business, they want to go where
the people are. That is inherently dangerous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
