<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-DRAFT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASH, NOWITZKI CONSIDER MAVS CONTRACTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Mavericks' whirlwind draft took a turn in the right
direction yesterday, as newly acquired point guard Steve Nash
indicated he is willing to sign a long-term contract.
</P>
<P>
   And as owner Ross Perot Jr., general manager Don Nelson and
assistant coach Donnie Nelson flew to Germany, the agent for
first-round pick Dirk Nowitzki also admitted there is at least a
possibility his client will play in America next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know these people and there are problems to work
out,'' agent Holger Geschwinder said by telephone from Wurzburg,
Germany. ``But we are honored and happy they are coming. Perhaps it
can finish with Dirk playing in Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson engineered a three-team trade Wednesday night that
left his team without its 1999 first-round pick but with Nash,
Nowitzki and the immense pressure of both having to immediately
sign the German prospect and make the playoffs next season in order
to make the deal a success. The team passed on Kansas forward Paul
Pierce, who was available at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he made the moves not only because of his affection
for his new players but also because an evaluation that next year's
draft _ expected to be headed by UCLA point guard Baron Davis and
Connecticut small forward Richard Hamilton _ will be generally
weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gamble, yeah, we could fall on our face again and give
up what could be the first pick in the draft,'' Nelson said
yesterday morning before boarding a 2:30 p.m. flight for Germany to
open negotiations with Nowitzki. ``But it's a risk worth taking.''
</P>
<P>
   The chances of signing the 6-foot-11 Nowitzki improved when
Geschwinder, who on Tuesday warned NBA teams that they would be
``wasting'' their pick on Nowitzki, petitioned the German
Basketball Federation yesterday for a special exemption that will
allow Nowitzki to stay in Germany over the weekend to talk with the
Mavericks instead of joining his Under-22 national team for a
tournament in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll talk to them out of respect for the NBA,'' said
Geschwinder, credited with discovering the 20-year-old
``wunderkind''. ``Every boy who bounces a ball in the streets of
Germany dreams of making the NBA. Dirk is no different.''
</P>
<P>
   Told that Nowitzki, who concludes a one-year commitment to the
German army Tuesday, is being billed as the best German import
since the Volkswagen, Geschwinder deadpanned that ``Dirk is a
Porsche.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, several roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   Geschwinder is concerned about the NBA's impending lockout on
July 1, and he said Nowitzki already has four contract offers of $1
million or more ]tax-free from Kinder Bologna, Bennetton Treviso
and Milan in Italy and Barcelona in Spain. He also said that the
team Nowitzki played on this season _ the DJK Wurzburg X-Rays of
the German League's weak second division _ is out of the running
for his services.
</P>
<P>
   Under the salary cap,the Mavericks will be able to offer
Nowitzki a three-year contract paying him approximately $1.3
million next season, but they will not be able to have contact with
him if the lockout is invoked Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Nelsons and Perot are scheduled to arrive in the Bavarian
town of Wurzburg and take Geschwinder, Nowitzki and his family to
dinner tonight. Nash, acquired for Bubba Wells, Martin Muursepp and
the '99 pick, declined an invitation to join the party because of
family obligations in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed I can't make it,'' he said from England.
``Maybe I'll send a singing telegram.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Nelson, ``I don't have a clue what's going to happen. I'll
just probably sleep on his porch until I convince him to come back
with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Geschwinder said the biggest hurdle will be Nowitzki's
commitment to the German federation] and his desire to play for his
country in the 2000 Olympics in Australia. Pointing out that
European teams are agreeing to make allowances for Nowitzki to play
in February-March qualifications in '99, he said a similar deal
would have to be part of an agreement with the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   Said Geschwinder: ``Money will be a factor but not the first
thing on the list. He wants to be able to play and develop his
game, not sit the bench. Dirk's family runs a profitable wallpaper
business. This isn't all about big money.''
</P>
<P>
   Nash, meanwhile, said the Mavericks have already spoken with his
agent, Bill Duffy, about signing a long-term contract extension
before next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very agreeable to that because I'm excited about this
team,'' said Nash, entering the final year of a three-year deal
scheduled to pay him $1.05 million next season. ``I'm ready to get
consistent minutes. I'm not going to out-athlete you or jump over
you, but I'm going to dive on the floor and beat you with my
balance of skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, who tried to acquire Nash before last February's trading
deadline, said yesterday he considers Nash a better prospect that
Arizona's Mike Bibby, the second player taken in Wednesday's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think \rNash\scan play 35 minutes and get you 20 points and
10 assists a night,'' Nelson said. ``He's that good.'' /
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
