<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC--WORLD </SLUG>
 CUP-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Stunning goal 
by Hernandez 
advances cause
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAINT-ETIENNE, France _ They called it a miracle, and they said
it happened because they felt the pride and the heart of the
Mexican people lift them.
</P>
<P>
   They prayed, too.
</P>
<P>
   They stopped the team bus on the way to Stade Geoffroy-Guichard
and visited a cathedral where a statue of the Virgin de Guadelupe
stood. They kissed the statue's feet and crossed themselves. They
lit candles. They went to the stadium and pulled on their jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   And then, they went out and played the most entertaining,
unlikely and dramatic game the 1998 World Cup has seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were close to dead,'' Mexico goalkeeper Jorge Campos said,
``but we came back.''
</P>
<P>
   The show put on by the tri-color Thursday afternoon wasn't only
about coming back from two goals down in the final moments to tie
the Netherlands 2-2. Mexico had come from behind twice in this
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   It was prayers answered in spectacular fashion.
</P>
<P>
   It was knowing that all hopes of staying alive in the World Cup
were slipping away. It was playing 10 men on 11 after a
questionable call led to Mexico's Ramon Ramirez arguing vehemently
and getting ejected.
</P>
<P>
   It was facing the mighty orange machine of the Netherlands, a
team many expect to lift the trophy at the end of this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   It was Luis Hernandez, the Mexican heartthrob with the flowing
blond hair, sprinting upfield, poking in the equalizing goal just
15 seconds before the final whistle and then falling to his knees
and crying at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you saw was the pride of the Mexican,'' said Hernandez,
whose goal came in the 95th minute and surely will be remembered by
Mexican fans for years to come. ``We are all like that. We don't
want to die without fighting to the last man. We don't want to give
up. Mexicans fight to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't have gotten any closer to the end at rollicking
Stade Geoffroy-Guichard.
</P>
<P>
   As Mexico trailed throughout, Belgium, the other contender for
the Group E berth behind the Dutch, was defeating South Korea in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to hope that the Koreans would tie the game
over there and help us,'' Mexican coach Manuel Lapuente said. ``We
knew we had to do it ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   And they did, in memorable fashion, clinching the berth and
moving on to face another World Cup favorite, Germany, in
Montpellier on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got out of a tricky situation,'' Mexican captain Alberto
Garcia Aspe said. ``Most of us didn't know what was going on in the
other game. We showed the kind of team we can be. Right now we feel
like we can take on anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The South Koreans did come back to tie Belgium in the other
Group E game, which meant Mexico would have advanced anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexican way is you go out and win or lose; live or die,''
Hernandez said. ``You give everything for the win.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the tri-color started slowly, as the Dutch whipped
through the Mexican defense for a pair of goals and three more
opportunities in the first 19 minutes, Mexico finally gathered
itself and counterattacked strongly in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Pelaez, a journeyman player rarely used on the national
team until recently, finally broke stout Dutch goalkeeper Edwin van
der Sar with a well-placed header off a corner kick only 15 minutes
before the end of regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an unforgettable moment now that I can remember my
whole life,'' Pelaez said.
</P>
<P>
   Campos then turned back a pair of Dutch chances with spectacular
saves, as Mexico pushed everyone forward trying desperately for the
game-tying goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was over, we thought we won,'' said Dutch
striker Phillip Cocu, who scored his team's first goal. ``It's
never over before the final whistle, but we had them down and we
were playing our game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought our hardest. We fought and fought to keep them away,
but Mexico was a champion today.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was Hernandez, whose sprained ankle had him listed as
doubtful before kickoff, who blasted through the middle of the
Dutch penalty box in the 95th minute, as referee Abdul Al Zeid was
looking at his watch, counting down the seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Pelaez headed a pass perfectly in front of Hernandez, who beat
Jaap Stam and nudged the ball past van der Sar.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium erupted with bedlam from the Mexican fans and groans
of agony from the Dutch.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know about the Mexican people, you know we do not do
anything without our hearts nearly breaking first,'' said
Hernandez, who was limping after the game and says he again is not
sure if he will be able to play against Germany. ``There is nothing
like this flavor in our mouths right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to lose. This is the ultimate triumph. We have
to dedicate this game to the people of Mexico. We felt their
support. They believed in us. We fought for Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it all seemed so divine for this once-embattled team
playing wide-open, dynamic soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the type of team that will attack with confidence
against anybody,'' striker Cuauhtemoc Blanco said. ``We're showing
a lot of character in this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second consecutive game in which Mexico trailed 2-0
against a favored team, only to come back for the tie. Had Belgium
been able to hang on against Mexico this week, it would have
advanced instead.
</P>
<P>
   And in the game Mexico won over South Korea, Mexico also was
losing in the second half 1-0,but came back.
</P>
<P>
   This time the odds seemed especially long, considering how
strong the Netherlands looked in a 5-0 win over South Korea on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very good show, but they outplayed us in the second
half,'' van der Sar said. ``We didn't win, we didn't lose, but it's
not enough to just get to the second round. We want to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, it felt like Mexico won that game today.''
</P>
<P>
   As Mexican fans went wild after the whistle, it felt like a
Mexican victory, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``El corazon! El corazon!,'' Blanco screamed, pounding his fist
into his chest, with Mexico's fans breaking into cheers and chants.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez made his way to the edge of the grandstands and led
thousands of Mexicans in one of their trademark cheers _ ``Mexico,
Mexico, rah-rah-rah.''
</P>
<P>
   Players draped Mexican flags over their shoulders and donned
sombreros. And choruses of Cielito Lindo, the unofficial Mexican
soccer anthem, rang through the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot to do,'' Hernandez said. ``If we can
outplay the Dutch like we did today, we can outplay anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
