<SLUG> BC-SOC--UNITED </SLUG>
 STATES -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Shutout loss to Yugoslavia compounds problems for Americans
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAINT-ETIENNE, France _ It was less than a minute into the game
Thursday when U.S. midfielder Frankie Hejduk's header bounced off
the Yugoslavian goal post.
</P>
<P>
   It was less than five minutes before the end of the game when
U.S. striker Preki Radosavljevic perfectly struck a free kick from
20 yards out, curving it over the wall of Yugoslavian defenders and
directly at the goal.
</P>
<P>
   It sailed inches high.
</P>
<P>
   And there you had the appropriate bookend images on the final 90
minutes of the 1998 U.S. World Cup experience.
</P>
<P>
   Clang. Whiff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were never able to capitalize in front of the net,''
embattled U.S. coach Steve Sampson said after the game. ``Everyone
gave it their best tonight, but we have to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could have epitomized the disappointing U.S. effort at
the World Cup better than its final game, a 1-0 loss to Yugoslavia
in which all the American problems came to light.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans played well in spurts, particularly in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   They had impressive moments, as good as any team in the world
could have had. It put a scare into a quality European opponent. It
had opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   But in front of the goal and on the scoreboard, the Americans
came up empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started off well, but unfortunately we conceded the early
goal,'' Sampson said. ``I thought we improved with every match we
played but we need to do better in front of goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We created some opportunities, but we couldn't take them.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia made the most of its chances, just as Iran did
against the United States on Sunday in a 2-1 win and Germany did
before that in a 2-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavians scored all they needed at Stade de la Beaujoire
in Nantes in the fourth minute.
</P>
<P>
   Defender Slobodan Komljenovic reacted perfectly after U.S.
goalkeeper Brad Friedel deflected a 35-yard free kick by Sinisa
Mihajlovic.
</P>
<P>
   Komljenovic headed in the rebound, and from there the
Yugoslavians merely had to step up the defense and hold on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were worried about playing the Americans,'' Yugoslavia
coach Slobodan Santrac said. ``We expected them to come out and
attack and they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the most of our goal, but the Americans played well
and I think they are a team that will continue to progress in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were only a few legitimate U.S. chances to tie the
game, but, like so many other times in this tournament, the
opportunities were not converted.
</P>
<P>
   The United States ends the 1998 Cup with just one goal in three
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavians move on to the quarterfinals, finishing second
in Group F behind Germany, which Thursday night defeated Iran 2-0
in Montpellier, where Germany can remain until Monday when it faces
Mexico in the round of 16.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia will face the Netherlands also Monday in Toulouse.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson, who was harshly criticized by some of his players for
what they said was a lack of direction going into the World Cup,
made significant changes in the lineup for Thursday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Four players started for the first time in the game. But most
notably, Sampson kept veteran U.S. defender Alexi Lalas, who was
among Sampson's most vocal critics, on the bench throughout the
tournament, as he substituted in other veterans such as Marcelo
Balboa, Eric Wynalda and Preki.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the snub of Lalas and again not starting Balboa,
Wynalda and Preki, Sampson said: ``We played well against Iran
without them and even better tonight, so I don't think that they
would have added much more to the team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
