<HEADLINE>
PARTY SWITCH POINTS TO SHIFT AMONG HISPANIC VOTERS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The political conversion of Herman Badillo, the
former U.S. representative, deputy mayor and mayoral candidate,
from Democrat to Republican was greeted Thursday largely with
dispassionate shrugs from the city's Hispanic politicians, most of
them Democrats, who portrayed Badillo as a political relic who was
out of step with the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   But despite such nonchalance, several of the city's Hispanic
politicians, all of them Democrats, said that Badillo's party
switch should serve as a call to Democratic Party officials to take
the city's Hispanic voters more seriously and to ensure that
Hispanic leaders play a more central role in the political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Badillo, a fixture in the city's political landscape for
decades, made official Thursday what many politicians already
considered a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials said they believed that Badillo's
announcement would have little meaning in terms of the Republican
Party's influence among Hispanic New Yorkers. But in recent years,
Republicans have made slight inroads among the 2.2 million Hispanic
New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll of 1,000 Hispanic New Yorkers conducted by the
Hispanic Federation indicated that the percentage of Hispanic
registered Republicans has increased to 12 percent, from 10 percent
a year ago. An even larger increase was recorded among Dominican
New Yorkers, who account for about a quarter of the city's Hispanic
residents and are the fastest-growing immigrant group in New York
City. About 16 percent of Dominican New Yorkers are registered
Republicans, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians suggested that the increased Republican
registration was the result of five years of New York City's being
led by a Republican mayor, Rudolph Giuliani, whose popularity among
Hispanic New Yorkers has climbed.
</P>
<P>
   Others said that many of the new Hispanic immigrants, especially
those from South and Central America, tend to be more conservative
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Miranda, a consultant and former president of the Hispanic
Federation, said there is a growing tendency among these Hispanic
New Yorkers to register as Republicans or as independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   While a subtle shift toward the Republican Party may be
occurring among some Hispanic voters, with the exception of Badillo
it is not reflected among the city's leading Hispanic politicians.
</P>
<P>
   The most influential of the current crop of Hispanic politicians
are all Democrats, and they include Fernando Ferrer, the Bronx
borough president; U.S. Rep. Nydia Velazquez; Rep. Jose Serrano,
and members of the City Council and the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Badillo's formal announcement, made at a press conference with
Giuliani and William Powers, the state Republican chairman, at his
side, caused some reflection among many of the erstwhile colleagues
of a man who was once the city's most prominent Hispanic
politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``In practical terms, it means very little except that the
Republican Party will be able to showcase Herman as a Puerto Rican
who found religion in their party,'' said Assemblyman Roberto
Ramirez, the Democratic Party chairman in the Bronx, Badillo's home
borough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that Mr. Badillo has been espousing Republican
ideology for quite a few years now,'' Ramirez continued. ``If we
were talking about Herman Badillo in the 1960s or the 1970s, when
he pushed issues that had meaning in the community, this would be a
big event. But the fact of the matter is, most of us wondered what
took him so long.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ramirez added that Badillo's announcement was nonetheless
``a real sounding alarm'' that the Democratic Party ``will have to
continue to reach out, to work with and to place actual value on
the Latino constituency.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ferrer, who is one of Badillo's successors as the Bronx borough
president and the highest-ranking Hispanic city official, said that
Badillo ``seems to have lost his way.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``All I can say is that I am really profoundly sad
that he's now seen fit to embrace a party that has been anti-city,
anti-immigrant and anti-opportunity. I don't profess to understand
it, but I'm just sad. I remember who Herman used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Badillo offered a strong attack on his former
political party.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a lifelong Democrat, I did not make this decision
lightly,'' he said. ``This is an extremely difficult step for me to
take, but in the end I had no choice. Over the years, I found
myself disagreeing more and more with city and state Democratic
policies and positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Badillo made his remarks after a speech at the Women's National
Republican Club in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, Democratic leaders have advocated the same old
conditions with no accountability,'' he said. ``Hard experience has
convinced me that Democratic leaders are never going to change.
It's sad to say, but as times have changed, the New York State
Democratic Party has largely remained in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats generally responded with derision, Badillo's
announcement was hailed by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of Herman as a pioneer in so many ways,'' Giuliani
said. ``This is one of the most courageous decisions, and once
again Herman Badillo is showing people a way they can improve their
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Miranda said, ``Herman Badillo will forever be a pioneer Puerto
Rican who opened doors for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   While he conceded that ``Latinos are, for the most part,
Democrats,'' he said there was the chance for Republicans to make
great inroads among Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment the Republican Party begins to embrace such issues
as immigration, expenditures in education and issues of concern to
Latinos, they will support the Republican Party,'' Miranda said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
