<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-HOLOCAUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: RECALLING PAIN IN A COUNTRY USED TO IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some out-of-towners come here not for shop-and-gawk
excursions but rather for lessons in life. They want to find out
why crime is down, or how well the subways run, or what to do about
the homeless. A few months ago, officials from post-communist
Mongolia went to Wall Street to pick up pointers on using
capitalist tools.
</P>
<P>
   Few, very few, come for ideas on how to remember perhaps the
most monstrous epoch of a century that has been filled with horror.
So it was interesting to tag along this week with a group of
Russians touring New York's most important memorial to the Nazi
Holocaust, the Museum of Jewish Heritage, which opened last year in
Battery Park City.
</P>
<P>
   These visitors, most of them officials of the Russian Jewish
Congress, hardly needed instruction in the Holocaust. Hundreds of
thousands of Jews from the former Soviet Union were among the 6
million European Jews who perished. And Jewish or not, Russians
don't need Americans to teach them about pain.
</P>
<P>
   But they could use help, this group said, in figuring out what
should be included in a Holocaust museum they plan to build in a
popular Moscow park that itself stands as a memorial to Russian
suffering in World War II. The very idea of such a museum in
Moscow, as implausible in Soviet days as walking on the clouds, is
still new and strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to the reality of it, you realize it's almost a
mission impossible,'' said Michael Steiner, director of the Moscow
office of the American Jewish Joint Distribution Committee, a New
York-based relief agency that sponsored the Russian group.
</P>
<P>
   It was not surprising, then, that questions outnumbered answers
this week. Even so, the visitors, who also went to Holocaust
museums in Los Angeles, Washington and Houston, left for home with
a basic sense of what they would like their own to be. ``We want it
to be expressive and impressive to non-Jews as well as Jews,'' said
Alexander Osovtsov, vice president of the Russian Jewish Congress.
</P>
<P>
   New York was their final stop. Each of the museums on their
itinerary had its merits, they said. But Pinchas Goldschmidt, the
chief rabbi of Moscow, was particularly struck by the one in lower
Manhattan, because it does not dwell on mass murder alone. It also
shows the vibrancy of Jewish life both before and after the war _ a
cautionary tale for those Jews who draw their identity principally
from the Nazis' attempts at extermination and not from their own
rich heritage.
</P>
<P>
   That lesson was not lost on the Russian visitors, most of whom
spoke English well. ``There is past, present and future,''
Goldschmidt said. ``It's not only about death and destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   It took decades of false starts and reversals for the New York
museum to become a reality. If anything, the complications may be
even greater for the Russian Jews. ``The soil for a museum is
different than in America,'' said one of them, Tankred Golenpolski.
</P>
<P>
   That's for sure. American civilians may have put up with
hardships during World War II, but nothing like the devastation
that the Soviet Union endured. More than 20 million people there
died, and for years the official line was that they were not Jews
or Belarussians or Ukrainians or Gypsies but Soviet citizens,
period.
</P>
<P>
   So any attempt to show the suffering of just the Jews requires a
balancing act worthy of the Moscow circus, Golenpolski said. You
have to present them not merely as victims but also as soldiers in
the Soviet army. You have to portray the centuries of Jewish life
in Russia, not just the pogroms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be able,'' Golenpolski said, ``to talk to the
Russian who will say: `I lost my father just like you lost yours.
OK, he didn't die in a gas chamber. But I still lost him.' That is
a just point. But you also have to give Jews their due. We were the
only ones destroyed because we were Jews, not because of political
inclinations. You have to figure out how to drive that point
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the rabbi, he was impressed by the New York museum, with
its biblical admonitions at the entrance: ``Remember, never
forget,'' from Deuteronomy, and ``There is hope for your future,''
from Jeremiah. Still, the Russians walked away realizing they had
far to go. But that is nothing to fear, they were told by David
Altshuler, the director of the museum here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news,'' he said, ``is that the work is forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
