<SLUG> BC-BBO-BRAWLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING UP SOME HIGH HEAT ON THE OLD BRAWL GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ American League president Gene Budig has had
a busy summer building his new reputation as Lord High Executioner.
</P>
<P>
   Budig suspended Seattle Mariners pitcher Randy Johnson in April
for three games after two consecutive pitches from Johnson sailed
near the head of Cleveland Indians outfielder Kenny Lofton. Last
month, Baltimore Orioles reliever Armando Benitez was suspended for
eight games for hitting New York Yankees first baseman Tino
Martinez, a move that started a fight and even angered his own
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim Angels manager Terry Collins and Kansas City Royals
manager Tony Muser were each suspended for eight games this month
after their teams engaged in a beanball war and bench-clearing
rumble. Nine players were also suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Budig called the brawls ``an embarrassment to Major League
Baseball'' and refused to reduce the penalties upon appeal. Nor did
he relent when Yankees reliever Mike Stanton appealed a five-game
suspension for hitting Orioles outfielder Eric Davis with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody agrees that player safety is our first concern, and
we're all committed to seeing that,'' Budig said.
</P>
<P>
   But if Budig is on a mission to do something about beanballs and
bench-clearing brawls, he's likely to run into resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the way the game has been played for 100 years,''
Texas Rangers reliever John Wetteland said. ``I don't like to see
people getting hit. I think it's sick. And it hurts. You win games
by getting people out. But sometimes people take liberties and they
need to be told those liberties won't be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it baseball's version of frontier justice or, if Moses had
been a baseball fan, a fastball inside for a fastball inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's important on every team,'' Rangers pitcher John Burkett
said. ``If a hitter thinks he's being thrown at on purpose, he has
no way to retaliate. He can go out after a pitcher, but then he'll
be thrown out and suspended for four or five games. The easiest way
to get back is to plug one of their hitters. They usually
understand, they take their medicine, and it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball players have always been slow at turning the other
cheek, and it doesn't always start with a hit by pitch.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the Rangers were angered when Orioles first baseman
Glenn Davis slid in high at home plate and severely spiked catcher
Ivan Rodriguez. The next day, the Rangers called on reliever Danny
Leon to retaliate, but he got his players mixed up and hit Cal
Ripken instead.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the Indians were furious with Rodriguez when he
slid hard into shortstop Omar Vizquel at second base, putting
Vizquel out for seven weeks with a torn ligament in his knee. The
next time the two teams met, Rodriguez got nailed in the left
shoulder by pitcher Jack Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Those seemed to be obvious situations for retaliation.
Retaliation seemed evident when Benitez threw at Martinez
immediately after giving up a three-run home run to Bernie
Williams. Benitez denied the accusation, but nobody in baseball
believed him.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing a knockdown pitch after a home run is ``wrong,'' Boston
Red Sox first baseman Mo Vaughn said. ``I still maintain if you
can't get guys out across the plate, get another job. You can
really hurt somebody. Tino Martinez didn't hit that home run.
Someone else did. You can really hurt someone pitching like that.
It can't be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Yankees pitcher David Wells: ``I think that was ridiculous
and uncalled for. It's not good for baseball. It's part of the
game, yes. But to be blatant like that is not acceptable. I've had
teammates upset with me for doing that once. I regret doing that
because you can really hurt somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, it's often difficult to distinguish when a
pitcher is deliberately throwing at a hitter and when one really
did ``get away'' from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who understand the game know when somebody is throwing
at somebody and when they're not,'' Rangers pitcher Aaron Sele
said. ``Ninety-nine percent of the time, it's by accident. There's
a difference between throwing inside and throwing at hitters. As
big and strong as some of these hitters are, you have to get on the
small part of the bat and the best way is to pitch inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rangers outfielder Rusty Greer: ``Pitching inside is part
of the game. When you're in the batter's box, you run the risk of
getting hit. At the same time, if the guy in front of you hits a
home run and the next ball goes behind your head, it might be a
little obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer said that when it comes to retaliation, ``Every case is
different. It's up to the pitcher to decide. I'm not going up to
the pitcher and say, `You need to protect me.' It's up to the
pitcher to decide if he wants to or not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
