u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LIVOTI-TRIAL-540&AMP;A     06-25 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LIVOTI-TRIAL-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL EVIDENCE SUGGESTS HOW POLICE SHIELD THEIR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI and BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three and a half years after a Bronx man's errant
toss of a football led to his death while he was being taken into
custody by Officer Francis Livoti, the federal case against Livoti
has provided new evidence suggesting an ingrained reluctance in the
Police Department to punish either abusive officers or those who
cover up for them.
</P>
<P>
   Since Anthony Baez, 29, died of asphyxiation on Dec. 22, 1994,
Police Department critics have viewed the Livoti case as an example
of the department's lax control of officers with abusive
tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   But a deeper picture has emerged from the federal civil rights
trial now under way in U.S. District Court in Manhattan and from a
lawsuit filed by Baez's family against the city.
</P>
<P>
   It shows that some in the department were concerned about
Livoti's long history of excessive-force complaints as early as
1991, but that he was allowed to remain on patrol in part because
he was a delegate for the powerful Patrolmen's Benevolent
Association and because he was protected by connections high up in
the chain of command.
</P>
<P>
   During the federal trial, the U.S. attorney's office has
presented testimony that officers were not asked for statements in
the immediate aftermath of Baez's death but were allowed to gather
and discuss their version of events in parking lots, the district
attorney's office and the police union office.
</P>
<P>
   The government said it also had evidence that officers even
concocted a cover story to protect Livoti, one in which they blamed
a fictitious black man for choking Baez to death before running
off.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not jurors, who began deliberations Thursday, convict
Livoti, the disclosures about the department mirror those in other
abuse cases, most notably the one involving Abner Louima, in which
officers are accused of covering up the wrongdoing of colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Livoti case is a huge black eye for the Police Department
and the city,'' said Hector Soto, executive director of the
Civilian Compliant Review Board between 1994 and 1996. ``They left
him on the street. They let the other officers cover up for him,
then they did as little as possible to punish the people
responsible. This case is going to haunt the city for a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Livoti, who was eventually dismissed from the department in 1997
after police officials ruled that he used an illegal choke hold on
Baez, was acquitted of charges of criminally negligent homicide in
1996 by a Bronx judge, who called his fellow officers' testimony a
``nest of perjury.'' Yet none of those officers accused of lying
under oath have faced departmental sanctions or criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   And Louis Anemone, the police commander who police officials say
discounted Livoti's history of brutality complaints and prevented
other supervisors from transferring him to desk duty, has since
been promoted to chief of department, the third highest-ranking
police official in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Anemone has refused to comment on the case. Police Commissioner
Howard Safir also declined to comment on the case while the jury is
deliberating but has indicated in the past that he may investigate
the perjury allegations against Livoti's colleagues after the
federal trial has ended.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Police officials noted that after Baez's death, they began a
program to monitor officers with multiple brutality complaints.
</P>
<P>
   But Soto said that as far as the perjury allegations, there was
no need for the Police Department to delay an administrative
investigation. Other present and former law enforcement officials
questioned the department's commitment to policing its own
aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Fishbein, who was chief of the criminal division of the
U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan until 1997, refused to comment
on the Livoti case but said that in past prosecutions of police
officers, department officials often showed ``an institutional
reluctance'' to investigate their officers even when presented with
strong evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some cases, you felt like every step of the way you were
basically fighting the entire Police Department,'' Fishbein said.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony in Livoti's federal trial and depositions in the civil
suit have given an unusually candid look at the power that the
police union is allowed to wield in police brutality
investigations. Livoti's role as a PBA delegate, for example, acted
as a kind of shield when a supervisor sought to transfer him in
1991 because of complaints of brutality.
</P>
<P>
   William Casey, commander of the 46th Precinct, was concerned
that Livoti had accumulated nine complaints of excessive force in
his nine years on the police force and wrote a recommendation that
the officer be moved to desk duty or a less volatile precinct,
according to a deposition in the civil case.
</P>
<P>
   Casey, now a deputy chief, admitted in a deposition that there
were ``different criteria'' used to transfer union representatives,
whose conduct had to be ``more egregious than normal police
officers'' before they could be disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   But in an unusual move, the recommendation was blocked by
Casey's supervisor, Anemone, then a senior commander in the Bronx.
According to two senior police officials, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity, one of Anemone's main concerns was Livoti's
status as a union delegate.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours and days after the fatal confrontation in 1994,
testimony in the trial indicated, Livoti was again protected by the
PBA. The department's rules, which had been negotiated by the
union, allow a 48-hour waiting period before investigators can
question any officer involved in an on-duty shooting or an incident
in which a suspect dies in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Livoti's colleagues used that 48-hour delay as a window of
opportunity, prosecutors said, meeting on several occasions in
parking lots and the union's offices to coordinate their accounts
and fabricate a cover story.
</P>
<P>
   Justice John Walsh of state Supreme Court in Manhattan, who
worked as the Police Department's top prosecutor in the 1970s, said
that if the PBA's influence bordered on obstruction, it would be a
perversion of the union's role in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``A delegate's job is to see that the officer's rights are not
being violated, not to become involved in the facts of the case,''
Walsh said. ``When they overstep those boundaries, we end up with,
at the very least, the appearance of impropriety. This is an
example that the 48-hour rule doesn't work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
