<SLUG> BC-AHCCCS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLIONAIRE ACCUSED OF FLEECING HEALTH CARE PLAN FOR POOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM HERMANN AND SUSIE STECKNER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scottsdale millionaire Michael Phillips recently got an
operation. Trouble is, authorities say, he claimed to be destitute
and conned the state into helping pay for his surgery.
</P>
<P>
   And he's far from alone, say officials of the Arizona Health
Care Cost Containment System.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word on the street was, and may still be, that anyone can
get AHCCCS,'' said Sharon Miller, who oversees the agency's member
fraud unit.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, who was indicted Thursday, might be only one of
hundreds of clients who've conned the state's medical insurance
program for the poor out of hundreds of thousands of dollars in
just the past year.
</P>
<P>
   From 10 to 15 percent of people receiving public assistance get
their benefits fraudulently, national estimates say. For the $1.8
billion AHCCCS program, that could translate into about $250
million.
</P>
<P>
   Injured last year when a car hit his bicycle, Phillips racked up
$37,000 in medical bills. The state paid out just $3,533; the
remainder was covered by the driver's insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   AHCCCS verified one claim made by Phillips, but the others went
unchecked.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that particular case, I think they took the person's word
for it,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, 50, was arrested Thursday at his Scottsdale home. He
has been indicted on one count each of fraud schemes and theft.
</P>
<P>
   According to investigators, Phillips has an investment portfolio
valued at more than $850,000 and more than $1 million in real
estate and vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   At a court hearing Thursday, Phillips appeared wearing plastic
thongs, a pair of rumpled shorts and a T-shirt. He said he is a
licensed residential real estate broker who has lived in Scottsdale
for 25 years and the area for about 40.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Judge Michael Simonson if he needed a court-appointed
attorney, Phillips said, ``I don't know. I am suffering from a head
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge told Phillips to try to hire an attorney on his own
and set his bail for $160,000.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference earlier in the day called by Maricopa
County Attorney Rick Romley and AHCCCS, state officials said they
have increased efforts to detect fraud.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the agency only investigated doctors and other
providers, but it began looking into member fraud in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, the agency has completed more than 500
investigations and found fraud in 30 percent of them.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the agency routinely investigates applicants'
claims, checking out Social Security and motor vehicle records,
welfare rolls and employment history.
</P>
<P>
   In July, she said, the agency will add investigators to conduct
more in-depth checks before a person is approved.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the agency will have several weeks to check out
an applicant. Because Phillips was hospitalized already, AHCCCS had
just 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was injured June 6, 1997, and admitted to St. Joseph's
Hospital and Medical Center. Four days later, he met with an AHCCCS
eligibility worker.
</P>
<P>
   He claimed to be indigent and said he had been living out of his
Volkswagen van. He also said he had to borrow money from his mother
to return to Phoenix from Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the agency verified the claim about borrowing money.
She said the agency ``had no way of knowing'' about his
out-of-state assets and would have had difficulty tracking the
local property he owns because of his common name.
</P>
<P>
   If officials had checked further, they would have found
Phillips' riches:
</P>
<P>
   The $850,000 investment portfolios with firms in Beverly Hills
and Scottsdale; five homes in the Valley with values ranging from
about $40,000 to $83,000; two parcels of land valued at $30,000;
and three vehicles registered in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   But Phillips was deemed indigent and enrolled in the AHCCCS
program for six months. The agency finally learned about the
alleged fraud last July the way they discover most abuse: through
an anonymous tip.
</P>
<P>
   AHCCCS has had its share of problems in recent years and is the
focus of a federal inquiry into allegations of fraud, abuse and
mismanagement. The three-year investigation stems from charges by
ex-employees that the agency left dead recipients on the rolls,
disabled critical computer checks and retaliated against employees
who spoke out.
</P>
</TEXT>
